A4011 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNSEL-LAW-770&AMP;ADD-N     03-02 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL-LAW-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Eds.: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page.)  
 JUSTICE OFFICIAL TO CALL FOR END TO INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT and DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department will declare on Tuesday that
it considers the independent-counsel law so ``fundamentally
flawed'' that it ought to be scrapped this year, two administration
officials said on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the department's stance on the law, the first
official pronouncement by the Clinton administration on the issue,
will be delivered by Deputy Attorney General Eric J. Holder Jr. on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Holder will tell a House Judiciary Committee panel that the
21-year-old statute is ``too flawed to be renewed'' and so should
be allowed to expire on June 30. The law expires on that date
unless Congress specifically reauthorizes it.
</P>
<P>
   Holder has been leading a group within the Justice Department
which has been studying the independent-counsel issue for Attorney
General Janet Reno, and he is known to have expressed reservations
about the statute. But his testimony four-square against it, which
was reported in Tuesday's editions of The Washington Post, is the
first official, unambiguous stand by the Clinton administration
concerning the law.
</P>
<P>
   Holder will appear before the House Judiciary Subcommittee on
Commercial and Administrative Law, headed by Rep. George Gekas,
R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Gekas was one of the managers of the Senate trial on articles of
impeachment that were a result of accusations made against
President Clinton by the independent counsel Kenneth Starr. Starr
is one of seven independent counsels who have investigated members
of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said through a spokesman on Monday night that it
would have no comment in advance of Holder's testimony, but the two
officials, who are familiar with the debate within the
administration on the counsel law, confirmed the outlines of
Holder's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Holder will declare that not only is there ``no way to
adequately fix'' the law, but that there is no need for it because
the Justice Department can investigate most official wrongdoing
itself, The Post reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Holder's reasoning, the Justice Department would retain
authority to name special counsels whenever it was determined that
it could be a conflict of interest for the Justice Department
itself to conduct an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The independent-counsel law was a creation of the post-Watergate
era. It was enacted in 1978, when people in Washington and across
the nation recalled how President Richard M. Nixon tried to thwart
investigations into wrongdoing within his administration by
dismissing the first Watergate special prosecutor, Archibald Cox,
in October 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The independent-counsel law was seen as a way around such
deceptions and conflicts of interest. It states that the attorney
general must seek the appointment of an independent counsel when
there is substantial and credible evidence that a crime has been
committed by the president or a number of other government
officials. A panel of three federal judges selects the counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The statute, conceived as a way to prevent a high official from
getting away with high crimes, has come under frequent criticism in
the past two decades. The law's critics, Democrats and Republicans
alike, have complained that some independent counsels have spent
too much taxpayers' money for too long pursuing supposed wrongdoing
that sometimes falls below the Constitution's ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' _ and sometimes trampling on individual rights while
doing so.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known independent counsel in recent times was Starr,
whose investigation of Clinton began with probing into long-ago
land deals in Arkansas and turned to Clinton's relationship with a
former White House intern, leading to the president's impeachment
on charges of perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   While many Democrats expressed aversion to Starr, earlier
independent counsels have sparked outrage among Republicans.
Independent counsels, for instance, investigated the Iran-Contra
matter in the Reagan years.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsels' inquiry at the time, and a parallel
investigation in Congress, produced high political and television
drama as they delved into the Reagan administration's sale of arms
to Iran and a diversion of some of the profits to the
anti-Communist rebels in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   Other independent counsels have been all but forgotten; at least
one was never even named publicly, so slender were the threads of
evidence in his case. Some independent counsels have spent
considerable time and money looking into matters that did not
appear to threaten the future of the Republic _ whether an aide to
President Jimmy Carter might have used drugs, for instance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before Starr's investigation, the Clinton administration was
more enthusiastic about the statute. Reno spoke strongly in its
favor in the spring of 1993, in the first days of Clinton's
presidency. ``It is my firm conviction that the law has been a good
one, helping to restore public confidence in our system's ability
to investigate wrongdoing by high-level executive branch
officials,'' she told Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Reno was pleading then for renewal of the statute, which had
lapsed in 1992. The law was renewed in 1994, before Democrats lost
control of Congress, for five more years. Those five years are up
this June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has recommended the appointment of several independent
counsels to investigate members of Clinton's Cabinet, but she came
under withering criticism over the past 18 months for refusing to
seek an independent counsel to look into fund-raising abuses in the
Democrats' 1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the law has been tinkered with, its language
refined. It has been defended, albeit lukewarmly, within the past
week, in other hearings on the law before the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee, headed by Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool it, think about it for a while, let the temper of these
times soften,'' Howard Baker said in urging no quick, irreversible
decision. As a former Republican senator from Tennessee and a
member of the Senate Watergate Committee, and later a chief of
staff to President Reagan, he had a rare perspective.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffin B. Bell, an attorney general under Carter and
cochairman with Baker of a national commission studying
governmental separation of powers, had a different view. ``I long
ago concluded that this statute is unworkable for a number of
reasons and represents very poor governmental policy,'' Bell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
