<HEADER>
A4018 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RODMAN-BICKLEY-AZ     03-02 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RODMAN-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEDAY SOON, RODMAN WON'T BE FUNNY ANY MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Oh, it's fine now. The photographers are safe. The
referees aren't worrying about their foreheads. The casino and
wrestling excursions are nothing but dormant demons.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually, the other Dennis Rodman will surface. The one
who spurns his teammates, tests their tolerance, pushes their
patience. The one who recedes into a world of self-gratification.
</P>
<P>
   It will happen because it always has, and when it does, what
then?
</P>
<P>
   Good luck, Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the freak show came to town. Pete Sampras was in the
crowd. Mo Vaughn was in the house. All for a glimpse of the purple
cash machine for NBC and the NBA, the glamour boys anointed to save
a league from air-ball apathy.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Lakers survived fatigue, immaturity and the
hurricane force of Luc Longley. And while Rodman didn't start, he
was the main attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Seven points and 16 rebounds later, the comic-book tandem of
Rambis and Rodman are 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what?'' Lakers Coach Kurt Rambis said. ``Not only is
he a great defensive player and an unbelievable rebounder, but that
guy knows more about basketball than 99.9 percent of the players on
the planet. I'm so happy the Lakers got him on this ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course he is. For now.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, Rodman gives the Lakers exactly what they need.
Toughness. Rebounding. Outlet passing to ignite the fast break. A
strong defender. But if you think he's the guy who will shut down
Karl Malone in the playoffs, well, you didn't watch the past two
NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think he'll be on his best behavior for the duration
of a short season, you haven't been paying attention. With this
guy, calm can only last so long, conformity gets boring very
quickly, and there can never be an abundance of good times.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's performance, Rodman wasn't in the mood to talk.
He issued a few thoughts to a Suns' official, quickly becoming
Rodman's new mode of communication with the press.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing is more fitting than what he recently told ESPN's
Dan Patrick:
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me,'' Rodman said. ``I will keep myself in front of
that damn lens right there as long as I live.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Bulls coach Phil Jackson says Rodman suffers from
Attention Deficit Syndrome. An undying need to be analyzed,
scrutinized, to be the subject of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the cameras caught Rodman and Rambis joking on the
sidelines. What they didn't see was Rodman taking a seat on the far
end of the bench during a timeout, tuning out the head coach.
Combined with missed practices and late arrivals and a few bad
losses, there will come a time when it won't be funny any longer.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three seasons, the Rodman experiment was equally
volatile, but the whole thing worked only because Michael Jordan
and Scottie Pippen would not let Rodman sink the ship. Simply put,
the Lakers don't have such strength of character.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Chicago, Rodman tried. And while everything was swept
under the rug _ the gambling excursions, the missed practices, the
verbal assault on Mormons _ his postseason detour to Detroit almost
broke the Bulls. If you don't remember, it was the day he bolted
town to wrestle with Hulk Hogan while the NBA Finals were reaching
a fever pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In his two successful stops, the two places where he's won
championships, there has been at least two veteran superstars
Rodman deeply respected and a coach that served as a surrogate
father figure.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, there is Shaquille O'Neal, a man who has been
swept four times in his playoff career, and the most frequent
target of Rodman's wrath in the past. There is the 20-year-old Kobe
Bryant, on his path to greatness, hoisting up ill-advised shots at
every turn. And there is Rambis, head coach for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, they are enjoying Rodmania. They are also ripe for an
attack of the Rodmaniac.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal says he forgives Rodman for past insults, saying he's
always wanted a ``thug forward.'' Bryant said he can put up with
anything in exchange for a championship ring. Rambis says he can
relate, once a self-described rebel himself.
</P>
<P>
   They really don't understand. But they will.
</P>
<P>
   It will either happen naturally or Rodman will create the
friction for excitement. It will happen because this is what his
life has become, a mixture of fact and fiction, of shock value and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was doing games for TNT, I was in a taxicab in New York
and the driver was listening to Howard Stern,'' Danny Ainge said.
``They were talking about Rodman's exploits, how he was out until
four in the morning. I get to Madison Square Garden and I run into
Jack Haley and I tell him that I heard they were out until four.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Danny, it's all a bunch of crap. Dennis was in bed
at 11. I was in bed at 11. He just made the whole story up for
drama.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there will be plenty of nights when Rodman ``is'' out
until 4 a.m. Followed by mornings when he doesn't feel like
practicing.
</P>
<P>
   He will explode when the initial embrace has worn off in Los
Angeles and the star-struck town begins to yawn at his hair color.
Or when the Lakers play like children and underachieve. Or if he
doesn't crack the starting lineup soon. Or when he believes he's
being targeted by David Stern and his referees.
</P>
<P>
   It will happen because it always has and who changes at age 37?
</P>
<P>
   What then?
</P>
<P>
   Good night, Lakers. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
