<HEADER>
A4020 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      03-02 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
It wasn't supposed to be like this.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Spurs visit the Rockets tonight in what was expected to be a
game between teams better than a combined .500. But the only sure
thing in the Texas portion of the NBA is the Mavericks, who never
seem to change.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets and Spurs have not slipped that far, but each can
commiserate with its I-10 rival.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, tonight's meeting of the 8-6 Rockets and 6-8 Spurs
can offer the Rockets some welcome relief from a stretch that has
seen them lose five of their past eight games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets insist they have reason to consider the recent slump
an aberration, citing a lack of depth because of injuries and the
growing pains expected with a lineup that for the past five games
has included just one starter from last season.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley, out for two weeks after arthroscopic surgery to
repair cartilage damage in his left knee, returned to the rotation
Sunday. Antoine Carr returned from his knee injury the day before,
and Rodrick Rhodes could be back sometime this week.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley contends the Rockets' problems can be traced directly to
their injuries. Before his surgery, they were 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right there,'' Barkley said. ``I like our team a lot.
We're going to be good. We've got a lot of good pieces. We were
playing really well before I got hurt. We just have to play like we
were playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were playing well and have since, as impressive
showings against the Suns and SuperSonics, and even stretches
against Vancouver and New Jersey, would indicate. But they have
been sporadic, citing the adjustment to one another required by all
their changes and youth. Even Barkley said it would take another
month for all the pieces to jell.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rudy Tomjanovich says the process has been slowed by
circumstances as much as injuries. The schedule has had the Rockets
playing nine games in 13 days and will not offer more than one day
between games until March 18-19. Thus, Tomjanovich has had to
experiment during games to find what will work best for each player
individually and the Rockets as a unit.
</P>
<P>
   Only in games has he been able to test new combinations and
rotations or find which new players are more comfortable in
specific game situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to find out what I've got,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I've
got to go through the process of having guys out there and figuring
out what's best for this guy or that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the offense has been changing in subtle ways. There
have been times the offense has clicked, most recently to start the
second halves at Vancouver and Los Angeles over the weekend, when
almost every basket came from running the offense and almost every
field goal was coupled with an assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would mean the offense was working,'' forward Matt
Bullard said. ``The guys are looking to the open man and passing
better. We've been working real hard on trying to find our plays
and certain things we can do to get guys comfortable. The coaches
have been doing a fantastic job to get guys doing things they can
do well.''
</P>
<P>
   On other occasions, the offense has become reliant on individual
moves. And the change to a more up-tempo style has been generally
limited to long rebounds grabbed by Scottie Pippen or a few Michael
Dickerson sprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been a team that didn't want to run, even the
water-buffalo team I played on,'' Tomjanovich said. ``Those first
couple strides, I see guys trotting instead of busting down there.
I've got to yell, `Run! Get down there! Cross on the break!'
There's never been anybody that just does it on their own. Bill
Fitch, that's one thing that he said: `You have to do that all the
time to wear them (opponents) down. Then, you'll start getting
them.' You might run five times and not see the ball, but you've
got to run on that sixth time.''
</P>
<P>
   Those problems, however, seem relatively minor compared to the
injuries that had removed four players from the planned rotation.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Rockets fret too much, they could always consider the
Spurs, who have been healthy and whose additions were expected to
step easily into familiar roles.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have struggled, however, even moving former Rockets
guard/forward Mario Elie into the starting lineup to add intensity
to a team with a tendency to underachieve without seeming to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to bust on this team all the time for being soft,''
Elie said. ``Now, I hear other guys calling us soft, and I'm on the
team. It bugs me. It doesn't seem to bug other guys, but it bugs
me. I know these guys are talented and all, but talent doesn't
always win in this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to win a championship in this league, you have to
have heart and soul. Talent doesn't always win championships. Blood
and guts do. We have a nice team on paper, but we're missing
something. This is the first team that I've been on that's had no
emotion. Other than me, Malik (Rose), Jerome (Kersey) and Avery
(Johnson), the other guys seem to be just walking around. That's
just the type of guys they are. I'm trying, yelling at guys, trying
to get them pumped up. But it takes a lot out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the luster also has been taken out of this meeting of
the Spurs and Rockets. But both might take a look across the court
to share a little early misery and consider their condition
temporary.
</P>
</TEXT>
