A4021 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-LAKERS-AZR &LR;      03-02 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-LAKERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS STUMBLE IN FOURTH QUARTER TO LAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ With a game on the line, nobody has been more
dependable than Rex Chapman for the Suns over the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Even on his worst shooting nights, Chapman has demonstrated a
knack for hitting big shots in pressure situations. But Monday,
that magic escaped him.
</P>
<P>
   And the Los Angeles Lakers, with Derek Harper and Shaquille
O'Neal making the big shots when they counted most, escaped the
Suns, 97-91, at America West Arena with their fourth straight
victory since Del Harris was dismissed as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman had three opportunities to score in the final 2:15 and
came up empty on each as the Suns lost for the fourth time in eight
home games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a guy that's won a lot of games the last
two years,'' Suns Coach Danny Ainge said of Chapman. ``Everyone on
our bench, the coaching staff, every fan knows that. Those things
happen. You can't make them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you this: I'll take those shots every day. And Rex
made the right decisions to take the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't make Chapman feel any better about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to try to explain it away,'' Chapman said. ``I
just blew them. The first one was point-blank. Another one I make
in my sleep it seems like. Our guys executed perfectly, set
screens, everybody did their jobs except the guy shooting the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Chapman wasn't alone. The Suns led by eight points
with 10 minutes to play and couldn't hold the lead. Ironically,
they have made a bad habit of falling behind by double-digits,
forcing big comebacks in many games this season.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they appeared to have control of the game. But the
Lakers reeled off a 12-4 run in a span of three minutes to tie the
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't execute as well in the fourth quarter as we had the
rest of the game,'' Suns forward George McCloud said. ``They're a
club we know we can play with and we know we can beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, with center Luc Longley playing his best game of the
season, did a reasonably good job on O'Neal. He had 25 points and
nine rebounds. And they did it without conceding open shots to the
Lakers' explosive wing players, Kobe Bryant and Eddie Jones, who
combined to make seven of 22 shots.
</P>
<P>
   But Harper killed them, connecting on four of his five
three-point attempts to finish with 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pops made some big shots,'' McCloud said of the 37-year-old
Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Suns were in position to win. They led 83-82 and set
up a play during a timeout that included several options, but the
one the Suns wanted was Chapman coming off a screen. It worked
beautifully, and Chapman took the ball to the basket. But he missed
a running scoop shot.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal made the Suns pay, scoring inside. Jason Kidd's 17-foot
jumper put the Suns back up by a point, but when Kidd double-teamed
O'Neal on the Lakers' next possession, O'Neal found Harper spotted
up at the three-point line.
</P>
<P>
   He hit it with 1:08 to play and the Lakers were up, 87-85.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq was getting what he wanted inside, and they kept digging
to try and get back to him (with a double-team),'' Harper said.
``My shot felt good, and fortunately Shaq got it out to me. I had
time to get set, so I was confident I was going to knock it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapman missed on the Suns' next possession when O'Neal helped
defensively and made him alter a shot low on the baseline. The Suns
sent Lakers forward Dennis Rodman to the line for a pair of free
throws, and he hit one of two.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the Suns set up a play during a timeout, this time with
51 seconds to play. Chapman came off a screen on the opposite side
this time, and again had an open shot. It missed.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman said the play was executed ``exactly'' as it was drawn
up except for one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't draw it up to be missed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns had a last gasp after Tom Gugliotta's three-point shot,
and a silly foul Harper committed on Kidd behind the three-point
line with 9.5 seconds to go and the Lakers holding a five point
lead. But Kidd hit just one of the three free throws and it was
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to say it had to do with the great coaching,''
Lakers Coach Kurt Rambis said. ``But I think Shaq had something to
do with that. Kobe making free throws, and a great defensive effort
by a few people. And I think Dennis probably got a couple of his
rebounds when we needed them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
