<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BROWN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWNS ACQUIRE BROWN  
 CARDS' NEGOTIATIONS TURN ELSEWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Soon after veteran offensive tackle Lomas Brown
rejected the Cardinals' two-year contract offer, the team stepped
up negotiations with linebacker Jamir Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals may also resume talks with free-agent offensive
tackle Wayne Gandy, who has spent his entire five-year career with
the Los Angeles and St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Brown &QL; 
spurned the Cardinals and agreed to a three-year deal with the
expansion Cleveland Browns, whose original offer was worth $10.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good sign for Wayne'' said Gandy's agent, Neil
Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had offered a two-year deal worth $6 million,
about $400,000 less than Cleveland's two-year contract was worth.
But the Cardinals refused to add a third year for a player who will
be 36 next season.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland offered a $3 million signing bonus. But $4.1 million
of the Browns' offer is in the final year, when Brown knows he
could be released.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the Browns said that Brown objected to such a
disparity between the second and third years and that Cleveland
increased the amount in the second year to pacify Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals offered a $2 million signing bonus but were
willing to give him $4 million in 1999, $500,000 more than the
Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not have been able to compete with them as far as
dollars were concerned,'' said a Cardinals official who asked to
remain unidentified. ``Still, I'm shocked that he made that
decision. For a guy who worked all his career to be on a playoff
contender, to make a decision like that . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven days ago, the Browns weren't even in the picture for
Brown, who said he was close to re-signing with the Cardinals. But
the Cardinals couldn't close the deal, and Brown visited Cleveland
last week.
</P>
<P>
   He still talked to Cardinals officials before making his final
decision and reportedly spoke with Coach Vince Tobin and
offensive-line coach George Warhop on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the starting left tackle the past three seasons, joins a
Cleveland offensive line that will be the strength of the team. The
line includes high-priced free agents Dave Wohlabaugh, the former
New England center, and Orlando Thomas, the former Baltimore right
tackle.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' talks with Miller's agent, Steve Baker, on Monday
were the most serious in several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``All along, we've made it known that we want Jamir Miller
back,'' the Cardinals official said. ``We still want him back.
Hopefully, we'll get him back.''
</P>
<P>
   But how hard will they try?
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the team's leading tackler last season, has been waiting
two weeks for the Cardinals to make an offer. It likely will be a
short-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   The only known competition the Cardinals have for Miller is the
Chicago Bears, whom Miller visited last week. But after signing
offensive tackle Blake Brockermeyer to a four-year, $17 million
contract, the Bears are trying to decide whether they still have
enough money to make an offer to Miller. The Bears have only about
$3.3 million in salary cap room available.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said the Cardinals had made it clear that Brown
remained their top choice and that Gandy was only an option if
Brown signed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Steelers are also interested in Gandy, who played
left tackle and right tackle for the Rams. &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
Cardinals backup quarterback Stoney Case, an unrestricted free
agent, visited the Seattle Seahawks last Friday. His former coach
at New Mexico, Mike Sheppard, is the quarterbacks coach of the
Seahawks. Seattle has only one quarterback, Jon Kitna, on its
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Backup offensive lineman Matt Joyce, a restricted free agent,
continues to attract interest from the Minnesota Vikings, who are
deciding whether to make him an offer. The Cardinals could match
any offer but wouldn't receive compensation if they didn't match
it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
