<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-SOSA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMMY SOSA, SUPERSTAR  
 AFTER HIS MVP YEAR, CUBS PLAYER IS CENTER OF ATTEN TION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. - The circus arrived in Mesa on Monday morning. The
Sammy Sosa circus, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, looking the part of the Pied Piper, led a throng of fans,
reporters and television cameras to different corners of the
Chicago Cubs' training facility at Fitch Park during his first
workout of the spring.
</P>
<P>
   An aerial view of the complex would have shown a glut of fans
and reporters at whatever field Sosa worked. It looked like the
overviews shown during golf tournaments when Tiger Woods
participates.
</P>
<P>
   The signs all around the complex say these are the Chicago Cubs.
But it was Sosa whom fans wanted to see most on this glorious day
in the Valley. For his part, Sosa did not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   He flashed his gleaming smile, the one that captivated a nation
last season, throughout the Cubs' 2{-hour workout. He then signed
autographs for nearly everyone who wanted one before heading into
the clubhouse to meet again with his teammates and eventually with
an eager horde of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa remained humble, even cracking jokes, while discussing his
1998 season, which culminated with him being named the National
League Most Valuable Player on a nearly unanimous vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's going to remember '98,'' he said. ``We've got to
put that away, because '99 is now the year. They already paid me
for '98.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's first press conference of the 1999 season was strikingly
similar to the ones he had almost on a daily basis during the final
month of last season. He was engaging and accommodating and seemed
the same genuine self he's been since making his big league debut
with Texas in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any kind of ego,'' said Sosa, who reported to
camp at a slightly bulked-up 222 pounds. ``I'm the same guy. I
showed I don't play for money. I play for myself and the team.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds nice on the surface, but the reality is that Sosa's
life will forever be changed. He is easily recognized wherever he
ventures. He can no longer duck into any establishment and expect
to roam around without being noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa willingly accepts the rewards and celebrity that come from
swatting 66 home runs last season, second in the history of the
game only to Mark McGwire's 70. He welcomed many of the accolades
showered on him during the off-season, notably being invited to
just about every awards ceremony conceivable.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's non-stop winter itinerary has been the cause of some
criticism. There are those who believe he may have run himself into
the ground with a grinding schedule that had him jetting off to far
corners of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   He played a series of exhibition games with major league
All-Stars in Japan and flew off to attend a soiree at Hugh Hefner's
Playboy Mansion in Hollywood. He also made time to help light the
national Christmas tree in Washington, D.C., and attend two parades
in his honor in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   He attended countless banquets, including the players union
awards in Orlando and the ESPN awards in New York. The Dominican
native visited Chicago several times, including for his MVP
announcement, and even attended the State of the Union address, his
favorite stop of the winter, as a personal guest of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He also visited Puerto Rico and Venezuela to receive
humanitarian awards for his efforts to aid Hurricane Georges'
victims in his country.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Henry Rodriguez, Sosa's neighbor a few miles away in
the Dominican Republic, said he never saw Sosa over the winter
except on television. Sosa estimated he slept in his own bed
``maybe two or three weeks'' during the 4{-month off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there will ever be another year like that
again,'' he said Monday. ``I have a lot of memories now. Everything
I did went to the foundation. I have an opportunity to be here and
ask for help. I think I'm doing something great. I'm satisfied with
what God gave me last year. I'm not asking to take the world. I
just want a piece of the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa firmly sits atop a once glorious but now ravaged, Chicago
sports scene, ready to take over as the city's No. 1 sports figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to replace Michael Jordan,'' Sosa said. ``I
don't want to be like Michael. I want to be like Sammy. I want to
be the best. He's the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star right fielder arrived in camp Monday brimming with
enthusiasm and talking about helping to lead the Cubs to their
first World Series appearance since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Several times during his meeting with reporters, Sosa emphasized
that he believes the Cubs are not far from being a World Series
club, how achieving that goal is really all he cares about.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we stay together as a family like we did in '98, then we're
going to go a long way in '99,'' Sosa said. ``The goal right now is
to go to the World Series. I'll never forget where I came from. I'm
still hungry.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
