<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-WOMACK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMACK HESITANT TO MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ If you're worth your salt as a middle infielder, you
stand your ground when a runner comes after you at second base with
his spikes high, trying to break up a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Womack has been in that situation many times. Now he is
standing his ground in a different way. Though he doesn't want to
create any seismic activity for his new team, the Diamondbacks, he
is not overjoyed about what appears will be a move from second base
to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Womack, acquired Friday in a trade with Pittsburgh, had his
first face-to-face meeting with Manager Buck Showalter on Monday
morning before joining his teammates on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both said what we had to say,'' Womack said. ``Although
there were no conclusions, it is important for us to be on the same
page. You can't settle everything in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   That case stated, your rebuttal, Mr. Showalter:
</P>
<P>
   ``He more than likely will be in right field. He understands the
way we feel, the way I feel. It will take a day or so for it to
soak in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that Tony has a lot on his mind. This is a new
organization, this is the first time he's ever been traded, and his
wife is two or three weeks away from giving birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murph (outfield coach Dwayne Murphy) and I spoke to him. He
presented his thoughts, and they were all good points. It's not a
surprise to him, though, that we want him to play right field. It's
been talked about for a while. But I'm not going to jam anything
down his throat.''
</P>
<P>
   While Showalter said that Womack's athleticism gives him several
options, the skipper has the only vote that really counts, and that
ballot reads: right field.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks had their first intrasquad game Monday at
Tucson Electric Park. Womack did not play. He joined a handful of
veterans on an adjacent field and took some infield practice _ at
second base and shortstop _ and a few swings in the batting cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to get out there, get a few swings in, work on a
few fundamentals and calm down,'' said Womack, who is expected to
be the leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the trade, the Diamondbacks have had a few
inquiries from other teams about Womack. It will be highly
unlikely, however, that he will wind up in another uniform this
season.
</P>
<P>
   One new set of threads will be enough to last him awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I have to get used to,'' he said. ``I felt
comfortable in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen other guys get traded and wondered how I would act
if I ever got traded. In a way, I wanted it to be someone else. But
it's me.''
</P>
<P>
   So the transition begins. It is uncertain whether Womack will
see action in today's intrasquad game at 1 p.m. at the minor league
complex. All the defensive work during batting practice will be
beneficial, but it won't be the same as stepping on the hot coals.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the flames flicker at his feet, he will stand his
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is give 100 percent all the time,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
