</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WINNING ON THE ROAD: EASY TO SAY, NOT DO 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Basketball is a simple game. Any pro will tell you
that. Such was the case on Monday night in Madison Square Garden.
And Chris Childs, a New York point guard, succinctly explained the
Knicks' 85-78 victory over the Cavaliers on Monday night after two
straight losses on the road. ``Enough,'' Childs said, ``was
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   And Allan Houston, the Knick shooting guard, said, ``We got our
emotional level back.''
</P>
<P>
   And the sage veteran and infrequent Knick center, Herb Williams,
added yet another perspective. ``Cleveland,'' he said, ``missed a
lot of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a matter of sometimes inexplicable record why the home
team generally has such an advantage in basketball. The Knicks have
a 9-5 record over all now _ 2-4 on the road, 7-1 at home. Perhaps
the home advantage has to do with the roar of the partisan crowd
that pumps up the local sweethearts and puts the tourists in a
profound funk that only Jung could plumb; or that the rims and
backboards and floorboards are more familiar, or less; or maybe
it's the difference between home cooking and room service.
</P>
<P>
   But the simple fact of this simple game is that for a team to
win to get to the playoffs and succeed on that level, it must win
on the road. Championship teams somehow find a way to master the
trick. The Knicks coach, Jeff Van Gundy, is aware of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes mental toughness to win on the road,'' Van Gundy said
after the game. ``To date we haven't shown yet. You don't develop
it as a player. You either have it or you don't. At times, we've
used the excuse of being on the road to explain the letdown. We
just need more discipline offensively and defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston and Detroit, in the two games on Friday and Sunday,
the Knicks played as though they were up against Bird's Celtics and
Isiah's Pistons, instead of teams with losing records.
</P>
<P>
   And then on Monday night, just when Cleveland closed a gap in
which they were down by as many as 16 points in the second quarter,
and now made the score 52-50 in the middle of the third period, the
Knicks sprang alive. They went on a 15-2 run. Charlie Ward threw a
beautiful lob pass to Patrick Ewing for a basket. Houston hit a big
three-point shot. Childs fed Ewing. Then came Marcus Camby with a
turnout jump shot and Larry Johnson with a twisting layup that
would have made Chubby Checker proud.
</P>
<P>
   And their defense had something to do with the victory, as well.
`Yeah,'' said Van Gundy, ``we fouled 'em every time they got the
ball.'' The stats confirmed the wry remark: The Cavs shot 43 free
throws to the Knicks' 22. But Van Gundy was also aware that his
team did have some shot blockers in attendance, especially Ewing
and Kurt Thomas, and especially against the suddenly earthbound
Shawn Kemp. Kemp, the Cavs' 6-foot-10 center, is listed at 280
pounds. Maybe one day he will be. Now, he is a decidedly more
portly player than fans have been used to seeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to play above the rim,'' said Williams, ``but now he's
more of a post-up player.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was quick to add that he has done very well in
transforming his game, in virtually one season, or since he found
the weight room during the lockout less to his tastes than the
buffet table. He did score 19 points and he did have 10 rebounds,
but down the stretch, he found Ewing and Thomas, particularly,
swatting away his shot attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Right after the game, the Knicks packed their shaving kits for
the trip to Miami, where they play the Heat on Tuesday night. Will
their resolve remain, or will it retreat?
</P>
<P>
   ``In pressurized situations on the road usually true character
comes out,'' said Van Gundy. ``In a few more weeks we'll have a
good idea about the character of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This league is so evenly matched now,'' said Childs. ``We have
to go out there and not lose our composure. When we lost in Boston
and Detroit, we lost our composure. We tried to do it one-on-one.
We have to stay within the concept of getting the ball inside first
_ and shoot jump shots when we're double-teamed and hit the open
man. We were going side-to-side today looking for the open shot. If
we do that, and hold a team to lowscoring, we'll win.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple game. The Knicks just can't let it become quantum
mechanics when they travel. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 0036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
