<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-FRAUENHEIM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON'S MEDICINE USE UNCLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - After  &UR; Mike Tyson assaulted a television set last
week, questions about his jailhouse tantrum lingered.
</P>
<P>
   One of Tyson's attorneys said Maryland jailers had denied him an
antidepressant drug, Zoloft, which he apparently had been taking
for four months.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no comment from Maryland. With only the
attorney's word, there's room for skepticism. Nothing about Tyson
is ever certain. He's got more spinmeisters than  &UR; President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But assume for a second that Tyson has been taking the drug. The
propriety of withholding medicine is one issue. What if he had been
diabetic? Would the jailers withhold insulin?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's his boxing license. It was restored by Nevada after
a messy hearing, which included a psychological report that deemed
him fit to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Tyson was prescribed Zoloft by the Massachusetts
psychiatric team that had him on its proverbial couch.
</P>
<P>
   A fighter on antidepressant medicine? According to the ``1998''
``Complete Drug'' ``Reference _ A Consumer Reports'' guide, Zoloft
``may cause some people to become drowsy.''
</P>
<P>
   Should we assume today's cornermen are sedating their fighters
with a couple of Valium and telling them to be happy? Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   If, in fact, Tyson has been on antidepressant medication, it
might explain his repeated, profanity-laced outbursts in Las Vegas
during the week before he beat  &UR; Frans Botha.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, he quit taking it as he marshaled his energies
during the days before the opening bell. It was then that he
verbally assaulted television correspondents. Not long after, he
went after the set itself. &QL; 
A recount &QL; 
Here's an argument for posting the judges' scores after each round:
</P>
<P>
   About 10 days after Phoenix middleweights  &UR; Anthony Brown and
 &UR; Roger
 &UR; Jones were judged to have fought to a draw at Midnight Rodeo, the
Arizona State Boxing Commission conducted a recount. Oops, the
addition was faulty. Brown, now 14-6-1, was declared the winner by
a split decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can accept a draw, but to tell me I lost 10 days
afterward,'' said Jones (4-2-1). ``That's unfair.'' &QL; 
Briefly . . . &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Carbajal's comeback victory Saturday night was a first step
in his plans for a 112-pound title. It was hard to judge. Carbajal
appeared to have regained hand speed that was absent in a 1997
loss. But he beat a fighter,  &UR; Jose DeJesus, 35, who appeared to be
in poor condition.
</P>
<P>
   Former International Boxing Federation middleweight champ  &UR; James
Toney will resurface as a cruiserweight Sunday at Celebrity Theater
against little-known  &UR; Onebo Maxine. How far has he fallen? Once,
Toney was a pound-for-pound contender. For Sunday's bout,  &UR; Sione
Asipelli of Mesa was offered as an opponent by Valley manager
 &UR; Steve Eisner. Toney's corner said no, which suggests fear that
Asipelli is too tough.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix attorney  &UR; Pat McGroder has been appointed to a seat on
the Arizona Commission. McGroder represented former Suns center
 &UR; Alvan Adams and former Suns Coach  &UR; John MacLeod.
</P>
<P>
   Promising yet idle  &UR; Fidel Hernandez of Carbajal's gym used to be
a roommate of newly crowned International Boxing Federation junior
middleweight champ  &UR; Fernando Vargas when both were amateurs.
Hernandez said he's going to ask his old roomie for a bout. Might
as well. Nobody else will fight Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tim Kawakami's biography of  &UR; Oscar De La Hoya, ``Golden''
``Boy,'' is on the book stands. It's an insightful look at a
fighter with pound-for-pound rivals but unchallenged popularity. &QL; 
Norm Frauenheim can be reached at 602-444-8259 or
norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com viae-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
