<HEADLINE>
RAFTER EASILY STEALS SHOW  
 QUESTIONS TOUGHER THAN HIS FOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - The questions from the ladies in the crowd
were tougher than Australian Pat Rafter's first-round match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you wear boxers or briefs?'' a woman asked Rafter, who beat
American Alex O'Brien, 6-3, 6-4, Monday night at the Franklin
Templeton Tennis Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, voted by ``People'' magazine in 1997 as one of the 10
sexiest men in the world, didn't blush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't wear my G-string. . .but it's whatever I've got,''
Rafter told the adoring fans at the Canadian Pacific Scottsdale
Princess. The questions didn't get any racier. They also had little
to do with aces and double faults.
</P>
<P>
   One fan asked him what he does to relax? Rafter said, ``To have
a bit of dinner and a couple of beers.''
</P>
<P>
   A female fan then shouted, ``Where?''
</P>
<P>
   His brothers, Peter and Michael, got a good laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, 21, made his first trip to the United States, spending
his vacation in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give one member of my family a holiday each year,'' said
Rafter, third youngest of nine children. ``He just turned 21, so he
can drink with the boys.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers also can play golf. ``My (golf) game is getting
good and that's the scary part,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter has become Australia's most recognized athlete the past
two years when he was ranked in the top five and won back-to-back
U.S. Opens.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when he plays in a tournament, such as in Scottsdale, he's
a main eventer. He had the featured match Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In three previous trips to Scottsdale, he was on the undercard
and played on the sunshine circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like day matches, personally,'' said Rafter, ranked fifth on
the ATP Tour. ``Being the featured match has happened more and more
and it's going to happen throughout the rest of my career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I'm going to deal with all these expectations
and do it (be ranked in the top five) again. It affects you
mentally and physically. I'd like to be back near the top again. I
didn't think I could do it last year and I did it. But it's very
difficult to get motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, seeded second in the Scottsdale event, admires the way
Pete Sampras, the world's No. 1 ranked player who is top seed, has
handled his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete has got to be tired,'' Rafter said. ``He has had an
incredibly tough last year. He has done it (been No. 1) for six
years. No one has been able to do it that long before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always finds something different, something new. He keeps
astonishing guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, meanwhile, had little trouble in advancing to the second
round. He had five aces in the first set and broke O'Brien's serve
in the sixth game.
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, he recorded a service break in the first
game, but then O'Brien broke back. Rafter scored another service
break in the third game and held on to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big relief at the end,'' he said. ``I got tighter and
tighter.''
</P>
<P>
   He had good reason. It was his first singles match since
suffering a knee injury Jan. 22 in the third round of the
Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``My knee is good at the moment,'' Sampras said. ``I've done a
lot of strength work back home at Australia. An MRI showed there
was little wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other night match, fourth-seeded Goran Ivanisevic beat
Aussie Scott Draper, 5-7, 6-4, 6-1. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
