<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS RUEFULLY RECALLS DELGADO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. -  &UR; Pete Sampras never will forget the last
time he played  &UR; Ramon Delgado of Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado knocked the world's No. 1 player out of the French Open
last May in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing about playing him this time is that it will be
on a much different surface,'' said Sampras, who will meet Delgado
in the first round of the Franklin Templeton Tennis Classic tonight
at the Canadian Pacific Scottsdale Princess.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the match was played on clay, which had turned into
mud. Tonight, the match will be on a hard court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone beating you has confidence, but I'm looking forward to
playing him again,'' said Sampras, who lost to Delgado, 7-6, 6-3,
6-4, at the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado, ranked 55th on the Association of Tennis Professionals
men's tour, said the victory over Sampras was the biggest of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best thing for me so far and was really important for
the sport in my country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Local ties &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tucson native  &UR; Jim Grabb, a doubles specialist who attended
Scottsdale Saguaro High School, is the new coach of American
 &UR; Justin
 &UR; Gimelstob, who beat  &UR; Thomas Muster of Austria, 6-4, 7-5, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done an excellent job,'' Gimelstob said of Grabb. ``We
play similar styles and get along well. I really respect his
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Gimelstob's trainer is  &UR; Nick Anthony, an Arizona State
University product, and he is a close friend of Phoenix native
 &UR; Farley Weiss, once a top junior player in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farley is a tennis fanatic,'' Gimelstob said. ``He has taken a
personal interest in my career.''  &QL; 
Bruins backer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gimelstob, who will play  &UR; Fernando Vicente in the second round,
hopes to still be in the tournament Thursday because his favorite
college basketball team, UCLA, will play at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   He played two years for the Bruins tennis team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a huge fan,'' he said. ``But it just bums me out that
(guard)
 &UR; Baron Davis kissed the floor Saturday and waved goodbye after two
years. That means he won't be back.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
