<SLUG> BC-BKC-ASU-RULE-DISPUTE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRONG CALL ON RULE HAS EVANS STEAMED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - An erroneous rule interpretation by officials
contributed to Arizona State's 78-73 loss to California in Oakland
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But if ASU Coach Rob Evans was peeved after the game, he was
even angrier Monday after the Pac-10 tried to own up to the
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The disputed call came in the final moments of the game after
Cal's Carl Boyd was fouled by Jason Patton while rebounding a
missed free throw. After play stopped, Boyd elbowed ASU's Mike
Batiste in the chest. Batiste took a halfhearted swing, and Boyd
did the same. Then the two squared off before teammates restrained
them.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Jerry White called a double flagrant technical foul and
ejected both players. Ryan Forehan-Kelly came off the bench to
shoot free throws in place of Boyd for the Patton foul and made
both. Cal led, 72-68, with 22.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   After huddling, White and umpires Steve Wilson and George
Arredondo awarded the ball to Cal. That shouldn't have happened.
According to the NCAA, on a double technical foul after the
whistle, the ball goes to the team with the possession arrow in its
favor _ ASU in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said that when he tried to point this out to White, he was
pushed slightly and told, ``Go coach your team.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of ASU having the ball and trailing by four, Cal kept
possession, and Geno Carlisle was fouled with 21.4 seconds left. He
made both free throws to give the Golden Bears a safe six-point
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The officials apparently were confused because there is a new
rule that after a double personal foul during play, the ball is
awarded to the team that had possession.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Pac-10 admitted the error. Booker Turner, the
coordinator of officials, said in a printed statement that
``because the double flagrant technical fouls were called during a
dead-ball period, the ball should have been awarded to the team
favored by the possession arrow after the free throws.''
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10 Commissioner Tom Hansen said, ``We regret the error . . .
Our officials are accountable for applying the rules properly, and
there must be consequences when that is not done.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, the three officials will not be assigned by the
conference to any games during November 1999. But an irate Evans
noted that the officials, as independent contractors, can work
games for other conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the punishment? But when Rob Evans or (UCLA Coach)
Steve Lavin or (UCLA player) Baron Davis does something, we're
publicly reprimanded, we've got to make a public apology or we're
suspended for a game,'' Evans said, referring to past incidents.
``Where's the equity there?''
</P>
<P>
   Evans also was upset at the Pac-10 statement, which made
incorrect reference to the score, making the mistake appear less
harmful than it was. The statement, later corrected, said ASU
trailed by six points, not four, when Forehan-Kelly made the free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said he doesn't believe the mistake cost ASU the game _
the Sun Devils blew an eight-point lead and had 27 turnovers _
``but we had no chance to win'' after it occurred.
</P>
<P>
   During the weekend, Stanford and Cal took a combined 67 free
throws to 19 for ASU. This isn't the first time for such a
disparity, and Evans is frustrated. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 0046EST &QL; 
