<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-LONGLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGLEY DOES HIS JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Suns are paying 7-foot-2 center Luc Longley an
average of $5.5 million per year over six years to give them a
presence against the Shaquille O'Neals of the world.
</P>
<P>
   He did just that Monday night in the Suns' 97-91 loss to the Los
Angeles Lakers before a sellout crowd that displayed all the
excitement one sees at the grand opening of a pack of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Longley scored a season high 16 points and
corralled eight rebounds, while O'Neal scored 25 points and had
nine boards.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line? O'Neal won the battle and his team the game.
But the point could be made that Longley at least gained a push in
the personal war, because O'Neal wasn't the reason the Suns lost.
</P>
<P>
   The reason pretty much stemmed from getting good looks and the
shots they wanted down the stretch, while displaying an inability
to put the ball in the hole _ or a good-size swimming pool _ at
crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the breaks of the game,'' Longley said. ``It was a fun
game, and we had our looks and chances, and we didn't make them. I
don't think you can cry over spilt milk. We had good shots. They
just didn't go down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played good ball, but we didn't seal the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Longley had 14 of his 16 points in the first half, making 6 of
11 shots, and 10 of those points came in a six-minute stint in the
first quarter. But strangely, he played only 14 minutes in the
first half, while exiting the half with six more points than any of
his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, second-guessers questioned whether Coach Danny Ainge
knows how to use a big center, or if the productive presence of
Clifford Robinson makes it difficult to find more court time for
Longley, who entered the game averaging 23.1 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Longley wasn't one to question his limited usage
while on a first-half roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, in this case I was running out of legs, and Danny
recognized it,'' Longley said. ``It was a sensible coaching move, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal scored 11 of his 25 points after intermission, including
five in the decisive fourth quarter, when the Suns for the most
part disdained double-teaming him. Or perhaps he awakened from the
peaceful slumber he had been taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to have more doubling on him, but the trouble
is, it gives them so many other things,'' Longley said. ``We went a
little bit with single coverage tonight, and he's so strong, I
couldn't really handle him very well down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very strong, and we need to give him different looks.
Hey, we'll get another crack at them in a couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Ainge was pleased with the work and the defense the
Suns got from Longley against O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I though he played real good and did a good job on Shaq, plus
he did a good job offensively for us,'' Ainge said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Longley has a history of playing well against
O'Neal. Last season with Chicago, he averaged 16.5 points and five
boards a game against the Lakers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 0048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
