A4038 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BRUINS-AZ     03-02 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BRUINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM SAYS COYOTES DON'T NEED TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Coyotes can quit wandering the streets and peeking
into phone booths searching for help.
</P>
<P>
   If they're going to get out of the fix they're in _ eight losses
in their past nine games _ they'll have to untie the ropes
themselves and battle the bad guys on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be waiting every day to see if some Superman is going
to come, because Superman ain't coming,'' Coyotes captain Keith
Tkachuk said. ``We've got a good team here. If they want to add
something, great. Until then, I don't want to hear about it, and I
don't want to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Colorado Avalanche acquired All-Star sniper Theo
Fleury from the Calgary Flames, Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith
said his team will probably have to make do with what it has. And
he thinks the Coyotes (30-20-10) are more than qualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen very few examples of teams that have added a
player in March that have put them over the top,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Smith won't necessarily be sitting on his hands as the
NHL's March 23 trading deadline approaches, don't expect a move of
Fleury-size proportions. Smith won't part with young players such
as Shane Doan, Brad Isbister or Daniel Briere, and he won't shell
out a fortune for veterans such as Adam Oates, Mark Recchi or Adam
Graves.
</P>
<P>
   If the Coyotes make a trade, it likely will be a minor one.
There's also a chance they won't make one at all. That's the
message Smith privately delivered to the team a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get up in the morning looking for the sports page,
wondering if you've got a new teammate,'' Smith said. ``We've got a
good enough team to compete with any team in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The players, at least publicly, seemed to be in agreement as
they prepared for tonight's game against the Boston Bruins, the
final game of a brutal seven-game trip in which they have gone a
miserable 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we've got a good team here,'' right wing Jim Cummins
said. ``We've won a lot of games this year with the guys right here
in this locker room. I don't think guys are waiting for a trade.
Bobby tried to make sure that's not in anybody's head, and I don't
think it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a former player, knows it's not an easy sell. Players
know the value of adding someone such as Fleury. They don't care
how it happens and don't consider what effect it could have on the
organization as a whole. They want to win now, not three, four or
five years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith is also smart enough to know he can't squeeze wine out
of lemons. The Coyotes have a bottom-third payroll of about $24
million. Trading away prospects and young players in a
get-rich-quick scheme isn't going to happen here.
</P>
<P>
   At least not until the Coyotes get their own arena. Which begs
the question: If the Coyotes had traded for Fleury, would he have
helped them get their new 20,000-seat arena built?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're still playing on May 18, I don't think it'll hurt our
arena cause,'' Smith said, referring to the upcoming public
referendum vote on the stadium issue. ``But I don't think we can
hinge everything on the arena here. I've talked to Richard (Burke,
the Coyotes' owner) about our agenda and my mandate, and it's not,
`I don't care about next year or the future, let's win the Stanley
Cup this year.' You want to have a strong franchise.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
