<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON: SHORTSTOP DECISION WILL BE HIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Los Angeles Dodgers general manager Kevin
Malone said _ given how 1998 finished _ the shortstop position was
Mark Grudzielanek's to lose.
</P>
<P>
   That might be the case, but Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said
when the time comes to decide between Grudzielanek and Jose
Vizcaino for good, he will do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it be my decision? Yes, it will be my decision,'' Johnson
said Monday. ``Have I made my decision? Maybe. But there could be a
trade. It wouldn't make sense, to me, if we were going to trade an
infielder or a pitcher ... it would be wrong to say this is my
starting five, and then there's a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin is a little more involved than a lot of general
managers, which is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he talked to Grudzielanek and Vizcaino on Sunday.
And though Grudzielanek is expected to be the shortstop when the
Dodgers open Grapefruit League play Friday against St. Louis,
Malone said the job wasn't awarded to Grudzielanek. Malone said he
was simply stating that Grudzielanek, acquired in a high-profile
trade involving Dodgers prospects, had a better finish to the 1998
season _ partly because he was on the field when the season ended.
Vizcaino missed the last few months due to injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no guarantee,'' Malone said. ``The job will go to who
performs the best. It's going to be an organizational decision.
Everybody will have an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins to sign?: Remember Rick Wilkins? The left-handed hitting
catcher who hit 30 homers and batted .303 for the Chicago Cubs in
1993? Well, expect him to join the minor-league pitchers and
catchers when they report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins, who lives in Jacksonville, showed up at an open tryout
at Dodgertown on Monday. And the Dodgers brain trust saw enough to
talk contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a guy like that who has major-league experience,
you have to see what they have left in determination, and by their
will and spirit,'' said assistant to the general manager Bill
Geivett, who oversees player development for the Dodgers. ``They're
going to be judged by how much they want it, and he got in a car at
4 a.m. and drove here for this tryout.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's premature to talk about Wilkins making the
major-league roster, an experienced backup catcher is something the
Dodgers desperately need. Add in his left-handed bat and his
experience, and health might be the only question.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Wilkins, 32, split time with the New York Mets and
Seattle but batted .179 in 24 games. However, he had bone chips
removed from his neck in the fall and appears to be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I remember of him is his 30 bombs,'' Malone said. ``It's
really no risk unless Billy and the other (minor-league personnel)
feel he's not healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's absence getting serious: Closer Jeff Shaw remains at his
Ohio home waiting for his wife, Julie, to give birth to their third
child. While the Dodgers have told him not to report until after
the birth, Johnson said it's close to becoming a serious situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say he needs to be here at the end of this week,''
Johnson said. ``I'd like to see him here by this weekend,
especially with games starting up.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Johnson did find a comical side to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe she's only eight months pregnant,'' Johnson said. ``If
this is the third child, maybe their calculations are off.''
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Intrasquad games begin today. The one
notable pitcher to be used is left-hander Greg Cadaret, who Johnson
said will work one inning.... Tom Lasorda is expected to arrive
Thursday... Minor-league pitcher Randy Galvez underwent ``Tommy
John'' surgery Monday in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
