<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON SERVES UP FLASHBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Diamondbacks left-hander  &UR; Brian Anderson picked up
where he left off in 1998 during the club's first intrasquad game
of the spring.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the starters, he had good control but couldn't keep
the ball in the yard. Newcomer  &UR; Greg Colbrunn sent a solo shot deep
to left field that landed near the top of the grass berm at Tucson
Electric Park.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Anderson tied Colorado's  &UR; Pedro Astacio for the
National League lead in home runs allowed with 39, and 26 of them
were with nobody on base.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the flashback, Anderson said he felt good while throwing
two innings in the near record heat that hovered in the mid-80s.
His fastball was buzzing a bit faster than that, Manager  &UR; Buck
 &UR; Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to have more pop to it than last year,'' Showalter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I am a little faster,'' he said. ``I did a lot of work
during the off-season. I cut down on the body fat a little and feel
stronger, so hopefully, that will help.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a fastball that Colbrunn hit, Anderson said, but a
change-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was over the plate but down, and he went and got it,''
Anderson said. ``He's a good hitter. He makes good adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Another adjustment that the burly Colbrunn will have to make is
in his handshake as he rounds third base, according to third-base
coach  &UR; Brian Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little weak, but I'm sure it will get better,''
Butterfield said. ``Next time, I want to feel it for a couple of
days.'' &QL; 
Chouinard gone &QL; 
In order to make room for trade acquisition  &UR; Tony Womack on the
40-man roster, the team designated right-handed middle reliever
 &UR; Bobby &UR; Chouinard for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard was claimed off waivers from Milwaukee on June 1, and
he was 0-2 in 26 games, including two starts. If he clears waivers,
the Diamondbacks likely will re-sign him and assign him to Triple-A
Tucson. &QL; 
The first time &QL; 
Right-handers  &UR; Brad Penny and  &UR; John Patterson and left-hander
 &UR; Nick &UR; Bierbrodt, the team's three young pitching phenoms, got their
first work in game conditions in the big league camp.
</P>
<P>
   Penny was the most impressive, throwing two hitless innings,
walking one man and striking out two. Patterson gave up a run on
two hits, walked one and struck out two in two innings. Bierbrodt
wasn't as fortunate, giving up three runs on five hits. All three
runs came on a home run by  &UR; Hanley Frias, who is making a bid for
one of the utility infield spots. &QL; 
Let's play another &QL; 
The second of the team's two intrasquad games will be played at 1
p.m. today at the minor league complex on the north side of Ajo
Way, opposite Tucson Electric Park. The game is open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled starters are right-hander  &UR; Armando Reynoso, a
free-agent signee, and non-roster right-hander  &UR; Dan Carlson, who
pitched for the San Francisco Giants' Triple-A affiliate when it
was in Phoenix. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
