<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-NELSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL OFFICE ACQUIRES GEM IN D-BACKS' NELSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While reading the Diamondbacks notes last week, you may have
noticed the item about Ralph Nelson leaving the club to take a job
with the commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Even to the most impassioned Diamondbacks fan, it probably meant
very little. After all, Nelson has never won a Diamondbacks game
with a diving catch or a clutch hit. He's never even worn the
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been one of the most valuable members of the
organization, dating to his hiring two full years before the club's
first regular-season game.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was one of the half-dozen or so front-office people who
routinely worked 16-hour days and seven days a week in the year
leading to the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a big part of this organization, especially with the
expansion draft,'' Manager Buck Showalter said. ``He's a guy you
can always call on to get something done.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he will become a guy the commissioner's office will count on
to straighten out one of the most glaring problems in the game _
umpiring. It's no secret that umpiring has come under intense
criticism the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Missed calls when it matters most, during postseason, have
resulted in the game being tarnished. Like it or not, baseball
needs to take a more proactive approach with its umpires, and Sandy
Alderson, Commissioner Bud Selig's handpicked man to oversee these
changes, is tackling the issue head-on.
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business for Alderson, longtime general
manager of the Oakland Athletics who is generally recognized as one
of the sharpest men in the game, was to go after someone he trusts
and could put in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was his first and only choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major League Baseball and Sandy Alderson's gain is the
Diamondbacks' loss,'' said agent Jeff Moorad, who represents
Diamondbacks Matt Williams and Travis Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you lose an experienced mind like Ralph Nelson's,
it's a loss. I think it's a perfect next step for him to join the
commissioner's office. To have Sandy Alderson reach out for you is
the ultimate compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, Nelson played what can arguably be called the
biggest role in the signing of Lee 2{ years ago. Moorad, who had
never dealt with Jerry Colangelo, didn't have a way to gauge the
seriousness of the team's interest when Lee became a loophole free
agent in the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Moorad said he had received one cursory phone call from General
Manager Joe Garagiola Jr., but little else. Lee was close to
signing with either St. Louis or the New York Yankees when Nelson
made a call to Moorad, a longtime friend, who was astonished to
learn how seriously Arizona wanted Lee.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Nelson's involvement turned Lee toward the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's office plans to take a season to review
umpires before it takes control over them. Currently, each league
has authority over the umpires in its league. You can bet this will
become a sticky issue at some point. You can also bet that Alderson
did not pick someone incapable of handling such duties.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, whose last day with the Diamondbacks will be Friday, is
a former NCAA basketball official. He has been involved in baseball
for more than 20 years, first spending time with the San Francisco
Giants, rising to assistant general manager under the meticulous
and respected Al Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing where this organization is heading, Nelson leaves
the Diamondbacks with a heavy heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked with some of the best people in the game, and I'm
going to work for one of the very best in Sandy Alderson,'' he
said. ``But there is no one in the game that I admire more than
Buck Showalter, and I mean that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always going to work harder when you're working for
people you respect and admire. They make a decision and never look
back. It's not like this everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson and baseball are counting on Nelson taking the same
tack with its umpires _ a decision they never want to look back at.
The bet here is that everyone in baseball will be thanking Nelson
one day. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
