<HEADLINE>
PAIN OF FATAL ACCIDENT LINGERS FOR D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Back to business, yes. As usual, no. It couldn't be _
it won't be _ for quite a while.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Diamondbacks were still dazed by Sunday's car
crash that killed minor league pitcher Ken Robinson. The driver,
minor league pitcher John Rosengren, was booked into Pima County
Jail on second-degree murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see the guys out there, but it's not going to
take the pain away,'' said Tommy Jones, the Diamondbacks' director
of minor league operations, who was watching the big club's first
intrasquad game of the spring at Tucson Electric Park.
</P>
<P>
   A large banner, with white letters on a black backdrop, hung
over the top of the right-field fence and served as a stark
reminder: DRIVING DRUNK WILL PUT YOUR LIGHTS OUT.
</P>
<P>
   Officers investigating the one-vehicle rollover on the city's
northwest side said Rosengren displayed symptoms of alcohol
impairment. A blood sample was taken, but the results won't be
available for a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Rosengren was released on a $75,000 bond Sunday night, checked
out of the Diamondbacks' minor league hotel and was with his
parents in the Tucson area Monday. He is not allowed to leave Pima
County. His next court appearance will be March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks officials said an autopsy for Robinson is scheduled
for Monday. Robinson was pronounced dead at the accident scene.
Investigators said Robinson suffered severe head trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials said funeral services likely will be held later
this week in Jacksonville, Fla., where Robinson lived with his wife
and 1-year-old son. Mel Didier, special assistant to Diamondbacks
General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr., is expected to represent the
club at the services. Garagiola is in Korea on team business.
</P>
<P>
   The accident brought flashbacks to team President Rich Dozer,
who, shortly after graduating from the University of Arizona in
1979, rolled his truck about five times after he fell asleep at the
wheel on Interstate 10 between Tucson and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cab was crushed, and it took several semi-truck drivers to
lift the truck up so I could get out,'' Dozer said. ``I still don't
see how I survived. I was lucky, very lucky, but these two guys
weren't. It's devastating. Our hearts go out to both families, in
particular the Robinson family.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozer said the club has not suspended Rosengren ``because we
don't know all the facts. He wants to try to take a step back and
get his life in order as best he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Clint Sodowsky wants to help Rosengren. The two were
teammates in the Detroit Tigers' minor league system in 1994 and
1995, and after the 1995 season, they played together in the
Arizona Fall League. They lived in the same apartment complex, and
Sodowsky often drove Rosengren to the park because Rosengren didn't
have a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be judgmental would be very hypocritical for most of us
here. We've all made mistakes,'' Sodowsky said. ``You ache for
Kenny's family, but Rosey needs support, too. I'd like to visit
him, but it probably would be kind of awkward. I'm sure he's
confused and scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know his parents. He's intelligent, very smart. On the
field, he had good stuff, especially for a lefty. He just needed a
little more control. He was working very hard on that. All he
wanted was to pitch in the big leagues, and he was very hard on
himself, as I'm sure he's being very hard on himself right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball has a substance-abuse policy for its
players, but it is not made public under the collective bargaining
agreement. The Diamondbacks have a separate policy and program for
its minor leaguers, coaches and non-field staff. Club attorneys
would not released details, citing confidentiality, but Dozer said
it is wide-ranging and covers many health issues.
</P>
<P>
   The club has a team support coordinator, John Michael, who meets
with players throughout the minor league system each spring and
during the season. He also assists the major leaguers and attends
most home games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important,'' Michael said. ``I'm on call 24 hours a
day and usually will go to where the situation calls for me to be.
And if I can't get there, I have a referral list of contacts in the
particular areas.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
