<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4046 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HAMPTON-HN     03-02 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HAMPTON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ If baseball's regular season were cut in half,
Mike Hampton probably would have a Cy Young Award hanging on his
wall.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1997, Hampton won a major-league-best 11 games and had a
sterling 2.53 ERA after the All-Star break. Last season, he won his
first four starts and had seven victories by the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the season always seems to get in Hampton's
way. But after seeing how both halves live over two straight
seasons, Hampton believes he has found a solution to putting a
complete year together.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, you tend to go through lapses that last two,
three or four starts,'' the 26-year-old Astros lefthander said.
``Hopefully, I've learned enough so that won't happen again. It's a
big key for me to not only put a full year of consistency together
but to also do it throughout my career. I've been getting better,
and it's time for me to take that next step, take my game to the
next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton enters this spring as the No. 2 starter in the Astros'
rotation behind Shane Reynolds. A control pitcher who doesn't
overpower hitters, Hampton has won at least 10 games in each of the
past three seasons, cramming a majority of the success into one
half or the other. Astros management believes he's capable of
delivering 15 to 17 victories annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been ups and downs,'' manager Larry Dierker said.
``Just like the stock market, there are going to be some down days,
but generally it's been going up the last few years. That's the way
Mike's progress has been, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Not before he took a plunge. Hampton felt like things couldn't
get any worse during the first half of the 1997 season, when he
started 4-7 and his ERA skyrocketed to 5.19. The front office
considered demoting him to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the toughest year I've ever had in baseball,''
Hampton said. ``The first 2{ months I was miserable, and I learned
quite a bit about myself. You start questioning yourself: `Man,
have I lost it? Where's it at?' I think the biggest thing is not to
get out of your game for one minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton proceeded to reel off a career-best seven-game winning
streak that included two shutouts. He went 11-3 following the '97
All-Star break and finished with 15 victories, the most by an
Astros lefthander since Jim Deshaies won 15 in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The success continued at the beginning of last season, when
Hampton became the National League's first five-game winner and
went 7-2 through May.
</P>
<P>
   But a strained left groin in mid-June forced Hampton to go on
the 15-day disabled list, and things were never the same. Battling
control problems, he went 3-3 over his final 16 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really knocked his season,'' Dierker said. ``Control is
the key to his success. He has plenty of good pitches, but he
doesn't have any one pitch that just absolutely overpowers hitters.
He relies on control, and when you sit out two or three weeks, it's
hard to fine-tune things.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Hampton has drawn comparisons to Atlanta
lefthander Tom Glavine, who earned his second NL Cy Young Award
last year. Neither has overpowering stuff, with their fastballs
ranging between 86 and 90 mph. They rely on an array of off-speed
pitches to coax batters into ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got at least as good of stuff as Tom Glavine, if not
better,'' Dierker said. ``Which isn't too bad since Glavine won the
Cy Young.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the past two seasons when Hampton worked with veteran
catcher Brad Ausmus, he will have to make adjustments this year
with rookie Mitch Meluskey projected to see a considerable amount
of playing time. Hampton has already begun discussing strategy with
Meluskey this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some adjusting on my part and a lot of
adjustment on his part being in the big leagues,'' Hampton said.
``With Brad out there last year, it took a lot of the equation out
of it, a lot of the thinking process. We worked so well together.
Very rarely did I ever have to shake (off pitches), because we were
thinking so much alike. It's tough to replace that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, however, insists the change may have a positive effect
on the entire pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brad was like having a Linus blanket something that makes you
feel comfortable,'' Dierker said. ``Now, they have to evaluate what
they are doing and why, rather than depend on somebody else to do
it. That could really turn out to make him (Hampton) even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hampton: ``The ultimate decision comes down to me making
the pitch, and it's the pitch I want to throw. If I give up a home
run or make a mistake with that pitch, who's to blame? There's no
one else to look at but myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
