<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4047 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-02 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IN the three weeks that passed between encounters by the Rockets
and Lakers at the star-studded Forum, much had transpired. Not the
least of which was the Rockets' having run up enough frequent-flier
miles to earn them all free round trips to Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, that's the neighborhood where the Lakers had
gone to shop for a new power forward and stabilizing influence for
their fractured team.
</P>
<P>
   Word has it that with Dennis Rodman on board, the Lakers' locker
room will now have a cover charge and two-drink minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful what you wish for.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still not a championship team,'' Charles Barkley said
Sunday after the Lakers hung a Rodman tattoo of 106-90 on the
Rockets. ``They're not the next great thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you tell? Well, for one thing, their record (10-6) is
about the same as ours (8-6).''
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question: Which team do you like better?
</P>
<P>
   Utah, of course. Trick answer.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not to say the Rockets should be all that unhappy
with their current standing in the middle of the Western Conference
pack.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that they have now weathered the most difficult stretch
of this compressed schedule _ nine games in 13 days, seven cities,
three time zones and two countries _ with a respectable, if not
fearsome, 4-5 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that it's going to get a whole lot better the rest of the
way, but I'm sure glad that's over,'' said coach Rudy Tomjanovich.
``We saw some good things and went through some tough stretches. I
can't say that I'm worried or disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because nearly a month into the season, the Rockets are
still fitting all of their parts together like one of those jigsaw
puzzles with 1,000 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley returned to the lineup in LA after having arthroscopic
surgery on his left knee and played like a man who had been off for
two weeks. He labored to get up and down the floor. He did not have
explosiveness in his legs. He missed layups. But give him a couple
of games on a healthy knee to knock the rust off, and the 15
rebounds and 15 or so points a game will return.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Carr, the Big Dawg, also made his belated season debut,
increasing the barnyard element on the Rockets' bench, which
already boasted a Pig (Miller) and a Cat (Cuttino Mobley). The
coming weeks should also see the return of Rodrick Rhodes and
Stanley Roberts, and only then will we see the real team the
Rockets have assembled to make their playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said all along that this was a group that wouldn't
produce our best results until May,'' said Rudy T. ``Even if we
hadn't had all of the injuries, this was going to be a slow
building process because of all the new faces and the lack of
training camp and practice time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see things that I like. But for the most part, they come in
brief flashes. Our guys are still settling in and learning each
other. They have the basics down but not the little things like the
exact comfort zones where different guys like to get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the Rockets could be like tonight's opponent,
their Lone Star cousin Spurs, who are currently dead in the water
at 6-8 with no excuses of significant core changes or injuries to
fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a nagging aspect to the Rockets so far, it is this
troubling habit of too many of their guns constantly deferring to
each other on offense. It is, at times, like watching a bad comedy
skit in which the characters constantly bow and say, ``After you.
No, after you.''
</P>
<P>
   You expect such behavior from rookies. But the truth is that
Mobley, Bryce Drew and Michael Dickerson have not often been shy
about shooting.
</P>
<P>
   It is Hakeem Olajuwon who needs to force himself more often into
his old rhythms. Of spinning this way and that way, of going from
the jump hook in the lane to the Dream Shake on the baseline, of
using one move to set up the next move and getting on rolls that
force the defense to adjust and then open up avenues for his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   It is Scottie Pippen who must stop constantly telling us and
himself that he's no longer playing the triangle offense of the
Bulls. We know the offense is different. Now, go find your spots
and attack them aggressively. Finish off plays. Make layups. Don't
whine. Pippen said Barkley embarrassed himself Sunday, but it is
Scottie who is a tentative 10-for-36 vs. the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, what we know about the Rockets now is what we knew
when the season started Feb. 5. They are a work in progress, still
full of more potential than results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
