<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAILY NEWS PRINTS PORTIONS OF ABC'S INTERVIEW WITH MS. LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - In a move that compromises the exclusivity of what is
expected to be the biggest television interview of the year, The
Daily News on Tuesday printed large portions of ABC's highly
anticipated interview with Monica Lewinsky, which is scheduled to
be broadcast on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The interview, conducted last month by Barbara Walters, has been
of enormous importance to ABC, which expanded its regular news
program ``20/20'' to two hours from one hour and sold commercials
in the program for as much as $800,000, a figure unmatched for
anything on television but the Super Bowl and the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News acquired a one-hour audio tape of Ms. Walters'
interview with Ms. Lewinsky on Monday through an anonymous source.
It was delivered to Eric Mink, the television writer for the News,
who sought and received confirmation from an ABC news executive
that the tape was authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Mink said on Monday night that the tape did not come though the
mail but was delivered to his desk. It was accompanied by only a
brief printed message describing the tape as the first hour of the
Lewinsky interview.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Murphy, the spokeswoman for ABC News, said on Monday
night that she had confirmed to Mink that the tape did contain
authentic portions of Ms. Walters's interview with Ms. Lewinsky.
She said the tape was ``an unedited portion of the interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Murphy would not speculate on how The Daily News might have
acquired the tape. But ABC executives acknowledged on Monday night
that the company has had recent problems with union members. Last
Friday, ABC unilaterally implemented terms of a new contract that
affected union members, including engineers who work in the news
division. That action was bitterly opposed by union members.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Murphy did say that lawyers for ABC informed The Daily News
that the paper `'was publishing portions of our interview at legal
risk.'' Ms. Murphy said ABC's lawyers told The News it was
potentially violating copyright laws by publishing material owned
by and under copyright to ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Mink said that lawyers for The Daily News were ``involved all
day in the process'' of writing and editing the story about the
interview, which Mink co-wrote with another Daily News reporter,
Helen Kennedy. The story was not accompanied by a transcript of the
tape, Mink said.
</P>
<P>
   Mink acknowledged that ABC had expressed its unhappiness about
the newspaper's plans to print a story based on the tape, but he
added, ``I don't believe ABC is really concerned. All this does is
create more publicity for their interview. Most of this story has
already been heard anyway, in front of the grand jury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
