<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SUNS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BEAT SUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ If it takes a village to rear a child, it apparently
takes a few village elders to rear a team of them.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Rambis has the Los Angeles Lakers' head-coach title now,
but he's polling the village for help with his young team, and the
elders delivered both wisdom and points down the stretch Monday to
pace the Lakers' hard-fought 97-91 victory over the Phoenix Suns at
America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven-year-old Derek Harper was buzzing in one ear,
38-year-old Dennis Rodman in the other, and the result was the
Lakers' fourth straight win and third under Rambis' village
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Harper? He called his own play, then hit the 3-pointer that gave
the Lakers the lead for good with 1:08 remaining. Rodman? He was,
get this, telling Rambis when to make !ital!defensive
substitutions!off! in the waning seconds of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis, only a few years older than either of them, listened and
won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just telling him, in certain situations you put
defensive players in, you put offensive players in,'' Rodman said,
``and we did that down the stretch. He's a young coach and I don't
think he thinks on that level yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis is thankful he has coach Worm to turn to.
</P>
<P>
   And when Rodman wasn't directing, he was collecting a
season-high 16 rebounds and seven points, including his first three
field goals of the season. And when crunch time came, the Lakers
down by seven to open the fourth quarter, Rodman was at his best,
delivering six rebounds and five points in the final frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is he a great defensive player and an unbelievable
rebounder,'' Rambis said, ``but I'll tell you what, that guy knows
more about basketball than probably about 99.9 percent of the
people on the planet. He just understands the game. He's always
thinking out there. I'm so happy the Lakers got him on this
ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Lakers are undefeated to date in the post-Del Harris
era and have beaten back-to-back playoff contenders, this was in
most respects not a game for the archives.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers committed 19 turnovers and through three quarters had
shot 42.9 percent _ with Kobe Bryant, Eddie Jones and Rick Fox
combining to go 8 for 28.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Luc Longley _ Luc Longley _ went for a season-high 16
points on them, and Tom Gugliotta gave the Lakers a 20-point,
nine-rebound reminder why they wanted him for their own.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers' own offensive juggernaut had come to a crawl
with a 16-point third quarter that tied their lowest-scoring period
this season. They bounced back with a 36-point fourth quarter _
their highest-scoring of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But it started with defense, usually Rodman's.
</P>
<P>
   And it ended, effectively, with Harper's called shot. The ball
went inside to Shaquille O'Neal, who dished back out to Harper for
the 3-pointer that gave the Lakers the 87-85 edge, just as Harper
scripted it to Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confident that I could knock it down, so it worked
out,'' said Harper, who hit 7 of 9, with four 3-pointers, for 18
points.
</P>
<P>
   As for the coaching double-team Rodman and Rambis provided? ``I
think this team was lacking stability,'' Harper said, ``and by
adding the two of us, it definitely helps our team.''
</P>
<P>
   They were steady down the stretch. Rodman provided a free throw
after getting fouled on a defensive rebound. O'Neal grabbed a
defensive board for a long pass to Fox for an easy layup. O'Neal
snatched a loose ball from Jason Kidd and drew another foul and a
free throw. Overall, the kind of night when it was apparent both
teams had played 24 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a grind-out game,'' Rambis said. ``I thought our team
was tired, their team was tired. Nobody's going to videotape that
(as a) game on how to play beautiful basketball. The guys did what
they had to do late in the game to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
