</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT CREDITS RAMBIS FOR TURNAROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Everyone has a theory on the Los Angeles Lakers'
one-week turnaround, from a team losing three straight to a team
winning four in a row: Dennis Rodman's arrival. The removal of
coach Del Harris. The team meeting after the loss at Vancouver.
Maybe all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   But Kobe Bryant said the key element in the turnaround is new
coach Kurt Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what to do now,'' Bryant said. ``Rambis is very big on
roles.... Everybody has particular roles that were unclear
before.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's referring not just to the interaction among the
starting five but every player, one through 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``From top to bottom, I think everybody is a little more
comfortable,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Rambis said he and his coaches haven't really
changed anything, though it seems the messages are getting through
with more regularity now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not telling them anything different now, really, than
what they were hearing before,'' he said. ``And I still think it
was an untimely firing of Del.... It was starting to turn the
corner (during the Vancouver game).... You just gotta believe that
with Dennis coming, things would have turned around for the better,
just like they have now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant firmly believes the coaching change, as much as
Rodman's arrival, did the trick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a load taken off our shoulders, because of the
situation we were in. It was a very tentative situation with Del,
we all knew that,'' he said. ``You bring Dennis in here, Del moves
on with his career, it was just, whew. It just lifted a weight off
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Case closed: Rodman was fined an undisclosed sum for arriving 30
minutes late to Saturday's practice, Rambis said, and he hopes
that's the final word on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   At least, of course, until Rodman's next infraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was late for practice, he was fined accordingly, and that's
just the end of it as far as I'm concerned,'' Rambis said testily.
``Everything is fine. We handle those situations internally.... To
me it's just a nonissue.''
</P>
<P>
   Dribbles: Rambis said he hasn't spoken with Harris since he was
fired last week. The two spoke briefly at the time, but a couple of
phone calls to Harris have so far gone unreturned. ``I just wanted
to say a few things to him,'' Rambis said. ``I know it was hard for
him to get fired.... Cotton Fitzsimmons told me a long time ago,
coaches are hired to be fired. So I'm the next Laker coach to get
fired.'' ... Robert Horry, once a starter but now backing up both
forward positions, played just three minutes, his lowest of the
season in a game for which he's been healthy. Corie Blount, who had
been averaging 12 minutes, has gone two games without playing....
The Suns are 8-6 but have yet to beat a team with a winning record
this season.... Lakers backup center Elden Campbell has the flu and
did not travel with the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
