<HEADER>
A4060 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      03-02 1548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATE AND A FASTBALL: LOSING DAD LET MESA FIND BIG LEAGUE CALLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Jose Mesa, No. 49 on your Mariners scorecard, is
not sure what number he is on his father's family roster. He might
be the 19th of Narciso Mesa's 25 children. He could be No. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa knows he's the 12th of 15 children his father had with his
mother. He also knows that the only reason he's in America, earning
millions of dollars to pitch the last inning of close baseball
games, is because his father died when Mesa was a boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt,'' Mesa said. ``Maybe when I was an old man,
like 20-some years old, I would have started playing, but I would
have been too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard thing that he died, because I had to start
working when I was 9 years old to support my younger three
brothers. But I guess God wanted him to die, because he wanted me
to play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Narciso was physically imposing, just as Jose would become. At
6-foot-3 and at least 200 pounds, he was, in Jose's words, ``a
strong dude.'' He never played baseball, but he'd seen many
Dominican youths become injured doing so. For a man who made a
living through physical labor as a farmer, this was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   But the game was alluring to Jose. He and his brothers would tie
up socks and sneak into the streets to play ball. The consequences
were grave if Narciso found out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime that he found me playing baseball, I've got to run or
he'll grab whatever he can grab and whip my ass with it,'' Mesa
said. ``I got to run when I see him coming. I was scared.''
</P>
<P>
   When a stroke killed Narciso at age 44 in 1976, Jose took his
place in the fields, working with the cows, mules and horses,
harvesting the watermelons, bananas and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   At idle moments, he would pick up rocks and hurl them at mango
or coconut trees in the distance. He was keeping his arm limber,
because he finally was free to play ball.
</P>
<P>
   One day, when Mesa was 15, a cousin came roaring by his house on
a motorcycle. It was midday, and Mesa, who had been working in the
fields at dawn, was taking a nap. The cousin told him a scout from
the Toronto Blue Jays wanted to see him, and he'd better hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa threw on his uniform _ he didn't take a shower _ and rushed
to meet the scout, Epy Guerrero, who had a contract ready for
another player. One look at Mesa's arm, and Guerrero forgot the
other guy.
</P>
<P>
   On Halloween in 1981, Mesa began his professional career. The
really scary stuff would happen 16 years later.
</P>
<P>
   MAN ON A MISSION
</P>
<P>
   The man the Mariners signed as their closer was not a closer
last year. He has not been a closer since failing to save the
biggest game of all, Game 7 of the 1997 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners tried to re-sign Mike Timlin, but were shocked when
Baltimore offered him four years and $16 million. So they turned to
Mesa, offering a two-year deal for $6.45 million, with an option
for a third year. Mesa had a three-year offer from his last team,
the San Francisco Giants, but that was to be a setup man.
</P>
<P>
   Believing he has plenty of good years left as a closer, the
32-year-old Mesa chose Seattle. He has lost a mile or two off his
fastball, thrown regularly at 96 mph while saving 46 of 48 games
for the Cleveland Indians in 1995, but he's impressed the M's so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa pumped heat to David Segui in batting practice Monday, and
pitch after pitch, Segui nodded or barked out in approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to be just a straight power pitcher, but he's learned
to move the ball now,'' said Segui, who has known Mesa since their
days as minor leaguers in the Orioles' system. ``The thing that
impresses me most is he's not scared on the mound. He's not
intimidated, he's going to come after you. That's what you want in
a closer. He has a good arm, and he's not afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says Mesa must be a wreck after what he has
gone through since December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In order, Mesa has been tried and acquitted on rape charges,
closed out the Indians' AL pennant, blown the save in the last game
of the World Series, lost his closer's job, gotten booed out of
town by Cleveland fans and been traded.
</P>
<P>
   But a crisis of confidence? Not so, said Indians bullpen coach
Luis Isaac.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mental toughness is still there,'' Isaac said. ``I know
him. Sometimes you need a new place, and I think this is going to
be a great place for him. Knowing Jose the way I know him, for him
it's going to be a mission to prove to everyone he still can be a
premier closer in baseball. I think the Seattle Mariners are going
to get the benefit of that.''
</P>
<P>
   NOW, IT'S FAMILY FIRST
</P>
<P>
   Mesa brushes off the confidence question. He is comforted by his
faith _ his knowledge _ that everything happens for a reason. He
uses an analogy of a flat tire. You might think a flat tire is a
bad thing, he said, but how do you know it didn't save you from a
horrible accident just down the road?
</P>
<P>
   As it is with his father's death, Mesa believes his personal and
professional trials in Cleveland the last two years were part of a
larger plan.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, Mesa was found not guilty of charges of rape,
felonious assault, theft and two counts of gross sexual imposition.
He faced up to 20 years in prison and wept in the courtroom after
the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa believes he was set up, and that the circumstances could
have happened to anyone. But he also believes God was telling him
something. The man who grew up surrounded by family needed to focus
on his wife and five children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've changed a lot of things, off the field and everywhere,''
Mesa said. ``You've got to change from that situation. ... You've
got to think about it and think about your family. They're the most
important thing in my life. Anytime that you think you're going to
be away from your family for a long time and stay somewhere else,
it's tough to think like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa still owns a home in Cleveland, but he's trying to sell it.
He hopes to buy a home in Florida, and dreams of his 13-year-old
son, Juan Jose, getting a scholarship someday to the University of
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa also has a home in the Dominican, and chose to spend the
whole winter there for the first time in years. He decided not to
play winter ball, and engrossed himself in the lives of his
children. It was, Mesa said, the best time of his life.
</P>
<P>
   He would take his kids with him every morning to an Olympic
sports facility in the Dominican, with six baseball fields, a
track, basketball and volleyball courts to keep them busy while
Jose and a brother worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks into spring training, he said he misses his kids ``so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime that you can spend time with your family every day,''
Mesa said, ``those are the good times that you never regret.''
</P>
<P>
   LOST JOB, NEW HOME
</P>
<P>
   It was Game 7 of the '97 World Series, and Mesa, warming in the
bullpen to hold the Indians' 2-1 lead, never looked better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching the same guy that saved 46 games in 1995,''
Isaac said. ``Oh, my God. He was throwing 95-96 (mph), good slider
and two-seamer, his sinker was real good. Something happened
between the bullpen and the mound that I couldn't help.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa allowed a leadoff single, recorded a strikeout, then gave
up another single and a sacrifice fly that tied the game. Both hits
came off the slider, which is not Mesa's best pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your best pitch is your fastball,'' he said, ``that's
what you've got to die with.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans cheered Mesa at the airport, but he skipped the downtown
rally for the AL champs, wanting only to stay in the house.
</P>
<P>
   He thought things would be fine in spring training, when Indians
manager Mike Hargrove assured him the closer's job was his. But on
opening night, against the M's at the Kingdome, Hargrove called him
into his office. Mesa thought he'd been traded, but the news was
worse. Mike Jackson was named closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're used to being a closer and then you lose it and you
stay with the same team, that makes it tougher on you and makes it
harder on your head,'' Mesa said. ``Every time it's the ninth
inning, you know that's your situation and you're not there.''
</P>
<P>
   He was shaky early, then dismal as the season wore on. His
earned run average at Jacobs Field was 7.16, more than four runs
worse than at all other ballparks. Fans booed him incessantly, and
while Mesa downplayed their impact, teammates knew better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're human, it has to bother you,'' said Mariners
infielder David Bell, who spent most of last year with Cleveland.
``... He couldn't do anything (without a reaction), and it's a long
run from the bullpen to the mound with a sold-out crowd so loud and
abusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa said he has no doubt he would still be with Cleveland had
he gotten two more outs that muggy Miami night. But everything
happens for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what keeps me going,'' Mesa said. ``Maybe God wanted me
to go over here, go in against the Cleveland Indians and clinch the
division, maybe go to the World Series and win it with the Seattle
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know. Maybe he didn't want me to win with the
Cleveland Indians. That's what happened. God can provide that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
