A4075 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     03-02 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOATED IOC DUE FOR A SLICE OF HUMBLE PIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ I have no firsthand knowledge of the tawdry bribes
that have plunged the entire Olympic movement into a state of gross
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   If Salt Lake tucked $1.2 million in free plane tickets, ski
vacations and surgical procedures into the pockets of IOC members
and if geishas and antique swords were being doled out in Nagano, I
did not see it.
</P>
<P>
   However, if the Olympics are a public trust, if the Olympics
truly do belong to everyone, I suppose that is why I felt slightly
envious of the lush amenities provided to IOC officials last
February during the 1998 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   While athletes and, yes, lowly journalists were housed in Nagano
apartments with sleeping quarters roughly the size of dog kennels _
albeit exceptionally clean kennels _ the IOC royalty got its usual
first-class suites, gourmet dinners and goodness knows what else.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, I now admit, I walked through the cold streets of
Nagano one night in search of the Kokusai Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   A friend, Olympics writer Mark Starr of Newsweek, had told me
about the four-star French restaurant housed at the hotel and how
IOC officials were feasting on haute cuisine nightly. After a week
of soba noodles and broiled salmon heads, news like this made me
shudder.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with my Post-Intelligencer American Express card, I was
determined to have a dinner fitting of an IOC member.
</P>
<P>
   The Kokusai was exactly what you would expect. Lots of granite
and marble. Lots of security. Lots of European, African, Asian and
North American Olympic ``family'' members roaming around in
expensive ski jackets and fur coats.
</P>
<P>
   It took no time to determine that the four-star French
restaurant in question was off-limits to anyone who did not rub
elbows directly with Samaranch. I then found myself at the entrance
of the Kokusai's quietly elegant Chinese restaurant, where I
smilingly weaseled my way in for one very sumptuous meal.
</P>
<P>
   I remember feeling not the least bit guilty about my fellow
journalists back at the Main Press Center who were slogging through
another bowl of miso ramen. It was then that I realized I had the
constitutional makeup of an IOC member.
</P>
<P>
   What do fine dinners and luxury hotels have to do with the
Olympics?
</P>
<P>
   That is a very good question, just as it is a good question as
to what free college tuition, Super Bowl parties and profitable
land deals have to do with a city's ability to put on the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has to answer these questions once and for all, or risk
losing its remaining integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, the foxes still are guarding the Olympic hen house.
But Monday, a ray of hope shone on the shamed Olympic movement. A
commission headed by former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell
said reform was needed. The IOC will meet March 17 in Switzerland,
where the Olympic organization is expected to deal with its mess.
</P>
<P>
   They had better make it good. And fast.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, with its quaint and quirky sense of self _ I mean it
as a compliment _ there is no issue about what ethical and
practical reforms the IOC and U.S. Olympic Committee must make.
</P>
<P>
   In December, just before the Salt Lake bombshell hit, Seattle
begged out of the bidding process for the 2012 Summer Games, citing
a giant case of Not in My Backyard _ and I mean it as a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is something inherently wonderful about an
Olympics. Despite the daunting task of putting one on, the
monumental effort and risks involved, there is little doubt that
the Olympics is an undertaking many American cities/regions still
eagerly desire.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, I talked with organizers from four of the eight U.S.
cities bidding to host the 2012 Olympics. All agreed that nothing
but good will come out of this round of tawdry revelations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are the games still valuable? No question,'' said Nick Vehr,
president of Cincinnati 2012 Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was anybody who wasn't aware of the
high-level entertainment involved in bidding for an Olympics, but
very few were aware of the other inappropriate activity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad the system for hosting something as valued as the
Olympics has eroded. But our view is ... the outcome of this
process will be that cities are awarded the Olympics on a level
playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Bay Area bid coordinator Susan Loder had a
suggestion: ``We hope that in the future the cities that are
selected are done so in a completely objective fashion. It should
almost be like an SAT test,'' Loder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be a list of 100 categories and you get 50 points
per category if your city fulfills that requirement. If you have
more hotel rooms than required, your city would get an extra 10
points and so on. Then cities will know exactly how they stack
up.''
</P>
<P>
   With reform suggestions like that, it is more than time to send
the IOC foxes back to their rooms ... with no dinner or geishas or
swords or land deals.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
