<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE REINSTATES MINOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Junior guard Greg Minor was reinstated to the Cal
State Northridge men's basketball team Monday after meeting with
the team and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Minor will travel with the team to the Big Sky Conference
Tournament, which starts Thursday night at Ogden, Utah.
Fourth-seeded CSUN (17-11) plays fifth-seeded Montana State (15-12)
at 8:15 p.m. PST.
</P>
<P>
   Rico Harris, who was suspended along with Minor last week for
what CSUN head coach Bobby Braswell termed ``conduct detrimental to
the team,'' did not meet with the team and coaches Monday evening
and remains under suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Minor, who played at Canyon High, had been a key for the
Matadors off the bench the week prior to his suspension. He
averaged 14 points in two games _ a loss to Montana and a win over
Montana State.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Minor had become a steady influence for the
Matadors when he substituted for Markus Carr at point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, a 6-foot-9, 250-pound junior forward, has been up and
down this season. He came in as a heralded transfer from L.A. City
College who declared for last year's NBA Draft, then withdrew his
name. He missed six games in December and January with injuries,
came back as a starter, then was benched after a few lackluster
efforts in early February.
</P>
<P>
   The suspensions were the first of the season for CSUN. Braswell
suspended five players last year.
</P>
<P>
   Montana State head coach Mick Durham said he agreed with
Braswell's decision to suspend players this late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Braswell's) 100 percent right,'' Durham said. ``If we
have guys who mess up we'll sit them. I don't think in this day and
age we can let the players run the program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
