<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-PAYTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS NEED MOOCHIE NORRIS TO STEP IT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When the Sonics published their media guides last
week, backup point guard Moochie Norris was noticeably absent from
the player profiles. Because of deadlines during training camp, the
team did not include unproven free agents.
</P>
<P>
   While Norris might have since solidified his place on the roster
_ profile or not _ he still is struggling to prove himself. Norris
is no longer living the rush of a dazzling training camp and his
3-point barrage that leveled Portland in the Sonics' home opener.
</P>
<P>
   That was 10 games ago, and one has to wonder what Norris has
done for his confidence lately.
</P>
<P>
   For the Sonics, Norris' so-so statistics through 12 games might
have been expected. He is still very much a rookie trying to adjust
to the NBA game. However, his 3.2 points, two assists and 32
percent shooting in 12 minutes might signal trouble ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The team is approaching the part of the abbreviated schedule
when it is going to need Norris to step up. The Sonics play 17
games in March, including two sets of three-games-in-three-nights.
</P>
<P>
   Coming are stretches where Sonics coach Paul Westphal will
reluctantly have to rest Gary Payton. The All-Star point guard is
averaging 40 minutes a game _ two minutes more than he played last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's iron-man performances can be traced to two things: He
has more fire than any of his teammates, and the ineffectiveness of
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   That Norris is not a threat on the perimeter is perhaps his
biggest problem. He handles the ball well, and finds teammates, but
opponents are backing off his dribble, daring Norris to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   When Norris does drives the lane, he rarely finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Norris has missed 23 of 31 shots since his 4-for-4 3-point
outburst Feb. 7 against Portland. He's shooting 25 percent over the
past 10 games and has made one 3-pointer in his past eight
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   During last week's loss at Houston, Payton insisted to coach
Paul Westphal that Norris come out of the game late in the fourth
quarter. At practice two days later, Norris heard Westphal bellow,
``You've got to take that shot or I can't play you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics continue to do their part for Norris by imparting
confidence through his meaty role. Now, Norris has to perform.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JUST ASKING
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Did Nate McMillan ever receive an official retirement ceremony?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JUST COUNTING
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   With all of the attention given to Vin Baker's free throw
shooting, the efforts of center Olden Polynice have gone unnoticed.
Polynice is shooting 31 percent from the line, hitting 7 of his 22
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Polynice will donate $25,000 to charity if he doesn't
shoot 75 percent from the line this season. Who does he make that
check out to?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are 8-0 when holding opponents under 100 points. But
they are 0-2 when opponents reach the century mark. The Sonics also
are undefeated on Thursdays. However, that doesn't necessarily mean
trouble for the Phoenix Suns, who arrive at KeyArena on Thursday.
The Sonics have yet to play on that day this season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WORTH REPEATING
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Baker on breaking out his slump: ``I leave the house every day
thinking that this is the day.''
</P>
<P>
   That's better than Dr. Joyce Brothers' advice. She suggested
Baker take a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AND FINALLY
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Perception: Dale Ellis was just 3 of 8 from the field,
missing all five of his 3-pointers at the Alamodome last week. He
almost air-balled a free throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened there,'' he said. ``But this is
really a difficult place to shoot in. The background perception is
ridiculous for basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dish: Ellis didn't have much trouble with the rims during
his two years (1992-94) with San Antonio where he hit 49.9 and 49.4
percent of his shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
