A4082 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      03-02 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER FINDS HIS GROOVE, LIFTING SONICS PAST KINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Vin Baker finally broke the shackles of hapless
play, Gary Payton manufactured a triple-double and the Sonics
finally shot 50 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   It took all of that and a late defensive surge, but the Sonics
finally escaped ARCO Arena with a 105-102 victory over the
Sacramento Kings Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 60-47 at halftime, the Sonics (9-4) stormed back to win
their second straight game. They also snapped a three-game road
losing streak and avenged a 109-106 overtime loss to the Kings on
Feb. 17 at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who showed signs of breaking out of his funk in last
Friday's 92-82 home win against San Antonio, made sure this night
against the Kings would be different.
</P>
<P>
   He scored a season-high 31 points on 15-for-19 shooting. Baker's
last was a 20-footer at the top of the key with 26.7 seconds left.
The basket put the Sonics ahead 100-96.
</P>
<P>
   It should have sealed the victory.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sonics missed three free throws down the stretch and
clung to a 103-100 lead with 6.7 seconds left. Then, Sacramento
rookie Jason Williams provided an interesting finish.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was fouled by Hersey Hawkins as he attempted a
game-tying 3-pointer. Hawkins thought he fouled Williams before the
shot, but the officials saw differently and sent the Kings'point
guard to the foul line. Williams buried the first two but then
missed the third attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The rebound fell to Payton, who was immediately fouled before
calmy hitting a pair of free throws that iced the victory. Payton
finished with 28 points, 12 assists and 10 rebounds for his first
triple-double this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to keep going,'' Baker said. ``In a subtle way, I
wanted to go to overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the way the Sonics shot free throws. They missed 16 of 34
free throws, which was the only reason for the close call.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make our free throws, we win by 10 or 15 points,''
Payton said. ``We've got to understand if we play a better team
than Sacramento, we gotta make free throws and concentrate at the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics did tighten their defensive pressure in the second
half. They slowed down Sacramento's transition game and stepped out
on the perimeter shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really got after it on defense,'' Sonics coach Paul
Westphal said. ``I thought we missed some back-breakers in the
fourth quarter, but it was nice to shoot 50 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker kick-started the Sonics' offense in the first two
quarters, scoring 19 points on 9-for-13 shooting. Even more
impressive was how he asserted himself. Most of his baskets came
from within five feet of the rim, a stark contrast to his first 12
games.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Baker had settled for 18-foot jump shots in the past, he
challenged Sacramento's burly front line all night. Baker mostly
went hard at Chris Webber, who posted 23 points and 14 rebounds in
their first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Baker was the aggressor from the start. He hit four
of his first six shots, which included a backdoor alley-oop dunk
assisted by Detlef Schrempf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat in the hotel and said this has got to be the game,''
Baker said. ``I didn't put any added pressure on myself, and God
blessed me with it. Like I said last game, I'm looking for anything
to kick-start my game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics began the game with their most efficient offensive
effort in several games but broke down, midway through the opening
period. Instead of padding the early lead, Payton was called for
traveling and committed a three-second violation on two straight
possessions. That led to five straight Sonic turnovers, while the
Kings climbed back.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento began to outrun the Sonics and scored easy baskets
off its fastbreak. The Sonics shot 54 percent in the first quarter
but only led 27-25.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied, 29-29, the Sonics fell behind when the
Kings got major contributions from their bench. Predrag Stojakovic
and Jon Barry began to slip 3-pointers past the Sonics defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics eventually fell behind by 13 points at halftime
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento led 62-48 early in the third. However, Billy Owens,
who returned to the Sonics' starting lineup Monday after missing
eight games with a broken pinky, scored nine points in the period,
and the Sonics outscored the Kings 29-20 the rest of the quarter to
get within 82-77.
</P>
<P>
   Payton scored 10 points in the final quarter and Baker added six
_ all in the final three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was feeling comfortable the whole night,'' Westphal said of
Baker. ``He hit some huge shots for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
