<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 03:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4101 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUICIDE-BILL-SFCHRON &LR;      03-02 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUICIDE-BILL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 RIGHT-TO-DIE MEASURE INTRODUCED IN CALIFORNIA ASSEMBLY  &HT;     By ROBERT B. GUNNISON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Igniting a debate over the right to die, a
California state legislator introduced a bill Monday that would
allow terminally ill Californians to take a prescription pill to
end their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, by Assemblywoman Dion Aroner, a Democrat from
Berkeley, mirrors Oregon's physician-assisted suicide law, enacted
in 1997, which allows terminally ill patients to ask a doctor for
lethal medications.
</P>
<P>
   Aroner said her bill ``will provide people suffering from
terminal illness the peace of mind to know that if their symptoms
become so severe and debilitating, or their pain so great, they
have the choice to end their suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   California voters in 1992 rejected a ballot proposition that
would have allowed physicians directly to help terminally ill
patients die. It was defeated, 54 percent to 46 percent, after a
multimillion-dollar ad blitz largely financed by Catholic
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gov. Gray Davis, a Catholic who _ contrary to
church teachings _ supports abortion rights and the death penalty,
had no comment on Aroner's bill, which will be fought by the
powerful doctors' lobby and Catholic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Introduction of the right-to-die measure comes as the pace of
legislative activity is accelerating. Lawmakers have proposed
measures dealing with topics as diverse as studying the effects of
the state's ``three-strikes, and you're out'' law to outlawing
discrimination at schools based on sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Aroner measure is certain to provide some of the most
intense debate and wrenching political decisions of the session.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Hogan, a lobbyist for the California Catholic Conference,
which represents the state's bishops, said her organization would
fight Aroner's bill vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compassion means to `suffer with,' '' Hogan said. ``It's
easier to offer someone relief, which may mean relief from looking
at them suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan also said terminally ill patients concerned about high
medical costs might choose to take the fatal doses. ``It's a whole
lot cheaper for someone to kill themselves than to ask their HMO to
care for them for another six months,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But a study published in the New England Journal of Medicine
last month reported that none of the 23 people in Oregon who
received prescriptions for lethal medications did so for financial
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the terminally ill were more concerned with loss of
autonomy or bodily functions because of their illnesses, according
to the study.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Of the 23 Oregonians who asked for the prescriptions, 15 took the
medication, six died from their original illness and two were alive
as of January 1, the journal reported. Eighteen of the participants
had cancer. Their average age was 69.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Twenty patients were given secobarbital or pentobarbital. Of the
15 who died, death came in an average of 26 minutes, although one
took 111/2 hours to die.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled closely on the Oregon law, Aroner's bill would require
that a physician determine that candidates for the prescriptions be
18 or older, of sound mind and have fewer than six months to live
because of an incurable and irreversible disease.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of SUICIDE0 (81762 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  A patient would make a written request for the prescription,
witnessed by two other people. The request could be withdrawn at
any time.
</P>
<P>
   No prescription could be written until at least 15 days after
the original request.
</P>
<P>
   Also opposing the bill will be the California Medical
Association. ``Physician-assisted suicide is the opposite approach
to what we should be taking,'' said CMA lobbyist Scott Syphax.
``There are far more compassionate approaches than to give
government sanction to affirmatively ending one's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Syphax said his organization supported legislation to expand
hospice care and to make it easier for patients to receive
pain-fighting medications.
</P>
<P>
   But Aroner cited polls showing that about two of three Americans
believe terminally ill adults should be able to ask a physician for
medication to end their lives. ``I believe it is finally time to
begin the discussion in California,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
