reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the terminally ill were more concerned with loss of
autonomy or bodily functions because of their illnesses, according
to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 23 Oregonians who asked for the prescriptions, 15 took
the medication, six died from their original illness and two were
alive as of January 1, the journal reported. Eighteen of the
participants had cancer. Their average age was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty patients were given secobarbital or pentobarbital. Of the
15 who died, death came in an average of 26 minutes, although one
took 111/2 hours to die.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled closely on the Oregon law, Aroner's bill would require
that a physician determine that candidates for the prescriptions be
18 or older, of sound mind and have fewer than six months to live
because of an incurable and irreversible disease.
</P>
