<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 03:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4104 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-IMAGE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-02 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-IMAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GORE WARMS UP FOR 2000 CAMPAIGN  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Vice President Al Gore, gearing up for his
presidential campaign and already targeted by Republicans,
acknowledged Monday that he may have to ``loosen up'' and change
his buttoned-down image with voters.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Chronicle on his 53rd trip to
California, Gore talked with unusual candor about ``the biggest,
most important state'' and about his unusually reserved public
image, which he said benefits from ``low expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   With Republican Texas Governor George W. Bush set to take the
first formal step toward a presidential run, Gore made sure there
weren't any doubts about his plans. He stopped saying he might run
for president _ and talked about when he runs for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't announced my campaign yet,'' Gore said. ``But when
the time comes, I will seek the judgment of the American people,
not on the basis of the polls, but on the basis of the ideas I
offer and the vision that I present.''
</P>
<P>
   He also made it clear where he plans to spend most of his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is the biggest, most important state,'' he said.
``It deserves the most attention, and I'm going to make sure it
gets it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's comments came during a packed one-day visit to San
Francisco and Oakland. The vice president held a breakfast meeting
with about 80 CEOs and political leaders at San Francisco City
Hall, then hosted a town hall meeting before 700 community leaders
on welfare-to-work issues in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, Gore traveled to Oakland to meet with Mayor
Jerry Brown and African American leaders, while his wife, Tipper,
went to San Jose to attend a session on homeless issues. The Gores
returned to Washington late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed and at ease after a day of meetings and public events,
Gore roared with laughter when shown a bumper sticker that was a
best-seller at last weekend's state Republican convention. It said,
``Nixon in 2000: He's not as stiff as Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I keep that?'' he asked. ``It's a classic.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Gore frankly addressed what many of his strongest
supporters have long talked about _ the need for him to relax his
buttoned-down image and show voters his real persona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm constantly being told by my close friends that the sense
of humor they enjoy, and know me by, doesn't come across in my
public appearance,'' Gore said. ``Maybe I'll yet figure out a way
to loosen up. ... I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some things that are hard to change about yourself,''
he said. But, he added with a smile, ``I benefit from low
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore gave a glimpse of that more personal side when he talked
about becoming a grandparent for the first time this summer _ and
how it may make him a different kind of man and politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows you to extend your personal connection with the
future, and feel the impact of policies that may last for
decades,'' he said. ``Becoming emotionally involved with
grandchildren, you can find it much easier to understand the
importance of balancing the long-term consequences of decisions,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was also unabashed about his attention to California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be here more often than in any other state,'' he said.
``America's future is born every day in California.''
</P>
<P>
   In his public events Monday, Gore won raves from some in
attendance who said he was showing the kind of personal touch
needed in the coming campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In his town hall meeting, at the Bill Graham Civic Auditorium,
the vice president walked around the stage, coaxing stories from
mothers formerly on welfare, and others like Stanton Richardson, a
former welfare recipient who is now a successful insurance agent.
</P>
<P>
   When Richardson almost broke down in tears, recalling how he
found himself and his children without a home in 1993, Gore paused
and said, ``You've really got your heart in this, don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   He then posed for photos on stage with a handful of families,
and also delivered a letter to a woman who had a bad fall and
couldn't attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to continue doing what he's doing,'' said San
Francisco Supervisor Leslie Katz, who said she met Gore in 1982 as
an intern for the House Committee on Energy and Commerce. ``Holding
one-on-ones, meeting in small groups, talking about issues, that's
important.'' She said Gore increasingly ``seems relaxed and he
really does have a great sense of humor,'' and Democrats now are
itching to hear him declare his campaign off and running.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Gore repeatedly pounded the theme that in
good economic times, ``our challenge is to make certain that no one
is left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I congratulate the whole Bay Area on what you've been doing,''
he told the town hall meeting. ``And I'll be there with you, to go
the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   In his interview, the vice president played down polls that show
Bush and former Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole already running
ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polls are unreliable, but I welcome the opportunity to take on
this challenge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is expected to announce the formation of an exploratory
committee, the first formal step in making a run for the
presidency. Gore formed his own committee earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also addressed criticism _ which Republicans lobbed at him
repeatedly during last week's GOP state convention _ that he wasn't
tough enough on President Clinton's actions and that, indeed,
Clinton was tougher on himself than Gore was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've repeatedly criticized the president's behavior as
indefensible, and everyone knows that he himself has apologized,''
Gore said, adding that Americans are ``beginning to be a little
puzzled as to why the Republican Party cannot seem to let go of
this matter. Wrong as it was, it's in the past. ... A judgment has
been rendered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to spend my time addressing the future,'' Gore said.
``It's for others to determine if they want to wallow in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there is a danger that some Democrats might see the
2000 presidential election as a ``slam dunk'' because both
Clinton's polls and the economy are in good shape, Gore nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said. ``I've certainly never regarded any election
as a slam dunk. ... The Republicans have made some unusually
serious mistakes ... but the American people will judge candidates
and the party by what they have to say about the future,'' said
Gore. ``And that's my focus _ the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
