<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4274 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN03-COX     03-02 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Decidingly female black electorate growing
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Today, chalk talk for political junkies.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Cathy Cox's office recently released an
analysis of voter turnout in last November's election. We already
know who won and lost, but the study is a useful reality check on
who voted.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls conducted on Election Day indicated African-American
voters made up 30 percent of the total votes cast, a staggering
leap in turnout. The state analysis, which can reference every
ballot cast by race, puts the actual percentage at just under 23
percent. This has a couple of implications.
</P>
<P>
   The information in this report doesn't tell us for whom people
voted. But if we assume Democrat Roy Barnes got 90 percent of the
black vote in this racially charged election, he must still have
received about 41 percent of the white vote to win by his overall
margin of 53 percent, according to the calculations of Bobby Kahn,
Barnes' chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   That's better than the 38 percent of white votes Max Cleland got
in the 1996 Senate race and close to the 42.9 garnered by Zell
Miller in the '94 governor's race. Barnes won with what is becoming
the target split of white votes a Democrat needs in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic pollster Alan Secrest said he was not surprised the
original estimates of African-American turnout were way off the
mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exit polls are spectacularly ill-equipped to say what the
racial proportion of an election is,'' Secrest said.
</P>
<P>
   The scaled-back assessment of black voting participation isn't
as dramatic, but it nevertheless is part of an important emerging
political trend.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout among African-Americans in Georgia has been on a slow,
steady rise since the passage of the federal ``Motor Voter'' law,
from 19 percent in 1994 to 21 percent in '96 to 23 percent in '98.
This corresponds with a big increase in the percentage of
African-Americans in the state who are registered to vote, from 49
percent in 1994 to 65 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   As the percentage of black voters has increased, the gender gap
has widened. Women now are 55 percent of all registered voters, but
women account for 60 percent of the registered African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   A higher percentage of African-American women also turned out to
vote last November. While overall black voter turnout still lagged
behind white voters, black women voted at a percentage close to the
average for all voters.
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Whit Ayres said he didn't think this
trendline can be sustained in the upcoming presidential election
year, without the ``peculiar set of circumstances'' that encouraged
black turnout in the past election. Those include the backlash
against the campaigns of Guy Millner and Mitch Skandalakis, Bill
Clinton's impeachment and a record number of black statewide
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   With white turnout likely to increase in 2000, African-American
participation might not increase as much as a measurable
percentage. But a new black electorate, better educated, more
involved, and at this juncture, one-sidedly female, is beginning to
take shape.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
