<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weather radios can save lives in event of tornadoes, storms
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If a tornado comes through, even in the
dead of night, a small radio will wake you up, perhaps in time to
seek safety.
</P>
<P>
   The weather service says the radios might have saved lives when
a string of tornadoes tore through Central Florida in February 1998
when most people were asleep.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service hopes to someday have a ``weather
radio in every home, just like a smoke detector, and in all
schools, hospitals and other public gathering places,'' said former
Director Elbert W. Friday Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The radio can be set to continuously play local forecasts. Or it
can be programmed to go off only in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   When the National Weather Service sends out a severe weather
warning the radio beeps loud enough to awaken someone, then
broadcasts the warning. It will broadcast not only weather
warnings, but also other major emergencies, such as wildfires or an
accident at a nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
   In newer models, users can now program radios to receive only
the most local warnings _ sparing Boca Raton residents, for
example, a broadcast of a waterspout off Miami Beach. Forecasters
are now working to break it down even more; splitting Palm Beach
County, for example into nine regions.
</P>
<P>
   Users can also eliminate certain broadcasts; someone who doesn't
boat may not want to hear every marine warning.
</P>
<P>
   The radios can run either on batteries or on house current with
a battery back-up. Deaf or blind people can connect radios to
special devices such as strobe lights, pagers and bed-shakers.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Division of Emergency Management thinks so much of the
devices it handed out 3,200 last year, one for every public school,
and distributed another 10,000 last week to places such as day care
centers and retirement homes. Counties were also given vouchers to
buy more of the $80 radios at a discounted price of $49. The radios
are available from electronic stores, department stores and
catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   In the state, Southeast Florida is second only to Central
Florida in the frequency of tornadoes, said Jim Lushine, warning
coordination meteorologist for the National Weather Service's Miami
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for a fairly active tornadic season in May and
June,'' Lushine said.
</P>
<P>
   And while South Floridians think less of tornadoes than they do
hurricanes, which they can see coming, hurricanes can spawn
tornadoes or flash floods, even from far away, Lushine said.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Kleinberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
