<HEADER>
A4279 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN03-CO     03-02 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Following the herd? That's a common investment mistake authors
say
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ My excuse is that I was much younger when I decided to
make my fortune by trading in silver futures.
</P>
<P>
   I have used that dodge for many years now. It still feels as
fresh, and as flimsy, as it ever has.
</P>
<P>
   My first two silver trades were swift, decisive and profitable.
It was the third that separated the sheep from the wool. I lost
more money than I like to recall, and I took my shorn self out of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Now, much too late, I understand a little bit more about why I
got so overconfident/dumb. I found the explanations in a newly
published book on a well-established field of study, behavioral
finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People confidently confuse familiarity with knowledge,'' Gary
Belsky and Thomas Gilovich write in their book, ``Why Smart People
Make Big Money Mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For every example of a person who made money on an investment
because she used a company's product or understood its strategy, we
can give you five instances where such knowledge was insufficient
to justify the investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Belsky and Gilovich don't cover new territory. Instead, they
recount the high points of about 30 years of academic studies in
the field of behavior and investment decisions. But Belsky, a
financial writer, and Gilovich, a psychology professor at Cornell
University, do an uncommonly good job of turning academic work into
everyday good sense. And they have an old-shoe approach that makes
it easy reading.
</P>
<P>
   One objection to the book _ and the entire field of study _
might be that it sometimes seems like an awful lot of gabble to
arrive at obvious conclusions. I want to agree. But I also have to
admit that I learned a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Take the question of overconfidence. The authors outline several
interesting reasons why people develop an unreasonable belief in
their investment ability. But they go on to a better question _ why
people stay overconfident. ``Frankly, we don't learn well enough
from our mistakes,'' they write.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard psychologist Eileen Langer describes this phenomenon
as `heads I win, tails it's chance,' '' say Gilovich and Belsky.
``When things happen that confirm the correctness of your actions
or beliefs, you attribute the events to your own high ability.
Conversely, when things happen that prove your actions or beliefs
to have been mistaken or wrong-headed, you attribute those
disconcerting events to some other cause over which you had no
control. The net result is that you emerge from a checkered history
of success and failure with a robust optimism about your prospects
for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? It does to me. I may be out of silver futures,
but I still buy a strange stock every so often.
</P>
<P>
   The authors also make themselves useful by following each
self-delusion with suggestions on how to overcome it. Most of the
suggestions sound like good old horse sense. But most of us can
benefit, one time or another, from a dose of horse sense.
</P>
<P>
   On another interesting point, the authors review a seven-year
study of the trades made in 10,000 accounts at a discount
brokerage. The study proved that investors are more likely to sell
their winners and hang on to their losers. It also showed that the
stocks the investors sold outperformed the stocks they held by 3.4
percent over the following 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your investments are the flotilla that you hope will carry you
to the shores of a secure retirement over the choppy seas of
life,'' the authors write in a metaphor that will soon get out of
hand. ``Rather than sticking with boats that have proven their
seaworthiness, you routinely abandon ship in favor of dinghies that
have already sprung some leaks. ... No sailor in his right mind
would behave in this fashion, yet many investors do so routinely.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Most people respond much more strongly to investment
losses than they do to gains. Anguish trumps elation. ``The
prospect of selling that losing investment (and the pain associated
with making the loss final) makes them more willing to dig in their
heels and take risks,'' the authors conclude. ``After all, until
you actually sell a losing investment, the drop in price is only a
`paper loss' _ it's not official. Once you sell it, though, it's
real.''
</P>
<P>
   There is much more. Why people freeze up, or turn conservative,
when they are faced with too many choices. Why consumers will pay
more for a given object if they charge it, rather than paying cash.
Why investors mistake a stampeding herd for ``the smart money.''
</P>
<P>
   I look over a lot of personal finance books. Many are
repetitious. Others are get-rich-quick schemes, and some are
downright squirrelly. But this book is worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail: hezell(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
