<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Simple lessons learned in a cemetery
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Long an avid student of Texas history, I've
stumbled upon another one of those folks who wasn't in my
textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   He was a wealthy landowner in Fort Bend County during the last
century and part of this one. He got into politics and was elected
sheriff and tax collector, then was elected to the Texas Senate.
While in the Legislature, he backed many education initiatives,
including one bill establishing a state university. He returned to
Fort Bend County, which sits along Houston's southwestern edge and
stayed active in politics and farming until he died in 1913.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, while on a trip to Richmond, the county seat, last
year, my family and I stopped at the historic Morton Cemetery. We
find it interesting to explore old cemeteries and talk about the
lives of the people who are buried there. On this visit, we spotted
a state historical marker near two of the graves at this final
resting place of many prominent Fort Bend County families.
</P>
<P>
   The marker, erected in 1992, told about a politician/farmer and
when we were through reading it, my husband turned to my son and
declared, ``You have got to do your history project on this guy.''
Our school requires a yearly history project from all fifth through
eighth graders and families learn to be on the lookout for great
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   So what was it about the life of the man on the marker, which
sounds like that of so many others who helped build this great
state, that would elicit such enthusiasm from a history nut like my
husband?
</P>
<P>
   He was a slave.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Moses Burton was born around 1840 in North Carolina and
brought to Texas by his master, Thomas Burke Burton in 1850.
Against all laws and customs, Burton taught the young slave to read
and write and when slavery ended after the Civil War, he sold to
Walter Moses Burton several parcels of
</P>
<P>
   land.
</P>
<P>
   The former slave, now a wealthy and influential landowner,
entered politics in 1869 when he was elected sheriff and tax
collector of Fort Bend County.
</P>
<P>
   His service in the Texas Senate began in 1874 and ended in 1882.
In 1879, he was instrumental in passing the bill establishing
Prairie View Normal School, now Prairie View A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   Burton and his son, Horace, are the only two black people buried
in Morton Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   My son listened to his dad and pursued the project for his
seventh grade year, which is the year Texas schoolchildren study
our state's history. He got an A and we all got a little richer in
our knowledge of black history, which after all is part of what
makes Texas history so rich.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, Longview, Texas. E-mail:
</P>
<P>
   awalker(AT)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
