<HEADER>
A4281 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN03-COX     03-02 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good intentions don't justify these bills; they're stinkers
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ My time would be better spent if the law required
my son to walk faster.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Legislature should step to it.
</P>
<P>
   When my son's voice changed, so did his gear ratio. Now he has
two speeds: ``slow'' and ``glacial.'' I want Texas to set a minimum
pedestrian speed for able-bodied Texans ages 13-18.
</P>
<P>
   With slouching a concurrent teen condition, Texas also should
declare an ``official body language,'' which would be upright.
</P>
<P>
   Stop me before I go much further. Someone in the state Capitol
is going to take these proposals seriously.
</P>
<P>
   As much as we mean well making requirements for young people, we
can overstep.
</P>
<P>
   Two bills before the legislature are examples of good intentions
gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   The first, by Rep. Rene Oliveira, D-Brownsville, would require
every Texas high schooler to take two years of Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The second, by Tony Goolsby, R-Dallas, would require high
schoolers to do 60 hours of community service to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   I should be singing the praises of both. Having two years of
high school Spanish and 60 hours of community service would be good
for any student. So would walking faster and not slouching.
</P>
<P>
   Texas should stomp these bills to death.
</P>
<P>
   Learning Spanish ought to be fundamental in the Southwest. It's
an argument I've made in my own home many times. It is
geographically self-evident. My son is taking French.
</P>
<P>
   He had his first Spanish in middle school. He knows just enough
to be dangerous. I can see him robbing a Juarez bank with tellers
mulling the warning: ``I've got cheese and I'm not afraid to use
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be to his benefit to be fluent in Spanish, but
requiring two years of Spanish would cause several problems. The
first is the way high schoolers see electives erode under
core-subject mandates. Heap on a few more mandates and there won't
be enough hours in a day for a high schooler to have an education
that suits his or her interests. Requiring two years of Spanish
would virtually erase French, Russian and Latin from Texas
offerings, because only hard-core language students would free up
the time for them.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is an accute lack of qualified Spanish teachers.
Texas is hard pressed to find enough bilingual teachers as it is.
</P>
<P>
   Topping this off is the fact that high school is too late. The
perfect-world solution: Learn Spanish in grade school. With that
underpinning, more students would be inclined to choose two years
of Spanish in secondary school. This is important enough to launch
a state initiative: Spanish from the bottom up. But don't order it
top-down.
</P>
<P>
   Good intention, bad law. Nothing so reflects the combination
than that other bad bill: the 60-hour ``community service''
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each school shall develop a list of approved community service
organizations from which a student may select,'' it says. Red tape
alert. Who on the average high school campus has time to administer
this?
</P>
<P>
   I'm a big advocate of volunteer work. Many youngsters would
benefit under this requirement, and so would agencies. But watch
out for coerced teen-agers slouching slowly toward make-work
opportunities in which they would end up rearranging dust with
leaden sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   As with TAAS drills and TAAS practice tests (even for students
who don't need them), and then three days of the real thing under
state decree, this sounds like one more way for Texas to say, ``We
interrupt your regularly scheduled education for . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   John Young is editorial page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
