<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4284 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS03-COX     03-02 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH BRIEFS: Dealing with death as a part of life
 &HT;    (EDS: This is a compilation of health stories which moved to the
wires this week.)
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Death does not come easily to doctors. Inevitable as
it is in their line of work, it flies in the face of their
training, purpose, even their egos.
</P>
<P>
   But many social and technological issues, such as
physician-assisted suicide and chemotherapy advances, are forcing
doctors to add end-of-life care to their purview of prevention and
treatment of disease and trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way is the American Medical Association with its new
program, ``Educating Physicians in End-of-Life Care.'' The
organization selected 250 health care and other professionals
across the nation to attend four regional workshops to better learn
how to help terminally ill patients and their families. The AMA
trainees, in turn, will educate their local communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death as failure is how many doctors think,'' said Dr. Russell
K. Portenoy, department chairman of palliative care at New York's
Beth Israel Hospital. ``Our medical model is returning patients to
a state of health.'' Portenoy is one of several doctors leading the
AMA two-year initiative, which is supported with a grant from the
Robert Wood Johnson Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1 million Americans who die annually, only 10 percent die
of an unexpected event such as an accident or sudden onset of
disease. The rest either face protracted fatal illnesses, such as
cancer and muscle-degenerative disorders, or the predictable and
steady decline of aging and its chronic conditions _ diabetes,
heart disease, Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   While more and more hospice centers and home-health care workers
are helping patients in their final days, the AMA wants end-of-life
care, known as palliative care, to begin much sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors above all are human beings and they are just as
uncomfortable with this subject as others,'' says Dr. Linda Emanuel
of Chicago's Northwestern University Hospital. ``But patients
expect physicians to introduce the topic of long-term planning for
their condition, and it's often left to others in the medical
system.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the End-of-Life project, contact the
Institute for Ethics, American Medical Association, 515 N. State
Street, Chicago, IL 60610; 312-464-4979.
</P>
<P>
   Minority workers lag in health coverage, study finds
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White workers are far more likely to have health
insurance paid by their employers than blacks or Hispanics,
according to a recently-released study.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the nonprofit Commonwealth Fund found that 69
percent of white workers were covered by employer-sponsored
insurance, compared with 52 percent of black workers and 44 percent
of Hispanic workers. The study found even wider disparities among
different occupations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A variety of additional barriers may account for the
difference in health care coverage rates between whites and
minorities,'' said Allyson Hall, lead author of the study.
``Certain groups may decline health care coverage not only because
of financial concerns, but also because of differing perceptions
regarding the propensity to become ill and the overall need for
health care coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 18 percent of workers between 18 and 64 were
uninsured in 1997, an increase from 15.7 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, minorities have been more likely than whites to be
uninsured. They often work in industries or in part-time jobs that
do not offer coverage, said Karen Davis, president of the
Commonwealth Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But even among fulltime workers, 37 percent of Hispanics were
uninsured, compared to 20 percent of blacks and 12 percent of
whites.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of workers in manufacturing jobs had
employer-provided health coverage. Whites were covered 85 percent
of the time, compared to 71 percent for blacks and 60 percent for
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Large firms were more likely to provide coverage than small
firms. In firms of more than 1,000 employees, 85 percent of whites
were covered, compared to 76 percent blacks and 72 percent
Hispanics. In companies of less than 100 workers, 63 percent of
whites were covered, compared to 47 percent for blacks and 38
percent for Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Lower wage earners also were less likely to be insured by an
employer. Among workers earning less than $7 an hour, 56 percent of
whites were covered, compared to 47 percent of blacks and 35
percent of Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workers who are poor, not well-educated, not U.S. citizens,
unmarried, younger or live in an inner city or rural area are less
likely than their counterparts to have employers-based health
insurance,'' the report concluded. ``Most of these characteristics
have a greater effect on minority than white populations.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
