<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FESTIVAL03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Music festival/conference now a teenager
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The music industry calls it ``spring break,'' as
its swarms invade the streets of Austin, Texas, with the
margarita-swilling abandon of collegians in Daytona, Fla. For the
Austin economy, it is ``Christmas in March,'' though local hotels,
clubs and restaurants consider it more like Mardi Gras and the
Super Bowl rolled into one. It is best recognized by the
unpronounceable acronym of SXSW, though it is more properly known
as the South by Southwest Music and Media Conference (by day, and
the South by Southwest Music Festival by night).
</P>
<P>
   Whatever one calls it, SXSW will mark its 13th year with this
year's run. From March 17-21, it will present more than 600 musical
acts at 37 clubs and other facilities throughout the city. It
expects to draw some 6,000 conference registrants from across the
country and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in 1987 as a regional alternative to New York's New
Music Seminar, it has grown into the country's largest and most
significant annual music industry gathering since the mid-'90s
demise of the NMS. The Austin location is a key to its appeal, as
SXSW has been able to capitalize on the city's reputation for
maverick musical creativity and downhome friendliness. From the
kickoff with the annual Austin Music Awards through the closing
softball tournament and barbecue festivities, the event has
retained its regional flavor throughout its boom as a national and
international attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the whole town becomes Musicville, U.S.A., for a
week,'' said Casey Monahan, director of the Texas Music Office for
the state government. ``It keeps Austin in the appointment books of
6,000-plus industry decision-makers every year.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of the event has spawned an accompanying film
festival and multimedia conference, preceding and overlapping with
the musical gathering. Still, the musical lineup remains the
primary draw, with SXSW '99 promising Lucinda Williams as keynote
speaker and perennial performer, British guitar legends Jeff Beck
and Robert Fripp in rare club appearances, former Talking Head
David Byrne spinning discs as a club deejay and hundreds of acts
who are unsigned or on independent labels hoping to generate the
buzz of discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the recent upheavals in the music industry _
particularly the consolidation of the Polygram and MCA groups, with
labels folded and the dismissal of some 1,300 employees _ this
year's conference might seem more like a job fair, filled with
industry veterans looking for work. It would also appear that the
music lineup might be suffering at the major-label level, a victim
of corporate belt-tightening. In contrast with previous SXSW fests,
which have featured artists ranging from Johnny Cash to Iggy Pop to
Tony Bennett _ this year's seems lighter on big names.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be a lineup that has as much celebrity appeal or
the kind of acts that trendy people look for,'' fest director Brent
Grulke told Chris Riemenschneider of the Austin American-Statesman,
``but our goal isn't to cater to that, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those participating in the event, goals and strategies for
making the most of it are as various as the music the fest
features. In 1994, three schoolboy brothers from Tulsa, Oklahoma,
were driven to the event by their father, and spent the weekend
singing to anyone within earshot, from the lobby of the Four
Seasons hotel to the sidelines of the softball tournament. Though
they'd never even applied for a showcase, they left the conference
with a manager, and were soon selling millions of records as
Hanson.
</P>
<P>
   More typical was last year's approach taken by Hollywood Records
with Austin's Fastball. Using the event to introduce the rising
band to the nation's music media, the label threw an open-bar and
free buffet bash during the hours preceding Fastball's showcase,
thus ensuring a packed house and an enthusiastic reception. The
evening served as a springboard for ``The Way,'' which soon became
a smash over alternative-rock radio.
</P>
<P>
   As founding festival director Roland Swenson has explained,
``This is an opportunity for people in the music business and
regional and national media to meet and share ideas . . . We are a
tool. And either you can figure out how to use us or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Don McLeese writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
