<HEADER>
A4287 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     03-02 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REAL ZERO OF A DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if we didn't already have enough to worry about, what with
the shrinking strike zone and the very real possibility that the
Rev. Jerry Falwell is the ``lost'' Teletubby, we now have to come
up with a name for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   According to an article in USA Today, there is no general
agreement as to what we should call the years 2000-2009. The Double
Ohs? Decade One? The Singles? Yech.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times language columnist William Safire has
suggested calling the first decade of the new millennium the Zippy
Zeros, which suggests to me that Mr. Safire may be a victim of Sick
Building Syndrome or perhaps is simply in need of a long, restful
vacation. (Yo, Bill: The Times early retirement package is very
generous. You may want to check it out.)
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s, for all its failings, at least had the decency to
provide us with an obvious name that was short, easy to pronounce
and lent itself well to newspaper headlines. It is unlikely that
the next decade will show us the same courtesy.
</P>
<P>
   The Two Thousandths? If Dan Rather tries saying that on the
evening news he'll swallow his tongue and his head will explode.
</P>
<P>
   (I know what you're thinking and you should be ashamed of
yourself.)
</P>
<P>
   The best suggestion I've heard so far _ and it is by no means
great _ is The Pre-Teens.
</P>
<P>
   If the next decade is anything like the one we're in now, it
will be unruly, unmanageable and susceptible to the most hideous
trends in fashion and music, just like a real pre-teen. The analogy
is not perfect, however, because I assume we won't have to remind
the next decade 100 times a day to pick up its clothes, get off the
phone or do its homework. Then again, we are headed into uncharted
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I think of it, Uncharted Territory would not be that
bad a name for the next decade, though it sounds a bit ominous and
could just as easily be applied to the decade after that or the
decade after that. Also, it does not fit well in headlines, which
is the main reason decades need a nickname in the first place, as
best I can tell.
</P>
<P>
   The Voice of America, which has an audience of more than 80
million people, is running a contest asking listeners to suggest a
name for the new decade. Entries, so far, include ``The 2KOs'' from
Israel, ``The Pre-Tens'' from Kazakhstan, ``The Digital Decade''
from Zimbabwe and ``Globacade'' from Ghana.
</P>
<P>
   Ghana undoubtedly has a lot going for it (abundant sunshine
springs immediately to mind), but its people have a lot to learn
when it comes to naming decades. Can you imagine a car salesman
slamming his palm on the hood of a new car and saying, ``Don't wait
another minute! Come on down and see our Globacade Toyota Camrys!
You'll be glad you did!''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I seriously doubt that anyone, least of all me, is
going to come up with a name for the next decade that is going to
meet with everyone's approval. The Zeros is out because it implies
futility, and that's not a healthy way to think of a decade until
you've lived in it awhile, as we have with the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The First Decade of the 21st Century makes up in logic what it
lacks in pizzazz, but headline writers will be tempted to
abbreviate it to FD21C, which is not something I or anyone else
would want to see happen.
</P>
<P>
   Given what we've been through, calling the next decade Not The
Nineties has a certain appeal, but there is always the possibility
that the Two Thousandths will be the '90s all over again, which is
a thought even more depressing than plunking down $20,000 for a
Zippy Zero Dodge minivan.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
