<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4291 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBIE-BEAUTY03-COX     03-02 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIE-BEAUTY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neferiti. Venus. Cleopatra. BARBIE!
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ How well does Barbie measure up against
the great beauties of history? Is she able to hold her own against
Nefertiti, Cleopatra, Phryne of Athens, Roxane of Bactria, who
married Alexander the Great and who was said to be the most
beautiful woman in Asia?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, maybe not. Barbie has an advantage over many of the
famous women of antiquity in that we know what she looks like, and
we often don't know what they looked like. But this is a
disadvantage too: The unknown can always be more lovely than the
known.
</P>
<P>
   Women mentioned in the Greek Anthology, a collection of 4,000
poems assembled by Byzantine scholars nearly a thousand years ago,
still glow in lines of exquisite beauty, like these, by Meleager:
</P>
<P>
   ``White violets flower
</P>
<P>
   lilies on hill-slopes
</P>
<P>
   narcissus nodding to rain-showers
</P>
<P>
   And the queen of lovers' hopes
</P>
<P>
   the sweet persuasive rose,
</P>
<P>
   Zenophile, more fair than those
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a single line, brief as a Japanese haiku, can be more
ravishing than a whole row of Barbies:
</P>
<P>
   ``Heliodore's myrrhed brows, wreathed curls, swim in petals ...
''
</P>
<P>
   Who Heliodore and Zenophile were, we know not; but it is perhaps
unfair to pit Barbie against poems.
</P>
<P>
   Here, instead, is a gallery of very old women, each considered
unrivaled in her day, beginning with the oldest of all:
</P>
<P>
   Nefertiti. She was the wife of the Egyptian Pharaoh, Amenhotep
IV, also known as Akhenaten, who reigned from 1353 to 1336 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   She was found at Amarna Dec. 6, 1912, by a German expedition led
by Ludwig Borchardt in the studio of an ancient court sculptor,
named Tuthmosis. Today the exquisite bust of Nefertiti is behind
glass in the Egyptian Museum of Charlottenburg, a suburb of Berlin.
It is the single most famous work of Egyptian art in the world,
about 20 inches tall, missing one in-laid eyeball and with one ear
sadly chipped. It never left the studio: It was meant to serve as a
model for all official portraits of the queen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It embodies our contemporary ideal of beauty: a faultless,
symmetrical face enhanced by make-up tastefully applied to brows,
eyelids and lips; and a long, graceful neck,'' writes Biri Fay in
the official 1984 guide to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the famous beauties of antiquity, Nefertiti is perhaps
closest to Barbie, especially the long, swan-like neck. Where
Barbie falls short, however, is in the mouth. Nefertiti's lips are
closed in exquisite, calligraphic line. Barbie _ at least the newer
versions _ wears her Colgate smile, mouth agape, for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   Venus. The famous Venus of Cnidos, by the Athenian sculptor
Praxiteles, dates to about 364 B.C. and is supposedly modeled after
one of the most famous beauties of Athens, a courtesan named
Phryne, who was the talk of the city. She was said to be so
extraordinarily beautiful that she went about veiled at all times,
except once a year, on the Eleusinian festival. Then she went to
the sea, stripped nude and swam in full view of anyone who cared to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   When she was sued for impiety, she went to court and disarmed
the judges by allowing her lawyer, Hypereides, to open her tunic
and reveal her bosom. The judges were so overwhelmed that they
acquitted Phryne on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   The original Aphrodite of Cnidos has been long lost, despite a
claim to have identified her badly damaged head in a Vatican Museum
storehouse in 1971 by archaeologist Iris Love (the New York Times
headline read: Love Finds Aphrodite). The best copy is in a small
room in the Vatican Museum and shows the goddess emerging from her
bath, chastely holding a hand in front of her midriff.
</P>
<P>
   She's a very fleshy lady; you almost want to tickle her stomach
or give her a hug. She is far removed from Barbie's taut,
aerobicized body, much closer to what Chaucer described as the
ideal beautiful woman: ``With buttokes brode and brestes round and
hye ...''
</P>
<P>
   While we are talking of classical sculpture, it is well to
mention that most ``ideal'' sculptures show a very definite,
precise ratio of head-to-body proportion. The ideal, seen in the
Farnese Hercules and the Capitoline Gladiator is 7.5 heads' height.
The Aphrodite of Melos in the Louvre, she of the missing arms, is 8
heads high. This is the upper limit, in antiquity. Beyond that
you've got a monster, a freak.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Barbie is a freak by classical standards. The entire
figurine measures 12.5 inches high and her head is 1.5 inches long.
Barbie is 8.33 heads high. Praxiteles would have kicked her out of
his studio.
</P>
<P>
   Roxane. The Bactrian belle whom Alexander conquered and married
on his march to India in 327 B.C. was said to be the most beautiful
woman in all of Asia. Her name meant ``little star.'' She was won,
almost like a fairy-tale princess, after Alexander's troops scaled
the eyeless, steep Sogdian Rock, where lay the palace of her
father, Oxyartes. The wedding took place in this airy, high
fastness.
</P>
<P>
   No historic portrait of her survives, but a description of the
wedding night, painted by the contemporary Greek master, Aetion, is
still extant: ``He showed a very beautiful bedroom on which Roxane
sat. She was an exceptionally lovely girl, but modestly she looked
down at the ground, feeling shy in Alexander's presence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italian Renaissance painter, Sodoma, read this passage and
decided to recreate the painting in the upper salon of the
Farnesina Palazzo in Rome, where it can still be seen today. Of
course Sodoma had no idea what Roxane looked like, but the painting
is so extraordinarily gorgeous that it deserves to be looked at, as
one of the great imaginary recreations of antiquity. In it, Roxane
is an improbable blonde, like Barbie, and a little Cupid is helping
her out of her see-through top.
</P>
<P>
   But any similarity to Barbie stops right after the blond hair.
This is an intensely erotic painting and if you were to substitute
Barbie for Sodoma's Roxane in your mind's eye, you would howl with
laughter. Barbie's blank, plastic bust is no match for Roxane's
ample bosom.
</P>
<P>
   But here again, the parallel is unfair. The real Roxane was just
14 when she married Alexander, 28. She was a little girl by our
standards. She may have really resembled Barbie in her skinny,
juvenile way. But she was almost certainly a brunette.
</P>
<P>
   Cleopatra. Finally, consider one of the most famous,
misapprehended women of antiquity. The French philosopher, Blaise
Pascal (1623-1662), is responsible for a famous witticism: ``If
Cleopatra's nose had been one inch longer, history would have been
utterly different.'' He used the shorthand expression,
``Cleopatra's nose,'' twice in his book of meditations, Pensees, to
stand for the absurd, crazy, minute things on which great events
sometimes hinge.
</P>
<P>
   We have portraits of Cleopatra on coins that show her to be a
very strong-featured, beaky-nosed Eastern Mediterranean type _
Pascal needn't have mocked her; her nose was plenty long already.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on ancient sources, Will Durant, in the third volume of
his Story of Civilization, writes that she was ``more probably
blond than brunette. She was not particularly beautiful, but the
grace of her carriage, the vivacity of her body and her mind, the
variety of her accomplishments, the suavity of her manners, the
very melody of her voice, combined with her royal position to make
her a heady wine even for a Roman general.''
</P>
<P>
   She was 24 when she met Mark Antony, 31 when she clasped the
fatal asp to her bosom in 30 B.C. Black revisionist historians such
as J.A. Rogers have claimed that she was black, but classical
scholar Mary Lefkowitz, in her 1996 book, Not Out Of Africa, has
pointed out that she was almost certainly of Greek, Macedonian
stock. She may, just possibly, have had a black grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie would probably have beaten Cleopatra in a beauty contest,
even in antiquity. But then Cleopatra would begin to speak, and
Barbie would simply fade away. The Egyptian queen had that quality
so mispraised on blind dates: She had personality.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Browning writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
