<SLUG> BC-BARBIE-SIDE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roman doll in coffin dead ringer for Barbie
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ On the morning of May 12, 1889,
construction workers building the new Ministry of Justice building
in Rome, on the right bank of the Tiber River near the mausoleum of
the emperor Hadrian, found a small marble coffin embedded in a
layer of blue clay, 25 feet below street level. It was filled with
water.
</P>
<P>
   It was inscribed simply, with a girl's name: Crepereia
Tryphaena. The eminent Roman archaeologist, Rodolfo Lanciani, was
present at the coffin's opening and describes the scene in his 1893
book, Pagan and Christian Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gazing at the skeleton through the veil of clear water, we saw
the skull covered, as it were, with long masses of brown hair,
which were floating in the liquid crystal. ... The mystery of the
hair is easily explained. Together with the springwater, germs or
seeds of an aquatic plant had entered the sarcophagus, settled on
the convex surface of the skull, and developed into long glossy
threads of a dark shade.''
</P>
<P>
   What set Crepereia Tryphaena apart, however, was not her
remains, or her vegetable hair, but the fact that she had been
buried with her doll, ``an exquisite little doll, carved of oak,
which was lying on the scapula, or shoulder blade.''
</P>
<P>
   The doll was about a foot high, just about the size of a modern
Barbie doll, and its limbs were jointed, like Barbie's. They could
still be flexed, even after so many centuries. The oak had hardened
over the years to the toughness of metal.
</P>
<P>
   It was a figurine of a full-grown woman, with breasts and hips,
and an elaborate hair-do piled up on the head in a style popular
with Roman women from about 150 A.D. forward. It had probably worn
clothes, but these had deteriorated over the centuries. She carried
two gold key rings in one hand, similar to those carried by Roman
housewives, which showed they had full authority over domestic
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In short, just like Barbie, Crepereia Tryphaena's doll was
intended to show a grown-up young woman, in the full bloom of
health, with a definite role in life: That of a prosperous
housewife or chatelaine, fully in charge of a large, well-ordered
household. She was not a mere plaything, but an expression of hope
in a happy future, a symbol of fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   Lanciani called the doll ``exquisite,'' ``a work of art in
itself. It is modeled in perfect imitation of a woman's form and
ranks among the finest of its kind yet found in Roman
excavations.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry, the style of the inscription and other items in the
sarcophagus help date it to around 200 A.D. Crepereia Tryphaena was
not a Roman noblewoman, but the teenaged daughter of a wealthy
freedman, or ex-slave. A betrothal ring inscribed Philotas shows
she was engaged to be married at the time of her early death to a
young Greek named Philotas.
</P>
<P>
   She wore a myrtle crown, a betrothal crown, around her head, and
its leaves were still preserved.
</P>
<P>
   It was customary for young women to give up their dolls on their
wedding day, dedicating them either to Venus or Diana. But because
Crepereia Tryphaena died before she was wed, her doll followed her
into the grave, whence it emerged nearly 1,700 years later, in far
better condition than its owner. Dolls can be a lot tougher than
little girls.
</P>
<P>
   Just as little girls look to Barbie and hope for the same
radiant glamor and success, with a handsome Ken silent and
supportive at their sides, so Crepereia Tryphaena probably loved
her doll for its promise of happy wedlock with Philotas. Both
Barbie and the ancient oaken doll have a kind of talismanic
quality. They are embodiments of wishful, make-believe joy.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen centuries are not enough to remake the human heart.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   Michael Browning writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
