<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Be mime, baby: Not all couples should talk it over
 &HT;    By Matt Reed
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Relationship experts have dished out the
same advice for years: If you've got a problem with your spouse or
sweetheart, talk it over, clear the air, don't avoid confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   And now, with the state pushing marriage-license applicants into
pre-wedding counseling, more Florida couples are bound to try
gabbing their way to happiness.
</P>
<P>
   But silence, it turns out, has been vastly underrated.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at two U.S. universities have found that couples
with excellent communication skills are not necessarily happier
than couples with poor skills. In fact, skilled communicators are
more likely to worsen an unhappy marriage, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be married to a skilled communicator if
things aren't going well,'' says Brant Burleson, a communications
professor at Purdue University. ``They know just where to stick the
knife _ and how to twist it to cause maximum pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Burleson and Dr. Wayne Denton, a psychiatrist at Wake Forest
University, studied 60 couples. Half were determined to be happy;
the other half were deemed ``distressed,'' based on results of
screening tests. The couples came from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
   The happiest of the happy couples had wives with strong
communication skills. The women used those skills to improve their
marriages, researchers found. And among those lovey-dovey couples,
the degree of happiness dropped when the women had poor
communication skills.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``distressed'' couples were a different story. The most
miserable were those with wives considered to be skilled
communicators. Those women, already in damaged relationships, used
language and psychology to inflict more pain, making it worse.
</P>
<P>
   With distressed couples, the less skilled the wife, the less
hurt and angry the husband. That doesn't necessarily mean women
should suffer in silence. It simply means that the less-skilled
women had better chances of fixing their marriages because they
weren't doing more damage, the research found.
</P>
<P>
   And the men?
</P>
<P>
   In both groups, the husbands' communication skills _ whether
good or bad _ didn't seem to affect couples' happiness as much as
the wives. That's because women's ``primary confidantes'' tend to
be other women, research showed. Men, on the other hand, seldom
confide in anyone but their wives, so they have more riding on that
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you listen to the talk shows, pretty quickly you might come
to realize that problems happen in relationships because couples
don't communicate enough. The pat answer is, `Talk more,'''
Burleson says. ``The clinical implication here is that
communication-skills training is not the panacea it's been made out
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Next time you feel conflict brewing, Burleson says, ask yourself
this: ``Do you really want to hurt your spouse? Or do you really
need some `time out' so you can focus on the goals of the
relationship?''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Reed writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
