<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHAMPBAILEY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Next Deion? Bailey set to make impact in NFL draft
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Roland ``Champ'' Bailey Jr. had the inscription
``DB-43'' stenciled onto his jersey at the NFL combine last week,
but he didn't need white block printing to distinguish him from the
46 other defensive-back prospects on hand.
</P>
<P>
   His performances have been enough.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, a former University of Georgia player, is being compared
to Deion Sanders and is listed as the No. 1 cornerback by scouts
preparing for the 1999 NFL draft on April 17.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts say Bailey should be selected in the first five picks and
might make an even bigger immediate impact on the league in 1999
than Oakland Raiders cornerback Charles Woodson, last season's
defensive rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's truly a great player, so I guess (the nickname Champ)
fits,'' Pittsburgh Steelers director of football operations Tom
Donahoe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His game is as good as his name,'' Donahoe said. ``When the
ball is in his hands, something is going to happen, and it's going
to be something good. The only question about him is how he's going
to be used at the NFL level. He's so good and such a catalyst that
there is going to be a natural temptation to do too much with
Champ.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey has sound techniques and an economy of motion rare for
such a young player. While he might lack the explosiveness of
Sanders, scouts think he will be the most complete cornerback to
enter the NFL since the former Falcons star in 1989. Bailey said he
is flattered by such comparisons but won't permit them to swell his
head.
</P>
<P>
   A strained hamstring, suffered running track this winter, kept
Bailey from challenging Sanders' combine record of 4.28 seconds in
the 40-yard dash.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, few prospects have matched the versatility of
Bailey, a Folkston native. During his final season in Athens, he
averaged 87 plays a game _ on offense, defense and special teams _
and excelled.
</P>
<P>
   Most scouts said the variety of roles at Georgia will enhance
Bailey's draft status. But those same scouts said Bailey should be
be evaluated as a cornerback _ and with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The corner spot has become a glamour position in the NFL and has
outdistanced wide receiver in overall significance. In the last two
drafts, twice as many cornerbacks as wide receivers (12-6) have
gone in the first round. During the '90s, the first round has
included 34 cornerbacks and 26 wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   The one-year contract tender for ``franchise'' free-agent
corners has increased to $4.269 million; only quarterback, at $5.88
million, is higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a premium position, and Bailey is a premium player,'' New
England secondary coach Ron Lynn said. ``There aren't many
'shut-down' corners like him who come along very often. Why clutter
up the kid's mind with offensive stuff his first year? To me, you
put him on the corner and let him play.''
</P>
<P>
   With the draft about seven weeks away, most teams rate Bailey as
the third-best prospect, behind Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch and
Texas tailback Ricky Williams. The only defender who might go ahead
of him is Southern Cal linebacker Chris Claiborne.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cincinnati appears to be leaning toward taking a
quarterback with the third overall choice, the Bengals will
consider Bailey to help shore up their secondary. ``He'd be the
least risk,'' Bengals owner Mike Brown said. ``He'd come in and he
would start. He'd be good. Take him first, and you could move on
then in later rounds to helping yourself elsewhere. You'd know you
had a least one 'keeper,' that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said he would prefer to spend his rookie season in the
NFL playing cornerback before expanding his horizons. He knows that
the position is daunting, with defenders one completion away from
disaster and disdain. But he said he is ready for the challenge of
trying to stop the league's top receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team I've met with here asks me what I like better, and
I've told them all I want to (play) cornerback,'' Bailey said.
``That's where I feel I can make the most impact for a team right
away. I really don't know what my upside would be (at wide
receiver). With the limited exposure I got there, I played pretty
well. But I really want to focus in that first season on being a
good cornerback.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland coach Jon Gruden, who flirted with the idea of teaching
Woodson a few basic pass patterns last year, agreed that Bailey
should be a one-position performer in 1999. Even in Woodson's
second NFL season, Gruden said, he might not play more than five or
six snaps a game at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a risk in putting him at wideout,'' Gruden said. ``We
want him on the field to be the guy erasing the other team's best
receiver. Champ will be the same, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most of the cornerbacks invited to the combine this
decade, Bailey is not noted for his trash-talking, and personnel
directors said they found that lack to be refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play with a lot of confidence, but I play calm,'' said
Bailey, who measured with combine officials at 5-foot-11 1/2, 184
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey will work out for NFL scouts in Athens on March 17, and
some might be surprised at his speed. In two meets in which he ran
the 55-yard dash, Bailey was timed unofficially at the 40-yard mark
in under 4.3 seconds. Such timings are unscientific, but they offer
a hint as to how well Bailey might perform for scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already a top five (pick),'' Tennessee Titans general
manager Floyd Reese said. ``If he goes out and runs under 4.4, look
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
