A4305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FISH-DEAD-COX     03-02 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FISH-DEAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    River waste killing marine life in Florida
 &HT;    By Sally D. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Jet black'' waste from a
citrus-processing plant south of Fort Pierce has been leaking into
the North Fork of the St. Lucie River, killing fish and microscopic
marine life along a 7-mile stretch of the waterway, state officials
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this has been killing fish since the beginning of
February,'' Department of Environmental Protection scientist Greg
Graves said. ``Nothing can live in that whole stretch of the river.
It has no dissolved oxygen in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The affected area reaches from the junction of Five Mile and Ten
Mile creeks south to Prima Vista Boulevard in Port St. Lucie,
including a section designated as an outstanding Florida waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists last week pinpointed SunPure's Indian River Foods
processing plant on Selvitz Road as the source of the pollution,
Graves said.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid waste, a byproduct of the juice-making process, is
usually stored in a canal on a nearby citrus grove, where it is
used in a diluted form for irrigation. But officials said it broke
through a rusted culvert and traveled down another grove's canals
into the river.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a citizen's complaint, DEP river-keeper Dana Fike
and scientist Doug Strom took a boat up the narrow, winding river
and saw the discharge coming from the grove.
</P>
<P>
   The waste, which Graves described as ``jet black,'' may contain
complex sugars that rob the water of dissolved oxygen which most
fish and microscopic marine creatures need to survive. Final test
results on samples of the waste will be available later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Air-breathing fish such as tarpon can survive in oxygen-poor
waters, but dozens of other species die. DEP officials said they
couldn't estimate the number of fish killed. Many of the fish were
eaten by birds and tarpon or sank to the river bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can be done, really,'' Graves said. ``The water moves
back and forth with the tides, and fish that swim into that area
will die. This could go on another month.''
</P>
<P>
   Resident Franklin Lofton, who lives near the place where Five
Mile and Ten Mile creeks converge to form the North Fork, said he
has seen dead mullet and small-mouth bass floating in the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd really like to see this river become something other than
a sewer,'' Lofton said. ``Manatees are here with their babies
now.''
</P>
<P>
   An unexplained fish kill in the same area last April could be
linked to the processing plant discharge, Graves said.
</P>
<P>
   John Moulton, DEP's assistant regional director, said the
processing plant could be fined or forced to buy fish to restock
the river, but penalties would not be imposed until bureaucratic
procedures, including warning letters, have been followed. That
could take months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indian River Foods officials responded quickly to stop the
discharge, filling a canal to stop the flow and repairing damaged
culverts, Moulton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a lot of pride in handling our waste,'' plant manager
Larry Gray said Monday. ``As soon as we discovered the leak, we
immediately dammed it off and repaired the culvert. We are very
concerned about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally D. Swartz writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
