<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4418 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FATHERS03-COX     03-02 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FATHERS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEW TV FATHERS PROJECT POSITIVE IMAGES
 &HT;    440&AMP;add. With TV-FATHERS-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (e)
entertainment categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Father rarely knows best on prime-time television
any more.
</P>
<P>
   Fathers are central, recurring figures on only 15 of 102
prime-time network comedies or dramas, and only four of these
programs portray the dad as both competent and caring, the National
Fatherhood Initiative reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of good dads on TV is especially problematic because
nearly 40 percent of the nation's children do not live with their
biological fathers, and whole communities exist where almost all
the households are headed by single mothers, said Wade Horn,
president of the non-partisan organization that aims to promote
responsible fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``For millions of America's children, the primary daily contact
they have with the idea of a father is the time they spend watching
a father on television,'' the group's ``Fatherhood &AMP; TV'' viewer
analysis concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were based on a five-week review of the prime-time
programming on the ABC, NBC, CBS, Fox and WB networks during the
late autumn of 1998. Shows were rated if they met three criteria: a
father was a recurring character, the relationship between the
father and his children was a defining feature, and the father's
children were 18 or younger.
</P>
<P>
   The reviewers _ National Fatherhood Initiative staffers _ found
only 15 programs, or 14.7 percent of the total schedule, that
featured fatherhood enough to be rated. NBC's ``Frasier'' did not
meet the criteria, for instance, because the central character's
son lives across the country in Boston with his mother, and they
are rarely mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 programs were rated as to the the dad's involvement in
family activities, one-on-one engagement with his child, guidance
as a positive role model, competence both inside and outside the
family, and priority of placing his family role first.
</P>
<P>
   The study rated only four programs as portraying fathers
positively: ``7th Heaven'' on WB, ``Promised Land'' on CBS, ``Smart
Guy'' on WB, and ``Two of a Kind'' on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime-time TV and the network bosses have a lot of work to do
to improve the way fathers are viewed and portrayed,'' said Rep.
Joseph Pitts, R-Pa., co-chairman of the Congressional Task Force on
Fatherhood Promotion.
</P>
<P>
   The report concludes that it is ``unrealistic'' to expect
television programmers alone ``to bear the responsibility for
promoting responsible fatherhood.'' However, it said TV should
portray more ``responsible, committed and responsible fathers'' at
a time when such dads are missing from the lives of millions of
young viewers.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Horn said there has been a dramatic change in television
families over the decades. Gone are most of the wise, loving dads
from '50s and '60s programs such as ``Father Knows Best'' and
``Leave It to Beaver,'' and even '80's programs such as ``The Cosby
Show'' and ``Family Ties.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's TV families mainly feature dads who are either competent
men but uninvolved parents, like the father on CBS's ``The Nanny''
and Fox's ``That 70s Show,'' or caring, engaged fathers who are
incompetent like Tim ``The Toolman'' Taylor on ABC's ``Home
Improvement.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, fathers and father figures have largely
disappeared from TV families, noted Horn. In the '50s and '60s, the
mother was the one missing from non-intact families on programs
such as ``My Three Sons,'' ``The Andy Griffith Show,'' and
``Bachelor Father.'' Today it is the fathers who are gone on shows
popular with children such as ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,''
``Sabrina,'' and ``Jessie.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, when many families watch TV together,
``network television is fatherless,'' the report said. On NBC,
there is only one father on the prime-time schedule, Paul Reiser's
character on ``Mad About You.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few permissible stereotypes still thriving on
television is the dumb dad like Fox's Homer Simpson, said Horn.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
