<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRDNAME-AUCTION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A UNIQUE FLIGHT OF FANCY: AUDUBON AUCTIONING RIGHT TO NAME NEW BIRD
SPECIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Immortality _ at least in birding circles _
will go on the auction block Friday when the Texas Audubon Society
sells the right to name a species of bird recently discovered in
the Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   Audubon officials described it as ``a subtly beautiful
antshrike,'' a robin-size bird that eats insects.
</P>
<P>
   The bird was discovered last year by Bret Whitney of Austin, who
donated the right to name it.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum bid: $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   It happens Friday at Bass Performance Hall, where the Texas
Audubon Society will host a gala in honor of its 100th birthday,
one of several celebrations planned statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity for one committed
auction guest,'' said Catriona Glazebrook, executive director of
the Texas Audubon Society. ``Never before has such a unique
privilege been made available to the public, and the benefit to
bird conservation will be an unprecedented one.''
</P>
<P>
   The highest bidder will have the honor of adding the Latinized
version of his or her name, or any name, to the scientific name for
the new species of thamnophilus antshrike.
</P>
<P>
   Should the winner be named ``Bubba,'' for instance, the bird
could become known as ``Thamnophilus bubbaus.'' The winner also
gets a watercolor painting of the bird and a taped recording of its
song.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bird is extremely nice-looking, especially the female,''
said Noreen Damude, director of bird conservation for the Texas
Audubon Society.
</P>
<P>
   Damude said 74 percent of the proceeds from the sale will be
used to launch the Important Bird Areas Program in Texas _ an
effort to identify the state's important bird habitats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know a lot of them, but what hasn't been done is monitoring
and habitat management,'' she said. ``Also, since Texas is 97
percent privately owned, the biggest challenge is getting private
landowners to join in wanting to conserve wildlife.''
</P>
<P>
   The other 26 percent of the auction proceeds will be used to
prepare a field guide to the birds of Brazil, where the antshrike
was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Charley Amos of Arlington, president of
Audubon's Fort Worth chapter, said he believes that an area on the
border between Fort Worth and Arlington may deserve classification
and protection as an important bird area, or IBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's at the Village Creek Drying Beds, an area at the
intersection of Green Oaks Boulevard and Fielder Road,'' Amos said.
``During migration we counted about 275 different species that use
that area. We would like to get it declared an important bird
area.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Audubon chapter in Texas was formed March 4, 1899, in
Galveston in an effort to save birds whose feathers had become an
important feature in ladies' hats. The Texas Audubon Society now
has 20 chapters with 40,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   Amos said the Fort Worth chapter was formed in 1941 and now has
about 1,500 members. Those interested in joining can call him at
(817) 265-9208.
</P>
<P>
   Several people, including Lady Bird Johnson, will be recognized
at the event Friday for their contributions to Audubon. The former
first lady has been invited but is not expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   More than four dozen items will be auctioned, including artworks
by Stuart and Scott Gentling of Fort Worth, air travel, hotel
accommodations, meals, jewelry, symphony tickets, wildlife tours,
gift certificates and various bird accouterments such as feeders,
baths and houses.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
