<HEADLINE>
WHY WE'RE SEEING DOLLAR SIGNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My sister is a teacher, and one of her students asked this
question: What's the origin of the dollar sign, and why is it the
letter ``S'' with a line drawn through it?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.W., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: The ``$'' sign appears to be a descendant of ``ps,'' an
abbreviation for the Spanish peso.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Adams writes in ``Return of the Straight Dope'' that
Florian Cajori researched the topic extensively for his book, ``A
History of Mathematical Notations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Spanish dollar, also known as the `peso de 8 reales,' was
the principle coin in circulation in the United States up until
1795,'' Adams writes. ``As time went by, the P and the S tended to
get mashed together and the result was $.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 18th century, ``$'' began to be used exclusively as
the symbol for the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm a big fan of ``Les Miserables'' and I understand there's
a newsletter called ``The Barricade.'' Where can I find this? Also,
will the show be in Texas soon?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.D., Granbury, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The Barricade'' is published by Sharon L. Taylor at Box
541885, Houston, TX 77254. The newsletter costs $4 for an issue or
$11 for a three-issue subscription.
</P>
<P>
   The production will be staged March 17-21 at the Will Rogers
Memorial Center in Fort Worth. Call (888) 597-7827 for ticket
information.
</P>
<P>
   It also is scheduled for Amarillo, now through Sunday; College
Station March 23-28; and Corpus Christi March 30-April 4.
</P>
<P>
   A complete tour schedule is available from the official World
Wide Web site at www.lesmis.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to NASCAR driver Bobby Labonte?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.W., Joshua, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: You can write to Labonte and other members of the Joe Gibbs
Racing team at 13415 Reese Blvd., Huntersville, NC 28078.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte also has an official fan club; membership costs $25.49
per year. Members receive a newsletter, cap, diecast 1999
Interstate Batteries car and souvenir discounts.
</P>
<P>
   To join, call (877) 426-2295 or write to Bobby Labonte Fan Club,
4707 East Baseline Road, Phoenix, AZ 85040.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
