<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK NEEDS TOUGH LAWS, NOT GIULIANI JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Walking by the Albany City Hall Friday, I found
myself wondering, ``Is Jerry Jennings as nutty as Rudy Giuliani?''
</P>
<P>
   So, I stuck my head inside the mayor's office. He was out, but
he came roaring in a few minutes later, preparing to do the local
radio talk show.
</P>
<P>
   What did I want, the mayor demanded?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you going to have your cops start confiscating the cars of
people they bust on drunken driving charges.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you, nuts?'' Jerry Jennings responded. ``Me and the
police are going to serve as judge and jury? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Good answer. But that's precisely what Rudolph Giuliani is doing
in New York City. That's what some other dangerously demented
politicians started doing in Nassau and Suffolk Counties on Long
Island, once Giuliani gave them the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy, Rudy, Rudy. What are we going to do with you? You can take
the mayor out of the prosecutor's office, but you can't take the
prosecutor's office out of the mayor. By any yardstick, Giuliani
has been a good mayor for New York City. Sure, he has benefited
from a booming economy. And, sure, the dramatic drop in the city's
crime rate has been mirrored across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But, on balance, Rudy rules. Rightly, he gets credit for
restoring New York City, the world's greatest urban center, to its
past glory. He has presided over the rebirth of Times Square. He
has waged righteous war on the seedier aspects of urban life.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, though, you have to wonder if this guy
doesn't have a screw loose somewhere. If he's not showing up in
drag on ``Saturday Night Live'' or leaping into some pointless
personal dispute with somebody, large or small, he's embarked on
yet another quest to display his relentlessly authoritarian
tendencies _ like his efforts to chase hot dog vendors off the
streets of Manhattan. With Giuliani as mayor, you could get busted
in the Big Apple for scalping low numbers at the deli.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, drunken drivers kill somebody in America every half hour
and injure somebody every minute-and-a-half. Sure, about 42 people
a year are killed by drunken drivers in New York City. OK, the city
cops bust 7,500 people a year for drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   But the way to fix that is to persuade those spaghetti-spined
wusses in the New York Legislature to mandate longer terms for
drunken drivers. Why, for instance, should Michele Tracey, who
drunkenly ran down and killed a 15-year-old girl in Troy, get only
five years in the slammer, as she did Friday? Confiscating the
property of the accused before a judge and/or jury finds them
guilty is no real solution, even though some district attorneys
have done it a few times.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Well, believe it or not, cops and prosecutors do make
mistakes once in a while. That's why we have courtrooms to begin
with.
</P>
<P>
   Under Giuliani's system, anybody wrongly accused will be without
a car until and unless he or she can prove his or her innocence _
not just in criminal court but in a separate civil court
proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's plan surely will be challenged, and it might not
hold up. On the other hand it might. This dangerous ground was
broken nicely by letting cops grab the assets of suspected, but
unconvicted, drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, only the Legislature can protect New York state's
residents from the law enforcement excesses of Giuliani and his
misguided imitators. Show some guts, lawmakers. Pass a few laws to
curb this nuttiness.
</P>
<P>
   Stop Rudy before he confiscates again.
</P>
<P>
   And stop the drunken drivers, too.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
