<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN YOU NAME TEXAS' ORIGINAL VICE PRESIDENT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BUD KENNEDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our ignorance of Texas history has been bared for embarrassing
public view of late.
</P>
<P>
   First, McDonald's published a page of Texas ``facts'' that is so
flawed, it is useful only to wrap burgers.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a Dallas newspaper reported that one-third of Texans and
``Tejanos'' can't name anyone who died in the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   Such memory loss is common among Texans who inhaled the Austin
air in the 1970s, or any Texan who has consumed too much Lone Star
beer. That's why this space is reserved today for a Texas
Independence Day history discourse, on one particular bit of
Republic lore.
</P>
<P>
   I know a favorite trivia question that stumps every audience. It
begins: ``Who became the very first president of Texas?'' Somebody
typically guesses Sam Houston, and he was the first ``elected''
president, succeeding appointed provisional President David Burnet.
</P>
<P>
   Most Texans recognize the name Burnet. They know the namesake
city, or the street in downtown Fort Worth, although city signs now
misspell it ``Burnett.'' (Maybe the signs were printed by
McDonald's.)
</P>
<P>
   I have yet to find a Texan, though, who can name Texas' original
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Remember this guy. He's relevant to modern Texas.
</P>
<P>
   When the struggling Republic of Texas was barely days old, the
second-in-command was a Texas settler from Mexico. He had been a
city council member, representative and senator in his native
Merida.
</P>
<P>
   From Day One on March 2, 1836, Texas was built jointly by two
cultures speaking two languages. The state's original No. 2
executive was Manuel Lorenzo Justiniano de Zavala y S enz _ known
as Vice President Lorenzo de Zavala.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a genuine intellectual,'' said Texas historian Margaret
S. Henson of Houston, author of a 1996 biography titled ``Lorenzo
de Zavala: The Pragmatic Idealist.''
</P>
<P>
   She went on: ``He was the best educated man at
Washington-on-the-Brazos,'' where Texans declared independence from
Coahuila and Mexico. ``He was the most experienced politician. He
was a published author who spoke three languages.''
</P>
<P>
   A seminary graduate and political progressive who had ascended
to become secretary of the treasury in Mexico, Zavala was sent on a
diplomatic mission to Paris as unrest began in Texas. A political
enemy of President Santa Anna, Zavala knew he could not return to
Mexico safely and instead returned to land he had bought in
southeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secretly, I think he wanted to go back and restore Mexico,''
Henson said. ``But he knew his only hope was in Texas. ... I bet
there was a very interesting conversation when he saw Santa Anna
again after the battle of San Jacinto.''
</P>
<P>
   The final battle was fought April 21 near Zavala's land,
although he was safely hidden away in Galveston. Now, Zavala is
remembered with a historical marker near the San Jacinto Monument,
across from the Battleship Texas.
</P>
<P>
   His 10-month term as vice president ended when he resigned with
Burnet in October, making way for elected President Houston and
Vice President Mirabeau Lamar. Days later, Zavala's rowboat
overturned in the bayou. He fell ill and died Nov. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he must have been depressed at the end,'' Henson said.
``He didn't like Burnet. Burnet didn't give him enough to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``And on the East Coast, he was well-known as this cosmopolitan
thinker.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in Texas, he kept running into discrimination. The Anglos
treated anyone from Mexico like some kind of servant. Even the
other Hispanic leaders didn't trust him, because he was from a
completely different part of Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Henson began studying Zavala when Hispanic
preservationists in Houston asked about his background. As she
recalls, they asked: ``The only Hispanic name around Houston is
Zavala. Can you tell us about him? We don't really know anything
about Zavala.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Texas needs to know more about Zavala.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
