r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     03-02 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD HEALTH IS NOTHING TO SNEEZE AT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``People who feel well are sick people neglecting themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jules Romains, French novelist, poet, dramatist
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what would happen if we spent as much time talking
about our good health as we do talking about our illnesses?
Certainly, I'm concerned about my friends' and family's state of
well-being. If they're going to be hospitalized or undergo
diagnostic tests, I'd like to be aware of it so that I can support
them. But some people are not content being sick alone, they have
to make you sick with them.
</P>
<P>
   I made the mistake of coughing during lunch one day and someone
commented, ``Oh, you're getting that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What stuff?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that awful virus that's going around. Next you'll have a
fever and cough and then you won't be able to walk for a week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was eating a cracker and it got stuck in my throat,'' I
protested. ``I'm not sick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, you are,'' she insisted. ``That's how it starts. The same
thing happened to me. You'd better go home and get in the bed right
away. Sometimes, your legs give out while you're driving. You'll
probably crash before you make it to your house. I sure feel sorry
for you.''
</P>
<P>
   I was in bed for two days before my husband said, ``Look, this
is not ER. You are not sick and that woman was not a doctor. Go
outside and get some fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   If you think I'm exaggerating, just try telling a few people
that you're having a root canal next week. You will hear the most
amazing and incredible tales of death and destruction than any
``Star Trek'' episode you have ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   ``My cousin had a root canal and it made her eyes turn blue and
her voice got real deep, like Barry White. Her mother kicked her
out and she traveled with the circus for a while. Now she works in
Jamaica selling mangoes to the tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy at my job got a root canal and he left his wife the
same day. Two days later he was in a car crash and totaled his
sports car. That tooth popped out and now he wears it around his
neck on a gold chain. His wife divorced him too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard that this girl had that procedure done and as soon as
she left the dentist's office, an elbow grew out her neck and now
she has to look down all of the time. Her shoes always look great,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazing, I say. Simply amazing.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the procedure is, someone has had it before or
they know someone who did and it definitely didn't go well. It
could be a technique that was just invented in Geneva yesterday and
I'm certain someone would say, ``No, my sister had that same
surgery except they went in through her navel and came out of her
nose. And you definitely do not want to be around when she
sneezes.''
</P>
<P>
   We all know that the vast majority of medical procedures are
successful. Sure, there are risks and side effects but science is
truly amazing. However, there was the time that my friend had that
sinus surgery and ... oh, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564 or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
