<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4473 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-02 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNING: LIFE MAY BE HAZARDOUS TO YOUR HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Warning: Subject looking back at you in mirror
may be stupider than he or she appears.
</P>
<P>
   Or so think the people who put warning labels on almost every
product you use.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: This Batman cape will not allow wearer to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: This army helmet is a toy and will not prevent injury.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: Avoid contact of Formula 409 with foods.
</P>
<P>
   Those are warning labels that already exist. It's all the
lawyers' fault. Lawyers fight for the right of stupid people to do
stupid things and survive _ and then get rich for being stupid.
</P>
<P>
   They're trying to counteract Darwin and the law of survival of
the fittest. It's survival of the fattest, and the fattest are
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Now the auto industry and federal safety officials are arguing
about how to warn people that certain sport utility vehicles roll
over easily. Come on. We want buyers of sport utility vehicles to
live?
</P>
<P>
   The current warning already fills visors of SUVs. Automakers are
fighting a new graphic that shows a tipping SUV with a passenger
falling out the window.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one looks at these warnings, except as the
defense's Exhibit A when some yuppie sues the manufacturer after a
triple lutz in a Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: Warning labels may cause unhealthy ideological battles
in America.
</P>
<P>
   A group called the Christian Action Network wants to put ``HC''
labels (for ``homosexual content'') on television shows with gay
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Winemakers are putting labels on bottles suggesting that wine
may be good for the health. This is opposed by a strange alliance
of Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., and do-good liberals who think
reading the labels will send innocents straight to hell or Betty
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Stamped on the side of guns are inscriptions like the following,
found on Berettas: ``Warning: Read instruction manual before
using.''
</P>
<P>
   The manual tells you useful things, like to unload the gun
before cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Do we really want people who clean loaded guns to live? I don't
know about women, but how many red-blooded American males have ever
read an instruction manual before they used anything?
</P>
<P>
   The first time a man looks at a manual is when he can't find a
car's jack, reset a videocassette recorder or put his disassembled
gun back together.
</P>
<P>
   If anti-gun groups really wanted to stop gun sales, they'd
legislate more warnings to be stamped all over firearms, ruining
the blue-steel allure.
</P>
<P>
   Make guns as wordy as ladders, and no one would buy them.
</P>
<P>
   Well, except criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: The number of warnings on a product is in inverse
proportion to the power of the product's lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The ladder lobby isn't as powerful as the gun lobby, so every
surface of a ladder has a sticker saying ``Danger'' and a picture
of a stick figure taking a header.
</P>
<P>
   A Davidson aluminum ladder has six warning labels with 27
warnings, ranging from ``Danger: electrical hazard, watch for
wires'' to ``Face ladder when climbing up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   Do we really want people who go up ladders backward to live?
</P>
<P>
   A hardware store is a veritable festival of warning labels.
</P>
<P>
   A tack hammer had a sticker that took up half the handle. It
started with ``Warning: protect your eyes`` and ended with ``Strike
squarely _ avoid glancing blows.''
</P>
<P>
   Like that's going to help if you failed shop in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Super Glue has a useful one. ``Caution: eye irritant. Instantly
bonds skin. See back panel.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, your eyes are bonded shut, but if you could see the back
panel you'd read ``Do not use Super Glue Remover or nail polish
remover in case of eye contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Do we really want people who rub nail polish remover in their
eyes to live?
</P>
<P>
   Warning: Warning labels warn us about all the wrong things.
</P>
<P>
   People with half a brain know not to leave loaded guns within
reach of children and not to stand on the top step of a ladder.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't know, they're definitely not going to read some
little sticker _ or be able to read it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
