<HEADER>
A4492 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-BIG-SCORE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     03-02 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BIG-SCORE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 MALDEN, Mass.: ... court documents.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``His face turned red. He was yelling and screaming,'' Chretien
said in an interview. ``He said he would throw me down the stairs
and kill me.'' Robbins also allegedly threatened to send someone to
Chretien's condominium in Revere and beat him up. Chretien said he
was so concerned about the threat that he asked Revere police to
accompany him back to his condominium.
</P>
<P>
   A similar tale of rage was told by Robbins's former wife,
Barbara, in court papers seeking a restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   On a late-night visit to his wife's condominium on Feb. 11,
1996, Robbins rushed to her upstairs bedroom and jumped her as she
lay in bed, she said. Kneeling on her chest to keep her down, he
held her arms down with one hand and squeezed her nose with the
other hand so she couldn't breathe, Barbara Robbins stated.
</P>
<P>
   One of their sons, called to the bedroom by his mother, broke up
the confrontation. Before Robbins left that night, he ``told my
boys he would have killed me if they weren't there,'' Barbara
Robbins stated in an affidavit seeking a restraining order against
her husband, preventing him from approaching her at home or work.
</P>
<P>
   The order remained in effect until last September. The couple's
divorce was finalized last May.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta was raised in the Edgeworth section of Malden on
Devir Street, near one of the city's showpieces, Devir Park. Always
the biggest kid on the block, Trischitta became a fixture at city
sporting events, but always on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   At Malden High School, from which Trischitta graduated in 1970,
he received varsity letters for managing the baseball, hockey, and
basketball teams. He kept score and watched the clock. It's a role
he kept through his life, refereeing Pop Warner and high school
games, and, as recently as last season, tending to the clock at
Friday night Malden Catholic football games.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta was known as a class clown, a teenager who considered
himself a thespian, choosing theater arts as an elective and
impressing the class with his improvisations of Casey at the Bat.
</P>
<P>
   More than one teacher said they have fond memories of
Trischitta, whose enthusiasm inspired classmates.
</P>
<P>
   But some of his peers, who remember him on the sidelines, said
his constant presence on the periphery, wanting desperately to step
into the center, struck them as pathetic. They called him the `bag
boy' and the `caddy' sometimes, teasing him. But Trixie, they said,
could take a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, Trischitta has struggled to control his
weight. At one point he underwent a stomach stapling operation to
remove fat, former coworkers said.
</P>
<P>
   As an adult, Trischitta managed the men's baseball team
sponsored by Augustine's restaurant, and spent summer nights under
the lights at Devir Park watching games.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta never graduated from college and made an unsuccessful
run at local politics when he lost a primary election for Malden
city councilor in 1978. That same year he landed a low-level job
working as a teller at the state treasurer's office.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta, who declined interview requests, dabbled in real
estate on the side but let his agent's license lapse. Since the
early 1980s, he earned extra income working as a justice of the
peace, marrying about a dozen couples a year for $100 each. His
wife, Diane, worked part-time as a home health aide, according to
friends. The couple have two young children.
</P>
<P>
   If Robbins was tasting the good life, there is no indication
Trischitta was living luxuriously. He owned a battered and aged
Honda Accord and his wife drove a seven-year-old Ford Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the couple built a home in Stoneham now valued
at $343,400. While the home might seem outside the price range of a
state employee earning $57,000 a year, the cost was offset by
Trischitta's mother selling her Medford home and moving in with her
son, friends say.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta seemed most comfortable when he was back in the gym
or at the field, operating the scoreboard and talking with old
friends from his days at Malden High.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought John would go into sports administration or
management,'' said Lou Racca, a former coach and teacher at Malden
High School. ``He really loved sports.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those who know both men say they were not friendly in high
school because of the four-year age difference.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, when Malden established a public access
cable channel, Robbins was involved with programming sports events
for the channel. He even had the license plate ``TV 13,'' which was
the channel number for the public access programming.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta also volunteered to help with the cable programming
and friends speculate the pair may have become acquainted then.
</P>
<P>
   Both men also moved in local political circles, although Robbins
was more active with Republicans and Trischitta with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible link to the pair is Robbins's younger brother,
Jerry, who is closer in age to Trischitta. Jerry Robbins has worked
for 1994 Senate candidate John Lakian and as a fund-raiser for
State Senator Richard R. Tisei, a Wakefield Republican, from 1991
to 1993. One Malden businessman said he remembers being introduced
to Trischitta by Jerry Robbins at an event three years ago. Jerry
Robbins declined an interview request.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say both Trischitta and Marty Robbins separately told
State Police who arrested them 10 days ago that they were friendly
with Metropolitan District Commission chief David B. Balfour Jr.
Balfour, a former advance man for President George Bush, has worked
for both Governor Paul Cellucci and former governor William F.
Weld.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Balfour said he recently ran into Marty Robbins
at Cellucci's inaugural in January, but was surprised Robbins would
use his name when arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a drink with him, I've never had dinner with
him, I've never had any business dealings with him, so I was
surprised to hear'' that, Balfour said. He added, ``I don't know
that I know Trixie.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Trischitta said that only recently did Robbins seek
to establish a relationship with Trischitta.
</P>
<P>
   People who grew up with Trischitta and worked with him at the
treasury said they doubt he came up with the alleged scheme to
steal the $6.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trixie didn't think this up _ trust me,'' said a top aide to
former state treasurer Robert Crane, who hired Trischitta.
</P>
<P>
   But Robbins's mother said she believes ``they want to make my
son a scapegoat.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, however, always had a reputation as someone looking to
be a player in the business world, the same way he was on the
football field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always on the make,'' said one lifelong Malden resident
who said he has known Robbins since high school and who asked to
remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had not lived in Malden since the 1970s, Robbins
returned to his hometown last fall and approached city officials,
including Mayor Richard C. Howard, with a proposition: He knew
where there was several million dollars in economic development
funds that the city could get its hands on. He said he could obtain
it for the city for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins told Howard he had gotten into the business of ``asset
location,'' finding public funds in state and federal treasuries
for cities and towns across the country. If Malden would contract
with him he would even consider reducing his usual 33 percent fee
as a favor to his hometown, and get the money that was now sitting
in a state treasurer's account.
</P>
<P>
   But Howard said he soon found out that the money wasn't really
due Malden, and didn't like the complicated contract that Robbins
wanted the city to enter into. A week later, in early October, he
called Robbins and declined his offer.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later Robbins was opening an escrow account at the
BankBoston branch in Lynnfield under the name Cambridge Economic
Development and listing himself as having the sole power to deposit
and withdraw funds. According to prosecutors, he had submitted a
document to Trischitta stating that he had been given the power of
attorney from the Cambridge Economic Development Authority, and the
agency was due the $6.5 million that had been in the Unpaid Check
Fund since 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
