<HEADER>
A4493 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-02 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEASON CONDUCIVE TO HEARTFELT WHINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to usage disputes, the message of history is ``Get
over it'' _ some changes will eventually become standard English,
others will disappear, and everyone gets to vote. But even if you
expect to lose in this most democratic of forums, there's no need
to go quietly; everyone's allowed a bit of kicking and screaming,
as long as it doesn't go on too many decades after the majority
decision is clear.
</P>
<P>
   So this week, we're offering a collection of complaints _ not
about the tame bugbears of the waning century, but about usages now
knocking at our door, and not yet guaranteed a place at the table.
Here's a sampling of some recent weeping and gnashing of teeth:
</P>
<P>
   Growing like kudzu: ``Everywhere I turn lately I seem to find
the word burgeoning being used to indicate a growing human
population,'' writes Ginny Luongo of Acton. ``According to my
dictionaries the word burgeon means 1) `to put forth new buds,
leaves, or greenery; begin to sprout, grow, or blossom. 2) To
develop rapidly (not increase), or flourish.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the purists, the new meaning is likely to
blossom; there's just not a clear enough distinction between rapid
plant proliferation and other kinds of speedy growth for the
distinction to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting word: ``Please tell me that I am justified in having my
hackles raised in the presence of . . . conflicted as an adjective
(e.g., `I'm really conflicted about this decision'),'' requests
Matt Norwood of Cambridge. Well, the altitude of your hackles is
your own business, but conflicted is already dictionary-approved,
and probably too useful to die anytime soon. But look on the bright
side: Conflictual, a '60s neologism, still hasn't caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Less than zero: ``Ginger Burr, commenting (to a Globe columnist)
on working with transgender clients, says `The only difference is
that usually we're starting at ground zero,' '' notes Laura
Gustafson of Acton. ``What she means is square one, the starting
point, not the spot above which a nuclear bomb exploded.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm all for keeping these expressions separate, but there's no
chance of limiting ground zero to actual bombing sites; it has
already extended its metaphoric reach to include the site of any
momentous undertaking. That's only to be expected in a language
that speaks of ``explosions'' of fashionable pink, sport-utility
sales, and new sitcoms. Square one sounds like the next step up
from ground zero, probably adding to the confusion, and its image
could blur further as computer games displace board games. Language
conservatives, teach your children Monopoly before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Taste test: Donald C. MacLellan is unhappy about ``the
increasingly common neo-proverb `the proof is in the pudding,'
which, of course, makes no sense.'' The correct version, he says,
is `` `The proof of the pudding is in the eating,' an honored
proverb of long standing.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is, but the saying seems a very good candidate for the
kind of condensation other proverbs and quotations have undergone _
as long as the short form is used properly, to mean something that
can only be judged by sampling it. The proverb was much more apt,
remember, when it was recorded in 1682: A pudding in those days was
as likely to be a steamed haggis as a sweet milk-and-flour dish,
and either would have been made from scratch. Nowadays the pudding
is Jell-O Instant, and the proof is in the ingredients list.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping the gun: ``I am struck with what appears to be the utter
misuse of the word historic,'' writes George Waggoner ``in
reference to meetings or events that are either currently under
way, are in the offing, or have just been completed. For example,
`As the delegates gather here in Washington for this historic
session of the Senate. . . .' My dictionaries offer no definitions
of historic that refer to current events.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all Greece to them: ``Sportswriters . . . keep talking
about Olympus and climbing Olympus in reference to the games,''
writes Sean Kelly . ``Don't they know that the games derive their
name from Olympia in the western Peloponnese where the original
games were played, not Mount Olympus?''
</P>
<P>
   Led astray: ``The weather's not very conducive for this time of
year,'' a local TV reporter told viewers during an unseasonable
period in November. It's not clear what synonym for ``typical'' he
was seeking, but conducive means ``promoting, furthering,'' from
the Latin for ``leading together.'' His choice was at least
conducive to the amusement, if not the edification, of his
audience.
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
