<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4494 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      03-02 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CARTER CLAY &QL; 
 &UR; Elizabeth Evans (HarperFlamingo, $24)
</P>
<P>
   Evans (``The Blue Hour'') begins this novel with a scene that is
benignly commonplace and yet, because we know we are on the brink
of tragedy, disturbingly prophetic. It is 1993 and paleontologist
Joe Alitz is lost on the road with his wife, Katherine, and their
12-year-old daughter, Jersey. They are driving back to Arizona
after a visit with Katherine's mother in Florida, and they have
stopped on an isolated roadside to scan the horizon and figure out
where they are. Joe might have asked directions when he first
realized they were on the wrong road. But he is a man who likes to
solve his own problems. Into this tableau comes a Vietnam veteran
named Carter Clay. A loner and an alcoholic, Clay has been trying
to patch his broken life back together, but on the road that day,
Clay is a fallen man. He is drunk. He is distracted. And in a
moment of terrible inevitability, he drives his van into the
Alitzes as they stand on the roadside, looking off into the Florida
grasslands. This disturbing scene sets up a story that is, at its
roots, about simple bad luck and a flawed man's search for
redemption. Joe Alitz is killed. Katherine is brain-damaged. Jersey
is paralyzed from the waist down. Clay, who drives away from the
carnage with just a gash on his head, is dazed by guilt and grief.
A self-imposed penance takes root in his obsession with his crime:
He insinuates himself into Katherine's and Jersey's shattered lives
and attempts to take responsibility for them as a way of saving
them all. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; CLEOPATRA'S PALACE &QL; 
 &UR; Laura Foreman (Random House/Discovery, $35)
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many of them, but it's the underwater photographs
that make this book worth its price. Since the early 1980s,
underwater explorer Franck Goddio has been fascinated by the story
of earthquakes and tidal waves that hit the northern Africa coast
near Alexandria in 365 and ensuing centuries. Alexandria sat on a
geological fault line, and the quakes and other geophysical changes
caused the city's shoreline to disappear beneath the Mediterranean.
In 1992, Goddio set out to locate, map and explore the sunken
portions of Alexandria, which included the palaces of the city's
rulers. This book, an illustrated biography of Cleopatra, is a
companion volume to an upcoming Discovery Channel special on the
search for Cleopatra's Royal Quarter, which has been submerged for
1,600 years. Goddio found jewelry, pottery and an ancient
shipwreck, but the stunning images here are of the statues,
otherworldly figures that rise like ghosts in the murky water. In
one photograph, Goddio in his diving gear stares into the face of a
sphinx believed to be the likeness of Ptolemy XII, father of
Cleopatra. The stone features are remarkably preserved. The eyes
gaze back at Goddio with deep serenity, the lips curve in what
looks like the slightest of smiles. It is a sight to see. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE 20-MINUTE VEGETABLE GARDENER &QL; 
 &UR; Tom Christopher and Marty Asher (Random House, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   This is the second book by Christopher and Asher. The first was
``The 20-Minute Gardener,'' which is now available in paperback
from Random House. We like the first one better. Both are notable
not so much for the tips they offer (or, unfortunately, for the
endless string of anecdotes Tom and Marty tell about themselves) as
for the contagious spirit of the thing, this new
gardening-on-the-run. It's all very easygoing and reassuring.
``Bugs,'' they write, ``are the gardener's equivalent of Vietnam _
they cannot be defeated by sheer firepower. They know the country
better than you do. But you can outsmart them.'' Or ``Nursery
catalogs, while a great pleasure to read, have no relevance to
gardening, unless used as mulch. The magnificent plants described
in and pictured on their pages have never actually appeared on this
planet.'' We notice, however, that one of Tom's and Marty's
``20-Minute Projects'' is the rooting of cuttings from rosebushes,
which requires finding healthy bushes, bagging and labeling the
cuttings, digging a bed and adding peat moss and sand, planting the
cuttings, waiting a month for them to root, then transplanting and
waiting a year or two for them to bloom. Twenty minutes, indeed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SCARS OF SWEET PARADISE &QL; 
 &UR; Alice Echols (Metropolitan, $26)
</P>
<P>
   She was rootless, she was unattached, she was defiant and she
was only 27 when she died. That, and the voice, made the legend of
Janis Joplin and have kept it alive for 30 years. This fine
biography is analytical, intelligently written and deeply attentive
to the social and cultural milieu in which Joplin rose to fame.
It's about drugs, sex, rebellion and rock and roll, and not
necessarily in that order. Echols admits it's sometimes sordid even
to her. ``While I can appreciate the social significance of Janis'
assault on good-girl femininity,'' she writes, ``I'm sure it was
sometimes more appealing in theory than in practice.'' The mythic
Joplin _ ``the tough, raw, trashy broad'' _ was a persona Janis
began inventing as a chubby, acne-plagued teenager in Port Arthur,
Texas, because it gave her a sense of control. And for all of the
hatred she felt for her hometown, she never really shook its hold
on her. ``Janis' rebelliousness,'' Echols writes, ``never entirely
overcame her conventionality.'' &QL; 
You can reach Anne Stephenson at &QL; 
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
