<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES PUTTING NEW SHINE ON HOCKEY IN PHOENIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Early on, when paradise was still a novelty, Bobby
Smith was watching his kids skate, trading glances between the
happenings on the ice and the constant, seductive stream of
sunshine outside the arena doors.
</P>
<P>
   It was another perfect winter's day in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I say to the guy standing next to me, ``How can I be in
here, in a rink, when it's so great out there?' '' said Smith, the
Phoenix Coyotes' general manager, a man who spent 15 NHL seasons
playing in the less-inviting climes of Minnesota and Montreal.
``Then the guy turns to me and says, `Don't worry, Bobby, we've got
330 more just like it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three full seasons into their desert digs, the Coyotes
now are somewhat blase about the blazing sun. Good weather is the
expected. It's also just, well, weather. Though they are now in a
skid, having won only one of their last eight games, the Coyotes
have been far better known this season for their winning hockey
than their strange fit as a franchise rooted in ice seeking fertile
ground among the cacti.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what, though,'' said ex-Bay Stater Jeremy
Roenick, back in the Hub Monday as his Coyotes prepared to face the
Briuns at the FleetCenter, ``I told my in-laws (from Quincy), `You
can keep this weather.' You get spoiled, no question. After a
while, it drifts into your subconscious _ you don't realize how
great it is until you're back in this cold and dreary weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey's efforts to shake the snow from its image began more
than 30 years ago when the Los Angeles Kings and then the Oakland
Seals came aboard as NHL expansion entries. Atlanta and Colorado
(after a two-year try in Kansas City) started up in the '70s, only
to pack up eventually for bigger promises in Calgary and New
Jersey, respectively. The Oakland-based franchise moved to
Cleveland after seven years, the league's first franchise to
transfer since the Ottawa Senators bolted for St. Louis in '34.
Initially, the mix of ice and and nice weather received a tepid
reception.
</P>
<P>
   But in the '90s, the NHL, seeking a broader North American
footprint in hopes of building a wider, richer television contract,
has renewed its dream to bring hockey to the hotlands. Expansion
has taken hold in Miami, Tampa Bay, Anaheim, San Jose, and
Nashville. When the Nordiques couldn't make a go of it in Quebec
City, Denver threw wide its arena doors one more time. The Hartford
Whalers swapped sweaters with North Carolina and became the
Hurricanes. The Minnesota North Stars dropped the North and went
south to Dallas, reborn as the Stars. Prior to their life in the
desert, the Coyotes were Winnipeg Jets. In June, there will be an
expansion draft here in Boston, stocking Ted Turner's Atlanta
Thrashers, who begin play in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   When the NHL commences its 1999-2000 season, 11 of its 28 teams
will be based in warm-weather climes. In the days of the Original
Six, member clubs could relay a snowball from rink to rink. Those
days have melted away, faster than a slush cone on Hollywood
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got in here and I was depressed,'' said Coyotes captain
Keith Tkachuk, another Boston boy who has seen the daylight in the
desert. ``I mean, it was raining out, and it just kept raining. We
never have rain in Phoenix. Boston's nice and everything, and it's
nice to come back here . . . you know, once a year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes were among the league's elite for much of the first
half this season. Led by a line of Tkachuk, Roenick, and Dallas
Drake, they were jockeying with Dallas and Philadelphia for the top
spot in league standings until injuries began to mount in January
and December. They're now 30-20-10, about to end a two-week road
trip in which they've gone 1-5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing hard right now, but we're not playing smart,''
said head coach Jim Schoenfeld, who spent 39 games behind the
Boston blue line toward the end of his career. ``Some of our guys
are trying to do too much. Before, when things were going well, we
had a healthy roster and everyone had a job description. Our big
guys were scoring. We didn't need our third- and fourth-line guys
to be more than third- and fourth-line guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps looking for an emotional booster shot, the Coyotes have
recalled 6-foot-2-inch tough guy Sean Gagnon _ he of 1,422 penalty
minutes in his first four pro seasons _ from Springfield (AHL) for
the encounter against the Bruins. If the Bruins roll out both of
their hired fists, Ken Belanger and Ken Baumgartner, the Vault
could have a heavyweight edge that hasn't been seen often on
Causeway Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for one guy to carry our muscle game, if
that's what you want to call it,'' said Schoenfeld. ``Sean's been
up and down with us, and we monitor our guys. He's playing well for
Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to think we have a team toughness, and that doesn't
mean fighting. It means winning the one-on-one battles in the
corners, winniing the races for loose pucks, and throwing yourself
in front of a shot to block it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, nee Winnipeg Jets, have in Roenick and Tkachuk two
of the game's more talented forwards. When his game is on, Roenick
plays with a darting, fearless abandon, to the point where he's
suffered a couple of serious knee injuries. Tkachuk is the
big-swatting power forward, the former Boston University left
winger who twice has hit the 50-goal plateau.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not really a point guy,'' Tkachuk said earlier this
year, while mending from a broken rib, an injury that continues to
have him wearing a flak jacket. ``I muck in the corners. I get in
front and take my hacks and whacks. I'm not flashy, but I get my
points. Hey, I've scored 50 goals. I don't have to prove that
again. I have to prove that I can win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes haven't won a playoff round since '87, nearly five
years before Tkachuk joined the franchise following the '92 Olympic
Games. In part, it was postseason failure that led the Jets to
leave Winnipeg, where revenues, already restricted by a small
population base, were diminished annually by the club's poor
playoff performances.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since the Jets bolted, it has become even harder
for Canadian-based NHL clubs to thrive, the imbalance in the US and
Canadian dollars shredding whatever profits Canadian clubs
generate. Today, Molson is considering selling the hallowed
Canadiens, a sure sign that red ink is bleeding all over the red
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have their cash concerns, too, but not like the ones
that drove the Jets south. They play in America West Arena in
downtown Phoenix, a basketball building with some sightlines that
cut off large portions of the ice. They'd like to build their own
arena _ a May 18 vote could give them that go-ahead _ stocked with
the requisite luxury suites and other modern-day bells and
whistles.
</P>
<P>
   Will the desert market bear it? Consider: Even in their
ill-fitting arena, the Coyotes have averaged around 15,500 per game
for their nearly three seasons, about 96 percent capacity. It may
be an uncharacteristic fit, but ice sells in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, when you're playing (in Phoenix) you get caught up
in it a little,'' said Tkachuk. ``It's always great outside, and
you're coming to the rink in shorts, and there's always the
opportunity to be out there playing golf and stuff. But
realistically, you have to think, `Why am I here?' You're there to
play hockey and you have to win _ and that's got nothing to do with
the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes aren't the powerhouse they were earlier in the
season, but they're a playoff lock, with a chance to place a desert
rose in the Stanley Cup Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   They just have to get back in touch with their winning ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix is a great place,'' said Smith, standing inside
Matthews Arena Monday, watching his club practice. ``But Anchorage
on a winning streak is nicer than . . .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
