<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING THE BARBARY TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston has the Freedom Trail, San Francisco now has the Barbary
Coast Trail.
</P>
<P>
   The trail, a 3.8-mile walk (just a bit longer than the Freedom
Trail) celebrating San Francisco's famous and colorful past, opened
last year. The walk, with 150 bronze markers, allows visitors to
capture the spirit of the eras of the Gold Rush, Comstock Lode, and
the 1906 Earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Walking down Market Street today, the center of San Francisco's
financial district, it is hard to imagine that in 1847 this hub was
once the dusty old Mission Trail, a half mile from the center of
town and often blocked by 90-foot sand dunes. Along the route is
the birthplace of the Gold Rush at Portsmouth Square; Hyde Street
Pier, which contains the largest collection of historic ships in
the United States; St. Mary's Cathedral, the oldest Catholic
cathedral west of the Rockies; and T'ien Hou Temple, the oldest
Asian temple in the United States, along with 20 historic sites,
six local history museums, indoor and outdoor pubs, and panoramic
views. The trail is a project of the San Francisco Historical
Society.
</P>
<P>
   Each end of the trail is connected by the scenic Powell-Hyde
cable car line.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ski specials
</P>
<P>
   At Okemo in Ludlow, Vt., beginning March 2, it's Two for Two on
Tuesdays. Skiers and riders can rent two pairs of Salomon
SnowBlades for two hours for the price of one; Tuesdays are also a
day for Tune-up and Tuna _ drop off your skis or snowboards for a
tuneup and enjoy a tuna melt sandwich or tuna macaroni salad for
just $12. Thursdays, beginning March 4, are Ladies Days, a special
package of lift ticket and ski or snowboarding lesson is $37,
regularly $75. There's also a special deal for day care, and rental
equipment (for details, call 802-228-1581).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Harbor
</P>
<P>
   The beginning and end of World War II in the Pacific have come
together at Pearl Harbor in Hawaii. ``Most people gather their
knowledge of World War II from books and movies, limiting their
appreciation for the human reality of what took place here and
throughout the world during the war,'' said Captain Gerald Hofwolt,
executive director of the USS Bowfin Submarine Museum and Park.
``Pearl Harbor puts it all in perspective. This is a place where
visitors can come in close contact with the brave men and women who
chose to serve their country, live, and die, for the cause of
freedom. By combining our efforts, we're helping to give visitors a
more tangible awareness of what it was all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Harbor is not only the site of the USS Arizona Memorial,
but also the USS Bowfin Submarine Museum and Park, and, now, the
Battleship Missouri Memorial. The Arizona was destroyed on Dec. 7,
1941, with a tremendous loss of life. The site now has become a
place of healing and unification.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowfin allows visitors to experience a World War II vintage
submarine and learn of the role subs played in Naval history. The
Bowfin was launched on Dec. 7, 1942, and became a permanent part of
Pearl Harbor in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri just became a part of the harbor on Jan. 29.
Visitors touring the battleship will see the unaltered
``signature'' deck where on Sept. 2, 1945, the surrender of Japan
took place.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the Missouri, call the USS Missouri
Memorial Association at 808-423-2263; for the Arizona, call the
National Park Service at 808-422-0561, and for the Bowfin, call the
Pacific Fleet Submarine Memorial Association at 808-423-1341.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exploratorium's 30th
</P>
<P>
   This is the 30th anniversary of San Francisco's Exploratorium,
considered by many to be the world's best science museum. It's also
the museum that changed the notion of what a museum should be. It
was here that the concept of ``hands-on'' and ``interactive''
exhibits began. The Exploratorium introduces people to science by
asking them to examine how they see, hear, and feel _ the basis for
finding out more about the world they live in. Now through Sept.
12, the museum goes to the frogs. Did you know there are 3,000
species of frogs and toads around the world on every continent
except Antarctica? Here you'll learn everything there is to know
about frogs and toads, even see some 75 live frogs representing 20
species.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can even get up close in a giant Tub of Frogs or Tub of
Toads. How nice. For information, call 415-561-0363.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only in California
</P>
<P>
   Tim Moreland knows his ``Rebirth of the Earth Tour'' down to a
fault _ the San Andreas Fault. Moreland and Miracle in the Desert
Destination Services is offering a three-hour Eco-adventure tour of
the San Andreas Fault in the Palm Springs Desert Resort area. ``It
is one of the most active geological areas in North America,'' says
Moreland. ``We take people down to where they can stand and look
directly into the fault.'' For information on this and other Palm
Springs activities, call 800-41-RELAX and ask for the Palm Springs
Desert Resorts Vacation Planner. The planner also includes
discounts on accommodations, dining, and activities.
</P>
<P>
   While in Palm Springs, why not pay your respects to Frank
Sinatra, Sonny Bono, and other celebrities. The Desert Memorial
Cemetery makes it easy with a free map to the stars' graves. Other
dignitaries who rest here include songwriters Frederick Lowe and
Jimmy Van Heusen, song and choreographer Busby Berkeley (who hails
from Athol, Mass.) and actor William (the Thin Man) Powell.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Monica, Clark Gable and Carol Lombard were frequent
guests of the Georgian Hotel when it opened its doors in 1933. To
celebrate the Art Deco hotel's 65th anniversary, a special Gable &AMP;
Lombard Anniversary package is available for $10 for the
first-night of a three-night minimum stay at $295 a night in the
Santa Monica Suite. The package is available through Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is home to a collection of notable architecture and
cultural sites. Architours offers a variety of tours and events
each month. Also Restaurant Design Tours offers visits to
restaurants known for both their culinary and design excellence.
</P>
<P>
   You can learn about these tours and stays from the Los Angeles
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau by calling 213-624-7300.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ranch vacations
</P>
<P>
   Heading West? Looking for a dude ranch? One source is the Dude
Ranchers' Association (PO Box 471-G, LaPorte, CO 80535; telephone
970-223-8440). They'll send you a free copy of ``The Dude
Rancher,'' a directory with descriptions of 100-plus ranches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alaska pass
</P>
<P>
   If you're out to do Alaska on your own, do obtain an AlaskaPass
Travelpass good for unlimited travel on the Alaska Marine Highway,
BC Ferries, Alaska Railroad, Alaskon Express Motorcoaches,
Greyhound Canada, Norline Coaches, and Laidlaw Coach Line. Passes
range from $499 for an 8-day pass to $999 for a 21-to-45-day
flexible pass. AlaskaPass is also offering planned tours as well as
a booking service ($79 a person). For a free newsletter, call
800-248-7598.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One-way drives
</P>
<P>
   From March 29 through May 15, Budget Rent a Car is featuring a
special one-Way Florida Drive-Out rate of $9.95 a day for
intermediate cars. Budget customers can rent an intermediate car
from participating Budget locations in Florida and drive one way to
any of 50 cities through the central and East Coast states. This is
one way Budget redistributes its Florida winter fleet. For
information, call 800-527-0700.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bears and more bears
</P>
<P>
   Why do many people head to Alaska? According to the Alaska
Division of Tourism, thousands of visitors come just to see
grizzlies, many of them crowding into the Katmai area and around
Brooks Lodge. Another way to see them is to stay at one of the
``bear camps,'' such as Great Alaska Adventure Lodge's Bear Camp
adjacent to Lake Clark National Park located in a principal grizzly
mating area and nursery on the Alaska Peninsula. At the camp,
guests get a personalized bear-viewing experience far from the
crowds. Three-day stays begin at $645 a person including a salmon
bake and scenic flight. For information, call 800-544-2261.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alaska guide
</P>
<P>
   The best guide to bring to Alaska is ``The Alaska Almanac''
(Alaska Northwest Books, $11.95). This handy book has everything
you ever wanted to know about Alaska within its covers, along with
the wacky wisdom of Mr. Whitekeys. The book is both easy and fun to
read _ lots of facts, lots of good information. The almanac is
available in stores or by calling the publisher at 800-452-3032.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nevada bonus
</P>
<P>
   The ``Discover Nevada Bonus Book'' provides travelers with
information on attractions in Nevada along with discount coupons
for use within Nevada's six tourism ``territories.'' For a copy,
call 800-NEVADA-8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Air Jamaica's 30th
</P>
<P>
   Air Jamaica is celebrating its 30th anniversary (April 1) by
awarding a free round-trip ticket to Jamaica on every flight
through May 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
