<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE AUCTION HOUSE E-BAY UNDER FEDERAL PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Federal officials are investigating the alleged
sale of contraband on the eBay Inc. Internet site, the on-line
auction house has confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate officials said in a statement that the investigation
was launched Jan. 29, when they received requests to provide
records and information ``relating to an investigation into
possible illegal transactions'' on the Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose-based company, which posts items for sale by
individual sellers and allows buyers to bid on those items in an
auction-like setting, disclosed the federal investigation in a
statement released after the close of the stock markets Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been one of the more bullish of the hot Internet
stocks. The company's stock split 3 for 1 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with the investigation say the probe is being
conducted by several agencies, including the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The company had announced on Feb. 19 that it was prohibiting the
sale of firearms on its Web site, citing the difficulty in
determining the legality of those sales.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Chu, an eBay spokeswoman, said the company had been
asked by a federal court not to reveal the nature of the
investigation. ``We've been asked not to disclose any information
in order to protect an ongoing investigation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The probe is the latest in a string of inquiries involving the
site. Last fall, the company disclosed it was being investigated by
an unnamed state attorney general's office for possible seller
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, it said it would cooperate with a New York City
Department of Consumer Affairs probe into charges of seller fraud,
primarily regarding sports memorabilia. And Microsoft recently
announced it would begin monitoring eBay for the possible sale of
pirated software.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Pursglove, another eBay spokesman, said the Internet
site's recent troubles could be attributed to a ``learning
process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``E-commerce is so very new,'' said Pursglove, referring to the
label bestowed on Internet-based selling and buying. ``The correct
policies as they pertain to sellers and buyers are still being
formed. We fully intend to meet those challenges as they arise.''
</P>
<P>
   Now claiming to have 2.1 million registered users, eBay was
founded by French-born software developer Pierre Omidyar after his
girlfriend, an avid Pez candy dispenser collector, complained that
there were no good collectible trading sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company was launched in September 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
