<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMOR FROM THE 49TH STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alaska not only has an abundance of natural resources, it has a
lot of humor, too. Consider these comical comments from tour
guides:
</P>
<P>
   --In Skagway: ``Our average summer temperature is 100 degrees.
That's 40 in the morning and 60 in the afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   --At the El Dorado Mine in Fairbanks: ``Did you folks bring your
old gold-mining clothes? Well, if they're not your old clothes now,
they will be when you're done!''
</P>
<P>
   --At Denali National Park: ``Yes, there are rest-room facilities
en route. We refer to them as bushes.''
</P>
<P>
   --Everywhere: ``Alaska has four seasons: winter, early winter,
late winter, and next winter.''
</P>
<P>
   --And once more in Skagway: ``Over there is a horse and carriage
that you can ride. We got another of those last year. Now we're no
longer a one-horse town!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: What is the northernmost capital in the contiguous
United States? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: ``Ukulele'' is Hawaiian for ``little jumping flea.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``You can go to hell; I am going to Texas.'' _ Davy
Crockett. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Freebie: You can walk through a glade surrounded by hundreds of
butterflies, including monarchs, swallowtails, and cabbage whites,
on the Hawaiian island of Kauai. Wings Over Hawaii, the state's
only producer of butterflies for release at weddings and other
special occasions, has its visitors' area and gift shop at
Kilohana, a former sugar plantation near Lihue that also contains a
dozen stores and galleries, a restaurant, gardens, and carriage
rides pulled by Clydesdales. For more butterfly information, call
808-2458838 or 888-BUTTERFLI. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deadly: We learn from the offbeat quarterly Out West that the Death
Valley National Park Visitor Center in eastern California is
coffin-shaped. And when you step outside, you get a fine view of
the Funeral Mountains. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Snappy slogan: Princess Cruises says its land and sea tours of
Alaska are ``designed to give you moosebumps.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
How times have changed: Hollywood was founded in 1888 by a
temperance society with the idea of making it a model community. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Same road, different destination: When Burt Bacharach, Hal David,
and Dionne Warwick collaborated on ``Do You Know the Way to San
Jose?'' nearly 30 years ago, the city in the song was an
agricultural-driven community of 359,000 people. A lot has changed
since then: San Jose is now home to 850,000 souls and is considered
the capital of high-tech Silicon Valley. Today, San Jose also has
luxury hotels, gourmet restaurants, a convention center and arena,
visual and performing arts venues, several professional sports
teams, and attractions for adults and children. One thing hasn't
changed since the song was written, though: LA is still a great big
freeway. (For a free visitors' guide, call 888 SAN JOSE.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Snappy slogan: (posted in Ketchikan, Alaska, which gets a lot of
rain): ``If you can't see the mountain, that means it's raining. If
you can see the mountain, that means it's about to rain.'') &QL; 
 &QL; 
The way it was: The Animal Kingdom at Walt Disney World isn't the
first time animals have appeared in a Disney park. When
California's Disneyland opened in 1955, a circus was to be one of
the attractions. But once a herd of llamas got loose and thundered
through the park. Another time, a panther and a tiger broke through
a partition and engaged in a death battle inside their cage during
a parade on Main Street, USA. The circus plan was quietly dropped. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wet wagers: The Tropicana hotel's 295-foot heated swimming pool has
two swim-up blackjack tables. Each can accommodate up to 14
players, who sit on marble stools in hip-deep water. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Olympia, Wash. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
