<HEADER>
A4511 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-RUN-BOS &LR;      03-02 1566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-RUN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POLITICS OF HILLARY CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With Hillary Rodham Clinton headed to town Wednesday,
New Yorkers by the millions wonder if she plans to speak to the
issue of the hour: Will she take the leap and run for Senate?
</P>
<P>
   But there are other questions: What sort of senator would the
first lady be? What does she stand for, how would she vote, what
would she do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Rorschach test,'' the first lady told Esquire magazine
in 1993. She has lived up to the billing ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Is she the ultimate do-good liberal who wants government to
intrude in everything from setting corporate profits to letting
teenagers sue their parents?
</P>
<P>
   Is she a New Democrat moderate, like her president husband,
reconciled to the precepts of a market economy and a trimmed-down
bureaucracy?
</P>
<P>
   Is she a canny pragmatist, her views evolving with experience
and maturation? Or _ a darker way of looking at the same thing _ is
she an opportunist, adapting her positions to fit new ambitions?
</P>
<P>
   She has been described, admired, and scorned as all the above.
And a review of her speeches and writings _ not just during her six
years in the White House, but over the past 30 years, as a
campaigner, a governor's wife, a law professor, and a graduating
college student _ reveals a record that friend and foe alike could
plumb for treasure.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's Republican mayor, Rudolph W. Giuliani, widely
seen as her most likely opponent, has already dipped his toe in the
pool, criticizing her support of a Palestinian state _ a stance
that could trouble the large number of Jewish voters here.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also said, on CNN's ``Crossfire,'' that a contest
against the first lady ``would be very important nationally _ it
would contrast two very different philosophies of governing.''
</P>
<P>
   The views for which Mrs. Clinton is best known are also the most
controversial _ health care and children's rights. In both cases,
everyone agrees, her beliefs are genuine and passionate, rooted in
the social activism of the Methodist Church and fueled by her years
at Wellesley College in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the student government, class of '69, she
delivered the ``counter-commencement'' address, a rousing speech
declaring that the ``prevailing acquisitive and competitive
corporate life is not for us. We're searching for more immediate,
ecstatic, and penetrating modes of living.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Greenberg, editorial-page editor for the Arkansas
Democrat-Gazette, who covered the Clintons during the president's
years as governor (and who coined the nickname ``Slick Willie''),
sees residual significance in that speech. ``At least since
Wellesley,'' he said in a phone interview, ``there's been a
principled drive toward a collectivist view of society. . . . She
sees a problem and thinks it can be solved by organized society,
from the top down. She's very leery of letting people make their
own decisions. She's afraid they'll make mistaken ones.''
</P>
<P>
   During her White House years, Greenberg said, this view was on
best display in her plan for health-care reform.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1993, in his first month as president, Bill Clinton
named Hillary as head of a task force to devise a system of
universal health insurance. She worked diligently, gave innumerable
speeches, testified before Congress alone and without notes _ and
failed miserably, outfoxed by industry lobbying and a growing
suspicion that her plan was too complex and gave the government too
much power.
</P>
<P>
   Although, in Arkansas, she had successfully led a commission on
education reform _ which recommended and pushed through the state
legislature a 1 percent increase in the sales tax and a requirement
that teachers pass a competency exam _ the health-care debacle
would be her last high-profile political initiative. The
Republicans would surely bring it up again if she ran for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   They might also resuscitate some of her more radical views on
child care, though they would have to dig back a quarter-century to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1973 article in the Harvard Education Review, Hillary
Rodham _ then still going by her maiden name _ criticized the
courts' presumption that children are incompetent to make their own
decisions. She likened the presumption to the view, held by courts
in earlier times, that wives, slaves, and Native Americans were not
entitled to their own views.
</P>
<P>
   She revised this view somewhat in a 1979 article, saying
disputes with children should be resolved by families, not by the
courts, ``in all but the most extreme cases.'' However, she defined
these ``extreme cases'' as ``decisions about motherhood and
abortion, schooling, cosmetic surgery, treatment of venereal
disease . . . and others where the decision or lack of one will
significantly affect the child's future.''
</P>
<P>
   At the 1992 Republican convention, Patrick J. Buchanan denounced
these articles and claimed that Hillary Clinton ``compared marriage
and the family to slavery and life on an Indian reservation'' and
that she believes ``12-year-olds have a right to sue their
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's reading was a caricature, but the Harvard sociologist
Christopher Lasch argued in Harper's magazine at the time that he
had a point. ``Hillary Clinton's writings,'' Lasch argued,
``exemplify the view of families that so many working people find
objectionable . . . the politicization of family life.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans were to revive this argument now, Mrs.
Clinton could note _ as did a number of legal scholars seven years
ago _ that she was writing mainly about parents who abuse their
children, or who deny them medical care or schooling on the basis
of religious beliefs that the children may not share.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, where universal health care is fairly popular and
child abuse widespread, attacking her on these issues could
backfire.
</P>
<P>
   It could also open a clear line of counterattack for Mrs.
Clinton. She has often spoken against slow and careless foster-care
systems _ and New York City's is among the nation's slowest and
most tragic.
</P>
<P>
   While she is at it, she might criticize Giuliani for a
too-strict anti-welfare policy. Under his workfare program, mothers
must turn their young children over to inadequate day care and go
sweep streets or clean parks rather than stay home. Students on
welfare must also work for their checks, even if it means dropping
out of school.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has declared herself in favor of welfare reform.
However, in her 1996 book, ``It Takes a Village,'' she called for
more government spending on child care. And in many speeches, she
has placed education, including higher education, above nearly all
other social goals.
</P>
<P>
   She might also attack the mayor _ as a federal judge did
recently _ for failing to inform welfare applicants of benefits
they are entitled to receive. In a speech last October at
Children's Hospital in Little Rock, she announced a radio campaign
to ``get the message across to families to take advantage of what
now is available to their children.'' She has also fervently
supported arts and after-school programs, which Giuliani has also
cut.
</P>
<P>
   On still other issues, Giuliani might find the first lady less
liberal than he might expect.
</P>
<P>
   At least as far back as Febraury 1992, in an interview with The
Boston Globe, Mrs. Clinton said she had changed her mind and come
around to her husband's view on the death penalty. ``The death
penalty, though regrettable, is necessary in some form,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In ``It Takes a Village,'' she came out in favor of charter
schools and giving parents more choice in selecting them _ though,
in speeches, she has still opposed school vouchers. Her book also
advocates urban and rural empowerment zones, reducing business
regulations, and the ``three-strikes-you're-out'' provision of her
husband's crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   Last year she told the graduating class at Harvard Medical
School, ``Let's be clear. As a nation, we have to continue to work
toward universal, affordable, quality health care for every single
American.''
</P>
<P>
   However, at the World Economy Forum in Davos, Switzerland, she
also declared, ``I believe, as we end this century, any doubts
about the effectiveness of organizing our economy along the lines
of a free market have finally been put to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   In her book, she added, ``Even those of us who are mindful of
the progress we have made through government recognize that there
are limits to what it can do. We reject the utopian view that
government can or should protect people from the consequences of
personal decisions or that it can legislate complete peace,
harmony, and brotherhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, of the Arkansas Democrat-Gazette, suspects these
pronouncements. ``Something rings tinny in my ear when she says
such things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Max Brantley, editor of the Arkansas Times and a
Hillary admirer, thinks she is sincere. ``People get more
conservative with age,'' he said. ``Idealism gets tempered with
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it may take the trench warfare of a campaign, running on
her own and not as a candidate's wife, to unravel the real Hillary.
``She's been in a carefully controlled cocoon for six years,''
Brantley noted. ``She's so guarded, it's hard to get from her
speeches a good fix on what she really feels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
