u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-BIG-SCORE-2TAKES-B     03-02 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BIG-SCORE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLIKELY PAIR CAUGHT IN WEB OF TREASURY SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALDEN, Mass. _ When Marty Robbins strutted through the halls of
Malden High School, he was envied as a star football player and
honors student, a young man who made it all look easy.
</P>
<P>
   When John Trischitta walked those same corridors, it was behind
the varsity lettermen, carrying a clipboard and clock as the
manager of four varsity sports. Nicknamed ``Trixie,'' Trischitta
was an oversized kid whose humor and pleasant persona helped him
make friends.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three decades after both men graduated from high school,
the unlikely pair stand accused of attempting to steal $6.5
million, the largest attempted theft of state funds in
Massachusetts. It was an alleged scheme striking for its simplicity
and the ease with which it was executed. If not for suspicious
BankBoston tellers, the two men may have gotten away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Although they touched some of the same circles of friends and
acquaintances after high school, the paths of Robbins and
Trischitta rarely intersected. It was only recently that Robbins,
the stellar athlete, made a closer connection with the boy who
carried the equipment bags.
</P>
<P>
   Following a string of failed and allegedly fraudulent business
dealings, Robbins last year began working as an heir finder, a
business where he would search out companies and people who for one
reason or another never received state checks issued to them. For a
cut of whatever was owed, Robbins would alert the company or person
to the uncashed check and tell them how to obtain the funds.
</P>
<P>
   In what was either a bit of serendipity or evidence of a
well-planned conspiracy, the person at the state treasury who
oversaw the millions of dollars in the state's Unpaid Check Fund
was Trischitta.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, according to sources, Trischitta, 47, gave Robbins,
51, exclusive access to the list of those owed the most from the
unclaimed money fund.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last fall, state prosecutors allege Robbins offered a
$50,000 bribe to Trischitta to issue $6.5 million in checks from
the Unpaid Check Fund to a defunct government development
corporation that Robbins fraudulently claimed to represent. Once
the money was safely deposited in Robbins's BankBoston checking
account, Trischitta was to receive one-third of the proceeds,
prosecutors charge.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicious BankBoston officials alerted the attorney general's
office after noticing the large deposit in Robbins's checking
account. Earlier this month he tried to withdraw $6.5 million in
cash. Perfunctory controls established by the state to detect such
an alleged scam failed to work.
</P>
<P>
   Now the talk in barber shops and barrooms throughout Malden is
of how Trischitta, forever a stagehand, and Robbins, the leading
man, ended up together in a scandal that has exposed glaring
weaknesses in the management of the state's multibillion-dollar
treasury.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years, Robbins Gas on Eastern Avenue was a landmark in the
Maplewood section of Malden. Marty Robbins and his two younger
brothers all worked at the gas station at one time or another, and
it was expected one of the sons would eventually take over the
business from their father.
</P>
<P>
   But Robbins had bigger plans. He co-captained the Golden
Tornadoes football team, a standout lineman who blitzed through the
Medford line for a crucial two-point safety during the Thanksgiving
Day game his senior year. He was a member of the student council
and the German Honor club, and he told other students in the class
of 1966 that he planned on being a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty was the real deal,'' said a former teacher who knew both
Robbins and Trischitta.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins went on to Boston University, where he played football,
joined a fraternity, and graduated with a journalism degree in
1970. In a brief interview last week, Robbins said that he had
considered becoming an investigative reporter but decided to pursue
a career in business instead. He declined to discuss the charges
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said he worked in a management program for an automobile
manufacturer after college, but he left that job to start a string
of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Although several of the ventures ended in bankruptcy and
allegations of fraud, Robbins always enjoyed the trappings of
success and created an impression he was flush with cash, according
to court records and friends.
</P>
<P>
   While his Associated Salvage business was going bankrupt,
Robbins was driving a $50,000 Mercedes 420 SEL leased by the
company. He also kept a Cherokee 235 airplane at the Lawrence
airport and listed a flight instructor as a creditor in bankruptcy
papers. He made trips abroad and owned a vacation condominium at
Loon Mountain in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   When his wife, Barbara, was seeking a divorce, she filed a court
memorandum in 1997 alleging her husband was maintaining a high
standard of living despite having declared personal and corporate
bankruptcy in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He currently drives a 1997 Jeep Grand Cherokee, lives in a
luxury apartment in Andover; dines out nearly every day; has a
professional cleaner for his apartment and is a current member of
The Thompson Country Club'' in North Reading, she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, having sold the couple's Lynnfield home to make ends
meet, she had moved with their three sons into a more modest
condominium in the town.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Robbins stated in the court filing that her husband had
been able to stay afloat financially by securing a line of bank
credit. For collateral, she said, he had used nearly $100,000 in
money that had been placed in three separate trusts set up in the
names of their sons.
</P>
<P>
   Former business partners allege Robbins lived well by scamming
them.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Lulay, Robbins's partner in the salvage business,
alleged in a 1990 lawsuit that Robbins manipulated the books of the
company in order to make money for another firm in which Robbins
was the sole stockholder.
</P>
<P>
   Lulay alleged in his suit that Robbins put his three sons, none
of them yet teenagers at the time, on the company payroll even
though they never did any work for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins's mother, Lorraine Miller, said some media accounts have
wrongly portrayed her son as ``the biggest hoodlum going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell you something: He is good, deep down,'' she
said, citing his generous gifts to temples and charities, his
volunteer work for B'nai B'rith, and his taking a son to
Jerusalem's Wailing Wall for his bar mitzvah. ``He'd have 100
friends who will vouch for him.''
</P>
<P>
   But court records suggest a darker side to Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1995, Thomas Chretien alleged in court papers
that Robbins threatened to kill him. Chretien was an investor in
Polar Seafood Corp., a company importing fish from Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins was brought into the company by two other investors to
help increase sales, in part because he had connections with large
supermarket chains, Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really didn't do any work,'' Chretien said. ``He always
seemed like a shady character.''
</P>
<P>
   The company continued to be unprofitable and Chretien said he
stopped receiving scheduled payments on loans he made to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1995, Chretien said he went to the company's
offices in Westwood to retrieve equipment he owned. When he
attempted to collect the items, he was met by an enraged Robbins,
according to Chretien and court documents.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
