<HEADLINE>
BASIC CAKE DECORATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Here are some of Paulette Karras' best tips for basic
cake decorating: &QL; 
 &QL; 
- Assemble all your equipment before you begin. &QL; 
- When coloring buttercream icing, make it a shade lighter than you
want the finished product to be, because it will dry darker. &QL; 
- Use pastels rather than dark colors. They are more appetizing. &QL; 
- Do not dye white icing black. It will stain the teeth when eaten.
Instead, start with chocolate icing and then dye it black. This
will require much less color. &QL; 
- Use clear vanilla to produce bright white icing. Regular vanilla
extract will give the icing a brownish or yellowish tint. &QL; 
- For icing that will be used to make leaves, add 1 teaspoon corn
syrup to 1/2 cup buttercream so leaves come to a smooth point. &QL; 
- Fill icing bags only half full. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
