<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4517 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAILOR-SHIP-ART-BOS &LR;      03-02 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAILOR-SHIP-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD FRIENDS TO ACCOMPANY BATTLESHIP ON ONE MORE VOYAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The young seaman and the mighty battleship came of age
together, when Boston was a teeming Navy port and a determined
nation marched off to war. They steamed together to Casablanca,
where history was made, and later saw fierce action in the South
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Harold Nye, the former seaman apprentice, and the USS
Massachusetts, a decommissioned warship with a storied history,
will be together again for what is likely to be the last cruise the
ship's World War II crew members could ever see.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like I've always been with that ship,'' the
84-year-old Nye said. ``I don't think there will be very many more
rides for either of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35,000-ton battleship _ built at Quincy's Fore River
Shipyard and now the centerpiece of a tourist attraction in Fall
River _ was sitting in dry dock Monday, as a small army of workers
put the final touches on an $8.5 million overhaul of sandblasting,
replating and repainting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a struggle, but everything turned out fine,'' said
Dan Schaab, general manager of Boston Ship Repair, which plans to
send the mammoth ship on its way back home to Battleship Cove
sometime Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And as a tugboat tows the Massachusetts on its 2 1/2-day journey
home, Nye and other veterans will be on board, hoping for some
stiff winds and rough seas, natural forces that would breathe some
life into the former warship its crew members affectionately called
``Big Mamie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to feel her move again,'' Nye said. ``She's such a
good ship.''
</P>
<P>
   When the battleship Massachusetts was commissioned in May 1942,
Nye was a $32-a-month seaman apprentice, who worked in the ship's
galley from its first shakedown cruise to the day he left the
service four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Nye was aboard when the ship's 16-inch guns, capable of hurling
20 tons of steel more than 20 miles, thundered to life on Nov. 8,
1942, during the North African invasion. The Massachusetts bested
its adversary, the French battleship Jean Bart, in a ferocious
seven-hour engagement.
</P>
<P>
   And Nye was aboard for the first of a series of battles in the
Pacific, where the ship destroyed 18 Japanese aircraft. In all, the
Massachusetts fought decisively in 35 battles and steamed 225,000
miles as a commissioned warship.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good hunk of her crew came from Massachusetts,'' said
Strafford Morss, the project manager and the ship's unofficial
historian. ``She did her job and brought her people home safely. No
man was ever lost on the ship due to combat. That is what the crew
members remember. They have a tremendous fondness for her.''
</P>
<P>
   The 680-foot ship, decommissioned in 1947 and stricken from the
Navy's register in June 1962, slowly lost its battle against time.
Big Mamie's steel hull corroded, its original teak deck faded and
cracked and became what Morss called ``an extraordinary jungle
gym'' for marine growth, which had accumulated nearly two inches
thick.
</P>
<P>
   During the four-month overhaul at Boston Ship Repair, more than
300 workers used 3,000 gallons of epoxy and 260,000 pounds of
half-inch-thick steel to reseal a ship whose waterline was damaged
by decades of wind and waves. Until it entered drydock last fall,
the Massachusetts had not been out of the water since the Truman
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you traipse around underneath her, you get to appreciate
just how darn big she is,'' Morss said. ``You get to thinking about
what those fellows at Quincy did as a matter of skill and art. She
came out as a gorgeous product.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, workers applied the last coat of battleship
gray paint, whose final gloss was tempered by Sunday's heavy rains.
But the repair crews are now ready to reattach the ship's anchor,
flood the dry dock, and prepare the old battleship for what will
likely be its last voyage in the life of former crew members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the first ride, and now I'll have the last ride,'' said
Nye, a Marion native and a member of the museum's board of
directors. ``I'm proud of the ship. I'm proud of what it's done. It
was the first battleship to fire its 16-inch guns in World War II,
and it was the last battleship to do that. We saw a lot of action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was astronomical to see its fantail again and to see its
beautiful bow,'' he said. ``I'd forgotten what it looked like out
of the water. It's got beautiful lines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
