<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-MCEWAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IAN MCEWAN TAKES HIS READERS TO THE EDGE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ian McEwan doesn't seem so creepy in the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think he would be, this novelist who has chalked up some
of the most vividly creepy scenes in contemporary literature.
</P>
<P>
   There's the savage betrayal that climaxes ``The Comfort of
Strangers.'' The act of incest in ``Cement Garden.'' The father
losing his daughter in the supermarket and, later, the slow-motion
car crash in ``The Child in Time.'' There's the chopping up of a
body in ``The Innocent.'' The haunted house scene in ``Black
Dogs.'' Most breathtaking, there's the wayward balloon at the start
of ``Enduring Love.'' Finally, there's the hillside rapist and a
witness's chilling passivity that marks the turning point of his
most recent work, the winner of last year's Booker Prize,
``Amsterdam'' (published by Doubleday).
</P>
<P>
   These are terrifying scenes _ McEwan moments, they might be
called _ in which characters move through a dreamlike haze with a
knife-sharp awareness of detail, time seems palpable and prolonged,
events spin out of control, characters are stripped to their core,
and lives are irreversibly transformed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the author of these tales, by all appearances, is a classic
mild-mannered fellow: 50, soft-spoken, slight of build, with
glasses, thinning hairline, dry humor. His longtime friend and
fellow British writer Christopher Hitchens confirms the impression:
``Ian is the most pleasant guy you'd ever want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   So what about those scenes that mark all of his novels, those
moments of gripping horror? Do they reflect nothing at all in
McEwan's own life?
</P>
<P>
   McEwan, who is passing through New York to promote his new novel
_ which has been on The New York Times bestseller list for six
weeks _ considers the question for no more than a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that some of these things are horrible,'' he says,
``is unimportant. I do love to generate a kind of narrative
intensity. I do like to take my readers to the edge. I like to
generate that sense of danger. I'm interested in finding out how
characters survive, or are shaped by, their destinies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But _ and it seems odd to say this,'' he goes on, ``but the
primary driving force behind these scenes is aesthetic. It's like a
painter using a certain color. I like novels in which something
happens. It's not the only thing one wants in a novel, but I hold
to quite old-fashioned beliefs in the power of the story, our need
for story. Even if we're no longer children, our habits of
narrative are very strong. So,'' he restates the point, ``it's
primarily aesthetic.''
</P>
<P>
   He expresses a slight annoyance at the numerous reviews that
describe his work as macabre. ``I see that word `macabre,' '' he
says, ``and I sense somewhere inside me a great yawn. It's idle.
It's lazy. The last really macabre scene was the cutting up of the
body in `The Innocent.' I wrote that in 1988.'' He pauses. ``I've
written plenty of other moods and scenes since.''
</P>
<P>
   McEwan's ``Amsterdam'' _ about two old friends, a composer who
thinks he's a genius and a journalist who knows he's a louse, the
scandals they sire, and the revenge that ensues _ certainly ranks
among his least macabre, though he takes some nasty jabs at his
characters toward the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had such fun writing it,'' McEwan exclaims, smiling. ``I
wrote it in a state of glee. It grew out of my love for certain
kinds of novels in the English comic tradition, the key figure
being Evelyn Waugh. I see it as a version of the comic novel that
does not attempt to be funny at every turn, which I find quite
oppressive, like someone blowing the trumpet in your ear.''
</P>
<P>
   McEwan has always been the least horn-blowing among the British
writers of his generation, a peculiarly cliquish bunch that
includes _ most well known on this side of the Atlantic _ novelists
Martin Amis and Julian Barnes and journalist Hitchens, all of whom
studied together at Oxford in the late 1960s and early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must be the only writer in Britain who did not go to Oxford
or Cambridge,'' McEwan cracks. ``Novel writing is such a democratic
activity, you don't need a lot of money to get started. So it does
seem extraordinary to me _ I mean, to write novels, you need to be
literate and imaginative, but I can't believe that Oxford and
Cambridge have a monopoly on them.''
</P>
<P>
   McEwan went to the University of Sussex, and cannot think of
another writer who did the same. His mother was a chambermaid. His
father joined the army to escape unemployment and ``rose through
the ranks slowly.'' Ian was, practically speaking, an only child.
(He has a half brother and half sister, but they are much older; he
didn't grow up with either.) At age 11, he was sent to a state-run
boarding school, not one of the private institutions that most
British writers attended. The masters who ran it, he recalls, ``had
the old-fashioned left view of taking working-class kids and
turning them into middle-class kids.'' Nearly all his classmates _
poor bright boys from central London _ went on to university.
</P>
<P>
   Sussex was a fairly new campus and, as McEwan puts it, ``had a
wish to redraw the map of learning.'' An English lit major at
Oxford focused on precisely that _ reading English literature, from
``Beowulf'' on up _ while his counterpart at Sussex delved into the
rest of European literature as well.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, at age 21, McEwan read Kafka, and that's when he
knew he wanted to be a writer. ``It seems odd to say this,'' McEwan
muses, ``but Kafka was like freedom to me. It wasn't bogged down in
a documented social world. Knowing nothing about the social world''
_ by which he means the world of high society _ ``I found it
liberating that I could be a writer and not know whether that's a
Louis Quatorze chair you're sitting on. British literature was so
much like an overstuffed chair. Kafka was much more elemental,
stripped down to the basics. It wasn't `Lady Olivia opened the
telegram, screaming with delight.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McEwan fell in with the Oxford-bred literati in the mid-1970s,
when he started attending the Friday lunches organized by a set of
young writers at the New Statesman, including Amis, the magazine's
literary editor at the time; Barnes, who was Amis's deputy; and
Hitchens, a political contributor. When the BBC banned a play that
McEwan had written, Amis, as a tweak to the establishment,
published it in its entirety. Their friendship deepened as a result
_ though McEwan's style has always stood apart: more Continental,
more Kafkaesque.
</P>
<P>
   Kafka's stories also appealed to McEwan for what he calls their
``dark humor,'' and though ``Amsterdam'' is his most explicitly
comic work, the earlier books, too, betray the occasional cocked
eyebrow lurking between the lines, sometimes all too subtly.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, ``Enduring Love'' ends with a 14-page appendix
purporting to be a clinical case study _ reprinted from the British
Review of Psychiatry, replete with bibliography and obscure
citations _ about an obsessive-deluded patient who appears to be
the real-life model of a deranged character in McEwan's novel.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, McEwan says, this case study is ``entirely made
up.'' The careful reader will note that the names of its authors,
Drs. Wenn and Camia, form an anagram of McEwan's own name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some reviewer criticized me for following the case study far
too mechanically,'' he says with a mischievous chuckle. ``Talk
about stepping in it. That gave me great pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   McEwan lives in Oxford with his second wife and, occasionally,
his two sons from a previous marriage, which ended in a nasty
divorce. (He wrote a children's book for them, ``The Daydreamer,''
a delightful work that didn't find an audience here.) He loves to
hike, a passion that informs the crucial scene in ``Amsterdam'' _
and another way in which he differs from most British writers, who
tend to be, as he puts it, ``lounge lizards.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls his politics ``soft leftish.'' In the '80s, he wrote an
antinuclear oratorio, titled ``Or Shall We Die?'' His most
critically celebrated novel, ``The Innocent,'' ended with a hope
that the dreams shattered by the Cold War might be rebuilt in the
new Berlin. Five months after finishing that book, McEwan recalls,
the Berlin Wall came crashing down and he rushed to the scene,
spending ``a delirious two days and nights, roaming the city'' _
which inspired the opening of his next novel, ``Black Dogs,'' a
more pessimistic post-Cold War parable.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, a Latin jazz tune wafts over the PA system of the
SoHo Grand Hotel lobby. McEwan sways his head and briefly hums
along. ``That's Ry Cooder and the Buena Vista Social Club,'' he
says. ``A group of Cuban musicians. They played in London. Great
stuff.'' He listens some more. ``I've got to get down to Cuba,
before American corporations take it over.'' He pauses. ``Not that
Castro was very brilliant at running things, either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
