u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-02 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONORING A DISHONORABLE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (w and k coding)  
 (For use by New York Times   News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; _ Three men and one woman, united in an artistic
triumph arguably without parallel in the American theater. Three
men and one woman, divided by the experience of evil _ large,
medium, and small. And then united one last time by happy and ugly
coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Broadway production of Arthur Miller's protean
``Death of a Salesman'' just happened to open last month as
Hollywood was arranging to give a career Oscar to one of its
trail-blazing directors, Elia Kazan.
</P>
<P>
   Those two occurrences link our cast from the original production
50 years ago: Miller; Kazan, its director; the late Lee J. Cobb
(the first Willy Loman); and the late Mildred Dunnock (the first
Linda). The link, however, is not merely artistic, but political _
the very different brushes each had with the fanatical
anticommunism that drove America crazy during the late '40s, '50s,
and early '60s in an effort to combat a bestial ideology with
enforced conformity and Constitution-shattering cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   Kazan's Oscar is properly controversial. He is a gigantic figure
in the performing arts, inextricably linked with the formative
period of Miller's and Tennessee Williams's explosion onto the
stage, and a director of seminal importance to Hollywood's
occasional flirtation with excellence (``Gentleman's Agreement,''
``Viva Zapata,'' ``On the Waterfront,'' ``East of Eden''). He turns
90 this fall, and Hollywood has honored many a less worthy creative
life.
</P>
<P>
   But Kazan is also a pathetically protypical rat-fink of the
anticommunist hysteria, whose self-serving opportunism before the
House Committee on Un-American Activities in April 1952 preserved
his prosperous career without advancing the struggle against
communism an inch; whose name-naming not only was restricted to the
weak or already black-listed; but whose service in the American
inquisition gave it the kind of legitmacy it craved to ruin the
lives of tens of thousands of teachers, writers, directors, and
performers on the basis of their associations and political
beliefs, not any crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The exquisite irony of his upcoming honor is the insistence of
the board of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences that
it is recognizing his artistic life, not his politics _ an
insistence made more cogent by the board member and Kazan friend
who started all this, veteran actor Karl Malden, who began his
career under Kazan in the 1930s in New York's Group Theatre where
more than one person eventually defamed by him worked.
</P>
<P>
   The academy's assertion that Kazan's art matters apart from his
politics is precisely the point. By blessing the inquisition, Kazan
got to have that life; no one will ever know how many other great
artists never got the chance to develop because of the system his
perfidy helped legitimize.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Miller chose a different path. Kazan decision's to
protect his own career at the cost of others split them deeply.
When Miller's turn before the infamous House committee came in
1956, he refused to talk names on First Amendment grounds,
testifying only about himself. And where Kazan took refuge in
simplistic melodrama to make the informer's case in ``On the
Waterfront,'' Miller took on the hysteria in memorable depth via
metaphor (``The Crucible'') and genuine moral dilemma (``A View
from the Bridge'').
</P>
<P>
   Lee J. Cobb's story is best told in Victor S. Navasky's
encyclopedic account of the Hollywood blacklist, ``Naming Names.''
Cobb held out for two years after the investigators came calling in
1951, during which he went broke and lost his first wife to
alcoholism. Shortly after he cracked and named 20 names, he had a
massive coronary. When Navasky interviewed him in the 1970s, he
showed regret, multifaceted bitterness and sadness. Said Cobb:
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the Mephistophelian mystery that the Reds have
bequeathed to the world is the ability to make one confess without
any truncheon marks on one's head. You start out wanting to keep
your friends. In a totalitarian country they want you to betray
your friends, and you persuade yourself finally it is your duty. On
the tortuous road to that conclusion lie many bleached bones of
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Mildred Dunnock was luckier. Utterly nonpolitical, she couldn't
get work after being named in a right-wing publication as being
friendly with the likes of Miller, Lillian Hellman, and even Kazan
himself. Her husband, a banker, used his connections to get a
retraction. ``It gave me an emotional understanding of being
accused,'' she told The New York Times years later in a clip
Navasky unearthed. ``I felt contaminated, I felt I had leprosy, I
felt I had incriminated my husband, a conventional man.''
</P>
<P>
   They say Malden himself may give the Oscar speech for Kazan this
month. One hopes the applause is scattered and perfunctory, for
this is a dishonorable man.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
