<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENDELL'S DELIGHTFULLY HORRIBLE `SIGHT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
A SIGHT FOR SORE EYES 
By Ruth Rendell 
Crown, 327 pp., $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This intricately structured novel weaves the lives of three odd,
damaged people into a plot drenched with impending tragedy. In this
delightfully horrible story, Ruth Rendell's main characters are on
an unavoidable collision course with catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of ``A Sight for Sore Eyes'' the three live
separate lives in different parts of London.
</P>
<P>
   At age 7, Francine Hill was found mute and soaked in blood,
sitting beside her murdered mother's body. Ten years later she
seems to have put the trauma behind her and has matured into a
lovely young woman. Richard, her guilt-stricken philosopher father,
is overprotective but emotionally distant. Julia, her paranoid,
crank-psychologist stepmother, tries to monitor and control every
aspect of Francine's life, which only makes Francine more naive and
vulnerable to evil.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful, feckless Harriet Oxenholme, thrown over and tossed
out by her rock-star boyfriend, found another meal ticket in
Franklin Merton, a dull, older, prosperous married man. Smitten
with Harriet's glamour, Franklin left his wife. Ten years later
Harriet is begining to lose both her looks and Franklin, and has
taken to scanning newspaper ads to find virile young handymen
willing to provide sex as well as home repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Teddy Brex was raised in squalor by benighted parents who never
kissed or cuddled him, rarely even talked to him. Against all
expectations, Teddy attended university and earned a degree in
ornamental art, winning the school's top prize for his work. Teddy
is drawn to beautiful things and will do anything to acquire what
he wants. Since his emotionally deprived upbringing has made him a
sociopath with the instincts of a weasel, ``anything'' includes
murder.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear from the outset of ``A Sight for Sore Eyes'' that the
lives of these three characters will intersect and that nothing
good will come of their meeting _ nothing good except the kind of
engrossingly nasty story Rendell's fans have come to expect from
her.
</P>
<P>
   The highly acclaimed Rendell is sometimes called ``the crime
writer's crime writer,'' though crime reader's crime writer might
be more apt. She's known for her innovative approach to the genre.
Even her Inspector Wexford police procedurals don't conform to
mystery conventions. She also writes more traditional novels under
the name Barbara Vine. In an interview she once said that she
started writing as Vine because she wanted to experiment with a
``more feminine'' approach, to try ``a softer voice speaking at a
slower pace, more sensitive perhaps, and more intuitive.''
Whichever name she writes under, Rendell is both sensitive and
intuitive _ psychologically insightful, brilliant at portraying
character, able to render her creations believably human and
sympathetic, if not always likable.
</P>
<P>
   To write much more about the plot would spoil the pleasure for
the book's readers. ``A Sight for Sore Eyes'' is high-quality
Rendell _ not in a class with her masterpiece, ``A Judgement in
Stone,'' but that's asking a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The novel has a small problem or two. Julia, Francine's evil
stepmother, could have stepped straight out of the Brothers Grimm.
Where did she come from? Why is she so crazy? It's never made
clear. The ending of the novel could be troublesome for some
readers. It's either a neat stroke of irony or a cop-out, depending
on one's point of view. It's probably not giving too much away to
reveal that by the last page, everybody gets what he or she
deserves. (Actually, one gets a lot more than she deserves, but
that's just one reader's opinion.) This is not always the case in
Rendell's books. Sometmes wickedness goes unpunished, or appears to
go unpunished. This seeming moral ambiguity is just one of many
reasons her novels are so consistently interesting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
