<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUOMO MISFIRES IN SUIT AGAINST BOSTON COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andrew, you're no Mario.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cuomo _ the US secretary of Housing and Urban
Development, son of the legendary ex-governor of New York, and Al
Gore loyalist _ greatly irritated the mayor of Boston last month
when he released a report charging the city with systemic
discrimination in its public housing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the HUD secretary is on the losing end of a lawsuit filed
on behalf of a Boston-based energy company. Damages _ monetary and
political _ could be hefty.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 12, the US government quietly conceded liability for
improperly canceling its lucrative contract with Energy Capital
Partners of Boston. The concession is bad news for HUD, the party
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   The company's two principals _ Alan M. Leventhal and Fred A.
Seigel _ are not just any Boston businessmen. They are two of the
Clinton administration's biggest supporters, and both are hugely
successful Democratic party fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Their lawsuit, filed in the US Court of Federal Claims, charged
that HUD wrongfully canceled its contract with ECP on the basis of
a Feb. 7, 1997, article in The Wall Street Journal. The Page 1
story suggested that ECP had obtained the contract strictly because
of Leventhal and Seigel's political fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   The government's position was greatly undercut by the language
in the letter of termination sent by Nicolas P. Retsinas, then an
assistant HUD secretary and commissioner of the Federal Housing
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Seigel, dated Feb. 14, 1977, Retsinas wrote:
``While I know that the FHA negotiated and entered into that
agreement solely to assist project residents and reduce taxpayer
risk by strengthening the FHA fund, the mention of the agreement in
the context of the larger Wall Street Journal article potentially
creates the appearance of an impropriety.''
</P>
<P>
   Would HUD terminate a contract on the basis of innuendo, not
because of an actual breach or other unlawful conduct? Apparently
the agency did just that, setting the stage for the suit filed in
November 1997 by Boston lawyer R. Robert Popeo.
</P>
<P>
   Popeo declined comment, referring only to the public record of
the proceedings. Leventhal and Seigel were also unavailable for
comment. They are said to be seeking damages in the $50 million
range.
</P>
<P>
   Ginny Terzano, a HUD spokeswoman, says the agency terminated the
contract because of concerns over the ``appearance of an exclusive
no-bid contract.'' The contract was awarded in September 1996,
after more than a year of negotiations and before Cuomo took over
HUD. Before the bad press, HUD touted the $200 million program to
make federally assisted housing more energy efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morally, it was the right thing to do, although legally, the
contract may have been valid,'' says Terzano now, about the abrupt
contract termination.
</P>
<P>
   Retsinas left HUD a year ago. Cuomo remains in charge of a
federal agency long blasted for fiscal mismanagement, as well as
for letting politics interfere regularly with government business.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming HUD secretary in 1997, Cuomo drew flattering
reviews for admitting the truth about the agency's weaknesses _ he
called it, for instance, a ``poster child for inept government.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he is trying to change the perception and reality at
HUD. But in the case involving Energy Capital Partners, his concern
for political image seems to have gotten in the way of political
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, a trusted adviser to Vice President Al Gore, is vying to
play a major role in Gore's presidential campaign. Just last week,
his dad told an audience at Harvard University that Andrew has
``everything his old man has . . . and he's the next generation.
You should keep your eye on Andrew.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Andrew has the family eloquence and the family arrogance.
Along with that comes an exceptional sense of entitlement that is
often part of the legacy famous men pass on to their sons. The
result: Mario Cuomo remains a hero to many Massachusetts Democrats.
At the moment, his son is out of favor with some of them, including
some key Gore supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo could very well be correct in his critique of the Boston
Housing Authority. The HUD report is based on old data, but the
BHA's historic treatment of minorities is shabby enough to be
suspect, even today. So perhaps Cuomo will proudly stand on
principle and believe it is worth upsetting Mayor Menino, despite
the dominant role he plays in Massachusetts politics.
</P>
<P>
   But going after the likes of Leventhal and Seigel on a
perception that now turns out to be a misperception? That is not
smart policy or politics _ for Andrew Cuomo or for Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
