<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW ISSUES TO BAT AROUND IN THIS CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Camp Tranquility, my guys call it.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to my distinguished Boston, Providence,
Worcester, Hartford, and All Points USA colleagues, so? Ever think
perhaps we've all been kind of spoiled over the years?
</P>
<P>
   In a normal major league baseball spring training camp,
five-time batting champions aren't revealed to have had major
extramarital affairs on the eve of spring training. They don't
speak of falling out of trucks or willing themselves invisible.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal major league baseball spring training camp, Cy Young
Award-winning pitchers don't show up late and then strap on
headphones while talking to their new manager.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal major league baseball spring training camp,
slugging, contract-challenged first basemen don't arrive direct
from acquittals in DUI trials and then launch three bombs in their
return game.
</P>
<P>
   All this constitutes falling-out-of-sky news. It constitutes
stories that write themselves. It is all sort of business as usual
for the Boston Red Sox, who, after all, are the only team in major
league baseball history to have a pitcher stabbed to death at a
spring training fish fry (Big Ed Morris, 1932). Spring training
always has had a special cachet around here.
</P>
<P>
   But this year it's a little quiet, which, come to think of it,
is probably how the GM likes it. Mo is about as far away as he
could be, and we know the GM likes that. There are no overt loose
cannons, only closet ones (my lips are sealed, the better to
protect a source or two).
</P>
<P>
   There are no festering personal issues, at least when it comes
to contracts. The key people are all signed up for a while. The
Closer is inked through 2000, plus option. The Shortstop is set
through 2002, with options running through 2004. The Third Baseman
is signed through 2001. The Ace of the Staff is theirs through
2003, plus option. The Knuckleballer is signed through 2000, plus
option. The Veteran Rehab is signed through 2001, plus option.
These six people represent the core of the team. They're all
well-paid, and they all know it.
</P>
<P>
   So scratch contracts as an issue. What we are left with is _ are
you ready? _ baseball. The game between the lines is the issue.
We're just not used to that.
</P>
<P>
   And even here there are really only two major topics of
interest. We all know that Mark Portugal and Pat Rapp are being
conceded the fourth and fifth spots in the rotation beyond Pedro
Martinez, Tim Wakefield, and Bret Saberhagen. We all know that Tom
Gordon is the closer and that Derek Lowe, Jim Corsi, and Mark
Guthrie will set up, and that John Wasdin is close to a lock. That
leaves one pitching job, if that.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that Jason Varitek and Scott Hatteberg will split
the catching, with Mike Stanley ready, just in case. We all know
who will play short and third. We all know that Troy O'Leary will
be the everyday left fielder. We all know that Darren Lewis is the
regular center fielder. We all know that the door is open for Trot
Nixon to take the right field job, but we also know that Damon
Buford is going to play, somehow, some way, and that Lewis will
wind up playing some right, as well.
</P>
<P>
   What we don't know is what's going to happen with the right side
of the infield. There are second basemen up the wazoo, not to
mention a proliferation of 1B/DH sorts. Figuring out what to do
with this bunch should give Jimy Williams something to think about
for approximately 22 hours of every working day between now and the
opener in Kansas City 34 days hence.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think so, anyway, but Williams is not necessarily like
most other managers, and he most definitely isn't like the average
Red Sox writer or fan. What obsesses us doesn't obsess this
tranquil man at all. He's been around baseball too long to worry
about every little thing. In the Jimy Williams world view, things
have a very convenient way of taking care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   We look at Jose Offerman and say, ``Where is he going to play?''
We know that Jeff Frye, Donnie Sadler, and Lou Merloni can all play
second base better than Jose can. That's just a given. We assume
that Williams would like Frye to earn his old job back. We also
assume that Dan Duquette would like to see Offerman play second
because that would make the GM seem less foolish for throwing $26
million at a slap hitter who does not fit the offensive profile of
either a first baseman or a DH. And if he plays first base, that
means Williams wouldn't have both Reggie Jefferson and Stanley in
the lineup at the same time, and Lord knows this team needs all the
thump it can get.
</P>
<P>
   Let's complicate things even more. There are some of us who
wonder why more consideration isn't being given to promote Sadler
to a position of importance on this team. Frye is a better major
league hitter, for sure, but while Frye is a good glove man he is
no Sadler. The young man's range is phenomenal, and if he hits even
a little he will bring almost unprecedented speed to the Boston
lineup. Sooner or later, the Red Sox must figure out what to do
with Sadler, who will turn 24 on June 24. But I assure you Jimy
isn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of stuff that makes a good Red Sox fan's hair
not just hurt, but ache, and ache incessantly. Offerman is an
expensive piece of the puzzle and he just doesn't seem to fit. You
know you want a guy capable of getting on base 40 percent of the
time in the lineup, but where can he play and not kill you? If he
winds up at second, we will know that the manager has lost a power
struggle with the GM. If he plays first, whither either Jefferson
or Stanley? And is any DH who doesn't hit for power worth $6
million a year?
</P>
<P>
   Well, guess what? The manager is right. It probably will sort
itself out through some kind of natural selection process. Hey,
it's all good baseball talk, and it's all we've got. I don't know
about you, but I don't need anything else.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1356EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4531 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SOSA-BOS &LR;      03-02 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA ISN'T ON A POWER TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ Same old Sammy Sosa. Coming off a whirlwind
offseason, the Chicago Cubs slugger may be even more powerful and
more motivated than he was last fall when he battled Mark McGwire
for home run supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa emphasized this Monday, his first day of spring training
with the Cubs. He was smiling. It was satisfying enough that he had
66 home runs, four behind McGwire. And he wouldn't mind being named
the National League Most Valuable Player for a second straight
year. He's hungry enough to go for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is for the Cubs to get to the World Series,'' Sosa
said at a news conference that seemed more like a gathering of old
friends. ``I want to do my job and put some numbers up. I want to
do what I can to help my teammates and earn their respect. We're a
family and if we stay together and play as a team as we did in
1998, we're going to go a long, long way.''
</P>
<P>
   What was that again?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play on a team where everybody is together and
everybody wants to win and everybody believes in himself, you know
we're going to do much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Many thought that a busy offseason may have worn down Sosa, who
traveled all over America and to Japan with a major league all-star
team. Many a gladiator has fallen victim to the knife-and-fork
circuit. Sosa begged to differ with those who asked. His weight is
222 pounds, 12 more than last year, but the extra bulk was pure
muscle. Sosa was away from his home in the Dominican Republic for
all but two weeks. The requests far outweighed the time he had
available. But Sosa was able to meet the demand. Spring training
will seem like a break for him.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be nice if Sosa and McGwire resume their battle in
1999?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the man,'' Sosa said in a familiar mantra. ``I hope he
has another great year. I say that because for the last three years
Mark has hit over 50 home runs. This is my first time going over
50. I have a lot of respect for Mark McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Sosa appended his remark when it was pointed out that
he was MVP and his team made the NL playoffs, while the Cardinals
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGwire is still the man,'' said Sosa. ``But I'm the man at
Wrigley Field. That's my house. I can't give that away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change. I never forget where I came from. No
matter how high or how low I am I want to keep it the same way.
Also, I'm still humble. This is my job. As long as I have a Chicago
Cubs uniform on my back I'm going to play hard every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Sosa went through his paces as if he'd been in camp for
weeks. He hit a home run on the second pitch thrown his way in
batting practice. He signed autographs for a half-hour. Finally, he
held separate press conferences for the electronic and print media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll have another year like that in 1999,''
said Sosa. ``But you never know what can happen. Facing McGwire was
great. I think it came at the right time and helped me put up some
big numbers. As for 1999, I don't need to go out and set records
again. Just go out and play the same game, be there for my team, my
teammates, and my manager. Go out and play the game and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa shook as many hands as he could Monday. Teammates were
pleased to see him in camp and already in playing condition. But
nobody felt better than manager Jim Riggleman. Sosa's presence
seems to lift everything and everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried about Sammy,'' said Riggleman. ``Japan was
good. He was playing baseball, which was good. He didn't get tired.
He knows how to take care of himself. I don't give Sammy advice.
He's pretty much in control of himself and his programs. His
responsibility to me is come out and play hard every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his travel schedule, Sosa made arrangements for
private workouts several times. He also lifted weights at home. All
this while overseeing the work of the foundation that bears his
name. Sosa was a major contributor to a relief fund for hurricane
victims in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important,'' said Sosa. ``The hurricane was unbelievable.
It went through my country and it destroyed everything. There were
a lot of people suffering. It's not like here in the US where you
have the opportunity to eat and to get whatever you need. Back
there, you don't have that kind of support. Here, I have the
support of the American people and it saves a lot of lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has a lot of memories that will last a lifetime. Hitting
home runs No. 61 and 62 rank high. Having his family in Chicago for
Sammy Sosa Day was another. The best might have been a two-week
break at Christmas, which he spent at home with his wife and
children. It was nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a beautiful wife,'' he said.``My kids, my family. They
understand everything. They understand I am in a situation where I
can't say no to people. She talks to me everyday and supported me
100 percent. I've been blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa had only one request before he stopped talking. Don't
compare him to Michael Jordan, the retired Chicago Bulls superstar
who still rules the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody will replace Michael Jordan,'' said Sosa. ``Besides, I
don't want to be like Mike. I want to be like Sammy Sosa. And
whatever Sammy Sosa gives is because he works hard. I'll play my
game. I want to be the best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
