<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINA, RISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So Carlos Menem of Argentina Monday abandoned his plans to press
for a third term as president of Argentina. That's good. The
flamboyant 68-year-old, who over the past eight years has
skillfully led Argentina back to democracy and economic stability,
would have had to badger the Supreme Court he mostly appointed for
permission to seek a third consecutive term _ a possibility
expressly forbidden by the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Menem also has as much as acknowledged as a nonstarter his
surprise proposal last month to abandon the Argentine peso to use
US dollars exclusively throughout the economy. That's good, too, at
least for now.
</P>
<P>
   For however desirable a spreading monetary union in Latin
America eventually might be, the ground has not been prepared for
it to succeed. Much work remains to be done. That was the message
that Adalberto Rodriguez Giavarini brought to Boston last week.
There were few who disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Giavarini is the man who presumably would serve as finance
minister should his Alliance defeat Menem's Peronist party in the
autumn elections. Formerly he was treasurer of Buenos Aires,
population 20 million. (The city's mayor, Fernando de la Rua,
leader of the liberal Alliance, is leading comfortably in the
polls.) The very fact that Giavarini is touring global financial
centers, working on regulatory issues and making plans makes an
important point about Argentina's success in narrowing its
differences of opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gap used to be very wide,'' he says, holding up his hands.
``Now it is 10 degrees, 12 degrees, 15 degrees. These are
manageable differences.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the best news of all. The last eighteen months have seen
one casualty after another among the the world's fastest growing
new market economies _ and never mind Japan, which remains sunk in
a stubborn slump. Thailand, Indonesia, Korea, Russia and most
recently Brazil have suffered major currency crises and
corresponding bitter recessions.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentine economy has shrunk, too _ but without the
exaggerating effects of a currency crash, thanks to the
government's policy since 1991 of converting pesos to dollars on
demand. With nearly 60 percent of bank deposits in Argentina
denominated in dollars and greenbacks circulating freely throughout
the cities, Argentinos have been untroubled by the soaring
inflation and capital flight that have plagued other transition
economies.
</P>
<P>
   Automated teller machines dispense dollars and pesos
side-by-side. Long-term contracts such as mortgages routinely are
denominated in dollars, says Giavarini.
</P>
<P>
   So why the sudden proposal to eliminate the peso altogether and
cede much of the right to run the Argentinian economy to the US
Federal Reserve Board, through a series of agreements on bank
supervision, deficit finance and layoffs?
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways of viewing the dollarization proposal,
Giavarini replies. One view is that it is an opportunity to enhance
Argentina's reputation. ``If somebody else devalues, you double
your bet on the dollar and put yourselves at the other end of the
deal _ or so the argument goes'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The other view paints dollarization as a panacea _ a seemingly
technical measure that might precipitate deep changes in the
Argentinian banking system and fiscal and monetary regimes. If that
were the government's purpose, then the plan was presented in a
decidedly ``untidy'' manner, Giavarini says. No wonder Fed chairman
Alan Greenspan has nixed the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Monetary agreement with the United States is a distinct
possibility, Giavarini says; so is a regional central bank, much
like the European Central Bank that is now in the early stage of
producing a pan-European currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   But such measures take time _ and they involve costs. Four or
five years is not too soon to be aiming for some form of
dollarization, says Giavarini.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the constant stream of meetings: Davos one week,
Washington and Boston the next, then off to Basel and Tokyo. Among
the many nations around the world playing catch-up, Argentina is
among those with good news.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe; his
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
