<SLUG> BC-MUSCULAR-DISEASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISEASE CRIPPLES VOLUNTARY MUSCLE FUNCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Lynn Deas had hoped to trump.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when she went to Orlando, Fla., to play in the national
bridge championships in December, she could endure only half a
session of cards before suffering a relapse.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the former world champion bridge player has been in
St. Peter's Hospital in Albany, waging her latest battle against
myasthenia gravis, a rare and chronic neuromuscular disease that
weakens the voluntary muscles of the body, including ones that
control eye movements, eyelids, chewing, swallowing, coughing and
facial expression. Today, 2 1/2 years after her original diagnosis,
Deas is no longer able to walk, sit, feed herself or play cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I used to travel around the country and the world,''
Deas said. ``It's terrible. You get dehumanized. I'm just ready to
go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Deas, 46, returns to her home, or goes to a nursing home
for rehabilitation, is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't kept Deas from organizing events from her
bedside to raise more research money for a disease that few people
know much about.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 35,000 Americans affected by MG are believed to
suffer from a type of the disease described as autoimmune. In those
cases, the body's immune system mistakenly attacks and destroys
special proteins on the muscle, known as receptors.
</P>
<P>
   When those receptors are healthy, they receive nerve impulses
from the brain that tell the muscle to contract. When those
receptors are damaged, the response of the muscle to nerve impulses
is poor and weakness occurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is a failure to communicate,'' said Dr. Charles
Thornton, clinical director of the University of Rochester
Neuromuscular Disease Center at Strong Memorial Hospital in
Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another, extremely rare type of MG is congenital, when the
disease is believed to be triggered by a genetic defect in
neuromuscular transmission.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers, however, still aren't sure what causes most people
to develop MG. Although it can strike at any time, MG tends to
affect women most often in their child-bearing years and men most
often in middle age.
</P>
<P>
   One common source of frustration for people with MG is that the
disease affects everyone differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unpredictable,'' Thornton said. ``It changes from day to
day.'' And because the symptoms tend to come and go, it's often
difficult to diagnose, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been progress in treating MG. ``Before 1960, when
there weren't any effective treatments, about 30 percent of people
who developed MG died from it,'' Thornton said. ``Today we expect
almost everyone to survive and their symptoms to be under excellent
control or adequate control. Many patients now go into remission.''
</P>
<P>
   Medications are usually aimed at boosting the nerve signals to
the muscles or at targeting the immune system. In some cases,
physicians are using the same type of anti-rejection medications
used in transplant patients to try to prevent the immune system
from attacking the muscles.
</P>
<P>
   A common surgical treatment is to remove the thymus gland, an
organ involved in the development of the immune system. For reasons
that are unclear, the thymus gland becomes unusually large in
people with MG.
</P>
<P>
   On a daily regimen of drugs, Deas is hopeful she'll soon go into
remission. Or in the very least, be stable enough to go home to her
husband and seven dogs. Until then, she's imagining her next trump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'll be able to walk in August,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
