<HEADLINE>
SUFFOLK TO GET AN EARLY START ON THE DUBAI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If you're an early riser, Suffolk Downs is the place to
be March 28. That's the date of the $5 million Dubai World Cup,
which has an 11:15 a.m. EST post, and Suffolk intends to run a live
10-race program that will alternate with the five-race World Cup
card from Nad Al Sheba. Gates will open at 9 a.m, the Dubai card
will begin at 9:30, and live racing will commence at 10. Final post
at Suffolk is set for 3 p.m. Suffolk is the only track in the
country that will race its own card in conjunction with the races
in Dubai.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Suffolk staged a similar morning program for the
inaugural World Cup and, with money pouring in from simulcasting
sites, established a then-record total handle of $2,359,863. The
first World Cup was run on a Wednesday, making that Suffolk handle
even more amazing, while this year's renewal will be on a Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates an opportunity to do much better than we normally
would on a Sunday,'' said Suffolk vice president Lou Raffetto. ``I
don't think it will be a windfall for us, but it's a chance to make
more, and we're going to take advantage of it. The early post will
be a help to our simulcast patners who would otherwise have
difficulty opening early for races from a foreign country that are
spaced far apart. Filling the void in this manner is also a service
to our on-track customers who come out early to see the World Cup
simulcast.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nad Al Sheba card is worth a total of $6.2 million in purses
and also includes the Dubai Turf Classic, the Dubai Duty Free, the
Nad Al Sheba Sprint, and the Nad Al Sheba Mile.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm lined up
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dubai World Cup is expected to feature defending champion
Silver Charm, who will race next in Saturday's $1 million Santa
Anita Handicap, Puerto Madero, who finished second to Skip Away in
last year's Massachusetts Handicap and is also headed for the Big
'Cap, and Victory Gallop, who won the 1998 Belmont Stakes. Silver
Charm has been assigned highweight of 124 pounds for the Santa
Anita Handicap, run at 1 1/4 miles, while Free House, winner of the
San Antonio, was given 123, and Puerto Madero, who defeated Silver
Charm in the Donn Handicap at Gulfstream, will carry 122. Next in
line is Event of the Year, winner of the Strub Stakes, at 119;
Malek, 118; Dr. Fong, 117; Behrens, 115; Budroyale, 114; Lord
Grillo, also 114, and Don't Blame Rio, 112. Richard Mandella, who
trains Puerto Madero, Event of the Year, and Malek, reportedly will
hold Malek back and enter his other two standouts. Malek, who was
fourth in last year's World Cup, is scheduled to return to Dubai .
. . Elliot Walden, who trains Victory Gallop, is going to avoid a
confrontation with Real Quiet, who defeated Victory Gallop in the
Kentucky Derby and Preakness. Walden had indicated that he would
send his charge against Bob Baffert's top 4-year-old in the New
Orleans Handicap at Fair Grounds Sunday but entered him in an
allowance race at Gulfstream Wednesday instead. ``We intend the
allowance race as a prep for the Dubai World Cup,'' said Walden.
``We are sorry not to be going to the Fair Grounds, but we have to
do what is in the best interest of he the horse.'' The allowance
race is at a mile and one-16th against four foes, and Victory
Gallop will be ridden by Jerry Bailey, who is slated to become his
regular rider. Neither Real Quiet nor Victory Gallop has started
this year, and Walden apparently decided a dramatic duel in a
graded stakes race was too much, too soon for his charge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coming north?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The victory by Behrens in the Grade I, $350,000 Gulfstream Park
Handicap Saturday gave a boost to the MassCap. Raffetto stays in
close touch with James Bond, who trains Behrens, and there is a
very good chance the 5-year-old son of Pleasant Colony will come to
Suffolk for the $600,000 event May 29. Bond supported the MassCap
in '97, sending up Will's Way, who ran third behind Skip Away and
Formal Gold. That contest highlighted an outstanding card that
established the current Suffolk handle mark of $5,867,419. Behrens
had run second, between Puerto Madero and Silver Charm, in the
Donn, and he captured the Gulfstream Park Handicap with authority
under Jorge Chavez. The Santa Anita Handicap is obviously too close
for Behrens, who has earned $1.2 million, and he will start next in
either the Oaklawn Handicap April 3 or, if he needs more rest, the
Pimlico Special May 8. Behrens, who won the Pegasus and was second
in the Travers at age 3, had an injury-plagued 4-year-old campaign
and did not win a race. ``I know he's a good horse,'' said Bond.
``I just don't think he got the respect he deserved as a
3-year-old. He's had three races here and he won't go in both the
Oaklawn Handicap and Pimlico Special. He loves this track, and our
main goal is to be here for the Breeders' Cup (Nov. 6).'' . . . The
Kentucky Derby picture heated up over the weekend with three
talented sophomores giving excellent accounts of themselves. Most
eye-catching was the determined victory by Desert Hero in the
$200,000 San Rafael at Santa Anita Sunday. The San Rafael, a Grade
II contest, was only the second start of Desert Hero's career, but
the 10-1 shot tallied despite being checked at the eighth-pole and
yanked to the outside by Corey Nakatani. Desert Hero, who is
trained by Wally Dollase, still got up in time to beat Prime
Timber, one of Baffert's talented 3-year-olds, by a neck. Finishing
fifth, but beaten only a length, was the previously undefeated
filly Honest Lady. A son of 1993 Derby winner Sea Hero, out of
Multiply, an Easy Goer mare, Desert Hero debuted just three weeks
ago, winning a maiden race by more than 6 lengths. ``I felt he
could be a Derby horse because he does everything right,'' said
Dollase, who had to delay Desert Hero's debut for three months
because of an infected hoof. ``He's a fast, intelligent horse
that's bred to go long. I think if he had a cleaner trip, he would
have won fairly handily.'' Also drawing attention were Lemon Drop
Kid and Menifee, who won allowance races at Gulfstream Saturday in
their 3-year-old bows. Lemon Drop Kid, who is trained by Scotty
Schulhofer, won the Belmont Futurity last year, and is headed for
the Blue Grass at Keeneland April 10. Menifee, who is trained by
Walden and is 3 for 3, will go in the Rebel at Oaklawn March 20 or
the Gotham at Aqueduct March 21 . . . Rowland Hoyt, the host of
Suffolk's in-house TV handicapping show, known affectionately as
``paddock prattle,'' has accepted a job with Racing Network, a
24-hour satellite service based in Philadelphia, which launches
March 8. Racing Network will cover more than 30 tracks, including
Suffolk and Rockingham Park. Hoyt, 27, known for his dubious wit,
will be a studio host.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nominees are . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Museum of Racing has announced its list of nominees
for the Hall of Fame. Up for the honor this year are: trainers D.
Wayne Lukas, Neil Drysdale, and Mandella; jockeys Russell Baze,
Earlie Fires, and the late Jack Westrope; contemporary horse, male,
A.P. Indy, Precisionist, and Exceller; female, Dance Smartly,
Miesque, and Winning Colors; and horse of yesteryear, Bald Eagle,
Bowl of Flowers, and Gun Bow. A panel of 130 racing writers and
broadcasters vote for the Hall, with results to be announced during
Kentucky Derby Week . . . Banshee Breeze, the champion 3-year-old
filly of '98 trained by Carl Nafzger, made a smashing seasonal
debut with a powerful victory in the $200,000 Rampart Handicap at
Gulfstream Park Sunday. Ridden by Bailey, Banshee Breeze defeated
Glitterowman by more than 6 lengths in the time of 1:42 4/5 for the
mile and one-16th. Timely Broad, trained by Mike Petro and ridden
by Nick Petro, who used to campaign in New England, was a distant
third. ``I never cracked my whip,'' said Bailey. ``She's awesome.''
. . . The Baffert Brigade was back in action Sunday, as undefeated
Exploit, the winter book favorite for the Kentucky Derby, worked a
mile in 1:37, and outstanding filly Excellent Meeting went 6
furlongs in a best-of-the-day 1:12, both at Santa Anita. Exploit is
heading for San Felipe March 13, and Excellent Meeting for the
Santa Anita Oaks the following day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various tracks was used to
prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
