 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, March 3,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-GARLAND _ Elizabeth Garland, daughter of the Miami (Ohio)
University president, escapes as Rwandan rebels killed three people
and kidnapped 13 foreign tourists _ including three Americans _
from a campground in southwestern Uganda. (Fisher, Dayton Daily
News). 12.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   MONUMENT _ WASHINGTON _ The high-tech decorative scaffolding
around the Washington Monument will be bathed in light Tuesday
evening, a milestone in the two-year refurbishing of the granite
obelisk. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   TV-FATHERS _ WASHINGTON _ The National Fatherhood Initiative
holds a news conference to release a study on television's
portrayal of fathers. The report finds that only four prime time
television shows portray fathers ``who are both competent and
involved.'' (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMS-READ _ WASHINGTON _ Heisman trophy winner Rickey
Williams reads Dr. Suess's ``Green Eggs and Ham'' on Tuesday to
promote a National Education Association literacy program.
(Moscoso, Cox News Service). (Attention Texas papers).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (s) sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   SYPHILIS _ WASHINGTON _ It's not completely clear whether it was
carried by truck drivers or crack cocaine dealers, but an epidemic
of syphilis appears to have swept down I-95, at least the North
Carolina part of it, in the first half of the 1990s. Researchers
from the University of North Carolina report that the rate of
infection by the sexually transmitted disease in rural counties
along the interstate highway was similar to what is normally seen
only in big cities. The best guess as to the cause is that the
crack cocaine trade at opposite poles of I-95, Miami and New York,
gradually spread along the the interstate and the syphilis epidemic
followed. But you can't rule out truckers and prostitutes, authors
say. (Nesmith, Cox Washington Bureau). 15.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ WASHINGTON _ Sens. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., and Robert
Bennett, R-Utah, hold a news conference to unveil the Senate Y2K
Committee's report. (Glass, Cox Washington Bureau). 15.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   STOCK-GIFT _ An elderly North Georgia woman, who was left
millions of dollars in Coca-Cola Co. stock, has left much of her
holdings to Emory University and Young Harris College. Young Harris
is expected to receive more than $60 million in stock, while Emory
will recieve about $80 million. Two other beneficiaries also will
recieve stock, for a total distribution of $200 million. (Saporta,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-INDEPENDENCE-DAY _ AUSTIN _ Coverage of Texas Indepence
Day, focusing on the barbecues and speeches at the Capitol and a
series of Texana readings at the Univeristy of Texas at Austin,
including the first public reading of the Alamo Diaries. (Lindell,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WRIGHTFLYER-TESTS _ Actual wind tunnel testing scheduled to
begin today on the Wright Flyer replica in California. (Gaffney,
Dayton Daily News). 12-15. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Story might come in late. Testing runs from noon to 9 p.m.
CST.
</P>
<P>
   SWT-BIRTHDAY _ Southwest Texas is celebrating its 100th birthday
of its charter. We take a look at the past and the future of this
school, the sixth largest in Texas, south of Austin. Once a teacher
college it has a colorful history that includes one president being
tossed out by a governor, the educating of a future president and
now the educations of most of Texas' teachers. (Roser, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   QALEARN _ WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. _In one of the first efforts to
examine the influence of computers on education from kindergarten
through college, Wake Forest University is holding a national
conference for educators this week. Q&AMP;A with Craig Runde, director
of the university's International Center for Computer Enhanced
Learning, the conference's sponsor. (Burritt, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Today, chalk talk for political
junkies. Georgia's Secretary of State Cathy Cox's office recently
released an analysis of voter turnout in last November's election.
We already know who won and lost, but the study is a useful reality
check on who voted. Exit polls conducted on Election Day indicated
African-American voters made up 30 percent of the total votes cast,
a staggering leap in turnout. The state analysis, which can
reference every ballot cast by race, puts the actual percentage at
just under 23 percent. This has a couple of implications. (Baxter,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER-RADIO _ If a tornado comes through, even in the dead of
night, a small radio will wake you up, perhaps in time to seek
safety. The weather service says the radios might have saved lives
when a string of tornadoes tore through central Florida in February
1998 at a time when most people were asleep. ``Our goal is to
someday have a NOAA Weather Radio in every home, just like a smoke
detector, and in all schools, hospitals and other public gathering
places,'' Elbert W. Friday, Jr., former Director of the National
Weather Service, said in a statement. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
