<SLUG> BC-WINE-LABELS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR ACCUSES WINERIES OF MANIPULATING DIET GUIDELINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sen. Strom Thurmond has accused senior
government officials and a California wine industry association of
conspiring to manipulate government nutritional guidelines to
promote the sale of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond, R-S.C., sent letters to the inspectors general of the
Department of Health and Human Services and the Department of
Agriculture, asking them to investigate possible improper contacts
between the San Francisco-based Wine Institute and government
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not interested in outlawing alcoholic beverages or in
legislating morality,'' Thurmond said Monday. ``I am interested in
protecting the sanctity of public policy and in making certain that
the government does not get in the business of promoting or
endorsing a product that has been linked to some very serious
health problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond said he believed the Wine Institute put tremendous
pressure on government officials working with an advisory committee
that changed the government's approach to wine between its 1990 and
1995 dietary guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   He said he suspected ``inappropriate influence played a
significant role in drafting of the 1995 version,'' which had a
much more favorable view of the possible health benefits of wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flabbergasted,'' said Wine Institute President John De
Luca, who was identified by Thurmond as the source of much of the
allegedly inappropriate pressure. ``Senators are not supposed to
use the tax code and agencies of government to pursue personal
vengeance.''
</P>
<P>
   De Luca said the revision of the nutritional guidelines was done
in the open and the revisions were widely supported by scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of anything that's been more out in the open,
more debated,'' De Luca said. ``I guess the question is, who's the
one politicizing this?''
</P>
<P>
   Before the new version of the guidelines, the government's
position was that drinking alcohol had ``no net health benefit''
and ``consumption is not recommended.''
</P>
<P>
   Some health studies have indicated that limited consumption of
red wine can reduce the risk of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines now point out that alcoholic beverages,
particularly wines, have been used historically to enhance the
enjoyment of life and meals.
</P>
<P>
   The portion of the guidelines about the possible health benefits
of moderate alcohol consumption has been moved from the end of the
1990 version to the top of the 1995 version.
</P>
<P>
   The new guidelines also dropped references to alcohol's ``drug
effects'' and a footnote underscoring that booze can be fattening.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond blamed Dr. Phillip Lee, then the director of the U.S.
Public Health Service and a friend of De Luca, for deleting the
note about drug effects and wants investigators to demand an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants Lee, now head of the Institute for Health Policy
Studies at the University of California at San Francisco, to reveal
the extent of his communications with De Luca and the Wine
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, whose father had a small vineyard in California's wine
country, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond introduced legislation last week to overturn a ruling
by the Treasury Department that would permit vintners to label
their bottles with a suggestion that consumers consult their own
doctors or the government's nutrition guidelines about possible
beneficial health aspects of wine.
</P>
<P>
   The Wine Institute is a public policy advocacy association
representing 450 wineries and affiliated businesses in California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
