r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-PREPARERS-HNS &LR;      03-02 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-PREPARERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTANTS FIND TAX LAW GOOD FOR BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Daunted by deductions and confused about credits,
taxpayers are expected to seek help for filing their income tax
returns in higher numbers this year.
</P>
<P>
   How many more won't be determined until after the April 15
filing deadline has passed and returns are tallied, tax preparers
said. But early indications are that more people will seek help,
ironically enough, because of the Taxpayer Relief Act of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the changes from the law went into effect last year, and
so are just showing up during the current filing season. Individual
taxpayers are complaining to accountants that the relief measures
simply make the returns more difficult to complete, at least in
this first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax simplification ... wasn't,'' said Beth Kissinger, a
certified public accountant in Schenectady, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Individual taxpayers are trying to read the instructions to
understand the new tax treatments of child care credits, education
credits, individual retirement accounts and other financial events,
she said. But they often find instructions baffling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're throwing up their hands and looking for a
professional,'' Kissinger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen an increase in people,'' agreed Katie Doran, a CPA
and partner at Teal, Becker &AMP; Chiaramonte in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the new tax provisions _ such as the child care
credit and educational credits _ disappear at certain income
levels, Doran said. That further confuses people.
</P>
<P>
   Even some ``borderline people'' who have fairly uncomplicated
returns ``this year don't feel comfortable,'' said Greg Lurie, who
runs his own CPA firm in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the newcomers will get a professional to do their
returns this year and then return to doing their taxes by
themselves by following the new format _ until the tax law changes
again, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other new clients will become longtime customers once they get
used to the convenience of having a preparer do the work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of people who will want individual help will start
coming in this month, Doran and others said.
</P>
<P>
   Tax preparers generally cope with the uptick in business by
working 12- or 14-hour days, and sometimes by working weekends.
Some larger firms, such as the 50-person office in which Doran
works, also hire skilled seasonal help to work just during tax
season, often people who return year after year.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers seeking help can find a variety of different kinds of
people willing to file returns.
</P>
<P>
   Chain tax preparation outfits, such as H&AMP;R Block, often train
staff internally. Chains often gear themselves toward individuals
with simpler returns and regularly hold weekend and evening hours.
</P>
<P>
   The average tax preparation cost from H&AMP;R Block last year was
$78.50, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   An established CPA firm may charge $250 or more, Lurie said. A
certified public accountant must hold a four-year degree and
complete additional training beyond that, Doran noted.
</P>
<P>
   Fees for tax preparation services are deductible but subject to
limits. A taxpayer must itemize deductions to get this break.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
