<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY: COOKIES AND COMPUTERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People love cookies and milk. People hate cookies and computers.
Harmless though they might be, most Internet users have a knee-jerk
reaction to anyone or anything trying to gather information about
them. The notion that merely typing in a Web address opens up the
opportunity for companies to find out anything at all about them is
distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   (INCLUDES A 3-COLUMN COLOR ILLUSTRATION OF CARTOON COMPUTER
USERS INTERFACING WITH A GIANT COOKIE)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH ISSUES: The Internet carries ads for a burgeoning and
largely uncontrolled industry of ``information brokers'' who, for a
fee, will reveal the most intimate details of someone's life, right
down to that birthmark on their backside or ancient records of
psychological treatment.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: Those who think the generation gap is marked
in distance with PCs _ with the young on one side of the chasm and
older folks on the other _ should take a look at a book from Intel
that hopes to bridge that gap. (INCLUDES PHOTO OF BOOK JACKET)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: The Year 2000 problem is a subject that has
received enough ink to float a battleship. But there are still
smart people out there who are mixed up about its impact.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL: BANFF, ALBERTA &LR;  &QL;
