<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Adding another bathroom leaves me
flushed
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ I went shopping with my wife yesterday,
shopping for commodes, not something I do every day.
</P>
<P>
   But what it is, we're adding a bathroom, just what we need now
that the children are grown and gone.
</P>
<P>
   You can't have too many bathrooms. At last count, we had but
four and a half, two and half in the main house, one in the garage
apartment and one in the little house where I work, a semi-chicken
coop my wife likes to call the cabana.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows how we made it so long with so little.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, we'll soon have facilities fit for a king. Indeed, the
commodes we looked at are the Royal Flush designer series, his and
hers, situated back to back and separated by a partition, which is
the way she wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   Fine with me, but I'd preferred both of them facing forward,
like seats on a train, which makes more sense, everybody going in
the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   She'll have her own tub, too, one of those ancient, claw-footed
monsters with gold fixtures, something she found at a home show a
couple of years ago and priced accordingly _ ever how many dollar
bills it'd take to fill it to overflowing, best I could figure.
</P>
<P>
   I like showers myself, and I'll have one all to myself in the
new bathroom, a big boy model that measures four-feet square, which
should allow easy access. A smaller one would have been cheaper,
but if there's anything I hate it's having to slather myself with
goose grease getting in and out of a shower.
</P>
<P>
   We'll have dueling sinks as well, side by side, atop huge
pedestals, creamy white and also with gold fixtures. I always knew
something would eventually sink me. Little did I guess that it'd be
sinks.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing the bathroom won't have is the one thing I really
wanted, the fixture that dares not speak its name, a male
engineered type of facility, preferably the floor model style that
stands a good five feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, it could be the antique kind, just like we had
in the boys room of the old Central Ward Elementary School, which
probably hardly would have ever overflowed at all.
</P>
<P>
   For my part I was willing to compromise. I told her we could
have it decorated with gold fixtures if that what she wanted, the
splash guards, too. She wouldn't even discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well, maybe in the next bathroom we add.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
