<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4639 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBIETALKS-AZR &LR;      03-02 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBIE ENDS SILENCE, BENDS OUR EAR ON GUYS, KNEES THAT BEND 
</HEADLINE>
 TALKS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CRAVEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - She sits rigidly on a chair in her Malibu home. Her
eyes are fixed forward in an unblinking stare.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is because she's in deep thought. Or focusing on her
future.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it is because she is plastic and has no eyelids.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie will be 40 years old in a week, and while she's been
everything from an astronaut to a rock star and has fit into tiny
bikinis and designer gowns, she has yet to blink.
</P>
<P>
   Never has. Never will. But certainly would like to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it too much to ask to be able to rest my eyes, even for a
few seconds or two?'' asks Barbie, sitting down for a rare
interview while her Supervising Companion (she hates the term
``owner'') is at preschool.
</P>
<P>
   She cannot believe it's been 40 years since she debuted as a
teenage fashion model. Most people might be upset missing their
childhood (``I was born a 16-year-old, so I was a teen with no life
experience''). Not Barbie. The advantages of being a
mass-merchandised doll more than make up for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My skin is still smooth, I never have to shave, and I look as
young as I did four decades ago,'' Barbie says. ``Every woman I
know would kill to be me.''
</P>
<P>
   With Barbie in such a good, though slightly catty, mood, we
indulged in a question-and-answer session about life at 40:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any midlife fears?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I'm so scared to gain a gram because my clothes wouldn't
fit, and I'd have to buy a whole new wardrobe. But for some reason,
I start thinking maybe that wouldn't be such a bad thing. That, in
fact, it would be a very, very good thing. It's just a feeling I
get. I can't really explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What still annoys you after all these years?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Have you ever woken up from a deep sleep and your head is
twisted around, and you're looking behind you? It's not painful.
Just a little disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   A: What's your biggest achievement?
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Oh, in 40 years, I've done so many things it's almost
impossible to say. Like that time I was an astronaut, though I
don't recall ever going into space. Or training for a mission.
Still, it was a great outfit. But my greatest advance, really, came
in 1967, when I was given knees. I can't tell you how having
bendable legs really changes your world. Until then, I had this
awkward, stiff-legged walk. It was so military or something. And
Ken gave me real strange looks, as if he should talk. He didn't get
knees until much later. At least I think so. I wasn't really paying
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Speaking of Ken, how have you and he managed to remain an
item for so long?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``It's called `packaging.' It is what the great and wise
Mattel has chosen for me. Who am I to argue? Sure, there have been
a few action figures over the years who have caught my eye, but
most are from a totally different world. Hasbro. It would never
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you at all different now from 1959?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``People think I haven't changed much in 40 years, but they
are so wrong. I have way more clothes now, so many I can't fit them
all in my Malibu Beach House (which, by the way, doesn't overlook a
beach but the rear end of a Baby Wet `N' Go. I can't really explain
it). And I've come to value my friends, at least the ones who
remain in demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you could change one thing about your life, what would it
be?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I don't want to be mean, but I must be blunt here since
this is the first time I've been able to speak my mind in 40 years.
At least if I had a mind. Anyway, I'd rid the world of every little
brother that's ever been. Do you think I like being handled by
sticky fingers that can totally wreck a good hair day? Do you think
I enjoy having my head ripped off and thrown under the bed? Do you
think it's fun watching the kid give your precious designer gown to
the dog? I'll tell you, if I bought myself, the first accessory
would be a Malibu Armored Safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've done more than most dolls twice your age, but are
there any regrets?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Well, there was that Disco Glitter period in the '70s which
still makes my Fashion Sense tingle. I can't even think about
polyester without retching, at least if I were capable of any
biological functions, like that disgustingly awful Baby Burp 'N'
Spit, as if base gastrointestinal achievements were something to be
proud of. But that's another story. There was also that ill-timed
affair with G.I. Jimmy or John, or whatever his name was. Joe, yes,
that's it. I guess I could still feel badly about that unfortunate
incident with the flamethrower, but if Ken didn't know how it
worked, he never should have picked it up in the first place. Good
thing for plastic surgery, is all I can say.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about people who still say that, despite your career
advances, you are an anachronistic doll whose attitudes and
measurements remain stagnant in a pool of political incorrectness?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``People want me to be politically correct? Hey, I'd settle
for being anatomically correct. But you can't have everything.
Yet.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1515EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
