<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4648 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBIE-ART-AZR &LR;      03-02 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIE-ART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOLLECTIONS OF BARBIE, THE LIFE A KID YEARNED FOR  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS)  
 (ADV: WITH BARBIE TIMELINE AND BARBIE TALKS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURIE NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - ``Do you want it or not?'' my mother asked on the
other end of the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because if you don't want it, I have no problem throwing it
away. The closer our moving day comes, the less sentimental I get.
And if you think I'm bluffing, the dumpster in the alley is lined
with the yellowing satin of my wedding dress. So you see, hauling
your old Barbie Country House to my new home really holds very
little appeal for me.''
</P>
<P>
   She was serious. My parents were moving from our family home,
and everything _ especially my stuff _ was tagged and 15 feet from
the trash.
</P>
<P>
   Although as an adult I'm not a fanatic about the doll I played
with as I was growing up, I hold on to a certain affinity for
Barbie. Barbie did things then that I couldn't in a household of
five, such as watching her favorite television show (``Little House
on the Prairie'') every week, using the bathroom whenever she
wanted, and opening the fridge and finding two leftover pieces of
pizza right where she had left them.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I decided that Barbie (I) needed her (my) very own
pad, and I spotted it at the Happiness House toy store for $10. It
didn't have an elevator, just three rooms and swinging saloon doors
into the kitchen, but I knew it would more than suffice. Emptying
the dishwasher at a dime a pop, I needed almost six months to save
up the $10 to bring the Country House to my bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie and I escaped to this vinyl paradise _ with the images of
furniture, pets and plants pasted to the walls in 2-D _ whenever my
younger sister recorded over my cassette of favorite songs I had
taped from the radio; whenever my mother's passion for ``Monday
Night Football'' overrode the fact that at the very same time, the
Ingalls were watching the School for the Blind burn down; and
whenever my other sister ate the two leftover pieces of pizza with
my name written into the tin foil wrapped around them.
</P>
<P>
   The Country House is where Barbie would run, throw herself on
the bed and have a cow without her mother grounding her or making
her friends go home. It's also the same place where Barbie felt
sexy and wore a tube-top dress made from one of my old socks and a
rubber band. Barbie was a symbol of what I could be, eventually:
independent and living in a house with no rent, no parents and no
apparent income. In this world, when Barbie's mom called on the
phone, sometimes Barbie hung up on her.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie wasn't as much of an influence to me as she was an
escape, although it's not like I had a childhood like Sybil's. My
childhood was fine, and Barbie just gave me my own space. I never
thought, however, that I would become her when I grew up or hit
middle school. How could I be Barbie when I wasn't even Skipper?
</P>
<P>
   Who, in all honesty, really thought they were going to be Barbie
when they grew up? In a completely non-scientific survey involving
several friends of mine in their late 20s and early 30s, none of us
woke up on our 18th birthday and wondered where the 17-inch waist
and the pink Corvette were. I had bendable knees. That was close
enough for me.
</P>
<P>
   I had already figured out in fourth grade that Barbie was a
something of a fraud when I tried to walk around for a whole day on
tiptoe. As I hobbled down the hall with a gripping charley horse in
each calf, my mother shot me a look as she was hauling out the
laundry and said, ``I'm not going to hurt your feelings by telling
you that you look like an idiot. But I will tell you that if you
lose your balance and break any of my crystal, you're really going
to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbie didn't set me up for a self-image fall, although in
hindsight, she could have done things that made me feel better
about myself as a preteen. I wonder who I would be now if Mattel
had introduced Acne Barbie, whose face would suddenly turn all red
and splotchy.
</P>
<P>
   As I got older and began to take on the qualities I had given to
Barbie, I gradually lost interest in her. Barbie was slowly
replaced with lip gloss and diaries. Sometime during the transition
from elementary to middle school, Barbie got stuffed into my
closet, next to the abandoned Holly Hobbie dolls and the Sunshine
Family, whose husband, years before, had had a fling with Barbie
when she appeared one day at his office, unannounced and wearing
the tube-top sock dress.
</P>
<P>
   Although I liked Barbie as a kid, I'm not one of those people
who have cleared out a bedroom and built shelves to accommodate a
collection of her. I won't call that silly, simply because I'm sure
that I collect things that other people consider silly. But as for
the Barbie debunkers, those who counter that Barbie is an
unrealistic image _ I say, well, just relax. Of course she is. The
world is unrealistic. Nothing in the world is the way we want it to
be; it's all an illusion. Things I buy from the Eddie Bauer catalog
don't look on me the way they do on the brunette on Page 45. My
spinach and ricotta rolls don't turn out the way they're delicately
pictured in Marcella Hazan's cookbook. Even a paint technique
doesn't come out the same way as it does on the Ralph Lauren color
chip. If Barbie looked real _ if she looked like me, or if she
looked like you _ no one would buy her. We don't want Barbie to be
us. We want Barbie to be who we're not.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, Barbie sat in the closed-up Country House
with her furniture and cat painted on the walls, collecting dust
and avoiding the leers of the Sunshine Family dad and the shameful
stares from the mother. The next time I remember seeing Barbie was
during the early '80s, when I decapitated both her and Ballerina
Barbie. With a red marker and a razor blade, I transformed the
smiling heads into the images of Annie Lennox and Cyndi Lauper, and
with some minor surgery involving thin wire, they became earrings.
</P>
<P>
   I subsequently lost the Ballerina Barbie/Cyndi Lauper head in a
bar, and the Annie Lennox head became a hanging ornament from the
rearview mirror of my first car. She swung and bobbed there through
three car accidents, two boyfriends and the eventual move out of my
parents' house. I piled clothes, records and my stereo into the
back seat but left the Country House on the top shelf of my closet.
I hadn't seen it for 17 years until the day my mother called.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you now, I will throw that thing away,'' my mother
repeated. ``The Barbie Country House is going . . . going . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take it,'' I conceded, as I imagined my husband doubled
over with laughter when I brought it home. I could tell him I
planned to sell it for hundreds of dollars at the online auction. I
could tell him that I was saving it for his niece.
</P>
<P>
   Or I could ignore his laughter, set it up in my bedroom, and,
whenever I wanted to use the bathroom and he was in it, I could
throw my headless Barbie on her bed and quietly, oh so quietly,
have a cow. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1518EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
