<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4655 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMATION-ART-AZR &LR;      03-02 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMATION-ART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING GAMES COME TO LIFE  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN SIDENER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A medieval king in deep contemplation lifts a bishop
from the chess board.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the animation playing on Paul Denigris' computer at
Rainbow Studios in Phoenix, a single soldier moves across the
terrain outside the castle.
</P>
<P>
   Another chess piece moves. More soldiers reposition themselves
until before you know it, the castle is under siege and catapults
are hurling flaming payloads over stone walls.
</P>
<P>
   An epic battle, complete with legions of foot soldiers and
cavalry, culminates in a close-up of the ruler's face as the life
passes out of him and the king piece tumbles from his limp hand.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone who follows the march of 3D computer animation toward
the grail of photo-realism, the video clip is clearly a significant
stride. The herky-jerky motions that too often characterize human
movement in computer animation are gone. Instead, the legs that run
and arms that swing swords are fluid and lifelike. The close-up on
the dying leader's face shows meaningful expression.
</P>
<P>
   The video clip, which will be the opening segment in the next
version of Microsoft's Age of Empires strategy game is one of
several video-game projects under way at the central Phoenix
animation studio, including a sequel to its Motocross Madness,
published by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Motocross Madness is on its way to selling a million copies and
has been named racing game of the year by two computer gaming
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite an honor,'' said Earl Jarred, CEO of Rainbow
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   The game also was singled out for praise by Bill Gates at Comdex
last year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to games, the studio is producing a full-length
animated movie and animation for educational videos and prototype
television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   In the ever-quickening pace of computer animation, there is no
time to rest on your 3D laurels. Today's cutting-edge becomes next
month's industry standard. Jarred is barely finished beaming over
the Age of Empires video when he heads off to flaunt a gaming
project that he promises is even more impressive.
</P>
<P>
   In Age of Empires, Rainbow Studios is doing the opening
animation, but in the new project, working title Max, the studio is
doing the entire game. Jarred and his crew of animators, producers,
artists and engineers have set a concise but weighty goal in Max _
give the interactive part of the game the same level of cinematic
animation as the opening video. When the player steers the
rough-and-tumble protagonist into a brawl or a shootout, the idea
is to have the animation as smooth and seamless as in the intro to
Age of Empires, which was painstakingly assembled frame by frame.
</P>
<P>
   The game is being written for the next generation of game
consoles and PCs. Computer-animated scenes and figures are made up
of thousands of tiny polygons. Max is being designed with the
assumption that game consoles in a couple of years will be able to
render 55 million polygons per second. That's 10 times the speed of
the Sega Dreamcaster, due out in this country this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow Studios has 47 employees, including three with doctoral
degrees, one in robotics, one in engineering and one in pure math.
</P>
<P>
   Jarred credits the company's games group president, Mark
DeSimone, the math Ph.D., with the technical vision behind the
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``My partner is the resident technical guru who makes it all
happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of Rainbow Studios facilities on Seventh Street is an
800-square-foot motion capture booth. The room is used to record a
person's motions and translates them into 3D figures. A model dons
a data suit containing up to 32 sensors. A clear globe hanging from
the ceiling creates magnetic fields. When the model moves his or
her arm, the computer records those movements along three planes,
up and down, east and west and north and south.
</P>
<P>
   The computer then translates those movements to a 3D model of
the same proportions. The glorified stick figure then mimics the
recorded movements. A demonstration of this technology can be seen
at www.rainbo.com, the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Using 3D animation programs, the figure can be given the shapes
and textures of a monster, a hero or a villain. A sample of this
process also can be seen at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The motion capture not only grabs an accurate picture of
movements; it also greatly speeds the animation process. If the
equipment is set to grab images at 30 frames per second, then a
10-second motion contains the foundation for 300 frames. Those
frames would have to be created manually otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   A wooden contraption sitting on the motion-capture stage
resembles a souped-up saw horse. At first glance, it appears to be
a horse from the Age of Empires video. It turns out to be the
motorcycle for Motocross Madness. Riders were recorded leaning
forward, back and to the side, mounting, dismounting and tumbling.
Artists and animators then added helmets and racing suits, and put
the riders in the game.
</P>
<P>
   A wooden substitute was used because the metal of the motorcycle
would have distorted the magnetic fields of the motion-capture
process.
</P>
<P>
   The company's engineers have developed a facial-motion camera
that records the movement of small facial muscles and are working
on a data glove that will record the movements of fingers and other
parts of the hand. Currently, face and hand movements must be
created frame by frame.
</P>
<P>
   Animation is a time-consuming affair. Six studio employees spent
six months on the Age of Empires video segment. Motocross Madness
took 15 studio employees two years to complete, and that doesn't
count the Microsoft employees who worked on the project.
</P>
<P>
   The sequel to Motocross Madness is expected to be out in about a
year. One of the big changes for the next version is the addition
of trees. A sneak preview of the work-in-progress shows the once
barren landscape studded with trees for riders to dodge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking of adding a duck function,'' says designer Rob
Rinard. ``If you come to a low-hanging branch, you can duck under
it. If not, you'll get clotheslined.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jonathan Sidener can be reached at jon.sidener(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
