A4658 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-CARJACKING-HNS &LR;      03-02 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-CARJACKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT UPHOLDS FEDERAL CARJACKING LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Upholding the federal carjacking law, the Supreme
Court ruled Tuesday that criminals who use weapons to steal
vehicles are violating that law even if they do not mean to hurt
anyone inside the autos.
</P>
<P>
   In a 7-2 decision, the high court rejected the argument of a New
York man who said he was innocent of carjacking because he would
have used his gun only if any of the victims had given him a ``hard
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law states that to be guilty of carjacking a person must
steal a vehicle by ``force and violence'' with the ``intent to
cause death or serious bodily harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Francois Holloway argued that he had no intention of causing
bodily harm to the drivers and passengers so long as ``everything
went smoothly,'' and, therefore, he was not guilty of carjacking
under the federal statute.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court majority, Justice John Paul Stevens said
Congress, which passed the law in 1992 after a spate of vicious car
thefts, meant to make carjacking illegal even when only the threat
of violence was used to steal the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that when a person points a gun at someone else while
stealing their car ... that entails a serious threat of violence
and that the driver has no idea if the criminal is serious or
not,'' Stevens said as he announced the decision.
</P>
<P>
   He said that to accept Holloway's argument would mean that the
carjacking law could apply only to those cases in which the
carjacker's ``sole and unconditional purpose at the time he
committed the crime was to kill or maim the victim.'' He said that
ruling would be ``clearly at odds'' with what Congress intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in the unusual carjacking does the criminal intend to
harm even if the driver or passenger doesn't resist,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day
O'Connor, Anthony Kennedy, David Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and
Stephen G. Breyer joined in the opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The court's most conservative justices, Clarence Thomas and
Antonin Scalia, disagreed with the majority.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusually personal opinion, Scalia said a carjacker had
killed the father and nearly killed the mother of a friend in an
incident after the car had already been handed over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not at all implausible that Congress should direct its
attention to this particularly savage sort of carjacking where
killing the driver is part of the intended crime,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia said that a simple reading of the Black's Law Dictionary,
which defines the word intent as ``a state of mind in which a
person seeks to accomplish a given result through a course of
action,'' shows that the carjacking law cannot apply to Holloway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holloway intended to steal the car; he did not intend to harm
anybody,'' Scalia wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He added that if Congress had meant to ``cast its carjacking net
so broadly, it could have achieved that result by defining the
crime as `carjacking under threat of death or serious bodily harm,'
rather than intent.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Holloway was sentenced to more than 50 years in prison
for his part in a carjacking ring that sold parts of stolen
vehicles dismantled in a Queens ``chop shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that on at least three occasions in the fall of
1994, Holloway confronted motorists with a gun and demanded that
they surrender their car keys.
</P>
<P>
   When one man hesitated, Holloway punched him in the face.
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge who presided over Holloway's trial told jurors
they could find the required intent if they thought Holloway would
have seriously hurt victims who did not comply with his demands.
</P>
<P>
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld Holloway's
conviction, ruling that such a common-sense interpretation was
valid despite what it called the law's somewhat ambiguous language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
