<HEADER>
A4688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIAMS-READ03-COX     03-02 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-READ03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEISMAN WINNER TACKLES READING PROGRAM
 &HT;    with photos
 &HT;    moving in (w) Washington and (s) Sports categories
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's not often Ricky Williams gets tackled
single-handedly.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, the Heisman trophy winner found himself on his
backafter a scuffle with the Cat in the Hat.
</P>
<P>
   A laughing Williams recovered in time to delight about 20
children with a rendition of ``Green Eggs and Ham,'' to promote a
National Education Association reading program.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me what my hobbies are and I say being around kids.
So for me, this is a lot of fun,'' said Williams, who hopes some
day to teach second grade.
</P>
<P>
   The event was one of thousands held Tuesday as part of the
second annual Read Across America. On what would have been Dr.
Seuss' 94th birthday, Williams honored the legendary author by
topping his trademark dreadlocks with red and white Cat in the
Hat-style head gear.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and NEA President Bob Chase took turns reading the part
of Sam. Eventually, the children joined in and finished each
sentence in unison.
</P>
<P>
   Eight-year-old Corrisma Walker said the book ``had good rhymes''
and taught her about taking chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone made green eggs and ham, I would try them,'' she
said, with a nod of determination.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he was inspired and challenged as a child by his
younger sister, Rebecca, who was at his same reading level despite
being a year and a half younger.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite childhood book was ``Where the Wild Things Are,''
by Maurice Sendak.
</P>
<P>
   Although several of the children had never heard of the
University of Texas football star until Tuesday, they turned into
fans in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a fast reader,'' said 7-year-old Robert Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
