<HEADER>
A4703 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIVORCE-MEDIATION-TEX     03-02 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVORCE-MEDIATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIATION EASES PAIN OF DIVORCE FOR INCREASING NUMBERS OF TEXAS
COUPLES
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanied by MEDIATION-GUIDELINES and MEDIATION-QUOTE) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Who gets the kids and the house?
</P>
<P>
   What about the pots and pans, retirement plans and stock
options?
</P>
<P>
   A young woman without children once complained that after 10
years of marriage, the biggest dispute in her divorce was over how
to divide up all the baseball cards she and her husband had
collected over the years.
</P>
<P>
   And for that they needed one tough umpire _ or, in this case,
mediator.
</P>
<P>
   Mediation, also known as ``alternative dispute resolution'' or
``assisted negotiation,'' involves communication and compromise
among warring parties, and it's gradually changing the
rough-and-tumble nature of traditional Texas-style divorce. It
makes for a kinder, gentler, more civilized and speedier divorce
than slugging it out in front of a judge and jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mediation is the single most significant change in family law
in the last 25 years,'' says Ike Vanden Eykel, a high-profile
Dallas divorce lawyer and author of ``Successful Lone Star Divorce:
How to Cope with a Family Breakup in Texas'' (PRO Solutions,
$16.95).
</P>
<P>
   Texas has the most progressive and intense use of mediation in
the country, with most family court judges ordering mandatory
mediation in all divorce cases in which there are any areas of
disagreement, Vanden Eykel says.
</P>
<P>
   These days you almost have to get mediation to get a divorce in
the Fort Worth-Dallas area, says Larry Upshaw, editor of Vanden
Eykel's book.
</P>
<P>
   ``This four-county area is a hotbed of mediation,'' the Dallas
attorney agrees. ``We've been doing it longer, and we have judges
who aggressively advocate it because it works, but it's gaining in
favor all over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, there were 9,808 divorces and 10,123 other family law
matters filed in the five family law courts in Tarrant County (Fort
Worth). Of the 9,808 new divorces filed, 7,300 of them were decided
by default or agreed judgments.
</P>
<P>
   Although no record is available on how many of the cases
involved mediators working quietly behind the scene, most agreed
judgments do involve mediation.
</P>
<P>
   The swing away from long and costly trials has been prompted by
overcrowded court dockets and the realization that making divorce a
long, drawn-out, adversarial process is not in the best interest of
children.
</P>
<P>
   Slugging it out over child custody and visitation, closely held
businesses, jewelry, toasters and baseball cards can get very
expensive in terms of time, lawyers' fees and mental health.
</P>
<P>
   A big advantage of mediation is that consumers have a direct
hand in the resolution of their cases, says Tarrant County District
Judge Frank Sullivan, who almost always requires mediation in
contended divorce cases and says that every family court in the
county has cases set up for the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for everybody,'' Sullivan says. ``It saves time, and
people come out of mediation feeling like they had some control
over the settlement of their cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Mediators most often are appointed by the court, usually with
agreement by the lawyers for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Those mediators come in several varieties. Professional private
mediators, many of whom are lawyers, eliminate the need for a jury
trial about 90 percent of the time. The cost varies from a flat
$250 per party to $250 per hour, with the average case totaling
$500 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   With volunteer mediators, many of them retired attorneys or
nonlawyers trained by Dispute Resolution Services of Tarrant
County, the settlement rate is 65 percent to 70 percent _ still
very high considering that the cases would not have gotten to
mediation if there were not some major bone of contention on which
the parties disagreed. These mediators charge a flat $25 fee if the
case is filed in Tarrant County or involves county residents, and
$125 per party for noncounty residents. The fee is waived for
residents who cannot pay. Primary funding comes from $10 taken out
of every county lawsuit filing fee.
</P>
<P>
   Dispute Resolution Services was set up 15 years ago under a
contract with the county. The social-service agency provides
mediation services in about 110 civil cases each month _ about 60
percent of which are divorces and child custody cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We save people time, money and relationships,'' says Marcia
Kazarian, program development coordinator for the private,
nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   Although most people don't know about mediation options until
after a divorce decree has been filed, Kazarian says, a savvy few
seek out Dispute Resolution Services first. When they reach
agreement on the terms of the divorce, they take it to an attorney
who drafts the decree and files it at great cost savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make decisions about what's fair,'' Kazarian
explains. ``We encourage the parties to consider all their options
and consider the cost of different choices, but we make no specific
recommendations.''
</P>
<P>
   Total confidentiality and neutrality are the cornerstones of the
mediation process, Sullivan says. ``When mediation fails, people
still have the courts available. When a case comes back to us, we
don't even want to know why. For this to work, the parties involved
need to be sure that nothing they say or do in mediation will be
held against them in court.''
</P>
<P>
   James Handy, a board-certified family lawyer who also does
mediation, says the process takes a lot of the adversarial aspects
out of family law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I explain the law to people and help them understand why their
position may not be a very strong position with the court, and I
offer ideas that both sides involved can live with and the court is
likely to approve.''
</P>
<P>
   Handy says mediation, in which clients can speak their minds
without regard to court rules of protocol, is almost like therapy
for his clients. ``People can vent their feelings and
frustrations,'' he explains. ``We are attorneys and counselors at
law, and the counseling aspect becomes very important. You don't
have the adversarial role that you do when you are the attorney
representing one side.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
