<P>
   SENATE-Y2K (Washington) _ A majority of doctors and hospitals
are not prepared for the year 2000 computer glitch, putting
diagnostic equipment and drug distribution in jeopardy, according
to a Senate committee investigating the nation's preparedness for
the so-called Y2K problem. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL (Washington) _ Deputy Attorney General Eric
Holder says the White House is withdrawing its support for the
independent counsel law, saying the Watergate-inspired statute
``was supposed to increase trust in our government'' but ``has
diminished it.'' By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-CARTELS (Washington) _ Sens. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
and Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., say there's no chance Congress will
reverse President Clinton's certification of Mexico as an ally in
the war on drugs. But they propose a ban on business dealings with
foreign companies that serve as fronts for drug-cartel smuggling.
By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-CARJACKING (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that
when criminals use weapons to steal vehicles, they are guilty of
carjacking even if they don't intend to harm anyone in the cars. By
MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-2000 (Washington) _ The General Accounting Office reports
that Texas and California have taken the biggest hits because of
undercounts by the U.S. Census Bureau. By JENNIFER DAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ANALYSIS (Washington) _ The Bush and Dole names are nothing
new to Republican presidential primaries. We look at the cool
relationship between these two establishment families and how the
party would fare with the son, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, and the
wife, Elizabeth Dole, on the 2000 campaign trail. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Austin, Texas) _ Facing mounting national pressure
from Republicans to run seek the presidency next year, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush announces he is forming a campaign committee that
will raise money and pave the way for a campaign. But Bush, 52,
continues to say he will make no decision about a campaign until
later this year. By LAURA TOLLEY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-LEGLISLATURE (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush stops
being coy and puts his presidential campaign in gear. Some people
are wondering if he can do the same with his legislative program.
Seven weeks into the legislative session, only one of Bush's
priorities _ a tax break for small oil and gas producers _ is
anywhere close to becoming law, and it may still spark a fight. By
CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN-MAFIA (San Antonio) _ As a so-called general of the
Texas Mexican Mafia, Robert Perez was by most accounts a powerful
man. But for all his influence, painstakingly illustrated in a
six-week racketeering and murder trial in San Antonio federal
court, Perez was in many ways just another guy from San Antonio's
poor, mostly Mexican-American West Side. By THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   PAROLE-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Amid high-level opposition from
parole officials, legislative committees debate the clemency
process. Under harsh questioning from minority lawmakers, officials
concede some tinkering is needed, but their immediate concern is
getting $2 million for a computer network to ease the board's
100,000 case reviews each year. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ The public weighs in on a bill
that would crack down on the practice of promoting failing public
school students. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-SLAYINGS (New Delhi, India) _ The 1997 slaying of four
Texas oil executives in Pakistan was a ploy by a radical
anti-government group to destabilize the country's economy,
according to a senior police official. The police announced earlier
this week that they have arrested two members of a Pakistani
political party with terrorist elements in connection with the
killings. By MARION LLOYD.
</P>
