<HEADER>
A4711 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      03-02 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S ONLY SO MUCH YOU CAN SWALLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some might consider it unladylike, but the Baroness Philippine
de Rothschild does it. I know that May-Elaine de Lencquesaing does
it because I've done it with her. And Serena Sutcliffe partakes all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   What is it they do? Why, they spit. Baroness Rothschild and Mrs.
de Lencquesaing own famous Bordeaux chateaus, Mouton Rothschild and
Pichon-Lalande. Ms. Sutcliffe is senior director of the
international wine department at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Tasting wine is central to these women's lives, and no one can
taste wine professionally without spitting out much of it.
</P>
<P>
   The term wine tasting has come to mean a social event at which
wine is served rather than cocktails. A professional wine tasting
is another matter entirely. It is hard work.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious tasting is done by professional wine buyers,
who prowl through damp, cold cellars of winemakers, sampling raw
young wines and trying to decide which ones will become great in
another 5 or 10 years. Given wine prices, fortunes can ride on a
taster's judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Spitting is essential to the buyers' work, and the wine cellar
floor is a perfectly acceptable target. No, don't call for the
health police: in a good winery, the floor is hosed down several
times a day.
</P>
<P>
   For a few years, I was part of the wine-judging team at the Los
Angeles County Fair. The team met several months before the fair to
work through hundreds of wines submitted by California growers and
winnow down the field.
</P>
<P>
   It was not unusual for the red wine panel to assemble at 7:30
a.m. to taste 100 cabernet sauvignons, rest for 30 minutes, then
move on to 95 zinfandels. After lunch, the panel might judge 35 or
40 merlots. This would go on for three days.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking all these wines probably would have been fatal. We spit
to survive _ into our own individual bucket, of course _ and to be
able to form clear opinions about all the wines, not just the first
half dozen in each group.
</P>
<P>
   In his Complete Guide to Wine Tasting and Wine Cellars, (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, 1984), Michael Broadbent, wine director of Christie's
auction house, wrote: ``It is nothing short of ridiculous to drink
one's way through a tasting. How can the last few wines yield more
than a hazy impression? To taste critically is one thing; to enjoy
wines with a meal is another.''
</P>
<P>
   The temptation to swallow is strong: it is what people do when
they eat or drink. But if all ``tasting'' was done in just the
mouth, anyone swallowing a bit of wine would immediately get all
the sensations it has to offer. In fact, the nerves that can sense
more than sweet, sour, salt and bitter are deep in the brain and
depend much more on aroma.
</P>
<P>
   In his World Atlas of Wine (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1994), Hugh
Johnson wrote: ``The real organ of discrimination is in the upper
nasal cavity and the only sensations that can reach it are the
vapors of volatile substances.'' Which means, simply, that with
complex substances like wine, critical judgments depend more on
smell than taste.
</P>
<P>
   A good friend, a wine professional, could drink no alcohol for a
year because of illness. Nevertheless, he attended tastings but
only smelled the wines. After he recuperated, he said he thought
his judgment of wines had been more accurate during that period
than before.
</P>
<P>
   Serious tasters smell a group of wines several times before
actually tasting them, and only rarely does tasting change their
opinions. And that's the secret to getting through an important
tasting in which the quality of the wines can range from superb to
execrable. Plenty of wines need not be tasted at all: they can be
eliminated by smell alone.
</P>
<P>
   Proust's memory may have been triggered by the taste of a
madeleine, but many would agree that aromas stir memories more
rapidly and vividly than any other sensation. An experienced wine
taster will derive almost as much pleasure from the memories of
other wines as from drinking the wine at hand.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon at lunch in Bordeaux, with a few bottles on the
table, I listened to several veterans of the wine trade reminisce
about memorable bottles from years gone by, and of great wines they
had sadly misjudged.
</P>
<P>
   But wine is, after all, a drink, and where fine wine is
concerned, tasting does add several important dimensions. Texture,
intensity and richness are qualities in a wine best defined by
tasting. Is the wine rough on the palate or velvety? Do the flavors
linger long in the mouth? Only tasting will tell.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that a lot of wine doesn't need to be tasted
seriously. Good, simple wines are just that, and searching for
subtleties they don't possess is a waste of time. Great wines, on
the other hand, are a cerebral pleasure as much as a physical one
and they warrant serious study.
</P>
<P>
   Once, at a tasting of Argentine wines at the consulate in New
York, Argentina's Consul General at the time, Rafael Vasquez,
watched the intense sipping, sniffing and spitting and asked me,
``Do you like tastings?'' I replied, ``Some.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer drinkings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   We all do. But tastings, serious tastings, are important. They
can teach us how and what to drink. As long as we don't swallow too
much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
