<HEADER>
A4731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEAT-MARINATE-ART-2TA     03-02 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-MARINATE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINADES: SO WHAT'S THE BEEF? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(editors: recipe at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ancient Romans lucky enough to have game to eat knew just what
to do with it. First, they hung it up to age and tenderize it. Then
they may have bathed the meat in wine, honey, herbs and spices
intended not only to soften the tough, sinewy meat but also to
flavor it, and perhaps to obscure the funky smell that develops
from old-fashioned aging.
</P>
<P>
   Since the earliest days of recorded history, and maybe even
before, humans have marinated their food, steeping meat, fowl and
fish in some combination of liquid _ usually oil or acid _ and
seasonings. At first, there were practical reasons: tough meat
needed to be made tender, it needed to be preserved, and with
humans ever attuned to improving their lot, it needed to be
flavored. But from ranch to refrigerator, almost everything has
changed about meat and the way it is treated today. Everything,
that is, except marination.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is meat the tough, stringy stuff of even 100 years
ago, but it is the rare home cook who has not tossed chicken or a
piece of beef into a bath of, say, wine and spices for a few hours,
even a few days, to tenderize it while adding some flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Now, most cooking experts scoff at the notion that marinating
makes meat more tender. Yes, they say, an acidic solution will
alter texture, but often not for the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, marinating has little or no effect on tenderness,''
said Jack Bishop, a senior writer for Cook's Illustrated who has
experimented with all sorts of marination techniques. ``Everybody
just assumes marination is going to tenderize meat, so they leave
it in the refrigerator for three days. It really just breaks down
and becomes soft and mushy. Tenderizing comes from the way you cook
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The science seems clear. ``Acid does break down protein, but
after it breaks it down, it causes it to coagulate,'' said Shirley
O. Corriher, whose book, ``Cookwise'' (William Morrow &AMP; Co., 1997),
explores the reasons some recipes work and others do not. ``If you
leave it too long, it toughens or turns to mush.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, bathing meat in acid begins the cooking process.
Just as ceviche is made by steeping raw seafood in lime juice until
the flesh is ``cooked'' by the citric acid, so are meat, poultry
and fish altered by an acidic marinade. By the time the acid
penetrates a piece of meat an inch or more thick to get to the
tough center, it will have had far too much time to work on the
surface, rendering it ``unpleasantly strange,'' said Edward Behr,
who writes The Art of Eating, a quarterly newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   So, if marinades tend to hurt meats rather than help them,
what's the point? Flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of marination is to add a layer of flavor, and
it's literally just the external layer,'' said Harvey Steiman, who
writes about cooking for Wine Spectator magazine. While some may be
tempted to poke holes in the meat to extend the flavoring beyond
the surface, that technique has more drawbacks than benefits. It
may improve the distribution of flavor, but more fluid will be lost
during cooking, resulting in drier meat, said Harold McGee, who
tested the technique in his book ``On Food and Cooking: The Science
and Lore of the Kitchen'' (Charles Scribner's Sons, 1984).
</P>
<P>
   Still, that extra layer of flavor can be important, and it can
be obtained easily without damaging the texture of the meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rub a butterflied leg of lamb with olive oil, garlic and
rosemary because there's nothing there that's breaking down the
meat,'' Bishop said. ``Even better is a spice rub, which at its
most basic is a 30-second operation and you don't even have to
think about the texture. But if you see a recipe that has a
half-cup of lemon juice in it, that's a red flag and you better be
careful.''
</P>
<P>
   With such a consensus about acidic marinades, why are acids
still frequently included in recipes? Behr believes this is a
holdover from earlier days. ``A lot of these recipes for using wine
and vinegar come from France, and it's a whole function of not
having refrigeration, '' he said. Technology changed, but not the
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   If you still want to add that acidic flavor before cooking,
Bishop recommends no more than a quick dip _ 20 minutes maximum for
fish, maybe half an hour for beef or lamb.
</P>
<P>
   While lemon juice and wine may be out as marinating agents, one
acidic ingredient still has its fans: yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Punjabi food, when you prepare chicken for the tandoor,
there's no question that yogurt breaks down fiber and tenderizes
the meat,'' said David Rosengarten, the Food Network personality
whose latest cookbook, ``Taste,'' was published by Random House
last year. ``Two days for a marinade is OK. Afterwards, it gets
unattractively mushy. I played around once using yogurt marinades
for tough cuts of lamb, and it was a great thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Science seems to support the yogurt partisans. Not only is the
acid in yogurt far milder than the acids in wine, lemon juice or
vinegar, but it also contains calcium, which McGhee says activates
enzymes in meat that break down the muscle fiber. ``It's
conceivable that the calcium in yogurt may result in the same sort
of tenderizing that you get when you age meat,'' he said. That's a
good thing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Short of marinating everything with yogurt, the never-ending
search for other methods of tenderizing tough cuts of meat has led
some cooks to brining, a method akin to pickling. Soaking meat in
mildly salty water, perhaps flavored with herbs, onions and garlic,
actually moistens the interior, making it more tender, without the
drawbacks of acidic marinades.
</P>
<P>
   ``By brining the meat for a few hours, you can actually
penetrate the meat without denaturing it,'' Steiman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Corriher concurs that brining keeps meat moist and
concentrates its natural flavor.
</P>
<P>
   If the mantra for marinating today is ``flavor, not texture,''
even that irks some cooks. Behr of The Art of Eating sees an
overbearing tendency in the development of modern marinades that
incorporate many different ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to use ginger and garlic and lemongrass and
mangoes, all these strong exotic flavors,'' he said. ``It treats
everything as if it's a chutney _ distinct from what it goes with.
It's too often a counterpoint. It's this age of chaos, in fashion,
in architecture, in the information overload. People are not
thinking about harmonies. They think about slamming stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   One area where even a harmonizing marinade is not necessary is
with an ingredient that is already great and distinctive, like an
excellent cut of meat, which needs no marinade to add flavor. ``I
would never marinate a prime porterhouse steak, never ever in a
million years,'' Rosengarten said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN CHICKEN THIGHS WITH SAFFRON SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from David Rosengarten &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes plus 24 hours for marinating
</P>
<P>
   For the chicken:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   3 medium garlic cloves, peeled
</P>
<P>
   \ cup coarsely chopped fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garam masala
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon Indian chili powder
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon ground fenugreek
</P>
<P>
   8 chicken thighs, boned
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Fresh coriander leaves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   For the sauce:
</P>
<P>
   2 small onions, peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   { green pepper, cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   2 cinnamon sticks
</P>
<P>
   2 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon saffron threads
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons flour.
</P>
<P>
   1. To prepare the chicken, place the yogurt, garlic, ginger and
all the spices in bowl of a food processor. Process for about 1
minute, or until the mixture is smooth. Place the chicken thighs in
a bowl and coat them well with the yogurt marinade. Cover and
refrigerate for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. When ready to cook, remove the chicken from the marinade, and
pat completely dry with paper towels. Season with salt and pepper.
Preheat the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   3. To prepare the sauce, place the onions, green pepper,
cinnamon sticks and cloves in a heavy saucepan. Add the chicken
stock and saffron, bring to a boil, and cook rapidly for about 30
minutes, or until the mixture is reduced by about two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   4. While the stock is boiling, place the chicken in a broiler
pan. Broil for 7 minutes, turn thighs over, and broil for another 7
minutes. The thighs are done just when they have lost the rosy
tinge at the center. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   5. Continue with the sauce: melt the butter in a saucepan, and
add the flour. Stir for 2 minutes over medium heat. Strain the
reduced chicken stock into the flour-butter mixture, discarding the
solids. Whisk rapidly to blend. Simmer for about 1 minute or until
sauce coats a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   6. Place 2 chicken thighs on each of 4 dinner plates. Pour the
sauce around the chicken, and garnish with a few fresh coriander
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
