<HEADER>
A4740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAPIOCA-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      03-02 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAPIOCA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSFORMING TAPIOCA FROM PUDDING TO PEARL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The appetizer was a vision in shades of pink and green. Chunks
of coral-tinged Alaskan king crab and matchstick cremini mushrooms
topped a frothy sea of moss-colored bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   The flavors of the buttery, slightly briny crab and the earthy,
sweet mushrooms were delicious and familiar. But as for the satiny
bubbles, if it did not say so on the menu, would anyone have
guessed they were tapioca?
</P>
<P>
   While to many Americans tapioca is merely a sweet custard that
brings back comforting memories of childhood, around the world it
has been used for centuries with much more versatility, in savory
as well as sweet dishes. Chefs in New York are catching on to
tapioca's special qualities.
</P>
<P>
   John Schenk, the chef at Clementine, created the king crab
appetizer, mixing tapioca with shiso, a tart Japanese herb. The
shiso provides a little bite, and the tapioca a velvety softness
that is a textural contrast to the crab.
</P>
<P>
   At Tabla, Floyd Cardoz uses tapioca in a savory way twice on the
current winter menu. He mixes it into a pan-fried potato cake that
is served as an appetizer, and pairs tapioca with braised oxtail,
garnishing the entree with fried leeks and beets.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really like about the tapioca is that on the tongue, it
feels like the fat of the oxtail,'' Cardoz said. ``And that's what
I'm trying to mimic _ that fatty, gelatinous texture.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Conant of Chianti is aware that not everyone was a tapioca
fan once upon a time, so he does not list it on the menu as an
ingredient in his cacciucco, an Italian seafood stew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that people are ready for it,'' he said, ``and I
worry that some people may be turned off from trying the dish.''
</P>
<P>
   Conant got the idea for his stew from a cooking teacher who used
tapioca to give beef soup depth and sheen. ``When I used to make
cacciucco, the lobster reduction would splash up onto the plate,
which ruined the presentation,'' he said. Tapioca, like flour or
cornstarch, adds body to the broth without making it cloudy.
</P>
<P>
   Because tapioca has no flavor of its own, it can be an ideal
thickener. Another benefit of its inherent tastelessness is that it
fully and deeply absorbs the essence of whatever liquid it's cooked
in.
</P>
<P>
   At Cafe Centro, Julian Alonzo makes a potent ``risotto'' using
tapioca pearls, chicken broth, mustard oil and a touch of coconut
milk. Unlike rice, tapioca has a buoyant mouthfeel that makes it
all too easy to eat, especially when it is not weighed down by
cream and eggs, as it usually is in pudding.
</P>
<P>
   Although standard pudding recipes call for granulated, or
minute, tapioca, purists favor the larger pearl tapioca, which
looks like albino salmon roe. Pearl tapioca, sold at Asian markets
and specialty stores, requires a longer cooking time than the
granulated sort, but rewards the cook with abundant voluptuous
texture.
</P>
<P>
   Derived from the dried root of the yuca, or cassava, pearl
tapioca is a common ingredient in tropical Asia and South America,
where it is used in dishes both savory and sweet. In Asia, tapioca
is added to desserts and sweet beverages.
</P>
<P>
   In Thailand, it is also cooked into spicy broths, which are then
pureed to serve as sauces. In Brazil, besides being mixed into
sweetened condensed milk for a sugary snack, the translucent orbs
are traditionally cooked into a rich soup flavored with beef broth
and beaten eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Tapioca probably made its way to Europe in the 17th century
along with other bounty from the Americas, but it wasn't
universally admired. The English liked it well enough, but it
wasn't adopted by any other cuisines, except, moving much further
east, by Armenia, which may have gotten it via Asia.
</P>
<P>
   There, says Geoffrey Zakarian, chef at Patroon, his forebears
combined it with barley and yogurt in a fortifying soup. At
Patroon, he uses tapioca in a vinaigrette drizzled over seared
scallops and pureed sweet peas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It lends textural diversity to the dish, and is nice and easy
in the mouth,'' he said. His customers, he added, ``like to try new
things _ not that tapioca is new, but when I want to find a new
idea, I go back and look for something so old that it seems new.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, there just aren't any new ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is lucky for those of us who want more of the old ones,
especially tapioca. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WARM ALASKAN KING CRAB WITH SHISO TAPIOCA AND RAW CREMINI
MUSHROOM SALAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from John Schenk, Clementine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup large pearl tapioca
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   4 bunches shiso leaves, available at Japanese markets
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch chives
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons rice-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   8 large cremini mushrooms, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cooked Alaskan king crab meat, cleaned. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring a large pot of water to a boil. Add the tapioca, lower
the heat, and simmer until tapioca is tender, about 1 hour. After
45 minutes, add a large pinch of salt. Drain tapioca, and rinse
well under cold water.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place 3 bunches of the shiso leaves, chives, peanut oil and
rice-wine vinegar in a blender, and blend until smooth. Season with
salt to taste. In a medium bowl, combine half the shiso-chive puree
with the tapioca, and toss well. Reserve remaining puree for
garnish.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a medium bowl, combine mushrooms, olive oil and lemon
juice, and toss well.
</P>
<P>
   4. Melt butter in a small saucepan, and add the crab. Saute
until crab is heated through, about 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   5. Chop remaining shiso, and stir into tapioca mixture. To
serve, divide tapioca among 4 plates, and top with mushrooms and
then with warm crab. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED GARLIC AND TAPIOCA FLAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Kevin Reilly, Zoe restaurant &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   4 large cloves garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup small pearl tapioca
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Pinch nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Pinch white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cayenne pepper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 300 degrees. In a small saucepan, combine
milk, 1 cup water and garlic, and bring to a simmer. Cook for 2
minutes, then drain garlic and pat dry.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place garlic in a baking pan, and drizzle with the oil. Roast
until garlic is soft and golden brown, about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, prepare tapioca. Bring a large saucepan of water
to a boil. Add tapioca, and simmer until tender, about 15 to 20
minutes. Drain and rinse well under cold running water.
</P>
<P>
   4. When garlic is roasted, transfer it to a large bowl and mash
it with a fork; leave the oven on. Add cream, eggs, egg whites,
honey, salt, nutmeg, white pepper and cayenne to the bowl, and mix
well. Stir in the cooked tapioca.
</P>
<P>
   5. Ladle custard into eight 4-ounce ramekins. Place a roasting
pan in oven, add ramekins, and fill pan with very hot tap water
until it reaches halfway up the sides of the ramekins. Bake flans
for 1 hour, until centers are set.
</P>
<P>
   6. Remove flans to a wire rack, and let cool for 20 minutes. To
serve, run a knife around the sides of each ramekin, and then
invert them onto serving plates. Serve as an accompaniment to lamb
or beef.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
