 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Wednesday, March 3. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-KIDNAP (Undated) _ At least eight Western tourists
kidnapped by Ugandan rebels, including two Americans, are killed.
By Neil MacFarquhar.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ With the Serbs moving aggressively
after Washington has repeatedly warned them not to, what is
Washington saying or doing?
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-WATER (Ramallah, West Bank) _ For first time, Israelis,
Palestinians and Jordanians cooperate in a study _ done by the U.S.
National Academy of Sciences _ on the vital question of water
resources. By William A. Orme.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON  &LR;  (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COUNSEL-LAW (Washington) _ Deputy Attorney General tells
Congress the independent counsel law should be scrapped. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ESPY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court hears arguments
growing out of the independent counsel case against Mike Espy: What
is it, exactly, that the federal gratuity statute prohibits? If
there's a quid pro quo, it's a bribe, a more serious crime; if it's
a gift for good will, as with the luggage and tennis tickets a
grower's co-op gave to the secretary of agriculture, is it an
illegal gratuity, or is it just business as usual? The high court
also issues some rulings on other cases. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN-POLITICS (Manchester, N.J.) _ Pat Buchannan announces
he's running for president, for the third time. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-POLITICS (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George Bush announces that
he's forming an exploratory committee for a run for the presidency.
By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   FOREST-ACCORD (Sacramento, Calif.) _ In a dramatic,
middle-of-the-night pact, Pacific Lumber Co. and the government
capped years of negotiations by agreeing to a $480 million plan to
set aside an ancient redwood grove for the public. The agreement
turns over to the public some 10,000 acres of forest _ about half
of them old-growth redwoods _ in the coastal hills about 250 miles
north of San Francisco. As a condition of the sale, Pacific Lumber
agreed to a number of stringent environmental rules on the rest of
its 211,000 acres in rugged Humboldt County. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CLINTONS (Washington) _ A look at the president and Mrs.
Clinton's New York connection. By James Dao. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   NY-JAIL-BEATING (New York) _ Following a guilty verdict in a
civil suit against a Nassau County for beating an inmate, the jury
weighs punitive damages. In the meantime, the guard is fired by the
jail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HEWLETT-REORG (Undated) _ Folo reports that Hewlett-Packard is
to announce a major corporate restructuring that could break up the
company into at least two separate publicly traded entities. By
Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The euro keeps falling. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
