</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEET-POTATO-EATING-WELL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET POTATO UNVEILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget most of what you think you know about sweet potatoes.
They aren't yams. They come in more than one variety. And they
definitely don't have to be candied to be good.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potatoes are surprisingly versatile. In fact, unless you
are making a dessert, they're much better when they are combined
with savory herbs and spices, like thyme or cumin, instead of
cinnamon and nutmeg.
</P>
<P>
   They can be used interchangeably with winter squash in soups and
stews. And they are just as delicous served with pork tenderloin or
chicken, lamb or tuna, as they are with turkey and ham.
</P>
<P>
   They are also a nutritional bonanza. Sweet potatoes are loaded
with complex carbohydrates, fiber and important nutrients like beta
carotene, an antioxidant that is believed to help prevent cancer.
Generally speaking, the deeper the orange color, the greater the
amount of beta carotene.
</P>
<P>
   Yams have much less beta carotene, but then they are seldom seen
in this country, despite the labels in supermarket produce aisles
and on cans. Real yams are a South American vegetable. Sweet
potatoes have always been called yams in the South, a name that
comes from an African word, name, but they are not the same.
</P>
<P>
   Five varieties of sweet potato are generally available, and
there's not much difference in taste. Whether they are called
Garnet, Jewel, Beauregard or Hernandez, they are deep orange
inside, no matter the color of the skin. One of the few sweet
potatoes on the East Coast with yellow flesh is the Jersey Sweet or
Hayman, which has whitish skin and is much drier than the others.
But all varieties can be used interchangeably.
</P>
<P>
   Some people say that one variety is sweeter than another, but I
couldn't tell the difference in my taste test. In each variety,
however, there were subtle taste and textural differences from
potato to potato.
</P>
<P>
   To bring out the best in sweet potatoes, do not microwave them.
The result is quick but tasteless. They're best baked, and even
more delicious if cut into strips, tossed with a hint of oil and
roasted at 425 degrees until browned, about 30 minutes. Unlike
white potatoes, they can be pureed in a food processor or blender
without turning gummy.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most valuable piece of information I picked up in a
conversation with the executive director of the Sweet Potato
Council of the United States, Harold Hoecker, is that you are
better off not buying sweet potatoes in June and July, when they
are anywhere from 8 to 11 months past harvesting. The older they
are, the stringier they get and the more wrinkled and shrunken. The
harvest begins in the Deep South in July and works its way north,
where it finishes by Nov. 1. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CREAMY CURRIED SWEET POTATO SOUP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 50 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 and two-thirds cups coarsely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coarsely grated ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon turmeric
</P>
<P>
   [ teaspoon hot pepper flakes, optional
</P>
<P>
   2{ pounds sweet potatoes, peeled and sliced \ inch thick
</P>
<P>
   6 cups no-salt-added chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 teaspoons fresh goat cheese. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oil in a nonstick pot large enough to hold all the
ingredients. Saute onion until it begins to brown, about 10
minutes. Add garlic, and saute, stirring, for 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   2. To make the curry flavoring, add ginger, cumin, coriander,
cardamom, turmeric and optional hot pepper flakes, and stir well.
Add sweet potatoes and stock, and bring to a boil. Reduce heat, and
simmer for about 20 minutes, until sweet potatoes are soft.
</P>
<P>
   3. Puree soup in batches in blender or food processor. Season to
taste with salt and pepper. (Soup can be made ahead of time and
refrigerated. Reheat slowly to serve.) If soup is too thick, add a
little more stock. Ladle into mugs, top each serving with a
teaspoon of cheese, and stir to melt a little.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 cups.
</P>
</TEXT>
