<HEADER>
A4759 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENGLAND-ECLIPSE-$ADV0     03-02 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENGLAND-ECLIPSE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORNWALL AND DEVON BRACE FOR SOLAR-ECLIPSE CROWDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 7)  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ What could eclipse something as historic as a total
solar eclipse in the closing months of a millennium? Answer: good
old everyday greed.
</P>
<P>
   The daytime sun is set to disappear behind the moon in parts of
Devon and Cornwall for up to 2 minutes 6 seconds on the morning of
Aug. 11 _ an event that has not been seen in Britain since 1927.
The next one, indeed, is not predicted to happen until Sept. 23,
2090.
</P>
<P>
   But what is transfixing some people is not so much the fading of
the light as the extraordinary prices that some homeowners in
England's westernmost county believe they can secure for renting
out their homes during what is called ``eclipse week.'' The
one-week rental for some family-sized houses in Cornwall has
quintupled from around $1,600 to around $8,000. A few homeowners
are asking the equivalent of over $16,000, hoping that rich
foreigners or corporations with deep pockets will pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``One or two people are asking astronomical prices,'' said Gage
Williams, the local coordinator of eclipse events, ``but there's
plenty of high-grade accommodation at normal prices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has paid anything like'' the highest prices, Williams
said. ``It's people just flying a kite on the Internet. People
should shop around and they shouldn't have to pay prices that are
out of the ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   In the resort of Newquay, he said, accommodation is roughly 40
percent booked, increasing to 90 percent along the center line of
the eclipse at Penwith, where the eclipse will last longest. (In
Newquay, it will be roughly 1 minute 40 seconds.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This eclipse will be seen by more people than ever before in
human history, and Cornwall will be its first landfall,'' said
Williams. Many of the visitors, he said, will be Americans, who are
among the 100,000 eclipse hunters who chase such phenomena around
the globe.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the event is momentous. Local authorities are
predicting that up to 1.25 million people will visit for the
eclipse. That's over two and one-half times Cornwall's year-round
population of 480,000 and more than four times the normal number of
290,000 August vacationers. Such is the scale of the anticipated
invasion that the military may be called in to preside over what is
expected to be a traffic jam as dense and enduring as the eclipse
is brief.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers are turning their fields into huge temporary campsites
to turn a buck from the crush. As a result, ecologists are warning
that the crowds will trample delicate flora and fauna. The Cornwall
Wildlife Trust says it is concerned that rare species such as the
silver-studded blue butterfly could be wiped out. The regional
water utility is considering a period of rationing to insure
supplies for the suddenly booming population. And local authorities
plan to plant huge boulders across the access routes to many of
Cornwall's hundreds of ancient monolithic and megalithic sites to
prevent damage by pagan and other revelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is particular concern about megalithic tombs, standing
stones and stone circles,'' said Steve Hartgroves, an archaeologist
at the Cornwall County Council. ``We are liaising with the pagan
groups to try to insure that, as far as possible, the right kind of
things will be going on.'' Police say they will be watching for
narcotics dealers and unauthorized mass celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Even surfers will be ordered out of the water when day turns to
night, according to the region's lifeguard service, which said it
had ordered the beaching for safety reasons. But not all living
things will be grounded: Bats could well make an unscheduled
appearance, duped by falling light levels.
</P>
<P>
   There is at least one way out of the crush. The British Pullman,
a luxurious train operated by Venice Simplon-Orient Express, is to
roll into the county on a two-day trip for eclipse watchers. The
eclipse will track across France, Germany, Romania, Turkey and Iran
until sunset in the Bay of Bengal. And while Iran may be trickier
to get to, it does have at least one advantage: Its weather
forecast for August offers 96 percent certainty of a clear viewing.
In Cornwall, meteorologists say, the chances are less than 50-50.
</P>
</TEXT>
