A4778 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYPHILIS03-COX     03-02 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYPHILIS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SYPHILIS TOOK A RIDE ON I-95
 &HT;    Moving in (W) Washington category
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - No one knows why, but an epidemic of syphilis swept
along Interstate 95 in North Carolina during the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   University of North Carolina disease investigators report state
health statistics reveal sharp increases in syphilis rates in 1989
in counties that either have or lie within five miles of I-95
exits.
</P>
<P>
   They speculate the sexually transmitted disease may have
followed an earlier traveler on the same interstate highway:
cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   There apparently have been no comparable studies of I-95
counties in other states, said Robert Cook, principal author of a
report on the North Carolina data in the current issue of the
American Journal of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syphilis was concentrated along I-95 in North Carolina and it
looks like it was linked to the influx of drugs in that area,'' he
said in a telephone interview. ``I feel the study presents
supportive evidence that drugs and sexually transmitted diseases
should not be treated as strictly separate problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Syphilis rates in the United States surged in the mid-1980s,
after years of decline, and some public health experts believe the
emergence of a national cocaine market was at least partly
responsible. Cocaine has been related to increased numbers of
sexual partners and less frequent condom use.
</P>
<P>
   Although truck drivers have been implicated in the spread of
sexually transmitted diseases in other countries, Cook said the
analysis found no evidence the I-95 outbreak was related to
truckers or truck stop prostitutes. The trend did not appear in
counties through which I-85, I-77, I-40 and I-26 pass.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina data showed cities not on the I-95 corridor,
particularly Charlotte and Greensboro, also had syphilis rates
above the state average.
</P>
<P>
   There are no large cities in North Carolina on I-95, although
the largest concentration of the disease appeared to surround the
Fort Bragg military reservation, which is near the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, now an assistant professor of medicine at the University
of Pittsburgh, said earlier studies have shown that after large
quantities of cocaine began appearing in the 1980s in metropolitan
areas, the drug spread out from these cities along interstate
highways.
</P>
<P>
   Two cities at opposite poles of I-95, New York and Miami, were
originally the primary entry points for imported cocaine in the
United States, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
