<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADWATERS-FOREST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST-MINUTE ACTION SAVES REDWOOD FOREST DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The head of a California lumber company
agreed at the last minute to sell a huge tract of redwoods to the
state and federal governments for $480 million.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden decision by financier Charles Hurwitz came late
Monday, just minutes before a midnight deadline and only days after
the boards of directors of the companies Hurwitz controls _ the
Maxxam Corp. and its subsidiary, the Pacific Lumber Co. _ rejected
the entire deal.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Lumber officials contended that environmental
restrictions contained in the deal put too many acres off-limits to
harvesting and would have financially crippled the 130-year-old
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This historic agreement will ensure the protection of one of
the world's most precious resources,'' California Gov. Gray Davis
said. ``I'm delighted that Pacific Lumber accepted this
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The state and federal governments have agreed to buy and
preserve about 10,000 acres of the Headwaters Forest in Northern
California, some of it ancient redwood groves, for $480 million.
The deal represents one of the largest per-acre prices ever paid
for a public park.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Hurwitz agreed Monday to restrictions on where and
when Pacific Lumber can log the rest of its land, about 211,000
acres. The area is home to the coho salmon, northern spotted owl
and a seabird called the marbled murrelet, all of them endangered
species.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton praised the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``These redwoods are a natural treasure, as much a part of our
legacy as the world's great libraries and cathedrals,'' he said.
``I am truly grateful that we are able to bestow this priceless
gift on generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The California Department of Forestry reinstated the company's
logging license last week. It had been suspended last fall after
the company was found to have violated forestry regulations dozens
of times.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Lumber and its corporate parent, Houston-based Maxxam,
had been negotiating for months with Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
D-Calif., and other officials over the plan to make a public
preserve out of private redwood groves in the Headwaters Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the company is bound to accept environmental
restrictions for the next 50 years. Davis, environmentalists and
state lawmakers insisted on the 50-year contract because they
feared Hurwitz would walk away with hundreds of millions of
taxpayer dollars, sell or bankrupt the logging company, and void
environmental safeguards they worked four years to write.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also requires any changes to the environmental
plan to be reviewed by forestry scientists at the University of
California at Berkeley, not just government officials, an attempt
to avoid political influence over the environmental process.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for fines between $1,000 and $3,000 for each
tree cut down in no-cutting zones near streams and in gorges. Under
the restrictions, for example, trees could not be logged within 30
or 100 feet of some streams, depending on their size, to prevent
erosion.
</P>
<P>
   Besides $380 million Pacific Lumber will get for the 10,000-acre
tract, the company agreed to sell two redwood groves for up to $100
million later this year. These so-called ``lesser cathedrals,'' and
10 more covering a total of 7,900 acres, are protected for 50 years
anyway because they are home to the endangered marbled murrelet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
