<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-MICHELIN-NYT &LR;      03-02 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-MICHELIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHELIN GALAXY RECONFIGURES AGAIN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The meeting had a slightly undercover feeling to it. A
tweedy, almost courtly man with a gray buzz cut escorted a visitor
to a small, chilly room in a trailer stationed in a driveway of a
gated compound on the Avenue de Breteuil, just a few blocks from
Napoleon's tomb.
</P>
<P>
   His office was being renovated, he said, but it was hard not to
feel as though he wanted to keep it off limits to prying eyes.
Certainly he was as adamant as any spy master about protecting the
identities of his inspectors, whose reports are published in what
is essentially code. Even the number in his employ was a secret.
</P>
<P>
   He himself looks as if he would melt into a crowd, and certainly
not attract a second glance in a restaurant, but his face and his
name are known to many of the top chefs in France. He is the man
behind the Michelin guides, the most powerful ranking of
restaurants and hotels in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Naegellen has worked for Michelin for more than 30
years, rising through the ranks at the 101-year-old tire company to
become director of the red guides in 1985. Sometimes, when push
comes to shove, he has to be the final arbiter on who gets how many
stars, or ``macaroons,'' as they call the highly prized little
rosettes awarded to top restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   A few get one, two or three, but the majority of restaurants
listed in the guides get none. The number of crossed-fork-and-spoon
symbols gives an indication of the quality of the setting. The
coveted stars are reflections of the food only _ or as Naegellen
put it, ``The stars are on the plate.'' Hotels have their own set
of symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Naegellen says the annual decisions are based on the findings
and opinions of a team of inspectors who are far more anonymous
than their boss.
</P>
<P>
   Their descriptions are reduced to symbols in the guides, with no
commentary, but the inspectors are not robots, Naegellen said.
``They are part of a team, but each keeps his personality,'' he
said. ``For that reason, we keep changing them around.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to evaluating a place, the two questions they must
answer are: Would I return on my own? Would I recommend this place
to friends?
</P>
<P>
   As for granting stars, and especially when a restaurant might be
elevated to two or especially three (or have them stripped away),
he said the procedure is to send one inspector, then a second one a
few months later, with perhaps a follow-up visit if necessary.
``Perhaps we'll even send one of our foreign inspectors as well,''
he said. ``We're not in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   The process is easier when the chefs and restaurateurs are very
familiar to the Michelin crews, he said. That's why three stars
came so quickly to the new Pierre Gagnaire restaurant in Paris last
year, and why Taillevent in Paris kept its three stars even after
the chef retired in 1991. ``Vrinat is a great restaurateur no
matter who the chef may be,'' Naegellen said, referring to
Jean-Claude Vrinat, the owner.
</P>
<P>
   The French inspectors are all men, although there have been
women in the past, and some women are currently inspectors in other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extremely demanding job,'' Naegellen said. ``They have
to cover a lot of territory, they're on the road most of the time
sleeping in different hotel rooms and eating in restaurants. It's
not conducive to family life.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelin inspectors work full time, and only for Michelin.
Forget about rounding up a group of willing friends for genial
lunches and dinners while checking out the pot-au-feu: mostly, the
inspectors dine alone.
</P>
<P>
   The red guides have been published annually since 1900, except
during the two world wars. Michelin publishes 13 red guides to
cities and countries in Europe. The green guides, in several
languages, give sight-seeing information on many regions of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Naegellen has engineered some changes. ``Le bib
gourmand,'' has been added _ an icon showing the face of the
Michelin mascot, Bibendum (recently slimmed down), in red to
indicate restaurants that provide good value. Last year, there were
458 listed throughout France; this year there are 509. There is
also a two-coin symbol for places with prix-fixe menus for less
than 85 francs (about $14).
</P>
<P>
   Asked about competition from the Zagat guide to Paris, which was
introduced with fanfare last year, Naegellen would only point out
that Michelin receives around 25,000 letters and comments from
readers every year, encouraged by a form in the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come right down to it, we're not Zagat, but we have
always paid attention to our readers,'' Naegellen said. ``We're
trying to do whatever we can to make the guides more
user-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting last year, there has been more general information _
vintage charts, wine maps, international dialing codes. And the
guides constantly add new European cities, including Prague,
Helsinki, Warsaw and Athens. St. Petersburg is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But what about extending Michelin's influence to New York,
Chicago or San Francisco?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, the quality is certainly there for the
hotels and restaurants,'' he said. ``We'll probably have to do it
some day. We attempted to get one for the United States going in
the late 1980s, but the logistics were too difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Michelin were to evaluate restaurants in the United
States, would it be biased toward French food? Naegellen explained
that outside France the inspectors are not always French and that
they value the local cuisine in countries like Spain and Italy.
``But if you're talking about England or the Low Countries, the top
restaurants happen to be French,'' he said. ``It's hard to find
good English food.''
</P>
<P>
   The distances from France and within the United States add to
the problems. ``It took us four years to develop a guide to
Switzerland,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The total number of starred establishments has risen by four in
the 1999 red ``Michelin France'' guide, released on Monday. But one
elevation and one demotion kept the number of three-star
restaurants at 21.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Bras, in Laguiole, joined the top-rated three-star ranks
this year. His eponymous restaurant and hotel has headed the list
of potential three-stars for a number of years, according to those
who read Michelin's tea leaves. More surprising, perhaps, is this
year's demotion of L'Esperance in Vezelay from three stars to two.
</P>
<P>
   Three stars to Michelin means ``worth a journey,'' and getting
to Michel Bras certainly requires one: the grand establishment that
grew out of the Bras family's small inn is more or less in the
middle of nowhere, in a town known for cutlery in the mountainous
Massif Central, in south-central France.
</P>
<P>
   The total number of Michelin two-star establishments increased
to 74, from last year's 70. New ones in Paris include Le Violon
d'Ingres, owned by Christian Constant, the former chef of the
Crillon hotel, L'Astor and Le Pre Catalan, both with chefs trained
by Joel Robuchon.
</P>
<P>
   There were some additions and subtractions among one-star
ratings, but the total remains the same as last year's: 405. The
new guide hits American bookstores on Wednesday, for $26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1647EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
