<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-MEAT-ART-2TA     03-02 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-MEAT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S MEAT HAS CHANGED, AND NOW IT'S THE COOK'S TURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bruce Aidells was doing his Cro-Mag-non shuffle
before the display case at Florence Meat Market in Greenwich
Village. Sporting a large leather newsboy cap, jeans and a denim
jacket emblazoned with the logo of his sausage company, the bearded
and Bunyanesque meat maven shifted from one size 14E foot to the
other.
</P>
<P>
   A self-described throwback who claims to ``personally consume at
least 20 times the national per capita average of beef a year,'' he
could barely keep from salivating.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Aidells tried to temper his hopes. The quality
of beef in this country has been going steadily downhill for nearly
30 years, he said. Prime doesn't mean what it used to.
</P>
<P>
   Aidells, the founder of the Aidells Sausage Co. in Northern
California, which produces links like smoked turkey-chicken pesto
and chicken-apple, and his collaborator, Denis Kelly, spent nearly
a decade studying the state of meat in America to produce ``The
Complete Meat Cookbook,'' published in November by Houghton
Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   Aidells approaches his passion with the cool calculation of the
scientist he once was. He holds doctoral degrees in endocrinology
and physiology and was a cancer researcher before his foray into
the sausage business took him out of the lab for good.
</P>
<P>
   Aidells formulates theories on meat cookery, of course _ but
then he investigates them with a rigorous scientific approach. So
the book became a treatise on modern meat cookery.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does it secure his image as a man unafraid of meat,
even in these vegetable-revering times, but it is rife with
heretical ideas. ``Meat has changed in America,'' he says. ``We
need to change the way we cook it.''
</P>
<P>
   Aidells may be a scientist, but he began by learning the
butcher's trade from an uncle when he was a teen-ager. In the
ensuing decades, the growing public clamor for a reduction of the
fat in beef and changes in the way cattle are raised have led to
leaner beef.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 2 percent of the beef sold in this country is prime,
the highest Agriculture Department (``USDA'') grade, with the most
marbling from fat, and hence flavor, Aidells says. And very little
prime meat is sold retail. In fact, he says, much of the beef sold
in supermarkets is either choice grade _ a wide category that
includes some decent minimally aged beef _ or is ungraded.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, butchers have become less inclined to take the
time and space to dry-age beef. The meat grows more dense and
flavorful, but it takes weeks to dry-age beef, and the meat loses
up to 25 percent of its weight in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The Florence market raised Aidells' hopes with meat that was
well marbled and dark rose, not bright red, in color. In the aging
room, a cool walk-in, hundreds of pounds of beef hung. Beef like
this, he said, needs nothing but salt and pepper and fire to make
its flavor blossom.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he does not scorn modern meat, viewing it instead as
``different meat.'' Getting the best flavor and texture, he has
found, is just a matter of cooking it differently.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the beef sold in the United States comes to market as
``box beef,'' which is cut into sections at far-flung
slaughterhouses, sealed in Cryovac packaging and then shipped. The
beef will age in the Cryovac, but not the way it does when exposed
to air. With this ``wet aging,'' as butchers call it, the meat
grows mushy and takes on a taste not of aging proteins but of
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Moist-heat cooking methods like braising, along with marinades
and dry seasoning rubs, add flavor to today's leaner meat, and
Aidells developed recipes for his book that rely on those devices.
But his overriding discovery is simple: ``Lean meat,'' he says,
``cooks a lot faster than old-fashioned, well-marbled beef.''
</P>
<P>
   To prove his point, he embarked on an experiment.
</P>
<P>
   He secured two porterhouse steaks from the Florence market, and
then headed for the Food Emporium on Union Square. He tried not to
compare the prime beef, by then wrapped in paper and string in the
canvas shopping bag he clutched, with the plastic-wrapped packages
of meat before him.
</P>
<P>
   In both his book and his life, his meat mantra is, ``We have to
get the most from what we have.'' The proper cooking equipment,
heat and recipes, he says, can turn ``so-so meat into a heck of a
meal.''
</P>
<P>
   He selected half a dozen cuts, including one labeled
porterhouse, and hurried north to a friend's kitchen. There, he
strapped on his oversize canvas apron, which more closely resembles
blacksmith garb, and began inspecting and testing his purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The dry-aged steak was all it should be: darker, rose colored,
clearly marbled with fat and dense looking. Aidells gave it his
``slap test'': when he slapped the steak onto a butcher block
counter, the meat was so taut that it bounced a little. He was
thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   The supermarket steak was barely marbled and looked redder and
very juicy, almost wet. This time, the slap test yielded a light
splattering of juices. The steak not only failed to bounce, but
even seemed to wince and be slightly flattened on impact. The
mushiness that Aidells complains of was evident.
</P>
<P>
   The denser steak, he said, would take longer to cook. Because of
its low moisture content, he said it could be seasoned lightly on
each side with salt and pepper and then broiled, either under the
flame of a conventional home broiler or in a cast-iron skillet on
top of the stove over medium-high heat.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the spongier steak, on the other hand, would need
very high, fast heat to develop a crusty exterior. The relatively
low power of most home broilers would yield a gray, well-done steak
before the meat could develop anything approximating a crust.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For a fair comparison, both steaks were panbroiled in the same
cast-iron skillet. The inch-thick dry-aged steak required five
minutes on each side over medium-high heat to come out rare; the
inch-thick supermarket steak took only three minutes a side over
high heat.
</P>
<P>
   The faster cooking time of the choice meat, however, could not
exactly be called an advantage, Aidells said. The meat was soft,
lacking the chewy texture and toothsome caramel tones and hint of
acidity that the prime steak had.
</P>
<P>
   Presalting and searing did improve the supermarket meat, but
Aidells would not leave good enough alone. Obsessed with turning
lemons into lemonade, he offered some final advice for this modern
meat. ``What you really need,'' he said, ``is a flavor boost, like
what you can get with a marinade or a spice rub.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CULOTTE STEAKS WITH ONION GLAZE AND HORSERADISH BREAD CRUMBS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Complete Meat Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 50 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { cup soft bread crumbs made from day-old bread
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons bottled horseradish, drained
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 culotte steaks (or hanging tenderloin, filet mignon, or New
York strip steaks), 7 to 8 ounces each and 1{ inches thick
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   } cup red wine. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Spread bread crumbs on a baking
sheet and bake until dry and toasted, 5 to 10 minutes. Melt butter
in a small, heavy skillet over medium heat, and add bread crumbs,
horseradish and mustard. Stir until crumbs are well coated and
golden brown, about 10 minutes. Season to taste with salt and
pepper, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Season steaks generously on both sides with salt and pepper.
In a heavy skillet large enough to hold them all without crowding,
heat oil over high heat. When very hot, add steaks, and brown 1
minute on each side. Reduce heat to medium high, and cook 3 to 4
minutes more on each side for rare to medium rare (internal
temperature 120 to 135 degrees). Transfer steaks to a platter and
cover loosely with foil.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pour off all but 1 tablespoon of the fat in the skillet, and
add onion and garlic. Cook over medium heat until soft, about 5
minutes, stirring occasionally. Pour in wine and bring to a boil,
scraping up any browned bits from bottom of pan. Continue to cook
until liquid is reduced and syrupy, and season to taste with salt
and pepper. Spoon onion mixture around steaks on platter, sprinkle
steaks with bread crumbs and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BONELESS SHORT RIBS WITH TOMATO AND FENNEL
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Complete Meat Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 3 hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3{ pounds boneless English-style short ribs, about 8 pieces (see
note)
</P>
<P>
   3 large onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 ribs celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   { cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   4 cups drained and diced canned tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1} cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped leafy fennel tops, or 1 tablespoon fennel seed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Combine basil, thyme, cayenne, 2
teaspoons salt and { teaspoon pepper. Rub into the ribs and let
stand 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a Dutch oven over medium heat, warm 2 tablespoons oil, add
ribs and brown on all sides, 7 to 10 minutes. Remove and set aside.
Reserve 2 tablespoons of drippings in pan.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add onion, celery and garlic to oil in pan; cover and cook
about 5 minutes, until vegetables begin to soften. Add wine and
stir well, scraping any browned bits from bottom of pan. Bring to a
boil; add tomatoes, chicken broth and fennel and simmer 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add short ribs to pan, cover and bake 1{ to 2 hours, until
meat is quite tender. If sauce seems too liquid, remove meat and
set aside in a warm place; then cook sauce over high heat 10 to 15
minutes, stirring frequently, until thick and syrupy. Adjust
seasoning with salt and pepper and return meat to sauce to coat.
Serve ribs and sauce over mashed potatoes, polenta, couscous or
pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: English-style ribs are sold in rectangular pieces with no
bones. If you cannot find them, substitute 4{ pounds bone-in short
ribs and remove the bones before serving.
</P>
</TEXT>
