<HEADLINE>
MONICA FOREVER AND EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After Babs interviews Monica Wednesday night, it's all
over, right? No more depositions. No more presidential hugs. No
more ``SNL'' skits. Please, please, puh-leeeeeeeez say it's all
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not exactly,'' says T.V. Skreen, Ph.D.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Dr. Skreen.
</P>
<P>
   Regular visitors will remember Dr. Skreen as the eminent
broadcast consultant and executive director of the Olden
Polynice/Vin Baker Straight Shooter Academy. In an unprecedented
hourlong interview airing exclusively inside my head, Dr. Skreen
puts the lie to any notion that Monica will be gone-ica after
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Because of space limitations, we can only print excerpts of the
far-reaching, wide-ranging, broad-based and totally imaginary
interview, which took place Tuesday as I was driving I-5 in an '81
Datsun with a broken radio. You'll notice that, despite the austere
surroundings, all of the questions were forceful and hard-hitting,
or, as we like to say in the mathematical arena, F2H2.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: Dr. Skreen, if Monica Lewinsky were a tree, what kind do
you think she'd be?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: A serviceberry.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: And if she were a sport utility vehicle, what kind would
she be?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: An Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: Intriguing. Why do you think her interview with Barbara
Walters Wednesday night on ``20/20'' (9 to 11, KOMO/4) won't be the
last time we hear from her?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: For one thing, you doofus, there's the interview she's
doing Thursday with Jon Snow on Britain's Channel Four Television.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: OK, fair enough. But after that, surely we'll have had
our fill.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Not quite. Andrew Morton, the guy who did that
best-selling bio of Princess Diana, hits the stands Thursday with
``Monica's Story.''
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: And after that?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Well, I recently signed her to a personal services
contract.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: Beg pardon?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Let me rephrase that. She has signed a deal with my
company to appear as a pundit on news and public affairs shows.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: Huh? (Notice how hard-hitting that was?)
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: So we might see her on ``Meet the Press'' or ``Northwest
Week?''
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Absolutely. I mean, can you think of anyone else who has
been that close to the president?
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: I'd rather not.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Me neither. But we owe it to the country to provide
fresh, new perspectives on events of the day.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: But, seriously, Dr. Skreen. Do you think Monica Lewinsky
might have a cogent, well-reasoned position on, say, the Kosovo
peace initiative?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: I'm not familiar with all her positions, but she has
told me on several occasions that she's very much in favor of
peace.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: And you think America will be interested in hearing what
she has to say?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Sure, at least until the next Monica Lewinsky comes
along.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: And then what?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: At that point, we'll probably move into talk radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
