<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADWATERS-HURWITZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIER MAY TRADE TREES TO SETTLE BANKING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: With HEADWATERS-FOREST)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As financier Charles Hurwitz negotiated the sale
of the biggest stands of privately held virgin redwood trees in the
world, he and his company, Maxxam Corp., faced $750 million in
federal claims stemming from a failed savings and loan in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Hurwitz agreed late Monday to sell a huge tract of redwoods in
Northern California to the state and federal governments for $480
million.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden decision came minutes before a midnight deadline and
only days after the boards of directors of the companies Hurwitz
controls _ Maxxam and its subsidiary, the Pacific Lumber Co. _
rejected the entire deal.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining redwoods that Pacific Lumber owns could be the
prize that Hurwitz trades to settle a U.S. government enforcement
action designed to win taxpayer restitution for the $1.6 billion
bailout.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and the Treasury's Office of
Thrift Supervision (OTS) allege in two separate cases that Maxxam,
Hurwitz and five other parties caused the failure of the United
Savings Association of Texas in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The OTS case against Maxxam and Hurwitz, Maxxam's major
stockholder, ended in Houston on Monday. Administrative Judge
Arthur Shipe is expected to rule by the end of the year. The FDIC
case is on hold, pending the outcome of the OTS case.
</P>
<P>
   Maxxam spokesman Robert Irelan called the government's claims
``totally without merit'' and ``an abuse of government power
stimulated by environmental activists'' who came up with a plan to
have the company pay off any settlement in trees.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called debt-for-nature swap was a plot ``to get more of
our trees and not have to pay for them,'' Irelan said.
</P>
<P>
   If Maxxam loses and the agencies succeed in winning up to $750
million in a settlement agreement, environmentalists say the
Houston-based company should pay off in trees.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Little, executive director of the Rose Foundation, a
nonprofit organization in Oakland, Calif., that works on
environmental and economic issues, called a payoff in trees ``a
good business deal for Maxxam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think they're going to be able to cut a lot of the
remaining old-growth stands anyway because of environmental
regulations,'' Little said. ``Getting rid of the environmental
liabilities and at the same time getting rid of $750 million in the
federal banking liabilities in exchange for property that won't
generate commercial income anyway is a good business deal for the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   The OTS and FDIC cases, filed in 1995, proceeded over 17 months
against Maxxam and Hurwitz and five other parties in Houston. The
five others settled last month, without admitting guilt, for more
than $1 million and a promise to refrain from banking activity.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the OTS and the FDIC allege that either Maxxam or
Hurwitz or both deliberately misled the bank regulators, engaged in
sham transactions, failed to keep sufficient capital in the
institution and masked its deteriorating financial condition.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agencies charged that the defendants changed a
conventional savings and loan into an institution that bought and
sold high-risk junk bonds and speculative real estate investments.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators say Maxxam and Hurwitz engaged in quid-pro-quo
transactions. The bank owners used the institution's cash to buy a
portfolio of Drexel Burnham Lambert, once the leading trader in
junk bonds and defunct since the late 1980s. Drexel returned the
favor by helping Maxxam finance the takeover of Pacific Lumber and
another company, they allege.
</P>
<P>
   Maxxam representatives have denied the charges and contend that
the banking regulators have failed to prove their case.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the company officials said, Maxxam had only a 24.9
percent ownership in United Savings.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the government has argued that Hurwitz had de facto
control of 25 percent because of his influence through contractual
agreements over other owners, primarily Drexel Burnham Lambert.
</P>
</TEXT>
