<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVENCAL HERBS  
 FROZEN RICOTTA  
 NONSTICK FLAMBEING  
 ROASTED PARSNIP SOUP
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the end note instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Where can I buy herbes de Provence?
</P>
<P>
   A. Herbes de Provence, which usually contain some combination of
crushed bay leaves, fennel seeds, lavender, marjoram, rosemary,
sage, summer savory and thyme, can be used like other dried herbs.
Whisk the blend into marinades, dressings or eggs; sprinkle it over
vegetables and meats before roasting, or crumble it into soups,
stews and casseroles. It is available in specialty stores, usually
in little clay pots or rustic-looking miniature burlap bags (often
lined with plastic to keep the herbs fresh).
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Dean and Deluca, 560 Broadway (Prince Street),
(212) 431-1691, carries herbes de Provence in 1.5-ounce tins for
$4.50 and 5-ounce bags for $7. Kalustyan's, 123 Lexington Ave.
(28th Street), (212) 685-3451, sells the herb blend loose for $1.50
an ounce. You may also find it in supermarkets like D'Agostino.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen Ricotta?
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you freeze fresh ricotta?
</P>
<P>
   A. You can, but like any other cheese, it will suffer. Fresh
ricotta, with its creamy texture and sweet, milky flavor, is best
used within a day of two of buying it. If you must freeze it, be
advised that it will break down on defrosting. The Italian food
expert Michele Scicolone, the author with Charles Scicolone of
``Pizza Any Way You Slice It!'' (Broadway Books, $20), says the
result is usually too grainy and watery to use in uncooked recipes
like a cannoli filling. It could be used in cooked dishes, where
its unpleasant texture will be hidden by the other ingredients
(like the tomato sauce and mozzarella in lasagna).
</P>
<P>
   Passing the ricotta through a sieve or whirling it in a food
processor or blender can help smooth out the curds, and draining it
in a cheesecloth-lined colander will also eliminate some excess
moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick Flambeing
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can food be flambeed in a nonstick pan?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not usually. Many manufacturers of nonstick pans use
plastic-based coatings that could burn off if subjected to a direct
flame as in lighting brandy or a sauce. (That is why the directions
warn against placing such pans under the broiler.) There is,
however, one type of nonstick pan that will withstand a flame
because it is made of a specially processed stainless steel. Called
French Cybernox, it is available in New York at Bridge Kitchenware,
214 East 52nd St., (212) 688-4220; (800) 274-3435 for calls from
outside New York; www.bridgekitchenware.com. The price is $145 for
a 9 1/2-inch pan or $160 for a 10 1/4).
</P>
<P>
   _ MELISSA CLARK
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Parsnip Soup
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had a great roasted parsnip soup in England. Do you have a
recipe?
</P>
<P>
   A. Roasting parsnips intensifies their already sweet flavor,
giving them a complex, caramelized edge. This technique works on
almost all root vegetables, especially those high in natural
sugars, like parsnips, turnips, rutabagas, onions, garlic, sweet
potatoes and carrots. This recipe combines roasted parsnips and
garlic with simmered parsnips for extra flavor.
</P>
<P>
   For a richer soup, garnish each bowlful with a little sour cream
or whole milk yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED PARSNIP AND GARLIC SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds parsnips, peeled and cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices
</P>
<P>
   8 unpeeled cloves garlic, plus 4 cloves peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 leeks, white part plus 1 inch of the green, washed and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 large yellow onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs fresh thyme or 1/8 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   6 cups chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   Fresh lemon juice to taste (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Chopped fresh chives or scallions, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In a bowl, toss together half
the parsnip slices, the unpeeled garlic and 2 tablespoons of the
oil. Spread vegetables out in one layer on a baking sheet and
season with salt and pepper to taste. Roast, stirring occasionally,
until they are tender and golden brown, about 40 minutes. Transfer
to a wire rack to cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   2. While vegetables are roasting, make soup base. In a pot, heat
remaining tablespoon oil over medium heat. Add remaining parsnip
slices, leeks, shallots, onion and thyme, and saute until softened,
about 10 minutes. Add minced garlic, and saute 2 minutes longer.
Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add stock, and bring mixture to a simmer over high heat.
Partly cover pot, reduce heat to medium low and simmer until
parsnips are very tender, about 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Squeeze roasted garlic cloves to extract the flesh,
discarding skins. Add to the stock along with the roasted parsnips,
and simmer 10 minutes to meld the flavors.
</P>
<P>
   5. If using fresh thyme, remove sprigs. Using an immersion or
regular blender, puree the soup (you may have to work in batches
with a regular blender). Adjust seasonings with more salt, pepper
and lemon juice, if desired. Serve hot, garnished with the chives
or scallions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about food and cooking can be sent to Food Chain, the
Dining section, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New York, NY
10036-3959, or by e-mail to: dining(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
