<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE STUDY SAYS HOSPITALS, DOCTORS UNPREPARED FOR Y2K GLITCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A majority of doctors and hospitals are unprepared
for the year 2000 computer glitch, putting diagnostic equipment and
drug distribution in jeopardy, a Senate committee warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's report on U.S. preparedness for the so-called
Y2K computer problem singled-out health care _ the nation's largest
industry _ as the most ill-prepared to cope with computer
malfunctions that could occur on or after Jan. 1, 2000, when some
computer systems are expected to misread the year 2000 as 1900.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe the health-care industry's lack of
preparedness will necessarily mean loss of life, but it could
seriously impact care for millions of Americans dependent upon
prescription drugs and regular medical treatments to stay
healthy,'' said Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate
special committee on the year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   One major problem facing the health-care industry is computer
chips embedded in a range of medical diagnostic devices like
Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) machines and blood-gas analyzers
used during surgery that could cause them to malfunction on or
after Jan. 1, 2000. While many medical device manufacturers have
made sure their devices won't have this problem, the Senate report
said the medical profession has experienced difficulty in getting
information from device manufacturers about their products.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that 90 percent of the more than 800,000
doctors offices nationwide have not fixed their computers to
correctly read the year 2000, which could result in the loss of
some patient medical records. The report also noted that 64 percent
of hospitals do not have computers that will work in the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said most large hospitals are
well prepared for the millennium-date change but small, rural and
inner-city hospitals lack the resources to upgrade computer
systems.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry is the best-prepared segment of the
health-care industry but pharmaceutical firms face potential
problems in dealing with foreign suppliers who may not have
up-to-date computer systems, according to the Senate report.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of the ingredients used to produce drugs in the
U.S. come from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that many foreign countries especially in Asia
and South America are lagging in fixing their computer systems.
Bennett said some countries such as the United Kingdom are in as
good as or better shape than the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett and Dodd said it was impossible to predict the exact
effects of the Y2K problem or the so-called millennium bug on the
U.S., but they think any problems would be relatively short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally it will be a bump in the road for the United
States,'' Bennett said. ``It will not be crippling.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said it was unlikely the millennium bug would cause
wide-spread power outages or disruptions in air travel in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The financial services and telecommunications industries are
well prepared for the Jan. 1, 2000, date change and have tested
many of their systems. For example, bank customers should be able
to withdraw cash from an Automated Teller Machine on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Dodd said Americans should prepare for Jan. 1 like
they would for a snow storm or a hurricane by having a few days of
food and water on hand. He discouraged people from stockpiling food
and other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   More problems may be caused from Americans overreacting to the
Y2K problem than from actual Y2K disruptions themselves, lawmakers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., said one of his constituents recently
had $30,000 stolen that he had withdrawn from a bank to protect it
from a potential Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Y2K panel also heard Tuesday from food-service
industry representatives who told the committee that there should
be few disruptions, if any, in the nation's food supply.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Herschel, executive vice president of the Kroger Co.,
which operates more than 1,400 grocery stores, said they generally
have 35 to 36 days of inventory on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Senate approved legislation that provides $500
million for the Small Business Administration to make loans that
will allow small businesses to address any Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett and Dodd also briefed the Senate in a closed-door
session about U.S. security concerns related to Y2K, including an
accidental launch of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said Russia's military, nuclear plants and weapons
systems are vulnerable to the Y2K problem, but said the probability
of an accidental weapons launch is ``low.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has invited Russian officials to the
U.S. Space Command headquarters in Colorado Springs, Colo., later
this year to participate in a joint project to assure that any
false computer signals do not lead to an accidental nuclear attack
by either country.
</P>
</TEXT>
