<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIGHTING MARKS NEXT STEP IN WASHINGTON MONUMENT'S REPAIR
 &HT;    430&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of the nation's most familiar landmarks glowed
a new blue hue Tuesday evening, lighting the way for another step
toward repairing the Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic lighting of 506 floodlights beneath a decorative
sheath capped five months of preparation for a project to repair
and clean the famous obelisk's 38,000 white marble and granite
slabs.
</P>
<P>
   In November, construction began on a lightweight aluminium
scaffolding that now surrounds the 555-foot-tall monument. The $3
million scaffolding, designed by Princeton University architect
William Graves, is a structure unto itself _ not fastened to the
114-year-old landmark for fear of damaging it.
</P>
<P>
   Strips of sheer blue architectural mesh were attached to the
outer girders of the scaffolding, an artistic covering that will
leave the monument visible throughout the restoration. A lighting
system was then wired onto the scaffolding.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt switched on the lights in a
ceremony Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our worries when faced with this restoration was
ensuring the Monument would retain its beauty despite the work
surrounding it,'' said Babbitt. But with the decoratively draped
scaffolding, ``we quelled those fears and, in fact, achieved a new
level of elegance for one of our nation's most prized structures.''
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after Egyptian obelisks and opened in 1888, the
Washington Monument is a free-standing masonry structure, which
means there is no internal skeleton of steel or iron beams to
support its 90,000 tons. The stones are 15 feet thick at the base
of the monument and taper to 18 inches at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure to the weather has eroded and loosened the mortar
joining many of the stones, and cracks have been found near the
top. In addition, the whole exterior needs to be cleaned of grime
accumulated since the last cleaning in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The project, to be completed by mid-2000, will cost about $9.4
million. It is being funded through a public-private partnership
between the National Park Service, a federal agency within the
Interior Department; the National Park Foundation, a private,
non-profit group set up ``to encourage gifts'' to the National Park
Service, and Target Stores, a national chain of discount retail
outlets based in Minneapolis that has helped raise about $6.5
million for the restoration effort. GE Lighting donated the
fixtures, bulbs and design to illuminate the scaffolding.
</P>
<P>
   After the scaffolding was completed, the Washington Monument
reopened to tourists on President's Day, Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Workers will inspect the entire monument, and then begin the
needed patching and repointing, or removing old mortar to the depth
of about an inch and replacing it with new mortar. The work is done
mostly with hand-held hammers and chisels. About 64,000 linear feet
will be repointed on the exterior walls, and another 3,900 on the
interior. Any cracks that are found will be sealed. The entire
exterior will be cleaned with low-pressure steam.
</P>
<P>
   The scaffolding surrounding the monument has become an
architectural attraction itself. Graves, its designer, is a
professor of architecture at Princeton. The scaffolding tapers to
conform to the dimensions of the monument, which narrows from about
55 feet at the bottom of the shaft to 34 feet at the top. The
pyramid-shaped top of the scaffolding matches the monument's
capstone, but does not touch it.
</P>
<P>
   The scaffolding contains 37 miles of aluminium tubing. Modules
were built in New Jersey, then taken to Washington on flatbed
trucks for assembly.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of its opening in 1888, the Washington Monument was
the tallest structure in the world. Its observation platform is
reached by a single elevator. On weekends, visitors _ which number
more than 1 million a year _ can walk accompanied by guides down an
iron stairway with 50 landings and 897 steps.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
