<HEADER>
A4870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EPCOT-SPEEDWAY-ART-NY     03-02 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPCOT-SPEEDWAY-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPCOT'S NEWEST ATTRACTION IS ALSO ITS FASTEST 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Ill., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DIANE LACEY ALLEN   
 The Ledger (Lakeland, Fla.)   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHAT: Test Track, Epcot's newest attraction.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN: Though it doesn't officially open until March 17, the ride
is already operating off and on during the park's regular hours.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: Epcot at Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   ADMISSION: Admission to Epcot is $44.52 for adults, $36.04 ages
3-9. Tax included.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: (407) 824-4321.
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Phil Terpolilli is too young to drive. But at
13, he knows a good ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild,'' he said. ``Especially when you hit 50 miles per
hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's more like 65 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But then, all you really feel is the breeze as Epcot's latest
adventure goes whipping around the outside of what used to be the
World of Motion.
</P>
<P>
   Terpolilli, vacationing with his parents from Rochester, N.Y.,
was one of hundreds in line recently for a sneak peak at Test Track
_ a cooperative thrill put on by General Motors and Disney.
</P>
<P>
   A year behind schedule and almost seven years in the making,
Test Track revs up to full speed March 17 and is Disney's longest
and fastest ride. The World of Motion was gutted to create a
150,000-square-foot mock proving ground that cars filled with
guests move through in 5 minutes 34 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Using three on-board computers, the six-passenger cars go
through 34 turns and two braking exercises, climb a three-story
hill and navigate a road lined with 85 signs.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers are bumped around on rough roads, slammed to a halt
and gently misted twice. The electric cars undergo a 100-degree
swing in temperature, although passengers just feel a mild
sensation of hot and cold.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, riders see crash-test dummies do their thing. The
dummies are struck in the chest, banged on the knees and have their
necks bent 720 times during the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   As on real roads, there are also surprises. The vehicle must
practice evasive maneuvers to avoid being struck by a
tractor-trailer.
</P>
<P>
   The real fun begins when the car swings outside the building.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle zooms from 0 to 60 in 8 seconds in the open air. The
grand finale comes on a 50-degree banked turn at 65 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Watching over the Test Track like a mother hen is John Maciarz,
residential director for General Motors Operations. Maciarz's
office is inside the Test Track, and as he makes his rounds he
greets riders as if they were long, lost friends.
</P>
<P>
   Maciarz makes a habit of riding the exhibit twice a day _ once
when he gets to work and again before he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   He's all smiles by the time his Test Track car hits the 65 mph
mark, a limit that was hashed out during the design of the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty-five was picked primarily because it was the speed limit
of our nation,'' Maciarz said. ``This is pretty fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the speed limits have risen across the country since
Test Track's inception.
</P>
<P>
   And riders like Brian Sanders, a 28-year-old systems engineer
from Chicago, wanted ``more speed and twists.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Joe Haveman, a 66-year-old commercial pilot from Akron,
Ohio, it was close enough.
</P>
<P>
   Haveman has a brother-in-law who works at the actual GM proving
grounds and has been lucky enough to check out the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like the test track,'' Havemen said. ``Not too bad.
They go faster at the test track. They really hot rod them there,
cause they run at night.''
</P>
<P>
   (Diane Lacey Allen writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. This
story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
