<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4872 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-02 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE SHOE FITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Beginning with Euripides, the great Greek tragedian
of the 5th century B.C., philosophers, poets and literary giants
through the centuries have mused wryly that the gods answer the
prayers of those they wish to destroy.
</P>
<P>
   If only the political midgets who fervently espoused the cause
of limiting congressional terms had accepted the ancient wisdom,
they might not be trapped today in the concept of a selfless
sacrifice they touted for others but prefer not to carry out
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican freshmen who took over the House in 1994 came to
power promising as part of their ``Contract with America'' to
impose term limits on themselves and every other member of
Congress. The issue was a political hit at the time, but now that
reality has set in, some incumbents are as loathe to give up power
as were their long-term predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   The House failed to pass a constitutional amendment mandating
artificially short terms for everyone, although it had a high GOP
priority. But individual members of Congress are still stuck with
their personal pledges to put their resignations where their mouths
were _ unless, of course, their constituents don't care whether
they keep their word.
</P>
<P>
   If they keep their promises, nine Republicans and one Democrat
will not seek re-election next year in order to fulfill their
philosophical goal of perpetually churning congressional seats. In
all, 45 House members signed pledges in recent years to limit their
service to six years, and 14 senators similarly agreed to only two
terms, or 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 House members whose six years expire in 2000, four are
now reluctant to give it all up. The most conspicuous is GOP Rep.
George Nethercutt of Washington state, who defeated House Speaker
Tom Foley primarily by depicting Foley as a career politician who
had been around too long.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt crusaded against the value of seniority in the
congressional system, making a great foofaraw about Foley's lawsuit
to block a local term-limits initiative. ``If I can't effect some
change in six years, maybe I'm in the wrong place,'' Nethercutt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, he has discovered that Congress is a nice place to
work and longevity of service brings rank, which has its privileges
and its usefulness. (What a revelation. Tell that to Foley).
</P>
<P>
   House GOP leaders, who need every vote they can get to keep
majority control in 2000, are eager to see Nethercutt and other
potential term-limits hypocrites renege on their promise and run
again. But U.S. Term Limits, an organization dedicated to the
cause, is not going to let its political pawns forget their oath.
</P>
<P>
   The group plans a $20 million campaign to push term limits
during the 2000 election cycle. One of its early moves was to put
up a billboard in Nethercutt's district sarcastically _ or
optimistically _ ``thanking'' him for keeping his word, which he
has yet to do.
</P>
<P>
   The term-limits issue has lost much of its political cachet
since the GOP took over Congress. The party leadership turned
against it, retroactive provisions were barred to protect aging
Republican incumbents and the constitutional amendment was
defeated. In recent elections term limits have helped some
candidates and not others.
</P>
<P>
   The original momentum for the cause was rooted in Republican
frustration that the Democrats had controlled Congress practically
forever. The idea was that forcing a turnover would give GOP
candidates a shot at more seats.
</P>
<P>
   In order to sell this notion, it was necessary to persuade
voters that experience was bad and political ignorance was good.
The less elected officials knew about the way Congress worked, the
better they would be at governing.
</P>
<P>
   And it took some doing to get around that awkward business about
elections, the democratic way voters have always been free to kick
out the bums they don't want without resorting to artificial
limitations.
</P>
<P>
   We needn't weep for legislators caught in a promise they are now
reluctant to fulfill. It is not a surprise that term limits look
less attractive when applied to oneself than when assigned to
others. Euripides, a master of human nature, could have told that
to Nethercutt and his fellow sufferers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
