A4875 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAIN-GRANADA-$ADV07-     03-02 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-GRANADA-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ALHAMBRA AND THE CATHEDRAL: TWO ESSENCES OF GRANADA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, March 7)  
 (bl)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news from North Africa is not good. Algeria operates as a
civilian slaughterhouse, Libya a university for terrorism. Morocco
struggles with separatists over the Western Sahara; Ethiopia lives
with endless revolution. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chaos and disorder, or so it would seem from our relatively
righteous vantage point across the Mediterranean and the Atlantic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So it is enlightening to take a walk through the Alhambra in the
crisp, January sunlight of Andalusia and then make one's way down
the hill and into the Cathedral of Granada, keeping in mind all the
while the violent separations between Islam and the West that we
read about in our newspapers every day. It is like passing from an
exquisite daydream into the house of a superpower, political will
exuding from every stone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cathedral, two square blocks of immensity and complication,
announces the defeat of the heathen. Granada was the last major
outpost of a Moorish domination that at its high point threatened
France and for 800 years controlled most of Spain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the surrender of the Alhambra _ part hilltop fortress, part
palace of kings _ in 1492, the shoring up of Christianity called
for strong measures, and under Queen Isabella's direction the
cathedral was begun, rising slowly over the duration of the 16th
century. It stands in what is now the middle of the city. The plan
was Gothic but the execution Renaissance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The connoisseur will find beauties in this church _ perhaps the
stained glass windows brought from Flanders or the gold and white
of the Capilla Mayor, or main chapel. Untrained, less articulate
eyes like mine feel it more from the gut. This is architecture as
threat. The intimidation begins with bigness. And indeed, to walk
between the two towering banks of organ works in the cathedral's
center is to run a certain gantlet: a stray chord is an alarming
prospect, capable of devastating the ears of unwary civilians from
both sides. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Granada's cathedral is big, but also aggressive. Here God is not
in the details but in the ornament. Every square foot to spare is
devoted to it. Decoration squirms across the chapels, demonstrating
an aliveness to foes of the Christian church. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the hill above the Cathedral of Granada, within the walls of
the Alhambra, stand the Nasrine palaces. They are essentially from
the 14th century, built by Yusef I and his son Mohammed V. If the
cathedral's columns are thick and powerful, supporting great
weight, those of the Alhambra are like the slender legs of
beautiful women. The cathedral's interior stretches nearly 400 feet
in length and rises 200 more. The Court of Comares in the Alhambra
shrinks those dimensions by three fourths and yet projects an
unparalleled air of spatial freedom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The graceful, reticent decoration and inlay of the Moors gives
the eye a sense of lightness. And then there is the sound of water:
fountains with plumbing so subtle that they are constantly but
never obtrusively in the ear. At Frank Lloyd Wright's Fallingwater
in western Pennsylvania, water comes in a powerful rush,
unavoidable and dominating every aspect of the house built above
it. The Alhambra never insists. A European visitor in 1494 remarked
on its properties as ``so magnificent, so exquisitely executed that
even he who contemplates it can scarcely be sure that he is not in
a paradise.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paradise, indeed. This is architecture as seduction. Modern-day
suicide bombers sacrificing themselves in the market squares of
Jerusalem are promised something like it beyond the grave. Is it
visions like the Courtyard of the Lions and the Gardens of El
Partal that appear before them as they detonate the explosives
strapped around their middles? V.S. Naipaul has described the
Islamic political mind and its failed attempts to create a real
world in the image of an imagined one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Alhambra is an earthbound dream of paradise on earth. In one
courtyard are two arches _ one round and one pointed. The visitor
looks through them to a wall on which the shapes of both arches are
repeated, now superimposed on it. The arches _ first real, then
idealized _ constitute an act of promise and fulfillment. This is
religion for the eye. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Generalife sits still higher than the Alhambra proper, a
summer palace above the heat and administrative din. It is
approached and ultimately surrounded by gardens. Once many of them
grew food; now all are decorative, but it is their placement that
beguiles. For those who take the ascending pathways, every glance
and turn of the head has been anticipated: always something new and
something pleasing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spanish builders made their own imprint on the Alhambra, but
after the 18th century its maintenance was let slide. Washington
Irving, a diplomat attached to the U.S. legation in Madrid in the
1820s, came upon it in the hands of a small family of caretakers.
Enchanted, he lived in the ruins for four months and absorbed the
stories and histories that became his ``Tales of the Alhambra.''
Here we read of Boabdil, the last of the Moorish rulers, who
climbed the Hill of Tears and looking back on his loss uttered the
legendary ``Sigh of the Moor.'' A lot of the Alhambra's history is
just plain wrong, but so compelling that it ought to be true and so
in a sense is. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is unwise to confuse the beautiful with the good. This
particular paradise struggled with insurrections from below and
cruelty within its walls. Legend or fact has it that in the
exquisitely decorated Hall of the Abencerrajes, one paranoid ruler
had the throats of many of his knights cut en masse. The marble
pool in its center bears stains. Blood, say romantics, though iron
oxide is more likely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Alhambra is pleasant in winter. There are fewer visitors;
mornings and evenings are chilly but the midday sun is surprisingly
warm. The forests on the surrounding hillsides (another example of
the Moorish way with water) are stripped of foliage, and it is easy
to trace the imposing fortress walls through bare branches along
the steep Cuesta de Gomerez. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cathedral of Granada _ huge, heavy and best seen from the
top of these walls _ looks back with another kind of militancy.
Violence and beauty coexist in both these sacred places, and yet
what different paradises they occupy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
