A4878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      03-02 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, March 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms, some with brief downpours and gusty
winds, will develop Wednesday ahead of a cold front sweeping across
the Southeast states. A few thunderstorms may approach severe
levels across the eastern Carolinas and eastern Virginia later
Wednesday or Wednesday evening as increasingly humid air from the
Atlantic Ocean and Gulf of Mexico is lifted by a potent jet stream
disturbance trailing the cold front. If severe weather develops, it
will be limited mainly to small, isolated pockets of damaging
winds.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rain will gradually spread across the Northeast
states from the eastern Great Lakes Wednesday and Wednesday night.
Rain will begin as wet snow in parts of upstate New York and
northern New England. In the wake of the system, moderate to
locally heavy wet snows will fall on mountain slopes in
west-central Pennsylvania as developing winds from the west are
forced to rapidly ascend the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean winds gusting over 75 mph will lash parts of the Oregon
coast Wednesday as an exceptionally strong Pacific low pressure
system slowly pushes northeast across Washington's Puget Sound.
Strong onshore winds will fuel rains in western Washington and
Oregon, with west-facing slopes of Oregon's Coastal Range likely
being deluged with the heaviest rains. Peals of thunder will
accompany some of the rain as a pool of very cold air at 17,000
feet arrives over western Washington and destabilizes the
atmosphere. Heavy mountain snows will fall in the Cascades of
Washington and Oregon and the Bitterroots of Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Lake-effect Slowdown
</P>
<P>
   The Great Lakes are an efficient snow machine, manufacturing
snow whenever Arctic air is moistened in transit over relatively
warm waters. In late winter and spring, this lake-effect-snow
machine operates at reduced capacity, owing largely to the waning
chill of Arctic air and the icy surface waters of the Great Lakes.
Indeed, on Monday, only light snowfalls were observed at low
elevations downwind of Lake Erie and Lake Ontario. But elevation
made a difference as 18 inches of snow fell at Montague, a town
located near 2,000 feet on the Tughill Plateau of northwest New
York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
