<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND PRICES RISE AS TRADERS COVER SHORT POSITIONS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices rose on Tuesday for only the second time
in almost a week as market participants covered short positions
after a benign report on new-home sales.
</P>
<P>
   Also contributing to higher prices were the unwinding of
positions in front of a large amount of corporate debt expected to
be priced during the next few days and the attractive yields
resulting from recent selloffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike existing-home sales, which rose to a record level in
January, new-home sales fell modestly during the month,'' said
Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management, ``and
while this was the second consecutive monthly decline, the sales
pace is still at historically high levels and shows no definitive
signs of slowing as of yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Although rising mortgage rates could dampen housing activity in
the short term, Fine added, ``keep in mind that housing is the
leading edge of broad economic momentum, and the economy's
rip-roaring advance is not likely to slacken significantly until a
housing slowdown is under way.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a separate report that the Conference Board's index of
leading economic indicators rose 0.5 percent in January did not
suggest a slowdown in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the market's recent swoon and concern about rapid
economic growth and Federal Reserve intervention, Fine said the
odds that the Federal Open Market Committee would raise interest
rates at its March 30 meeting were slim but that there was a good
chance that the committee could shift its stance in favor of higher
rates in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the recent onslaught of strong economic data, the labor
market data to be released this Friday could prove very
instrumental in this decision,'' Fine said.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year bond rose 24/32, to 94 26/32.
Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the price,
fell to 5.61 percent, from 5.66 percent on Monday. The two-year
note gained 3/32, to 99 24/32, to yield 5.13 percent, down from
5.18 percent the previous day.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury was an active seller of debt on Tuesday, selling
$10 billion of new 52-week bills and $19 billion of 12-day cash
management bills. The 12-day bills are used to meet the Treasury's
short-term cash needs and are an addition to its regular schedule
of debt sales.
</P>
<P>
   The auction of 52-week bills went well, analysts said, thanks to
the increase of nearly 30 basis points in yields since last month's
auction. The bills were awarded at an average rate of 4.665
percent, with the number of bids the best since last September's
auction. The rate of the 12-day cash management bill came in at
4.79 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the bond market, Colombia sold a five-year note
that was priced to yield 11.587 percent, or 6.3 percentage points
over the comparable Treasury issue. The issue was another
indication that Brazil's devaluation of its currency in January has
had much less fallout than feared.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first bond that Colombia has sold since Russia
devalued the ruble and defaulted on some bonds last August. The
high yield attracted enough investors to raise the issue to $500
million from $400 million, said Rachel Hines, the managing director
for Latin American capital markets at J.P. Morgan Securities, one
of the joint lead underwriters on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1739EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-U.S.-ASSESS-NYT     03-02 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT DOWNPLAYS PROBLEMS IN U.S.-CHINA TIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ On her departure from China on Tuesday, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright put the best face on the fractured
U.S.-Chinese relationship, saying it was mature enough to withstand
sharp disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   As she headed for Thailand for talks about that country's
economy, she lauded the Chinese for the ``depth and ease'' of her
discussions here, which were crammed into less than 48 hours. She
emphasized that there would be no going back on the Clinton
administration's policy of broad engagement with China.
</P>
<P>
   In short, she suggested, the United States has managed despite
the rough bumps of the last few months to get beyond a relationship
whose health depended primarily on one issue, whether human rights
or trade or national security.
</P>
<P>
   But in each of those areas, which were the hottest topics in the
talks, Albright and her advisers acknowledged that they still faced
significant obstacles in China and at home in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   On human rights, Albright told the Chinese authorities that the
recent arrests and long prison sentences for members of a fledgling
opposition party were a breach of the Universal Declaration of
Human Rights, not just an internal matter as the Chinese insist.
From the U.S. point of view, she said, the political stability that
China values so highly cannot be bought at the price of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Fairly predictably, her advisers said, the Chinese rejected the
arguments. But less predictably, a senior administration official
said, the Chinese did not ``go through the roof'' as they have in
the past at the mention of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the official said, slow progress is being made in
persuading the Chinese to set up an information exchange on
prisoners that would allow the U.S. Embassy in Beijing to have
regular contacts with the Chinese Foreign Ministry on the status of
individual prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese were also told that the visit of the Prime Minister
Zhu Rongji to Washington in early April would present them with an
opportunity to make a positive move on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   To coincide with his visit, Albright suggested that the Chinese
formally agree to one of the United Nations civil rights covenants
they have signed but not yet ratified: the International Covenant
on Civil and Political Rights or the International Covenant on
Economic, Social and Cultural Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Congress remains angry over China's human rights policies, and
the recent arrests and sentences of opposition party members in
China has heightened the antagonism.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of this renewed ire, the Senate unanimously adopted a
resolution last week urging the administration to condemn China at
the annual meeting of the U.N. Human Rights Commission in Geneva,
which will begin at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   One of Albright's tasks on this trip was to assess whether the
administration should introduce a resolution against the Chinese in
Geneva and what effect it would have on the Chinese leadership, who
have always interpreted such resolutions as highly negative acts.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of Albright's talks, her advisers said, no decision
was made on the touchy subject _ but they allowed that it was not
such a bad idea to keep the Chinese guessing.
</P>
<P>
   In another area of discussion _ China's possible membership in
the World Trade Organization, which governs global trade _ Albright
came away somewhat heartened.
</P>
<P>
   Her aides said that for the first time, Zhu, who has major
responsibility for the economy, appeared to understand the positive
aspects for China of joining the trade organization, even as the
Chinese economy was being shaken by slowing growth.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has hammered at the idea that opening the
Chinese market for services, goods and agriculture are likely to
create job growth, not job loss, as the Chinese have feared.
</P>
<P>
   While the prospects for China's entry to the trade organization
have improved, officials said, the details of the concessions China
was prepared to make for what the administration insists must be a
``commercially viable'' agreement, were far from clear.
</P>
<P>
   China sees membership in the World Trade Organization as an
opportunity to enhance its national prestige and to insure that
other countries cannot discriminate against Chinese products. The
United States, which has a virtual veto over who can join the
Geneva-based organization, believes that membership would force
China to agree to a schedule for lowering tariffs and trade
barriers and would subject China to the rulings of the trade
group's court, which enforces trade rules.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky is due in Beijing
on Wednesday and will make a specific proposal that addresses the
outstanding issues, a senior administration official said. ``After
her visit we'll have to see where we are,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the administration has, for the moment, made the trade
organization its central focus in the relationship with China,
there are problems with gaining support from Congress for Chinese
membership.
</P>
<P>
   Various interest groups in Congress will be taking a close look
at how the administration negotiates requirements for market
openings in such areas as agriculture and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, China would no doubt tie its agreement to join to
ending the annual vote in Congress on whether China should have
``most favored nation'' trading status _ which despite its name
means the basic rights enjoyed by most U.S. trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear, several aides to Democratic senators said
recently, that lawmakers will favor waiving the annual debate over
the economic relationship between the two countries. At the very
least, they said, senators will want to see improvement by China on
the human rights front in exchange for granting permanent trade
status.
</P>
<P>
   A specialist in China's economy, Nicholas Lardy, a senior fellow
at the Brookings Institution in Washington, said that the Chinese
are nervous about their prospects in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has got only one carrot _ that is permanent
trade status _ but the Chinese say, `What if we don't get the vote
in Congress?' '' Lardy said. ``The Chinese say, `We've made all
these concessions but what do we get?'''
</P>
<P>
   On U.S. national security interests, which have also riled
Congress, Albright had to reply to some tart complaints from the
Chinese about Washington's intentions to deploy a missile defense
shield in Asia. The Chinese view this plan, which could involve a
protective shield around Taiwan, as a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's answer was apparently equally tart: ``I replied that
instead of worrying about a decision that has not been made to
deploy defensive technologies that do not yet exist, China should
focus its energies on the real source of the problem _ the
proliferation of missiles,'' she said at a news conference today.
</P>
<P>
   China should use its influence on North Korea to help restrain
missile development there, she said. And China should work with
Taiwan to reduce tensions so that the Chinese can reverse their
recent buildup of missiles on the Chinese coast opposite Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   If the missile threat from North Korea and China were not
perceived to exist, then the need for a United States missile
defense shield in Asia would diminish, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
