<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox Cable expands East marketBy Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cox Communications has added more than 100,000 new
subscribers in a series of transactions that gave it cable TV
systems in New England and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   These deals are part of a strategy by the Atlanta-based cable TV
concern to expand in areas where it already has a high
concentration of subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clustering strategy continues to pay off in our ability to
offer new services more efficiently to a larger number of
consumers,'' said Jimmy Hayes, Cox Communications' chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The largest group of new subscribers were gained in a series of
swaps in New England with cable operator MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications took control of systems representing 105,000
subscribers in Enfield, Conn., and Westerly, R.I. It traded away a
series of smaller systems scattered across Massachusetts. The new
systems join a New England cluster, which already has 428,000
subscribers and is Cox Communications' third largest.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, Cox Communications bought a system with 11,000
subscribers owned by 1st Commonwealth Communications. The system
serves the Virginia communities of Gloucester, New Kent, West Point
and King and Queen County.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications already has 394,000 subscribers in the
Norfolk, Virginia Beach and Newport News areas.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of neither the Virginia nor the New England deal were
disclosed. The deals are expected to close in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is one of the largest cable TV operators,
with 3.8 million subscribers in Oklahoma City, Okla., Phoenix,
Orange County, San Diego and Las Vegas, among other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is controlled by Atlanta-based Cox
Enterprises, which also owns the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
