<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield feeling better after flu
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Evander Holyfield, who in 1995 was admonished for
keeping secret a virus he had before a loss to Riddick Bowe, vows
that a recent bout with the flu will not affect him in his upcoming
heavyweight title unification against Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling a lot better now,'' said Holyfield, who resumed
full workouts last week after missing three days of sparring.
``With Bowe, I didn't start feeling better until the week of the
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who meets Lewis on March 13 at Madison Square Garden,
missed workout sessions Thursday and Friday, Feb. 18-19 and didn't
spar the following Monday, Feb. 22. He returned home to Atlanta and
was examined by physician Dr. Christopher Vaughns, who prescribed
an antibiodic. Holyfield also took a blood test.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are coming out with this flu bug, especially
in the South,'' Holyfield said. ``The big thing for me was just to
not take it for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   In November 1995, Holyfield knocked down Bowe in the sixth round
of their third fight but didn't have the energy to finish his
opponent. Bowe rallied and stopped the depleted Holyfield in the
eighth. After the fight, Holyfield admitted that a virus, which he
previously had claimed cost him only a few workouts, actually hung
with him for three weeks. Fitness coach Tim Hallmark said Holyfield
ran and lifted weights only twice during that span. Officials of
the Nevada Athletic Commission criticized Holyfield for
understating the seriousness of his illness.
</P>
<P>
   Fight night
</P>
<P>
   Fight Night VIII, a black-tie boxing fund-raiser, will be held
tonight at the World Congress Center. Joe Frazier, Michael Spinks
and Mills Lane will be among those in attendance. Five fights are
on the card, headlined by WBC Continental Americas light
heavyweight champion Napoleon Tagoe (18-1) of Atlanta against Ray
Berry (17-2-1) of Sevierville, Tenn. The event, which benefits
inner-city youths, is sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Akinwande returns
</P>
<P>
   Henry Akinwande, ranked as the WBA's No. 1 contender, fights for
the first time in 15 months Saturday when he meets unknown Reynaldo
Minus of the Bahamas in Minneapolis. Akinwande was to meet
Holyfield June 6, 1998, but the fight was canceled when Akinwande
tested positive for hepatitis B. Holyfield has said he would fight
Akinwande in his next defense if he defeats Lewis, possibly in
South Africa. Akinwande took a blood test in December that came
back negative.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis responds
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he was amused by Holyfield's prediction of a
third-round knockout. ``I fail to see the realism in that,'' Lewis
said from his camp in the Pocono mountains in Pennsylvania.
``Evander Holyfield never knocks anybody out in three rounds. But
it's interesting that he's making predictions for the first time.
He says he's going to come straight at me, which is great. That
will make it an easier fight for me. He'll be right there to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
