<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LATIN AMERICA SPECIALIST'S BOOK CATCHES CLINTON'S ATTENTION
 &HT;    200&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton spent part of his long weekend at
a Utah ski resort consumed by the ruminations of Emory University
Latin America specialist Robert Pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton read Pastor's ``Integration with Mexico,'' a treatise on
the need for formalizing what has become one of the most
complicated and comprehensive bilateral relationships in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is, number one, to help people understand that we
are part of a larger region, North America, and that this region
accounts for the largest share of our trade in the world,'' Pastor
explained in a telephone interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He argues in his book for the creation of a permanent North
American Secretariat, made up of government officials and private
citizens from Canada, the United States and Mexico, to devote
fulltime policy attention to emerging issues in the multi-faceted
and often vexing relationship among the three countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``An inter-governmental organization is necessary at this
time,'' said Pastor. ''There's nothing like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House had no comment Tuesday on whether Clinton, who
visited Mexico last month, had embraced the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I hope so,'' said Pastor. ''That would be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tapped the former Carter administration aide as his
choice for U.S. ambassador to Panama in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination fell prey, however, to the opposition of Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C. Now chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, Helms still blames Pastor for policies that will result
in the handing over of the 85-year-old Panama Canal to Panama at
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Internet marketer Amazon.com sells Pastor's book for $8.95 and
ranks it number 981,468 on its in-house best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   For Pastor's latest thinking, though, readers will have to wait
until this summer's release of his newest effort, ``A Century's
Journey: How the Great Powers Shape the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastor was hammering out the final chapter Tuesday afternoon _
and facing a Wednesday morning deadline for delivery to his
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
