<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Robinson takes plea on solicitation charge
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The attorney for Falcons Pro Bowl free safety Eugene
Robinson accepted a plea bargain Tuesday in Miami that will allow
the player to enter a pre-trial diversion program that could result
in dismissal of Robinson's charge of solicitation on the eve of
Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 35, did not appear Tuesday morning in county court for
his arraignment on the misdemeanor charge of soliciting oral sex
Jan. 30 from an undercover police officer, but his case is all but
resolved anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, one of about 25 people arrested the night before Super
Bowl XXXIII in a prostitution sting operation in Miami, will not
have to go to trial. But he must take an HIV test and enroll in an
AIDS awareness program near his home in Woodinville, Wash., outside
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he complies, . . . essentially we will dismiss the charge,
as long officials in Seattle verify that the programs there are
similar to what we have here,'' said Don Ungurait, spokesman for
the Florida state attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney's offer is contingent upon proof that
Robinson had not been charged previously with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Pro Bowl cornerback Ray Buchanan will have arthroscopic surgery
today to help re-attach a ligament that tore partially loose in the
back of his shoulder last season. . . . More than a dozen Falcons
officials traveled to Greenville, S.C., on Tuesday to inspect the
campus of Furman University, where training camp is scheduled to
begin July 29. . . . Former Vikings defensive tackle Jason Fisk, an
unrestricted free agent, visited team officials Tuesday afternoon,
but he appears likely to accept a substantial offer from Tennessee,
where he probably would start. . . . Former Redskins defensive end
Rich Owens, who missed last season with a torn anterior cruciate
knee ligament, might visit in the next week. He already has been to
Miami. . . . If Tony Martin's trial on five counts of money
laundering and one count of conspiracy is delayed until next year,
Atlanta officials say they might be interested in bringing back the
wide receiver whom they waived Friday. . . . The agent for former
Minnesota and Jacksonville defensive end Fernando Smith, whom the
Falcons courted last season, has told general manager Harold
Richardson that his client would like to play in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
