<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4926 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDWEB-LIFEBEAT-ART-N     03-02 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDWEB-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WWW.AM I OK.COM?
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a fanciful, color illustration of a man looking worriedly
at a computer screen. The illustration, in Adobe Illustrator
format, is available in minutes via e-mail by calling Joe Applegate
at 212-499-3342 or graphics assistant William Gonzalez at 499-3355.
 By STEPHEN G. REED 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, there was a brief fling with a prostitute. Then, a month
later, a flu-like illness.
</P>
<P>
   For one man, that's all it took to get the ball rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that he'd contracted HIV, the virus that causes AIDS,
the man went to a doctor for an expensive genetic test to detect
the virus. It came back negative.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he'd used a condom during sex, he didn't believe the
test. He took another. And another.
</P>
<P>
   Over many months, the man had more than 100 tests to detect HIV
antibodies, the standard test for HIV infection. He spread them out
over 30 different labs, taking as many as four or five a week.
</P>
<P>
   Because it takes time after infection for antibodies to form, he
also took many expensive tests designed to detect the virus itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the negative results rolled in, it simply solidified my
belief that I was infected with some unusual variant of the virus
that was eluding detection,'' he wrote on an HIV-related Internet
Web site called The Body. ``My obsession and fear went well beyond
excessive testing. My life, which was previously productive and
active, was reduced to surfing the Internet for information on
(HIV). Often, I would stay up all night reading about (HIV).''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the man said, he spent more than $20,000 on tests,
nearly lost his job, tried to commit suicide and had to seek
psychiatric treatment. He still gets tested, but only once every
few months. He's still negative.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Sowadsky, a counselor for the Nevada AIDS Hotline who
staffs a question-and-answer forum on the Web site, said the man's
posting is not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who take the test over and over and over, and
usually the issue isn't HIV,'' he said. ``Usually the issue is,
they've done something sexual that they're remorseful about, and
they're punishing themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Sowadsky said it's become easy for him to distinguish between
postings by people with legitimate concerns about infection and the
``worried well'' _ people at low risk who believe they're sick
despite medical evidence to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   For many such people, the Internet has become an engine driving
their fears. Loaded with medical information, including
hard-to-interpret scientific studies and vague descriptions of
general symptoms, it's a big, scary world where ``fatigue'' could
herald anything from sleep deprivation to leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   HIV may be especially fertile ground for such concerns, being
infectious, potentially fatal, and linked to activities that carry
heavy social baggage. But any message board on America Online, from
colon cancer to chronic fatigue, contains postings from people
trying to diagnose themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Message boards and Web sites exist for almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet search using the Yahoo search engine, for example,
recently turned up 42 sites mentioning chronic fatigue syndrome.
Crohn's Disease, a chronic intestinal disorder, got 37 sites.
Lupus, an inflammatory illness, was mentioned on 75 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Even highly unusual conditions, such as the inflammatory disease
Wegener's Granulomatosis, have an Internet presence.
</P>
<P>
   For people who are truly ill, and whose maladies have been
diagnosed by doctor, the Internet can be immensely helpful _ a
place of virtual support groups and up-to-date news flashes.
</P>
<P>
   For people who simply think they're sick, it can be a minefield.
</P>
<P>
   In a very general sense, people who are overly concerned about
their health are called hypochondriacs. They feel every pain
acutely and believe the worst. A muscle pull becomes kidney
disease. A swollen lymph node becomes cancer.
</P>
<P>
   True hypochondria _ a sometimes debilitating preoccupation with
health or dread of disease _ is not very common, doctors said. It's
not the same as being briefly worried about a single symptom until
it subsides, or until a doctor explains it.
</P>
<P>
   Hypochondriacs often focus on one particular problem or illness
that they believe they have. That ``illness'' may have many
symptoms. Once identified, hypochondria itself can be treated with
antidepressant medications and therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all who question a set of symptoms on the
Internet are truly hypochondriacal. They may really have a physical
problem.
</P>
<P>
   But when they've already been checked out by a doctor and given
a clean bill of health, the potential for hypochondria is there.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Parlane Reid, a psychiatrist at Sarasota Memorial Hospital's
Bayside Center for Behavioral Health in Sarasota, Fla., said
hypochondriacs do feel a need to research each perceived illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to find out about it, try to understand it, and see
what they can do to fix it,'' he said. ``My guess is that because
(the Internet) is a source of information, people are going to look
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Brownlee, chairman of the Department of Family
Medicine at the University of South Florida, said he'd rather have
educated patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a question of how well-educated they get on the
Web,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, aside from serving as a hotbed for bad
information and scams, the Internet also contains highly technical
information. Journal articles and studies, for example, rely
heavily on statistics and scientific language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Previously all this medical information was just being read by
medical professionals. It wasn't for the general public,'' said
Sowadsky. The Internet is not increasing hypochondria, he said, but
``it's making it worse for many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joel Gallant agrees. A physician at Johns Hopkins University
in Baltimore, Gallant staffs an Internet question-and-answer forum
on treating HIV.
</P>
<P>
   He gets ``worried well'' questions, too _ lots of them. Because
his focus is on HIV treatment, most of them he simply deletes. But
sometimes he uses sarcasm or even scorn to remind people that their
fears are groundless: that HIV won't go undetected by blood tests
for years, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Gallant acknowledges that the Internet can contribute to
unwarranted health panics.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have to say before the Internet there were still a huge
number of people who were what we call Tthe worried well,' '' he
said. ``I don't know that the Internet is causing this. It just
gives a forum for people and gives them access.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid took a similar stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, namely those that are hypochondriacs, (the
Internet) may make it easier for them to do that kind of
research,'' he said. ``But what those folks would probably have
done before is run down to the library and look that stuff up
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there are illnesses that are hard to pinpoint with
traditional medical testing, said Dr. Wallace Kennedy, a clinical
psychologist and professor at Florida State University.
Fibromyalgia, for example, is a little-understood ailment that
causes fatigue, muscle pains and other symptoms, and it could be
easily mistaken for hypochondria.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is, accurate diagnosis requires a doctor. If the
patient doubts the doctor, he should get a second opinion. He
shouldn't practice self-diagnosis or try to become his own
physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person needs medical advice regarding personal concerns,
that person needs to see their physician in person,'' Sowadsky
said. The Internet can be a tool if used properly, but it can't be
a substitute for medical care.
</P>
<P>
   After all, ``anyone can put anything on the Internet whether
it's true or not,'' Sowadsky said.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Stephen G. Reed writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
