<HEADLINE>
DECODE YOUR BABY'S SIGNALS
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a 200-word sidebar on baby-reading tips.
 (Eds.: Sirgay is cq.) 
 By SHARON GOLDMAN EDRY 
 c.1999 Child  
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rachel Wilson was only a few weeks old, but her parents had
already noticed that she cried every time she was exposed to loud
noise. Any loud noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was a month old, I breastfed her in front of a group
of friends and told a joke,'' says her mother, Jennifer Wilson, of
St. Paul, Minn. ``When I got to the punch line and everyone started
to laugh, Rachel turned her head away from my breast, scrunched up
her face, and began to shriek. Now, says Wilson, ``we're careful
not to startle her, and we prepare her for transitions as
thoroughly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment you bring your new baby home, you begin a dance
straight out of ``The King and I'' called ``getting to know you.''
Even though your baby can't talk, she can communicate through her
cries and her body language. She can let you know whether she's
hungry or happy, nervous or calm, sleepy or ready to play. The
trick is to learn how to decipher those cues in order to respond
appropriately to her needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't understand your baby's signals, you don't know
what her mood is at the moment or what mood she seems to be heading
toward,'' says Dr. Sirgay Sanger, a founder of the Parent Child
Center at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center in New York City.
``You need to get the drift of your baby in order to build a close
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   As you develop that intimacy, she'll learn how to encourage you
to give her more of what she wants and less of what she doesn't
want says Marilyn Segal, a developmental psychologist and dean
emerita of the Family School Center at Nova Southeastern University
in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. ``The more adept you are at reading her
cues,'' notes Segal, ``the more likely it is that she will use
those cues to initiate a response.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, as your baby grows, so does her repertoire of signals.
Here are some tips on how to read her cues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Birth to 3 Months &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   Babies are born with the ability to communicate on a very basic
level. They can convey interest or distress or tell you that they
want something. By crying, for example, a newborn could be saying,
``I'm hungry'' or ``I need comfort'': wide-open eyes and a relaxed
mouth may mean ``This is interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Most babies can also frown right after birth, and while it's
several weeks before you'll see a true smile, its obvious when an
infant brightens up and becomes alert: His eyes open wide, his
eyebrows rise, his mouth drops open, his hands and shoulders relax.
A baby in a wakeful, happy state is most receptive to new
information, Sanger says, so take advantage of this: Sing, make
faces, put up an interesting mobile for him to gaze at.
</P>
<P>
   An unhappy baby, however, may show his feelings in a variety of
ways. He may have a passive expression with slack facial muscles
and glazed eyes, showing that he wants to tune out or that there's
too much sound, fight, or activity. He may also show distress by
changing expression rapidly or breaking down into all-out crying.
The challenge is to tune in to what's making your baby feel this
way and to coax him gently out of his mood.
</P>
<P>
   By 2 to 3 months, your baby's cues become more complex. ``You'll
find emotions such as curiosity and pleasure mixed together, or
even blends of curiosity and anticipatory displeasure,'' Sanger
says. You'll be able to see these conflicting emotions in his
facial expressions. While you change his diaper and dress him for
bed, for instance, he may show interest by opening his eyes wide.
At the same time, he might be wondering if all this means playtime
is over, and he may relay his apprehension to you by knitting his
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4 to 6 Months &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   Anger, surprise, sadness, fear and joy_by the middle of your
baby's first year, she has developed several new ways to react to
her surroundings. This gives you more opportunities to understand
her personality, Sanger points out.
</P>
<P>
   Another plus: Your baby now has a longer attention span, so she
won't immediately shut down if she's overstimulated. This means
you'll have more time to distract her.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to grasp toys (and noses, glasses, hair and
earrings) is perfected at this age and lets babies show off some
new signs of happiness, says Segal. ``By doing all of these
things_such as sticking her fingers in Mommy's mouth_a baby is
saying, 'I want to play' or 'You can help me explore,''' she
explains.
</P>
<P>
   You'll notice your baby's cues have become more organized by 4
months_her body, face, mouth and eyes will communicate the same
emotion. If she's expecting something, such as a warm bottle, not
only will her wide eyes and eager face show it, but her hands will
be open and relaxed, too.
</P>
<P>
   Communication becomes easier at this stage, and you can even let
your baby know when it's her turn. If you're shaking a rattle in
front of her, stop for a moment. This gives her the chance to cue
you with a coo or to reach out a hand, encouraging you to continue
the game. ``By dropping the pitch of your voice, moving your head
and hands, or becoming quiet you can elicit a smile or sounds from
your baby,'' explains Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   If she doesn't react, this may be a sign that she's had enough
and would like you to stop shaking the rattle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 7 to 12 Months &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   Your baby comes a long way during the last months of his first
year. He'll begin to look to you for reassurance and approval and
may point whine, or smile to get your attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can really begin to see a greater variety of emotional
expressions,'' says Segal. ``As your baby grows, you'll continually
see more differentiated cues.'' Your little one may display some
new emotions like boredom, shame, confidence and wariness. As he
begins to explore his world through crawling and walking, wariness
is very important, Sanger explains. He will hesitate while he
assesses a situation, which helps to keep him out of danger.
</P>
<P>
   Babies also begin to blend more emotions in complex combinations
as they approach their first birthday. Your child may smile happily
but seem fleetingly fearful or shy as he tries to reassure himself
in an unfamiliar situation, such as a loud party.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 months, hell learn to maneuver his facial muscles better
and will raise his eyebrows to ask a question or flirt by wrinkling
his nose.
</P>
<P>
   Your baby's cues may become more like an older child's as well.
If he wants to disengage from something, he might shake his head
from side to side or scissor his arms. And his signals may have
different meanings, too: The word no, for example, might mean ``I
don't like what's happening'' or ``Give me time to figure this
out.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're not sure what that no means, watch and wait _you'll
come to understand his message as he uses more familiar signals.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR: Baby Reading Tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ Take time to observe your baby. This will help you figure out
what he's trying to communicate, and then you can decide on an
appropriate response.
</P>
<P>
   _ Watch closely to see what mood he's heading toward. Look at
his face specially his eyebrows, cheeks, and mouth-for clues.
Raised cheeks and a tongue sticking out of the middle of his mouth
may signal joy, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Look for early warning signs of distress. Your baby's eyebrows
will draw together, the corners of his mouth will pull down or
sideways, his upper lip will flatten and he'll look down or narrow
his eyes. If you see these signals, try to figure out what's
setting him off, such as a room that's too bright or a wet diaper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encourage playfulness by sticking out your tongue or swiveling
it from side to side; see if you get a positive reaction. But if
your baby scrunches up her face, squirms, or turns away, these are
clear signs that she's overstimulated and that you need to switch
to a calmer mode.
</P>
<P>
   _ Watch your own signals. Don't loom over your baby-remember
that you're a big object. ``Wait to be invited in,'' suggests
Sanger. ``If you enter into her space, you should do it gradually
and see whether your baby welcomes your presence with her eyes and
eyebrows.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Be a good role model. If you have fun with your baby, you're
showing him that smiling and playfulness are allowed, which
encourages communication.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SHARON GOLDMAN EDRY is a free-lance writer based in New York
City.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
