<SLUG> BC-TV-SWEEPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS RENEWS 12 SHOWS, BEGINS ADVERTISING PUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unusual gambit designed to throw its rivals off-balance,
CBS Tuesday jumped the gun by two months and announced it has
renewed 12 of its most popular shows for next season and will begin
selling advertising slots on those shows immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Customarily, networks do not announce show renewals until May,
and then begin to sell time to advertisers in what is known as the
``upfront'' season. But CBS Television president Leslie Moonves
said Tuesday the network has decided this year, ``Why wait till May
when we know what we're going to be doing?''
</P>
<P>
   Top executives at NBC and ABC, in separate telephone conference
calls Tuesday with TV writers, indicated they have no plans to
follow suit. NBC Entertainment president Scott Sassa expressed
skepticism that a change in traditional ad-buying patterns would be
succesful, and ABC Entertainment president Jamie Tarses insisted
``there is no advantage to making an announcement'' on shows this
early.
</P>
<P>
   But Moonves is clearly confident his tactic will separate CBS
from the pack and be a magnet for advertisers. In fact, he
predicted double-digit increases in ad rates for CBS, which is the
top-rated network this season. ``We're now the prettiest girl in
town in terms of our ability to sell'' advertising, Moonves
boasted.
</P>
<P>
   There are potential flaws in CBS's strategy, however. While
ahead of NBC, ABC, and Fox in both households and total viewers so
far this year, CBS's older demographic is markedly less attractive
to Madison Avenue _ and consequently less able to command premium
ad rates _ than the younger-skewing viewership of its rival
networks. It is unlikely that many advertisers intent on capturing
young viewers will choose to steer dollars to CBS because the
network has its program lineup in place earlier. Even though
Moonves said CBS has enlarged its audience among viewers aged 18 to
49, the demographic deemed most desirable by advertisers, many of
the shows renewed Tuesday appeal largely to older viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The shows CBS renewed Tuesday are its Monday-night comedy lineup
of ``Cosby,'' ``King of Queens,'' ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' and
``Becker''; ``60 Minutes'' and its spinoff, ``60 Minutes II,''
along with its other newsmagazine, ``48 Hours''; three hit dramas,
``Touched by an Angel,'' ``Nash Bridges,'' and ``JAG,'' plus ``Kids
Say the Darndest Things'' and ``Candid Camera.'' Moonves said
``Walker, Texas Ranger'' and ``Chicago Hope'' are not on the list
because of ``contractual situations,'' but indicated those shows
will return as well.
</P>
<P>
   As for NBC, which is expected to win the Februrary sweeps that
ends Thursday, Sassa expressed satisfaction in the performance of
the network's new hit drama ``Providence'' and such high-rated
movies as ``Alice in Wonderland'' and ``The '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   He said some NBC shows are sure bets to return: ``Dateline,''
``Frasier,'' ``ER,'' ``Just Shoot Me,'' ``Law and Order,'' ``3rd
Rock from the Sun.'' However, Sassa said it is too soon to say
whether perenially-endangered ``Homicide'' will return next season.
While praising the show, he noted that its ratings have been ``a
little soft'' this year, and indicated the fate of ``Homicide''
hinges on the quality of other shows NBC has in development.
</P>
<P>
   Another show that has been a critical favorite, ABC's ``NYPD
Blue,'' will temporarily be replaced in the next month by a new
drama, ``Strange World.'' ABC Entertainment chairman Stu Bloomberg
said the network didn't want to run ``NYPD Blue'' repeats because
``We thought it would be a little peculiar to have repeats with
Jimmy Smits in them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
