<HEADER>
A4935 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NYMETS-COX     03-02 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NYMETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mets aim for the top of NL East
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ To Mike Piazza, the view is remarkably
the same from the East as it was throughout his years on the West
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's been saying for the last 10 years that this is the
season they're going to knock the Braves off,'' Piazza said. ``And
they never do. The Braves always win.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the New York Mets, who have been 28 games over .500 the
past two seasons and finished a combined 31 games behind Atlanta.
This winter, the front office had had about enough. After spending
$163 million on free agents during the offseason, club CEO Fred
Wilpon arrived in Florida saying he would be ``very disappointed''
if the team didn't break their 10-year playoff drought this season.
When manager Bobby Valentine welcomed Piazza to camp with a kiss on
the cheek, was he just happy to see him? Or was he sending him on a
holy mission?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the axiom is that pitching wins games, the Braves still
have the best pitching,'' New York general manager Steve Phillips
said. ``But I think we have a better team (than 1998). Now, you
have to play 162 games. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were underpowered last season (136 homers ranking 12th
in the NL), remarkably slow (a major-league low of 62 stolen bases)
and remained an arm or two shy on the pitching staff. Bobby Bonilla
and Robin Ventura (33 HR and 136 RBIs last year) were added to
strengthen the offense. Rickey Henderson, whose AL-high 66 steals
surpassed the Mets team total, will play left field. Armando
Benitez and his 98-mph fastball joins the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' rotation _ Al Leiter, Rick Reed, Bobby Jones, Masato
Yoshii and Hideo Nomo _ might be suspect, but every other aspect of
the roster has been improved. Since the 1994 strike, only one NL
East team _ the 1997 Florida Marlins _ was realigned enough to
challenge the Braves, and that team eliminated the Braves on the
way to a World Series title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this year as 1997 almost,'' Marlins alumnus Leiter said,
``with the additions they've made here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely like our team,'' Phillips said. ``We won 88
games last year, but we weren't scoring enough runs. Of 162 games,
108 were decided by three runs or less. Our pitchers didn't have
any margin for error. That really showed in the last five games.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Mets closed out the schedule 0-5, even as they
remained alive for a playoff spot until the season's final out. The
cash the franchise has laid out _ the payroll will come in between
$65 million-$70 million _ heightens hopes, as well as the pressure
on management.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, entering his third full season with the Mets, has
managed 1,541 games without taking a team into the postseason, the
longest streak by any manager to debut in the last 40 years, which
is as far back at the Elias Sports Bureau researched. And Phillips,
his resume spotted by last year's sexual-harassment case, is in
deeper jeopardy than Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we look better on paper,'' Piazza said.
``But we still have to come together on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
