<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-03-COX     03-02 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS GRAPPLES WITH Y2K PROBLEMS
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON The millennium bug took center stage in Congress
Tuesday as lawmakers sought to respond to the risk that computers
will fail on Jan. 1, while warning against either public apathy or
doomsday scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   A special Senate panel on the Year 2000 problem was unable to
find any ``data to suggest that the United States will experience a
nationwide social or economic collapse.'' But, it concluded, ``some
disruptions will occur and that in some cases (they) may be
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel's 160-page report ``exposes the vulnerability of
nearly every major sector of the economy,'' said Sen. Robert
Bennett, R-Utah. ``Progress is being made, but in various key
sectors, efforts remediation for Y2K have fallen behind,'' the
panel chairman noted.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the bug could set off civil unrest in poor
countries, retard economic growth in Asia, Latin America and
Africa, and disrupt global trade in oil and other key commodities,
the panel warned.
</P>
<P>
   While it saw only a low chance of an accidental nuclear weapons
launch, missile systems in other nations could malfunction and
terrorists could take advantage of weakened security.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. military may experience some minor disruptions, but
its mission-critical, war-fighting capability will not be
compromised,'' Bennett said after releasing the report.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a technological glitch. On Jan. 1, many computers
could fail to distinguish the year 2000 from 1900 because of a
two-digit dating system embedded in both software and hardware. As
a result, many old systems that haven't been debugged could falter
or spew out bad data.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the panel had been unable to ``conclusively
determine how extensive the Y2K disruptions will be.''
</P>
<P>
   One major concern, the report noted, is that 90 percent of
doctors haven't fixed their computers and could temporarily lose
medical records. Smaller hospitals also may not be ready for
possible shutdowns of such critical devices as dialysis machines.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of major Y2K lawsuits, the report also noted, had
shadowed the panel's work from its inception. Bennett said he will
soon hold hearings on the litigation issue _ which according to
some estimates could exceed $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he urged consumers to keep detailed financial records
because of the potential of disruption in the banking system.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the Senate sought to ease the problem for small
businesses by setting up a $500 million loan program.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, approved 99-0, would require the Small Business
Administration to guarantee loans for businesses trying to fix
their own computers or threatened by the Y2K problems of their
suppliers, customers or financial institutions. It is expected to
easily pass in the House and be signed into law by President
Clinton before April 30.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo., the measure's chief sponsor, said
``the outlook for small business is not good'' because ``many small
companies have not yet begun to realize how much of a problem Y2K
failures could be for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   Bennett and Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., the panel's vice-chair,
held an hour-long classified briefing for about 40 senators. It
focused on the threat posed by the Y2K issue to nuclear
installations in Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   Food industry representatives assured Bennett and Dodd at a
hearing that they would have adequate stocks on hand Jan. 1. ``We
believe ... unless there is widespread hoarding or excessive
stockpiling, Jan. 1, 2000, will be a routine shopping day,'' said
Michael Heschel of the Kroger supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of Defense John Hamre told the House Government
Reform Committee that, despite numerous Y2K problems that have yet
to be solved, the Pentagon ``will continue operations and maintain
military readiness before, during, and after 1 January 2000.'
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
