<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAX-EMAIL-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY'S SERVICE CONVERTS FAXES TO E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
 (mk) 
 By RON TRUJILLO   
 Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ Fast-moving business executives,
international globetrotters and out-of-the-office road warriors
could benefit from a free high-tech service that converts faxes
into e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Barbara start-up CallWave could connect more than 1
million computer users to its FaxWave service, delivering fax
documents _ from critical contracts to detailed maps _ through
e-mail messages nationwide by the end of the year, said Dave
Hofstatter, co-founder and executive vice president of CallWave.
</P>
<P>
   CallWave's FaxWave allows computer users around-the-clock access
to data anywhere. FaxWave also eliminates the need to toggle
between the fax machine and phone, saving at least $250 for a
fax-dedicated second line, said company spokeswoman Antonia Inman.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of consumers are thinking about a second line, but it's
expensive,'' said Inman, adding that 29 million computer users
nationwide operate with a single phone line. ``There's an enormous
market.''
</P>
<P>
   The company _ at www.callwave.com _ is currently conducting
private trials, with a national release by the end of March,
Hofstatter said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer response ``has been overwhelming,'' he said. The
connections ``are instantaneous, it's very real time. It's the same
experience as sending a fax to a machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers Dave and Nancy Oster of Santa Barbara agree, adding
that they sent data from their fax at home to their FaxWave e-mail
account in less than 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so cool and really easy to use,'' said Nancy Oster, who
has telephone land lines for their computer, fax and phones.
``We're paying a significant amount for those three phone lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, computer-users must have e-mail access _ a cost of at
least $15 per month _ to link with the free FaxWave service.
</P>
<P>
   CallWave issues customers individual fax lines, Hofstatter said.
</P>
<P>
   CallWave will profit from additional fee options _ such as local
or toll-free phone numbers or pager services _ while banner
advertising will also help raise revenue for the 6-month-old
start-up, Hofstatter said. But customers' fax numbers will not be
released, an increasing concern and problem with no-charge services
on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   CallWave is benefiting from the fast-paced Internet, as more
companies compete with new and improved services, said GTE
spokesman Mike Raydo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already know there are going to be a lot of changes from
the Internet,'' said Raydo, adding that GTE offers Internet
Protocol Fax, a similar service. The consumer services are also
money-making opportunities, compared to the low-growth phone
service. ``We know there's a lot of technology out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And eventually, e-mail could eliminate fax machines, a more than
30-year-old technology, industry leaders said. But that is not
likely to happen any time soon: Fax machine sales have climbed from
about 3.4 million in 1993 to almost 6 million units last year,
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   (Ron Trujillo writes for the Santa Barbara, Calif., News-Press.
This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
