<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, March 3. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
DRY ARIZONA (Phoenix) - Arizona is having its driest winter in
recorded history, water experts say. Runoff for the Salt River
Project is 17 percent of normal, there's no snow on ground and
hardly any has fallen all winter. What's happening? La nina, of
course. It has broad implications for the summer fire season. By
MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
IRIDIUM (Phoenix) - Iridium LLC, the world's first global phone
network dreamed up by three Motorola engineers working in Chandler,
is struggling to sign up enough customers. Since the service
launched in November, Iridum has had trouble getting handsets and
pagers to its customers and building a fully-trained sales network.
Iridium warned Tuesday that it will likely fail to meet the minimum
sales and subscriber targets for the first quarter of 1999 that
were set in the company's $800 million credit agreement. By REBECCA
ROLWING. Story will move in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LAMB-FRAUD (Phoenix) - When the driver for Always Trucking in New
Jersey knocked one car into another last year, the company tried to
place a claim with Jim Wright at Writer's Direct Insurance in
Miami. ``We called their number and all we got was people speaking
Spanish,'' said Mike Baker, a manager of the All Ways office in the
town of New Brunswick. ``Finally we had the Miami police check the
address. It turned out to be an old, abandoned factory.'' Now
federal prosecutors say Jim Wright was an alias for J. Brian Lamb,
the Chandler, Ariz., justice of the peace who was indicted last
week on charges of selling more than $1.5 million in bogus
insurance policies to truckers looking for a bargain. By JERRY
KAMMER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BARBIE-ART (Phoenix) - Barbie turns 40 in a week. Here's a
recollection of Barbie: the life a kid yearned for, the look she'd
never have. With PHOTO. By LAURI NOTARO. With BARBIE TALKS AND
BARBIE-TIMELINE. Stories moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ANIMATION-ART (Phoenix) - Motocross Madness, published by
Microsoft, is on its way to selling a million copies and has been
named racing game of the year by two computer gaming magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite an honor,'' said Earl Jarred, CEO of Rainbow
Studios, a Phoenix animation studio. In the ever-quickening pace of
computer animation, there is no time to rest on your 3D laurels.
Today's cutting-edge becomes next month's industry standard. With
PHOTO. By JONATHAN SIDENER. Story moved in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CAKE-DECOR (Phoenx) - Cake decorating can seem as intimidating as
freeway construction: underpasses, overpasses, cloverleafs,
offramps. Don't picture the sagging tiers that Sleeping Beauty's
fairy godmothers whipped up in mortal fashion. Picture how they
looked after a wave of a magic wand. Includes recipie. With
CAKE-TIPS and CAKE-SIDE. By BARBARA YOST. Stories moved in the
``D'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
