<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SONY-GAME-MACHINE-550     03-02 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONY-GAME-MACHINE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONY LOOKS TO DUPLICATE SUCCESS WITH PLAYSTATION II 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Making what could be a quantum leap in the march to wed
consumer electronics to computers and the Internet, the Sony Corp.
on Tuesday introduced the widely anticipated second generation of
its hit Playstation video-game console.
</P>
<P>
   Sony, the leading consumer electronics company, has high hopes
for new console and has bet more than $250 million on it. The
machine, which the designers are calling Playstation II for now, is
far more powerful than the current model, with a 128-bit
microprocessor compared with the current generation of 64-bit
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Playstation II has markedly increased graphics abilities and
speed, providing greater realism in video imagery. It can produce
three-dimensional characters of the same quality as those seen in
the movie ``Toy Story.'' It can connect users to the Internet and a
personal computer. It can play music and movies using CD-ROM's and
the more cutting-edge DVD's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just an extension of the line of game machines,''
Ken Kutaragi, executive vice president of Sony Computer
Entertainment Inc., Sony's video-game business, was quoted as
saying by the newspaper Nihon Keizai Shimbun in an article
published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential selling point for Playstation II is that the
3,000 software titles made for the classic Playstation will work on
the new machine. That makes Playstation II the first video-game
player that allows users to play games designed for its
predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   While Sony did not announce a suggested price, the cost of
developing Playstation II means it will probably take a few years
for the company to start making money from the machine.
Playstations generally sell for about $130 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sony said it was likely to start selling the machines in Japan
by next winter and to start selling them in the United States by
fall 2000.
</P>
<P>
   With Playstation II, Sony is essentially betting that it can
take the computer out of the desk-top box in which it currently
resides and put it onto the television screen, where Sony has long
been a dominant force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the next-generation Playstation will become one of
the pillars of Sony's business,'' Nobuyuki Idei, the president of
Sony, said at a news conference held to announce the design of the
new machine.
</P>
<P>
   Playstation is already a major contributor to the company's
financial well-being. Sony Computer, which is largely the
Playstation business, accounted for 26.5 percent of Sony's
operating profits in the first half of this fiscal year, according
to Nikko Securities Smith Barney (Japan) Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   The business has been a phenomenal success, essentially
redefining the home-video game market and far exceeding Sony's
wildest expectations. More than 50 million Playstations have been
sold since the product was introduced in 1994, and software
developers, which are critical to the success of game consoles,
have embraced it.
</P>
<P>
   That widespread acceptance makes Sony a formidable contender in
the $15 billion video-game business, where Sony competes with the
Nintendo Co. and Sega Enterprises Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts expect the torrid pace of Playstation's sales to
taper off in a year, severely decreasing profit unless Playstation
II duplicates its predecessor's success.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Moreover, Sony is not the first to offer a more powerful machine
than the current 64-bit models. Sega announced last month that it
would start selling its next-generation machine, called Dreamcast,
in the United States next fall. That machine, which also features a
128-bit processor and can connect to the Internet, is expected to
sell for $200 to $250.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sony has to transform Playstation into something more than a
game console, and they know it,'' said Koichiro Chiwata, a consumer
electronics analyst at Nikko Smith Barney. ``It has to be
revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiwata and other analysts have said that the 128-bit computer
processor that Sony developed together with the Toshiba Corp.
probably exceeds the performance of the Intel Corp.'s famed Pentium
III processor, based on a demonstration at a recent trade show.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, Sony may be trying to establish a new
standard, although it denied Tuesday that it was trying to take on
Intel.
</P>
<P>
   But Sony did boast that the abilities of the Playstation II
processor exceeded those of leading personal computers and the best
graphics work stations, allowing previously unattained levels of
sophistication and realism.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the processor, together with other components,
would be able to simulate physical attributes like gravity,
friction and mass as well as materials like water, wood and gas _
and how characters and objects think, act and behave.
</P>
<P>
   A chip made by LSI Logic will enable Playstation II to use the
same software as the existing Playstation.
</P>
<P>
   Sony shares fell 30 yen in Tokyo Tuesday, to 8,690. In the
United States, Sony American depository receipts fell 12.5 cents,
to $73.875.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1812EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
