<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4948 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QALEARN-COX     03-02 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QALEARN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q and A on the influence of computers in education
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. _ Educators from kindergarten through
college spend hundreds of millions of dollars a year on computers
to enhance learning. But how well does it work? In one of the first
conferences focused on that question, more than 80 educators are
meeting through today at Wake Forest University in Winston-Salem,
N.C. Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Chris Burritt talked
to Craig Runde, director of the university's International Center
for Computer Enhanced Learning, sponsor of the first Congress on
the Impact of Technology on Learning.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Explain the growing interest in assessing how computers
influence learning.
</P>
<P>
   A: I think in some respects we are fairly early on in this
investigation, but the timeliness of looking at the question is
very ripe. The question being put to administrators is very
important because the investments are large. Are these going to be
cost effective investments? They are quite unsure.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are universities investing in technology?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most of the decisions have been marketing driven as opposed
to proven effective in learning. Could they get the benefit in
recruiting students if they are seen as a high-tech school? The
administrators of educational institutions would like nothing
better than to get a report that says these are the areas where
technology makes a qualitative difference in learning outcomes. But
that report does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is that research being collected?
</P>
<P>
   A: A number of people are trying to assess whether these
different approaches provide measurable improvements. But that very
term ``measurable improvements'' is a little slippery. How would
you measure that improvement? Is it better grades? Is it better
results on standardized tests? Is it some sort of subjective
measure of critical thinking skills? Is it measured by greater
amounts of communication between faculty and students? How can you
isolate it in such a way so as to determine whether it was a
technology factor as opposed to another factor?
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the types of technology investments?
</P>
<P>
   A: It runs into millions of dollars for a school system or a
college. You have the need to improve the computer network and the
support services for computing. And you need to provide access to
everybody, either with a laptop for everyone or an expanded lab.
Regardless of how it is done, it is a significant financial
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How widespread is the interest?
</P>
<P>
   A: I would not call it a rage yet, but I would definitely say
there is a great deal of interest in the area. In higher education,
there are probably fewer than 100 institutions which made the
investment. In kindergarten through 12th grade, a small percentage
of the total has jumped in. But there are large numbers of other
schools which are looking closely at what is happening.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are some common uses of computers in learning?
</P>
<P>
   A: One is using technology as a communications tool to expand
and enhance communications among students, faculty and outside
visitors in the class. This is where you would have e-mail
discussion forums. Outside of class, either in a preparatory
fashion for the next class or in a follow-up from the last class,
you have an electronic discussion that extends the discussion that
took place in class. The other common use is to provide access to
material content. This is where you would have students go out to
relevant Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How about in the public schools, kindergarten through the
12th grade?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are more types of educational software in the K-12
rooms. You have more software where students are doing exercises on
the computer. There's probably less emphasis on communications
because of concerns about the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
