<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4956 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-COMPANY-LADN     03-02 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-COMPANY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALVIN AILEY COMPANY SHOWCASES FOUR DECADES OF DANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: ``Tonight'' refers to Wednesday, March 3). 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Hitting the big 4-0 needn't be the prologue to a
full-blown midlife crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, according to Judith Jamison, is to just keep doing
what you've always done before.
</P>
<P>
   ``So in this 40th anniversary (season), I did what I normally
do,'' says the artistic director of Alvin Ailey American Dance
Theater. ``Commission new works, bring back old works, have company
revivals and generally spread the word that dance can be something
that can affect you deeply inside emotionally and really change
your perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by phone from a friend's house in Philadelphia,
one-third of the way through a 19-city U.S. tour, Jamison's words
tumble out in great gusts of unpremeditated enthusiasm. Still, her
modestly stated goals don't quite do justice to what she and her
31-member company will be up to this week at the Ahmanson Theatre,
where they'll open a six-performance engagement tonight.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the company will be presenting the L.A. premieres
of two highly anticipated works, Jamison's autobiographical ``Echo:
Far From Home,'' and ``Lettres d'Amour,'' a sexually charged work
about isolation in modern society by the French-born choreographer
known as Redha.
</P>
<P>
   ``Echo'' makes its local debut at 8 p.m. Saturday and 3 p.m.
Sunday in a program that also will include three Ailey signature
works, ``Streams,'' ``Cry'' and ``Revelations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lettres d'Amour'' will be performed at 8 tonight and Friday,
along with ``Revelations'' and a new production of Geoffrey
Holder's ``The Prodigal Prince,'' a pageantlike work inspired by
the life and art of Haitian primitive painter and Voudoun (or
voodoo) priest Hector Hypolite.
</P>
<P>
   Two other performances, at 8 p.m. Thursday and 2 p.m. Saturday,
will be devoted entirely to ``Ailey Classics,'' a full-evening
lineup of excerpts of works by company founder Alvin Ailey, who
died in 1989 at age 58. Highlights include ``Memoria,'' to music by
Keith Jarrett, ``Night Creature'' and ``The Mooche'' to music by
Duke Ellington and ``A Song for You'' to the music of Leon Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you see, there's the old and the new, there's the veteran
and the emerging, and within that company is also that quotient of
diversity,'' Jamison says.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison says ``Letters d'Amour'' is a work very much in keeping
with Alvin Ailey's tradition of seeking out experimental,
postmodern works that will stretch her dancers. Although Ailey
himself created nearly 80 ballets during his lifetime, he believed
in developing an eclectic repertory of works by other modern dance
pioneers as well as up-and-coming innovators. (At present, there
are some 170 works by 63 choreographers in the company's
portfolio.)
</P>
<P>
   Set to music by Apocalyptica, Arvo Part, Einstrurzende Neubauten
and Pieter Bourke, among others, ``Lettres d'Amour'' is an overtly
erotic piece danced by men in long, flowing capes and women in
provocatively slashed gowns. At the work's U.S. premiere last fall,
one New York reviewer described it as ``glorious trash,'' while
another approvingly noted its ``imaginative decadence.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jamison says she doesn't read reviews, she's quick to
respond when it's suggested that ``Lettres d'Amour'' amounts to a
dance critic's guilty pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very interesting, I was talking to somebody and they
said, `Oh, but this is so new, isn't this a European way of
moving?' What are you talking about, a European way of moving?
Where do I live, you know what I'm saying? What is this country I'm
in?
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that Redha has a vocabulary that is very close to
the earth. It's very, very weighty. And he also incorporates
popular dance. And the dancers love that. They love the challenge
of being able to combine his ballet background _ which is what they
do with every ballet that they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamison, 56, describes ``Echo: Far From Home'' as ``a very
personal statement, as are most choreographies,'' about her own
evolution as a dancer, dovetailing with the historical and cultural
odyssey undertaken by African-Americans. Against a backdrop of
oversized paintings depicting scenes from the Middle Passage, the
dancers represent Jamison, her parents, a love interest and various
mentors, including a regal figure in a flowing gown who might be
Ailey himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love putting men in long, draped things that move, and
jewels,'' Jamison says, ``because men in history have been the ones
that dressed! So I loved putting this gorgeous man, (dancer) Edward
Franklin, in a long kind of sarong, with one of my earrings on, and
a large bracelet, and a kind of stance as a guru and a mentor and a
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's Jamison doing the leading, moving forward while
looking back.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did (this year) was to stop and say, `Thank you,
Alvin! Thank you for thinking of this in the first place!' And that
we continue, and everything is all right.'' &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
