<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CARJACK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES UPHOLD FEDERAL CARJACKING LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled Tuesday that a carjacker
cannot escape federal prosecution by arguing that he meant his
victims no harm so long as they complied with his demand for their
car.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision marked a victory for the Justice
Department, which urged the justices to interpret broadly the
federal Carjacking Correction Act, to cover a wide range of
instances in which thieves steal cars under threat of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The law was passed in 1996 following a rash of violent
carjackings.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal defense lawyers assailed the court's broad reading of a
law they say is designed to trap only the most vicious car thieves.
</P>
<P>
   In its 7-2 ruling, the court rejected arguments that the 1996
statute prohibits only those automobile thefts in which the thief
plans to harm the driver even if he surrenders his keys. Justice
John Paul Stevens, writing for the court's majority, said the law
should be read broadly to trap also those carjackers who intend
primarily to steal automobiles but who would harm motorists if they
put up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprising move, the court's two most unflinching
law-and-order justices _ Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas _ said
the court misread the law, which outlaws carjackings committed
``with the intent to cause death or serious bodily harm.'' Scalia
and Thomas said the court should have overturned the convictions of
New York carjackers Francois Holloway and his armed accomplice
because their primary intent was to steal cars, not to injure
motorists.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers called the
court's broad interpretation of the carjacking statute improper and
found itself in the unusual position of supporting Scalia and
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legislatures should be held responsible for the words they use
when they write laws,'' said NACDL spokesman Jack King.
</P>
<P>
   A federal district court jury in eastern New York found Holloway
and his accomplice guilty in 1996 of three carjackings in which
they accosted motorists, displayed a gun and threatened to shoot
the drivers if they did not surrender their car keys. The
accomplice, Vernon Lennon, testified that he and Holloway planned
to steal the cars without harming the drivers but that they would
have shot the motorists had they given the thieves a ``hard time.''
</P>
<P>
   On appeal, the carjackers argued that the federal law did not
apply to their crime because they intended not to injure the
drivers but simply to take their automobiles. The 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in New York rejected that argument, saying
Congress intended the law to prevent a wide gamut of carjackings.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, agreeing with the 2nd Circuit, said a
carjacker who is willing to shoot a driver for failing to hand over
car keys is in violation of the law's prohibition on violent
intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether a person who points a gun at a driver,
having decided to pull the trigger if the driver does not comply
with a demand for the car keys, possesses the intent, at that
moment, to seriously harm the driver,'' Stevens wrote. ``In our
view, the answer to that question does not depend on whether the
driver immediately hands over the keys or what the offender decides
to do after he gains control over the car. At the relevant moment,
the offender plainly does have the forbidden intent.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalia, in an unusually personal dissent, said the specific
words of the law indicate that Congress intended the statute to
apply only to the especially heinous carjackings in which the
criminal intends to seriously injure the driver even if the keys
are surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a friend whose father was killed, and whose mother was
nearly killed, in just such an incident _ after the car had already
been handed over,'' wrote Scalia, who provided no further details
of the episode. ``It is not at all implausible that Congress should
direct its attention to the particularly savage sort of carjacking
_ where killing the driver is part of the intended crime.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
