<HEADER>
A4969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-MEAT-ADVICE-     03-02 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-MEAT-ADVICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE YOU HUGGED YOUR BUTCHER TODAY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: With AMERICAN-MEAT) 
(mk) 
 By BRUCE AIDELLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Aidells has a lot to say about making the most of modern
beef. Here are some words of advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``TALK TO THE MEAT GUY'': The single most important factor in
determining tenderness is the part of the carcass that the meat
comes from. Talk to the butcher (even supermarkets have them) and
find out what the label won't tell you. The most tender cuts come
from the sirloin, top loin (New York strip steak) and tenderloin
(fillet). The Agriculture Department (USDA) grade is less important
today; most supermarket beef is choice grade, but many chains do
not even buy graded beef.
</P>
<P>
   MATCH MEAT AND METHOD: The second most important factor for
flavor is the cooking method. Decide on that first, and then buy
the meat. All lean meats cook quicker than traditionally dry-aged
beef once did. If you intend to grill or broil, look for a tender
cut. If you plan a long, slow, moist cooking, like braising or
stewing, look for chuck, brisket or short ribs.
</P>
<P>
   SALT IS A FRIEND: Forget the old theory that salting draws out
moisture and makes meat dry and tough. Salt is the most important
seasoning for meat, accentuating the beefy taste in meats that are
just not as flavorful as they once were. In addition, it brings
together a number of chemical reactions and promotes a nice, tasty
crust.
</P>
<P>
   WIELD A HEAVY SKILLET: Use old-fashioned, well-seasoned cast
iron skillets for panbroiling or grilling. Such pans retain heat at
very high temperatures. Lighter pans cannot produce a crust to firm
up today's meat, with its high moisture content _ the beef sweats
instead of searing.
</P>
<P>
   TIME IS NOT THE ESSENCE: Meat today cooks quicker, but cooking
times don't matter so much anymore. Old cooking charts list minutes
per pound to reach the desired state of doneness, but those numbers
are no longer useful. An instant-read thermometer is a meat cook's
best friend; a digital instant-read model can give an accurate
temperature when only a quarter-inch of the tip is inserted into
meat, so it works even for thin cuts like steaks, chops and
burgers.
</P>
<P>
   GIVE IT A BREAK: Meat should also be allowed to rest after
cooking to reach the ideal state. A beef roast should be taken off
the heat when the internal temperature is 125 to 130 degrees for
medium, for instance, and beefsteaks need to reach 120 to 130
degrees to be rare. As the meat rests, it continues to cook from
the heat it has absorbed. And before cooking, bring beef to room
temperature, whether you plan to grill, braise, saute, broil or
stew; take it out of the refrigerator an hour ahead.
</P>
<P>
   SPICE TO START: To make up for the flavor that is lost in beef
bred to be less fatty, rub meat with dry mixtures of herbs and
spices and let it sit a day or two or just a few minutes before
broiling or grilling.
</P>
<P>
   DO THE TENDER THING: The only way to make tough meat tender is
to cook it slowly in liquid, as in a braise or stew. Commercial
tenderizers give meat a soggy texture and unpleasant taste; steaks
sold as ``tenderized'' have been run through a piercing machine and
have all the flavor of cardboard. Marinades will not tenderize cuts
like brisket that have a lot of connective tissue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1836EST &QL; 
