<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4970 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGANDA-GARLAND-COX     03-02 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-GARLAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daughter of university president escapes African terror
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Elizabeth Garland, the daughter of Miami (Ohio)
University President James Garland, awakened to the sounds of
grenade explosions and machine-gun fire early Monday as attackers
overran a tourist campground no more than 30 feet from where she
was staying in southeast Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Garland quickly dressed, but did not leave her tent for fear she
would be discovered, according to her father, who talked with her
Tuesday. An hour after the last grenade explosion, a camp manager
approached and called out, ``Elizabeth, are you alive?'' She
emerged to find smoldering vehicles and buildings and the body of a
person who had been burned to death, and she learned the Rwandan
Hutu attackers had abducted more than a dozen tourists. Later in
the day, eight of those tourists were dead; an American survivor
said the rebels, 100 to 150 of them, brutally hacked some victims
to death with machetes. Six tourists were rescued and taken to a
safe location.
</P>
<P>
   Garland, an anthropology Ph.D. student at the University of
Chicago, was conducting field work for her dissertation at the
Bwindi National Park, home of 320 rare mountain gorillas. She was
living in a tent on the northern edge of the park, waiting for her
permanent quarters at a nearby village to become available. Her
tent was concealed in bushes, her father said Tuesday, separated
from the main camping area by a short trail.
</P>
<P>
   That short distance saved her life, Garland, 29, told her
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said it sounded like the gunshots were just outside her
tent, and they lasted for more than two hours,'' he said. ``She
kept saying to herself, 'Please don't let them find me, please
don't let them find me...' ``
</P>
<P>
   The Miami president said his daughter ``was still pretty much in
a state of shock'' when he spoke to her shortly before noon Tuesday
after she was evacuated to nearby Kampala. But then, the full
impact of what happened didn't hit her father right away, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of what she's been through has been sinking in to
me as the day goes by,'' Garland said. ``She came close to being
killed in a horrible way. It gives me chills. It's a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Witness accounts of the incident were indeed nightmarish.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Ross, a tour operator and pilot who was born in Arkansas
but has spent years in Africa, told reporters the rebels rounded up
tourists from several jungle camps in southwestern Uganda. Ross
said he was among those taken captive, but was freed later with a
political message from the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels _ who came to Uganda after Rwanda's 1994 genocide _
marched their captives through the rain forest, where Ross said
some were hacked to death Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came across the first set of bodies. The women that we'd
been told would be escorted back had been killed on the spot. It
looks like one was raped prior to being killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he saw five bodies, and ``the ones that I saw had
their heads crushed in and deep slashes.''
</P>
<P>
   His account clashed with that of Ugandan police spokesman Eric
Naigambi, who told The Associated Press there was a shoot-out and
that the rescue operation was carried out this morning in a
mountainous rain forest made famous in the film ``Gorillas in the
Mist.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``tourists were killed in the crossfire during the rescue
operation,'' Naigambi said.
</P>
<P>
   But another Ugandan, Hussein Kivumi, manager of a rain forest
camp, said the rebels targeted Americans and Britons. ``They killed
four women and four men with knives, machetes and axes. There were
no gunshots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hutu rebels fled Rwanda after they took part in a 1994
genocide of more than 500,000 minority Tutsis and politically
moderate Hutus. The rebels are angry at Uganda for supporting the
Tutsi-dominated Rwandan government.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department spokesman James Foley said two
Americans were murdered as they were being marched away by their
captors. The remaining six victims were killed the same way, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said the victims cannot be identified until their
relatives are notified. The six released hostages were returned to
Kampala and taken to a safe location, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ugandan government did not give names or nationalities of
the dead, but said that those rescued included an American, two
British, one Canadian, one Swiss and one New Zealander.
</P>
<P>
   Garland told her father she wasn't sure of her future plans. She
had intended to spend a year in Uganda, researching her
dissertation on the impact the tourism was having on the native
people of the forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``She expressed great sorrow about the impact of this incident
on the native people in the area, for whom she has great respect,''
Garland said. ``She was concerned that the publicity over this
event would undo years of effort and would reinforce undesirable
stereotypes about Africa and her peoples.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio. The
Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1837EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
