<SLUG> BC-OSHUN-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OSHUN': WOMAN SEEKS A PLACE AMONG YORUBAN SAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Propelled by the spirited, captivating performance of
Keisha Monique Booker in the title role, the dance-drama ``Oshun''
at the Nuyorican Poets Cafe revisits the tumultuous world of
orishas, the Yoruban saints, which proved so entertaining and
memorable in the theater's 1995 production of ``Shango da Ima.''
</P>
<P>
   In the potent and rewarding ``Oshun,'' subtitled ``The Goddess
of Love,'' the focus of the West African legend told in words,
music, song and sound by David D. Wright is a strong, determined,
complex young woman who simply will not be denied her place in the
Yoruban pantheon.
</P>
<P>
   What makes these extraordinary creatures such splendid material
for drama are their imperfections. Like the Greek gods, they
bicker, battle and foment mischief. They are proud, arrogant,
greedy and covetous yet fully capable of goodness and generosity,
though Olofi, the Supreme Being, at times grows weary of their
foolish ways and is prompted to abandon them after distributing
power and knowledge among them.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Oshun (pronounced Oh-SHOON) seeks equal
status in the male council. As her story unfolds under the skilled
direction of Rome Neal in 30 lively scenes of chant, dance,
drumming, conflict and conciliation, she employs her intelligence,
wiles and courage to enhance her powers and win her place among the
orishas.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, there are encounters with the black-hooded ajes,
or witches; with the fierce Shango, who controls fire; Ogun, the
orisha of iron and warfare, and the ominous Elegba, the orisha of
the crossroads and the bearer of messages. There is an abusive
marriage to Orunmila, the orisha of divination, and the seduction
of the married Shango. Oshun is not always wise, but she is always
riveting.
</P>
<P>
   With flashing eyes, haughty demeanor, lithe, seductive body, wit
and intelligence, Ms. Booker gives a multifaceted performance that
is the key to the success of this handsome and energetic shoestring
production, with costumes by Marcel Christian, dance by Angela D.
Brown, musical direction by Vanessa A. Wright, masks by Hjordis
Linn and lighting designed by Christophe Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century after its beginning with a series of poetry
readings in the Lower East Side apartment of its executive
producer, Miguel Algarin, the Nuyorican Poets Theater, now at 236
East Third St., remains a vibrant contributor to the city's
culture.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `OSHUN: The Goddess of Love'
</P>
<P>
   By David D. Wright; directed by Rome Neal; choreography by
Angela D. Brown; musical direction by Vanessa A. Wright; costumes
by Marcel Christian; masks by Hjordis Linn; lighting by Christophe
Pierre. Presented by Miguel Algarin, executive producer, in
association with Frank Silvera Writers' Workshop, Garland Thompson,
executive director. At the Nuyorican Poets Cafe, 236 East Third
Street, East Village, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Keisha Monique Booker (Oshun), Angela Brown (Ofunile and
Eagle), Robert Turner (Elegba), Spelman M. Beaubrun (Shango) and
Henry Afro-Bradley (Obatala).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
