</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV game might make Monica, like, interesting
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs with MONICA-GAME)
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, the big night on ABC television is finally here: Monica
Lewinsky meets Barbara Walters tonight at 9 for two hours of
chit-chat.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Starr has finally relented to letting the infamous intern
rehash the relationship that almost brought down the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   All of which has us wondering what she'll actually say and what
PG words she'll choose to explain some raunchy, R-rated behavior.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good bet the L.A. resident, fluent in valley girl, will
use some of the same language she employed in the Starr report and
during her two dozen interrogations.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a good guess that you might be tired of the whole
affair. So, let's make it fun and turn it into a game _ a
family-friendly version of the frat house drinking game. Every time
Lewinsky uses certain words, follow it with a corresponding action.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
