<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY TIES: BUSH, DOLE LEAD PROSPECTIVE NOMINEES IN GOP RACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The more things change, the more they stay the
same: a Bush is edging toward a campaign for the Republican
presidential nomination, and his chief competitor may be a Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   In the six national elections beginning in 1976, a Dole or a
Bush has been on every Republican ticket. The sometimes angry,
psych-out competition between the patrician George Bush and the
hardscrabble Bob Dole was one of the most interesting _ if not
edifying _ political exercises of the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bush's son, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, and Dole's wife,
former Cabinet official Elizabeth Hanford Dole, are considering
bids for the Republican presidential nomination and have quickly
emerged in national polls as the front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the surveys and political buzz nationally and in key
states, the nomination is either Bush's or Dole's to lose as the
GOP selects a candidate for the open race to succeed President
Clinton, the Democrat who sent Bush's father into political
retirement in 1992 and buried Dole's husband three years ago in a
landslide.
</P>
<P>
   The two dominate the field _ George W. Bush with his polls and
his pledges from key Republican figures around the nation, and
Elizabeth Hanford Dole with her zoom to virtual parity in the polls
with the governor after she quit as president of the American Red
Cross to consider making the national race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between them, they have sucked almost all the oxygen out of
the Republican political atmosphere, especially Bush,'' said a top
adviser to another prospective GOP candidate. ``This race is likely
frozen between the two of them until George W. makes his first
mistake and we see how he handles it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other big question,'' the strategist said, ``is does Dole
really get in?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush signaled his intentions Tuesday with a long-anticipated
announcement in Austin, Texas, that he will soon authorize a
committee to explore a presidential candidacy and raise money. That
is expected to lead in the coming months to a formal announcement
that he is running.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's steps have been less precise, but she is expected this
spring at least to form an exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strong poll showings by Bush and Dole, experienced
Republican strategists know that survey results can't be taken to
the bank almost a year before the first caucuses and primaries.
Even politicians favorably disposed to Bush, such as recently
retired former California GOP chairman Michael Schroeder, warned
against the governor relying on his currently strong press notices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's way too early to say the race is in the hands of one
person unless he makes a mistake,'' Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least nine other prospective nominees, with varying
degrees of ability to attempt to fight their way into the top tier
with Bush and Dole. They are: Sens. John McCain of Arizona and Bob
Smith of New Hampshire, former Vice President Dan Quayle, House
Budget chairman John Kasich of Ohio, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar
Alexander, commentator Pat Buchanan, magazine publisher Steve
Forbes, conservative broadcaster Alan Keyes and conservative
activist Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them privately have expressed irritation that the race
is dominated by relatives of famous Republican politicians of the
recent past.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes has remarked publicly on the fascination of party
officials with what might be viewed as dynastic politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a Republican establishment that's doing its best to
promote the usual list of suspects,'' Keyes said. ``With those old
horses, we'll lose in the same old way.''
</P>
<P>
   But that seems to be a minority view, as Keyes found out at the
California state Republican convention last weekend where Bush was
the major topic of conversation without even showing up. Dole also
skipped the event, which drew seven prospective GOP candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the delegates, such as Betty Cordoba of San Diego, who
also has been a national convention delegate, already has Bush
nominated and has penciled in Dole as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   There was no question Bush appealed to many Republicans because
of his family ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's anything like his mother and father, I'll adore him
and he'll win,'' said Lois Glab, a state delegate from Camarillo,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   To more hard-eyed Republican pros, Bush's allure stems from his
political record _ defeating Gov. Ann Richards, a seemingly popular
Democratic incumbent, in 1994 and then sailing to re-election last
fall when other big-name Republicans across the country were felled
by a Democratic tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so successful where we were so miserable,'' said Allan
Hoffenbloom, a GOP operative in California, where in November
Republicans lost the governorship for the first time in 16 years.
``We took such a shellacking. When we look at George W., he looks
like Ronald Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is unlikely to shy from such comparisons. His campaign, in
fact, may have more similarities to those of conservative icon
Reagan than to his father's less robust political efforts. But
former President Bush will always be a strong point of reference
for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Some pollsters and strategists still believe the governor fairs
so well in surveys because respondents are confused and thinking of
the former president.
</P>
<P>
   So what, said Hoffenbloom: ``In politics, an easily recalled
name is a very, very important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
