u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUGS-MEXICO-03-cox     03-02 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-MEXICO-03-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPUBLICAN LAWMAKERS SEEK TO DECERTIFY MEXICO DRUG EFFORTS
 &HT;    moving in (w) washington category
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Calling President Clinton's certification that
Mexico is cooperating in efforts to fight drug smuggling ``a
sham,''a group of Republican lawmakers filed a bill Tuesday to
overturn his action.
</P>
<P>
   The bill by Rep. Spencer Bachus, R-Ala., calls for revocation of
U.S. economic and diplomatic support of Mexico, but would allow the
president to waive those sanctions in the national interest.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., a Republican from Fort Lauderdale and one
of the bill's co-sponsors, said he doubted it would become law. But
he said it would result in Mexico's role as a leading drug producer
and transit country being exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, who has been involved in previous unsuccessful attempts to
decertify Mexico's drug status, said he would prefer to see stiffer
sanctions imposed against America's southern neighbor to force
officials there to take action.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my way I'd stop every truck coming across the border
and unload it,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw noted that the United States took unilateral action to
eradicate weapons of mass destruction in Iraq and should act
against Mexico for exporting drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These weapons of mass destruction are killing Americans,'' he
said. ``These weapons of mass destruction are contributing to
growing crime in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Mica, a Republican from Winter Park, Fla., said he
will hold a hearing of his Government Reform drug policy
subcommittee Thursday to review Mexico's anti-drug efforts and the
proposed legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Sens. Paul Coverdell, D-Ga., and Diane
Feinstein, D-Calif. _ who supported decertification for Mexico last
year - said they would not seek it this year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they said would introduce a bill that would bar reputed
drug kingpins from engaging in legal business with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
