<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4992 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA03-COX     03-02 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strong economy gives airlines a lift
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines (ticker symbol DAL) shares have risen
25 percent just in the past two weeks as confident investors helped
the Atlanta-based airline and other big air carriers pull out of a
share-price dive.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the persistent strength of the U.S. economy is
responsible for investor interest in airline stocks. Investors are
confident that business growth will translate into busy airline
schedules later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists entered 1999 forecasting slower growth, along
the lines of 2 percent to 2 1/2 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, government numbers continue to reflect a
stronger-than-expected economy.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the growth rate for the fourth quarter was revised
upward to a 6.1 percent annual rate from an initial estimate of 5.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs analyst Glenn D. Engel said in a report Tuesday
that the economy's strength points to increased air travel this
spring, especially among business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Engel raised his ratings on the shares of UAL (UAL), the world's
largest airline; American Airlines parent AMR (AMR), and
Continental Airlines (CAI/A, CAI/B). This boosted the shares of
Delta and other airlines whose ratings were not changed.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's shares rose Tuesday by $2.68 3/4 to $65.62 1/2 on
turnover of more than 2.6 million shares, or almost double the
average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on Tuesday, LHS Group (LHSG) fell $2.43 3/4, or 5.6
percent, to $41.43 3/4 on news of a large sale of shares by a group
of insiders and investors in the Atlanta-based provider of
telephone billing and customer service software.
</P>
<P>
   The company filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission to
offer 3.34 million shares owned by a venture capital group and by
insiders including Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Hartmut
Lademacher.
</P>
<P>
   All the shares will be offered by the shareholders and not the
company, LHS Group Senior Vice President Rainer Westermann said.
</P>
<P>
   The largest block _ 2.5 million, or about 75 percent of the
total _ will be sold by General Atlantic Partners LLC, which
Westermann described as a venture capital group that had invested
in LHS Group.
</P>
<P>
   Lademacher will offer 500,000 shares, according to the filing,
reducing his interest to 30.6 percent from 36.1 percent, Bloomberg
News said.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg said the other shareholders are Jerry W. Braxton,
chief financial officer and treasurer; Hansjorg Beha, executive
vice president of technology; Erik Froberg, special adviser to the
chairman; Ulf Bohla, a director; and Jon Limbird, executive vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   HypoVereinsbank AG, Deutsche Bank Securities and SG Cowen will
underwrite the offering.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus-based Total System Services (TSS) rebounded Tuesday
from Monday's 10 percent share price decline with a gain of 25
cents, or 1.2 percent, to $20.62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which provides third-party credit card processing
services, had announced that one of its larger clients _ a Citibank
subsidiary _ will not renew its processing relationship beyond Aug.
1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gulfstream Aerospace (GAC), a Savannah-based manufacturer of
corporate jets, rose $1.68 3/4, or 3.6 percent, to $48.06 1/4 a day
after announcing plans to buy back up to $200 million worth of its
common stock.
</P>
<P>
   The share price leader among Georgia stocks was Atlanta-based
Security First Technologies (SONE), which provides Internet
services for financial institutions. The stock rose $4.37 1/2, or
almost 5 percent, to $70.12 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
