<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMESHOPPING-WEB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Diller no 'pretender' in online worldBy Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Who needed me to muck everything up?''
</P>
<P>
   That's how Barry Diller, chairman and chief executive of USA
Networks ,which owns Lycos and the Home Shopping Network among
other things, began his keynote address to the 1,600 plus attendees
of the Jupiter Online Forum underway at the Sheraton New York.
</P>
<P>
   Diller, a seasoned media veteran, seemed oddly humble before the
high-tech Web-savvy crowd.
</P>
<P>
   His self-deprecating speech surely scored points with a
potentially hostile crowd who didn't like the idea of their
bleeding-edge Web sites and business models suddenly becoming so
closely intertwined with a TV network best known for selling
bracelets and blenders to bored housewives in Des Moines. (Somewhat
defensively Diller pointed out that HSN also sells millions worth
of computers via TV every day. ``It's not just about little rings
anymore,'' he insisted.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get away with saying 'we' in the Internet world','' he
said. ``I'm just a pretender.
</P>
<P>
   However, Diller is not as naive as he'd have you believe.
Comparing the Internet of the '90s to the great land rush of the
1800s, Diller explained the process that led him to believe there
is gold in the Internet hills.
</P>
<P>
   To put it as simply as possible, Diller did the math. And the
answer came up Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Diller is one of the few people in or out of the Internet
business willing to admit up front he's building an online presence
squarely aimed at selling people things. It may not be as
altruistic as content sites such as Salon or the New York Times on
the Web, but if it's done right, online shopping can be one Diller
of a money-maker. And he would like to make a lot of money, not in
inflated Internet stock certificates, but in cold, hard cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw QVC (the first shopping channel Diller
bought, now owned by Tele-Communications Inc. and Comcast), I saw
that it used television to attract viewers, phones to get orders
and computers to tie it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Diller bought Ticketmaster Online and the CitySearch
network of local sites and merged the two into the Ticketmaster
Online-CitySearch Inc. He saw the combination as a way to generate
revenue from CitySearch users looking for arts and entertainment
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see the Internet only through its global mystique is a
mistake,'' he said. ``Search global but live local,'' he said.
``It's intriguing to look at movie times in New York City when
you're sitting in Kenya, but ultimately it's a frustrating
experience, because you can't get there in time for the 8 O'clock
show.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to describe his new alliance with Web portal Lycos as
``real business combined with 'a world where possibilities
exist.''' However, he knew some people in the Jupiter audience,
perhaps more than would admit it, still aren't making money. What's
more, they may never make the money that Diller has made off-line
and now proposes to make online. ``Have I in this transaction (with
Lycos) pulled one or two items of clothing off the emperor?'' he
asked rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Net companies will make money. Some won't,'' he said. ``I
want to make a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   However, while Diller believes he can make money with his
combined TV and Web ventures, he knows he is rolling the dice just
like everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in on a great game,'' he said in his closing comments,
signalling his uncertainty about the Web. For all his pragmatism
and real world databases of active, credit-card wielding customers,
at the end of the day, not even Barry Diller knows if he can make
money on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange way that is sort of reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
