<TEXT>
<P>
   (Eds.: Changes slug to BUDGET-SOCSEC sted REPUBS-BUDGET) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, March 3. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-SOCSEC (Washington) _ The Republican leadership debates a
plan that would force Congress to become more fiscally responsible
by ending the longstanding practice of using Social Security money
for other purposes _ but not right away. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Frankfurt, Germany) _ In the two months since the European
single currency was introduced, pretty much the only direction it
has moved is down. From a buoyant and technically smooth start-up
on Jan. 4, the euro has steadily slipped against the United States
dollar. An initial exchange rate of $1.17 is now around $1.09. The
decline has surprised most experts and puzzled the overseers of the
new currency at the European Central Bank. It could also strain
relations with the United States, where government officials now
loudly complain that Europe has to do more to stimulate world
growth. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-SUPERVISION (Undated) _ Three decades after American
college students defiantly threw off the vestiges of curfews, dress
codes and dormitory house mothers, a revolution is under way in
undergraduate life that may be quieter but no less significant.
Reflecting a range of societal changes _ consumerism,
litigiousness, a shift in intergenerational relations, new
technologies _ colleges are offering and students are often
demanding greater supervision of their lives. By Ethan Bronner.
With photo. 2,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOREST-ACCORD (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Pacific Lumber Co. and the
government cap years of negotiations by agreeing to a $480 million
plan to set aside an ancient redwood grove for the public. The
agreement turns over to the public some 10,000 acres of forest,
about half of them old-growth redwoods, in the coastal hills about
250 miles north of San Francisco. As a condition of the sale,
Pacific Lumber agrees to a number of stringent environmental rules
on the rest of its 211,000 acres in rugged Humboldt County. By
Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-KIDNAP (Undated) _ At least eight Western tourists
kidnapped by Ugandan rebels, including two Americans, are killed.
By Neil MacFarquhar.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ A hardline political leader of
the Kosovo Liberation Army resigns, raising hopes among diplomats
that the ethnic Albanian guerrilla movement will sign an autonomy
plan proposed at peace talks last month. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   COUNSEL-LAW (Washington) _ Deputy Attorney General tells
Congress the independent counsel law should be scrapped. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
</TEXT>
