<SLUG> BC-BUSH-LEGISLATURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH INITIATIVES OFF TO SLOW START IN LEGISLATIVE SESSION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush finally stopped being coy
Tuesday and put his presidential campaign in gear. Now, some people
are wondering, can he do the same with his legislative program?
</P>
<P>
   Supporters from near and far, urging a Bush run for the White
House, have been moving in and out of the Governor's Mansion a lot
faster than most of Bush's legislative proposals have moved at the
state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks into the legislative session, only one of the
governor's priorities _ a tax break for small oil and gas producers
_ is anywhere close to becoming law, and it may still spark a
fight.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to predict success or failure for most of Bush's
program because it is still relatively early. Lawmakers will not
adjourn until May 31, and the House, under Speaker Pete Laney,
normally does not pass much legislation during the first two months
of a session anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But there already have been strong hints that rough sledding
awaits several of the governor's proposals, partly because of
budgetary restraints and philosophical differences and partly
because of his upcoming presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The success or failure of Bush's initiatives _ and how he
handles the give-and-take with lawmakers _ may have a major impact
on how Bush is perceived nationally as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate already has given quick passage to three major bills
backed by Bush _ the energy tax break, a $57 million franchise tax
exemption for small businesses and one of the governor's top
priorities, a measure to crack down on social promotions in the
public schools by requiring children to pass a standardized test
before they are advanced to the next grade.
</P>
<P>
   But all have been slowed down in the House, where a number of
Democrats, who hold a 78-72 majority, disagree with the Republican
governor's priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly a difference in philosophy,'' said state
Rep. Kevin Bailey, D-Houston, chairman of the Legislative Study
Group, an organization of Democratic lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Major fights also are brewing over the governor's proposals to
cut school property taxes by $2 billion, establish a pilot program
of tax-backed vouchers for private schools and require parents to
be notified before their minor daughters could have abortions.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Capitol insiders believe the voucher program, which
would benefit only a limited number of children from low-performing
public schools, is dead on arrival. Public support for the idea is
dwindling, according to a recent Scripps Howard Texas Poll, despite
an expensive lobbying effort by voucher supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Voucher advocates believe a majority of legislators would vote
for the program, if given a chance, but the voucher bill is
believed to lack the two-thirds support necessary to be debated by
the full Senate and may be blocked in the House by the Public
Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   A parental notification bill, one of the most emotional issues
lawmakers will face, won Senate approval during the 1997 session
but was killed in the House on a procedural maneuver that sparked a
nasty partisan fight late in the session.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is expected to win Senate approval again, but a vote
in the House, if the measure emerges from committee, may be close.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of this issue will be important to Bush's support
among the religious and social conservatives who are instrumental
in nominating Republican presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Price, president of Texans United for Life, an
anti-abortion group, said he believed Bush was committed to getting
the bill passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would generate a lot of concern among social
conservatives if he wasn't able to get this through,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's $2 billion school tax cut proposal anchors a tax
reduction package that also includes $307 million worth of business
tax credits and exemptions and a $330 million cut in sales taxes on
diapers, other health aids, over-the-counter medicine and Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also wants to increase state funds to the public schools by
$1.6 billion during the next two years _ on top of the $2 billion
that he wants the state to reimburse districts for lower property
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   One key Republican lawmaker, state Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount
Pleasant, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, has warned that
the state budget surplus is not big enough to cover all of the
governor's requests and also meet other spending needs.
</P>
<P>
   And some Democrats would rather see less money spent on tax
relief and more money spent on children's health care and other
early intervention programs.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Paul Sadler, D-Henderson, chairman of the House
Public Education Committee, which plans to overhaul the social
promotion bill, believes the measure also should require children
to attend kindergarten. Sadler's proposal would cost the state $500
million and further jeopardize Bush's tax cut plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, the governor has said the oil industry is facing an
emergency but children are not,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to a bill, designated an emergency by Bush, to
provide as much as $45 million in severance tax exemptions for
owners of marginal oil and gas wells. The House Ways and Means
Committee was expected to approve that bill Wednesday after
delaying action last week. The Senate approved it last month.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed $483 million in funding for a health insurance
program for needy children, but some Democratic legislators want to
make even more youngsters eligible for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said the governor was ``working
with legislators to provide coverage for more children and to be
fiscally responsible for the state in the long term.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; State Rep. Paul Hilbert, R-Houston, said he believed some
Democratic lawmakers are trying to take advantage of Bush's need to
avoid a disruptive session to negotiate with the governor over
children's health care and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to slow it (the governor's program) down,'' Hilbert
said. ``I think at this juncture the governor is minding the store
very well. But they (Democrats) see an Achilles heel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
