<SLUG> BC-HEWLETT-SPINOFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HP TO SPLIT INTO TWO FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 2,760 Massachusetts employees of Hewlett-Packard Co. will
soon be working for a new company, due to a dramatic corporate
reorganization at the pioneering Silicon Valley firm.
</P>
<P>
   The electronics titan will split into two separate independent
firms. The lion's share of the business _ the $40 billion
computing, imaging and printing operations _ will go on as
Hewlett-Packard Co. Meanwhile, the firm's $7.6 billion medical
instruments, measuring devices and electronic test equipment
business will become part of a new company, which has not yet been
named. HP employs 2,200 workers in Massachusetts at its medical
systems operation in Andover, and another 560 in Burlington work
for the company's measuring devices unit.
</P>
<P>
   HP officials say the split should help stimulate faster growth
in both companies. ``We are taking this action to sharpen the
strategic focus of our businesses, improve their agility and
increase their responsiveness to customers and partners,'' said
Lewis Platt, HP's chief executive. Platt will continue to lead the
computer and printer business during a transition period, and will
then step aside.
</P>
<P>
   The new medical instruments and electronic devices business will
be headed by Edward Barnholt, currently executive vice president of
the unit inside HP. Barnholt said that giving the unit its
independence will allow it to become a more aggressive competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully by being more focused, well be faster on our feet,
we'll be more responsive to the market opportunities,'' he said.
The new firm will sell 15 percent of its stock to the public;
Barnholt said the public offering will probably occur in October.
The remaining stock will be distributed among HP shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the company rose 2 3/4 to 68 5/8 Tuesday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Barnholt's new company will include the electronic
testing business that gave rise to Hewlett-Packard in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   The company was the original high-tech start-up, begun by
Stanford University buddies William Hewlett and David Packard in
Hewlett's garage in Palo Alto, Calif. in 1939. There they built
audio oscillators for the Walt Disney Co., which used them to make
the movie ``Fantasia.'' The garage still stands, and is now a
national landmark, cited as the official birthplace of Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The company got into medical devices in 1961 when it bought the
Sanborn Co. of Waltham. HP began making computers in 1966. Hundreds
of people who established the modern computer industry learned
their trade as HP employees, including Apple Computer Inc.
co-founder Stephen Wozniak.
</P>
<P>
   Today computers, printers and scanners are HP's biggest
businesses, producing far more revenue than test equipment and
medical devices. Cynthia Danaher, vice president and general
manager of the medical products group, said that being part of a
much larger company had become a hindrance. ``I don't think the
company's been able to grow up to its ability,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Jay, vice president at BT Alex Brown in Boston, said the
spinoff could liberate the new company for strong growth in the
medical equipment market. ``Over the past five years we have seen a
number of medical technology companies spun out from larger
parents,'' said Jay. ``With independence and entrepreneurial
management, these companies in many cases have performed quite well
as investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Danaher predicted the new company would move quickly to make
strategic acquisitions in the medical equipment industry. She also
expected it to produce more products for use outside of hospitals,
such as home defibrillator units for emergency treatment of heart
attack victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
