<SLUG> BC-PAROLE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATURE URGED NOT TO REQUIRE OPEN-DOOR CLEMENCY HEARINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
and JAMIE STOCKWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The state's top parole official Tuesday urged
the Legislature not to require open-door clemency hearings for
murderers facing the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles should fine-tune
its deliberations, which recently were upheld as constitutional,
and upgrade its computer-dependent review process, said board
chairman Victor Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we meet constitutionality,'' Rodriguez told the House
Appropriations Committee, ``why would we want to do more for
someone that has committed the most heinous crime against our
people?''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez acknowledged there have been ``serious challenges'' to
existing procedures from condemned inmates Joseph Stanley Faulder
and Henry Lee Lucas, executed inmate Karla Faye Tucker and others.
</P>
<P>
   But ``those cases have been decided in our favor. Now that those
things are cleared for us, we are contemplating a series of rules
changes that better spell out our clemency review process,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``we don't anticipate going above and beyond what the
courts have ruled is a system that's constitutional,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's stance drew biting questions from Reps. Sylvester
Turner, D-Houston, and Robert Puente, D-San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just having a philosophical problem with a board choosing
not to meet; when the public doesn't have the right to see what
you're doing,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no constitutional right to clemency,'' Rodriguez
responded. ``And I believe it would create a right _ to have a
public meeting,'' he said, adding, ``the full board is supposed to
be a representative body of the people of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Puente countered by saying ``it's not that it's the inmate's
right to a hearing necessarily. It's the public's right to know how
your board makes decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a hearing of the House Corrections Committee, Rep.
Elliott Naishtat, D-Austin, presented two measures, House Bills 397
and 398, that would require open proceedings on clemency questions;
require voting members to state reasons for their decisions and
establish criteria for granting clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board doesn't hold public meetings; doesn't meet at all to
deliberate or review clemency applications; relies on packets of
information that often aren't timely received; votes by phone or
fax; doesn't give reason for its actions; has no written guidelines
or criteria for evaluating requests and in a nutshell, does its
business in a secretive, arbitrary and perhaps capricious manner,''
Naishtat said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker noted that Gov. George W. Bush has not embraced his
proposals because the process passed constitutional muster, and
Naishtat's bills are opposed by the Justice For All victims rights
group.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``it's the right thing to do,'' Naishtat said. However,
his measure produced no immediate action.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez appeared before the spending committee to request $2.2
million for a new computer network to make deliberations more
efficient. He said the agency reviews 60,000 to 70,000 cases a year
and needs the network to link numerous field offices and board
members.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to discouraging an overhaul of the clemency process,
Rodriguez disputed the need for a new life-without-parole
sentencing option in Texas. Several related proposals are pending
in the House Criminal Jurisprudence Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said the existing 40-year minimum term attached to
life sentences fulfills the same purpose and would have a
negligible impact on public safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, we have it,'' Rodriguez said. Forty calendar years
behind bars ``in fact constitutes a life-without-parole program.
The impact of that would be nominal,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
