<SLUG> BC-BKC-A10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-10 TEAMS HOPES BALL _ AND PLAYOFF BID _ BOUNCES THEIR WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The operative word is redemption. Virtually every
Atlantic 10 team will be looking for it during the conference's
postseason tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to vying for an automatic bid to the NCAA
Tournament, most of the teams are hoping to bounce back from
worse-than-expected regular seasons that made the league one of the
biggest disappointments in major college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no team has more to gain than the University of
Massachusetts (13-15), which was ranked as high as ninth in the
country in some preseason polls but never went above .500 after
winning its opener. UMass finished third in the Atlantic 10 East
Division and will meet Duquesne, sixth in the West, in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   In other first-round action, Fordham, the fifth seed in the
East, meets Virginia Tech, fourth in the West, at noon; St.
Bonaventure (fourth in the East) meets Dayton (fifth in the West)
at 7 p.m.; and St. Joseph's (sixth in the East) meets La Salle
(third in the West) at 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Four teams earned first-round byes and won't begin play until
Thursday. East champ Temple meets the Virginia Tech-Fordham winner
at noon; East runner-up Rhode Island meets the St. Joseph's-La
Salle winner at 9 p.m.; West champ George Washington plays the St.
Bonaventure-Dayton winner at 7 p.m.; and West runner-up Xavier
plays the UMass-Duquesne winer at 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   UMass has made seven consecutive NCAA Tournament trips, but to
reach the Big Dance this season, it must win the A 10 tourney.
Reaching the tournament championship game could be worth a National
Invitation Tournament bid.
</P>
<P>
   With so many teams looking to salvage seasons, none can be taken
lightly, according to UMass coach Bruiser Flint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone is dangerous in their own way,'' said Flint.
``Sometimes you can overlook teams. Sometimes all of a sudden teams
who have been struggling all year can get it together and play well
for four nights. But then, some might continue to struggle, and
some might put it together one night and struggle the next.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic 10 had four teams ranked in both preseason polls,
tied with the Pac-10 for the most. UMass and the three others
(Rhode Island, Temple, Xavier) dropped out as the season
progressed. Temple (19-9, 13-3) returned last week, only to be
knocked out when it lost to UMass in the regular-season finale
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot of basketball left,'' said UMass point
guard Charlton Clarke, who has been playing with a stress fracture
in his right foot for three weeks. How he fares with the injury
this week might determine how far the Minutemen go.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Atlantic 10 has put five teams in the NCAA Tournament
each of the last two seasons, it might not be so fortunate this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Temple is considered a lock, regardless of its showing this
week. George Washington (19-7) likely will earn at least an
at-large berth as long as it doesn't lose its first-round game.
Ditto for Xavier (20-9), which has two narrow defeats (to UMass and
GWU) in its last three games.
</P>
<P>
   URI (17-12) is in an intriguing situation. The Rams appeared to
have things turned around a week ago following a season-high
four-game winning streak, but they closed out the regular season
with consecutive losses. The Rams might have to win the tourney to
secure an NCAA bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
