<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING AN INDELIBLE IMPRESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For most people, a misspelled word isn't that big a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   You may be briefly embarrassed if someone points it out in a
letter or something. If you work for a newspaper, you may even have
to correct it in the next day's paper. But it passes.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the misspelled word is tattooed on your arm. Then you've
got troubles.
</P>
<P>
   A man in Roseville, Mich., recently sued a tattoo parlor for
$25,000 for misspelling ``villain'' on his arm. He and the workers
at the parlor debated how to spell the word, according to a
newspaper story; they settled on ``villian.''
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   The man got the tattoo in 1996 but didn't notice the misspelling
till a friend made fun of him. Now he has a ``scar as long as his
forearm'' where he had the tattoo removed, according to his
attorney. (That still beats having a misspelled word there; you
might as well have a tattoo on your forehead that says ``stupid,''
too.)
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the tattoo parlor, meanwhile, says that if a
customer agrees to a misspelling _ the parlor's policy is to ask
customers how they want words spelled _ it's the customer's fault,
not his.
</P>
<P>
   As you might guess, local tattoo artists sided with him. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hairy situation &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell (customers), `If you're not sure, think before you
ink,' '' said Daniel Rees, the manager of Arizona Ink. ``Be really
sure before you make that step because once you've got it, you've
got it. Diamond rings are lost, stolen, hocked. Relationships come
and go, but that tattoo is still there.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, he urges caution. Most shops do. Usually, a customer has
to write out what he wants tattooed, then sign a release. Then the
artist draws a stencil, so the person getting the tattoo can see
what he's getting into before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   And it never hurts to double-check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got `incomplete' across my wrist,'' said Lloyd Parrack, a
body piercer at Crawling Squid Tattoo Studio. ``I checked three
different dictionaries to make sure it was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Good for him. Maybe it's just me, but if I were going to have
something as permanent as a tattoo needled onto my body _ making me
in effect a walking billboard _ I'd want to make sure it was
spelled correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even then, there are no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember this one guy was in a shop in South Dakota,'' said
Gene Roberdeaux, a tattoo artist at Mom's Tattoo. ``The guy spelled
`Harley-Davidson' wrong. He spelled it `Hairy-Davidson.' And it was
HUGE on the guy's back. I think if that ever happened to me, I
would quit tattooing.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd think you wouldn't have any choice, since your fingers would
probably be gnarled and covered with motorcycle tire tracks. At
least your fingers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Yeah, but . . .' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people get really upset,'' said Michael Hoffman, a tattoo
artist at Ultimate Art Tattoo. No doubt.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think you'd feel bad with a misspelled word or
slogan, think how you'd feel with a misspelled fiancee's name.
Ex-fiancee, probably, at that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are usually, `You spelled her name wrong,' '' Parrack
said. ``No, this is the way you spelled it. You told me. They
usually go, `Well, yeah. But you spelled it wrong.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman once tattooed a fellow who misspelled (begin ital) his
own middle name. (end ital) Hard to blame Hoffman for that one. But
he also acknowledged misspelling ``vengeance'' _ as in, ``powered
by vengeance'' _ when tattooing someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked right,'' he said of ``vengence'' _ the way he
spelled it. ``It went by for weeks and nobody knew it. Then
somebody said something to the kid. He was embarrassed. He came
right in and got it fixed.'' A wise choice.
</P>
<P>
   Rees, of Arizona Ink, is right. Despite all the blood and
needles, this isn't brain surgery. It's tattooing. If you're going
to get something permanent, think.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that difficult,'' Rees said. ``Common sense would
tell you to take $3 and get a dictionary. Or go back to school and
get a GED or a high school degree.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
