<SLUG> BC-BJS-FOURTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BJ'S WHOLESALE CLUB POSTS BETTER-THAN-EXPECTED EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fourth-quarter earnings for BJ's Wholesale Club Inc. handily
beat Wall Street expectations Tuesday, partly as a result of lower
expenses and strong holiday sales of jewelry and apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by the news, BJ's shares hit a 52-week high of 47 3/4 on
the New York Stock Exchange. The price dipped slightly at closing
to 47 11/16, up 4 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a sensational quarter,'' said Jack Nugent, BJ's
president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The Natick, Mass. operator of 96 wholesale warehouse clubs had
been expected to earn 93 cents per share for the fourth quarter,
according to analysts surveyed by First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, BJ's earned $1 a share before results were adjusted for
a 2-for-1 stock split investors will see in Wednesday' trading
price.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-quarter profits jumped from $29.6 million to $37.7
million, or about 27 percent, after earnings were restated to
reflect an accounting change.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Jan. 30, sales rose nearly 6 percent to
$1.03 billion. At stores open for at least a year, sales were up
4.5 percent when compared with the same 13-week period from a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   So far, a robust economy and a strong holiday shopping season
have helped many retailers post better-than-expected earnings for
the fourth quarter, said Charles L. Hill, First Call's director of
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date, 73 percent of the retailers in our survey have
exceeded expectations, and 72 percent have surpassed year-ago
results,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even in a strong quarter for retailers, ``BJ's' performance
stands out,'' said Sally H. Wallick, an analyst with Legg Mason
Wood Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Several small factors contributed to BJ's' big quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sales were especially encouraging at the 12 club stores BJ's
opened last year, according to Amy E. Ryan, an analyst with
Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, sales were brisk for jewelry and apparel, which
tend to have higher profit margins than most of the
supermarket-type items found at a BJ's. A year ago, a chunk of
BJ's' holiday sales came from TV sets and consumer electronics,
which have lower profit margins than jewelry and apparel, Ryan
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, fair weather meant BJ's never had to dip into the
money it had set aside for snow removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saved a lot of money against our plan,'' said Nugent, who
added, ``A lot of little things went our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Beating Wall Street's expectations is nothing new for BJ's.
</P>
<P>
   This is the company's eighth consecutive year of both operating
and net income improvements, Nugent said.
</P>
<P>
   For its full fiscal year, BJ's said sales rose 10 percent to
$3.5 billion. Excluding a charge, earnings were $81.8 million, up
from $68.3 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
