<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSSORGSKY-OPERA-REVI     03-02 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSSORGSKY-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KHOVANSHCHINA': ELOQUENT CHORAL WORK IN VIOLENT, POLITICAL TALE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (jw)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Being just across town anyway, the United Nations
might want to send over a few of its delegates to see the August
Everding production of ``Khovanshchina'' now in revival at the
Metropolitan Opera. Diplomats trying to sort out Kosovo, Bosnia,
Serbs and Albanians could possibly find Mussorgsky's views on late
17th-century Russia chillingly familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Opera is filled with gallant causes and tragic results, but the
political despair of ``Khovanshchina'' elevates it to a different
level of sophistication. There are few poetic deaths in this vast,
unfinished piece; even the self-immolation of fundamentalist
Christian Old Believers at the end can be taken as an act of
fanaticism as much as one of devotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Khovanshchina,'' which opened at the Met on Monday night,
depicts a quartet of political and religious forces hacking away at
one another in search of ultimate power. To somehow bind them
together, Mussorgsky has invented a female character named Marfa.
Alternately Old Believer, protector of feminine virtue against the
military police and soothsayer to one set of czarist pretenders,
Marfa is a somewhat artificial construct. But the composer
certainly needed some kind of cohering force in this jumble of
hostility.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Boris Godunov,'' true eloquence belongs to Mussorgsky's
chorus and to individuals like the drunken sentry, Kouzka (Nikolai
Gassiyev), and the Public Scribe (Constantin Pluzhnikov), acting as
marginal commentators on lofty doings. If ``Khovanshchina'' has a
message for us, it is that the global pockets of insurrection we
contend with today are sometimes less moral crusades than matters
of lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   For what better way to escape the oppression of drab
surroundings and vacuous tranquillity than to manufacture a
dramatic, violent life for one's self, feeling heroic about it all
the while? The causes come and go, but the bloody-mindedness
remains.
</P>
<P>
   The Met production from 1985 replaces Rimsky-Korsakov's
posthumous 1886 revision with Shostakovich's less intrusive version
first heard in 1960. The cast here is largely Russian, occasionally
American and in one prominent case Italian. Ming Cho Lee's design
features two elegant interiors and some plain outdoor scenes: one
with cutout Kremlin spires, the others formed largely from boards,
nails and rough carpentry.
</P>
<P>
   Valery Gergiev, who conducted, is now the Met's official
Russian, and he evidently has access to the best singing talent his
country offers. As usual, low voices dominate. Vladimir Ognovenko
is a booming, radiant Khovansky. Roberto Scandiuzzi _ singing
Dosifei, leader of the Old Believers _ smolders eloquently, if at a
slightly lower volume.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Forbis (Khovansky's son) takes one of the tenor roles
firmly; Vladimir Bogachov (Golitsin) sings the other in the
piercing, somewhat wavering Russian style. Nikolai Putilin
(Shaklovity) is a solid baritone.
</P>
<P>
   Dolora Zajick, big of voice and seemingly an apt Marfa, is
strangely subdued here. It behooves Ms. Zajick to dominate the
explosive personalities around her (Emily Pulley as Emma, Irena
Milkeviciute as Susanna). But often she seems almost to sleepwalk
through the part. Phebe Berkovitz, the stage director for the
revival, has her hands full with the large number of mob scenes,
sometimes too full.
</P>
<P>
   Gergiev brought his rough-cut conducting style to music close to
his heart. Offstage, the chorus was prone to confusion. Onstage, it
sang gloriously, as the music Mussorgsky wrote for it demands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
