<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADMINISTRATION BACKS KILLING INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration came out Tuesday against
the independent counsel act, saying that public confidence in the
fairness of the Watergate-inspired law has been ``undermined rather
than enhanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the administration, Deputy Attorney General Eric
Holder told a House panel that the law ``has failed in its goal of
removing politics from the process'' and that its ``structure comes
dangerously close to tipping the traditional balance of fairness in
the conduct of criminal investigations and prosecutions,''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said that he saw no way to fix the ``fundamental flaws''
in the statute and urged Congress to let it expire on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Justice) Department has reluctantly concluded that
decisions and actions under the act, both by independent counsels
and attorneys general, inevitably and unavoidably become such
targets for attack that public confidence in the administration of
justice in these high-profile cases has been undermined rather than
enhanced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holder suggested that investigations into the president and
upper-level administration officials should be handled by the
Justice Department in a manner similar to the system used before
passage of the 1978 independent counsel act.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that act, the attorney general would turn over credible
allegations against the president, vice president, most cabinet
officials, the CIA director and the FBI director to the Justice
Department's Public Integrity Section. The section would
investigate the allegations and recommend whether a special
prosecutor should be appointed.
</P>
<P>
   Holder's comments to the House Subcommittee on Commercial and
Administrative Law marked the first time the Clinton administration
has gone on record against the statute. The president and Attorney
General Janet Reno successfully lobbied for its renewal five years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The administration will likely continue its campaign against the
law _ which has been attacked by many Capitol Hill lawmakers _ on
Wednesday when Clinton's personal attorney, Robert Bennett, appears
before the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee. Reno is scheduled
to testify before the same committee later this month.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Barry Toiv said Clinton ``concurs
with the judgment of the Justice Department that the statute should
not be renewed _ that its flaws outweigh its benefits.'' Toiv said
Clinton's judgment was ``a policy decision based on his observation
of how the law has been implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law requires the attorney general to
seek appointment of an independent counsel when there is
substantial and credible evidence of a crime by any one of 49 top
federal officials, including the president. A panel of three
federal appellae judges then picks an attorney for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans opposed the law when it was passed in the wake
of the Watergate scandal. During that time President Richard Nixon
ordered the attorney general to dismiss special Watergate
prosecutor Archibald Cox, who had refused to drop a subpoena for
Nixon's incriminating White House tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Under Presidents Ronald Reagan and George Bush, congressional
Republicans complained that the statute permitted independent
counsels to conduct politically inspired investigations. They cited
Independent Counsel Lawrence Walsh's probe into the Iran-Contra
arms-for-hostages deals of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans were so upset over the six years and $48 million
Walsh had spent investigating the Reagan and Bush administrations,
that they almost prevented the act, which had lapsed in 1992, from
being renewed. In 1993, 28 Senate Republicans threatened a
filibuster, but a newly elected President Clinton lobbied for the
measure and won.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, when a three-judge panel appointed Kenneth Starr to
investigate Clinton, Democrats have repeated many criticisms of the
law that Republicans had voiced earlier.
</P>
<P>
   However, Holder repeatedly emphasized that the administration's
reversal on the independent counsel law ``does not have to do with
any particular inquiry or investigation, but rather (with) the fact
that the types of decisions we are talking about here can be
controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that a ``climate of politicization pervades the process
regardless of which way a specific decision, investigation or
prosecution comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said independent counsels are ``largely insulated'' from
the normal checks placed on prosecutors because they have unlimited
time and resources to investigate one individual or event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This insulation contributes greatly to the independence of
these prosecutors, but it also eliminates the incentive to show
restraint in the exercise of prosecutorial power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has spent nearly $50 million on his investigation of
allegations against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Holder also said independent counsels are given too much
authority to expand their investigations, going far beyond their
original mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's mandate, for example, began with inquiries into
Clinton's Whitewater land deals in Arkansas and widened repeatedly,
finally to the Monica Lewinsky scandal that led to his impeachment
and trial. The Senate acquitted him Feb. 12 of perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
