<HEADER>
A5019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARCIA-MARQUEZ-MAGAZI     03-02 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-MARQUEZ-MAGAZINE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOBEL LAUREATE RETURNS TO HIS FIRST LOVE: JOURNALISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ He has already won a Nobel Prize, says there
are still books he needs to write and is about to celebrate his
72nd birthday. So it came as something of a shock to Colombians
when the novelist Gabriel Garcia Marquez recently bought a
money-losing newsmagazine here and then promptly joined the ranks
of its reporting staff.
</P>
<P>
   But to Garcia Marquez, the decision makes perfect sense. For
years, he said, he had dreamed of using his Nobel Prize money to
organize a newspaper to be called El Otro, or The Other, so when a
group of young editors and reporters came to him with a proposal to
buy and overhaul the newsweekly Cambio, he welcomed it as a chance
to return to his first love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalism is the only trade that I like, and I have always
regarded myself as a journalist,'' said Garcia Marquez, who earned
a living as a newspaper and news-agency reporter before writing
``One Hundred Years of Solitude,'' the 1967 novel that established
his literary reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But nobody would employ me'' after he won his Nobel in 1982,
he added jokingly, ``because it was too expensive. So now I pay so
that I can be published.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Garcia Marquez is president of the seven-member
board of directors of Cambio and the magazine's chief stockholder,
roles he is not accustomed to playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here,'' he said, handing a business card to an American
visitor, an amused grin on his face. ``I've never had one of these
before.''
</P>
<P>
   By choice, though, his week-to-week duties at Cambio range as
far afield as editing copy and reviewing photographs. When peace
talks between the government and left-wing rebels began in early
January, he even went to the site of the negotiations as part of
the magazine's reporting team, sending dispatches that were
incorporated into the main article without his byline appearing.
</P>
<P>
   Mauricio Vargas, the magazine's new editor in chief, said that
one of the great advantages of having the Spanish-speaking world's
most eminent author on staff is that ``many doors open to him, and
he knows how to ask that they be opened.''
</P>
<P>
   That celebrity status has resulted in exclusive interviews with
heads of state and business leaders, but can create difficulties in
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to feel the atmosphere, to be a reporter, but I have a
problem,'' Garcia Marquez acknowledged, referring to the commotion
caused when he appeared at the start of the peace talks. ``My
presence causes other reporters to treat me not as a colleague, but
as news. So I have asked my fellow journalists to respect my right
to exercise our craft.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cambio also provides a vehicle for Garcia Marquez's
ruminations about current events and the international scene.
Several of his essays have already been syndicated to publications
throughout Latin America and Europe, helping enhance the magazine's
reputation and improving its bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the article most widely reprinted was one in which
Garcia Marquez, to the consternation of Latin American feminists,
defended president Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   After recalling how Clinton dazzled him at a dinner on Martha's
Vineyard in 1995 by reciting from memory long passages from ``The
Sound and the Fury'' by William Faulkner, Garcia Marquez went on to
attack what he sees as an unhealthy moralism in American life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president only wanted to do something that ordinary men
have done behind the backs of their wives since the beginning of
the world, and Puritan obtuseness not only prevented him from doing
it but even denied him the right to deny it,'' Garcia Marquez
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It is one thing to lie to deceive, and something
altogether different to hide the truth in order to preserve this
mythic instance of the human being that is one's private life.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether because of the lure of Garcia Marquez's presence or the
series of political crises Colombia has been experiencing lately,
the circulation of Cambio has risen sharply since the new
management took over at the start of the year. In the first four
weeks, newsstand sales doubled to more than 12,000, editors said,
circulation rose to about 45,000, compared with 171,000 for Semana,
Colombia's main newsmagazine, and advertising quintupled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Miguel Silva, president of Semana, said Garcia Marquez's
involvement with the rival publication ``is the culmination of a
process'' that has injected new life and energy into the Colombian
press, benefiting both reporters and readers.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, two new television networks have begun
broadcasting, and one of the two main daily newspapers in Bogota,
El Espectador, has been reinvigorated with new resources after
being bought by the country's leading business group.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a consumer of information, I'm all in favor of more
competition, whether on television or in print,'' said Luis
Norberto Restrepo Godoy, 31, a computer technician interviewed as
he bought a copy of Cambio at a newsstand here. ``The more
information I have at my disposal, the better off I am, so I
welcome the arrival of Garcia Marquez and the resurgence of
Cambio.''
</P>
<P>
   Silva said he was confident that more than one newsweekly could
thrive in Colombia, which has a population of 40 million. ``You
don't compete with Gabo,'' he said, using the nickname by which the
Nobel laureate is universally known here, ``but you can compete
with his magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both magazines are trying to be better, and to be better than
the other,'' Silva continued. ``It's like a good jazz concert,
where you have the trumpet and the saxophone responding to each
other. Having Gabo back in the trade makes everyone want to write
and investigate better every day.''
</P>
<P>
   As Garcia Marquez sees it, Cambio is carving out a niche that
allows it to avoid what he calls ``the scoop syndrome'' and to
treat ``journalism as a literary genre.''
</P>
<P>
   True to his novelist's instincts, he argues that what
subscribers really want is for reporters ``to tell a story, to go
back to the time when a reader could know what happened as if he
were there himself.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Garcia Marquez seems energized both by his
return to his original profession and the chance to work with much
younger reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this experience is making him feel profoundly alive,''
Vargas said. ``It is an antidote to his sacred status'' as Latin
America's most revered writer.
</P>
<P>
   With enthusiasm, Garcia Marquez recalled that the night in late
January that Cambio held a party to celebrate its rebirth, he
stayed at the event until midnight, greeting 2,000 invited guests.
He then returned to the office, working through the night to write
a long article about Venezuela's new president, Hugo Chavez, which
he finished as the sun was rising, just ahead of deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 40 years since I've done that,'' he said, delight in
his voice. ``It was wonderful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
