<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL-LAW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADMINISTRATION NOW OPPOSES INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration reversed course Tuesday
and announced opposition to the independent counsel law, saying the
21-year-old statute has diminished trust in government and should
be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   The Watergate-inspired act ``has failed in its goal of removing
politics'' from investigations of top administration officials,
Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said, urging House members to
let the law expire June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The climate of politicization pervades the process regardless
of which way a specific decision, investigation or prosecution
comes out,'' Holder told a House subcommittee. ``The act was
supposed to increase trust in our government; unfortunately, it has
diminished it.''
</P>
<P>
   The position outlined by Holder, which was developed by a
Justice Department task force and cleared by the White House, is a
turnaround from the position staked out five years ago when Clinton
and Attorney General Janet Reno urged lawmakers to renew the law.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Barry Toiv confirmed that Holder
was speaking for the administration and that White House Counsel
Charles F.C. Ruff had been involved in discussions with the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The president ``concurs with the judgment of the Justice
Department that the statute should not be renewed, that its flaws
outweigh its benefits,'' Toiv said, adding that Clinton's new
position is ``a policy decision based on his observation of how the
law's been implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   It marks the first time the administration has gone on record
against the law, which provided the statutory muscle for Kenneth
Starr's five-year investigation of Clinton's Arkansas business
dealings and cover-up of his affair with former intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's examination of the White House sex scandal prompted him
to recommend Clinton's removal from office on charges of lying
under oath and obstruction of justice. Divided along party lines,
the House impeached Clinton, which led to only the second Senate
impeachment trial of a president in U.S. history. The trial ended
last month with Clinton's acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law was passed by Congress in 1978 in
reaction to President Nixon's effort five years earlier to thwart
investigations of his administration by dismissing Archibald Cox,
the first Watergate special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires the attorney general to seek appointment of an
independent counsel when there is substantial and credible evidence
a crime has been committed by the president or a number of other
top government officials. A panel of federal judges appoints the
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   While Reno has sought appointment of seven independent counsels
in six years to investigate Clinton administration officials, she
has refused to seek appointment of a special prosecutor to examine
alleged violations of federal campaign fund-raising laws during the
1996 campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, renewal of the independent counsel law was
fought by Republicans, angered over the multiyear investigation of
the Iran-Contra scandal during the administrations of presidents
Reagan and Bush. Over the past year, Democrats have been turned
against the law by Starr's investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During his testimony Tuesday, Holder emphasized several times
that the administration's new opposition ``does not have to do with
a particular inquiry or investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said the law insulates independent counsels from normal
budget constraints and traditional Justice Department rules for
prosecutors. As a result, it ``comes dangerously close to tipping
the traditional balance of fairness in the conduct of criminal
investigations and prosecutions.''
</P>
<P>
   If the law is allowed to expire, investigations of high-ranking
government officials would revert to the Justice Department. The
attorney general, Holder said, could appoint special prosecutors in
cases where conflicts of interest clearly exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress' substantial oversight and funding powers, when
coupled with the power of the press, constitute a structure of
accountability,'' Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   Holder's comments before the House Subcommittee on Commercial
and Administrative Law were the latest from Democrats and
Republicans who favor allowing the law to expire June 30 rather
than trying an overhaul and extending its life for another five
years.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was chaired by Rep. George Gekas, a Pennsylvania
Republican who was one of the 13 House members who prosecuted the
impeachment case against Clinton during his Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Another hearing into the future of the independent counsel law
is set for today before the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee,
which is expected to hear from Washington lawyer Robert Bennett,
one of Clinton's personal attorneys. Reno is to testify later this
month before the Senate panel, chaired by Sen. Fred Thompson,
R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
