<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORY  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BAND-IN-BERLIN-THEATER (New York) _ Broadway is new territory
for Susan Feldman. Not that she works far away: she is the director
of the well-known Arts at St. Ann's program in Brooklyn Heights.
Nor is she a stranger to music theater. She has produced and
commissioned a range of work since 1979, including ``Songs for
'Drella,'' Lou Reed and John Cale's piece about Andy Warhol. But
Arts at St. Ann's, at the Church of St. Ann and the Holy Trinity,
is more commonly associated with the Brooklyn Academy of Music than
with Broadway, and Ms. Feldman is thought of more as a producer of
other people's work than as the creator of her own. Nevertheless,
after a long incubation period, she has conceived, written and
co-directed her first Broadway show. Entitled ``Band in Berlin,''
it opens Sunday night at the Helen Hayes Theater. By Anne Midgette.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIAL-FILMS (New York) _ A series of millennial films from
seven countries entitled 2000 Seen By, opens in New York on Friday
for the first leg of a pre-millennial tour around the country. By
Karen Durbin.
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-SHAKESPEARE (Los Angeles) _ Even before the nominations
for the 71st annual Academy Awards were announced on Feb. 9, the
Miramax the Disney-owned company's juggernaut was at work, spinning
journalists and spending lavishly on trade paper advertisements
promoting the films, notably ``Shakespeare in Love.'' The
nominations cemented the belief that ``Shakespeare in Love,'' a
charming romantic comedy, directed by John Madden and starring
Gwyneth Paltrow and Joseph Fiennes, had emerged as (italics)the(end
italics) rival to ``Saving Private Ryan'' for the best picture
award. The awards will be given, for the first time ever on a
Sunday evening, on March 21. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   ACADEMY-AWARDS (Undated) _ With only two weeks to go until the
Oscars, my local movie theater is running a promotional spot for
this year's Academy Awards show. There they are, all the memories _
James Cameron crowing, David Niven fielding the streaker, Cher
winning for ``Moonstruck'' in the bird headdress _ in a pitch meant
to trumpet Oscar's glory. ``It's the night that brings the whole
world together and sets Hollywood apart!'' the ad exclaims. Since
when do we need reminding? At the very least, America's love-hate
relationship with the most divine of traditional awards shows
should mean a red-circled date on the calendar. Yet each year, the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences comes closer to
weakening its franchise and its hold on our collective imagination.
By Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   20-DATES-FILM (Undated) _ For his first film, Myles Berkowitz
set up his camera and hoped for the worst. Inspired by Ross
McElwee's personal odyssey ``Sherman's March,'' a funny, rambling
first-hand account of that director's fraught relationship with
women, Berkowitz decided to film a series of his own dates. The
resulting movie, ``20 Dates,'' nudges real life along by
orchestrating its humorous situations. Closer in technique to MTV's
``Real World'' than to ``Sherman's March,'' it is cinema verite
that has slipped on a banana peel. By bending the rules to send up
the conventions of romance, Berkowitz, 36, produced a movie that
defies genre labels. By Ted Loos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DANCEGALAXY (New York) _ Dance, like youth, may be wasted on the
young. That is one of the premises of DanceGalaxy, a new ballet
troupe founded by Judith Fugate and Medhi Bahiri, which makes its
formal New York debut on Tuesday at the Joyce Theater. Ms. Fugate
and Bahiri are part of a growing trend, in modern dance for the
most part, of providing showcases for the kind of burnished
artistry that comes only with age. By Jennifer Dunning. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (Undated) _ Vincent Canby reviews: ``Not About
Nightingales'' ``The Hothouse'' and ``Bright Lights Big City.''
</P>
<P>
   SLY-OPERA (Undated) _ Like Verdi's ``Falstaff,'' which preceded
it on the boards of La Scala by nearly three and a half decades,
Ermanno Wolf-Ferrari's ``Sly'' plays fast and loose with
Shakespeare, in the process enriching the material almost past
recognition. Unlike Falstaff, who marched straight from
Shakespeare's quill onto the Great Stage of Archetypes, Sly is a
character even his begetter promptly forgot. But Giovacchino
Forzano, a man of letters and the theater active at La Scala in the
first half of this century, saw Sly's potential. A play resulted,
and eventually an opera, which receives its belated American
premiere on Wednesday at the Washington Opera. By Matthew
Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   SNAKEBIT-THEATER (Undated) _ David Marshall Grant's first play,
``Snakebit,'' which reopens Monday at the Century Center for the
Performing Arts in New York City, seems to succeed in keeping
things small. Peter Marks, writing in The New York Times, called
the play ``the intimate sort of Off Broadway theater that has you
picking apart the characters long after the curtain falls.'' Not
that you would want to trade places with any of the central
characters in ``Snakebit''; they are all at various stages of
anxiety or depression. By Jesse Mckinley. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-LANGUAGE (Undated) _ Why is it that Americans (with
splendid exceptions) are valued internationally more for their
usefulness and versatility than for intimate personal contact with
Verdi or Puccini? And why do Italians, often with sketchy musical
backgrounds and faulty technique, sometimes penetrate their roles
more convincingly. The question is easy to answer. Italian is the
Italian's language, and Puccini begins with words. Melody, harmony
and rhythm are his way of getting words off the printed page and
into our ears. Italian singers don't imitate their language's
distinctive vowels and consonants; the right sound is a birthright.
And when a word in a libretto bears specific emotional baggage, the
Italian shapes it without thinking. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   COSI-FAN-TUTTE-OPERA (Undated) _ Many Mozart experts and opera
buffs will no doubt dismiss a recent release of ``Cosi Fan Tutte''
from Sony Classical with a knowing huff. It is a reissue of a 1952
recording, with Fritz Stiedry conducting the orchestra and chorus
of the Metropolitan Opera Association, as it was then called
(Masterworks Heritage MH2K 60652; two CDs). So what's the problem?
Mozart's opera, written in Italian, is performed in English. ``Cosi
Fan Tutte'' becomes ``Women Are Like That.'' And the recitatives
are accompanied not by a historically appropriate harpsichord or
fortepiano, as they would be today, but by a modern piano. Yet the
recording is a joy. The pleasure comes partly from nostalgia. By
Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY-CLASSICAL (Undated) _ Country has long been packaged as
the classical music of simple American folks. The transformation of
hillbilly entertainment into an official repository of our national
traditions has extended from the fancy naming of the Grand Ole Opry
in 1927 to the appointment of William Ivey, the director of the
Country Music Hall of Fame, to the chair of the National Endowment
for the Arts in 1998. Country music finds its real power in the
tension between nostalgia and the need for change, a contradiction
mined on two new albums. ``The Mountain,'' by Steve Earle with the
Del McCoury Band, investigates country's most classical form,
bluegrass. ``What I Deserve,'' by Kelly Willis, takes a more
eclectic approach. By Ann Powers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BECKER-PHOTOGS (Los Angeles) _ Harold Becker, a former
commercial photographer in New York, used a restored 1920s camera
more than 30 years ago to take a series of abstract portraits of
the female form. An exhibition of his work opened in Los Angeles
last month at the New Alchemy Gallery. The show is the fifth in a
series titled ``Still/Moving'' and runs through April 6. Since last
May, it has been a showcase for the still photography of Hollywood
professionals, for the most part cinematographers. By David Hay.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
