<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAWN-MULLINS-MUSIC-A     03-02 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAWN-MULLINS-MUSIC-ART-825(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURTURING AN `OVERNIGHT' SUCCESS, 9 YEARS IN THE MAKING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ga., Fla.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (jw)  
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shawn Mullins was nearly two hours into his stay on
``Regis and Kathy Lee,'' and the three or so minutes he would spend
playing music had just concluded. Mullins, a Georgia-based
singer-songwriter, grinned while Regis Philbin quizzed him about
his recent Grammy nomination. In his worn brown jacket and rumpled
blond hair, Mullins looked as if he would be more comfortable
discussing poetry in a Village bar.
</P>
<P>
   He did not fade when he had to recount stories that he has
shared with scores of other interviewers about his nine years of
struggling and his break with the hit single ``Lullaby.'' He kept
smiling because he felt pleased to be there, but also because right
now smiling is part of his job.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after a limousine sped him south from Lincoln Square,
where the ABC morning show is taped, to the Paramount Hotel, where
he was staying, Mullins excused himself to decompress briefly.
``I'm just real honest,'' he said upon resurfacing. ``By the eighth
interview of the day if I think I'm going to be bad, I'll say we
need to reschedule. I just ask for what I need and try to do it
like a gentleman. A lot of artists don't want to say anything, and
then they eventually blow up. I am a product, I know. I'm pretty
aware of how to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   If things were different, if he were different, Mullins, 30,
would be a perfect candidate for psychic explosion. Last spring,
after nearly a decade of playing tiny clubs, he won the lottery of
pop. He had hoped to spend his life as a moderately successful
singer-songwriter, and his countrified soul man's voice and
empathetic songs had gained him some attention. But he got more
than he had dared hope for.
</P>
<P>
   He'd written ``Lullaby,'' a song about a Hollywood wild child
with a sweeping chorus and a hip-hop beat, for ``Soul's Core,'' his
eighth album, initially released on SMG Records, the label he runs
with his fiancee, Kelly Hobbs. Atlanta's Top 40 radio station 99-X
started playing it, and it became a local smash. Mullins, who had
often played smaller spots like the Bitter End, showcased at the
Bottom Line, New York City's renowned singer-songwriter venue in
June, to a house full of record executives eager to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about labels feeding off the one song,'' he
said. ``I listened carefully as I was talking to people. One in
particular, he's the head of a huge, huge music group, a great guy
and I'm sure a brilliant man, but he didn't know anything but
`Lullaby.' I asked him if he'd heard anything else on the record,
and he said no. I saw his two assistants gritting their teeth and I
was so sorry but that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   He chose Columbia, the label of Bob Dylan and Bruce Springsteen,
partly because Columbia's president, Don Iennar, had more deeply
understood ``Soul's Core.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he thought `Lullaby' was awesome, a great hit,''
Mullins said. ``But he also said `Twin Rocks, Oregon' was a really
cool song. His intention from the get-go was to make me a career
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   The executives at Columbia assured Mullins that the label would
be committed for the long haul. First, though, everyone agreed to
put some serious promotional money behind ``Lullaby.'' A
publicity-garnering video featuring the actress Dominique Swain,
who played Lolita in Adrian Lyne's 1998 film, turned the song into
an event. Columbia heavily marketed the single to radio, television
and the press.
</P>
<P>
   Led by ``Lullaby,'' the rereleased ``Soul's Core'' went gold by
the year's end. He said he had hoped that it would sell 20,000
copies last year; now it was selling 30,000 to 40,000 a week. Soon
the former folk music road warrior was sharing an arena stage with
Shania Twain and other hit makers. He was nominated for a Grammy
for best male pop vocal performance. (Eric Clapton won.)
</P>
<P>
   ``One month I'm playing at coffeehouses for 40 or 50 people, and
in debt,'' he said. ``Three months later I'm at Madison Square
Garden. It's a blessing, and it's a hard thing to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lullaby'' was a gift, a country-flavored, rap-influenced
modern rock song with an infectiousness that songwriters aim for
but rarely capture. It suited today's diverse pop market, which
unites teenybopper bands like 'N Sync with heavy metalists like
Korn, hard rappers like Jay-Z and silky divas like Kelly Price. Now
it is lodged in the brains of pop listeners, guaranteeing Mullins a
lifelong ounce of fame. But he wants a serious career as a
singer-songwriter.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Carter, the Atlanta-based manager who represents his
friends the Indigo Girls and fellow fledgling hit makers Fastball,
plans to help Mullins earn it. ``Shawn is prolific, he has great
production ideas and he has his ear to the ground,'' he said.
``He's not a Top 40 act like 'N Sync. What we want to do is create
a singer-songwriter career that can sustain him as an artist for
the next 25 years.''
</P>
