<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, March 3, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact David Brady at the Daily News, (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN-PRESIDENT (Los Angeles) _ Blenda J. Wilson, president of
California State University, Northridge, and the first
African-American president in the CSU system, announced she is
ending her seven-year tenure at the college and taking a job with
the Nellie Mae Foundation, a Braintree, Mass.-based nonprofit
organization that provides federal and private loans to students.
By Sharline Chiang. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-STUDENTS (Los Angeles) _ Police located two of the 32
missing Chinese students at a home in suburban Covina and believe
their disappearance from Los Angeles International Airport was the
result of a communications mix-up between tour operators. By
Deborah Sullivan and Sharline Chiang. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   SLIDE-THREAT (Los Angeles) _ Robert Weinstein says the abandoned
house on the hill behind his was badly damaged in the 1994
Northridge Earthquake and now is about to slide into his home _ and
the city won't do anything to stop it. By Phil Davis. (Will move in
the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   XYLAN-DEAL (Los Angeles) _ Alcatel's purchase of Calabasas,
Calif.-based Xylan Corp. will allow the French telecommunications
company to strengthen its position as a major equipment supplier to
U.S. telephone companies, using Xylan's switches to provide
high-speed data networks. By Ben Sullivan. (Will move in the ``f''
financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   XYLAN-PROFILE (Los Angeles) _ What is Xylan, what does it make
and why is it so important that a number of companies were rumored
to be interested in buying it? By Ben Sullivan. (Will move in the
``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-TRADE (Los Angeles) _ Despite the Asian economic crisis, Los
Angeles still beat out New York and the nation's other customs
districts for import-export traffic in 1998, according to a report
released Tuesday. By Jason Takenouchi. (Will move in the ``f''
financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAWN-MULLINS-MUSIC-A     03-02 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAWN-MULLINS-MUSIC-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: 25 years.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To that end, Carter is bent on establishing a live reputation
for Mullins. ``He needs to headline his own dates and find his own
audience as a live act,'' he said. ``That might mean turning down
an opening slot on a big tour. It's critical for him to perform a
90-minute set for people who are there to see him.'' He will play
one such date on Friday night at Irving Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins is not above doing promotion-driven events like the
championship round of Bandemonium, a battle-of-the-bands tour,
organized by the record-store chain Sam Goody, that concludes on
March 17 in Panama City Beach, Fla. Sharing the bill with two
unknown contest winners will keep his name in the media; it is
unlikely, though, that the spring break crowd will be the attentive
kind Carter wants.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Mullins will still manage to capture some new fans. He
is unusual among Top 40 performers, who are often unseasoned. He
has spent years learning how to woo a crowd. ``I was so impressed
with him,'' said Alan Pepper, an owner of the Bottom Line. ``With
all that pressure, if he was nervous you couldn't tell. He just
gave a great performance. He's got the goods: He sings great, he's
a writer, he's got a totally winning manner onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Danay, the executive who brought Mullins to Columbia, said
the label supported Carter's strategy. (Ms. Danay declined to
discuss details of the contract but the industry standard usually
binds an artist for six albums.) `` `Lullaby' has exposed Shawn to
an audience, and now we have to make sure that people really hear
his other songs,'' she said. `` `Soul's Core' is a very deep album;
there are a lot of potential singles.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Soul's Core,'' earnest love songs balance witty slices of
life and social commentary. But the depth Ms. Danay observes may
make no difference. ``The attention span of American record buyers
has shrunk incredibly,'' said Joe Fleischer, a columnist for the
trade magazine Hits, who first brought Mullins to the attention of
the industry. ``Nobody's waiting for the next single from Shawn
Mullins. All they want is another song. And the companies, artists
and managers are now OK with the idea that one single may be all
they'll get. They just try to get all they can out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice of a second single from ``Soul's Core'' is delicate.
Mullins said he would still like to be on the radio but wanted a
broader perception of his work. That was why he proposed that the
follow-up to ``Lullaby'' be ``Shimmer,'' a ballad about racial
tolerance and self-love that shows off Mullins' voice and his
musical chops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote `Shimmer' five years ago, and recorded it at the end
of 1994,'' Mullins said. ``When Columbia and I finally sat down to
plan things, I said, `I think I'd like to give this song a shot
because it's really strong.' I played it for them, and they said,
`That's the second single.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shimmer'' is initially being targeted at Triple-A radio, the
musical equivalent of VH1, which favors an older audience known to
enjoy songwriters like Billy Joel. Z 100 (WHTZ-100.3 FM), New York
City's biggest Top 40 station, is not yet playing the song, though
it favored ``Lullaby'' enough to invite Mullin to play at its
annual Jingle Ball at Madison Square Garden in December with Shania
Twain and other hit makers. Tom Poleman, Z 100 program director,
says he will pay attention to its status on less mainstream radio
stations, listen for fan requests and see how its video does.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Christopherson, who directed the ``Shimmer'' video, not
only had to follow up a splashy clip that had featured a movie
starlet; he also needed to present Mullins in a way that took him
beyond novelty status. The clip, shot in Atlanta, features a group
of locals in their Sunday best and in homey spots like a
barbershop. Mullins wears ordinary clothes and his patented sunny
smile; he has lost the groovy pink sunglasses he wore for
``Lullaby.'' His shoulder-length hair, little beard and sincere
gaze fulfill the poetic image of the modern-day troubadour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some artists require a tremendous amount of styling, but Shawn
is absolutely not one of those guys,'' Christopherson said of the
make-over process that helps many pop stars express their
personalities through clothes, hair and attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins embodies the stereotype of the sensitive artist, the
same one fulfilled by popular singer-songwriters from ``Sweet Baby
James'' Taylor to Jewel. He knows, however, that pop runs on a
paradox, requiring endless variations on the same basic themes. He
could become a mainstay of a particular pop arena, like his hero
Kris Kristofferson, whose ``Sunday Morning Coming Down'' he covers
on ``Soul's Core.'' Or he could be replaced next season by another
strumming balladeer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get emotional about it, it gets sickening,'' Mullins
said. ``So I have the artist part of myself, and the business part.
And my business person is just ruthless: He was careful to
negotiate a contract with Columbia that allows him the kind of
control he wielded by adding `Shimmer' to `Soul's Core.' '' He is
investing his money carefully, making prudent purchases like an
Atlanta house for himself and Ms. Hobbs. They still own the rights
to his seven independent albums, which are sold through their SMG
label.
</P>
<P>
   If he does end up a one-hit wonder, Mullins says, he still sees
a decent future for himself. He is writing songs these days on a
tour bus since he doesn't have to drive his van from gig to gig.
``I'll be able to play large clubs and small theaters for the next
20 years,'' he said. ``I'll probably always have Triple-A radio
play. I'll have something going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
