<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-OBASANJO-ART-     03-02 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-OBASANJO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIAN LEADER DECLARES `ABSOLUTE' BELIEF IN DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Pledging to rebuild Nigeria but also urging
caution, the president-elect said on Tuesday that he would bring
together this fractious country, where years of military
dictatorships have heightened ethnic tensions.
</P>
<P>
   The president-elect, Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, who was declared
the winner of Saturday's election on Monday, promised in his
victory speech that he would restore openness and justice. To
ordinary Nigerians who have ``borne the frustrations and
inconveniences of the past,'' he said he would revive ``the dignity
of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My first duty and priority is to reconcile the people of this
country and heal their wounds,'' he said. ``I have no doubt in my
mind that every one in our ethnically diverse society has suffered
in many ways from the unacceptable and undemocratic manner in which
we have been governed for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo, who served as military ruler from 1976 to 1979, said
he would fight corruption, clean up the military and police, remove
obstacles to domestic and foreign investment and draw home the
thousands of Nigerians who have fled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contest is over, but the process of democracy is
continuous,'' he said. ``I will continue to deepen and widen that
process for the benefit of all Nigerians. I call on all parties to
join me in that process. My belief in democracy is absolute.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked whether he favors establishing a
reconciliation commission, like the one in South Africa, to
investigate Nigeria's recent history of corruption and brutal
repression of human rights, Obasanjo did not give a clear answer.
</P>
<P>
   Many Nigerians have clamored for such a commission. But others
oppose the idea, fearing it would further divide the country and
perhaps even provoke an angry reaction from the powerful military.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Obasanjo accused him of being the candidate of these
powerful retired generals, who financed his party, the People's
Democratic Party, and who endorsed him personally.
</P>
<P>
   The general's political opponents contend that the retired
generals supported him because they felt confident he would not
investigate them if he was elected.
</P>
<P>
   His televised speech, in Abuja, the capital, was preceded by a
private meeting in the presidential suite on the seventh floor of
the Hilton Abuja, where Obasanjo is staying. In a small inner room,
surrounded by supporters, new governors and his wife, Stella,
Obasanjo received Gen. Yakubu Gowon, who ruled Nigeria from 1966 to
1975.
</P>
<P>
   Gowon was deposed in a bloodless coup by Gen. Murtala Muhammed,
whose assassination in 1976 led to the elevation of his deputy,
Obasanjo, to the presidency. Gowon offered congratulations and
urged all Nigerians to rally around the president-elect.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of journalists present were on their way out of the
suite when another visitor offering congratulations walked in: Gen.
Ibrahim Babangida.
</P>
<P>
   Babangida ruled Nigeria from 1985 to 1993 and set no fewer than
five dates for a transition to civilian rule that never came. He
was the one who annulled the 1993 presidential elections, which
Moshood Abiola apparently won, a decision that plunged Nigeria into
the political darkness from which it is still emerging.
</P>
<P>
   Babangida _ whose nicknames run from Evil Genius to Maradona,
after the Argentine soccer star, for his crafty footwork _ is
thought to have been Obasanjo's chief backer during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The three generals embraced and bantered, and traded a local
joke about winning and winning well.
</P>
<P>
   Babangida took no questions but allowed photographs and made a
brief comment: ``I believe the people have made the right choice. I
said six months ago that this country needs him. So I say
congratulations. Over the years, people didn't get to know what
government is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``All hands must be on deck to move this nation forward. We can
always build it together. I believe in the greatness of this
country, and I think we will get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
