<SLUG> BC-MUSKET-EXEMPTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECREATORS' MUSKETS EXEMPTED FROM STIFF BAY STATE WEAPONS LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Declare it a victory for historic battle buffs.
</P>
<P>
   Those who reenact famous battles will be able to carry antique
or replica muskets without worrying about breaking the law,
following votes Tuesday in the Legislature. Lawmakers amended the
stringent controls on assault weapons by exempting the older
firearms from required safety locks.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, guns stored or transported in Massachusetts
must have locking devices or be in locked containers. But a debate
has been raging as to whether the new law applied to antique and
replica muskets.
</P>
<P>
   While lawyers tried to sort it out, reenactors planning to
attend the Battles of Lexington and Concord next month _ a dress
rehearsal for next year's huge 225th anniversary staging of the
Revolutionary War events _ said they might not attend for fear of
being arrested.
</P>
<P>
   But the quick movement on Beacon Hill saved the Patriots Day
battles, as well as Friday's reenactment of the Boston Massacre
near the Old State House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were we not to act today, the echo would be still heard on
Friday and on Patriots Day,'' said Representative Jay Kaufman, a
Lexington Democrat. Patriots Day, a Massachusetts holiday, is April
19.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci is expected to sign off on the amendment
exempting muskets made before 1899 from trigger locks and storage
requirements. The amendment passed the House and Senate unanimously
Tuesday, however, not without a few members offering the proverbial
I told you so.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we debated the gun bill last year, those of us who
opposed it said it was poorly written and riddled with errors,''
Representative Ronald Gauch, a Shrewsbury Repulican, said on the
House floor. ``We are correcting a problem that should have been
avoided. The bill placed a tremendous burden on law-abiding gun
owners and sportsmen. It should have been focused on punishing
criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   The reenactments, drawing participants from around the world,
had been in a state of chaos over the last few months since the
assault weapons controls were enacted. British forces even
threatened to pull out of the events.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment will have an immediate impact on two historic
muskets hanging in the Senate chamber, one from the battle of
Lexington and Concord and the other the first gun seized from the
British during the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham recently had both firearms
outfitted with trigger locks after the Gun Owners Action League, a
group that fought the new law, pointed out the guns violated the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Now those bright orange locks will be removed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 1932EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
