A5046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-MEXICO-COX     03-02 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-MEXICO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Penalties against Mexico unlikely
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two of the harshest critics of the Clinton
administration's Mexican drug policy said Tuesday they will not
seek to reverse President Clinton's decision to certify Mexico as
fully cooperating with the United States in the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement from Sens. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) and Dianne
Feinstein (D-Calif.) means that Clinton's decision Friday to
certify Mexico in the war on drugs probably will not be overturned
by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think in the end that will happen,'' said Coverdell, a
member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, which has
jurisdiction over Mexican issues.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) joined a handful of GOP House
members in what they conceded was an uphill battle to overturn the
president's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell and Feinstein have been among the harshest critics of
the administration in the annual battle over certification of
nations cooperating in the drug war.
</P>
<P>
   A decision not to certify can mean cutoff of trade and other
economic subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Coverdell and Feinstein withdrew a bid to overturn
the administration's decision to certify Mexico after extracting a
commitment from Clinton to measure more carefully Mexico's progress
in eradicating drug production and cracking down on the powerful
cartels that ship drugs to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Drug Enforcement Administration Director Tom
Constintine recently testified that Mexico had undertaken ``limited
enforcement action'' in the past year, both senators said they
wanted to give the effort more time to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican government is doing everything they can to be
cooperative,'' Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of fighting the Clinton administration over
certification, Coverdell and Feinstein will back new legislation to
blacklist individuals and businesses associated with the drug
trade. Individuals and businesses placed on the list would be
barred from doing any trade or business with the United States and
U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 companies associated with drug trafficking were
forced out of business in Colombia, where a black list has been in
effect since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It simply says you cannot participate in any trade of any kind
with the businesses and corporations of this nation,'' Coverdell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to certify Mexico still faces considerable
opposition in the House, where two committees plan hearings this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sorry story down there,'' said Rep. Spencer Bachus
(R-Ala.), who has introduced a resolution to overturn Clinton's
certification but exempt Mexico from any financial penalties. ``It
just defies imagination that the president would say Mexico is
fully cooperating.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual twist, Barr and Coverdell are on opposite sides of
the certification issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be privy to some information that I don't have,'' Barr
said of Coverdell. ``The information I have leads me to believe
that Mexico is not fully cooperating.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
