A5047 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-Y2K-BOS &LR;      03-02 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-Y2K-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS CONFRONT Y2K REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Forget Y2K. Now, it's all about TEOTWAWKI.
</P>
<P>
   The dire acronym for ``the end of the world as we know it,''
which predicts what will occur at the stroke of midnight, Jan. 1,
2000, is in vogue on Web sites. Tuesday it made its way at last
into the Senate, as lawmakers met in a closed session to discuss
the potential Year 2000 crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Most said afterward that there was no reason to panic. But as
senators discussed the contents of a 160-page report on the topic,
they occasionally uttered warnings that made the Y2K problem seem
like a legitimate threat.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Dodd advised citizens to stock up on canned goods.
Senator Gordon Smith suggested passengers ask airlines about Y2K
before boarding a plane that night. Senator Robert Bennett said
there was a great likelihood of economic disruptions around the
world as a result of computer glitches accompanying the turn of the
millenium _ though he said national-security concerns appeared to
be less of a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a low probability of a nuclear launch,'' Bennett
said, while refusing to rule out the possibility of
intercontinental warfare.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks followed a private session devoted in part to
informing senators about the Y2K problems faced by other countries
_ particularly Russia and China, whose military forces appear
ill-equipped to handle the added stress of a possible computer
breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said Russia in particular faced the threat of
``deterioration of their military capabilities because of Y2K
simply adds to their problems,'' such as their inability to pay the
salaries of members of the military in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the world, particularly in regions with shaky
economies, Bennett said there is a ``medium probability of economic
disruptions that will lead to civil unrest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the chances of difficulty are much higher
internationally,'' said Bennett, the Utah Republican who heads the
Senate's Special Committee on the Year 2000 Problem.
</P>
<P>
   To address the potential threat of international war, lawmakers
are considering establishing a center in Colorado Springs, Colo.,
where officials from foreign countries would gather to observe one
another at the turn of the millenium, to make sure no nation was
launching a military offensive. Dodd described the facility as the
``Center for the Year 2000 Strategic Abilities,'' and said Russia
was the only nation on the guest list so far.
</P>
<P>
   To address potential problems at home, the Senate Tuesday
unanimously passed legislation to help guarantee loans to small
businesses in order for them to fix their computer systems. The
House has yet to act on the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry of Massachusetts, ranking Democrat on the
Small Business Committee, said that ``unless businesses deal with
that issue now, they can wind up losing money and being hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   But in general, Kerry said, ``in this country, I think the
effects will be negligible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's great dangers here,'' he said. ``I think
there are much greater dangers abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Although domestic companies are far better equipped to face the
new millenium, medical centers are still unprepared; some 64
percent of the nation's 6,000 hospital facitilies have yet to
adjust their computer systems, according to a report by the Gartner
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Some 80 percent of all doctors offices _ many of whom would
qualify for assistance through the loan bill the Senate passed
Tuesday _ are equally unprepared for the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications and energy systems are far better off,
Bennett said. He also dismissed a test failure at a power plant in
York, Pa., last month as ``not in any way life-threatening or
safety-threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   The failure, Bennett said, occurred when power plant officials
turned the clocks forward during a Year 2000 test. The plant's
system failed, leaving officials mystified for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   But, Bennett said: ``That's why you do tests. Let's not
overreact to that.''
</P>
<P>
   But senators did hint at fears of traveling on the night the
century turns. Smith, a Republican from Oregon, said airlines are
likely to hold their computer systems to a higher standard than
even the government recommends, but cautioned that passengers
should contact airlines before taking a flight.
</P>
<P>
   And Dodd, a Democrat from Connecticut, said travelers going
abroad for New Year's Eve ``might want to go a few days early and
stay another couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The analysis we've been given here is that about 90 percent of
the problems that we could face at home should be remediated or
resolved within 72 hours...So I wouldn't be discouraging people
from foreign travel,'' Dodd said. ``But if I had to make
reservations today or had to do it, I'd certainly leave a little
leeway on either side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
