A5048 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-02 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WORKING ON POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (jw)  
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Courage is a quality in short supply with
politicians of any era, and especially now. So it seemed odd at
lunch this week with Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of Housing and
Urban Development, to hear him insist, passionately and
un-self-consciously, that now is the time to move on behalf of the
perennial underdogs in our society _ the families living in squalor
and hopelessness on Indian reservations, or in the economic and
social wreckage that has defined Appalachia for decades, or in the
worst of our inner cities, which continue to be dangerous and
isolated crucibles of despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have real people in real pain that we have to attend to,''
said Cuomo, who toured the poverty-ridden coal mining regions of
West Virginia last week.
</P>
<P>
   With the U.S. economy humming, and with the budget deficit gone,
there is an unprecedented opportunity to make investments that will
bring training and real jobs to men and women for whom employment
has been little more than a distant memory, or a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is breaking all sorts of records,'' Cuomo said.
``And because the economy is strong we want to say everything is
good. A lot of things are good. Employment is up, crime is down,
poverty is down, welfare is down. But at the same time we have a
lot of significant problems.''
</P>
<P>
   He picked up a stack of large color photographs and spread them
across a table. ``The Dow Jones? They don't know from it,'' he
said, pointing to individuals in the photos who have been so
hounded for so long by poverty in the Mississippi Delta, on the
Pine Ridge Reservation in South Dakota, on the South Side of
Chicago, that they cannot imagine an economically viable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great economy, yes,'' said Cuomo. ``But you go to
Appalachia, it's just like it was 30 years ago. We've had some
success with the cities, but overall the cities are not doing well.
They are smaller, poorer, and the poverty is more concentrated than
20 years ago. You want to say the poverty rate has come down? Yes.
But it's still one in five.'' He was referring to the fact that
even in these most prosperous of times, one in five American
children lives in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 poorest counties in the United States are rural, and
their poverty rates are staggering, in some cases higher than 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The way to deal with these problems is to put people to work,
said Cuomo. And because the economy is doing so well, the necessary
investments should be made now. ``You fix the hole in the roof when
the sun is shining,'' he said, ``not when it's raining.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal, said Cuomo, is to get businesses and jobs into
poverty-stricken areas, or to get residents of depressed areas into
jobs that are located elsewhere. ``We have some new approaches to
these problems that are designed to create jobs by stimulating the
private market economy,'' said Cuomo. ``It will require government
action because the private market is not going to South Central Los
Angeles without a subsidy. Period. So you have to say, `If you go
to South Central L.A., I'll give you a tax break.' That's Jack
Kemp's enterprise zones. Or you say, `If you hire a person from
South Central, I'll subsidize their salary.' That's Charlie Rangel.
We do both, but it has to be about either creating jobs or getting
people into jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   In an era in which technological miracles have become
commonplace, it is possible to get good jobs to the unlikeliest
places. Cuomo recently asked a gathering of executives if their
operations could function out of the Pine Ridge Reservation. Sure,
he was told. For the right price, they could work anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo is trying to spread the word that there are many Americans
living in squalor and with very little hope at a time when the
nation is more prosperous than ever. He insists they can be helped
to help themselves, and that it is in the national interest to
offer that initial help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president talks about untapped markets,'' Cuomo said.
``Where do we still have the economic potential, the untapped
markets where the economy can still grow? It's the very same areas
that need the help. The high-unemployment areas. The high-poverty
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how to do this. We have the resources. The excuses are
gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
