<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5050 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-OPTIONS-BOS &LR;      03-02 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-OPTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY ENTERS NEW PHASE WITH TV APPEARANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Let the marketing of Monica begin.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night the former White House intern known almost
exclusively for her sexual escapades with the president talks to TV
celebrity confessor Barbara Walters. Thursday her own story in her
own words hits bookstores. By Friday, the campaign to resuscitate
her reputation _ and make everyone a pile of cash along the way _
will be as intense as the campaign for New Coke.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains to be seen whether consumers will accept the
newly sweetened version of Monica Lewinsky. She was, after all, an
unknown before dallying with Bill Clinton. Now she is known mostly
for the sort of behavior that makes people smirk, or simply makes
them mad.
</P>
<P>
   Still, public relations specialists and others who sell America
on people and products said the name Monica Lewinsky could also
mean money, and not just the quick kind. The trick, they stressed,
is in knowing which opportunities to grab and which to flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who's given their 15 minutes of fame can turn it into
something positive or negative,'' said Steve Connelly, president of
Ingalls Advertising in Boston. ``How the fame is acquired is moot.
Give me 15 minutes with Barbara Walters and I can make something
happen. The question is: Is she savvy enough to do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, 25, has been smart enough to surround herself with
handlers. There is a publicist retained by the publisher of
``Monica's Story,'' St. Martin's Press, and another retained by the
Lewinsky family. There are agents and legal advisors, not to
mention her parents.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the strategy has been one of restraint, at least in the
United States. Except for her televised deposition, Lewinsky has
not been heard from publicly since her relationship with Clinton
became known more than a year ago. Beside a starlet spread in
Vanity Fair magazine, the only photographs of her have come from
the paparrazzi.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks building up to the book's release, she and her
family have been more forthcoming in Europe, where Channel Four in
Britain paid $600,000 for an interview and where Lewinsky has posed
for magazines and will soon be signing copies of her story. No
signings are planned statewide. Still, reporters everywhere will be
stuck interviewing biographer Andrew Morton, who actually wrote the
book, since Lewinsky is still under a contract of sorts to
independent prosecutor Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to me that distance and dignity was the way to go,''
said Lynn Goldberg, who is handling publicity for Lewinsky and
Morton. ``This woman has been exploited. We want to sell books, but
we also need to protect her.''
</P>
<P>
   Also needing protection is Lewinsky's long-term image,
specialists said. Unlike actress Pamela Lee Anderson, caught on
videotape having sex with her husband, or sportscaster Marv Albert,
captured in court testimony wearing women's underwear, Lewinsky has
no reservoir of good will to draw on now. As Barry Glassner, a
sociologist at the University of Southern California who has
studied career crashes, put it, ``They had something to go back to.
In her case, it's all about what she becomes in the public mind in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the image experts agreed, Lewinsky must appear
sympathetic in Wednesday night's television interview (Walters says
she does) as well as remorseful (Lewinsky, apologizing to the
nation and First Family, says she is). Once that is done, they
added, she could capitalize on her notoriety in any number of ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would put her up for guest roles and Hollywood would jump
because Hollywood is the most forgiving place in the world,'' said
Sherri Spillane, president of the Ruth Webb Talent Agency in Los
Angeles, whose clients have included disgraced auto mechanic Joey
Buttafuoco, disgraced televangelist Tammy Faye Bakker, disgraced
ice skater Tonya Harding and Divine Brown, the prostitute who
helped disgrace actor Hugh Grant when he was arrested in her
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as she didn't make silly moves, she'd be off and
running,'' Spillane added. ``I'd try to get her a commercial,
personal appearances. It'd be endless.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the jokes that have Lewinsky as their punchline,
many of the career avenues now open to her are obvious. She could
do product endorsements, although advertising specialists advised
against cigars or lipstick if she wants to be more than a famous
fluke. She could even get her own talk show, since her name alone
would guarantee an audience at least briefly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely difficult to put your name in the public mind,
so she's 99.9 percent of the way toward having an enormous career
as, what else, a celebrity,'' said Al Ries, a marketing strategist
whose firm is based in the Atlanta suburb of Roswell. ``Of course
she's got to have a message. She's got to tell the public what she
has learned and how this has made her a better woman and tell women
how this will help her help them deal with the issues that they
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Ries urged Lewinsky to shun advertisements, no matter how
tasteful. Otherwise, he said, she could become another Donna Rice,
who posed for No Excuses jeans after her relationship with
Democratic presidential hopeful Gary Hart was exposed and then
disappeared from public view. A better role model would be Vanessa
Williams, who lost her Miss America crown after magazines published
nude pictures of her, kept a low profile for some time, then went
on to become a movie and music star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously she could have her own talk show, but that would be
a sad exploitation of what seems to be an intelligent woman caught
in a difficult or interesting situation,'' said Larry Weber, chief
executive officer of Weber Public Relations Worldwide in Cambridge,
Mass. ``She should definitely not do commercials unless it's
absolutely necessary to pay off her debts. That would be wrong for
living a happy and thoughtful life, and I know I sound more like a
therapist than a marketing adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives make no secret of the fact that they expect the
Lewinsky interview to be a ratings bonanza. Though the network is
in third place with two days remaining in the February ``sweeps''
period, Stu Bloomberg, chairman of ABC entertainment, said that
``it ain't over until the intern sings.'' He added: ``We hope
everybody's going to be watching Wednesday night.''
</P>
<P>
   As the image specialists recommended she should, Lewinsky
reportedly speaks candidly Wednesday night about her experiences
with Clinton and since Clinton -- and she does in the company of
the interviewer troubled celebrities everywhere seek out. Walters,
in a network statement, called her ``extremely articulate, poised
and often quite funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky also says she loved the president, an admission that
some image consultants said could make her more likable to
Americans in general and to American women in particular. Neither
of them felt good about what the affair, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a very sensual man who has a lot of sensual
feelings,'' Lewinsky said in an excerpt from the interview released
Tuesday. ``And I think he also has a very strong religious
upbringing. . .I think he struggles with his sensuality because I
don't think he thinks it's okay. . . . He tries to hold himself
back. And then can't any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Don White, who heads the marketing group at Hill, Holliday,
Connors, Cosmopulous, a Boston-based communications agency, said
Lewinsky will be performing a delicate balancing act Wednesday
night. She must appear confident, but not too confident or viewers
may be reminded of early and misleading allegations that she
stalked the president. She needs to show that she is both
intelligent and a victim. She needs to help people get past their
first impressions of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should never put herself in a position that reminds people
of what she's famous for,'' said White, who did not spurn the idea
of endorsements as long as they are not self-parodying. ``She could
have some longevity, but if everything she does is based on what
happened to her last year, then no.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what steps Lewinsky takes or who she becomes, several
consultants said, the reason for her initial fame will haunt her.
Spillane, the Hollywood publicist, went so far as to insist that a
``normal'' life is now impossible for Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way for that to happen is for her to change her name
and have plastic surgery to look like someone else and move to the
middle of nowhere,'' she said. ``No one will ever let her forget
it. She's just got to figure out how to use that to her
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Don Aucoin, a Globe TV writer, contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
