<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOCK-GIFT-COX     03-02 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-GIFT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unexpected gift given to Georgia beneficiaries
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Emory University, Young Harris College, a children's
home and retired Methodist pastors are the beneficiaries of the
$192 million estate of a South Georgia woman and her father.
</P>
<P>
   The gifts will fund scholarships at Emory's Candler School of
Theology and at Young Harris, shore up a ministers pension fund
that labors under a $30 million liability and secure the future of
a children's home in Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Adger Pitts of Waverly Hall, near Columbus, died in
July at the age of 104. Her death activated conditions not only of
her will, but also the will of her father, W.I.H. Pitts, who died
in the mid-1960s at the age of 103.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Pitts was a Waverly Hall dry goods merchant who built a
fortune based on Coca-Cola stock in the 1920s. His estate is worth
about $130 million and his daughter's is valued at about $62
million.
</P>
<P>
   The institutions will receive dividends from the investments of
the estate held in trust, about one percent of the value each year.
They will ask SunTrust Bank, the trust administrator, for the total
annual return of the trusts' value, about 4 or 5 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   For Emory University, the gift is the third-largest in its
history. Emory's Candler School of Theology will receive the income
from half of the W.I.H. Pitts estate, which currently would be
worth about $65 million.
</P>
<P>
   Young Harris College in North Georgia will receive the income
from about $63.5 million, coming from both estates. Young Harris
now has the highest endowment of any two-year college in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The Methodist Home for Children and Youth in Macon, also a
beneficiary of both estates, will receive the income from about
$47.25 million _ multiplying its current $8 million endowment by
six.
</P>
<P>
   A pension fund for ministers in South Georgia will receive the
income from about $16.25 million, about an eighth of Mr. Pitt's
estate. The Board of Pensions for the South Georgia Conference of
the United Methodist Church currently has an unfunded liability of
$30 million for ministers for the years they served prior to 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very significant in the history of American
philanthropy,'' said William Chace, president of Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Emory received $105 million in 1979 from Robert W. Woodruff, the
late Coca-Cola magnate. In 1996, the Emory Health Sciences received
$295 million from the Robert W. Woodruff Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great impediment to going into the ministry is the student
loans that have to be paid off,'' said R. Kevin LaGree, dean of the
Candler School of Theology. ``We will begin next fall to fund six
full scholarships named for Margaret Pitts. It will be full tuition
plus $3,000 annual stipend. We will add six scholarships a year for
three years for a total of 18.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Harris, the tiny North Georgia college that boasts alumni
such as former Gov. Zell Miller, also intends to spend much of its
new-found income on scholarships, according to President Thomas S.
Yow III. Yow said Mr. Pitts became interested in Young Harris
because the son of his secretary was a student there.
</P>
<P>
   Yow said he would occasionally visit with Miss Pitts, who never
married, and they would have lunch together at a restaurant in Warm
Springs. ``On her 100th birthday, I asked her what she was going to
do for the next 100 years,'' Yow said. ``She said, `I'm going to
find me a man.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Yow laughed. ``I thought to myself, `Gosh, I hope not.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Pitts was always interested in the Methodist Home for
Children and Youth in Macon. ``We have a cottage on our campus that
we call Miss Margaret's house,'' said Steve Rumford, administrator
of the home. ``She was here at the groundbreaking, and she had a
shovel in her hand. She was 103. She was sitting in a wheelchair
with the shovel. She had a tremendous love for Methodist
institutions in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumford said the children's home will use its proceeds from the
estate to help fund prevention services for disadvantaged children.
``This is a defining point in how we will address the next
century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Donald M. Kea, chairman of the Board of Pensions for the South
Georgia Conference of the United Methodist Church and senior
minister of the Albany First United Methodist Church, was a pastor
in Waverly Hall when Mr. Pitts died. The minister recalled how he
was always concerned with the support of retired preachers. ``He
had given two homes to retired ministers in Waverly Hall,'' Kea
said. ``It was one of his philanthropies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kea credits Columbus industrialist W.C. Bradley with influencing
Pitts to make the investment that grew to a fortune: ``It was Mr.
Bradley's persuasive powers that got Mr. Pitts to invest in the
Coca-Cola Company. He must have been quite persuasive because Mr.
Pitts was not one to throw money away. Coca-Cola was a risky
investment then.''
</P>
<P>
   When W.I.H. Pitts drew up his will in 1938, the value of his
estate was $1.2 million, Kea said. At the time his daughter died
last July, the value had shot up to $166 million, falling a bit
since then because of a slide in the price of Coca-Cola stock.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Saporta writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
