<HEADLINE>
BUSH, IN STEP TOWARD CANDIDACY, TO FORM EXPLORATORY COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush announced Tuesday he
would form an exploratory committee that would allow him to raise
money as he continues to contemplate the possibility of running for
the Republican presidential nomination next year.
</P>
<P>
   Although the announcement was expected and is not a formal
commitment to seek the presidency, the move is significant because
it marks the first official step Bush has taken in what promises to
be a long, expensive process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the Texas press, and therefore my fellow Texans, to
hear it from me first, that this coming Sunday I'm going to
announce the formation of an exploratory committee to determine
whether or not I should seek the presidency,'' said Bush, the son
of former President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of you who have been covering me every day know I don't
make this decision lightly. I've carefully considered its
ramifications,'' said Bush, who was joined on the Governor's
Mansion lawn by his wife, Laura.
</P>
<P>
   As he mulled the idea of running in recent months, Bush emerged
as a leading contender in a crowded field of would-be Republican
candidates, including Elizabeth Dole, magazine publisher Steve
Forbes, former Vice President Dan Quayle, Arizona Sen. John McCain,
former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and conservative commentator
Pat Buchanan, who announced Tuesday he was launching a third bid
for president.
</P>
<P>
   Some right-wing Republicans question Bush's conservative
credentials, but a number of GOP officials believe his brand of
politics, which he calls ``compassionate conservatism,'' represents
the party's best chance of retaking the White House after an
eight-year shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 52, said that although he needed to stay focused on
legislation session in Texas, he believes it's time to find out if
there is enough support to launch a formal candidacy. And a key way
to gauge political strength is through fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``First things first. I'm going to start raising money to
determine whether or not there is an interest beyond people just
coming to Austin,'' he said, referring to delegations of GOP
lawmakers from other states who have gone to the Texas capital to
urge Bush to run.
</P>
<P>
   Jokingly, Bush said he needed to know if his popularity extended
beyond the fact that he is the governor of a big state and the son
of a ``famous mother,'' a reference to former first lady Barbara
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has the luxury of tapping into a well-established,
fund-raising network that traces its roots back to his father. The
governor also flexed considerable fund-raising muscle by gathering
more than $17 million for his re-election campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   The governor did not say when he would make a decision on a
formal candidacy or how much money he thinks he needs to raise for
such an effort.
</P>
<P>
   He has held back making a decision as he thought about the
effect a race would have on his wife and 17-year-old twin
daughters, Jenna and Barbara, all of whom have voiced reservations
about him running for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have talked a lot with Laura and the girls, and while
there's some natural concerns about the potential major change in
our life, I am convinced, and Laura is convinced, that our love for
each other is strong enough and our family is close enough to take
whatever life brings,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I was hesitant about is the ugliness that we all see in
political life,'' Laura Bush said. ``George and I went through the
1992 election with his dad. It was a very miserable year for all of
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dread criticism of my husband. On the other hand, I love
George, and I'm very proud of him. And I know he'd make a great
president,'' she continued, her words bringing tears in the
governor's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had compelling reasons to consider running for
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``For my family and for every family in America, I want the 21st
century to be prosperous,'' Bush said. Additionally, he said, he
wanted to usher in what he called a ``new era of responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Bush has conceded he was ``young and
irresponsible,'' but he has declined to cite specifics about any
youthful indiscretions, other than to say he drank too much alcohol
but stopped when he was 40. But he also has insisted there is
nothing in his past that would prevent him from running for
president.
</P>
</TEXT>
