<P>
   SENATE-Y2K (Washington) _ A majority of doctors and hospitals
are not prepared for the year 2000 computer glitch, putting
diagnostic equipment and drug distribution in jeopardy, according
to a Senate committee investigating the nation's preparedness for
the so-called Y2K problem. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL (Washington) _ The Clinton administration
comes out against the Independent Counsel Act, which will expire
this summer, saying the Watergate-inspired law ``has failed in its
goal of removing politics from the process.'' By MARK HELM.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-CARTELS (Washington) _ Sens. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
and Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., say there's no chance Congress will
reverse President Clinton's certification of Mexico as an ally in
the war on drugs. But they propose a ban on business dealings with
foreign companies that serve as fronts for drug-cartel smuggling.
By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-CARJACKING (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that
when criminals use weapons to steal vehicles, they are guilty of
carjacking even if they don't intend to harm anyone in the cars. By
MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-2000 (Washington) _ The General Accounting Office reports
that Texas and California have taken the biggest hits because of
undercounts by the U.S. Census Bureau. By JENNIFER DAY.
</P>
