<HEADER>
A5082 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BISHER-COLUMN-TRIBUTE     03-02 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHER-COLUMN-TRIBUTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The writer who awoke the master
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jack Nicklaus will never forget him. He was his
motivator, the burr under his saddle, the guy who pricked his
self-esteem and brought his game alive for one more dramatic
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that might be a little strong, but you could never tell
John Montgomery that. The year was 1986. It had been 11 years since
Nicklaus last won the Masters. He was now 46 years old. You found
his name down around the journeymen of the PGA Tour, 160th on the
money list. His career was making the hard turn from playing golf
courses to building them. On his way to Augusta, he had stopped
over to see how work was going on his project at Country Club of
the South.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, his partner in business, had reached their rented
house in Augusta first, and when Nicklaus arrived he found the
clipping attached to the refrigerator door. What Tom McCollister
had written in the Sunday sports section of these papers was what
``most of the media and many of his fellow competitors agreed _
that Jack Nicklaus' championship days were over,'' as it is written
in the Masters yearbook. But Tom had put it in print, that
Nicklaus' game was beyond championship caliber. He was through.
</P>
<P>
   Oft times, we in the press are inclined to overvalue the
influence that something written has on the outcome of a sports
event. Clippings on bulletin boards before football games, or
basketball tournaments. Horses can't read, or we might even take
credit for upsets in the Kentucky Derby. In this case, Nicklaus
left no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   He turned the back nine at Augusta National in 30 strokes that
Sunday afternoon. Seve Ballesteros knocked it in the water on 15.
Greg Norman missed the green on 18. Tom Kite couldn't make the putt
that would have forced a playoff. Nicklaus had won at age 46, and
one of the first things he did in the champion's interview was to
call for Tom McCollister. Not to hassle him, but to tell him what
an inspiration he had been.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked into the interview room, Tom said, `I guess I'm
the last person in the world that you want to see,' '' Nicklaus
recalled on Tuesday. ``And I said, `No, you're the first person in
the world I want to see.' ''
</P>
<P>
   I know of no man who loved golf more than Tom McCollister. He
loved to play, he loved to talk it, he loved to walk it. Once had a
hole-in-one in the Atlanta Classic pro-am. He had a sweet swing
that I envied. Mine looked like a logger trying to fell a tree. He
was good company on a golf course. I raged in despair. He took the
breaks as they came and moved on. That was just his nature, as it
was when he was moved from the golf beat to the snarling world of
stock-car racing. He took it and moved on, did well and soon had
the respect of those guys used to living at 190 mph.
</P>
<P>
   He had come to Atlanta in 1963, purloined from one of the
Jacksonville papers. He was a good journalist who could handle any
assignment and, for a long while, endured the most agonizing. What
we called ``working the slot'' in those primitive days, when we had
a staff of 15. (We have so many now, we should wear convention
tags.) That meant editing, moving copy, riding herd on plodding
writers, getting the section out on time and reaching for the
Alka-Seltzer.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably what drove him to try public relations with the
Atlanta Hawks. Even with Pete Maravich to glamorize, he found that
wasn't what it had seemed to be. He went to Birmingham, his
hometown, to try PR in the World Football League. When that league
up and died, he came back to The Constitution and finally made his
marriage with golf.
</P>
<P>
   After all those nomadic years on the stock-car run, this was to
be a homecoming. No more bags to pack, no more Holiday Inns, no
more accursed jams trying to get to the track. Home at last. Return
to the Masters. Back to what he loved. Golf. And what happens? One
mile from home, the car of another person he had never seen and his
car come together at an intersection, and Tom McCollister is gone.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the saddest days of our life around here. Not
that we'd seen that much of him around the office, but he was
always there in one form or another. He had a warm, easy laugh, a
pleasantness toward everyone, and he was a professional. I don't
know how old he was, but it didn't matter. He was always young to
me. Life is not fair. Why is it death always reaches out for the
good ones?
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is Sports Editor of the Atlanta Journal, Atlanta,
Ga. email: furman(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
