<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-TV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not-so-secret interview kicks off Lewinsky tell-alls
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don't even pretend like it's over.
</P>
<P>
   The Year of Monica enters its 15th month and we're just now
getting to the good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The Barbara Walters two-hour interview with Lewinsky airs at 9
tonight on ABC's ``20/20'' _ though its allure diminished Tuesday
when much of the interview was leaked. (Walters has a chance to
salvage her ratings and what's left of her ``exclusive'' on this
morning's ``Good Morning America,'' which starts at 7).
</P>
<P>
   The interview has become the worst-kept secret since the
semen-stained dress. Lewinsky quotes had been leaking in the media
since last week. ABC, tired of all the leaking, finally leaked its
own quotes Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some highlights from the interview, taped in ABC's New
York studios Feb. 20:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lewinsky, 25, said, ``I never will have an affair with a
married man again,'' and apologized to first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton and Chelsea Clinton, saying she was sorry for ``what
they've been through.'' She also said the president never discussed
his marriage with her, and never told her he loved her.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On Bill Clinton's sensuality: ``I think he's a very sensual
man who has a lot of sensual feelings. And I think he also has a
very strong religious upbringing. And I think that he struggles to
. . . I think he struggles with his sensuality because I don't
think he thinks it's OK. And . . . I think he tries to hold himself
back. And then can't anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning there was a very intense sexual attraction,
and I don't necessarily think a sexual attraction is a bad thing,''
she said. ``I didn't feel that way _ and I still don't.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On Linda Tripp: ``I pity her. I would hate to be her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On how hurt she was when he didn't call after he hugged her at
the ``black beret'' event: ``That was the starting event . . . that
led me to be susceptible to making a bad judgment in confiding in
Linda Tripp. It was devastating, devastating for me . . . that he
didn't call. . . . This unexplainable behavior in my mind meant:
`It's over. He didn't really care about you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For those still interested after the Walters interview, there's
the tell-all book ``Monica's Story,'' as told to Princess Diana
biographer Andrew Morton, delivered to bookstores Thursday (NBC's
``Today Show,'' airing 7-9 a.m., interviews Morton on Thursday).
</P>
<P>
   There's also an overseas TV interview with Britain's Channel 4
on Thursday (which Channel 4 said Tuesday will not be available to
satellite dish owners in the United States). In that interview, for
which Lewinsky is being paid $660,000 and 75 percent of
distribution sales, interviewer Jon Snow told TV Guide,
``(Lewinsky) sees Linda Tripp as contributing to the very specific
moment when she did feel suicidal. . . . She literally runs out of
damnation for Tripp.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow also said Lewinsky is ``angry, very angry at (Kenneth)
Starr. . . . She feels completely let down and violated.''
</P>
<P>
   Will this be it? Not likely, though the media that people love
to hate might finally get its due: Hustler publisher Larry Flynt,
displayer of Republican sex scandals, recently told the Internet
magazine Salon he'll start investigating the sex lives of media
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the media moguls better look out,'' Flynt said.
``Apparently (one prominent anchor) is like a rabbit _ I mean, he's
got a revolving door to his office. Many of them have been divorced
four or five times. A lot of the divorce transcripts are
available.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   _ News services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
