<HEADER>
A5089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      03-02 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYE ON THE PRIZE (2ND, THAT IS)  
 PROBLEM SOLVING  
 LONESOME RANCH  
 GOING LIVE, FOR ONCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: bylines follow notebook items.) 
(jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a ratings sweep month marked by success for
``event'' programs at most of the networks, the final outcome
remains in some doubt until two last events are figured into the
total numbers: the opening of an Egyptian tomb on Fox on Tuesday
night and, potentially the biggest event of all, the Barbara
Walters interview with Monica Lewinsky on ABC Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The results are important to the two networks because ABC is
still hoping to beat Fox for second place behind NBC in the
young-adult audience that all three networks regard as the main
field of competition. For several years' worth of sweeps, Fox has
beaten ABC among viewers between 18 and 49, and ABC would sorely
like to reverse that trend.
</P>
<P>
   That feat would require an enormous showing by the Lewinsky
interview because Fox was ahead of ABC by a substantial margin
going into Tuesday night. Neither network had any hope of
overtaking NBC, which will win the February sweep by a comfortable
margin in every ratings category. That amounts to a comeback of
sorts for NBC, which in November slid all the way to a near tie
with Fox among young-adult viewers and behind CBS among total
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But NBC had an especially good month with several special
programs, including the miniseries ``The '60s'' and the movie
``Alice in Wonderland'' _ both big hits _ and the final appearance
by George Clooney as a regular on ``ER,'' which was the most
watched show of the month.
</P>
<P>
   CBS acknowledged that NBC had a more formidable sweep
performance in February, but pointed to a heavier total of special
programming on NBC. CBS said it used 86 percent of its regular
programs while NBC used 72 percent. Still, the biggest difference
for NBC may have been the presence in February of one new regular
series, ``Providence,'' which has become a hit on Fridays. That was
four hours' worth of hit ratings NBC did not have in November.
</P>
<P>
   CBS had effective special programs of its own, including a
miniseries called ``Too Rich: The Secret Life of Doris Duke'' and
the Grammy Awards. The latter did so well with younger viewers that
CBS, which usually ignores the ratings for the young audience that
the other network lust after, pointed out that the Grammy show had
its best young-adult ratings in six years.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives said they had their most competitive sweep since
May 1997. One big reason was ABC's special event, a three-part
Stephen King movie, ``Storm of the Century.''
</P>
<P>
   That helped push the four networks to one of their best overall
performances in some time. On the Thursday night when Part 3 of
that movie was shown opposite Clooney's departure from ``ER,'' the
four networks reached 72 percent of the total audience, up more
than 12 percent from the average network share for the season.
Scott Sassa, the president of NBC Entertainment, said those results
showed what the networks were still capable of doing when they
provided ``good programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how well the Lewinsky interview does for ABC on
Wednesday, three networks may improve on their performance from
November. Only Fox would be down.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   PROBLEM SOLVING
</P>
<P>
   The end of the sweep usually means a sudden flood of repeat
episodes for most of television's best shows (which have to hoard
most of their remaining episodes for use in the next sweep month,
in May). But ABC finds itself in a difficult position with its
drama ``NYPD Blue,'' because the first five episodes this season
all involved the illness and eventual death of the character played
by Jimmy Smits.
</P>
<P>
   Stu Bloomberg, the chairman of ABC Entertainment, said Tuesday
that the network felt it would be awkward to repeat episodes with
Smits, and besides, that repeats of ``NYPD Blue'' never did very
well anyway. So ABC is replacing ``NYPD Blue'' on Tuesday at 10 for
five weeks starting on Tuesday with a new series, ``Strange
World,'' an ``X-Files''-like look at an alien invasion of Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The show was always intended as a regular series, and ABC
committed itself to making 13 episodes. But the network, looking to
kick up interest, is promoting the show as if it were a miniseries,
calling it ``an exclusive limited series from a producer of `The
X-Files.' '' The network hopes to give the impression that the show
is a special event and to let ``NYPD Blue'' fans know that their
show is in no danger of being replaced.
</P>
<P>
   But if ``Strange World'' shows any signs of life in this trial
run, it will continue after its ``limited run'' concludes in five
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   LONESOME RANCH
</P>
<P>
   Is there a booby prize? Not exactly, but during every sweeps
period there has to be a show that finishes last. This time, among
the major broadcast networks, the dubious distinction will go to a
UPN period drama, ``Legacy,'' about a horse-ranching family in
Kentucky in the 1880s. While it earned some critics' praise, few
viewers were interested. It clocked a 1.1 average Nielsen rating
for the February sweep period, or 1.09 million homes, and a 2
share, meaning 2 percent of sets in use.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   GOING LIVE, FOR ONCE
</P>
<P>
   ``All That,'' a sketch comedy and variety show that anchors the
Saturday night lineup on Nickelodeon, has often been called ``
`Saturday Night Live' for Kids.'' This weekend, it will be exactly
that.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate its 100th episode, the show is being produced live,
with plenty of star trappings. Cast members and other celebrities
will arrive to red-carpet-and-flashbulb treatment, mimicking the
Academy Awards. The teen-age pop star Britney Spears will sing (her
single ``Baby One More Time'' is No. 1), Busta Rhymes will rap and
Melissa Joan Hart (former star of the Nickelodeon hit ``Clarissa
Explains It All'') will be a guest star.
</P>
<P>
   Another teen-age pop star, Mya, will be host and will interview
celebrities in the audience, including the former cast members Lori
Beth Denberg, Alisa Reyes, Angelique Bates and Catrina Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Kenan Thompson and Kel Mitchell, both now 20, and Josh Server,
19, are the only cast members remaining from the original ``All
That,'' which first appeared in January 1995. Most of the others
are young teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out in theater, and Kenan and I still do live comedy
routines, so I'm not scared about it,'' said Mitchell, who with
Thompson also stars in ``Kenan and Kel,'' which usually follows
``All That'' on Saturday nights but will be bumped this week to
expand the 100th episode to an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The younger kids haven't done live stuff,'' he added, ``but
they're all psyched up for it. They're like our little brothers and
sisters, and we just tell them, if something goes wrong, you
improv. You say another quick line, something witty, and keep going
_ never panic, never stop.``
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
