<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWT-BIRTHDAY-COX     03-02 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWT-BIRTHDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southwest Texas State at 100: Notice us, we're getting better
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MARCOS, Texas _ The university that groomed U.S. President
Lyndon Johnson, country music star George Strait and syndicated
consumer columnist Heloise brings you this important message: The
school is better than you think.
</P>
<P>
   Today as Southwest Texas State University marks the the 100th
anniversary of its founding, the school is touting its academic
victories and trying hard to shed its party school image.
</P>
<P>
   Decades after its modest beginnings as a teacher training
academy, called a normal school, SWT remains a leading producer of
Texas teachers. But its mission today is far broader. And its
problems are as complex as those of most big schools.
</P>
<P>
   As a major liberal arts university, SWT now attracts more
prominent faculty and better-prepared students than at any time in
its history. After the school dramatically raised admissions
standards in 1992, a fourth of the students who used to be admitted
no longer were eligible, President Jerome Supple said.
</P>
<P>
   SWT boasts a geography department that was ranked first in the
country by the Association of American Geography; a master of fine
arts in creative writing program considered among the top 20
nationally and aspiring to be in the top 10 within five years; a
jazz ensemble that is one of the few college bands featured at the
Montreux Jazz Festival; and a physics program cited as exemplary by
the American Physical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Faculty cited in recent years as the being among the best in
their fields by national organizations include physicist Carlos
Gutierrez, business educator Beverly Chiodo and speech
communication professor Steve Beebe, SWT spokeswoman T. Cay Rowe
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just behind UT and Texas A&AMP;M as the third- or
fourth-most selective public university'' in Texas, SWT President
Jerome Supple said.
</P>
<P>
   Supple hopes to spread that word, especially during this
centennial year of campus festivities and lectures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we've made a lot of improvements in quality over the
last several years,'' said Supple, who became the school's eighth
president in 1989. ``But we don't believe we've made equivalent
improvements in prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   Affecting SWT's prestige is its lingering party image, which
Supple said had been fading until it got national attention last
month. At separate fraternity parties, one student was beaten to
death by an ex-student; another was hospitalized with a blood
alcohol level more than five times the legal driving limit.
</P>
<P>
   Supple responded by taking the unusual step of suspending 12
fraternities. But he is not optimistic the drinking problem is
solved.
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat ironic that a school that had strong prohibitions
against drinking for most of its history developed a party
reputation, said Ron Brown, an SWT history professor and acting
dean of general studies.
</P>
<P>
   When the school opened in 1903 to 303 students and 17 faculty
members, Principal Thomas G. Harris, a strict Baptist, preached
prohibition. He was so vehement that when prohibition foe Oscar
Colquitt was elected governor, Colquitt ordered Harris'
resignation, Brown writes in SWT's centennial history book, ``Up
the Hill, Down the Years.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris' successor, Cecil ``Prexy'' Evans, who was in office from
1911 to 1942, was equally strict but avoided Harris' fate. Not only
was drinking prohibited, he banned women from riding with men in
cars. Evans _ who had a major influence over aspiring teacher
Lyndon Johnson, a 1930 graduate _ called SWT ``a poor man's
school.'' It almost exclusively drew students from the Austin-San
Antonio corridor.
</P>
<P>
   That began to change as the school transformed from a teacher's
college to a liberal arts college under James McCrocklin, president
from 1964 to 1969. His also was the first administration to allow
alcohol at university functions, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Supple became president in 1989, SWT had grown
dramatically for more than a decade and was still growing. The
schools' main campus lies along the San Marcos River in the heart
of a city of 39,000 people, a fourth of whom are students. The
campus consists of 160 buildings spread over 428 hilly acres. SWT
enrolled 21,504 students in the fall, its second-highest. They came
from virtually every Texas county.
</P>
<P>
   Like most public institutions, SWT has turned to private sources
for support. On Saturday, it ended its first major capital campaign
with $67.5 million, well above the $60 million goal. That will help
boost the school's $29 million endowment, meager compared to the $7
billion Permanent University Fund that helps support the University
of Texas and Texas A&AMP;M University systems.
</P>
<P>
   Faculty salaries also are lower at SWT: an average of $46,865
compared with $64,546 at UT, which has many more prominent faculty
and is nationally known for its research.
</P>
<P>
   But SWT students and faculty said they like their school's focus
on undergraduate teaching. Faculty typically have their office
doors open, and are often seen chatting with students.
</P>
<P>
   Heather McKnight, 19, a freshman majoring in health care
administration, said that she was attracted to SWT from the Houston
area because ``it's a lot more friendly, and it's really beautiful
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although SWT is now the sixth-largest university in Texas, it
still feels small, students and faculty said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when I would have regarded UT as more
prestigious, but now I'm not interested,'' said Faculty Senate
Chairman Jon Bible, who teaches business law. ``I'm happy here.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean SWT is problem-free, he said, citing large
classes and indications that research is getting much more
attention. Although SWT does not aspire to be a research
institution, ``some faculty fear, in practice, we are getting more
and more research-oriented,'' Bible said.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Grant, a junior who is majoring in education and serves
as president of the Black Student Alliance, said she is happy with
the school. Even so, she said, she is aware some blacks feel
alienated on the campus, which had racial tensions last year after
three black football players were accused of raping two white
women. A grand jury found insufficient evidence to charge the
players, and they were reinstated on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics are the largest minority group on campus, 18.1 percent
of the student body; black students make up 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More students are choosing SWT as their first choice for
college, Supple said. Without tinkering again with standards, the
school could balloon to 30,000 students in a half a dozen years, he
said. He wants enrollment capped at 26,000.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Supple expects the school to add doctoral degree
programs, beyond the one in geography. He also wants to improve
freshman retention. Almost a third of last year's freshmen did not
return as sophomores this fall. But before admissions standards
were raised, 42 percent were not returning.
</P>
<P>
   Retention affects graduation rates, and SWT needs to improve
that as well. Only 41 percent of students graduate in six years or
are still enrolled, Supple said.
</P>
<P>
   The school also plans to serve more working adults by expanding
the graduate school and its evening programs at the Westwood High
School in north Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Supple noted that the first edition of the yearbook, the 1907
``Pedagog,'' which still is being published, described the school's
role as a citizen-maker, not merely as a maker of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred years from now, he said, ``I would hope that we would
still see ourselves as citizen-makers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Roser writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: maroser(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
