<SLUG> BC-DAYTRADER-SHUTDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER DAY TRADER SHUT DOWN BY BAY STATE REGULATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In yet another move against the increasignly popular
day-trading industry, Massachusetts securities regulators shut down
the Boston office of TCI Corporation Tuesday for allegedly making
``outrageous'' claims of guaranteed income.
</P>
<P>
   In newspaper advertisements and an Internet website,
California-based TCI claims day traders who speculate in the stock
market using TCI's ``formula'' for investing will make six-or
seven-figure profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see guarantees of success like that, we have to take
action,'' said Matt Nestor, Director of the Massachusetts
Securities Division. ``Everything we've seen around the country,
every bit of experience we have tells us that people don't make
money day trading, certainly not that kind of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Day trading _ which gets its name from the practice of holding
stocks for less than a day _ has become big business across the
country. Firms have sprung up nationwide catering to a growing
number of speculators who trade huge blocks of stock in
transactions that often last only seconds. Dedicated traders make
hundreds of such trades a day. And untold numbers have reportedly
taken up day trading at home using personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators, alarmed by day trading's sudden popularity, have
taken a dim view of the practice, saying it's little more than
gambling. Massachusetts led the nation with the first regulatory
action against a day trading firm last October, shutting down Block
Trading in Boston. Regulators from the state securities division
alleged that just one of a total 68 day traders at Block Trading
made money. Block denies the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the securities division has taken action against
local offices of Bright Trading Inc. for failing to register with
the state, All-Tech Investment Group for abuses ranging from
deceptive marketing to forging customers' signatures, and On-Line
Investment Services for deceptive marketing and churning accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In moving against TCI Tuesday, the securities division alleged
that TCI engaged in deceptive marketing with promises of huge
profits for investors. Secretary of State William F. Galvin has
said his office will move aggressively against any firm making such
claims.
</P>
<P>
   But Timothy Cho, TCI's founder, said he's outraged by Tuesday's
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand behind all our claims,'' he said. ``How can a
government agency come in here without any basis and close us down.
I thought this was America. It's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   He said day traders who come to TCI pay $6,000 to learn the
firm's investment formula, which Cho claimed is a system of
indicators telling speculators the best time to buy and sell
stocks. He claimed all but a small percentage of those investors
make six-figure incomes, though he didn't have records that
specifically track the performance of TCI day traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an impeccable record,'' he said, adding that despite
the claims in TCI advertisements, ``everybody knows there's
absolutely no guaranty. Past performance doesn't guarantee what
will happen in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
