<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ART-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL QUITS, ENDING OBSTACLE TO KOSOVO ACCEPTANCE OF PACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-U.S.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ A hard-line political leader of the
Kosovo Liberation Army resigned on Tuesday, raising hopes among
diplomats that the ethnic Albanian guerrilla movement will sign an
autonomy plan proposed at peace talks last month.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Kosovo, meanwhile, Yugoslav tank and mortar fire
pounded the hillsides along the Macedonian border, striking at
rebel positions and driving thousands of ethnic Albanian civilians
from their homes in some of the heaviest fighting since the start
of the peace talks at Rambouillet, France.
</P>
<P>
   American and NATO officials said on Tuesday that the Yugoslav
military buildup in Kosovo was a clear violation of a cease-fire
reached in October. However, they said that NATO would probably
refrain from punitive strikes to avoid undermining efforts to reach
an accord between the Yugoslav government and the ethnic Albanians
once talks resume on March 15.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the Kosovo Liberation Army's political
representative, Adem Demaci, that he would step down was widely
interpreted as clearing the way for the rebels to accept the peace
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Demaci opposes the peace plan, which would grant Kosovo, a
province of Serbia, autonomy under the protection of a NATO-led
military force.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia is the dominant republic in Yugoslavia. Demaci has argued
that the ethnic Albanians who make up about 90 percent of Kosovo's
population should hold out for full independence. He said he would
continue to campaign against the plan, but he is not expected to
rally much support for his position.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanian delegation at the talks have already given
the deal conditional approval and is expected to make a formal
decision within a week.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kosovo Liberation Army, which is emerging as the dominant
political force on the ethnic Albanian side, accepts the autonomy
plan, the pressure will be on President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia to accept a NATO-led force in Kosovo to enforce the
peace, or face NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, however, Milosevic reiterated his refusal to accept
any foreign military force in a meeting in Belgrade with Knut
Vollebaek, the chairman-in-office of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe. Yugoslav army and Serbian police forces
have meanwhile stepped up military operations, with heavy shelling
reported in the south of Kosovo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reaction to my proposal for an international force was
very, very negative,'' Vollebaek said on Tuesday of his meeting
with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   From Belgrade, Vollebaek traveled to Pristina, the capital of
Kosovo, to meet with ethnic Albanian leaders on Tuesday.
Afterwards, he expressed his grave concern about the stepped-up
fighting in the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movement of troops is serious and a cause for great
concern,'' Vollebaek said. ``A further escalation of the conflict
could put the whole peace process at great risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces have massed large numbers of tanks and armored
personnel carriers in the south of Kosovo along the Macedonian
border. All Tuesday morning, tanks, ranged on the main road close
to the border, shelled the hillsides where the KLA rebels holds
positions amid mountain villages.
</P>
<P>
   The shelling has caused thousands of people to flee their homes
over the last few days, and some 350 women and children have been
camping out for two nights in forests carpeted with snow.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA has largely shown restraint in the face of broad attacks
from Yugoslav army and Serbian police units, according to the
international verifiers monitoring the October cease-fire. There
have been several incidents this week, however, in which Serbian
civilians and police have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt, however, that the major military
initiatives are being taken by Serbian forces, who are thought to
be deployed in Kosovo in greater numbers than ever before.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The KLA is a secretive organization, but its central leaders are
emerging as four commanders in their late 20s, all former student
activists and now possibly the most powerful military figures in
Kosovo. One of them, Hashim Thaci, who led the negotiating team at
last month in Rambouillet, France, is being viewed as a likely
prime minister in a new provisional government in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats had blamed Thaci for throwing away the ethnic
Albanians' best chance when they left the talks last month without
signing the peace plan. The delegates explained that they wanted to
return to Kosovo to consult with their people.
</P>
<P>
   But OSCE cease-fire verifiers, who are in contact with many in
the KLA leadership, say they sense that the majority in the KLA
support the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bear their responsibilities heavily,'' said one Western
verifier who has met several of the key commanders. ``They feel
deeply the loss of those killed. They regret every one and it does
make them look at the loss and at what Rambouillet could resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   William Walker, the American head of the OSCE verification
mission in Kosovo, said he was encouraged by a recent meeting with
a senior member of the KLA's general staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do see the agreement as their best option,'' he said this
week. ``There were difficulties of communication from Rambouillet,
but I think they are pulling together.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hill, the U.S. mediator at the peace talks, told
reporters much the same during a visit to Pristina on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty convinced that this deal is going to stick, that
we'll have Albanian signatures,'' he said. ``And I hope the Serbs
will come to understand that it's in their interest to sign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
