<HEADER>
A5103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HALL-CEPEDA-BOS &LR;      03-02 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALL-CEPEDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEPEDA NOMINATED FOR HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ When Orlando Cepeda arrived in Boston in
1973, there were detractors who said the Red Sox had hired a
wounded buffalo rather than the Baby Bull who had dominated the
National League with his big bat. They were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   As Boston's first designated hitter, Cepeda batted a solid .289
in 142 games with 20 home runs and 86 runs batted in. Anyone still
not convinced of his credentials can head to Cooperstown, N.Y., in
July when Cepeda and six others will be inducted into tbe baseball
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Cepeda was one of four men selected for induction Tuesday by the
Hall's Veterans Committee. A 12-man panel gave the necessary nine
votes (75 percent) to Cepeda, as well as late umpire Nestor Chylak,
who died in 1982; Frank Selee, a turn-of-the-century manager (1890
to 1905) in the NL with Boston and Chicago; and Negro Leagues
pitcher Smokey Joe Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a thrill,'' said Cepeda, who works in community relations
for the San Francisco Giants after playing 17 seasons in San
Francisco, St. Louis, Atlanta, Oakland, Boston, and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with Hall of Famers Juan Marichal, Willie McCovey,
and Willie Mays for many, many years. It's great to join them in
the Hall of Fame. The year with Boston saved my career. I had bad
knees but they still gave me a chance to stay in the game. That was
a wonderful year.''
</P>
<P>
   You had to like Cepeda's chances. He had the backing of
Marichal, a voting member of the committie for the first time, as
well as Ted Williams and Stan Musial. Others under consideration
for induction were Bill Mazeroski, former Sox outfielder Dom
DiMaggio, former Sox manager Dick Williams, and umpire Doug Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rookie on the Veterans Committee,'' said Marichal, ``I'm
glad he got in on my first year. He was the type of player who had
no fear, the type of player you wanted playing behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cepeda, 61, said he spent the morning in Buddhist prayer, hoping
for the best. Bad knees weren't his only problem. After finishing
his career in Kansas City, he was arrested a year later at an
airport for trying to pick up 160 pounds of marijuana. Cepeda was
sentenced to five years in prison but served only 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the moment that pays off for whatever I went through
in life,'' said Cepeda.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Cepeda missed by just seven votes in balloting
by the Baseball Writers Association of America. He was the NL's
Rookie of the Year in 1958 with San Francisco and the league's
first unanimous MVP in 1967 with St. Louis. The first baseman was a
lifetime .297 hitter, with 379 home runs and 1,365 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   It was widely believed that Cepeda's chances of making the Hall
of Fame were crushed by his conviction. But in the last two decades
he has been a model citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning,'' said Cepeda, ``it did work against me.
(The sportswriters) didn't know me. Maybe they heard some things.
Once they got to know me, it was better. I made a mistake. But I'm
only a human being. I've learned from my mistakes big time.''
</P>
<P>
   The veterans panel was down to 12 from its usual 15 because of
the retirement of longtime executive Buzzie Bavasi and the health
of writer Leonard Koppett and Hall of Fame shortstop Pee Wee Reese.
</P>
<P>
   Induction ceremonies will be held July 25 at Cooperstown, when
Nolan Ryan, George Brett, and Robin Yount _ elected by the writers
in January _ also will be enshrined.
</P>
<P>
   Chylak, the eighth umpire elected to the Hall, worked in the
American League from 1954-78 and called five World Series and six
All-Star Games. Williams, who died in 1946, pitched from 1910-32
with several teams, including the Homestead Grays and New York
Lincoln Giants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
