<HEADLINE>
BUSH ANNOUNCES FORMATION OF PRESIDENTIAL EXPLORATORY PANEL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush announced the formation of a
presidential exploratory committee Tuesday, saying only a total
flop in his support would keep him from seeking the GOP nomination
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A giant thud. A huge yawn. It turned out it was my mother they
were interested in,'' Bush responded when asked what could keep him
from running.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is the eldest son of former President Bush and first lady
Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his exploratory committee's first task will be to
raise money while he tends to the state Legislature, whose session
ends at the end of May. Bush said he and his wife, Laura, will then
travel the country to see if there really is grass-roots support
for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have a compelling reason to consider running for
president: I want the 21st century to be prosperous, and I don't
want anybody being left behind,'' Bush said. ``America must be
prosperous so people can realize their entrepreneurial dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 52, the father of twin, 17-year-old daughters, often has
expressed concerns about the impact on his family if he runs for
president. But Tuesday he said he believes that has been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced and Laura is convinced that our love for each
other is strong enough and our family is close enough to take
whatever life brings,'' Bush said. ``I'm committed to making sure I
spend quality time with Laura and the girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush said she also has come to grips with her husband
seeking the office his father won in 1988 and then lost in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I was hesitant about is the ugliness that we all see in
political life. I dread criticism of my husband,'' Mrs. Bush said,
but added: ``I love George, and I'm very proud of him. And I know
he'd make a great president.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush wins his party's nomination and then the White House, it
would mark the first time a father and son have held the presidency
since John Adams and John Quincy Adams did more than 170 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his press secretary, Karen Hughes, chose Tuesday to
make the announcement because it was Texas Independence Day, not
because one of his father's former political rivals, conservative
commentator Pat Buchanan, was launching his own presidential
campaign in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan challenged Bush's father in 1992 and exposed the
weakness of the president's re-election bid by winning 40 percent
of the vote in the New Hampshire primary. Buchanan won New
Hampshire in 1996, but lost the GOP presidential nomination to Bob
Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Buchanan, other potential Bush opponents next year
include U.S. Sen. Robert Smith of New Hampshire, former Tennessee
Gov. Lamar Alexander, conservative activist Gary Bauer, U.S. Rep.
John Kasich of Ohio, U.S. Sen. John McCain, former Vice President
Dan Quayle, former Cabinet official Elizabeth Hanford Dole,
publisher Steve Forbes and broadcaster Alan Keyes. On the
Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore and former U.S. Sen. Bill
Bradley are running.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he is pleased Mrs. Dole is in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is instructive to America that the first viable
female presidential candidate is a Republican,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will have a formal news conference Sunday to
discuss the details of his exploratory committee, which will be
officially filed with the Federal Election Commission on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush declined to set a fund-raising goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have to be enough to make sure we can get out of
Texas, the early states and be able to endure on March the 7th,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten states, including New York, California and Florida _ where
Bush's brother, Jeb, is governor _ are expected to hold primary
elections March 7, 1999, The Texas primary is set for March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Bush friend Don Evans of Midland, Texas, is expected to
be named as campaign finance chairman. San Antonio lobbyist Tom
Loeffler is expected to be named as a finance co-chairman, as is
another longtime Bush friend, Los Angeles investment banker
Bradford Freeman. Loeffler and Evans are University of Texas
regents.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising activities are expected to be coordinated by Jeanne
Johnson of Dallas and Jack Oliver, who raised almost $3 million
last year for Missouri Sen. John Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has until December to decide whether it will
accept federal matching funds for his primary campaign. If he takes
the money, he will be limited to certain spending levels in each
state and a total cap for the nominating process of about $45
million.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Bush can raise more than $45 million
without taking the $13 million to $15 million in federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a while to crank up our organization.
Unlike state politics, it's $1,000 at a time. That's a lot of
$1,000s to be competitive,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's state political fund has more than 12,000 donors who gave
$1,000 or more to his campaign. If those people donate again, Bush
could count on quickly having a presidential campaign fund of at
least $12 million. Bush's name recognition and popularity
nationwide _ as evidenced by the politicians from numerous states
that have urged him to run _ and a political network left over from
his father's campaigns make it likely Bush can raise significant
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said while the fund-raisers concentrate on raising money
for his campaign, he plans to concentrate on getting his agenda
through the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to finish the legislative session. I've told you all
numerous times that I'm going to stay home in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   But Texas Democratic Party Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm said
Bush already is neglecting the job he was elected to do last
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he had done what he said he would do and kept his focus
on Texas until after the Legislature was over,'' Malcolm said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won election as governor over incumbent Democrat Ann
Richards in 1994 with 53 percent of the vote. He defeated
Democratic challenger Garry Mauro last year with 69 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush banned national news media from attending Tuesday's news
conference on the gated back lawn of the Governor's Mansion because
he ``wanted the Texas press and therefore my fellow Texans to hear
it from me first.''
</P>
<P>
   Hecklers chanted against Bush outside the walls of the mansion
grounds during the news conference. The protesters were from
American Disabled for Attendant Programs Today, or Adapt, and the
Coalition of Texans with Disabilities. People from both groups,
many in wheelchairs, were arrested at the mansion last month while
protesting housing choices for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
