<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT ASKED TO DECIDE WHEN A GIFT BECOMES A BRIBE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif.) (nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Somewhere between bribing a federal official and
bestowing an innocent gift on one lies an illegal gratuity. Federal
law punishes giving a gratuity with two years in prison but, as a
Supreme Court argument on Tuesday demonstrated, it defines the
offense so imprecisely that the search for meaning is almost as
much an exercise in metaphysics as in law.
</P>
<P>
   The case before the court is an outgrowth of an independent
counsel's failed prosecution of Mike Espy, the former secretary of
agriculture who was acquitted three months ago of having accepted
illegal gifts from companies regulated by his department.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the independent counsel, Donald Smaltz, had obtained a
conviction of one of the corporate donors, Sun-Diamond Growers of
California, an agricultural cooperative of raisin and nut producers
whose vice president, Richard Douglas, was Espy's college classmate
and longtime friend. This was the case before the court on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The gratuity statute under which Sun-Diamond was convicted, for
giving Espy $5,900 worth of tennis tickets, luggage and other
gifts, makes it a crime to give ``anything of value'' to a public
official ``because of any official act performed or to be performed
by such public official.'' In accepting the independent counsel's
expansive interpretation of the law, the trial judge instructed the
jury that it could base a conviction on a simple finding that the
gifts were motivated by Espy's position, without respect to
anything the secretary had done or was expected to do.
</P>
<P>
   The federal appeals court here overturned the conviction last
year, ruling that the 1962 law linked the prohibited gifts not only
to an official's status but to his actions, and to the giver's
efforts to influence those actions, albeit not by the outright quid
pro quo of a bribe.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing the appeal of that ruling before the justices on
Tuesday, a deputy independent counsel, Robert Ray, met a court that
appeared wary to the point of hostility toward efforts to
criminalize interactions between federal officials and interested
citizens that several justices described as innocent or even
commendable. Ray made little headway with his argument that to be
illegal, a gift need not be linked to any particular action as long
as it reflected the giver's awareness of an official's ``capacity
to act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we have such an extensive reading of a criminal
statute?'' Justice Stephen Breyer asked. The justice said that
ethics regulations could handle problems of questionable gifts, and
were preferable to ``bringing the blunderbuss of federal law into
the prosecutor's arsenal, where they can prosecute trivial
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer was obviously not reassured when Ray, in answer to a
hypothetical question, said a group of farmers might violate the
law if they invited the secretary of agriculture to come talk to
them on matters of farm policy and provided the secretary with an
airline ticket and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``So farmers who invite the secretary of agriculture to speak
are all committing federal crimes?'' Breyer asked. He added: ``I
would have thought it was good for secretaries of agriculture to
explain their policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony Kennedy asked Ray whether he realized that
``there's a huge gap between the general understanding'' of
acceptable official behavior and the independent counsel's
interpretation of the gratuity law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to bar access,'' Ray replied. ``We're talking
about buying access.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun-Diamond's lawyer, Eric Bloom, faced a friendlier audience.
But he also had some trouble defining his terms as he sketched for
the court a ``hierarchy of conduct'' in the area of gifts to
federal officials. Most serious, he said, was bribery, which he
defined as a quid pro quo, a gift ``with strings attached.'' Then
came a gratuity, defined as ``a reward, a tip, a thank you.''
Finally was a gift given solely ``because of an official
position,'' which Bloom said was not a crime but should be
``covered as an ethics matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloom said that someone who liked to hobnob with high government
officials because it enhanced his prestige, and bestowed gifts
accordingly, would not be violating the gratuity statute unless a
prosecutor could tie the gift-giving to past acts or hoped-for
future acts by the officials. Gifts while particular regulatory
matters were pending could lead to criminal liability, Bloom said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the statute would not be violated in a situation
depicted by Justice Antonin Scalia, in which a hypothetical
chairman of AT&AMP;T gave ``enormous quantities of money'' to the
chairman of the Federal Communications Commission, without
reference to any particular issue, because ``you have been a friend
to AT&AMP;T over the years.'' Other prohibitions might well apply,
Bloom said, but not the gratuity statute.
</P>
<P>
   One unusual feature of this case, United States vs. Sun-Diamond
Growers, No. 98-131, is that the Justice Department, which would
ordinarily handle such a case, is only a bystander to an
independent counsel's prosecution. Solicitor General Seth Waxman,
in a brief filed as a friend of the court, conspicuously did not
endorse the disputed jury instructions that the independent counsel
was defending and generally offered a more nuanced view of the
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Although government prosecutors will have to live with whatever
the court decides, for purposes of this case, Smaltz _ seated at a
table in front of the courtroom as his deputy argued _ was the
government. When Bloom, Sun-Diamond's lawyer, referred to the
opposing side as the independent counsel, Chief Justice William
Rehnquist instructed him to say ``the government.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Separately on Tuesday, the court upheld a conviction under a
1994 law making it a federal crime to hijack a car ``with the
intent to cause death or serious bodily harm.'' The question in the
case, Holloway vs. United States, No. 97-7164, was whether the
carjacker actually had to intend to kill or harm the driver, or
whether it was sufficient to prove a ``conditional intent,'' namely
that if the driver failed to hand over the keys, the carjacker was
prepared to be as violent as necessary to get the car.
</P>
<P>
   Conditional intent sufficed, the court said in a 7-to-2 opinion
by Justice John Paul Stevens, who said that this was the ``common
sense reading'' of the law. Scalia and Justice Clarence Thomas
dissented in separate opinions. Scalia said it was ``not at all
implausible'' that Congress had meant the law to apply not to
carjacking generally, but only to the ``particularly savage''
version of the offense that befell a personal friend whose father
was murdered after the car was handed over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
