A5116 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      03-02 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL PREDICTS Y2K CHAOS ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah)  (jw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American industry and the government are generally
winning the race to fix year 2000 computer glitches by year's end,
but the problem is likely to cause widespread civil unrest and
economic disruption abroad, a Senate panel reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With only 304 days to go, most federal agencies, utilities and
large companies are solving the computer flaws that may spew out
faulty data or worse, the panel said. But its 160-page report
warned that the nation's health care industry ``lags
significantly'' in fixing the problem, as do millions of small
businesses and scores of state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   More chilling are the findings from abroad. Global
communications, financial systems, air transportation and oil
supplies could be interrupted for days or weeks, depending on the
country. Important allies like Japan, Mexico and Germany are nine
months to two years behind schedule in preparing for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In a closed briefing at the Capitol, senators were told that
computer failures in Russia could blind early-warning radar systems
and lead to false alarms of nuclear attacks. Soviet-built nuclear
reactors in Russia and Eastern Europe could abruptly and perilously
shut down. And there is a ``low to medium'' probability that
terrorists will try to exploit the resulting chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country we will have a bump in the road but it will
not be crippling,'' said Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, who heads the
panel called the Special Committee on the Year 2000 Computer
Problem. He briefed his colleagues on the national security risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internationally, we think the chances of difficulty are much
higher,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, in its quest to resume a regular legislative agenda
after President Clinton's impeachment trial, took the unusual step
of devoting its entire day to aspects of the year 2000 problem.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 99-0 Tuesday morning, to authorize the
government to guarantee loans to small businesses to fix computer
problems.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon, the Senate voted 92-6 to extend the
panel's work through February 2000 and approved its $800,000
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the House and Senate are considering bipartisan bills
that would limit litigation, lawyers' fees and damage awards from
breakdowns related to the problem. Lloyd's of London, the insurance
exchange, has projected that the worldwide legal costs may reach $1
trillion.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely coalition of insurers, high-technology companies,
and large and small businesses support the legislation, which is
opposed by consumer groups, trial lawyers and the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders have put the bills on the fast
track, making full consideration by the House and Senate likely in
the next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As 2000 approaches, experts around the world are concerned about
computer crashes that might occur if software, written to recognize
the year by the last two digits, mistakes 2000 for 1900.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
