A5120 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-SUPERVISION-A     03-02 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-SUPERVISION-ART-1,015(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PARTY'S OVER: COLLEGES BEING ASKED TO PROVIDE GREATER
SUPERVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wisc., Pa., Va., N.J., N.H., Mass., Calif., Conn., Iowa)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three decades after American college students defiantly threw
off the vestiges of curfews, dress codes and dormitory house
mothers, a revolution is under way in undergraduate life that may
be quieter but no less significant.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting a range of societal changes _ consumerism,
litigiousness, a shift in intergenerational relations, and
increased fears about campus drinking _ colleges are offering and
students are often demanding greater supervision of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   What is evolving is a tamer campus and an updated and subtler
version of ``in loco parentis,'' the concept that educators are
stand-in parents. College administrators are struggling with the
two questions that are emerging as central: Are undergraduates
really adults? And should they be seen as the college's customers
or more as its products?
</P>
<P>
   ``Until recently, we had an almost Darwinian experience for
students,'' said David Ward, chancellor of the University of
Wisconsin, referring to a sort of survival of the fittest mentality
at universities, which offered students little help as they tried
to adjust to college life.
</P>
<P>
   Recent changes at Wisconsin include the creation of residence
halls offering more interaction between students and adult staff
members through a host of programs such as theater outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1970s and '80s, we lost our way'' in educating students
outside the classroom, Ward said. ``We were staggered by what
happened in the late 1960s and in a state of sheer exhaustion. The
view then was, if you could go to war, you were an adult. But that
view was wrong. There needs to be an assimilative process in the
crucial years of 18 to 21. Undergraduates are quasi-adults and we
are asking, what kind of parents can we be?''
</P>
<P>
   The changes take many forms. Pennsylvania State University has
opened a renovated, alcohol-free, adult-supervised student center.
The University of Virginia is drafting rules to inform parents of
drinking violations, which would have been unthinkable during the
1970s, when some schools did not even send parents student grades.
Lehigh University has just banned parties on campus without a staff
member or other adult present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's young people are growing up in different
circumstances,'' said Graham B. Spanier, the president of Penn
State and a sociologist. ``We do not want to make them more
childlike. But parents are constantly contacting us asking what is
going on with their kids. They want in loco parentis. Parents say,
`Give them structure.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Parents stay in much closer contact with their college-age
children than did those of a generation ago. This is partly the
result of better access to telephones _ one per room rather than
one at the end of a long dormitory hall _ and the advent of e-mail.
And many parents are former students who worry that their children
will repeat their wild college years and who have much to say about
how college life ought to be led.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, students come from more varied and difficult
backgrounds than in previous decades. Some parents are divorced or
alcoholic or homosexual; some students have eating disorders.
Unlike in the past, they want to talk about it with someone. So
institutions take on a parental-like involvement.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Princeton University ended a 25-year tradition known
as ``Nude Olympics,'' in which sophomores ran naked at midnight
after the first snowfall. Harold T. Shapiro, the president of
Princeton, said that the drinking associated with the event posed
risks ``that we can no longer tolerate.'' Princeton and many other
universities worry about lawsuits that might arise from the abuse
of alcohol by students.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Dartmouth College announced that it was ending
single-sex fraternities, which served as the basis for the 1978
movie ``Animal House.'' Dartmouth is planning to invest tens of
millions of dollars in creating a new form of undergraduate
community life that better reflects the school's diversity and
intellectual mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students don't rebel against adult guidance in the way they
did 30 years ago,'' said James Wright, Dartmouth's president.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Biles, a 21-year-old senior at the University of
Virginia, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You change a lot in college,'' she said. ``When you get here
you are still a high school student.'' But students, she said,
``need a lot of direction at least in the first year and it is
almost comforting when someone steps in.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Virginia has postponed the fraternity rush
process from fall to spring semester of the freshman year to give
students a chance to explore other options for campus life.
</P>
<P>
   Many universities, like Lehigh in Pennsylvania, have extended
what was once a two-day freshman orientation to a full semester of
meeting weekly with a faculty member to discuss everything from
alcohol to a choice of major.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get paid not only to teach but to mentor and we better do
that well,'' said Lehigh's President, Gregory C. Farrington.
``There is a much greater focus on adult supervision today.''
</P>
<P>
   But some students are offended by what they see as a new
paternalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see all this as coming out of baby boomer guilt,'' lamented
David Schleicher, 21, a Dartmouth junior from New York City,
referring to the excesses of the '60s. ``I've had many wonderful
times at college but they have largely been outside of the
college-sponsored group-bonding events which I consider somewhere
between absurd and offensive. It's not so much Big Brother as a
kind of condescending big uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrie Mayer, 22, a University of Wisconsin senior who is
working on a project to offer alternatives to drinking in college,
disagreed. A history major from Clinton, Iowa, she was intimidated
by professors in her first years and only this year has she
realized that ``they are people, too.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds, ``When I think about the new learning communities vs.
the Animal House era of the 1980s, I feel it is just great. There
is an enormous need for structure and a certain comfort in
returning to the era of `Donna Reed' and `Leave It to Beaver.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even the word ``adult'' is noteworthy. Until the late 1960s,
18-year-olds were often called boys and girls. But, as Janina
Montero, dean of student life at Princeton, notes, feminism and the
Vietnam-era draft changed that. Feminist students were tired of
being called girls, and insisted that the word ``woman'' be
employed.
</P>
<P>
   Passions have cooled to the extent that students who were
drafting a survey on residential houses suggested the question, Is
there any adult in the Harvard community or some other adult with
whom you would feel comfortable sharing a personal problem?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that `adult' was the wrong word,'' Harry R. Lewis,
dean of Harvard College, recalled. ``It would offend some of their
fellow students.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis also found himself writing a guest column for the Harvard
Crimson this past Valentine's Day, taking exception to the editors'
suggestion that Harvard involve itself more closely in fostering
student interpersonal relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I graduated from college in 1968 and the whole point of going
to college then was to get institutions and parents out of my
life,'' Lewis said. ``That is clearly no longer the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard already plays a much greater role in students' lives
than most. It has long run a system in which virtually the entire
student body lives in houses supervised by faculty members, staff
and resident tutors. Harvard's system is being studied by many
other universities seeking to emulate it in creating what are
called ``learning communities.''
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring of undergraduate life is partly a response to
the consumer values of recent decades. Students and their parents
are demanding better living quarters, better food, better safety
and better service for their tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the rise of interactive computer technology in the
past five years has raised the genuine possibility of obtaining a
college degree without ever setting foot on a campus. The result is
that colleges are looking for ways to increase the appeal of their
residential experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Learning has to go beyond downloading,'' Farrington of Lehigh
said. ``Undergraduate education can't be something we do on the
side to support our habit of research.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew S. Santirocco, dean of arts and sciences at New York
University, added, ``Distance learning and for-profit universities
are delivering one product. Our kind of university is delivering
something different, in loco parentis, a model of community with
mentoring and classroom interaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Geshekter, a history professor at California State
University at Chico, points to the growth of offices of student
affairs, combined with parental neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the parents whose kids go to college have abdicated
their responsibility, so when the university takes it upon itself
to be the arbiter and source of this moral development, parents
agree,'' he said. ``The administration likes it because it can
proliferate itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger W. Howard, longstanding associate dean of students at the
University of Wisconsin at Madison, notes the huge growth in the
student body and in the research budget of the university in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faculty became entrepreneurs just at the time when student
culture became self-defined,'' Howard said. ``By the end of the
60s, there was no longer faculty oversight over student
organizations and discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard added that until about 1970, all undergraduates under age
21 were required to live in university housing that included
inspectors and house mothers. But after the National Guard was
dispatched to campus three times to quell student protests, things
changed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common life of the institution was dramatically eroded,''
he said. ``By the mid-1970s, there was no staff link to student
groups, no staff link to off-campus housing and there were no
faculty advisors for non-declared majors.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Wisconsin now places great emphasis on
freshman orientation, involving the parents in a separate program.
It also has two new ``learning communities'' based partly on the
Harvard house model and the similar Yale college model.
</P>
<P>
   In what used to be a dormitory, Chadbourne Residential College
has 400 undergraduates 25 faculty fellows and a total involvement
of 150 adults. There are bicycle trips, pumpkin carvings, dinners,
current events evenings all in an effort to integrate daily life
and intellectual pursuit. In its first year of operation, the
college turned away as many applicants as it accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts see the new structured environments as a
continuation of the day care centers, soccer leagues and summer
camps in which the current generation has been brought up. Those
institutions became far more prevalent after women began entering
the work force in large numbers in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Many say something else is behind the effort: the perceived need
to make their campuses more welcoming to those who had not been
part of them before the 1960s in large numbers _ minority groups
and women.
</P>
<P>
   By breaking down the old order _ fraternities, in particular,
but also a fend-for-yourself social scene _ colleges hope to build
a new model for American society.
</P>
<P>
   As Wright of Dartmouth put it, ``Campuses have become far more
diverse than 30 years ago and we haven't made them as fully
inclusive as they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics see the sensitivity training and community building as
the imposition of a liberal orthodoxy. Alan Charles Kors, a history
professor at the University of Pennsylvania, considers the changes
to be a kind of infantilization of the student body.
</P>
<P>
   Most administrators, however, see the shifts as healthy. Lewis
of Harvard is among those who generally applaud the narrowed
generation gap. But he has his concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about the narrowing impact that such a well-supervised
college experience might offer,'' he said. ``There is something
troubling about students working so hard to fulfill the dreams of
others. It makes it harder for them to discover something on their
own, get excited and pursue it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
