<HEADLINE>
HENRY HYDE'S POST-GAME WRAP-UP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   After suffering a TKO in the Senate impeachment hearings,
Chairman of the House Judiciary Committee  &UR; Henry Hyde &LR; , R-Ill.,
takes off the gloves in an interview in the National Review.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on an emotional speech by former Arkansas Senator
 &UR; Dale Bumpers &LR; , who described waiting with his father when he signed
up with the Marines, Hyde writes, ``The guy never heard a shot
fired in anger. He didn't go overseas or anything. To get a catch
in your voice over that is  &UR; Laurence Olivier &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Of Senator  &UR; Tom Harkin &LR; , D-Iowa: ``He takes an oath to do
impartial justice, and within minutes he's on television saying
that our program is a `pile of dung.' And of course, he hadn't
heard a damn word of it. But that's typical Harkinism.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde says White House deputy counsel  &UR; Cheryl Mills &LR;  had ``played
the race card beautifully.'' He played the race card himself, noted
Roll Call, by not calling  &UR; Betty Currie &LR;  as a witness. ``And then
you get into the race issue,'' Hyde writes of that decision.
``Picking on a black woman. What if she starts to cry in the well
of the Senate? Oh, God.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HINDUS PROTEST WARRIOR PRINCESS EPISODE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An angry group of Indian and Hindu organizations has complained
to the producers of ``Xena: Warrior Princess,'' about an episode
broadcast Friday, in which Xena asks Lord Krishna to save her
lover, a woman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Smarandam Das &LR; , director of the Meditation Center in San
Francisco, says the episode undermines ``Vedic religion by treating
it as fiction.'' Furthermore, ``While `Xena' is financially
capitalizing on people's interest in Vedic spirituality, yoga and
Hinduism, it portrays a lesbian relationship between the lead
characters. The Vedic scriptures reject homosexuality as a
perversion.''
</P>
<P>
   Smarandam Das told Personals yesterday that members of the World
Vaishnava Association, American Hindus Against Defamation and other
groups had been in touch with the producers of the program for a
year and a half, hoping to stop the episode from being made, then
broadcast. After months of being treated ``flippantly,'' he said,
he received a phone call from the producers three days after the
broadcast, asking him to fax his complaints.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A New York theatergoer attending a performance of ``Death of a
Salesman'' wrote to the New York Times that he noticed
 &UR; Arthur Miller &LR; , the playwright, taking notes at the performance. At
one point, near the end of the play, when the stage went dark for a
moment, one member of the audience began clapping, and Miller
whispered loudly, ``Not yet!''
</P>
<P>
   _ More on the divorce of Revlon mogul  &UR; Ron Perelman &LR;  and ex-wife
 &UR; Patricia Duff &LR; , who had converted to Judaism for the marriage
(which ended in September 1996): A judge ruled on Friday that
Perelman have custody of the couple's 4-year-old daughter for Purim
and Passover because Duff staged an Easter Egg hunt and baked
cookies last Passover.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tony Bruno &LR;  observes that the historic Hibernia Bank in San
Francisco, robbed 25 years ago by  &UR; Patty (Tanya) Hearst &LR;  and the
Symbionese Liberation Army, is now Hollywood Video, where customers
can rent ``Pecker,'' ``Cry Baby'' and ``Serial Mom,'' movies that
feature Patty Hearst Shaw. Mindful of the site's history, store
management is trying to get Shaw to do a book signing on the
premises.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Operation Flea Collar'' involves the Coalition to Advance
the Protection of Sports Logos prowling flea markets looking for
counterfeit goods.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sorry, you missed Sunday's UC Berkeley lecture,
``Decapitations, Scalpings and Throat Cuttings Among Ancient
Eurasian Nomads: Evidence From a Cemetery in Tuva, South Siberia.''
But  &UR; Cindy Tast &LR;  found in the Fairfield Daily Republic an ad for
the Center for Laser and Cosmetic Surgery, ``Specializing in Laser
Surgery, Eye Bags, Liposuction, Dermabrasion, Face, Eyelid and Neck
Lifts, Skin Care and Conditioning, Nose and Ear Reshaping, Chemical
Peels, etc.,'' on Butcher Road in Vacaville.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The song is about communication and modern technology, so I
think it's the perfect combination.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Madonna telling Entertainment Weekly that her decision to let
AT&AMP;T use ``Ray of Light'' in an ad campaign wasn't commercially
motivated.
</P>
