<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5130 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAKISTAN-SLAYINGS-HNS     03-02 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-SLAYINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADICALS KILLED TEXAS OIL EXECUTIVES TO DESTABILIZE PAKISTANI
ECONOMY, POLICE SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By MARION LLOYD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The 1997 slaying of four Texas oil executives
in Pakistan was a ploy by a radical anti-government group to
destabilize the country's economy, a top police official said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Police announced earlier this week that they have arrested two
members of the Muttahida Qaumi Movement, a Karachi-based political
party with terrorist elements, in connection with the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The four Union Texas Petroleum auditors from Houston and their
Pakistani driver were shot and killed in November 1997 while
driving to the company's office in the Pakistani port city of
Karachi. The Houston-based Union Texas, which has since been
purchased by the Atlantic Richfield Co., is the largest foreign oil
company operating in Pakistan and accounts for about half the
country's oil production.
</P>
<P>
   The killings shook of the confidence of foreign investors at a
time when Pakistan was desperately in need of investment to prop up
its shaky economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (suspects) clear motive ... was that no foreigners should
come to Pakistan, there should be chaos in the economy, no
investment and Americans should vacate this place,'' Karachi Police
Chief Farooq Amin said in a telephone interview from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, Mohammed Saeed Eharim and Mohammed Salim,
confessed publicly to the killings Sunday during a press conference
in Karachi. However, officials from their party, known by its
initials as the MQM, say the confessions were extracted under
torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a police state; even the most powerful person can be
subjugated in 24 hours and he will say anything,'' MQM spokesman
Kanwar Khalid Younus said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani human rights groups have said police often use torture
to force confessions from suspects, and then terrorize them into
restating their confessions in public.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Amin denied the charge. He said the suspects were
``hardened killers,'' and were wanted in connection with at least
10 other murders in Karachi.
</P>
<P>
   He said the police were still looking for two other suspects,
also militants of the MQM. The group, a former ally of Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif's Muslim League party, is fighting for
control of Karachi, Pakistan's largest city and its commercial
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The organization draws support from millions of Urdu-speaking
migrants, called Mohajirs, who came to Pakistan from India when the
subcontinent was partitioned in 1947. The Mohajirs claim they have
since been discriminated against by other ethnic groups and the
central government, which is dominated by residents of northern
Punjab province.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people have been killed in Karachi since the MQM
emerged on the political scene in the mid-1980s and launched a
struggle for control of Karachi. But this week was the first time
police have accused the MQM of targeting foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials denied any involvement in the killings of the
four Union Texas auditors, Ephraim C. Egbu, 42; William L.
Jennings, 41; Joel Enlow, 40; and Tracy Ritchie, 49. All had lived
with their families in the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman at the U.S. Embassy in Pakistan declined to
speculate on whether police had arrested the right suspects. ``It's
too early to say that these are indeed the culprits,'' Lee James
Irwin said from Islamabad, the Pakistani capital. ``There still has
to be a lot of investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Pakistani police were working in close collaboration
with the FBI, which has an agent permanently stationed in
Islamabad. U.S.-based FBI agents have also made several trips to
Karachi over the past 1 1/2 years to join in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin said he was not surprised that police had singled out the
MQM, though the group, the third-largest political party in
Pakistan, is not known to have anti-American sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Previously, investigators had attributed the killings to radical
Shiite Muslim groups in northern Pakistan, who are opposed to U.S.
intervention in Pakistan and other Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police chief Amin said officers learned of the alleged MQM plot
to scare off foreign investment from another MQM member, Solat
Mirza, who was arrested in December while returning from hiding in
South Africa. Mirza is charged with several high-profile killings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amin said Mirza had told him the killings were part of a larger
MQM plot to scare off outside investment. The police chief
speculated that the order to kill the Americans must have come
directly from Altaf Hussain, who is living in self-imposed exile in
London.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Houston Chronicle last year, Hussain
denied any involvement in the slayings. He accused ``agencies'' of
Pakistan's government of orchestrating the killings in an attempt
to bring disrepute and financial insecurity to the MQM stronghold
of Karachi.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The suspects now face trial in special anti-terrorist courts set
up in the mid-1990s in reaction to increasing political and
sectarian violence in the country. If convicted, they face a
maximum sentence of death by hanging.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Dozier. a spokeswoman for Atlantic Richfield, said, ``We
certainly hope these developments will bring some closure to this
tragedy and that justice will be done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
