<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING-LEAR-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      03-02 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-LEAR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: IN A GLOVE COMPARTMENT, NEW CLUES TO `LEAR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (jw)  
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Put off by the prospect of any more radio blather
about Monica Lewinsky or Latrell Sprewell, I decided before setting
out on a recent drive to rummage through the glove compartment for
any books on tape I might have stored for future listening.
</P>
<P>
   There I found a recording of a BBC radio production of ``King
Lear'' with Alec Guinness as Lear that had arrived with a Modern
Library edition of Shakespeare's tragedies. Having always been
intrigued by ``Lear'' as supposedly Shakespeare's most difficult
play to stage and having once promised myself to understand its
text completely, I stuck the first of its two cassettes into the
tape deck and started off on my trip.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows the basic story of how Lear decides to divide up
his kingdom among his three daughters so that he can ``shake all
cares and business from our age ... while we unburthen'd crawl
toward death.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cordelia, his youngest, refuses to compete with her sisters
in declaring her love for her father, he disinherits her and gives
everything to Goneril and Regan, only to have them turn against him
and thereby drive him mad. I had read the play in school at least
twice and seen it in production several times, albeit several
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on listening to the tape I was immediately struck by how
nearly incomprehensible some of the language is. As always in
Shakespeare, the idioms are so dated as to seem a foreign language.
How is one to know just from listening that when Goneril's husband,
Albany, questioning her mistreatment of her father, concludes,
``Well, well, th' event,'' he means something like, We'll see what
happens when the time comes?
</P>
<P>
   Or that when Kent, disguised as Lear's messenger, gets into a
dispute with Oswald, Goneril's steward, and says, ``If I had thee
in Lipsbury pinfold, I would make thee care for me,'' he means,
``If I had you between my teeth ...,'' Lipsbury being a slang
place-name, like Lipsville, for mouth, and a pinfold being an
animal pound?
</P>
<P>
   Even when no idioms were involved, I sometimes foundered. A
simple example: What first-time spectator, even an Elizabethan with
an ear attuned to Shakespeare's language, could immediately catch
the meaning of the King of France when he chides the duke of
Burgundy for his devaluation of Cordelia:
</P>
<P>
   Love's not love
</P>
<P>
   When it is mingled with regards that stands
</P>
<P>
   Aloof from th' entire point.
</P>
<P>
   A little reflection is required to realize that the ``s'' at the
end of ``stands'' is probably extraneous, and that the statement
simply means that love isn't real when it gets mixed up with
irrelevancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lear'' seemed filled with such confounding passages. So when I
got home, I went straight to a text with annotations (``The
Riverside Shakespeare,'' edited by G. Blakemore Evans, Houghton
Mifflin, 1974) and read as much of the play as I had just listened
to.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I came to a difficult passage, I would study the notes
and keep rereading it until it more or less made sense. Then, when
I happened to be in the car once more, I would listen to the same
parts over again. Frequently I had to go back and forth between the
text and the tape several times before certain lines unveiled
themselves. In this obsessive manner, I worked my way through the
entire play.
</P>
<P>
   The experience was astonishing, far more gratifying than any
previous encounter I had ever had with Shakespeare, whether on the
stage or through reading. My gratification was largely irrelevant
to the quality of the particular production I was hearing or to the
Guinness performance, which seemed to me of high quality although
I'm not in a position to compare it with other noteworthy Lears.
(I'm certain that any of the other recordings of Lear available
would offer equal rewards.)
</P>
<P>
   What I found was that with each successive playing of the tape,
the play's meaning began to reveal itself like one of those
pictures that at first ap pears two-dimensional and then by a trick
of the eye suddenly opens up into three dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lear'' seems at first to be a simple cautionary tale about
learning not to judge people too quickly from their words and
appearances. One might even complain that Lear's temper tantrums
are so sudden and unreasonable that the play is hard to take
seriously as deep tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   But as your understanding of the language grows, you see that
Lear's blind impetuousness is a symbolic vehicle permitting
Shakespeare to explore the loss of power in old age, the
inevitability of generational conflict, the thinness of
civilization's veneer, the fragility of authority, the ambiguity of
sexual feeling, among a dozen other timeless and universal themes.
Most revealing are the exchanges between Lear and his Fool, which
often strike one as cryptic _
</P>
<P>
   FOOL. Dost thou know the difference, my boy, between a bitter
fool and a sweet one?
</P>
<P>
   LEAR. No, lad, teach me.
</P>
<P>
   FOOL. That lord that counsell'd thee
</P>
<P>
   To give away thy land,
</P>
<P>
   Come place him here by me,
</P>
<P>
   Do thou for him stand.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet and bitter fool
</P>
<P>
   Will presently appear:
</P>
<P>
   The one in motley here,
</P>
<P>
   The other found out there.
</P>
<P>
   LEAR. Dost thou call me fool, boy?
</P>
<P>
   _ but after repeated readings begin to resemble Beckett-like
exchanges between Lear and his alter ego, implying that he is
simultaneously going mad and becoming sane, which of course is more
or less what happens.
</P>
<P>
   But the point here is not to add to the mountains of verbiage
already written about the meaning of ``Lear.''
</P>
<P>
   I want simply to celebrate a form of reading unique to the
electronic age, when anyone with a tape recorder and a book can
both control the sound of the text and see it on the page.
</P>
<P>
   An even purer version of this experience would be to listen to
Homer, originally meant for only the ear. But you would have to
understand Greek. In English, the translator has already done the
knotty work of interpretation. Shakespeare offers you rich raw
material.
</P>
<P>
   Encountering ``King Lear'' in this way, you go by gradual
degrees from puzzlement to reflection to comprehension to a rush of
feeling to a tragic sense of pity and fear leading on to catharsis.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Stuck in a Manhattan traffic jam, feeling a kind of exhilarated
sadness after listening yet again to Sir Alec delivering Lear's Act
V speech to Cordelia about going off to prison together _
</P>
<P>
   So we'll live,
</P>
<P>
   and pray, and sing, and tell old tales, and laugh
</P>
<P>
   At gilded butterflies, and hear poor rogues
</P>
<P>
   Talk of court news; and we'll talk with them too _
</P>
<P>
   Who loses and who wins; who's in, who's out _
</P>
<P>
   And take upon 's the mystery of things
</P>
<P>
   As if we were God's spies; and we'll wear out,
</P>
<P>
   In a wall'd prison, packs and sects of great ones
</P>
<P>
   That ebb and flow by th' moon.
</P>
<P>
   _ I felt I understood afresh what Aristotle meant by catharsis,
the purging of guilt feelings attached to one's identity with the
sufferer and exultance over escaping his punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Can there be a more satisfying way to experience a work of
literature?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
