<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-SIBLINGS-COX     03-02 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-SIBLINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Benjamin Kline
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The remains of the infant twin brother and sister
of Wilbur and Orville Wright might be reunited with other dead
members of the Wright family at Woodland Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson Wright, spokesman for the Wright family, said Tuesday
he would approve of such a move after it was proposed to him by
Woodland horticulturist Jim Sandegren.
</P>
<P>
   The Wright babies, Otis and Ida, were born to Susan and Milton
Wright on Feb. 25, 1870, and lived just a few days. They were
buried at Greencastle Cemetery, an old graveyard in southwest
Dayton. The almost forgotten site abruptly came into focus this
week when Thomas Bradley of Farmersville announced in a story in
Monday's Dayton Daily News that he had taken the twins' tombstone
to have it repaired or replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in complete satisfaction the twins will be taken back to
their mother and father,'' Bradley said Tuesday. He said the
original stone also would be moved to Woodland, at his expense if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Sandegren said the Wrights ``have a pretty good-sized lot up in
Section 101. It just strikes me as a matter of closure to have them
included in the family plot with the others. Why it was not done
sooner, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Greencastle's records were destroyed by the Great Flood
of 1913, historians believe the location of the Wright babies'
grave can be pinpointed. Whether anything remains in it is the next
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would guess they just had wooden coffins, and these were
tiny babies,'' Wilkinson Wright said. ``There can't be much there.
It is more of a token gesture.'' ``It would be pretty close to just
plain earth,'' Sandegren agreed. ``There could be bone fragments,
but it's not likely. But there would be a discoloration that would
differentiate it from the surrounding earth.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1800s, the funeral business did not have today's
1,000-pound, precast concrete vaults. People who could afford it
had their graves lined with brick walls on a slate floor, the
coffin covered with slate before the dirt was put back, Sandegren
said.
</P>
<P>
   Greencastle trustee Jim Kitchen said he cannot prevent
disinterment of the babies if that is the family's wish, but he is
worried about possible damage to adjoining burials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to turn into a mess, a circus,'' Kitchen
predicted. ``They're going to tear up and disturb a lot of graves
if they go in there with a backhoe, just to get to these two little
babies. We don't know if they are side by side, end to end or
what.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandegren said the reburial would not be done until spring. He
referred the Wright family to an attorney who does work for
Woodland and said the family might have to obtain Probate Court
approval to open the twins' grave.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Kline writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
