<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-2000-HNS &LR;      03-02 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS FIGURES COST TEXAS $1 BILLION IN LOST FEDERAL FUNDING, GAO
REPORT INDICATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By JENNIFER DAY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas has been short-changed about $1 billion in
federal funding during the past decade because the Census Bureau
undercounted the state's population by almost a half-million people
in 1990, according to a U.S. General Accounting Office report.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report will be released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Medicaid fund was shorted nearly $85 million
annually, while programs ranging from adoption to the treatment and
prevention of substance abuse could have received as much as $9
million more per year if the national headcount had been more
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was entitled to $7.9 million more in federal funds
annually because the bureau overlooked about 67,000 people, said
Rep. Gene Green, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're saving any money,'' Green said. ``Texas is
losing it, and somebody else is getting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three states, mostly in the Northeast and Midwest
received more federal funding than they would have had the census
count been more accurate, according to the GAO report. Ranking
first in excess funding was Pennsylvania, which received $110
million annually that should have gone elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   California, which may have been entitled to about $2.2 billion
in federal funding over the decade, was the biggest loser of the 27
states that were shorted funds.
</P>
<P>
   Although the numbers over a 10-year period sound dramatic, the
overall effects are not that severe, said Chip Walker,
communications director for the House subcommittee on the Census.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO analyzed 15 federal programs that rely on population
counts to apportion funds to states. Of the $147 billion spent each
year on these programs, $449 million annually would have been
allocated differently had the census data been more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, for example, would have received a 1 percent increase, or
$93 million per year, over federal funding levels throughout the
1990s, the GAO report stated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers to be redistributed have been greatly
exaggerated,'' Walker said. ``You have to recognize that half the
states are losers. This notion that everyone wins under sampling is
not true.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court in January struck down a plan to use
statistical sampling rather than traditional enumeration to compile
the census, which is conducted nationwide every 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping allocate federal funds to states, the
census is used to determine how many seats each state will receive
in the U.S. House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, the Census Bureau announced a plan to
conduct two counts, one using enumeration for apportionment of
House seats and one using sampling that could be used to redraw
congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats have argued the Supreme Court's ruling permits
sampling to determine not only congressional redistricting but also
distribution of funds for federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the House Subcommittee on the Census, Rep. Dan
Miller, R-Fla., on Tuesday said having two sets of data will only
confuse people and inspire lawsuits. He also introduced a 10-point
plan to help make the 2000 census more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt said three of the
representative's initiatives would require contracts to be
renegotiated and may delay Census Day, which is April 1, 2000. Such
a delay could lead to even more inaccuracies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This depends on how long it takes Congress to make up its
mind,'' Prewitt said. ``We are at the point in the census, where if
we don't get about it, we don't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
