<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNSEL-LAW-670&AMP;ADD-N     03-02 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL-LAW-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS CHALLENGE RENO AIDE ON VALUE OF COUNSEL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., S.C., Ark.)  (mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several House Republicans challenged an assertion
by the Clinton administration Tuesday that the independent counsel
law should be permitted to fade into extinction, using a hearing on
the law's future to pose pointed questions about what other
safeguards exist against unlawful conduct by high-ranking federal
officials.
</P>
<P>
   After Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder Jr. told a House panel
Tuesday afternoon that the administration considered the law so
irredeemably flawed that it should be scrapped upon its expiration
at the end of June, Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., wondered aloud just
what kind of shape that would leave the country in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried sick about the prospect of it dying without a
developed mechanism in place,'' Gekas, chairman of the House
subcommittee on commercial and administrative law, said during the
hearing. Gekas further demanded that the administration present a
proposal explaining precisely how allegations of official
wrongdoing would be credibly handled in the absence of an
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., joined Gekas in that call, telling
Holder, ``I think you owe that to the country. I think you owe that
to Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder responded that while he thought he had been clear in his
testimony before the House subcommittee that the Justice Department
itself had powers and avenues of investigation that rendered the
independent counsel statute moot, he would be willing to spell out
the procedures for handling allegations of official wrongdoing in a
more detailed document.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll come up with something that's responsive,'' Holder said
as the hearing concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Holder's remarks reflected a remarkable turnaround by Attorney
General Janet Reno, who in the early days of the Clinton
administration was one of the independent counsel law's strongest
defenders and who, in fact, recommended the appointments of five
independent counsels to investigate President Clinton and various
members of his Cabinet. But she was heavily criticized for not
naming a counsel to investigate questionable fund raising by
Democrats in Clinton's 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's hearing took place in the same room where the House
Judiciary Committee, in a vote that split along party lines, passed
articles of impeachment against Clinton last year, and it involved
some of the same players, themes and tensions that informed that
drama.
</P>
<P>
   Gekas and Graham had served on the team of House members who
prosecuted Clinton during his Senate trial, and their questions
Tuesday revealed suspicions about the administration's impartiality
in calling for an end to the statute that gave Kenneth Starr the
authority to investigate Clinton on a variety of fronts and
allegations, none definitively proven.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Democrats on the subcommittee railed about what
they portrayed as the excesses and abuses of Starr, and many of
them said that Starr's conduct had revealed inherent problems with
the statute.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the subcommittee, the elimination of the independent
counsel law appears to enjoy considerable bipartisan support, and
the drumbeat for letting the law expire _ or, at least, severely
curtailing it _ grew louder during the president's impeachment and
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The law was initially passed in 1978 in the aftermath of the
Watergate scandal, to meet concerns about the need for an authority
outside the government to be able to investigate the president and
other high-ranking federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel statute was reauthorized repeatedly over
the next two decades, though there was tinkering with its specific
provisions and it was allowed to lapse from 1992 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing Tuesday was the first that the House held to examine
the future of the law. In addition to Holder, three congressmen who
have drafted legislation to abolish or drastically amend the
statute testified. One was a Republican and two were Democrats, but
all expressed profound reservations with the statute.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They focused in large part on the many witnesses and targets of
these probes whose bank accounts had been cleaned out by legal fees
and whose lives had been shattered, with Rep. Jay Dickey, R-Ark.,
drawing special attention to the effect of so many investigations
by independent counsels in the president's home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a devastation,'' Dickey said. ``It's been like a
tornado has hit, like Sherman's march to the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder's testimony, the contents of which had already been
reported by several news organizations Tuesday morning, marked the
Clinton administration's first official statement of its position
on the law's future. Holder cited a litany of problems with the
statute, from the ease with which it triggers the appointment of an
independent counsel to its failure to rein in that counsel's
investigations and spending. He also said that as soon as an
independent counsel is appointed, that counsel has a vested
interest in justifying his existence and budget by ferreting out
even the barest traces of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the old adage, adopted from Mark Twain, goes: To a man with
a hammer, a lot of things look like nails that need pounding,''
Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   In light of this, Holder said, ``the Justice Department has
reluctantly come to the conclusion _ and I must emphasize
reluctantly _ that there are fundamental structural flaws with the
act. These flaws, we believe, pervade the entire statute.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the department ``joins the many experts who have
concluded that the fundamental flaws in the act will remain, even
if Congress addressed all of the other problems in the act.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said that with the exception of Watergate, the country's
history before the adoption of the independent counsel law in 1978
suggested that the Justice Department itself could be trusted to
handle the kinds of allegations now being referred to independent
counsels.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that the Justice Department has the power, even
without the independent counsel law, to appoint special counsels in
circumstances where department officials might be perceived to have
conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation should not feel that it is somehow at risk if we
fail to reauthorize this act,'' Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gekas and Graham pressed him to defend that statement in a
more detailed presentation to the subcommittee within the next 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to say 1978 is good enough, I'm going to ask
you to come back up here and explain why,'' Graham said, adding
that he worried that public distaste for Starr's tactics might lead
to rash decisions about a law that had drawn broad congressional
support when it was last reauthorized just four years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
