<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-KIDNAP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
8 TOURISTS, INCLUDING A U.S. COUPLE, KILLED IN UGANDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:45 p.m.) 
(sw) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Treks through the Bwindi Impenetrable Forest of southwestern
Uganda to see the rare mountain gorillas are small, exclusive
forays that begin in a tranquil agricultural valley.
</P>
<P>
   But that calm was shattered on Monday when some 30 tourists
scattered among three campsites were set upon by a band of Hutu
rebels armed with automatic rifles, machetes and spears _ remnants
of the murderous army that laid waste to Rwanda in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the attack ended, four men and four women, all
tourists, lay hacked or bludgeoned to death in the jungle, while
four Ugandan park employees were slain in the campsites. The
foreign victims included four Britons, two New Zealanders and an
American couple who worked as executives for the Intel Corp., the
Oregon-based computer chip manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that I saw had their heads crushed in and deep
slashes,'' said Mark Ross, an American tour leader who was released
by the attackers after a forced march into the jungle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women that we'd been told would be escorted back had been
killed on the spot,'' said Ross, speaking to reporters at a news
conference on Tuesday in the Ugandan capital of Kampala. ``It looks
like one was raped prior to being killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the attack apparently lies rooted in the murky
violence that has beset central Africa for years, gradually seeping
over the national borders linking Rwanda, the Congo and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors said as many as 150 ragtag soldiers materialized out
of the trees and sought out Americans and Britons among the
tourists. The soldiers were Hutu, the ethnic group that fled
neighboring Rwanda after killing over 500,000 rival Tutsi and
moderate Hutu in the mass killings of five years ago. Now regrouped
in the wilds of the Congo, the Hutu oppose American and British
support for the Ugandan military and others who are seen as
sympathizing with the Tutsi.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 2102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
