<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3COM-MARKETPLACE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: 3COM FALLS SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Any doubts that technology stocks were undergoing a
correction evaporated Tuesday as yet another prominent maker of
computer equipment, 3Com Corp., announced that its sales and
earnings would fall short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   3Com, which makes computer networking equipment as well as the
popular Palm Pilot electronic organizer, said that an ``unexpected
slowdown'' in parts of its business would cause earnings for the
quarter ended Feb. 28 to be far less than Wall Street had
estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies, which have led the entire stock market
higher since October, are having ever-greater difficulty
maintaining prices, and therefore corporate profits. In recent
days, Compaq Computer and Micron Electronics have warned that sales
of their personal computers were disappointing, as Dell Computer
did a few weeks ago. That, in turn, has led investors to edge away
from stocks of semiconductor companies, which make the chips for
computers, and other computer-related companies.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, technology stocks have now fallen more than 10
percent from their highs of last month and are slightly above where
they started the year. The Pacific Stock Exchange technology index
declined by nearly 2 percent Tuesday and is now 11.7 percent below
the high it reached on Feb. 1; at 456.72, the index of 100
technology stocks is 1.7 percent above where it started the year.
</P>
<P>
   The shortfall announced Tuesday by 3Com did not take everyone by
surprise. The company made its announcement after trading in its
shares was halted late in the day, but by then its stock price had
fallen more than $3, to $27. Volume was an exceptionally heavy 31.4
million shares, making it the second-most active stock on the
Nasdaq market Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In after-hours trading, the shares fell as much as $1 more, to
$26.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Claflin, 3Com's president and chief operating officer,
said in a telephone interview that the announcement was made ``as
soon as it became clear'' that the company would not meet growth
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also clear that there is something more broad going on in
the industry,'' he said, referring to recent announcements of sales
and earnings disappointments by companies like Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   3Com said it expected sales for the three months ended in
February to be about $1.41 billion, resulting in earnings of
roughly 23 cents a share. Analysts had been expecting sales of more
than $1.5 billion and earnings of about 36 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The company's sales and profit figures are nevertheless well
above those reported a year earlier. 3Com reported revenues of
$1.25 billion and profits, before merger-related adjustments, of 2
cents a share a year ago. In fact, sales appear to have accelerated
in the last nine months. For the quarter ended in November,
revenues grew 10 percent from a year earlier, twice the growth rate
of the previous quarter. And in the three months ended Feb. 28,
sales apparently grew at a 13 percent rate. Still, profit margins
are under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the disappointing financial results could be
traced to three areas of its business. First, 3Com said that some
independent distributors of its products experienced their own
unexpected shortfalls in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, sales of 3Com's modems and other products to
personal computer manufacturers were lower than the company had
anticipated. That shortfall follows warnings in recent weeks from
Dell Computer, Compaq and other computer manufacturers that their
growth was slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, 3Com said that sales to commercial customers in the
United States and Latin America of the company's modems and its
switches, routers and hubs, which allow personal computers to
connect to networks, fell short of its growth plans. That
development echoes an announcement last month by Dell Computer
about disappointing sales to corporate customers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   3Com also said that the leader of its clients access unit _ the
division that markets 3Com's modems and internal cards that allow
computers to connect to networks _ would leave the company on June
1. Doug Spreng, a senior vice president, will be replaced by Jef
Grahman, general manager of its mobile communications division.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings warnings that technology companies have made in
recent weeks seem incongruous in light of the extreme popularity of
the Internet among individuals, who seemingly cannot get connected
quickly enough, and among corporations, which are rushing to do
business in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   But Claflin said that Wall Street was disappointed by mostly
slowing rates of growth rather than declines in overall demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly at the unit level, volume is still going up at a
rapid rate,'' Claflin said. ``People are still buying modems, ports
and other products. But there is more price pressure,'' so the sale
of more units has not necessarily translated to comparable growth
in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Claflin also attributed some of the weakness announced Tuesday
to seasonal factors, noting that the first months of the calendar
year are the least active for many technology companies. But 3Com
investors in particular have suffered through more than their share
of disappointments over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Since the company completed the acquisition of U.S. Robotics,
one of the largest makers of traditional computer modems, in
mid-1997, 3Com's shares have fallen from the high $40-a-share range
to the mid-$20s. Claflin, who was not at the company at the time of
the acquisition, said that despite the recent weakness in the modem
business, one of the company's most promising products was the Palm
Pilot organizers, which also came to the company in the U.S.
Robotics purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Investors surprised by the earnings warning will probably get
little comfort from the fact that several 3Com executives sold big
blocks of stock in December and January, when the company's stock
price was significantly higher.
</P>
<P>
   According to CDA/Investnet, which tracks sales and purchases by
corporate executives, 3Com insiders sold 3.8 million shares of
stock in December and January. A spokeswoman for 3Com said Tuesday
that the company did not comment on trading by its executives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
