<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-MILK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill would require insurers to pay for formula
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ After five miscarriages, Lydia Bogan and her
husband, Ed, of West Alexandria had reason to rejoice 16 months ago
with the birth of their daughter, Kaitlynn Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   Severe food allergies, however, have made life a daily and
expensive struggle for Kaitlynn. She and her parents appeared at a
Statehouse news conference Tuesday with Rep. Gene Krebs, R-Camden,
to support legislation that would require health insurance
companies to pay for the special formula that has kept Kaitlynn
alive.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealth Care of Ohio, the family's insurer, has declined to
pay for the formula, and the company's decision has been upheld by
the Ohio Department of Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, we have found no material evidence that the
company has acted improperly, so we cannot require a change in
their position,'' Julie Phillips, an insurance department analyst,
said in a Sept. 28 letter to the Bogans.
</P>
<P>
   To pay the $1,000 a month for Neocate, the special British-made
formula, the Bogans have taken out a second mortgage on their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more than one-half of our monthly income,'' Mrs. Bogan,
44, said of the monthly expense. She is a licensed practical nurse
but currently is not working. Bogan, 45, is a technician at Mound
Metrology, a calibration lab in Miamisburg. The Preble County
residents have a son, Matthew, 14.
</P>
<P>
   Before doctors switched Kaitlynn to Neocate, the infant reacted
with ``blood-curdling'' screams to other nourishment, once for 18
hours straight hours, her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   The baby had a look on her face that said, ``Mommy, please help
me,'' Mrs. Bogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaitlynn was diagnosed with an allergy to milk, soy and protein.
Her digestive system was unable to break down protein into amino
acids, causing adverse reactions. Less than half of 1 percent of
all infants are diagnosed with such an allergy, Mrs. Bogan said.
Neocate comes with the protein already broken down.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealth Care said Neocate is classified as an
over-the-counter product that is not covered by health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a food product. We do not cover those,'' said Karen
Fennerty, manager of process improvement for the company.
</P>
<P>
   The Bogans said Neocate has been more than food to their young
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was her source of life. The Neocate was what kept her
alive,'' Mrs. Bogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaitlynn now is able to tolerate small amounts of carrots,
squash and sweet potatoes, her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that UnitedHealth Care recently has not returned phone
calls nor answered mail.
</P>
<P>
   Fennerty said she is confident that calls and letters have been
answered.
</P>
<P>
   Also attending the news conference were Joel and Tammera Busch
and their daughter, Emily, 1, who had an allergy similar to
Kaitlynn's. The Buschs, who live in Xenia, said that after some
discussions, their insurer, Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield, paid
for their daughter's special formula.
</P>
<P>
   Krebs said his legislation would require health insurance plans
to cover infant formula prescribed by participating doctors and
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make an extremely compelling case,'' Krebs said of the
Bogans.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
