<HEADER>
A5190 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUCHANAN-POLITICS-810     03-02 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-POLITICS-810&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW HAMPSHIRE, BUCHANAN RIDES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., W.Va., Maine) (biobox follows; see also BUSH-POLITICS) 
(nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Patrick Buchanan, who in two previous
presidential forays fashioned himself the icon of the disaffected
worker and the iconoclast of the Republican Party, is back for a
third run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mount up and ride to the sound of the guns,'' Buchanan ordered
his loyalists Tuesday in announcing his latest bid for the White
House and offering up his familiar platform: for restoring
America's ``lost sovereignty,'' for trade protection, for a
moratorium on immigration and for ``the rights of the innocent
unborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Added to his populist stew was a repudiation of President
Clinton, who, he said, has desecrated the White House by using it
``to shake down corporate executives, to lie with abandon to the
American people,'' and by turning it into ``a place to exploit
women.''
</P>
<P>
   It is time, he said, ``to call down the curtain on the sorry
soap opera in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's candidacy, which became abruptly evident when he took
a leave from his role as co-host of the CNN television program
``Crossfire'' just a week ago, is widely perceived as more of a
vanity run or even a mischief run than a serious campaign for the
White House. Friends say he was bored with his television job.
Although he is passionate about his crusade against what he calls
the elite global economists, even his fervent supporters say he has
no chance of becoming president.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say Buchanan, who won the 1996 New Hampshire
primary, has the ability to shake up a Republican field crowded
with lower-wattage conservatives who have been unable to
distinguish themselves from one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have a dramatic impact on the second- and third-tier
candidates who are trying to carve out a niche on the right,'' said
David Carney, a venerable New Hampshire Republican strategist who
is not affiliated with any presidential campaign. ``He may peter
out, but between now and Labor Day he will be the 800-pound gorilla
in that half of the party and will drive these other guys crazy
trying to figure out how to deal with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Mueller, Buchanan's communications chief in 1992 and 1996,
said his old boss seemed driven by a preoccupation with economic
dislocation and believed it was an issue that no other candidate in
either party was addressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a cause and a mission that he's taken upon himself,''
Mueller said. ``He believes that the Republican Party must identify
with those working-class issues to rebuild the Reagan coalition to
take back the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the populist pitch to the downtrodden worker may have
less resonance in an economy that has now been expanding for eight
years, and it is unclear whether the 60-year-old Buchanan can
recapture the romanticism and the early momentum of his previous
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's announcement Tuesday took place at the scene of his
greatest electoral vindication _ his 1996 triumph over Bob Dole,
the party's eventual nominee, when Buchanan conjured up the image
of peasants ``coming over the hills'' with pitchforks and
overthrowing the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire's rough-hewn individualists have always been good
to Buchanan, giving him 37 percent of the vote in 1992. George Bush
won New Hampshire that year, but Buchanan's strong showing was a
searing indictment of the incumbent president, who went on to lose
to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's event lacked the kind of full-dress, media-savvy
theatrics that Buchanan watchers have come to expect. The usually
spontaneous candidate, well practiced on his feet, read his speech
to about 200 people at a sterile, low-ceiling conference center
here. There was no music, no warm-up act, no grand entrance, no
sense that something historic or even new was happening. Only one
man came with a pitchfork, a smoothly carved work of art that was
actually crafted in Germany, an unintended illustration of
Buchanan's message that foreign-made goods are flooding the
American market.
</P>
<P>
   Except for his wife, Shelley, Buchanan has no entourage, no
spokesmen, no consultants, no advance team. In part, that is the
nature of his new insurgent candidacy. This year it also reflects
the fact that his 1996 aides are working for other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller, for example, plans to sign up with Steve Forbes.
Perhaps the biggest absence is that of Bay Buchanan, Buchanan's
sister, who served as the central strategist in his previous
campaigns. This year she plans to keep her job as a commentator at
MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan downplayed the need for such aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find the big entourages cost you an awful lot of money,''
and ``then you run out of money,'' he said in a brief interview as
he stepped off a commercial flight at the airport here. ``You don't
need all this in the early days. These consultants, I used to know
them when they were all kids. They weren't that bright then!''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Buchanan has little money, counting instead on his knack for
sound bites, his clear-cut message and his almost cult-like
following to propel him through the early primary states. This
self-reliance lends his candidacy the air of having kick-started
itself, picking up where Buchanan trailed off in 1996 after he
never officially dropped out and never officially endorsed Dole.
</P>
<P>
   At his announcement speech here, he was preaching to the
converted. The single pitchfork-toting supporter, Craig Henne, a
lumber salesman from Eliott, Maine, said that when he heard
Buchanan was running again, he ``dusted off'' his old Buchanan
bumper stickers from the last time around. He said that even if
Buchanan's campaign ``amounts to nothing,'' he wanted to show his
support for a man who says what he thinks and believes what he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time he was asked, `Would you have a homosexual in your
cabinet?' And he said, `No,' '' Henne said by way of example. ``He
didn't say, `I'll take a poll and tell you in two weeks.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Marie Therese brought two dozen schoolchildren from the
Immaculate Heart of Mary in Richmond, N.H., to hear Buchanan
because, she said, ``I wanted to give them someone to look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   At a rally with 1,300 people on Monday in the gritty steel town
of Weirton, W.Va., Buchanan demonstrated something important _ that
he could conceivably win over support from those who had not voted
for him before. Weirton is a heavily Democratic town where the
steel mill has been stricken by the ``dumping'' of cheap foreign
imports, which has become a cause celebre of Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one well-known person who is taking an interest in
what is happening to us,'' said Janet Stagani, 55, a bookkeeper at
the steelworkers' union and a Democrat. ``If he's willing to take a
stand, regardless of the outcome, then I can support him,
regardless of the outcome. I'll see what my choices are down the
road. But right now, I want to give him a vote of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   PATRICK JOSEPH BUCHANAN
</P>
<P>
   CURRENT JOB: Conservative commentator.
</P>
<P>
   BORN: Nov. 2, 1938, in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION: Graduated from Gonzaga High School in Washington,
1956; Georgetown University, A.B., 1961; Columbia University, M.S.,
1962.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION: Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY SERVICE: None.
</P>
<P>
   MARRIED: Shelley Ann Scarney in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN: None.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT POSITIONS: Special assistant and consultant to
President Richard Nixon, 1969-74; consultant to President Gerald
Ford, 1974; White House director of communications under President
Ronald Reagan, 1985-87.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER MAJOR PROFESSIONAL POSITIONS: Editorial writer and
assistant editorial editor, St. Louis Globe-Democrat, 1962-66;
executive assistant to Richard Nixon, 1966-69; syndicated
columnist, 1975-85, 1987-91, 1993-1995; co-host ``Buchanan-Braden
Show,'' 1978-83, and ``Crossfire,'' 1982-85, 1987-91, 1993-95,
1997-present (on leave); panelist, ``The McLaughlin Group,''
1982-85, 1988-91, 1997-present.; moderator, ``Capital Gang,''
1988-91; host ``Pat Buchanan and Company,'' 1993-95.
</P>
</TEXT>
