<HEADER>
A5191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-TYPHOID-OUTBREAK-     03-02 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TYPHOID-OUTBREAK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Test show high levels of E. coli
 &HT;    By Peter Donald
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Tests on frozen mamey products
confiscated by the state have yet to isolate any of the germs
suspected of causing a typhoid fever outbreak in Florida, but
instead have identified alarming levels of E. coli bacteria, an
official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These products are filthy,'' said Terry McElroy, a spokesman
for the Florida Department of Agriculture. ``We have isolated lots
of E. coli. What's significant is it identifies the presence of
fecal matter.''
</P>
<P>
   McElroy said the sheer volume of E. coli in the samples was
making it difficult to isolate Salmonella typhi, the bacteria that
cause typhoid fever. The samples were taken from the same stores
and brand names as those used by the 15 typhoid fever victims
reported in Florida since late December.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the patients were from Palm Beach County. The illness
can cause prolonged fever, constipation and other symptoms, but can
nearly always be successfully treated with antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   The cases were unusual because health officials said people
appeared to have gotten sick from eating frozen mamey _ a tropical
fruit product used to make the popular shakes known as ``batidos''
in the Hispanic community. Usually, typhoid fever cases diagnosed
here were contracted by visiting other countries where the disease
is more common.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are focusing on two frozen mamey brand names
produced in Guatemala and Honduras _ El Sembrador and La Fe _
suspected in the typhoid fever outbreak and found to be tainted
with E. coli, McElroy said. He described the germs as a garden
variety that could make you sick, but not the potentially deadly
strain known as E. coli 0157:H7.
</P>
<P>
   The Guatemalan Embassy Office in Miami referred calls to a trade
representative who was traveling in Guatemala and unavailable for
comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Of 81 frozen mamey samples tested by state agriculture
officials, 17 were packed with germs, carrying counts of 1000 parts
E. coli per gram, officials said. Twenty-three samples had counts
of 100 parts E. coli per gram and another 13 samples had counts of
10 parts per gram.
</P>
<P>
   Although small levels of E. coli may be found on animal products
and can be killed through cooking, any amount of the germ is
unacceptable in raw fruits and vegetables, McElroy said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, health officials continue to comb the country for
additional typhoid fever cases that may be connected to frozen
mamey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally we're concerned that we have a health problem that
may be nationwide,'' said Joy Wells, a scientist with the Centers
For Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta. ``If it's determined
there's a more widespread problem, action will be taken.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, no new typhoid fever cases connected to frozen mamey
have been reported in states with huge Hispanic populations such as
California, New York and Texas, said Dr. Eric Mintz, chief of the
CDC's Diarrheal Diseases Epidemiology Section.
</P>
<P>
   But in an urgent health bulletin sent last week, the CDC warned
epidemiologists and directors of public health laboratories to
update their typhoid fever records because of the scare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enhanced our surveillance,'' Mintz said.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials suspect frozen mamey was tainted with typhoid
fever-causing germs because 73 percent of 11 patients in Miami-Dade
County ate frozen mamey in the four weeks before they got sick. In
contrast, only 19 percent of 48 healthy people studied had eaten
mamey products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The epidemiological evidence is strong,'' Mintz said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida agricultural officials have stopped the sale of frozen
mamey in the state and seized 200,000 pounds of the product from
store shelves. Whether all such imports should be stopped is up to
the Food and Drug Administration. So far, the FDA has only taken
the step of warning consumers not to eat frozen mamey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at lab results to determine what the next step
will be,'' said Lynn Issacs, an FDA public affairs officer in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Issacs said she expected the FDA to make an announcement on
frozen mamey in the next two days, but declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   CDC investigators said that like most bacteria, Salmonella typhi
can survive in a frozen environment. In fact, they store bacterial
samples in their research collection 70 degrees below zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``They live longer and better at lower temperatures,'' Mintz
said.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria's resilience at low temperatures could help explain
its presence in frozen mamey products. But investigators are still
trying to determine at what point the mamey could have become
tainted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's highly contaminated fruit, whether the contamination
occurred in the field through unsanitary irrigation or people not
washing their hands at the frozen processing phase,'' McElroy said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Donald writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
