<HEADLINE>
FOR FIRST LADY'S VISIT TO NEW YORK, `INTENSE' EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-CLINTONS) 
(sw) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The trip was planned months ago as just another visit
of the first lady to a favorite city. But when Hillary Rodham
Clinton arrives in New York on Wednesday to give speeches, meet
with supporters and tour schools, the visit will instantly be seen
as the first exploratory trip of a potential Senate candidate from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Attention from the news media will rival, if not surpass, that
for a presidential visit, officials said. ``I think this is
probably as intense for us as it's gotten,'' said Marsha Berry,
Mrs. Clinton's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, organizations that do not routinely cover the first
lady's travels _ networks, newsmagazines and the foreign press _
deluged Mrs. Clinton's office with questions about the trip. A
secretary at a school in Queens that Mrs. Clinton planned to visit
on Wednesday morning described the atmosphere there as ``crazy.''
And Laura G. Ross, the head of a fund-raising group that Mrs.
Clinton was scheduled to address at lunch, said the event sold out
two weeks ago at 900 people and that there was still a waiting list
of several hundred.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always a draw, but this is bigger than ever,'' Ms. Ross
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices for the event range from $10,000 to $150. For
$10,000, for example, a donor can participate in a ``round-table
discussion'' with Mrs. Clinton and 49 others before lunch. For
$1,000, the donor gets a picture taken with the first lady. Ms.
Ross said the event had raised more than $500,000 for the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who said two weeks ago that she was giving
``careful thought'' to the possibility of running for the Senate
seat that Daniel Patrick Moynihan will vacate in 2000, planned to
speak on Wednesday morning on arts education at Intermediate School
25 in the Flushing section of Queens, then tour a classroom.
Afterward, she planned to appear at the Plaza Hotel in Manhattan
for the fund-raising lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton planned to spend the afternoon in ``private time''
at the Waldorf-Astoria, where she is staying. In the evening she
expected to attend a dinner at the Manhattan home of Jurate
Kazickas and Roger C. Altman, an investment banker who was
President Clinton's deputy Treasury secretary and whose firm bought
The National Enquirer and Star magazine two weeks ago. The dinner
was described as a gathering of 15 people, not a fund-raising
event, that would include business executives and leaders of
nonprofit groups.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, Mrs. Clinton is to give an address at the
United Nations to commemorate International Women's Day, and on
Thursday afternoon will speak about Women's History Month and
female athletes at the Lab School at the O. Henry Learning Center
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much like all the trips she does where she tries to
highlight issues that are important to families and the general
public,'' Ms. Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   At I.S. 25, Mrs. Clinton is scheduled to release a study by the
President's Committee on the Arts and Humanities describing how
school districts can improve arts education. Community School
District 25 in New York, which includes I.S. 25 and 30 other
schools in northern Queens, is one of eight districts nationwide
that the report singled out as exemplary in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who is also considering running for
Senate from New York, said this week that Mrs. Clinton was
highlighting a school program, Project Arts, that he had announced
financing for in his State of the City speech two years ago. He
joked that he hoped she would bring a check for the program from
Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
