<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL INTERVENES AS INFLATION FEAR SENDS CURRENCY DOWN
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By LARRY ROHTER 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Weakened by uncertainty about revisions
in the government's agreement with the International Monetary Fund
and growing fears of a rise in inflation, the Brazilian currency
continued its slide to a record low against the dollar on Tuesday,
forcing the central bank to intervene for the fourth time in a
week.
</P>
<P>
   The currency, the real, dropped as low as 2.22 to the dollar
before recovering somewhat and settling at 2.16 after the central
bank stepped in. In New York, the real edged up to 2.10 to the
dollar from 2.13 on Monday after falling 8.6 percent in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Since Brazil devalued its currency in mid-January, it has
declined more than 40 percent, leading to sharp increases in prices
of imported goods and forcing the government to raise interest
rates to levels that threaten to suffocate the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate cause of the sharp drop in the real's value over
the last two days was the need for Brazilian companies to pay
obligations to foreign creditors. The lenders, because of their
continued concerns about the economic crisis here, have been
unwilling to roll over about $2 billion in bonds and other payments
due this month, and Brazilian debtors have been forced to scramble
to obtain dollars. ``This is not really a run against the real,''
Paulo Ferraz, president of Banco Bozano Simonsen, said Tuesday.
``This is a specific demand for payments of Eurobonds, and once it
is met, I would hope the dollar will begin to fall.''
</P>
<P>
   But market analysts said other factors, chiefly a sharp rise in
the rate of inflation, traditionally the Brazilian economy's great
worry, have also played a role in the decline of the real this
week. By official calculation, prices rose 3.61 percent last month,
more than double the 1.79 percent recorded during all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation, which as recently as five years ago had been running
above 1,000 percent annually, is expected to increase further in
March and April, as January's devaluation makes the price of
everything from medicine to wheat more expensive. As a result,
interest rates, which already stand at a punishing annual rate of
41 percent, may soon be running behind inflation, increasing the
likelihood they will have to be raised more.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, has exacerbated fear that the recession brought
on by the collapse of the real will be longer and deeper than the
government is willing to acknowledge. Hence, the anxiety about the
precise terms of the new targets for spending cuts and taxes
contained in the revised agreement being negotiated with the IMF _
something made necessary after President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
abandoned the defense of the real in mid-January.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When the decision to allow the real to float freely on the
foreign-exchange markets was announced then, the government
indicated that it would no longer intervene to prop up the
currency. The central bank reversed course once the real passed the
symbolic level of 2 to the dollar, but has acted inconsistently in
recent days, encouraging speculators to mount attacks on the
currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Above all, what is needed is a more active posture by the
economic team, especially the president of the central bank,'' said
Carlos Kawall, chief economist for Citibank. ``Absent a more
vigorous role as regards exchange policy and other initiatives, the
market will continue'' reacting unfavorably.
</P>
<P>
   The real's recent decline has come despite a statement Monday by
Michel Camdessus, managing director of the IMF, that good news
would soon result from the negotiations with Brazil. The market
``was anticipating a quicker freeing up'' of IMF money and a return
of bank credit ``than we are seeing now,'' Kawall said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, impatience with the IMF and the deep spending
cuts required as part of its $41.5 billion aid package is growing.
Some of Cardoso's closest political allies have joined in the
chorus of complaints, spreading concern that the Brazilian Congress
may not agree to some of the IMF's demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that the government needs to go to the IMF,''
Antonio Carlos Magalhaes, the president of the Brazilian Senate and
Cardoso's most powerful political associate, said last week. ``But
that doesn't mean the IMF can interfere in national problems, above
all to create difficulties for the poorest sectors in Brazil.''
</P>
<P>
   Arminio Fraga, president-designate of the central bank, has been
having acrimonious confirmation hearings in Brasilia. Opposition
senators have interrogated him mostly about his ties to the
financier George Soros, his previous employer. But some questions
have elicited indications that he intends to move ahead with an
austerity program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monetary policy in the next few months will necessarily have
to be characterized by a restrictive slant so long as the
transitory effects of the devaluation have not disappeared,'' Fraga
said on Friday. He warned that ``the next few months are going to
be difficult,'' with unemployment likely to rise and businesses to
go bankrupt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
