<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5206 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANDIDATE-BUSH-COX     03-02 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDIDATE-BUSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gov. Bush gets ready to run
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After months of soul-searching for reasons to
run for his dad's old job, George W. Bush hit upon the same ones he
came up with when he decided to run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Tuesday he is convinced he can make a positive
difference for his country without making too much of a negative
difference for his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have a compelling reason to consider running for
president,'' he said at a news conference outside the Governor's
Mansion. ``For my family and every family in America, I want the
21st century to be prosperous. And I don't want anybody being left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Tuesday's announcement was a political baby step _ Bush
will form an exploratory committee to begin raising money for a
potential candidacy _ the governor left little doubt that he wants
to become the first son of a president to get the top job since
John Quincy Adams in 1825.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what could happen to prevent the exploratory effort from
blossoming into a full-fledged candidacy, Bush said: ``A giant
thud. A huge yawn. That it turns out it was my mother they were
interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   Huge yawns and giant thuds greeted the last three Texans who
sought the presidency: Democrat Lloyd Bentsen in 1976, Republican
John Connally in 1980 and Republican Phil Gramm in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   On the family front, Bush and wife Laura said they have decided
they can jump into the fishbowl without drowning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along the biggest hesitation is the impact on my
family,'' said Bush, father of twin 17-year-old daughters. ``I have
talked with Laura and the girls, and while there is some natural
concern about the potentially major change in our life, I am
convinced and Laura is convinced that our love for each other is
strong enough and our family is close enough to take whatever life
brings.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated next to her husband, Laura Bush said she is ready to go
down the presidential campaign path again, this time with a husband
instead of a father-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows, I think, that I was hesitant about this,'' she
said. ``This is just one step, obviously, just the first step. What
I was hesitant about was the ugliness that we all see of political
life. George and I lived through a 1992 election with his dad. It
was a very miserable year for us, and I dread criticism of my
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand,'' she added, ``I love George and I am very
proud of him. And I know he would make a great president.''
</P>
<P>
   As the news conference ended, Laura Bush talked about the
campaign the way some people talk about going to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prepared for it. I know what it will be like. I've been in
a couple of presidential races before. Not as the wife of the
candidate, but I'm prepared and I know what it is going to be
like,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as if she sensed a tone more negative than she
intended, she added, ``Looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Months of speculation
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush's step into the race comes after months of private
talks with potential supporters and polls that show him as an early
frontrunner for the GOP nomination. Though some have been
campaigning for years, Bush and former Red Cross President
Elizabeth Dole have topped recent polls by wide margins.
</P>
<P>
   As many Texans suspected, Bush said he made up his mind to head
down the presidential path weeks ago, right around the Jan. 19
inauguration that started his second term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to get more comfortable with the idea,'' he said.
``It's a hard decision to make, and I began to feel comfortable
inside. I began to get a sense of peace inside my soul and in my
heart, and I began to think seriously about setting up the
exploratory committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he occasionally drifted into a tone that made a
full-blown candidacy seem like a sure thing _ ``One of these days
I'm going to be in Des Moines'' _ Bush insisted this really is an
exploratory effort to test whether people who have opened their
mouths in support are now willing to open their checkbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to have all the interested people fly down,''
he said of the stream of out-of-staters who have been to the
mansion to talk presidential politics. ``The next step is to
determine whether I can raise money. And that's what we are going
to start doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate goal is working toward a $25 million war chest.
Bush also must decide whether to take federal matching money for
his campaign. That cash comes with strings, including a limit on
campaign spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the current legislative session, which ends May 31, is
his top priority and he has no political travel planned until after
then. The immediate schedule calls for a formal Sunday announcement
of the exploratory committee, which will allow him to raise and
spend money in furtherance of his candidacy, followed by a
pre-announcement tour during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura and I will begin to do some travelling around the
country to meet with people, to listen to their concerns and
explore on our own the prospects of becoming a formal candidate,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dispelling the rumors
</P>
<P>
   In addition to putting the fund-raising machine in motion,
Bush's announcement ended months of speculation that he might skip
the race because of something from his self-titled ``young and
irresponsible'' period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though most people in the political system have long
believed that he would run, there is a persistent rumor in
political circles that family considerations and past sins will
keep him out,'' said University of Virginia political scientist
Larry Sabato. ``And this goes part of the way toward dispelling
those rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said there is nothing in his past that would disqualify
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had there been skeletons that would have destroyed a
candidacy, you'd have found them in 1994 and 1998,'' he said of his
two gubernatorial races.
</P>
<P>
   Texas media only, please
</P>
<P>
   The Tuesday news conference initially was intended as a briefing
for Texas reporters in advance of the formal announcement on
Sunday. It grew into a news conference of major proportions, with
about 30 television cameras. The national press, however, was
excluded. Those who showed up were turned away at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a briefing for the Texas media,'' Karen Hughes, Bush's
press secretary, told a CNN crew.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bush: ``I'm sure we did ruffle feathers by excluding the
national media. I respect the national media, but I hope the
national media respects my desire to fulfill a promise I made to
the Texas press corps.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments were occasionally accompanied by shouts from
about 12 people who gathered across Lavaca Street, behind the
mansion, to continue their protest of the state's decision to join
a court challenge of the Americans with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Partisan reactions
</P>
<P>
   Bush's announcement drew predictably partisan reaction.
Republican Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, who would become governor if Bush
becomes president, said it sounds like a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``America needs a leader of his character, conservative vision
and compassionate, unifying philosophy,'' Perry said. ``It's his
decision to make, but a President George W. Bush would be great for
Texas and great for America.''
</P>
<P>
   Au contraire, said Texas Democratic Chairwoman Molly Beth
Malcolm, who declared Bush the wrong man at the wrong time. Despite
Bush's pledge that the current legislative session is his top
priority, Malcolm said, it sounds like Texas is about to have an
absentee governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that people that ran for office give their
total, undivided attention to this great state,'' she said. ``I
certainly doubt he is going to be able to pay the kind of attention
here he needs to in the middle of organizing a presidential
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's announcement came the same day that commentator Pat
Buchanan, a longtime nemesis of the elder George Bush, went to New
Hampshire to announce he will make a third bid for the GOP
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his announcement was timed to coincide with Texas
Independence Day, not Buchanan's entry into the race.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kherman(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
