<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC SERIAL NUMBERS RAISE PRIVACY CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   From computers to cellular phones to home electronics, everyday
devices and software programs are increasingly embedding telltale
identifying numbers that enable them to interact. That trend is
generating a bitter dispute pitting the interests of security and
convenience against privacy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy groups argue that the merger of computers and the
Internet has brought the specter of a new surveillance society. But
a growing alliance of computer industry executives, engineers, law
enforcement officials and scholars contend that absolute anonymity
is not only increasingly difficult to obtain technically but is
also a potential threat to democratic order because of the
possibility of electronic crime and terrorism. ``You already have
zero privacy _ get over it,'' Scott McNealy, the chairman and chief
executive of Sun Microsystems, said recently.
</P>
<P>
   SINCE BIRTH, EURO HAS FIZZLED
</P>
<P>
   In the two months since the European single currency was
introduced, pretty much the only direction it has moved is down.
The decline has surprised most experts and puzzled the overseers of
the new currency at the European Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
   CAR SALES STRONG IN FEBRUARY
</P>
<P>
   Major auto makers reported record sales for February. Ford Motor
and DaimlerChrysler both said sales rose 8 percent. American Honda
said sales rose 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SONY INTRODUCES PLAYSTATION II
</P>
<P>
   Making what could be a quantum leap in the march to wed consumer
electronics to computers and the Internet, Sony introduced the
widely anticipated second generation of its hit Playstation
video-game console.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCASTER WANTS TO TRY BANKING
</P>
<P>
   Pat Robertson, the religious broadcaster, wants to go into the
banking business. He and the Bank of Scotland applied for a charter
to operate a new national bank that will not have any branches but
will instead deal with customers by telephone and mail.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL GIANTS POST GOOD PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   The retail giants Federated Department Stores and Dayton Hudson
reported quarterly profits that beat forecasts, aided by the
economy's strength, which spurred sales of home goods and clothing.
Shares of Federated gained 75 cents, to $40.625, while Dayton
Hudson fell $2.25, to $61.437.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER SHARES PULL STOCKS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended lower, led by Intel and 3Com, on concern that
waning demand and increased competition will hurt profits in the
computer industry. Nasdaq fell 36.15 points, or 1.6 percent, to
2,259.03. The Dow industrials fell 27.17 points, or three-tenths of
a percent, to 9,297.61. The S.&AMP;P. 500 declined 10.66 points, or
nine-tenths of a percent, to 1,225.50.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year bond rose 2432, to 942632.
Its yield fell to 5.61 percent, from 5.66 percent on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
