<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Remember Lucent? Don't Write Off HP's Misfit Measurement Unit  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Don't be so eager to dismiss Hewlett-Packard's laggard measurement
business as the runt.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, sure HP's better-late-than-never decision to emancipate
its core computer business from its disjointed test-and-measurement
businesses should unlock the value of HP's listless shares.
</P>
<P>
   An immediate bump in HP's stock price is most assuredly one of
the obvious benefits to shareholders after the proposed velvet
divorce occurs sometime over the next 12 to 18 months. In fact, HP
jumped &UR;  &LR; 4 percent to $65.63 on the news yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   However, investors should not be so quick to conclude that HP's
proposed carve-off is a turkey when it comes to its measurement
operations. Remember Bell Labs? It was once considered the runt of
Ma Bell's litter when Washington directed the mother-of-all telcos
to bust up its cozy monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the prized offspring were the regional telephone
companies, such as Pacific Bell, which is now a unit of SBC
Communications of San Antonio (formerly Southwestern Bell).
</P>
<P>
   But something funny happened on the way to the Information Age.
Many of the gadgets that dowdy Bell Labs made became integral to
the explosion of the Internet. So, AT&AMP;T repackaged boring Bell Labs
with a slick new name and spun off the once-unrespected division as
a sexy reborn technology company.
</P>
<P>
   Voila, Lucent Technologies was born. And it has made its
long-term holders very happy. If it were not for a 2-for-1 split,
Lucent shares would be trading at about $200, up sizeably from
their April 1996 IPO price of $27.
</P>
<P>
   Now, don't get me wrong. I'm not predicting that HP Test and
Measurement Inc. (or whatever moniker the spin-off adopts) will be
the second coming of Lucent. It's just that Edward ``Ned''
Barnholt, the measurement unit's new chief executive, may be in
position to turn his stepchild into a better investment than most
people realize at this point.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPIN CYCLE &LR; : Speaking of unlocking shareholder value, one of
Street Smarts' favorite targets (pun intended) for a spin-off,
sell-off or some form of divestiture is Dayton Hudson of
Minneapolis. The retailing giant and parent of discount juggernaut
Target Stores and middlebrow also-ran Mervyn's of Hayward, reported
its year-end earnings yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Powered by Target, DH reported that profit from operations
soared 27 percent to 97 cents a share, 7 cents better than the Wall
Street consensus estimate. Despite the stellar showing, DH shares
slipped about 3 percent to $61.88.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET03 (87780 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  As regular readers of this column are aware, Street Smarts thinks
that DH should unload Mervyn's and /or its department store
division to unlock the value of Target, which could then allow DH
shares to perform more in step with those of retail stock superstar
Wal-Mart. (Full disclosure: I have been beating this same drum
since I covered the company for a Chicago publica tion several
years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   In response to a recent column whereby Street Smarts reported
that Kohl's of Wisconsin showed interest in Mervyn's (a story I
stand by), Mervyn's President Bart Butzer suggested that we focus
our coverage on his company's performance.
</P>
<P>
   OK, here goes. Mervyn's pretax profit for the fiscal year ended
on January 30 was $240 million, down 14 percent from the previous
year. In addition, total sales were down about 1 percent for the
fiscal year. Mervyn's comparable sales for stores open a year or
longer _ a key retail measurement _ increased barely 1 percent.
Target's comp-store sales, on the other hand, rose about 6 percent
for the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon me, that's hardly evidence of a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a Mervyn's spokeswoman put a positive spin on the
results (Butzer was unavailable for comment), pointing out that
same-store sales for the fourth quarter were up more than 4
percent. And same-store sales growth is what DH chief executive
Robert Ulrich is asking from Butzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased with that performance. That's what Dayton
Hudson wants to see from us,'' says Mervyn's spokeswoman Carol
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Mervyn's needs to continuously grow same-store sales
to prove that it is on the right track and worth keeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to meet that commitment,'' Johnson says. ``(Anything)
beyond that would be speculation as to what would become of
Mervyn's.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, nothing was said by DH management regarding
potential divestiture during yesterday's conference call with large
investors and research analysts, according to analysts on the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one had the nerve to bring it up,'' says analyst Edward
Weller of Sutro in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of STREET03 (87780 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE COMEDY CHANNEL &LR; : Publicly held companies revel in the free
television exposure their chief executives often receive from CNBC
at stock conferences. Usually, it involves several vanity-filled
minutes of softball questions lobbed against a desert or mountain
backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   But, unbeknownst to him at the time, Charles Schwab Co-CEO David
Pottruck became comedic fodder at the expense of a rival online
brokerage during his interview yesterday on the financial cable
network.
</P>
<P>
   As Pottruck was fielding questions from a Wall Street Journal
reporter at the Hambrecht &AMP; Quist Internet stock conference at
Snowbird, Utah, a superimposed graphic popped up directly beneath
his talking head. It said (I kid you not): ``Ticker sponsored by
E-Trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, you can bet that E-Trade CEO Christos Cotsakos is
pinching himself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
