<SLUG> BC-JESSE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Workforce Coalition Lashes Out at Cypress CEO  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The head of a community group pushing for greater diversity in
Silicon Valley's workforce yesterday criticized Cypress
Semiconductor CEO T.J. Rodgers' for saying on television that the
Rev. Jesse Jackson was ``like a seagull that flies around leaving
droppings.''
</P>
<P>
   John Templeton, founder of the ad hoc Coalition for Fair
Employment in Silicon Valley, said he was ``appalled'' because
Rodgers' ``scatological'' remark was insulting to Jackson and
African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it crossed the line,'' Templeton said. ``This is the
leading black preacher in the country. I took it as an insult and
would expect any black person who saw it to take it as an insult as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers, whose comments were broadcast on KRON-TV during a news
report on Jackson's visit Sunday and Monday to Silicon Valley,
could not immediately be reached for comment. He has a reputation
for being blunt and stirring up controversy.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman, though, said the remark was not meant as a
racial insult, but was a comment about Jackson interfering in
Silicon Valley's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Wing, statewide coordinator for Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition, said he had no comment until he discussed the issue with
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights leader was in the Bay Area to launch a Silicon
Valley version of his Wall Street Project. His Rainbow coalition is
buying small amounts of stock in publicly traded companies as a way
to encourage boards of directors to hire and do business with more
women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers has long contended that Silicon Valley's booming
technology industry is a meritocracy, where talented people of any
race and gender can get ahead.
</P>
<P>
   However, a story in The Chronicle last year revealed that
Cypress' workforce in 1996 was only 3 percent black and 6 percent
Latino. Rodgers told The Chronicle last year, ``We hire the best
people for the job, regardless of race, color or creed, and we find
that we end up with a pretty fair mix of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Templeton was originally upset that KRON-TV chose to air
Rodgers' comment but later said his group would focus its protests
on Cypress Semiconductor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comments that Mr. Rodgers made were quite strong and quite
striking,'' KRON news director Dan Rosenheim said. ``Coming from a
prominent leader of the Silicon Valley business community and head
of a major semiconductor company, I think those comments were very
newsworthy. So we felt it ought to be aired.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of JESSE03 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
