<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Cisco Systems Seeks to Build New Campus  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon and Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Cisco Systems, growing so rapidly that it's bursting at the seams,
said it plans to build a $1 billion, 400-acre campus in Coyote
Valley, about 14 miles south of downtown San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The networking company, which has added more than 8,500
employees in the past two years, said it needs more space to
accommodate its growing workforce. The new site could house as many
as 20,000 employees and would double both Cisco's employment
worldwide and its real estate holdings in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're announcing today is really the future growth of
Cisco,'' John Chambers, Cisco president and chief executive, said
at a press conference yesterday at the company's San Jose
headquarters. The expansion is the largest in Cisco's history, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco, which makes much of the plumbing that runs the Internet,
has expanded rapidly since it was founded by a husband-and-wife
team in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cisco employs about 17,000 workers worldwide, with about
10,000 in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   As competition in the networking industry heats up, Cisco has
made no secret about its intention to continue growing. The company
has announced hundreds of new hires almost every quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco currently operates from 40 buildings on about 300 acres in
San Jose but is rapidly running out of room. Cisco officials said
the company had been looking to expand for several months and
settled on Coyote Valley because of its proximity to the main
campus on Tasman Drive in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers said the new site may also provide some transportation
and housing relief to employees. Besides being adjacent to the
Caltrain route, the location is closer to affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the new campus is contingent upon approval from
the city of San Jose, which needs to give Cisco building permits
and pay to upgrade roads and other infrastructure in what is now a
mostly rural area. Neither Cisco nor the city would disclose how
much the company plans to contribute toward those costs.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of CISCO03 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Approvals may be required from the Santa Clara Valley Water
District, the U.S. Department of Fish and Game (because of a nearby
creek) as well as the city zoning board, planning commission and
the San Jose City Council, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to make this happen in the near future,''
said San Jose Mayor Ron Gonzales. Once San Jose gives its approval,
the campus should be complete within three to five years _ not a
moment too soon for a company that is experiencing explosive
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco, which makes routers and switches that transmit data
across the Internet, has been growing rapidly through expansions
and internal hires. Cisco has acquired more than 30 companies over
the past several years and is expected to buy additional technology
companies in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company that plays to win and that's what they've
done,'' said Michael Cristinziano, senior vice president and equity
analyst at Gerard Klauer Mattison in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Cristinziano and others expect Cisco's revenue to grow by at
least 30 percent over the next few years, boosted by sales of
networking equipment to service providers, such as telephone
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Phone companies and other businesses are looking to networking
companies like Cisco to help manage their corporate voice and data
networks. The amount of data traveling across networks now outpaces
the amount of voice traffic. Companies want to shift voice and data
onto a single network so it can be managed more efficiently. Cisco
just happens to have the technology and the products to help
achieve that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, such as Lucent Technologies and Northern
Telecom, are also developing that technology and going after the
same customers, but Cisco has managed to grab significant market
share.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of CISCO03 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Cisco has really grown their revenues and profits much faster
than their peers,'' said Megan Hackett, senior technology analyst
with S&AMP;P Equity Group in New York. ``The company has been superior
in executing its business strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco has also been helped by the popularity of the Internet,
which is powered by much of Cisco's equipment. That has boosted
Cisco from obscurity to a company that's now considered one of the
computer world's Big Three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cisco has achieved the status of a Microsoft or an Intel,''
Cristinziano said. ``They are one of the real leading companies.
Now they're even starting to advertise on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Cisco is attempting to create name recognition and
the addition of a new campus are signs that the company is geared
for battle, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The new campus) is a strong statement as to how much they've
grown and how much they intend to grow,'' Hackett said. ``Cisco is
definitely a company arming itself for this new market.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of CISCO03 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
