<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Editors: Note ``UNDERSCORE'' in Web address should be
replaced  with underline   More Tax Tips for Small Firms 
 &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Is it necessary to keep receipts, canceled checks and
other records for business expenses under $75? Some small-business
friends say you don't have to but when I called the IRS, the
official line is you need to have documentation for even the
smallest expense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  It is true that many companies don't require receipts
for small expenditures, like $10 for office supplies. But the
Internal Revenue Service can disallow any deduction you don't have
a receipt for, says CPA Rich Gunn of the San Francisco firm Burr
Pilger &AMP; Mayer. Nevertheless, many businesses establish a cutoff of
$50 or $75, he says, because they figure it's not cost effective to
track and maintain the records for every paper clip and plastic
pen. Ultimately, not maintaining all records is based on your level
of risk and willingness to lose an unsubstantiated deduction if
confronted by an eagle-eyed auditor.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you are traveling on business, instead of keeping
records of your meal expenses and deducting the actual cost, you
can generally deduct a standard meal allowance ranging from $30 to
$42 depending on where and when you travel. For more information on
business travel expenses and restrictions, refer to Tax Topic 511,
or Publication 463, Travel, Entertainment, Gift, and Car Expenses.
Federal business tax information is available online at
( &LR; www.irs.ustreas.gov/ &LR;   &LR; prod/bus(UNDERSCORE)info &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Road Worrier
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband is self-employed and to cut down on the cost of
flying and renting a car, he often drives from San Francisco to Los
Angeles. Should he take a standard mileage deduction or deduct the
cost of gasoline and actual expenses?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not sure how your husband values his time, or whether he
charges clients for his road work. In any case, there are two ways
to account for business travel: You can take actual expense plus
depreciation, or you can take the standard mileage deduction of 31
cents per mile. Do the computation both ways for the entire year to
see which yields the higher deduction.
</P>
<P>
   You must stick with one method to figure your annual costs,
according to CPA Rich Gunn. No deductions are allowed for personal
use of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the total deduction and depreciation you can take on a car
you first used for business in 1998 cannot exceed $3,160 unless it
is a ``clean fuel'' vehicle. Check the section 179 deduction at the
IRS Web site mentioned above.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GROW03 (31777 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Welfare Benefits
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the tax benefits for hiring people coming off of
welfare?
</P>
<P>
   A: Businesses can definitely do well by doing good. The
welfare-to-work credit lets companies that hire qualified long-term
family assistance recipients deduct $3,500 of the first $10,000 of
qualified wages paid each worker against their tax liabilities in
the first year. In the second year, they can offset half of the
first $10,000 of qualified wages directly against their taxes. The
program applies to those who begin work after Dec. 31, 1997, and
before July 1 of this year.
</P>
<P>
   To get the credits, companies must hire workers through programs
certified by the IRS and remember to apply for credit within 30
days of hiring the employee. If you wait until you file your tax
return, Gunn warns, you're too late. Check the IRS tax guide for
small business, or Form 8861.
</P>
<P>
   Vexing Vacation Rules
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the changes in deducting vacation pay or other
employee benefits?
</P>
<P>
   A: Employers who use the accrual method of accounting used to be
able to deduct vacation and severance pay even if employees didn't
receive it until 2-1/2 months after the end of the tax year. Now
employers are limited from deducting these expenses until the year
they actually occur. For tax years ending after July 22, 1998,
vacation and severance benefits are not considered ``paid'' until
the tax year the employees receive them.
</P>
<P>
   Self-Employment
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have recently made the leap from working for a company to
being self-employed. What are the main tax consequences?
</P>
<P>
   A: The two biggest problems for those who used to work for
someone else and now work for themselves is ``not realizing the
amount of taxes they must pay now that they are self-employed and
not making estimated tax payments,'' says San Francisco CPA Bruce
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers accustomed to having Social Security and Medicare
taxes (6.2 percent and 1.45 percent of gross wages, respectively)
taken out of their paychecks automatically often fail to realize
the impact of the self-employment tax.
</P>
<P>
   They must pay about 12 to 13 percent of their net profit in
self-employment taxes in addition to federal income taxes (15
percent to 39.6 percent) and California taxes (1 percent to 9.3
percent). To avoid underpayment, a self-employed person must pay
100 percent of the prior year's tax or 90 percent of the current
year's tax in four equal installments due by April 15, June 15,
September 15, and January 15. For those whose adjusted gross income
exceeds $150,000 on a joint return or $75,000 for a spouse who
files separately, the 100 percent is replaced by 105 percent for
the 1999 tax year.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of GROW03 (31777 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  So what do you do if you had a good job and paid a lot of taxes
last year but now face an uncertain future in the ranks of the
self-employed? Instead of using the above formulas, you are allowed
to use ``the annualized income method'' and make four installment
payments based on actual income, expenses, deductions, credits,
etc. for the periods ending March 31, May 31, August 31 and
December 31. However, Hall cautions, these calculations can be long
and tedious.
</P>
<P>
   Correction
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five percent of health insurance premiums for the
self-employed are deductible for 1998. That is up from 40 percent
in 1997, not 25 percent as I suggested in last week's column. For
California taxes, the deductible amount remained at 40 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
