<HEADER>
A5213 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GELATO-SFCHRON &LR;      03-02 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GELATO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Entrepreneurial Double Dipping  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The father-and-son team of John and Tom Heffernan liked Gelato
Classico so much they bought the company _ twice.
</P>
<P>
   Retired executive John Heffernan first bought the San Francisco
maker of Italian-style ice cream when it was a little two-shop
business. He and Tom built the business and sold out to
Baskin-Robbins, which was itself part of a much larger British
conglomerate that also operated Dunkin' Donuts and the Hiram Walker
liquor business.
</P>
<P>
   But like many big companies that diverge from their main
corporate menu, the new owners messed with the successful formula
and ultimately lost their appetite for running the business.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Tom Heffernan stepped in to buy it back at a bargain
price.
</P>
<P>
   Many entrepreneurs buy and build businesses and then sell out to
a corporate giant for a sweet price. But few get to buy them back.
And even fewer redeem their enterprises for less than they sold
them for in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known local example of entrepreneurial double dipping
is Charles Schwab, who sold the discount brokerage bearing his name
to BankAmerica Corp. in 1983 for $57 million. Four years later, he
bought it back in a deal that cost $328 million. Today, the company
is worth close to $30 billion, or nearly 100 times as much, and
Schwab's personal stake is worth about $3.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Caffe Classico, as it is now called, is a
pip-squeak, but its story illustrates the promise _ and perils _ of
building a business.
</P>
<P>
   The company began to take shape in 1976 when Charles Boles, a
local glider flight instructor and tow-plane pilot, was looking for
a way to give his income a lift. By chance, he heard about a pair
of Italian gelato-making machines and agreed to pay $7,000 over two
years for them.
</P>
<P>
   By 1979, Gelato operated two stores in San Francisco. Its creamy
vanilla, coppa mista and other ice creams and fruit sorbets were
creaming the competition in taste tests, and there were lines out
the door.
</P>
<P>
   Enter John Heffernan, who had recently wrapped up an executive
career at the Kaiser family of companies and then managed an Amazon
jungle project for world-class entrepreneur Daniel Ludwig. Infected
by the startup bug, Heffernan saw Gelato as a cool opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People called all the time and wanted me to reveal my secrets
over the phone,'' Boles recalled. ``Or they wanted to buy the
business for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Heffernan was different. ``He was gentlemanly, professional
and persistent,'' said Boles. After a few months of negotiations,
Heffernan agreed to pay Boles' asking price of $309,000 _ about
what it made in annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in heaven,'' Boles remembers. ``This was the first time
I had money in the bank and freedom. It was wonderful to be paid
for all your troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   While Boles took off for southern France for a couple of years,
John and Tom Heffernan began to grow the business, boosting
manufacturing capacity and developing franchises. Then in 1985, the
Heffernans began adding other attractions, starting with espresso
and other drinks, then pastries and soup, salads and sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that a retail store that didn't open until noon
and sold only gelato couldn't have peak sales throughout the day,''
explained current President Tom Heffernan, 36. To better fit the
new concept of a European sidewalk cafe, the company changed its
name to Caffe Classico from Gelato Classico.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the company's pricey ice cream and concept of offering
other products to draw traffic and spread expenses from morning to
night attracted the attention of Baskin-Robbins. With about 3,500
domestic outlets, Baskin-Robbins had pretty much saturated the
market and was looking for new concepts, Tom Heffernan said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GELATO03 (91286 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  As a sign of its seriousness, the ice cream giant reportedly paid
an acquisition search firm a fee of $2 million to find just the
right opportunity. John Heffernan wasn't looking for a buyer, but
the takeover offer of about 100 times earnings was ``too good to
refuse.''
</P>
<P>
   After nine months of negotiations, Caffe Classico, which had 31
stores at the time, agreed to sell out for an undisclosed price.
Baskin-Robbins and its corporate parent, Allied Domecq Plc, also
committed about $12 million to grow the business, according to Tom
Heffernan. ``They were talking about having 1,000 retail stores,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners quickly invested about $1 million in new ice
cream-making machinery and coffee roasting equipment to fuel the
expansion. That was fine with Tom Heffernan, who remained in charge
of production and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   But Baskin-Robbins also expanded the number of managers from
three to a dozen, and Heffernan said the amount spent for
management salaries soared from about $200,000 a year to $300,000 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners also elected to double the size of new stores to
about 1,200 to 1,400 square feet, which tripled the capital
investment to about $300,000 per unit. And also opened in
higher-rent locations.
</P>
<P>
   Heffernan was alarmed and offended by the meddling with Caffe
Classico's nonbureaucratic, low-overhead strategy. Looking back at
Baskin-Robbin's fat purchase price, he wonders, ``Why pay so much
for something you are going to change?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Allied put Baskin-Robbins and Caffe Classico under the
wing of its Dunkin' Donuts division. That change made it even more
clear to Heffernan that his business was just a crumb on the plate
of Allied, which aside from food is the world's second-largest
liquor-maker.
</P>
<P>
   For about a year, Heffernan said he was told to sign no new
leases or sell any new franchises, in other words, ``to stay
still.'' It was great for his golf game, but not his psyche. ``I
realized they will sell it or shut it down,'' he said. ``But in
either case, it's not good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   So Heffernan approached a senior director of Dunkin' Donuts, a
man he respected who had started out cutting doughnuts when there
were only four stores. ``I said `(Caffe Classico) is losing money,
so let me take it off your hands,''' Heffernan recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate owners agreed to sell. The price has not been
disclosed, but Heffernan insists it was well below what
Baskin-Robbins had paid and invested in new equipment.
</P>
<P>
   John Heffernan, who has invested in real estate and the stock
market since he was bought out eight years ago, said that when
Baskin-Robbins bought Caffe Classico in 1991, his lawyer told him
he ``shouldn't be surprised if they would later offer the company
back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is apparently somewhat common when a very large company
acquires a very small one, they fail with their effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past four years, Tom Heffernan has quietly returned to
practices that made Caffe Classico successful &UR;  &LR; at the company's
unmarked manufacturing plant and office off of Seventh Street in
San Francisco. He also has altered strategy. &UR;  &LR; Caffe Classico is
adding a few stores in Arizona, Southern California and elsewhere.
But adding franchise outlets is no longer the principal way to make
fuller use of the company's underutilized ice cream-making and
coffee-roasting machinery.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, Heffernan is expanding sales to hotels, restaurants
and other retailers. Customers include Hyatt Hotels, restaurateurs
Jeremiah Tower and Wolfgang Puck, and recently Nordstrom cafes. The
company also has talked with United Airlines about serving its
gelato to first-class customers, and it may license some chain
stores to put gelato freezer cabinets and neon signs in their
stores.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of GELATO03 (91286 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  With its new wholesaling efforts, Heffernan said the company had
record revenue in 1998, and sales could more than double this year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the man who started the company has no regrets.
Charles Boles still counts the Heffernans as his friends and
customers. Caffe Classico buys its hot fudge toppings from Boles'
MPK Sonoma food packaging company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5214 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETADS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-02 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETADS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 New Rules Try To Bring Order to Tracking Web Ads  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
In a big step toward imposing order on the wild and woolly world of
Internet advertising, an industry group yesterday published
voluntary guidelines for tracking the viewership of Web ads.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Web sites, ad-serving networks like DoubleClick and
third-party tracking services such as Media Metrix employ vastly
different methods and technologies to measure the viewership of a
given Web ad. The varying results frustrate advertisers, who need a
reliable system for evaluating who is seeing their messages and how
often.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the top reasons advertisers aren't putting more
money into the Web,'' said Jim Spaeth, a member of the FAST (Future
of Advertising Stakeholders) Steering Committee, which developed
the guidelines (posted at  &LR; www.fastinfo.org &LR; ). ``There's really
been chaos in measurement.''
</P>
<P>
   The new protocol is designed to standardize audience tracking
across the Web and also bring it in line with conventional media.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is comparability,'' said Spaeth. ``When a media
planner sits down to do a plan for the brand, he looks at outdoor
and radio and magazines and matchbook covers and online. If the
data for all of them don't reflect the same comparative value, the
planner has no way of judging'' which media will meet his
viewership goals.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposed standards catch on, Web ad measurements should
be accurate within 5 percent, according to FAST. A 45-day comment
period on the protocol began yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the initiative's key elements is its definition of the
impression, the basic unit of Web audience measurement.
</P>
<P>
   FAST defined an impression as an ``opportunity to see,'' which
means that the ad appeared on a page that was viewed by a Web
surfer, even if the visitor did not necessarily see the ad. For
example, if an ad appears at the bottom of a page and the visitor
never scrolls to the bottom, it is still counted as an impression.
</P>
<P>
   The committee chose this criterion, although inexact, because it
is used by other media. Television viewership, for example, is
based simply on whether the tube is turned on, not on whether
anyone is actually watching it.
</P>
<P>
   The FAST standards also address one of the biggest hurdles in
counting impressions, which is caused by a process called
``caching.''
</P>
<P>
   Caching happens when elements of a Web site are automatically
stored in a computer's memory to make downloading quicker on the
next visit. But most Web trackers can't measure the later visits.
This glitch causes a significant undercounting of ad and site
viewership.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of NETADS03 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  To ensure that visits using cache memory are counted, the FAST
group proposed that every Internet ad be embedded with a code to
alert the site where it appears that it has been viewed.
</P>
<P>
   Rex Briggs, a vice president of Millward Brown Interactive, a
Web marketing research firm, said the guidelines are important
because they ``make the ground rules clear.''
</P>
<P>
   But bigger questions remain about the effectiveness of Web ads,
he said. ``What the senior marketing people are hung up on is
whether (the Web) is the most effective way to reach consumers and
how it can be used to build relationships with consumers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   FAST is supported by the Advertising Research Foundation, which
Spaeth chairs; the Internet Advertising Bureau; and major
advertiser and ad agency trade associations.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of NETADS03 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
