<SLUG> BC-BLACK-FARMERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK FARMERS ARE DIVIDED ON SETTLEMENT OVER RACISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., name Stephon in 3rd graf is CQ) 
(HLW) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A split emerged in court on Tuesday among a group
of black farmers who had sued the federal government charging that
the Department of Agriculture had discriminated against them in
denying or delaying approval of loans.
</P>
<P>
   At an emotional hearing in federal district court before Judge
Paul Friedman, a number of black farmers urged that the
$400-million settlement reached in January in a class action
lawsuit be rejected as inadequate and failing to root out racism
within the Agriculture Department's loan program. Among those
dissenting from the settlement was Timothy Pigford, a North
Carolina farmer whose original complaint led to the class action
suit and for whom the case, Pigford vs. Glickman, is named.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no meaningful relief that talks about systemic change
in the department,'' said Stephon Bowens, a lawyer who represents
some of the black farmers who dissented from the settlement. ``All
of us here agree that there are systemic problems and that they're
pervasive.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, which could cost the government at least
$400 million, black farmers who say they were discriminated against
by federal farm loan officials could receive damage awards of up to
$50,000 that would be virtually free of federal taxes. The
settlement also called for the Agriculture Department to forgive
any outstanding direct loans it made to black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Tuesday's hearing was a three-cornered affair with
Justice Department lawyers and those representing the 13 original
plaintiffs teaming up to fend off complaints from other black
farmers who said the cash settlement was too meager and that the
deal did not address the problem of racism within the Agriculture
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the farmers say Agriculture Department policies have
shrunk the number of black farmers from a high of 925,710 in 1920
to fewer than 20,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs and the government argued that the
settlement was one of the best deals ever negotiated in a class
action discrimination suit. They said that the $50,000 award was
larger than the average of $20,000 that was paid to Japanese
Americans who were interned during World War II, and more than the
$37,000 awarded to victims of the infamous Tuskegee experiment in
which unsuspecting blacks were injected with the syphilis virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case, this proposed settlement represents a watershed for
justice for blacks in places like Alabama and Georgia,'' said J.L.
Walnut, a lawyer representing the original plaintiffs who
negotiated the deal. ``It's not the end. It's just the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of black farmers _ a few in suits, a few in bib
overalls, most in open neck casual shirts _ and their supporters
squeezed into Friedman's courtroom. They took up every seat,
including those in the jury box, and leaned against walnut-paneled
walls under gilt-framed portraits of white men and women who were
former judges. Most of those in court appeared to be against the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman cast aside the usual court decorum and permitted
spectators to emit the occasional ``Amen!'' or break into applause
when they agreed with a speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also allowed non-lawyers to speak, including the Rev.
Joseph Lowery, the former head of the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference who supported the agreement, but asked for some modest
changes. Lowery and other speakers at times brought the emotion and
cadence of Southern Baptist preachers to the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for a change,'' said one of the dissenters, Mattie
Mack, a farmer from Brandenburg, Ky., who at one point wiped tears
away from her checks. ``Change the policy. Let the farmers be free.
That's what the Lord wants for us, to be free.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman did not give any indication of how soon he would rule.
But throughout Tuesday's proceedings, he gave broad hints that some
of the objections that were raised about the settlement were beyond
the scope of his authority to fix. For example, he noted that he
agreed with some of the problems with how the Agriculture
Department runs its loan program, specifically the amount of power
it delegates to local county agricultural committees. But he added
that such changes required political, not legal solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the Congress,'' he said. ``I'm not a state
legislature. I'm not the secretary of agriculture. There are things
I can do and pressure that I can bring to bear. But I think
everybody has to understand that all I can do is approve the
settlement of the lawsuit or not approve the settlement of the
lawsuit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
