<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5223 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JONES-NINE-WEST-NYT     03-02 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONES-NINE-WEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES APPAREL TO ACQUIRE NINE WEST FOR ALMOST $900 MILLION IN CASH
AND STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
 (fe) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jones Apparel Group Inc., a leading women's clothing
company, said Tuesday night that it would acquire Nine West Group,
one of the nation's largest shoe companies, in a deal valued at
nearly $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, worth $26 a share in cash and stock for Nine West's
shareholders, will combine two giants that market women's retail
apparel to many of the same customers: women who are willing to pay
moderate to high prices to fill their closets.
</P>
<P>
   It will also force Jones Apparel, a New York-based company that
sells suits, dresses and sportswear under such brands as Jones New
York and Evan Picone, to quickly master the business of footwear.
Jones will also take on problems now faced by Nine West, including
slowing sales and an investigation by the Federal Trade Commission
into the company's pricing practices.
</P>
<P>
   According to the companies, Nine West, which will be operated as
a separate unit, will get a new chairman when the deal closes: Mark
J. Schwartz, the president of Palladin Captial Group, a leveraged
buyout firm, and a member of Jones' board, will replace Nine West's
chairman, Jerome Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who founded Nine West with Vincent Camuto in 1977, will
become a consultant to Nine West, the companies said. It was not
clear whether Camuto, now Nine West's chief executive, will keep
his title. The companies' statement said only that Camuto ``will
continue to be actively involved.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Schwartz said that he believed Nine West
had already begun to reverse its disappointing results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see strong positve trends in their business,'' Schwartz
said. ``Customers are responding very positively to new spring
product. Positive steps have and will continue to be taken to
improve the operating performance.''
</P>
<P>
   But before the companies' announcement was made, some Wall
Street analysts who cover Jones Apparel said they had concerns
about a potential merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't make sense,'' said one Wall Street analyst who
would talk only on the condition of anonymity. ``Other than sharing
the same customer base, the strategic benefits to Jones are not
obvious, given that their background is in apparel and their
knowledge of footwear is limited.''
</P>
<P>
   The analyst said the business of selling footwear was much more
complicated and difficult than the business of selling apparel.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came hours after regulators halted trading of
the companies' stock because of rumors of the pending merger. The
last price for Nine West was $22.8125.
</P>
<P>
   But while the price of Nine West's stock has risen in the last
two weeks on rumors of a merger, Jones Apparel's shares have been
slipping. Jones' stock price was $25.9375 on Tuesday when trading
was halted, down $1.375 from Monday's closing price and down $4.125
from a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, each Nine West share will be acquired for 0.5011
of a Jones share and $13 in cash, adding up to $26 a share. The
cash and stock portion of the deal will total about $885 million,
and Jones will also assume Nine West's hefty debt, making the
overall obligation about $1.4 billion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The transaction is expected to close by the end of June and will
require approval of Nine West stockholders and antitrust
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have long sold their merchandise in large
department stores. But in recent years, Nine West has also begun
selling shoes in its own retail stores. The shoe company now has
more than 1,000 retail stores in the United States and another 169
stores in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Susan B. Silverstein, an securities analyst who covers Nine West
for Nationsbanc Montgomery, said one question the companies must
answer was what they would do with those stores. It might be
difficult for Jones to market its clothing in the current stores
because of the shoe stores' small size, and so the companies might
decide to close some stores, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nine West, which is based in White Plains, was once a darling
among retail stocks, selling shoes under brands like Enzo
Angiolini, Easy Spirit and Bandolino. But sales have slowed in the
last three years, and the stock price fell in May 1997 when the
company announced that securities regulators were investigating its
financial reporting practices.
</P>
<P>
   Early last month, executives of NIne West announced that
regulators had told them they had ended the investigation and did
not plan to take any action.
</P>
<P>
   But the Federal Trade Commission is currently investigating the
shoe company's pricing practices. And in January, lawyers filed a
lawsuit against the company on behalf of millions of women who have
purchased Nine West shoes at large department stores, contending
that the company conspired with the stores to fix prices illegally.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second major acquisition in six months for Jones
Apparel. In September, the company said it was buying the clothing
maker Sun Apparel Inc., which holds the license for Polo Jeans Co.
clothing, for $212 million in cash and stock. That purchase added
to the lines of clothing that Jones already made that are marketed
under the label of Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Jones reported 1998 earnings that were better than
expected and up 30 percent from 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
