*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 02, 1999 -- AMERICAN-MEAT-2, 3-02 -- A
butcher at work in Lobel, a meat market on Manhattan's upper
Eastside. Only about 2 percent of the beef sold in this country is
prime, the highest Agriculture Department (''U.S.D.A.'') grade,
with the most marbling from fat, and hence flavor, according to
Bruce Aidells, author of ``The Complete Meat Cookbook.'' (Norman Y.
Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- March 02, 1999 -- AMERICAN-MEAT-1, 3-02 --
Bruce Aidells in a meat market. Aidells and his collaborator, Denis
Kelly, has spent nearly a decade studying the state of meat in
America to produce ``The Complete Meat Cookbook,'' published last
November by Houghton Mifflin. Not only does it secure his image as
a man unafraid of meat, even in these vegetable-revering times, but
it also is rife with heretical ideas. (Thor Swift/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHIRAZ, Yugoslavia -- March 02, 1999 -- KOSOVO, 3-02 -- A
young ethnic Albanian is comforted as she weeps during a ceremony
marking the first anniversary of the first massacre of ethnic
Albanians in the Kosovo region on Tuesday. Ethnic Albanians claim
the massacre was carried out by Serb forces in the region. Adem
Demaci, the hardline political representative of the Kosovo
Liberation Army and opponent of the international community's peace
plan for the province, said Tuesday he had resigned. (Alan Chin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
