<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTONS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS' ARKANSAS ROOTS TRANSPLANT EASILY TO NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
   (See NY-MRSCLINTON) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They cause traffic jams of epic proportions. They
hold so many Manhattan fund-raisers that even their Democratic
allies complain. They have endorsed policies that have infuriated
labor unions, hospital officials, advocates for the poor,
immigrants and, oh yes, Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   So why is it that Bill and Hillary Rodham Clinton seem so
popular in New York?
</P>
<P>
   That is a question many New Yorkers may be asking themselves
these days as they watch Mrs. Clinton's very public exploration of
whether to run for the U.S. Senate from New York next year.
</P>
<P>
   They may also be pondering the question as they sit in midtown
traffic awaiting Mrs. Clinton's motorcade to pass Wednesday and
Thursday. The first lady is in town to deliver speeches before a
women's political group and the United Nations, meet with local
Democratic supporters and tour public schools in Queens and
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the idea that New Yorkers would embrace a former
governor of Arkansas and his Illinois-born wife still seems a bit
improbable. Neither has lived or worked in New York, and except for
occasional excursions to Manhattan or the Hamptons, they have not
even vacationed here much. Most of their visits have been to
campaign or to raise money. And they have feuded with a host of
local officials, including the Democratic senior senator, Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, who is retiring next year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet their connection to New York is strong for a range of
reasons, including their deep base of support among major
Democratic voting groups, the large number of New Yorkers in their
inner circle, widespread distrust of their conservative opponents
and the sense among some people that they radiate New York-style
panache and sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   A consensus of New York pollsters say both Clintons' ratings in
New York state tend to be several points higher than nationwide.
Clinton's job approval ratings in New York have been hovering in
the 60-percent range for more than a year now. And recent polls
show Mrs. Clinton scoring between 60 and 70 percent favorable
ratings statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Voters seem to respect her even in traditionally Republican
strongholds in the suburbs and upstate.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yorkers like the Clintons,'' said John Zogby, a pollster
from Utica. ``Period.''
</P>
<P>
   The clearest reason is that New York is a Democratic state _
registered Democrats outnumber Republicans by a ratio of 3 to 2 _
and the Clintons, despite their many scandals, have been the
country's most successful Democratic political couple in a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   But it is more than that, political analysts assert. New York,
they say, has higher concentrations of the major voting groups that
are the Clintons' most ardent supporters nationwide: professional
women, homosexuals, Jews and black and Hispanic residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are groups that are important to the Democratic Party
nationally,'' said Philip Friedman, a Democratic public relations
consultant in New York. ``But they are absolutely central to the
New York state Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of those groups were big fans of the Clintons during the
early years of the administration. But through politics and
policies, the Clintons have won them over. Many Irish-Americans, a
major New York voting bloc that is no longer reliably Democratic,
like Clinton for his role in helping to broker peace in Northern
Ireland, while Jewish-Americans have come to view the
administration as a stalwart defender of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   And a preponderance of blacks view Clinton as not only
sympathetic to their concerns about racism, but also
extraordinarily in tune with their culture, black politicians and
intellectuals say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton is functionally an African-American politician,''
said Manning Marable, the director of African-American Studies at
Columbia University, noting that the president gets higher approval
ratings among blacks than many black officials.
</P>
<P>
   But will the administration, and Clinton's, high job ratings rub
off on Mrs. Clinton if she runs for the Senate? Marable says yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a general perception that she is to his left,'' he
said. ``And that is just fine. Because ideologically, black
politics is social democratic. There is a deep belief in state
intervention to redress social problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The same may not be true with other groups. Mrs. Clinton may be
less trusted by Jews because of her open support for a Palestinian
state. Wall Street barons who like the administration's economic
policies may be uncomfortable with Mrs. Clinton's more expansive
view of government. Centrist Democrats and Republicans may view her
as too liberal on crime or social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is identified ideologically with the left,'' said Mitchell
Moss, the director of the Taub Urban Research Center at New York
University. ``That helps her in New York City, and it mobilizes her
core constituency. But New York state has not been electing
liberals for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and some pollsters also say that the moment Mrs.
Clinton becomes a candidate, her poll numbers will drop as she is
pressured to explain her positions in detail and demonstrate her
understanding of New York, a place she has never lived. State law
requires only that she be a resident as of Election Day next year
to seek the Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Politics aside, the Clintons clearly have a social affinity for
the city, one that many New Yorkers relish. There was the whirlwind
birthday party for their daughter, Chelsea, a couple of years ago,
complete with stops performances on Broadway. And there were the
visits to the Hamptons, featuring the omnipresent shoulder-rubbing
with society and Hollywood types.
</P>
<P>
   But what amazes some analysts is the fact that the Clintons have
received such loyal support from core Democratic groups despite
having taken positions that have angered those groups on numerous
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Many blacks objected vehemently to the 1994 crime bill that
expanded the federal death penalty and established mandatory
sentences for many crimes. Black and immigrant politicians in New
York were also furious with the president for signing the sweeping
welfare bill in 1996 that sharply curtailed benefits.
</P>
<P>
   New York hospital officials perennially fight proposed
administration cuts in health care spending. Most labor unions
hated the North American Free Trade Act, which the president
championed. Gays were deeply disappointed in 1996 when he signed
legislation allowing states to outlaw same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   But what has helped the Clintons overcome such anger has been an
even greater antipathy among New Yorkers toward the first couples'
opponents, many political analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican revolution of '94 and '95 really just scared
the hell out of New Yorkers, including moderate Republicans,''
Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Marable said, ``Even though African-Americans have had many
criticisms of this administration, from the crime bill to the
welfare bill, on balance, in the era of the Contract With America,
in the era of the Christian Coalition, in the period of attacks on
affirmative action, Clinton looks almost like a positive good
rather than a necessary evil.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' enemies may have helped them on another issue:
impeachment, which appears to have solidified Clinton's support in
New York and raised Mrs. Clinton favorable ratings, analysts say.
The first Lady has long been popular among professional women. But
her stoic, steadfast defense of her husband last year won her
additional support among more traditional, conservative women,
pollsters say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the year softened her image,'' said Lee M. Miringoff,
director of the Marist College Institute for Public Opinion in
Poughkeepsie, N.Y. ``People can, in different ways, identify with
the trauma she's gone through.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hope, chairwoman of the New York state Democratic Party,
said Mrs. Clinton should therefore benefit in a race against New
York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who is considering a run for the
Republican Senate nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think New Yorkers see her as the personification of the new
woman in transition,'' Ms. Hope said. ``That she has juggled a
child, a job and a loss of personal privacy with such style and
grace really inspires women.''
</P>
<P>
   But there may be vulnerabilities hiding inside Mrs. Clinton's
apparent strengths on the impeachment issue. While many people like
Mrs. Clinton for standing by the president, a smaller but still
substantial number of people seem to dislike her for exactly the
same reason.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say Mrs. Clinton may benefit from the competition
between New York City, a place she professes to love, and
Washington, a town she seems to despise. Many New York politicians
assert that their hometown is more sophisticated than the nation's
capital, more drawn to independent women, less upset by sexual
scandals. It may also help that some of her closest advisers are
New Yorkers, including Harold M. Ickes and Susan Thomases.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Manhattan might be the ideal place for both
Clintons to settle after he leaves office, whether she runs for the
Senate or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yorkers love people who live near the margins,'' said
Moss, the NYU political scientist. ``The very qualities that make
people like Billy Martin or Joe Namath helps explain why they like
the Clintons. New Yorkers like risk takers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
