<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5233 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGANDA-KIDNAP-ART-2ND     03-02 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-KIDNAP-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the Tutsi.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though the border with Congo is easily within an hour's
walk from the entrance to the forest park, the violence there
seemed far away on Monday as the camp was gradually coming to life
at 6:45 a.m. The sun was up, but it had yet to peek over the
surrounding hills.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the tourists were shaking themselves from sleep at that
point since the starting time for the trek up into the hills was at
8 a.m. They never made it.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels burst into the camp with a blast of grenades and
automatic weapons fire. The Ugandans _ a game warden and three park
rangers _ were killed in the initial assault. The rebels looted the
buildings, setting a few on fire and torching the vehicles they
came across as well.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors said that initially the rebels herded 31 tourists into
the Abercrombie and Kent encampment and began stripping them of
their valuables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly some soldiers came in the tent and they asked for
money, for jewelry, for watches,'' said Anne Peltier, the French
deputy ambassador to Uganda, who was among the survivors
</P>
<P>
   At first the rebels seemed to be treating the tourists well, but
some of those captured had a foreboding of what was to come by the
treatment of one group of British tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Adams, 54, from California, was among the 15 hostages
rounded up and sent into the jungle with the troops about 40
minutes after the first attack. She had already seen that the
British man sitting next to her had purple toenails from where he
had been beaten on the feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British people were being forced to walk barefoot if they
had no shoes,'' said Mrs. Adams, who feigned an asthma attack and
waved her inhaler as the march got underway. The soldiers let her
walk back into the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Studd, the mother of Susan Studd, a 46-year-old Oregon
woman who survived the attack, said she talked to her daughter in
Kampala on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   She said her daughter and her daughter's husband, Robert
McLaurin, 44, were awakened in their tent in the Abercrombie and
Kent encampment by grenade explosions and gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``They heard a woman scream, so they got out the back of their
tent and went into the bush and hid there,'' said Mrs. Studd. ``It
was just a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Another American, Elizabeth Garland, 29, a Fulbright scholar
from the University of Chicago, told her father that she escaped by
hiding in her tent. Her father, James Garland, the president of
Miami University in Ohio, told The Associated Press that his
daughter, too, had been awakened by gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Western governments had already warned tourists against
traveling through much of western Uganda because of rebel and
bandit activity near the border with Congo. Until now, however, the
Bwindi gorilla reserve had been considered safe.
</P>
<P>
   The attack struck a blow at Uganda, itself on the mend after
years of chaos. The State Department warned American citizens to
postpone travel to the region until further notice and at least two
tour companies said they were suspending trips to the region until
further notice.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Acacia Expeditions said six of the people killed were
on one of its tours. Its travelers, known as ``overlanders,'' are
generally budget tourists who spend weeks traveling across Africa
in large, open trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The other tour group, the upscale Abercrombie and Kent, which
ran the most exclusive tent encampment at the forest, announced on
Tuesday that it was closing the facility until it had assurances
that security could be maintained. Its clients would be offered
full refunds or alternative trips, said Alistair Ballantine,
president of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their income level, the tourists at the Impenetrable
Forest all lived in fairly close proximity in a series of clearings
that resembled a small village built near the entrance to the park.
</P>
<P>
   The most budget conscious tourists _ including most of those
sent by Acacia _ camped in a clearing. Nearby was a series of round
African huts known as bandas and a lodge run by the African Pearl
safari tour company. The Abercrombie and Kent Gorilla Forest Camp
was a series of 10 tents with concrete floors that were tucked in
amongst the trees for privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The search for a sight of the mountain gorillas had become
especially popular after the 1988 movie ``Gorillas in the Mist,''
which starred Sigourney Weaver as the researcher Dian Fossey who
dedicated her life to saving the gorillas in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Before Monday, the Impenetrable Forest was considered the last
safe place to seek out the gorillas because civil strife had put
the other habitats out of bounds. Three tourists trying to visit a
sanctuary in the embattled Congo have been missing since they were
kidnapped by rebels there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
