A5234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHTFLYER-TESTS-COX     03-02 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHTFLYER-TESTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wright Flyer to catch a wave of wind
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNNYVALE, Calif. _ Perched on its mount in the middle of a
giant NASA wind tunnel, the Wright Flyer replica looked ready to
catch the wind.
</P>
<P>
   But a large group of NASA workers and volunteers was still
working around the delicate craft Tuesday evening to make sure it
was indeed ready before the immense wind tunnel powered up to
gather the first full-scale data on the world's first airplane.
</P>
<P>
   The tunnel is a part of NASA's Ames Research Center here at
Moffett Field, a former Navy air station. The Ames center is
supporting a volunteer effort called the Wright Flyer Project to
test a full-size reproduction of the airplane the Wright brothers
flew at Kitty Hawk, N.C. in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles chapter of the American Institute of Aeronautics
and Astronautics, which developed the project, had hoped to start
wind tunnel tests on Monday, but preparations took longer than
expected. It was still uncertain Tuesday afternoon whether a test
would be run Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Tuesday, project chairman Jack Cherne carefully
jockeyed a large electric cart around the flyer, rising up and down
on the cart's swaying platform to make adjustments. Others used a
laser to align the flyer precisely in the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   The tunnel can generate winds up to nearly half the speed of
sound to test models of jets, but it will limit winds to 30 miles
per hour for the flyer. That's about the top speed it attained at
Kitty Hawk, project members said.
</P>
<P>
   Orville and Wilbur Wright made just four brief flights on Dec.
17, 1903, before a gust of wind wrecked the flyer as it stood
unattended. They knew their machine lacked stability, but Wright
Flyer Project members say no full-scale aerodynamic studies have
ever been done to find out exactly how the machine performed.
</P>
<P>
   Project members say they have an educational goal of learning
more about the airplane that changed the world, but they also hope
the data will aid in the building of another Wright Flyer replica
that they can fly safely at Kitty Hawk in 2003, on the 100th
anniversary of the first flights.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the poor stability of the flyer was a tribute to the
Wrights' flying skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that their first flight was 120 feet and their last
one was 852 feet shows they were learning,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
