<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5237 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-SECURITY-SPI &LR;      03-02 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-SECURITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS DOWNPLAY DANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVEN GOLDSMITH  
 and ELAINE PORTERFIELD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ ``Chester the Molester,'' as the cops called him,
accosted six women last year in the Los Angeles International
Airport garage.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh time, police were ready.
</P>
<P>
   An officer monitoring cameras at each entrance saw the suspect
drive up, and ``Chester'' is now behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is just one of the airports around the nation using
cameras and heavy patrols to fight crime in airport lots _ measures
that are lacking at Sea-Tac.
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Intelligencer found that the Sea-Tac garage is patroled
an average of less than once a day, that the few cameras in the lot
are linked to maintenance rather than security, and that a
half-dozen of the port's own police officers had warned of security
gaps long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sea-Tac's police force also is stretched more thinly than at
those airports, the P-I found.
</P>
<P>
   Port Commissioner Paige Miller Tuesday said she has asked port
staff to review how Sea-Tac differs from other airports in patrols
and surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is reasonable,'' she said, ``to ask what other airports are
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But like other three other port commissioners interviewed, she
stressed that the garage has been the scene of very few violent
crimes. Miller said it's important to note that most crimes at the
garage have been crimes of property, like car prowls, and not rapes
or assaults.
</P>
<P>
   And that leaves little reason for boosting garage staffing, said
Aviation director Gina Marie Lindsey.
</P>
<P>
   ``History doesn't seem to warrant throwing a lot of folks and
technology at the garage,'' Lindsey said.
</P>
<P>
   A woman shot two years ago in the huge Sea-Tac garage is suing
the port for negligence, but port officials say no security
measures could prevent that kind of sudden attack.
</P>
<P>
   But interviews with police at other airports around the country
show that they devote special resources to keeping their garages as
safe as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Police at Washington's Dulles aim cameras to cover every blind
spot at the lot. At Boston's Logan, troopers sometimes stake out
BMWs and other fancy cars on the chance thieves will target them.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's lots are watched by private security guards on
every floor, while L.A. officers sometimes use military
night-vision goggles to watch the sprawling airport lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of proud of what we've been able to do,'' said L.A.
airport police Capt. John Bangs. ``Every garage gets patrolled at
least a couple of times every shift.''
</P>
<P>
   Documents filed with the lawsuit indicate that the Sea-Tac
garage is not routinely patrolled, though officers from other beats
sometimes make checks there.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at other airports _ as well as nationally recognized
experts on parking _ say garages require special vigilence. They're
where people leave one of their most valuable and treasure-filled
possessions, and any theft that's interrupted has the potential to
turn violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Security should be at the top of the mind of anyone who's
offering parking to the public,'' said Brad Parrish, president of
V.P. Services, a consulting firm for parking operators.
</P>
<P>
   Another Seattle parking consultant, Greg Jacobson, said visible
security is simply good business, making people more more likely to
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling,'' he said, ``is spend the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Many garage planners at malls and other facilities follow that
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Below downtown Seattle, the 1,200-stall Pacific Place garage is
literally as bright as day thanks to white metal-halide bulbs
cranking out an average of 7.5 foot candles of illumination.
</P>
<P>
   That's about 14 times the brightness given off by the amber
lamps at the Sea-Tac garage, where Jacobson said the lighting level
is about one-half a foot candle _ roughly the visibility of the
desert in a full moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was really key for us,'' said Pacific Place spokeswoman
Jane Lewis, ``is that from the drawing board on up, the security
and comfort of the user were important.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Place designers also enhanced security by painting the
walls a reflective white and by removing such hiding places for
crooks as columns near car doors or areas with dark shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Port of Seattle officials have prepared a capital-budget
proposal to boost the lighting levels in the Sea-Tac garage, but no
date has been set, said Lindsay.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras monitored by security personnel, while not provided at
the 10,000-stall Sea-Tac lots, are an increasingly common safety
feature of large garages, said Norman Bottom, a Miami security
expert and author.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one location is more dangerous than a parking garage _
that's an external ATM,'' Bottom said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kingdome, movable cameras are used in the parking lot,
said Gene Willard, chief of security. If a person of interest is
seen in the lot, they can use the camera to zoom in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find surveillance cameras are excellent tools,'' Willard
said. ``The guard at the gate can find the suspicious person on the
camera and another guard can respond.''
</P>
<P>
   They also use employees to patrol rows of parked cars on foot
during events, along with a guard in golf carts to make rounds, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say cameras are part of an array of security devices and
visible uniformed patrols that ward off would-be criminals. Sea-Tac
airport's own employees are protected by some of those measures:
barbed wire surrounds their lot, which is controlled by a
round-the-clock employee.
</P>
<P>
   But the garage that travelers use needs more attention, said Don
Riser, a retired King County police sergeant who provides security
to car rental companies at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the port should put more security within the
structure itself,'' Riser said. ``It's dangerous, no question about
it ... if they can't afford cops, at least they could hire security
guards.''
</P>
<P>
   What would be especially helpful are patrols by bike or golf
carts, said Riser, who has worked in the garage since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bike guys in these kind of situations are great,'' he
said. ``The information they can pick up is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bike officers do sporadically patrol the Sea-Tac garage,
officials said, but the airport's police staffing is stretched
thinly as the growing number of flights brings a more visible
problem: lines of drivers clogging the pick-up and drop-off lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Sea-Tac ranks last in the size of its police force in a survey
of nine airports done by the Port of Seattle's own police in 1995 _
and recently updated by the Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   Portland, Orlando, Dallas/Fort Worth, Los Angeles, Denver,
Vancouver, B.C., Boston and San Francisco all had more police
officers in 1994 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sea-Tac travelers also were more likely to be crime victims than
at those at the seven airports for which statistics were available.
Vancouver did not report equivalent crime statistics, and
Portland's were incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the five port commissioners said Tuesday that port
police have never come to them with any concerns about security at
the garage. Miller, president Pat Davis, and commissioners Jack
Block and Clare Nordquist said recent requests for more police
officers have revolved around congestion on the drives.
</P>
<P>
   Though commissioners had not been alerted to any garage-security
concerns, the shooting victim's lawsuit turned up prior written
warnings of security lapses sent to superiors by a half-dozen of
the port's own police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Pat Davis said the port must base its police
staffing decision on the numbers of serious crimes at the airport,
and not what meaures other airports are taking to combat crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
