<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5240 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURWITZ-HEADWATERS-HN     03-02 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURWITZ-HEADWATERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC LUMBER SELLS REDWOOD TREES FOR $450 MILLION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
 
By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pacific Lumber Co., the Northern California logging
operation owned by Houston-based Maxxam, pulled off a last-minute
deal to sell a stand of centuries-old redwood trees to the federal
and California governments for $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after declaring the agreement to sell the Headwaters
Forest all but dead, the parties announced Tuesday they had
salvaged the 1/2-year-old effort to preserve the largest grove of
ancient redwood trees left in private hands.
</P>
<P>
   And while the participants may differ over whether the final
agreement is substantially different from the proposal rejected
last week, they agreed the signing just minutes before the deadline
represented a monumental achievement.
</P>
<P>
   California's Democratic Gov. Gray Davis said the benefits of
preserving the Headwaters will live on ``long after our mortal
footprints will be swept away by time,'' while Pacific Lumber
President John Campbell called it ``a sound and sensible solution
to a decade of controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord creates a 7,500-acre preserve near Fortuna, Calif.,
to protect the soaring redwood trees of the Headwaters _ some of
which date back 2,000 years or more _ as well as several, smaller
stands of old-growth redwood trees.
</P>
<P>
   To safeguard rare species like the marbled murrelet, the spotted
owl and the coho salmon, the agreement also restricts Pacific
Lumber's logging practices on its remaining 211,700 acres for the
next half a century.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is providing $250 million, while
California is contributing $130 million. In addition, the
California Legislature has agreed to spend $112 million more to
purchase an additional 2,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the federal and state governments will pay $492
million, with $450 million accruing to Pacific Lumber and the rest
going to another timber company and the local communities.
</P>
<P>
   To call the Headwaters deal an 11th-hour agreement does not do
justice to the negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress authorized the federal share back in 1997, it
required the money to be spent by March 1. The parties used a
tortured interpretation of the deadline to give themselves until
11:59 p.m. Monday _ California time _ to cut a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who had so beat up on Maxxam on Monday, celebrated
the news of a deal Tuesday. Maxxam shares rose 9 13/16 to close at
57 11/16 on the American Stock Exchange, capturing most of the
ground lost when the deal seemed imperilled.
</P>
<P>
   As late as Friday, Campbell had complained the combination of
state and federal restrictions would so limit the company's ability
to produce lumber as to wreck its financial viability.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement bars any logging within 100 feet of fish-bearing
streams and within 30 feet of other waterways. They also ban
logging operations in about 8,000 acres of old growth set aside as
conservation zones for the marbled murrelet.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said those and other restrictions would have slashed
the company's lumber production to about 136 million board feet,
down 42 percent from the company's plan for about 233 million board
feet and well shy of what the company considered necessary to
remain economic.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Campbell said the federal and state officials had
provided enough flexibility to give the company confidence that it
could produce a minimum of 200 million board feet annually.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will, for instance, allow the company to cut
selected trees in landslide-prone areas.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Department officials, conceding earlier projections of
136 million board feet were inaccurate, calculate the company will
be able to harvest about 177 million board feet annually, David
Hayes, counselor to Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said Tuesday.
And he contended that the agreement is no different from the
agreement that state and federal regulators had proposed last week.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who had called Maxxam Chief Executive Charles
Hurwitz last week in an effort to keep the talks alive, called the
redwoods of the Headwaters ``a natural treasure, as much a part of
our legacy as the world's great libraries and cathedrals.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt argues the real significance of the deal is the habitat
conservation plan drawn up as part of the agreement, which he
contends will be a guide for many future logging plans.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, who have battled Hurwitz for years in an
effort to ensure the redwoods of the Headwaters were not cut down
to make lumber for hot tubs, fence posts and leisure decks, reacted
cautiously to the agreement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Ratner, president of the Oakland, Calif.-based Rose
Foundation, said it was too early to tell if the agreement would
truly protect the environment. ``It certainly is a good deal for
the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the agreement will really end the battle that has raged
in Northern California between the environmental community and
Maxxam for more than a decade remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Earth First, a more radical environmental group, held a
demonstration in Northern California Tuesday to protest the
Headwaters deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people know how much land is being saved in the
Headwaters agreement,'' said Earth First activist Darryl Cherney.
``What they don't realize is how much land is being destroyed. It's
a license to kill endangered species.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia ``Butterfly'' Hill has spent nearly 15 months perched in
one of Pacific Lumber's old-growth redwood trees. She has no plans
to climb down from the tree she calls Luna.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement ... is based on the premise that a bare minimum
needs to be protected for endangered species recovery, and from the
beginning it has failed to require what is biologically necessary
to accomplish even that,'' Hill said in a prepared statement issued
by her Luna Media Services.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
