<HEADER>
A5241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-INDEPENDENCE-DA     03-02 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-INDEPENDENCE-DAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas Independence Day celebrated Austin-style
 &HT;    By Chuck Lindell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Brian McGill was standing under the Capitol dome
amid the costumes and pomp of Texas Independence Day when a certain
governor locked eyes and crooked a finger in his direction.
</P>
<P>
   Thus summoned, McGill brought forward his son Garrett, a
21-month-old who became the envy of many a Republican leader _
eyeball to eyeball with Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The governor smiled, the child stared. The governor talked, the
child stared. The governor produced his palm, the child slapped.
</P>
<P>
   A ``high five'' with a probable presidential candidate on the
day Texas declared independence from Mexico 163 years before?
That'll give Brian and Kelly McGill a little family history to pass
along once Garrett grows older.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we live in the Austin area, we're going to make
this (celebration) our Texas tradition,'' Brian McGill said, still
smiling moments later. ``I'm a native Texan and proud of my
state.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day for women in bonnets and men wearing string ties. A
drum and fife corps played ``The Yellow Rose of Texas,'' and
couples two-stepped under the dome.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, hundreds of people chewed and talked beneath large red
and white tents, free servings of barbecue slopping over the sides
of their paper plates.
</P>
<P>
   Kay McAnnally, 2, and her nanny, Ailana Larson of Austin, picked
at their food and waived small Texas flags. It being near Kay's nap
time, Larson had to carry almost all of the conversation. Mostly,
she said, Tuesday's events will make a wonderful lesson in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good thing to teach our heritage,'' Larson
said. ``We went to the Alamo a couple of weeks ago, so we're just
getting a big run of Texas history here.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos, who acted as emcee during the
Capitol celebration, promised even larger festivities in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to celebrate this like it ought to be celebrated.
Next year, it's going to be five times bigger. We'll probably have
to hold it outside,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go around all over the world and brag about being Texas.
But if you ask people, I'd say about three-quarters don't even know
when Texas Independence Day is,'' said Barrientos, D-Austin. ``It's
part of our culture. It's part of our history.''
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Texas, a celebration of a different sort
began several hours later, one that glorified the quiet heroes who
valued intellectual activity, books and music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone who came then was rough and ready, loud and
brash,'' said Tom Hatfield, dean of continuing and extended
education.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from the Alamo Diary, an account of the Alamo battle
attributed to a Mexican officer, UT Center for American History
director Don Carleton held the audience of 300 spellbound.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Jose Enrique de la Pen(tilde)a describes a battle of
unimaginable horror, where Mexican soldiers ``climbed over the
bleeding bodies of comrades,'' Carleton read. After the Mexican
army breached the walls, several defenders refused to hide,
including William Barrett Travis, the Alamo commander.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a few steps and stopped, turning his proud face toward
us to discharge his shots. He fought like a true soldier,''
Carleton read. ``Finally, he died, but he died after having traded
his life very dearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Liz Carpenter, author and speechwriter for former President
Lyndon Johnson, said the story of the Alamo continues to resonate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson for us today is that rallying cries for great
causes _ for justice, for liberty _ do bring recruits. A handful of
committed people still create legends, in peace as well as war,''
Carpenter said, praising those who fought for civil rights, women's
equality and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we have our own Alamos of ignorance and poverty and
despair,'' she said. ``A few idea-driven people can make a
difference in making a more civilized society.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Lindell writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: clindell(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
