u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-TALLAS-BOS     03-02 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-TALLAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALLAS SECURE IN BACKUP ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rob Tallas didn't wear the usual number for a goalie in
his first training camp with the Bruins, back in September 1994. He
was given No. 80 when he tried to make the team as a free agent out
of Seattle of the Western Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Tallas, now the backup to Bruins starter Byron Dafoe, has that
jersey framed in his bedroom so he can stare at it whenever he
wishes. It's a reminder of where he has been in his struggle to
beat out other goalies, some of them draft choices, in a bid to
make the big club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reminder of what it took to get here and the dues I had
to pay,'' said Tallas, who has a 2.68 goals-against average and
89.9 save percentage in 14 appearances this season. ``Sometimes you
take it for granted when you get caught up in the middle of the
season. It's nice to look at it. It's something I take a lot of
pride in.
</P>
<P>
   Tallas has other sweaters from his rookie year, but none is
framed. ``I knew (No. 80) was a keeper,'' he said. ``You look at it
as a challenge, an obstacle as a walk-on, and you stay here five
years later and you're part of a strong organization. The jersey is
a large part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The jersey didn't even have Tallas's name on it at first. While
everyone else had their names sewn on, Tallas's name was in velcro
when he played in an exhibition against the Philadelphia Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never looked at it as anything negative,'' Tallas said. ``I
was so excited to be here and be around the guys and just to be
playing. That's what my focus was. Now that I look back on it, it
was such an uphill battle for me and I made it. It's a story some
guys respect and they look at it as a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas, who has a 6-5-2 record, always has done well in training
camp. ``I spend a lot of my time during the summers getting ready
for camp, always making sure that I'm in shape, spending a lot of
time focusing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The story of how the Bruins discovered him is not your
run-of-the-mill tale. The team spotted him while he was playing for
Seattle at Kamloops, British Columbia, in a game broadcast on The
Sports Network. Tallas shined, winning, 3-1, and ending Kamloops's
31-game home winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a neat way for me to get here,'' Tallas said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Jim Carey has moved from the Bruins' Providence AHL
affiliate to the St. Louis Blues, Tallas said he feels relief, even
though the move eventually could mean Tallas will be exposed in the
expansion draft. Carey, the former Vezina Trophy winner, made more
than $2 million per season, and could have taken Tallas's spot with
the big club this season. For a while, at least, Tallas can sleep
soundly again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if management realized the pressures that were on
me,'' said Tallas. ``Every day in practice I had to work hard.
That's a lot of pressure. With Byron playing so well and me and him
getting along so well, it's always in the back of your mind that
(Carey) could be called up. There are guys down there who always
want your job. We have to realize that. It pushes us to work hard.
I thought about it a lot. It's a relief to see him go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 2201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
