<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5250 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-TEX     03-02 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH INCHES A LITTLE BIT CLOSER TO PRESIDENTIAL RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Saying he has a ``compelling reason to consider
running for president,'' Gov. George W. Bush announced on Tuesday
that he is taking the first formal step toward launching a bid for
the White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will file papers next week creating an exploratory
committee which will allow him to raise and spend money exploring a
national campaign before making a final decision this summer.
</P>
<P>
   At a packed news conference in Austin, the eldest son of former
President George Bush declined to lay out in detail his vision for
America, but he did indicate he has one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the 21st century to be prosperous,'' Bush said. ``I
want prosperity to spread its wings across America. I don't want
anybody left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's announcement came on the same day that Pat Buchanan, the
arch-conservative television commentator, vowed a fiery race for
the GOP nomination at an appearance in New Hampshire, where he
embarrassed President Bush in 1992 by finishing a close second
behind the incumbent president.
</P>
<P>
   The governor passed up a chance to comment directly on
Buchanan's announcement, but vowed a positive campaign that will
take him around the nation this summer as he explores a candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush laid to rest any notion that putting his wife and twin
teenage daughters through the ``meat grinder'' of presidential
politics _ a worry he has voiced again and again _ would keep him
out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Seated before some 30 television cameras and dozens of
journalists in the back yard of the Governor's Mansion, Bush and
his wife Laura both said they no longer fear the well-known
disruptions of a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our love for each other is strong enough to take whatever life
brings,'' Bush said. ``We've discussed some ways to try to keep a
normal family life. I'm committed to making sure I spend quality
time with Laura and the girls.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor was visibly moved when his wife responded to the
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dread criticism of my husband. On the other hand, I love
George, and I am very proud of him,'' she said, turning toward the
governor. ``And I know he would make a great president.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush added that she was ``looking forward,'' to a
campaign. Bush said the two will travel together when he embarks on
a national tour.
</P>
<P>
   With the family concerns put to rest, Bush, who is deemed an
early favorite for the Republican nomination, was asked what could
keep him from turning his ``exploratory'' effort into a full-blown
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``A giant thud,'' Bush answered, provoking howls of laughter
from the assortment of journalists, aides and supporters. ``A huge
yawn. That it turned out it was my mother (former First Lady
Barbara Bush) that they were interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   As for timing, Bush said he would stay at home to fight for his
agenda during the legislative session, which ends May 31. After
that, he'll hit the campaign trail, visiting, for example, the
traditional first caucus and primary states of Iowa and New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to raise money without leaving (Austin),''
Bush said. ``I need to be here now. Now one of these days I'm going
to be in Des Moines and around ... I hope the people of Iowa and
New Hampshire and America understand I was elected to do a job.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with Bush's promise to tell Texas about his plans
first, Tuesday's media briefing was for Texas reporters only. A
representative of Time magazine and CNN's Charles Zewe, for
example, were turned away at the gate by Bush aides.
</P>
<P>
   But it only took a few minutes for a crew aboard a CNN satellite
truck from Dallas to copy a local affiliate's videotape of the
event and shoot it up on a satellite in time for ``Inside
Politics.'' Broadcast network affiliates did the same routine.
</P>
<P>
   The approach allows Bush to get a ``two-fer'' out of the
announcement of the exploratory committee, said University of
Virginia political scientist Larry Sabato _ one now and one Sunday
when Bush briefs national reporters. Aides already have requests
from 50 journalists for that session.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that Bush would run for president has been raging
for months, though nothing formal had been announced until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Bush has been carefully assembling a team of
advisers and heavyweight fundraisers, the latter expected to start
collecting contributions this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Though his advisers have been helping him study up on national
issues, Bush stuck mostly to broad themes on Tuesday, applying much
of what he said on the campaign trail in Texas to a larger,
national audience.
</P>
<P>
   He did add a populist note to his long-standing call for a new
``responsibility era,'' saying he envisions a world in which
``corporate America understands that they're responsible for their
employees, and responsible for the clean water and clean air of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   As for possible rivals, the only candidate Bush specifically
talked about was Elizabeth Dole, the former head of the American
Red Cross and wife of former presidential candidate Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he found it ``instructive to America'' that the first
viable woman presidential candidate is from his own Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Buchanan, Bush said he looks forward to seeing ``all
these people should I decide to run.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have a few differences here and there,'' added Bush,
who nevertheless vowed his campaign would be ``above board,
positive, energetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush even declined to draw contrasts between his possible
administration and the one that replaced his father's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let the historians judge President Clinton,'' Bush said,
adding that he would talk about his possible agenda for Washington
at the ``appropriate time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, who sprinkled Spanish into his answers for the benefit
of some Spanish language media outlets, said he believes a
presidential administration could ``change the tone of America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a huge responsibility, and I'm awed by the
thought and humbled by the opportunity should I decide to go
forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
