<SLUG> BC-MA-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COMPROMISE, SILBER WOULD QUIT EDUCATION BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH AND FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John R. Silber offered to resign as chairman of the
state's board of education Tuesday, an act of political
self-sacrifice designed to break an impasse over the selection of a
new education commissioner. The showdown has proven a major
embarrassment for Silber's boss, Governor Paul Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   Silber called on Cellucci to replace him as chairman with James
Peyser, whom the governor initially wanted as the next education
commissioner but who had failed to win enough support from the rest
of the administration-appointed board.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation would also clear the way for the board to
appoint David Driscoll, Peyser's rival, as commissioner on a
permanent basis. In an initial vote last week, Driscoll, the
interim commissioner, received five of the necesssary six votes for
the job, while Peyser received four.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman oversees the board's work, which involves setting
statewide education policy and regulations. The commissioner
implements them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although this will not give the Department of Education
leadership by the best qualified candidate, this solution is better
than the alternative of impasse,'' Silber said in a letter
delivered to Cellucci late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of education reform is far more important than my
continuance on the board or the continuance of any other of its
members,'' said Silber. He was appointed to the post in early 1996
by Governor William F. Weld in a move calculated to shake up the
education establishment and challenge the politically powerful
teacher unions. Silber has not been paid for his work as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday night, Cellucci said he would consult
with the rest of the board over the surprise development. But
administration sources said the governor would eagerly accept
Silber's resignation because it would resolve a standoff that has
become a major political gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like this compromise is going to fly,'' said one top
Cellucci adviser, who described the deal as a ``win-win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We get Peyser, who will take the lead on setting education
reform policy. Driscoll will do the day-to-day management. And
Silber gets to hand off the baton to someone he has confidence
in,'' the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the compromise would represent an about-face for
Cellucci, who along with Silber has privately argued that Driscoll
is too tied into the education establishment to carry out needed
overhauls.
</P>
<P>
   Peyser, executive director of the Pioneer Institute, a
conservative think tank, is viewed as much more committed to
sweeping changes to the system. However, his advocacy of vouchers
and charter schools has alienated teachers' unions and other
educators.
</P>
<P>
   Administration sources said Driscoll was told by a top Cellucci
aide late Tuesday that the job was virtually his. And Peyser said
of the chairman's job, ``If it were offered, I would take it.''
Peyser recently resigned his position on the board to be considered
for the commissioner's job.
</P>
<P>
   Silber's made his announcement at a news conference after he and
two other board members met with Driscoll in a session said to ease
their concerns about having the career educator as commissioner.
Cellucci learned of Silber's decision early Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Although the possibility of Silber's resignation had been
floated by the administration, until midday Tuesday Cellucci had
held out hope he could resolve the standoff in a way that kept the
Boston University chancellor at the helm of the education board.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cellucci unsuccessfully pressed Roberta Schaefer and
Abigail Thernstrom _ two board members he and Weld had appointed _
to switch their support from Driscoll to Peyser. Tuesday morning,
according to several sources, Cellucci made another appeal to
Thernstrom, only to be rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Silber's resignation would remove a hard-edged personality who,
for all his educational expertise, had polarized the board and
alienated several key board members who otherwise share the
governor's philosophy on education. Several of those members have
refused to back Peyser.
</P>
<P>
   While saying his departure from the board may be necessary for
education reform to advance, Silber Tuesday continued his attack on
those members _ particularly Thernstrom and Schaefer _ saying they
should bow to the governor's wishes and back Peyser for the
commissioner's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have already said that I thought those who couldn't support
the governor who appointed them to the position should resign,''
Silber said.
</P>
<P>
   Silber's relationship with Thernstrom and Schaefer had
deteriorated in recent months, to the point where they were arguing
over seating arrangements at board meetings. Thernstrom hailed the
proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Driscoll is made commissioner and Peyser is made chairman
of the board, this is the best of all possible worlds for Governor
Cellucci,'' she said. ``He has got his man in the top policy
position . . . and we have got a wonderful man to carry out that
policy, who has tremendous credibility in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   But she defended her stand against Peyser as commissioner. ``I
am not on the governor's staff,'' she said. ``I am a member of an
independent board, and voted the way I have thought long and hard
about during the search.''
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer hailed the compromise as an ``excellent combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was so positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was totally unfair to the board members that differ
with (Silber) and unclear how this offer will really resolve the
impasse,'' said Paul Reville, a professor of education at Harvard
University and chairman of the Massachusetts Education Reform
Review Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting that paved the way for Silber's gambit, sources
say, Silber; Edwin Delattre, a board member and Silber supporter;
and Charles Baker, recently appointed by Cellucci to the board,
talked with Driscoll in Silber's Boston University office on Bay
State Road for several hours Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   One person familiar with the conversation described it as
productive, saying that Driscoll made progress in allaying concerns
Baker and Delattre _ who had backed Peyser for the commissioner's
post _ had about him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tina Cassidy of the Globe staff contributed to this report. Wire
service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
