<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR AUTOMAKERS REPORT RECORD SALES FOR FEBRUARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., N.Y.)   (jw)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ March blew in like a lion for the auto industry as
major automakers, including Ford Motor Co., DaimlerChrysler AG and
American Honda, reported record sales for the previous month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the end of the General Motors strike in August, the
industry has had an incredible run of monthly records,'' David
Healy, an auto analyst for Burnham Securities in New York, said.
``The reasons are the usual suspects. Car prices are reasonable, if
not declining. Employment levels and consumer confidence are very
high. Used-car prices are strong, making trade-ins worth more and
causing people to buy new cars instead of used ones.''
</P>
<P>
   At Ford, sales of Ford, Mercury, Lincoln and Jaguar cars and
trucks rose 8 percent to 319,340 vehicles from the preceding
February, surpassing the previous February sales record set in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler reported sales of Dodge, Jeep, Chrysler and
Plymouth cars and trucks totaled 215,450 units, also up 8 percent
over a year ago and beating the previous record set 1996.
Mercedes-Benz posted slightly lower sales from a year ago. Several
other companies, including General Motors Corp., have not yet
reported sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's sales rose on the strength of trucks, most notably the
full-size Ford F-Series and compact Ranger pickup trucks as well as
sport-utility vehicles like the Ford Explorer and Expedition.
Ford's total truck sales climbed 20 percent to 193,779 vehicles.
F-Series sales rose 27 percent, breaking the previous monthly sales
record set in 1978; Ranger sales rose 46 percent for the best
February since 1978. Combined sales of the Explorer and Expedition
set new records, and the redesigned Ford Windstar and Mercury
Villager minivans also posted increases.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's car sales, however, dropped to 125,561 vehicles, down 6
percent from a year ago, because of lower sales to daily rental
fleets, Ford said. Excluding fleet sales, retail car sales rose 12
percent, the company said. Sales of the redesigned Ford Mustang and
Mercury Cougar were higher, but sales of Ford's high-volume Taurus
fell. A redesigned Taurus will be unveiled at the New York auto
show in April and put on the market in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   At DaimlerChrysler, truck sales rose 7 percent to 145,436
vehicles, setting a new record for the sixth month in a row. Sales
of sport utilities led by the Jeep Grand Cherokee and Dodge Durango
and minivans, especially the Dodge Caravan, contributed to the
increase. The automaker's car sales rose 9 percent to 70,014
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Honda also reported record February sales for its Honda and
Acura brands. Its car and truck sales totaled 81,910 units, up 14
percent from a year ago. Honda's new Odyssey minivan and redesigned
Acura TL entry-level luxury car had triple-digit gains.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen reported its best February in 18 years; Audi had the
best February since 1986. Volvo, Subaru and Kia also reported
higher sales.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers said the continued upswing likely would carry through
to spring, typically the strongest season of the year, with March
sales already coming in strong.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``There is very little doubt that March sales will be higher
than a year ago,'' said Robert Rewey, Ford's group vice president
for marketing, sales and service, in a statement. ``After that, the
mountain is going to get a little steeper because the sales rate in
the second quarter of 1998 was very fast. Still, momentum is on the
side of a strong U.S. economy and confident U.S. consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Healy of Burnham Securities said he was uneasy with the
industry selling significantly above recent levels. When the rest
of the auto companies, including General Motors, report sales
Wednesday, Healy said he expected the seasonally adjusted rate
would be at a lofty 16.7 million for cars and light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems too good to last, but I don't see anything to spoil
it,'' he said. ``Every month I raise my forecast, and I suppose
I'll keep raising it.''
</P>
<P>
   Automakers are also increasing their forecasts for this year's
vehicle sales. DaimlerChrysler's early February forecast put car
and total truck sales for 1999 at 15.6 million vehicles. ``We've
increased the forecast every month for the last three months, and I
wouldn't be surprised if March gets off on a good foot and the
forecast ticks up a little more,'' said Jamie Jameson, vice
president for sales and marketing operations at DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
</TEXT>
