<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: FLIGHTS OF FANCY; HOTEL SANS CASINO; PASSENGERS
BEWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Japan, Great Britain)  (Also moved in ``t'' category.) 
(mk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a bird. It's a plane. It's ... Strauss? Pokemon cartoon
characters? The Union Jack? Actually, it is all three _ or soon
will be at airports around the world, as more and more airlines
discover that a picture can indeed be worth a thousand words.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an Austrian Airlines Airbus 321 not only now
emblazons the name ``Johann Strauss'' in large letters across its
fuselage, but a 40-foot image of the legendary waltz king playing
his violin runs from fuselage to tail. In addition, Strauss is
depicted surrounded by treble and bass clefs, and animated quarter
notes and eighth notes in a waltz rhythm. Altogether, it required
180 man-hours to glue the decoration to the newly painted aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Characters from Pokemon, a popular game and television cartoon
series, now decorate four All Nippon Airways jets, including a
747-400 that flew from Tokyo to New York last Friday and is now
being used on the Japanese carrier's routes to North America.
</P>
<P>
   And Virgin Group's Virgin Atlantic, whose maverick founder,
Richard Branson, delights in tweaking his bigger rival, British
Airways, announced two days ago that Virgin would soon change its
corporate logo but would continue to use the Union Jack on the
fuselage of its planes _ in part a jab at British Airways for
replacing its abstract design of the British flag two years ago
with multicultural images.
</P>
<P>
   In all three cases, the immediate reason for the colorful
designs is to call attention to the airlines that own the planes,
but the longer-range reason is strictly business. Virgin Atlantic,
for example, coupled its announcement of the new corporate look
with the promise of new routes and more frequent flights _ aimed at
winning more corporate accounts.
</P>
<P>
   All Nippon Airways already flies 49 flights a week between Japan
and New York, Los Angeles, San Francisco, Washington and Honolulu,
and has applied to the Japanese government to begin daily service
April 13 between Tokyo and Chicago. More than 250 Japanese
companies have offices in Chicago, the airline said, and the city
is one of the most popular destinations for Japanese visitors. If
and when it begins flying to Chicago, the airline's code-share
flights to other American cities will increase by five, including
Cincinnati and Miami, for a total of 12.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian Airlines, having named its colorful airplane in
commemoration of Strauss, who died 100 years ago, plans to fly it
only to Paris; London; Berlin; St. Petersburg, Russia, and other
European destinations this year. It is the same plane that from
1996 through 1998 carried portraits of 24 prominent Austrians,
including Strauss, Mozart, Beethoven, Freud and Schubert.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has daily nonstop flights between Vienna, Austria,
and New York, and Vienna and Atlanta. It also has daily flights
between Vienna and Washington via Zurich, Switzerland. The Austrian
carrier serves 26 American cities through its code-share with Delta
Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Update
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons hotel opened in Las Vegas on Tuesday, the only
luxury hotel on that city's strip that does not have a gambling
casino. But there is a casino in the 43-story tower that the Four
Season shares with the Mandalay Bay Resort and Casino. Amenities
include private bars in each room, 24-hour concierge and room
service, twice-daily housekeeping service and free overnight
shoeshines.
</P>
<P>
   Add the Omni Ambassador East in Chicago to the growing list of
hotels that want to rent out for New Year's Eve 1999. The 275-room
hotel, the home of the well-known Pump Room restaurant, is asking
$450,000 for rooms, food and beverages for two days and two nights
_ Dec. 31, 1999, and Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Not Yet Spring
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks from spring, many fliers might naturally assume the
worst of winter travel is behind them. But there is still plenty of
time for ice and snow to disrupt even the best-laid travel plans,
and if winter storms result in canceled flights, passengers should
be aware that they are not entitled to compensation from the
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the carriers have written right into their tickets that
they are not responsible for weather-caused delays,'' said Robert
Jarvis, professor of law at Nova Southeastern University in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla. ``If the airline cancels the flight, it has to
give you your money back or put you on the next available flight if
you still want to go. But passengers are responsible for hotel
costs, missed opportunities or ruined vacations.''
</P>
<P>
   That is all the more reason, said Jarvis, one of the authors of
``Travel Law'' (Carolina Academic Press, 1998), for travelers
booked on tours, cruises or other expensive trips to guard against
such contingencies by buying trip insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
