<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VP WEST BACK AFTER SHORT BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A coach was fired and a controversial power
forward arrived, but Jerry West didn't stick around the Forum to
watch the results of those moves.
</P>
<P>
   West, last seen in public last Wednesday when the Los Angeles
Lakers fired Del Harris, took the next several days off to recover
from the mental stress, even skipping the press conference to
announce Kurt Rambis' appointment as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just getting away from the craziness of this business . . .
trying to get away from you people,'' the club vice president told
a small group of reporters Tuesday. Trade rumors involving Eddie
Jones, the acquisition of Dennis Rodman, which West adamantly
opposed, and the decision to dismiss Harris, a friend, made for a
difficult week. ``It hasn't been a very pleasant time for me
personally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he dropped out of sight. ``It kind of helps to step back and
look at things from a different perspective,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   West watched the Lakers' four-game winning streak on television,
and while he's just as pleased as anyone, he stopped far short of
declaring the team's troubles over. He praised the work of Rambis
and called Rodman ``a genius'' but said the Lakers are far from
championship contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a honeymoon now, guys,'' West said. ``We've won four
straight games and I know someone is gonna be happy because we've
won four straight games. . . . We SHOULD be a good team. Are we
striving for something that we're not capable of at this point in
time? I don't think anyone knows that. We need to see improvement
in a lot of areas, and I think we will see improvement, I really
do.''
</P>
<P>
   How much better are the Lakers than the team that lost to Denver
and Vancouver a week ago? Hard to say. Two wins over the Clippers
don't mean much, but the wins against the Rockets and Suns did. Now
the Suns come to town for a rematch, and Seattle and Utah are up
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think by the end of this week we'll have a little bit better
idea how we shape up and are we making some improvements,'' West
said.
</P>
<P>
   __ West on the Worm: Privately, West fumed over the addition of
Rodman, and privately, he probably still is. But publicly, he
sounds like his biggest fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geniuses come in all different shapes. And as a basketball
player he has a genius to rebound, but he also has a genius to know
how to play the game. And that's a pretty good combination,'' West
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch him play, he's exactly what (was expected) _ an
infusion of energy, incredible basketball intelligence. Those are
the things this team probably needs, more people that can do the
things he has. . . . My goodness, you wish everyone had the same
effort he has when he's on the basketball court.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Taking it easy: Rambis held an optional practice Tuesday, and
11 of 15 players showed for light workouts. Only Rodman, Shaquille
O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Eddie Jones took the day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys haven't had a true day off in a long time,'' Rambis
said. ``We've got some tough stuff coming up. We dragged a little
bit in the game (Monday). I just thought it was time for a break.''
</P>
<P>
   Elden Campbell, out two games with the flu, practiced for about
45 minutes and should be available tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
