<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-LANGUAGE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LANGUAGE SUNG BEST BY ITS OWN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It should be no surprise that Americans heavily populate foreign
opera companies. The soprano from Indiana University is usually
better educated than a lot of her counterparts elsewhere. Her voice
is healthy by virtue of what is coming to be known in the world as
the American technique of singing.
</P>
<P>
   She can negotiate three or four languages. Most likely, she has
played the piano since prepubescence. Italy, as a voice teacher
from Lucca once told me, has relatively few pianos, much less
people who learn music from playing them.
</P>
<P>
   Then why is it that Americans (with splendid exceptions) are
valued internationally more for their usefulness and versatility
than for intimate personal contact with Verdi or Puccini? And why
do Italians, often with sketchy musical backgrounds and faulty
technique, sometimes penetrate their roles more convincingly. As
Rodolfo, Richard Leech makes a beautiful sound; Luciano Pavarotti
in his best years inhabited the part.
</P>
<P>
   The question is easy to answer. Italian is the Italian's
language, and Puccini begins with words. Melody, harmony and rhythm
are his way of getting words off the printed page and into our
ears. Italian singers don't imitate their language's distinctive
vowels and consonants; the right sound is a birthright. And when a
word in a libretto bears specific emotional baggage, the Italian
shapes it without thinking.
</P>
<P>
   This all came up as I listened to Dawn Upshaw sing songs by
Vernon Duke on a Nonesuch CD and, not long after, heard songs in
English from the American years of Kurt Weill in Weill Recital
Hall. I'm not sure that Ms. Upshaw's operatic fastidiousness,
bordering on fussiness, or her operatic vibrato is right for Duke's
music, but I knew even before the piano introductions to ``April in
Paris'' or ``Autumn in New York'' had started that I would
understand the words. That is again no mystery: English is Ms.
Upshaw's language and mine.
</P>
<P>
   So never think that our hypothetical Italian is more musical or
has a bigger heart than our hypothetical American. The Italian is
at home in Puccini, and the American is just visiting. It works
both ways. Anyone who has listened to Enrico Caruso, Renata Tebaldi
or even such an eminent musical intelligence as Placido Domingo
struggle with English texts knows how close to ridiculous they can
sometimes sound. It's not their language. It's ours.
</P>
<P>
   Language and music are indistinguishable in other ways. The
flatness of American vowels not only captures a Cole Porter song;
the Cole Porter song may not have been imaginable without them. The
soft and recessed consonants of German must have something to do
with similar qualities in German-trained voices. And when the
French sing off key, it is not flat, as so often with the rest of
us, but sharp: above the pitch. Listen to the rising cadences of
French speech and its occupation of the nasal passages, and that is
also not hard to understand.
</P>
<P>
   When language fails music, singing as a dramatic language fails
as well. Hence the repertory of arm-waving, staggering and
head-holding that passes for theater in the opera house. These
exercises scarcely work as drama. They are more like a capitulation
_ a throwing-up of hands _ to the impossibility that music and
language will operate equally in the modern theater.
</P>
<P>
   With the rise of big opera houses and the big, engulfing
technique needed for singers to be heard in them, even the
pleasures of Italian sung by Italians stand little chance. The
listener has two alternatives: first, to accept opera as an excuse
to hear beautiful singing, or second, to use the intermediaries of
titles to get at what is going on.
</P>
<P>
   The second gives you drama in the form of hearsay; it distracts
as much as it informs. The first gives you no drama at all. Anyone
who questions the death of words in the opera house need only note
the use of English titles for English-language librettos.
</P>
<P>
   For Monteverdi, Purcell and other operatic pioneers of the 17th
century, music was a conveyance for poetry aimed at small groups of
people. I don't think anyone will be purveying poems in the
Metropolitan Opera House (3,900 seats). Spaces like it, and even
those a lot smaller, dictate that opera will be a magnificent
musical and visual art. Similarly, vocal concerts with full
orchestra will be about sound, not texts.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Weill songs, in a hall holding only a few hundred,
``September Song'' and ``Speak Low'' spoke as well as sang. Weill's
music without the words of Maxwell Anderson or Ogden Nash was
unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe opera as true theater has the best chance of reviving
itself in places like this, or in the living room, through
television and the record player. Ms. Upshaw makes contact one on
one by way of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Operas like Berg's ``Wozzeck'' manage to be text-driven, but
there are few like it. Still, we can all dream about a
studio-produced ``Boheme'' for television, a production shrunk to
conversational dimensions and as detailed in execution as an
episode of ``N.Y.P.D. Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Puccini's best opera is at heart chamber music, filled
with intricate ensembles and subtle exchanges. It is the thin
person trapped within the enormous fat of Franco Zeffirelli's Act
II at the Met.
</P>
<P>
   Big and spectacular opera has simply evolved, and it provides
great joys. But maybe there is room in small spaces for another
kind of opera, actually an old kind of opera that technology and a
little modesty might help us regain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
