<SLUG> BC-KIASMA-ARCH-ANTIQUES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MUSEUM FITTED OUT WITH FINNISH FLAIR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland _ Throughout the galleries at Kiasma, the new
Museum of Contemporary Art here, a ubiquitous black chair stands
like a silent fixture that could even be mistaken for sculpture. In
the cafe just off the street is another chair, one of translucent
green fiberglass that appears to float above the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The two types of chairs illustrate how the museum's designer,
the New York architect Steven Holl, incorporated Finnish design
into his plans for the new building and its furnishings. At a time
when much new architecture is almost interchangeable from country
to country, Kiasma is distinctive for the way it expresses the
national character of Finland and its landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The name itself describes an intertwining of genetic material,
but here it takes on a more metaphoric meaning, evoking the
confluence of the urban streets that surround the museum.
</P>
<P>
   On a dark wintry afternoon, the spectacle of the building's
curved, translucent glass wall, glowing from within like an
illuminated sheet of ice, has become a welcome lantern to people as
they wend their way home between snow drifts. The look is akin to
Finnish glass designs like Tapio Wirkkala's famous 1960 block of
cast glass called ``Paadar's Ice.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for Holl, in the country that produced Alvar Aalto
and Eliel Saarinen, was how to design and furnish a museum that
lived up to their standards. One day, standing atop Aalto's
Finlandia Hall near the site of the new museum, Holl is reported to
have looked across the road at Saarinen's National Museum and said,
``Aalto did not borrow any details or furniture from Saarinen, and
out of respect we will avoid using any of Aalto's.''
</P>
<P>
   To discover the essence of Finnish design, Holl traveled to the
countryside to visit a craft village called Fiskars. Situated
between Helsinki and Turco, it is a collection of 19th-century
industrial buildings and workers' housing once occupied by the
Fiskars metalworks company, manufacturers of the popular
orange-handled scissors.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, artists, designers and artisans have
moved into the vacant buildings, and the village, along with its
cooperative exhibition gallery, has become an important showcase of
Finnish design.
</P>
<P>
   The village is especially picturesque blanketed in snow on a
bright sunny day with mists rising from the river that winds
through the town. The gallery Holl visited was just above the
rapids in an old copper smith's workshop.
</P>
<P>
   Among the furniture exhibits was a simple chair designed by Kari
Virtanen, regarded as one of the best cabinetmakers in Finland. He
recalled Holl having said during his visit, ``This is a good chair
because it is a silent chair and not overdesigned.''
</P>
<P>
   Holl saw the chair as a perfect fit for Kiasma's spacious
galleries, which he views as empty barnlike spaces for the display
of art.
</P>
<P>
   Fabricating the chair then became a local industry.
Square-looking with square legs and a slightly tilted back rest
that fits the small of the back, the chair was fashioned of birch
and painted dull black to blend with the black-dyed concrete floors
of the galleries. (The original design was altered slightly so that
the chairs could be stacked when not in use.)
</P>
<P>
   Virtanen and his crew made 174 such chairs, 60 for children and
various tables, including the director's desk.
</P>
<P>
   The cafe chair drew on another traditional Finnish design
industry: shipbuilding. Since the cafe was to be a lively public
space, it required a different sort of chair. Holl, who is also
well known for his watercolors, did a sketch of a chair in green
with a tongue-shaped seat. Vesa Honkonen, the project architect for
Kiasma, recalled that the sketch reflected Holl's fascination with
Andy Warhol's trademark green sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   When the cost of manufacturing the chairs in plastic became
prohibitive, the designers resorted to fiberglass and the
experience of Finnish shipbuilders to achieve a high-quality
translucency and the right shade of green. To make the chair appear
lightweight, the sand-cast aluminum legs had to be fabricated as
separate parts.
</P>
<P>
   A Finnish sculptor, Ilona Rista, fashioned the legs in wood as a
model for the mold. The cafe tables with aluminum pedestals are
topped by reddened brass like that on the facade above the entrance
to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the blown glass lights in the cafe that sparkle like
ice cubes, these chairs are another example of Holl's ideas about
natural light and translucency that make the museum a luminous
presence in the urban landscape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
