</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-THEFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT SAYS TREASURY FUNDS RETURNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN AND LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The defense strategy emerging for the businessman
charged in the alleged theft of $6.5 million from the state's
Unpaid Check Fund will be that he attempted to give the money back
to the state, according to Robbins' lawyer and others.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Albert F. Cullen Jr. said in an interview Tuesday that
Martin Robbins sent a check for $6.5 million, plus interest,
written on his account at BankBoston to the state treasurer's
office on Feb. 11. Delivered by a courier service, the check was
made out a day after Robbins was rebuffed in his effort to withdraw
the money in cash.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter that accompanied the check, Robbins wrote that he
was returning the money on the advice of his attorney and
accountant because he had learned that the Cambridge Economic
Development Corporation, which had been given the money three
months before, was ``not in existence.'' Robbins had secured the
money from the Unpaid Check Fund by claiming that he represented
the firm as an ``heir finder,'' those who track down the rightful
owners of uncashed state checks, in return for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   The defense strategy for Robbins recalls that of another
defendant in a celebrated local corruption case: former state
senator Vincent Piro of Somerville. In 1985, Piro was acquitted of
charges that he accepted a $5,000 bribe from a federal undercover
agent after successfully arguing that he had been entrapped into
accepting the money and that he had returned it three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   However, to convince any jury to acquit Robbins, Cullen will
have to confront key discrepancies in Robbins' account of why he
gave back the money, as well as other allegations that point to his
involvement with co-defendant John F. Trischitta in the $6.5
million theft.
</P>
<P>
   They include:
</P>
<P>
   --Robbins paid Trischitta, who headed the fund, a $50,000 bribe
to get him to approve the issuance of the $6.5 million check to
Cambridge Economic Development Corporation, according to the
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   --Robbins' bank account contained another half-million dollars
that investigators believe may have come from other apparently
illegal withdrawals from the Unpaid Check Fund.
</P>
<P>
   --Trischitta cooperated with investigators, at least until the
time of his arrest on Feb. 19, and, according to sources, confirmed
some of their suspicions about his dealings with Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Carol Ann Starkey said at
Trischitta's arraignment that in exchange for ``services and
information,'' Robbins had paid Trischitta the bribe money and
agreed to split a third of all fees he gained as an heir finder.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Starkey, Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly, nor
State Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien made reference to Robbins'
effort to return the money in their Feb. 19 press conference
announcing that Robbins and Trischitta had been charged in the
case. Spokesmen for both Reilly and O'Brien declined to comment
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Following Robbins' arraignment in Boston Municipal Court on Feb.
22, Cullen told reporters that Robbins had returned the money to
the state when he became concerned about the validity of his claim
to it. Robbins called unnamed officials at the Cambridge Economic
Development Corporation, and on learning that the corporation was
not owed any money from the state he returned it, Cullen said.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, dated Feb. 11, to Trischitta, Robbins wrote: ``I
am returning these funds based upon advice received from my
attorney and accountant since the Cambridge Economic Development
Corporation is no longer in existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Cullen confirmed the wording of the letter but declined to
answer other questions about the case against Robbins, of Peabody.
According to sources, the envelope containing the letter and check
was delivered by a messenger from Boston Bicycle Couriers to
Trischitta's office on the 12th floor at 1 Ashburton Place on the
morning of Feb. 12. State Police investigators, having been alerted
to Robbins' attempt to withdraw the money in cash on Feb. 10, were
already in Trischitta's office and took control of the check and
the letter.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston spokesman Bruce Spitzer declined comment, saying:
``We cannot confirm or deny any specific details because of the
ongoing investigation by law enforcement officials.''
</P>
<P>
   But a source said Robbins transferred the money from an escrow
account he had set up under the name of ECDEV _ apparently a
reference to Cambridge Economic Development Corporation _ to one in
the name of his heir-finder firm, Robbins Associates. The source
said he then wrote a Robbins Associates check to the Commonwealth.
There were no BankBoston signatures on the check, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, investigators have seized documents from
Trischitta's office that cast doubt on Robbins' version of events,
sources said. They include the power-of-attorney document that
Robbins submitted under the signature of the former treasurer of
Cambridge Economic Development Corporation stating that Robbins is
authorized to receive the $6.5 million on behalf of the firm.
However, Robert DeGregorio, the former treasurer, has already told
investigators that his signature on the document is a forgery,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, although Robbins contended in his letter that the
Cambridge Economic Development Corporation was defunct, state
records show that an identically named company had been
incorporated six weeks before. The president and treasurer of the
company is listed as Judith Fagin, of New York, whom a former
employee of Robbins' heir-finder business told the Globe had worked
for Robbins last year. Fagin has not returned calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Reilly Tuesday called for an end to the heir-finder
industry in Massachusetts. ``We should end this practice right now
until people have an opportunity to evaluate other alternatives,''
Reilly said. ``It may very well be the state can do this.'' He was
referring to the practice of having state employees work as heir
finders.
</P>
<P>
   Treasurer O'Brien said she wants to have four heir finders on
staff at the Abandoned Property Division, which is where unpaid
checks are moved after being outstanding for 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   Former treasurer Joseph D. Malone had two state heir finders,
both of whom have left. His predecessor, Robert Crane, had eight
in-house heir finders. ``I think there should be a happy medium,''
O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she also wants to cap at 10 percent the fee heir
finders can charge when reuniting owners with their unpaid state
checks. Currently there is no limit on what heir finders can charge
individuals and firms owed money from the state's Unpaid Check
Fund, even though they are restricted to a maximum 10 percent fee
when locating people who are owed assets from the Abandoned
Property Division.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tina Cassidy of the Globe staff contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
