<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA PRESSES ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Without injured center Dan Gadzuric, the Bruins
believe the best way to combat late-season pressure is with
pressure of their own _ a swarming, relentless, full-court press
that created 81 turnovers in three games against Syracuse and the
Washington schools.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike past years, when a shallow bench and fear of fatigue
prevented them from pressing, the Bruins have the manpower to
attack as often as they like. Tactically, it makes sense.
Gadzuric's absence has forced them to mask their weakness (size) by
accentuating their strength (speed).
</P>
<P>
   ``We were building towards wanting to press and we've
accelerated the use of the press because Dan got hurt,'' UCLA coach
Steve Lavin said. ``In past years, we couldn't stay with it for
sustained periods of time. But with the combination of depth and
Dan's absence, we have to extend our defense to create the tempo we
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Three factors have made the press productive:
</P>
<P>
   __ Forward Matt Barnes, with his 6-foot-8 frame and long arms,
is an ideal front man. His size forces opponents to throw bounce
passes and lob passes upcourt, and they're easy to intercept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is no straight-line passes,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Baron Davis thrives as the center fielder. Stationed near
midcourt, Davis' job is to snatch long passes. Usually, he does it
with space to maneuver, accelerating UCLA's conversion from defense
to offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's special back there,'' Lavin said. ``He's like Lester
Hayes or Ronnie Lott. He's good at reading and anticipating. He
reads the eyes of the passers.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Davis' dream was to play safety for Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Bruins have become more efficient. Instead of stealing
the ball directly from an offensive player, they're stealing the
passes, enabling them to pressure without fouling.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the success, the Bruins might not apply constant
pressure this weekend. More likely, they'll use it to increase
tempo at selected moments. It's also an effective means of
preventing Arizona point guard Jason Terry from dictating play.
</P>
<P>
   __ The healing begins: Gadzuric has started a preliminary
rehabilitation program to prevent muscle atrophy and restore range
of motion in his left knee. In about six weeks, when his repaired
meniscus cartilage has healed, he'll begin a more strenuous
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be able to resume normal activity in about three
months and there should be no permanent effects from the injury,''
said Dr. Matthew Shapiro, who performed the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Guard Earl Watson (bruised quadriceps) and
forward JaRon Rush, who was briefly knocked unconscious against
Washington, are expected to play Thursday at Arizona State. Rush
did not practice Tuesday because of the flu. . . . Thursday's game
begins at 5:30 p.m. and will be broadcast on a tape-delayed basis
at 10 p.m. on Fox Sports West 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
