<SLUG> BC-NY-JAIL-BEATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTY TO PAY $500,000 IN BEATING OF RETARDED JAIL INMATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (jw)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One day after a federal jury found a veteran Nassau
County jail guard liable for the brutal beating of a mentally
retarded inmate, Nassau officials abruptly agreed on Tuesday to pay
the former inmate $500,000 to settle his civil rights lawsuit
against the county.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement put an end to a four-day trial that had already
painted a damaging portrait of one man's ordeal at the jail and
would have raised an array of allegations against several other
guards, had it continued. It also ended the possibility of a huge
jury award against the county.
</P>
<P>
   The guard found liable, Salvatore Gemelli, a 15-year veteran,
was dismissed by Sheriff Joseph Jablonsky on Monday, shortly after
a U.S. district court jury ruled that he had violated the civil
rights of Thomas Donovan Jr. by attacking him at the jail in 1993.
The beating left Donovan with broken ribs and spinal fractures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The liability judgment speaks for itself,'' Jablonsky said.
``Obviously, Mr. Gemelli was involved in improper behavior. It is a
black mark against the entire department, starting with me all the
way down.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement concluded the fifth brutality case to be filed by
former jail inmates against Gemelli. Together, those cases have
cost the county $900,000 in jury awards and out-of-court
settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan's father, Thomas Donovan Sr., said he was pleased with
the settlement. ``I am totally satisfied that justice has been
done.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped the case would encourage Nassau County
officials, who have spent years investigating brutality charges
with little results, to change what many critics say is a
systematic pattern of abuse at the jail. ``If my little son, with
his limited IQ, can beat these guys,'' Donovan added, ``then why
can't the DA, with all his resources, beat them?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the jail remains the focus of an investigation by the
U.S. attorney's office into other reports that jail guards have
beaten inmates. That inquiry began after the Jan. 13 death of
Thomas Pizzuto, 38, an inmate whose family says he was beaten by
guards and then left untreated for days.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Barber, the president of the unit of the Civil Service
Employees Union that that represents 1,000 Nassau County
correctional officers, said Gemelli's dismissal was an attempt by
county officials to avoid any blame in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a personal attack on Sal because he's a union
official,'' Barber said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
