<HEADLINE>
DEAL IS REACHED TO TURN 10,000 ACRES OF ANCIENT REDWOODS INTO A
PUBLIC PRESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds.: Subs 8th graf to correct the percentage increase of the
stock to 20 percent, not 24. Adds a new 9th graf saying the renewal
of the deal was NOT because of Monday's stock plunge. Subs 10th
graf to improve wording of second sentence. Subs 11th graf to
correct the various sides' figures on the timber harvest. Subs 12th
graf to change ``spawns'' to ``swims.'' Subs 16th graf to remove
reference to Milken, which is not relevant. Subs 4th graf from end
to say why Sierra Club favors the deal.) (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After years of negotiations that were completed
only two minutes before the deadline of midnight on Monday, federal
and state officials and Pacific Lumber Co. have agreed to a
landmark $480-million deal that will turn the largest privately
owned grove of ancient redwood trees in the world into a public
preserve.
</P>
<P>
   The complex deal, which government officials said was as
significant as turning Yosemite and the Grand Canyon into national
parks, will preserve about 10,000 acres of giant redwoods in
Humboldt County, about 250 miles north of here, including the
majestic Headwaters forest and some smaller groves.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is significant because only 3 percent of the
nation's original redwood trees, some of them 2,000 years old,
remain unlogged, and it marks the biggest government acquisition of
land in California since the creation of Redwood National Park 30
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Diane Feinstein, D-Calif., an architect of the agreement,
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, Gov. Gray Davis, and President
Clinton all called the deal ``historic'' on Tuesday. Clinton said:
``I am truly grateful that we are able to bestow this priceless
gift on generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   But some environmental groups were unhappy with the deal, saying
that it did not do enough to protect endangered species and
expressing deep skepticism about what the government may have
conceded to the lumber company at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, capping one of the longest-running environmental
stories in recent history, was more than 10 years in the making.
The most contentious part of the plan requires Pacific Lumber, the
largest private logger of old-growth redwoods in the country, to
agree to a 50-year Habitat Conservation Plan governing how it logs
its remaining 211,000 acres of timber.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, the boards of Pacific Lumber, based in
Scotia, on the northern California coast, and its Houston-based
parent company, Maxxam Corp., rejected the proposal, contending
that environmental restrictions added to the deal in recent months
would cripple the company and force hundreds of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Maxxam's stock price tumbled on Monday, in the first trading
after it rejected the deal, but it rose more than 20 percent on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   John Campbell, president of Pacific Lumber, said the revival of
the deal had nothing to do with the stock's plunging.
</P>
<P>
   Both government and company officials said that the contract,
which was signed two minutes before the federal government's
$250-million offer for its share of the purchase was scheduled to
expire, was essentially unchanged. What was different, they said,
was the interpretation of how much Pacific Lumber could harvest
under the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The state had projected the company could harvest 136 million to
137 million board feet a year, far below the 210 million board feet
the company said it needed. But federal officials said that the
state figures had been interpreted incorrectly. ``That's a figure
that we can accept,'' he said. The government said the figure was
more like 179 million.
</P>
<P>
   In what sounded like another change in the deal, Campbell added
that Pacific Lumber would be able to cut trees selectively on about
60,000 acres of unstable ground even before watershed analysis is
done that will determine ``no-cut'' buffer zones around streams
where the endangered coho salmon swims. ``They have decided it is
appropriate for us to selectively log while we do the watershed
assessment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tim Ahearn, a spokesman for Babbitt, said no concessions had
been made that would compromise the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Environmental Protection Information Center, a
watchdog that has filed numerous lawsuits against Pacific Lumber,
said that it sounded as though the federal government had given the
company a wink and a nod.
</P>
<P>
   ``You show me how you can come up with 45 million additional
board feet a year without changing a comma, and I'll show you
something fishy going on,'' said Kevin Bundy, a spokesman for the
organization. ``We're going to be looking at this very closely to
see whether the government is willing to sacrifice an endangered
salmon in order to help a company finance its debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Lumber is $865 million in debt. In 1985, Charles
Hurwitz, the president of Maxxam, acquired the then-family-owned
logging company for $900 million in a hostile takeover using junk
bonds. Shortly after Maxxam acquired Pacific Lumber, it tripled its
logging output to finance its purchase. The noticeable increase in
logging set off continuous environmental protests _ including the
largest forest rally in the country in 1996 _ as well as lawsuits
by environmental groups charging the company with violating the
Endangered Species Act and Clean Water Acts.
</P>
<P>
   Under those acts, Pacific Lumber would not be able to log
Headwaters and other ancient redwood groves because of danger to a
number of threatened and endangered species, including the coho
salmon and the marbled murrelet, a seabird that nests on the tops
of old-growth redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   But Hurwitz sued the federal government, arguing that Pacific
Lumber was entitled to compensation for land that the government
was preventing it from using. The lawsuit, called a ``takings''
lawsuit, was expected to be a long and expensive headache for the
government, which decided to deal with Pacific Lumber rather than
engage in a costly and lengthy court fight.
</P>
<P>
   Congress appropriated $250 million for the Headwaters purchase,
and the state of California is to pay $130 million now and $100
million over five years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Sierra Club applauded the deal, saying it was satisfied that
habitats would be protected. But some other environmental groups
said that they remain suspicious about whether the government will
be able to properly monitor whether Pacific Lumber adheres to the
plan. In the last three years, the company has been cited for 128
violations of state forestry rules.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the California Department of Forestry suspended
Pacific Lumber's license to log, citing continual and egregious
violations. The suspension was cited for 180 layoffs out of a labor
force of 1,600 employees. But it did not affect the company's
ability to log because the suspension did not include logging done
by subcontractors for the company.
</P>
<P>
   In Berkeley, Calif., on Tuesday, members of a number of
environmental groups called a news conference to declare they would
continue protests against Pacific Lumber.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who calls herself Julia Butterfly, who has lived in a
tree for more than a year to protest the company's logging
practices, spoke at the conference by cellular phone from her tree.
``We will not rest, we will not give up, we will not go away until
we see the necessary protections for the forest,'' she said, as a
windstorm blew around her.
</P>
</TEXT>
