an assertion by the Clinton administration that the independent
counsel law should be permitted to fade into extinction, using a
hearing into the law's future to pose pointed questions about what
other safeguards exist against unlawful conduct by high-ranking
federal officials. By Frank Bruni. (The story has moved in ``w''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ESPY (Washington) _ Somewhere between bribing a federal
official and bestowing an innocent gift on one lies an illegal
gratuity. Federal law punishes giving a gratuity with two years in
prison, but as a Supreme Court argument demonstrated, it defines
the offense so imprecisely that the search for meaning is almost as
much an exercise in metaphysics as in law. The case before the
court is an outgrowth of an independent counsel's failed
prosecution of Mike Espy, who was acquitted three months ago of
having accepted illegal gifts from companies regulated by his
department. By Linda Greenhouse. (The story has moved in ``w'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY-BOOK (Washington) _ In a book to be published later
this week, Monica Lewinsky is so critical of the independent
counsel Kenneth Starr that several of her friends and associates
say they fear Starr will become angry and try to revoke her
immunity agreement and prosecute her. By Don Van Natta Jr.
(Scheduled to move by 10:45 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.) 980 words.
