<HEADLINE>
MISTRIAL DECLARED IN FRAUD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., N.Y., Calif.)   (jw)  
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After almost two weeks of deliberations, a U.S.
district court jury here said on Tuesday that it could not agree on
whether a Syracuse, N.Y., businessman was guilty of orchestrating
one of the largest financial frauds in American history and a judge
declared a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   The jury did find the businessman, Patrick Bennett, guilty of
seven counts of perjury and obstruction of justice, to which
Bennett had admitted on the witness stand. He could face decades in
prison for these crimes, although such a stiff sentence is unlikely
under federal guidelines. But the jury declared itself at a
stalemate on the more substantive charges, including more than 50
counts of securities fraud, mail fraud, bank fraud and money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
   After Chief Judge Thomas Griesa declared a mistrial, Robert
Khuzami, chief of the securities and commodities fraud task force
at the U.S. attorney's office, said authorities would try again to
convict Griesa.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stem from the collapse of Bennett Funding Group,
which purported to be in the business of financing the leases of
office equipment like copiers and fax machines. Some of these
leases were sold to investors, who also lent money to Bennett's
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of investors in New York, New Jersey, Florida and
other states lost about $700 million after the company went
bankrupt in 1996, according to the court-appointed trustee.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's lawyers, while not denying that investors suffered
huge losses, said that their client was just a bad businessman, not
a crook. Bennett was ``unprepared, untrained, unqualified _ a
hard-working guy who was in way over his head,'' said David Levitt,
one of the public defenders.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the defense's story of a ``country bumpkin,'' the
prosecution marshaled more than 30 witnesses and hundreds of
documents, contending that Bennett had deliberately sold leases on
equipment that did not exist and falsified his books, while taking
money out of the business to buy himself gambling properties,
including a racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, witnesses identified papers and discussed the arcana
of receivables and lease-back transactions. The jury of seven women
and five men visibly struggled to stay alert throughout the
proceedings, even when Bennett himself admitted on the stand last
month that he had lied to try to thwart a federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors continue to believe that their losses were caused
by fraud, as does Richard Breeden, the former chairman of the
Securities and Exchange Commission, who is now running the bankrupt
Bennett estate. Though the bankruptcy has been extremely
contentious and convoluted, lawyers involved in it say, investors
are likely to recover more than 36 cents for every dollar lost,
which is unusually high.
</P>
</TEXT>
