<HEADLINE>
CHANGES FOR MONDESI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Raul Mondesi swears he worked hard in past
spring-training camps but never like he's worked this year.
</P>
<P>
   Although he arrived at camp 15 pounds over his playing weight _
he's since cut that in half _ it was a marked improvement over
previous springs. And he said he's running and working out much
more than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure my body is healthy and in good shape to
play 180 games,'' the Dodgers right fielder said. ``That's how many
games you have to play to make it to the World Series. Every year I
have to watch these other teams in the playoffs, and I don't want
to watch them. I want them to watch me.''
</P>
<P>
   In his five full seasons with the Dodgers, Mondesi is averaging
25 homers and 82 RBI per year. He's one of baseball's best
defensive players, but questions of his commitment and work ethic
have haunted him.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros was cautious in his
observation of Mondesi but did say he noticed a change in Mondesi's
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not getting here right before we go on the field and he's
not leaving right after we're done,'' said Karros, who dresses next
to Mondesi. ``I think (the Dodgers brass) has been waiting for that
the last couple of years. He's obviously someone with a lot of
talent and a lot of ability. He has as much ability as anybody in
the game. No question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Shaw due in today: Dodgers manager Davey Johnson might have
been right when he said ``Maybe their calculations were off'' on
the due date for Jeff and Julie Shaw's third child.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors told the Shaws the birth might not take place until
mid-March, so the right-handed closer is expected to arrive at
Dodgertown today. He'll fly back to Washington Court House, Ohio,
for the birth.
</P>
<P>
   __ Signings: As expected, the Dodgers signed former Chicago Cubs
catcher Rick Wilkins to a minor-league contract Tuesday. He broke
into the major leagues in 1991 and hit 30 homers for the Cubs in
1993. Wilkins, who lives in Jacksonville, drove to an open tryout
Monday at Dodgertown and agreed to the contract Tuesday morning. .
. . The Dodgers announced they have reached contract agreements
with the 18 remaining members of their 40-man roster, which
included third baseman Adrian Beltre and outfielder Trenidad
Hubbard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
