<SLUG> BC-NJ-STATE-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. LAWMAKERS SEEK TALK WITH CLINTON ON COMPLAINTS AGAINST
TROOPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Three members of the state Legislature's Black
and Latino Caucus said they would speak to President Clinton when
he visits New Jersey on Wednesday to urge him to speed up a federal
investigation into allegations of racial profiling by state
troopers.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers _ Assemblyman LeRoy Jones Jr., state Sen. Shirley
Turner and Assemblyman Nellie Pou, all Democrats _ said they would
greet Clinton at Newark International Airport on Wednesday
afternoon when he arrives to attend a fund-raiser for Democratic
U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli at the New Jersey Performing Arts
Center in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Goldberg, a spokesman for the White House press office,
said the lawmakers would be among several people in the welcoming
party. ``I think it is inaccurate to characterize it as a
meeting,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, the Justice Department has been reviewing
complaints that New Jersey troopers single out minority drivers in
searching for drug traffickers. But the issue generated renewed
attention on Sunday when Gov. Christie Whitman dismissed the state
police superintendent, Col. Carl Williams, for suggesting in an
interview with The Star-Ledger of Newark that cocaine and marijuana
traffickers were most likely to be members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time we have what could be direct evidence of an
attitude, perhaps of a policy of the state police coming from the
department itself,'' said Assemblyman Joseph Charles Jr., chairman
of the Black and Latino Caucus. ``We need to get a complete
investigation so that the cloud that currently exists over the
state police will either be removed or be dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   The caucus also announced that starting in April, it would hold
statewide hearings into complaints of racial profiling and police
brutality by state troopers, said Charles, who is from Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   The caucus also joined calls for a delay in the nomination of
the state attorney general, Peter Verniero, to the state Supreme
Court until the federal investigation is complete. Verniero
oversees the state police. Whitman nominated him last week to fill
the place of Associate Justice Stewart Pollock, who will retire on
Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman continued to oppose any delay, and on Tuesday, she
submitted a formal notice of the nomination to the state Senate,
said her spokesman, Jayne O'Connor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
