<SLUG> BC-LA-TRADE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A.'S TRADE BUSINESS NO. 1 DESPITE ASIA WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Asian economic crisis cut into Los Angeles'
trade business last year, leading to the area's first decline since
1982, a top analyst reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Asian flu was not enough to keep the region from being
the top trade area in the country for the fifth straight year, said
Jack Kyser, chief analyst with the nonprofit Los Angeles Economic
Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the ill winds blowing out of Asia, Southern
California actually did pretty well,'' Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   According to an LAEDC analysis of U.S. Department of Commerce
figures, imports and exports at Los Angeles International Airport
and the ports of Long Beach, Los Angeles and Hueneme slipped 2.4
percent to $181.5 billion last year. But even with the decline, the
Los Angeles Customs District -- as it's known -- squeaked past New
York's 1998 trade total of $180.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser estimated that trade this year will grow by 3.3 percent,
spurred in part by recovering Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, local trade in 1998 benefited from a flood of Asian
goods that have become cheaper because of struggling Asian markets,
Kyser said. The value of total imports to Los Angeles increased 5.3
percent to $117.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That increase was more than offset by declining exports,
however. According to Kyser, total exports from the region fell
13.9 percent to $63.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the decline in dollar figures does not necessarily mean that
Los Angeles trade is suffering, said Art Wong, spokesman for the
Port of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The port recently posted its highest trade volume in history,
with over 4 million TEUs, or Twenty-foot Equivalent Units, passing
though in 1998, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade still looks to be very strong,'' Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Winter, executive secretary with the Foreign Trade
Association of California, agreed that the region is poised for
growth in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll see an increase compared to last year, assuming
we don't see any major labor disruptions,'' he said. ``A lot of the
Asian economies are coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
