<DOCNO> NYT19990302.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERRILL-AD-COLUMN-NYT     03-02 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH'S NEW CAMPAIGN PUTS BULL OUT TO PASTURE (SORT OF) 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch is bullish on _ mankind?
</P>
<P>
   According to an unconventional campaign that begins Thursday,
the employees and executives of Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. are as devoted
to furthering ``human achievement'' _ as the theme of the ads
proclaims _ as they are to selling stocks, offering financial
advice and making deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always viewed ourselves as an engine for human
progress as we move capital around the world from areas with
surplus to areas with need,'' Paul W. Critchlow, senior vice
president for marketing and communications at Merrill Lynch in New
York, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to capture the voice of Merrill Lynch in a way that
differentiates us from the incredible noise and clutter in a
competitive category where we think most others are narrowly
focused,'' he added. ``This captures the fact we stand for
something with a higher purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertising, with a budget estimated at $75 million, is
intended to appear around the world and ranges from print and
television to the Internet and radio. The campaign, to be
introduced in phases in the next several months, is the first from
J. Walter Thompson New York since the agency was awarded the
Merrill Lynch account in June.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from Merrill Lynch and the agency gave a preview of
the campaign at an hourlong meeting at the Thompson office in
midtown Manhattan. One recurring question was whether the
achievement theme _ replacing a theme, ``The difference is Merrill
Lynch,'' which has been in use since 1993 _ was too lofty and
ethereal for a financial services marketer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we've researched it, we've found it is not up in the
clouds,'' said Thomas C. Cotton, executive vice president and
global business director on the Merrill Lynch account at Thompson.
``Prospects and current clients say it's very relevant and
persuasive and meaningful.''
</P>
<P>
   That is particularly true in the financial services field, said
Dan J. Haughton, first vice president and senior director for
marketing services at the Merrill Lynch Private Client Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human relationships become important,'' Haughton said. ``When
people get more money, they say, `I don't have the same level of
comfort I did as when I was starting out and didn't have
anything.'''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign arrives at a moment fraught with possibilities, and
risks, for both agency and client. The response to the unusual ads
will be crucial to efforts by Thompson New York to regain a
reputation for creativity. The campaign was supervised by Bill
Hamilton, a new worldwide creative director at the Thompson New
York parent, the J. Walter Thompson Co. unit of WPP Group P.L.C.
</P>
<P>
   The ads also arrive as WPP is completing discussions with
Charlotte Beers to join Thompson, most likely as chairwoman. If WPP
hires Ms. Beers, who formerly led the Thompson sibling Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather Worldwide, she would help Chris Jones, the Thompson chief
executive, with current clients and work on attracting additional
blue-chip advertisers like Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   For Merrill Lynch, the campaign comes as the company is
scrambling to confront challenges from scrappy, upstart online
brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not see technology as an end,'' Critchlow said, ``but as
a means to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, the nation's largest retail broker, will soon
begin a limited online trading service; later stages of the
campaign are intended to remind consumers that the company also
provides broader services like tax advice and estate planning.
</P>
<P>
   And Merrill Lynch finds itself continually steering customers
through the turbulence roiling the global financial system. In
fact, the campaign was supposed to start in January, but work on it
was postponed last fall in favor of creating ads that were intended
to reassure nervous investors after a worldwide plunge in stock
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign seeks to be ``a re-presentation of the firm as it's
evolving,'' Cotton said, invoking ``values like optimism, the long
view versus the short, principles driving performance, the wisdom
of the firm and the indomitable human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The posture and tone of the campaign contemporizes the
brand,'' he added. ``That's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Critchlow said, ``We see this as the next chapter in the
evolution of the Merrill Lynch brand, from making the financial
markets accessible to Main Street to being `Bullish on America.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some elements from past campaigns that focused on the familiar
Merrill Lynch bull will continue to appear. But results from
consumer research show that concentrating more on the bull would be
counterproductive, said Charles V. Mangano, first vice president
and senior director for marketing at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quote that seemed to sum it up,'' Mangano said, ``was
someone in a group we showed the new ads to, who said, ` ``Bullish
on America'' is about them; ``Human achievement'' is about me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The initial print ads and television commercials are practically
spiritual in their attempts to build the Merrill Lynch brand.
</P>
<P>
   One print ad begins, ``If you want to see something done, just
tell some human beings it can't be done.'' And it ends: ``Dangle
the undoable in front of the world. Then, consider it done.''
</P>
<P>
   One commercial features a young girl who is meant to symbolize
the changes the world has undergone since 1989. She appears, in the
manner of Forrest Gump or Zelig, amid historical events from the
fall of the Berlin wall to the arrival of democracy in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   A second spot about techno-mania shows the blues singer B.B.
King and his guitar Lucille. The spot contrasts technology, which
an announcer asserts is ``plastic and metal and wire,'' with
people, who represent ``brilliance and discernment and vision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Admire machines,'' the announcer concludes. ``Worship their
inventors.''
</P>
<P>
   In a third commercial, a man on a rainy Manhattan street gives
up his taxi to a woman and her children. ``If you're looking for a
hero,'' an announcer declares, ``look around.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jeffrey, who joined Thompson New York as president 11 months
ago, said: ``Great brands link up with people more one-on-one on
`soft' issues, not just `hard' ones. In financial services, people
want a company that cares about more than performance; they want a
company they can like, a `company that understands me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent parts of the campaign include an eight-page magazine
insert and commercials promoting the U.S. private client business
of Merrill Lynch, comparing a family to a business with the theme
``Your Life Inc.'' In addition, print ads aimed at high-technology
entrepreneurs will praise the Merrill Lynch capital-raising efforts
for companies like Cisco Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``CEO's and players don't see us as the fast-moving investment
bank we really are,'' Cotton said.
</P>
<P>
   That must be some kind of achievement, too, when an agency
executive uses ``us'' and ``we'' to refer to a client rather than
``them'' and ``they.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
