<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN'S HARRIS STILL A NO-SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ It appears Rico Harris' season with the Cal State
Northridge men's basketball team is over, and his future as a
Matador is also in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN head coach Bobby Braswell had not heard from his suspended
forward Tuesday, two days before the Matadors' first-round game in
the Big Sky Tournament at Ogden, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't spoken to him,'' Braswell said Tuesday morning.
``I'm going to try to reach him at his mom's house. . . . At this
point, if we don't get this thing resolved, it probably won't be
resolved this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors (17-11) leave for Utah today. They play Montana
State (15-12) Thursday night at 8:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' unknown whereabouts put a damper on a day when senior
guard Derrick Higgins was named All-Big Sky Conference. Higgins,
CSUN's leading scorer at 13.7 points per game, was the Matadors'
only first-team representative. Sophomore center Brian Heinle was
an honorable-mention selection.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, a junior transfer from L.A. City College, was suspended
with junior guard Greg Minor last week and missed CSUN's last two
regular-season games at Weber State and Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all feel Rico made his decision and his decision was not to
be with this team,'' Heinle said. ``Rico is his own person. He has
his life to lead. We're not going to dwell on (his absence).''
</P>
<P>
   Minor met with the team and coaching staff Monday, offered an
apology, and was reinstated. Harris did not show at the meeting
despite phone messages from Braswell.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I just don't want any distractions or anything
that is going to keep this team from being focused,'' Braswell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris (6-foot-9, 250 pounds) appeared in 20 games this season,
starting 10. He missed five games with injuries and also was
suspended for the Matadors' game at Tennessee on Nov. 17 for
violating a team rule. He was the Matadors' top rebounder (6.6 per
game) and third-leading scorer (11.7).
</P>
<P>
   CSUN has won eight of its last 11 games and established a season
high in points in a 99-65 win at Sacramento State on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell said team morale has been better since the suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any second-guessing or doubt that they
can win (the tournament),'' he said. ``They are locked in. Right
now, our morale is higher than it's ever been. I look at these guys
hanging out with each other . . . hugging and talking and
laughing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-99 2235EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
