A5289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HALLOFFAME-NYT &LR;      03-02 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HALLOFFAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MARGIN OF ERROR: CEPEDA ELECTED TO HALL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Five years after he missed election to the
Baseball Hall of Fame by seven votes on the writers' ballot,
Orlando Cepeda gained election Tuesday with not many more votes
than that.
</P>
<P>
   An abbreviated version of the Veterans Committee elected the
first baseman; an umpire, Nestor Chylak; a turn-of-the-century
manager, Frank Selee, and a Negro leagues pitcher, Smokey Joe
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Only 12 members of the 15-man committee attended the annual
meeting, meaning nine votes _ three-fourths _ were needed for
election. The committee did not disclose the number of votes
received by those elected or those who were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to,'' Joe L. Brown, the committee chairman and
former general manager of the Pittsburgh Pirates, said when asked
why the committee would not give vote totals.
</P>
<P>
   Cepeda, who hit 379 home runs and drove in 1,365 runs in a
17-year career that ended in 1974, was not elected in 15 years on
the ballot of the Baseball Writers Association. In his last year on
the ballot, 1994, he received 335 votes, seven short of the 75
percent needed for election. This was the second year he was
eligible for consideration by the Veterans Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that Dom DiMaggio, Joe Gordon, Mel Harder and Bill
Mazeroski were among others who were considered, but he also
declined to give their vote totals. Committee members can vote for
as many as 10 players.
</P>
<P>
   Cepeda, hampered by bad knees throughout his career, said he
believed his arrest in Puerto Rico in 1975 for smuggling marijuana
had worked against his earlier election.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't know me,'' he said of the writers who voted.
``Maybe they heard some things about me that weren't too cool.
Later on, I don't think they felt that way. When they got to know
me, they knew I was a human being who made mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cepeda, who works for the San Francisco Giants in community
affairs, said he closely followed the recent debate involving
Lawrence Taylor's election to the Pro Football Hall of Fame. ``I'm
glad they voted for him,'' Cepeda, who served a 10-month prison
sentence, said. ``When you are human beings, you can make mistakes.
I learned from my mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent to his arrest, Cepeda became a Buddhist and Tuesday
he said he believes he will be the only Buddhist in the Hall of
Fame when he is inducted July 25 with Nolan Ryan, George Brett and
Robin Yount, whom the writers elected last month.
</P>
<P>
   Cepeda was a unanimous winner of the National League rookie of
the year award with the Giants in 1958 and of the NL's most
valuable player award with the St. Louis Cardinals in 1967. He also
played for Atlanta, Oakland, the Boston Red Sox and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Chylak was elected 17 years after he died at the age of 59. He
served as an American League umpire for 25 years, from 1954 through
1978, and is the eighth umpire elected to the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Selee began managing the Boston Beaneaters, later the Braves, in
1890. He remained in Boston through 1901, then managed the Chicago
Cubs until tuberculosis forced him to retire during the 1905 season
while assembling the nucleus of the Cubs' dynasty in the
Tinker-Evers-Chance years. His career record, 1.284-862, gave him a
.598 winning percentage, fourth best in history.
</P>
<P>
   Williams pitched from 1910 through 1932 for five Negro league
teams, including the Homestead Grays and the Pittsburgh Crawfords.
In 1952 he was elected to an all-time Negro leagues all-star team,
edging Satchel Paige by 1 vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
