u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-BUDGET-NYT     03-02 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, March 3.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-ASSESS (Chiang Mai, Thailand) _ A news analysis:
Secretary Albright tries to put best face on the U.S.-China
relationship, saying it can progress despite disagreements on human
rights, trade and missiles, but administration faces big problems
on all these issues in Washington and in China. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-SUPERVISION (Undated) _ Three decades after American
college students defiantly threw off the vestiges of curfews, dress
codes and dormitory house mothers, a revolution is under way in
undergraduate life that may be quieter but no less significant.
Reflecting a range of societal changes _ consumerism,
litigiousness, a shift in intergenerational relations, new
technologies _ colleges are offering and students are often
demanding greater supervision of their lives. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ESPY _ Somewhere between bribing a federal official and
bestowing an innocent gift on one lies an illegal gratuity. Federal
law punishes giving a gratuity with two years in prison, but as a
Supreme Court argument demonstrated, it defines the offense so
imprecisely that the search for meaning is almost as much an
exercise in metaphysics as in law. The case before the court is an
outgrowth of an independent counsel's failed prosecution of Mike
Espy, who was acquitted three months ago of having accepted illegal
gifts from companies regulated by his department. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Frankfurt, Germany) _ In the two months since the European
single currency was introduced, pretty much the only direction it
has moved is down. From a buoyant and technically smooth start-up
on Jan. 4, the euro has steadily slipped against the U.S. dollar,
and the decline has puzzled the overseers of the new currency at
the European Central Bank. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-PRIVACY (San Francisco) _ An outcry over privacy flared
recently when it was learned that Intel's new Pentium III chip
would leave a traceable footprint so that users could be
identified. Further examination of the issue now finds that there
are already widely used computer programs that make it possible to
trace documents to their source. ``You already have zero privacy _
get over it,'' says one computer executive. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MONSANTO-DUPONT (Chicago) _ At the same time that Robert
Shapiro, chief executive of Monsanto Co., is beating a drum for an
open and free-thinking corporate environment, he and other
executives are in merger negotiations with DuPont, a much larger
company with more traditional ways. The result has been a peculiar
courtship in recent months, with Shapiro searching for a way for
Monsanto to become acquired by DuPont and still retain its special
character and habits. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on major cultural differences between Monsanto
and DuPont has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   3COM-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Any doubts that technology stocks
were undergoing a correction evaporated Tuesday as yet another
prominent maker of computer equipment, the 3Com Corp., announced
that its sales and earnings would fall short of expectations. By
Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL-AD-COLUMN _ Merrill Lynch is bullish on _ mankind?
According to an unconventional campaign that begins Thursday, the
employees and executives of Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. are as devoted to
furthering ``human achievement'' _ as the theme of the ads
proclaims _ as they are to selling stocks, offering financial
advice and making deals. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KING-LEAR (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook: Listening to ``King
Lear,'' then reading the play. By Christopher Lehmann-Haupt.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-TECH (Tempe, Ariz.) _ The International Dance and
Technology Conference is held in Tempe, Ariz. By Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Bob Herbert examines Andrew Cuomo's
jobs strategy for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HKN-VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on the
N.Y. Rangers, who are 2-0 with Wayne Gretzky on the sidelines and
now try to make it three in a row against the team with the best
record in hockey _ the Dallas Stars. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-MEAT (New York) _ Bruce Aidells and his collaborator,
Denis Kelly, has spent nearly a decade studying the state of meat
in America to produce ``The Complete Meat Cookbook,'' published
last November by Houghton Mifflin. Not only does it secure his
image as a man unafraid of meat, even in these vegetable-revering
times, but it also is rife with heretical ideas. ``Meat has changed
in America,'' he said. ``We need to change the way we cook it.'' By
Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MEAT-MARINATE (Undated) _ Since the earliest days of recorded
history, and maybe even before, humans have marinated their food,
steeping meat, fowl and fish in some combination of liquid _
usually oil or acid _ and seasonings. At first, there were
practical reasons: Tough meat needed to be made tender, it needed
to be preserved, and, with humans ever attuned to improving their
lot, it needed to be flavored. But from ranch to refrigerator,
almost everything has changed about meat and the way it is treated
today. Everything, that is, except marination. By Eric Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-MICROWAVE (New York) _ A new question is creeping into wine
service in New York: How do you want that cooked? For many years,
Americans have confounded the rest of the world by drinking their
white wines too cold and their red wines too warm. Sommeliers no
longer hesitate when diners ask that a luscious Corton-Charlemagne
be plunged into an ice bucket. They just do it. It's easy. Red wine
poses a different problem. If it arrives at the table with slight
chill, and the diners want it the temperature of a blood
transfusion _ fast _ the sommelier must resort to wiles, and the
wiliest wile of all, it turns out, is the microwave oven. By
William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
