A5292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-BORDER-HOMES-CO     03-02 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BORDER-HOMES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plan calls for 40,000 homes on border
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The new executive director of the Texas
Department of Housing and Community Affairs is proposing a
five-year, $2 billion program to build 40,000 single-family homes
along the Mexico border. It would be the largest housing-assistance
program ever undertaken by the state in the border region.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy Stiner said the program would be an ambitious undertaking
to help eradicate substandard neighborhoods known as colonias,
where a mostly Hispanic population lives in ramshackle construction
with leaking septic tanks and inadequate roads.
</P>
<P>
   She outlined the proposal last week before the Senate's Special
Committee on Border Affairs. Legislators and housing advocates were
surprised by the scope of the plan. The state traditionally has
relied mainly on the federal government for housing assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The plan could not proceed without legislation, and the
prospects for that are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a program yet; it's a concept,'' Stiner said. ``The
details will have to be worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the state would hire a large-scale homebuilder
to build prefabricated houses. Building a large number of houses
would keep the purchase price to $50,000 per house. The monthly
mortgage, utility and insurance payments would total $375 for a
typical family with an annual income of $15,000. Down payments
would be financed by a no-interest loan or a government grant.
</P>
<P>
   The largest share of the $2 billion plan, $1.3 billion for
single-family mortgage loans, would come from bonds issued by the
state. Depending on the type of bonds, voter approval could be
required. Down payment assistance totaling $730 million would come
from general state revenues or federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph K.M. Haurwitz writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. E-mail: rhaurwitz(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
