<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-BOOK-NYT &LR;      03-02 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOOK, LEWINSKY LASHES OUT AGAINST STARR
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a book to be published later this week, Monica
Lewinsky is so critical of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr that
several of her friends and associates say they fear Starr will
become angry and try to revoke her immunity agreement and prosecute
her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky says in the book, ``Monica's Story'' by Andrew
Morton, that she was so despondent at her treatment by prosecutors
who confronted her at a hotel in suburban Virginia on Jan. 16,
1998, that she briefly considered killing herself in their
presence, said a person familiar with the contents of her book.
</P>
<P>
   Plato Cacheris, one of her lawyers, said Tuesday night that
neither he nor her other lead lawyer, Jacob Stein, had seen the
book's manuscript or galleys. ``Monica and Andrew Morton did this
on their own,'' Cacheris said. ``We did not vet the book.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to speculate about how Starr would react.
</P>
<P>
   But several friends of the Lewinsky family said Tuesday that
they were very concerned that Ms. Lewinsky's remarks might
backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big concern to us,'' an associate of Ms. Lewinsky said.
``She's bound by this agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the immunity agreement under which Ms. Lewinsky testified
about her affair with President Clinton and efforts to cover it up,
Starr forbade Ms. Lewinsky to discuss his office's conduct in an
interview with Barbara Walters to be broadcast Wednesday night on
ABC. But Ms. Lewinsky was free to discuss Starr's office with
Morton because her agreement did not apply to the book.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Ms. Lewinsky says that after one of Starr's
prosecutors told her that she faced 27 years in jail if she refused
to cooperate with their criminal inquiry of Clinton, she
``contemplated throwing herself'' through a plate-glass window on
the hotel's 10th floor, where she stood at the time with several
prosecutors, the person who had read the manuscript said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky also complains in her book that her initial
attempts to call her lawyer and her mother were rebuffed by
prosecutors and agents.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky says that prosecutors on Jan. 16, 1998, confronted
her with a copy of her false affidavit in which she swore that she
did not have an affair with the president. But at that time, Ms.
Lewinsky's lawyer, Francis Carter, had still not filed the
affidavit yet with a federal court in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office had been sent the affidavit anonymously by James
Moody, a lawyer for Linda Tripp who had obtained it from lawyers
for Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's prosecutors are facing an inquiry by the Justice
Department on their conduct in the Lewinsky inquiry, including
whether they improperly attempted to coerce Ms. Lewinsky to
cooperate with their investigation while her lawyer was not present
and had improper contacts with lawyers for Ms. Jones that were not
disclosed to Justice Department attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky also says in her book that prosecutors rebuffed her
first requests to call her mother and her lawyer, the person said.
During her grand jury testimony, Ms. Lewinsky said that after she
had said she needed to consult her mother, Marcia Lewis, prosecutor
Jackie Bennett told her: ``You're 24. You're smart. You're old
enough. You don't need to call your mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   Under her immunity agreement, Ms. Lewinsky is not permitted to
speak with the media without Starr's permission. For months, Starr
insisted that Ms. Lewinsky remain silent. Several weeks ago, he
permitted Ms. Lewinsky to speak with Ms. Walters only after
insisting that she not discuss her knowledge of their ongoing
investigation or any issues involving Starr.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ms. Lewinsky reportedly tells Ms. Walters during their
interview that she is not ``allowed'' to discuss her treatment by
Starr's prosecutors. But that same admonition did not hold for her
book, which was not covered by her immunity agreement, her lawyers
said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past two days, Ms. Lewinsky's friends and lawyers
have become aware of the criticism of Starr's prosecutors. One
associate, who has not seen the book, said Tuesday night,
``Apparently she is very, very critical of Starr's people, and
we're worried about how they will react.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bakaly III, spokesman for Starr, did not return phone
calls Tuesday night. But in the past, Bakaly has defended the
treatment of Ms. Lewinsky as ethical. During his testimony before
Congress in November, Starr said that Ms. Lewinsky was incorrect in
saying that prosecutors had barred her from calling anyone she
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it clear to the witness that she was, in fact, free to
leave,'' Starr said then. ``And the Ritz-Carlton, shall I say, is a
fairly comfortable and commodious place.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky has told associates that she resented her treatment
by prosecutors after she struck her agreement in late July 1998.
She met with prosecutors nearly 20 times and was asked repeatedly
to describe ``intimate details'' of her relationship with the
president, an associate said Tuesday night. ``She just thought it
was truly humiliating,'' the associate said.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Ms. Lewinsky also recalls how she felt when she
realized that her friend, Mrs. Tripp, had betrayed her. She had
bumped into Mrs. Tripp later that afternoon in the Pentagon City
mall. Ms. Lewinsky recalls how she told Mrs. Tripp, sarcastically,
``Thanks a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp replied, ``They did it to me, too,'' meaning that
Starr's prosecutors had also tricked her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky says in the book that she knew right away that Mrs.
Tripp had lied to her again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
