<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5299 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-STJOHNS-BARKLEY-A     03-02 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHNS-BARKLEY-ART-1,120(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME OF THIS POINT GUARD'S BEST MOVES HAVE BEEN OFF THE COURT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Erick Barkley is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Erick Barkley and Tyrone Grant, their low voices
spiked with bravado, had a conversation recently that turned civic
pride on its head _ debating which one of them came from the worse
Brooklyn neighborhood. Grant _ from Brownsville, ``a few blocks
from Mike Tyson,'' he noted _ brought the debate to a quick
conclusion when he conceded that Barkley's was ``the worst
neighborhood in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either be a drug dealer or play basketball,'' Barkley
said in perhaps an overstatement about the Farragut houses in Fort
Greene. ``You took one side of the road or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Barkley can still look out her apartment window at
Farragut and see the concrete court below where her small son took
his first underhand shots when he was 6 and began to make that
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was terrible; ``I was an ant,'' he said. But basketball
led him on a circuitous course fraught with the perils of the urban
ghetto, a course he managed to navigate from childhood games
against Stephon Marbury to a key role in the elevation of St.
John's to a top 10 ranking this season. From the chaos rose the
consummately controlled, reticent fulcrum of St. John's offense, a
freshman who will be on display this week in the Big East
Conference tournament, which begins Wednesday at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Good point guards, St. John's Coach Mike Jarvis said, give teams
the chance to win every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for Erick, we wouldn't be in the top 10,'' said
Grant, the senior center. ``He's made all of us better. His
decision-making has been perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   His decision-making off the court has been nearly as good.
Barkley was born in 1978 and grew up during the crack scourge, when
one early mentor used to hear gunshots and gang fights as he
escorted young Erick home from the gym. Shirley Barkley, an
evangelist, did not want Erick, the youngest of nine children, in
the projects then, and still tries to dissuade him from visiting
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was drug-infested,'' she said. ``You couldn't help it. I
never had any problems with Erick, though. He was always a good
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was the beneficiary of what now looks like the smooth
exchanges of a practiced relay team: a handoff from mother to
church league coach to high school to concerned friends to a
fortuitous trip out of town to improve his grades, to college.
</P>
<P>
   It was not so smooth, of course. When Erick was still in high
school, Shirley Barkley left her son behind with friends and went
to Georgia, a move she made to get away from the neighborhood, her
son said. And Barkley struggled so much academically in high school
that there were doubts he would be eligible to play for St. John's
this season.
</P>
<P>
   But the inner city has forged that most legendary of New York
athletes _ the playground point guard _ and Barkley figured out
that he could steal the moves from the good ones like Marbury and
still avoid the pitfalls that swallowed other street phenoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball was his salvation,'' said Bob Oliva, Barkley's
coach at Christ the King High School in Queens. ``I've never
coached a player who had such a one-track mind. Erick's social life
was going to the gym and playing basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Francis knew that from the first time Barkley showed up for
a St. Ann's Catholic Youth Organization practice. Barkley was about
6 then, and very small. Francis, a dean at Xaverian High School,
has a picture of Barkley standing next to a water fountain; the
fountain is taller than Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Francis became one of the people Shirley Barkley relied on to
rescue her son. He shooed away the gang members when they tried to
woo a 12-year-old Barkley, and Francis' gym became the haven for
Barkley and the place where the first glimmers of his future became
clear.
</P>
<P>
   He once scored 20 points in a half during a 12-and-under
tournament, when Barkley encountered Marbury at a Christmas
tournament in Coney Island. Barkley was 9 and Marbury was 11. The
final score was 54-48.
</P>
<P>
   ``His team had 48 and Steph had 44,'' Barkley said. ``We won the
game and I was the MVP. I will never forget that game.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he got to Christ the King, Barkley was already a
standout player _ Oliva said he was the most controlled freshman he
had seen _ and the team won the Catholic league championship in
Barkley's sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   The personal turning point came before Erick's senior year, when
Shirley Barkley moved to Georgia. Mother and son agreed that Erick
would stay in New York and then go to prep school to help his
grades.
</P>
<P>
   Francis talked to the family of Craig (Speedy) Claxton,
Barkley's close friend, who is now Hofstra's point guard. Yvette
and Steve Claxton run a quiet household where the television is off
and the schoolwork is done. They have seven children, the oldest of
whom is about to graduate from medical school. When Barkley moved
to the Claxtons' home in Hempstead, on Long Island, it was his
first brush with the dynamics and discipline of a middle-class
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saw that people could live better, so that's the way he
chose to go,'' Shirley Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Claxton said: ``When he moved in with me, it was a nice
neighborhood, and he didn't have a choice about getting into
trouble. My father drove my sister to school every day, so he had
to go. It's tough on you if you don't have somebody looking after
you telling you to go. They treated him like another part of
family. I think he was more friendly and easier to get along with
afterwards. Living with my parents, it opened him up to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley is now so quiet and composed that an on-court flare-up
between him and Ron Artest during a game against Connecticut in
January was shocking. But in high school, Barkley displayed a fiery
temperament, and he was ejected from a diocesan championship game
for scuffling with an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was uncoachable,'' Barkley said. ``I had a bad attitude. I
didn't listen. At Christ the King, I would mumble something under
my breath if things didn't go my way. I'd point my finger at
somebody else. My temper was so quick.''
</P>
<P>
   That changed when Barkley got to Maine Central Institute in
remote Pittsfield, a prep school powerhouse Barkley attended to
improve his grades. He got the test score he needed, and with the
change in scenery came a change in style. His coach, Max Good, told
him that the innate New York suspiciousness and street-tough
attitude would have to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Erick came to visit he said, `Coach, let me use your
car.' '' Good said. ``I tossed him the keys. I don't think he
really wanted the car; he wanted my trust. His host parents said he
hardly left the driveway. When I gave it to him it had an eighth of
a tank of gas. When I got it back, it was full. I think he learned
to trust people here.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As his personal life settled down, so, too, did his game. The
temper faded and so did the flashy plays. Barkley had seen
prodigies whose games were so full of juking and thread-the-needle
passes that colleges spent two years changing their style. Why, he
wondered, shouldn't he just develop a stripped-down game from the
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never used to settle for the easy play,'' Barkley said. ``At
Maine, I was watching a lot of games. I really liked John
Stockton's game a lot. One move, and he'd go right by them. Being
flashy doesn't get you anywhere. Being a fundamental point guard
gets you places.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's is going places with him. Barkley's minimalism _
crisp passes and simple moves _ has enabled him to play four games
this season with no turnovers, and seven games with just one. He
has 74 steals. He is the point guard St. John's didn't have during
the Felipe Lopez era. Last season, St. John's two point guards,
Tarik Turner and Collin Charles, turned the ball over 113 times and
made 169 assists. Barkley has 62 turnovers and 133 assists.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's is where it needs to be, a likely third seed when the
national tournament brackets are announced Sunday. Shirley Barkley
is back in town for a while, too, to see her son finish his season.
The latest handoff has been made. Barkley is taking St. John's to
the top level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of games, I was nervous and I tried to make
everybody feel I was perfect,'' Barkley said. ``Once I got that out
of my head, it's worked out. I guess I've got a game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
