<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNCLAIMED-DEAD-CHILD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No calls on child keep cops puzzled
 &HT;    By R. Robin McDonald
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The shoelaces on a pair of small brown boots signaled
DeKalb County, Ga.'s forensic investigators that someone cared
about the child whose remains were found last Friday in a stand of
pines below an aging cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   They were double-tied.
</P>
<P>
   Those shoelaces, knotted so they would not trail along the
ground are, in part, why investigators are puzzled that no one has
come forward with information that would help them to identify the
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disturbing not to have gotten any calls,'' said Paul
Kelhofer, chief forensic investigator at the DeKalb County Medical
Examiner's Office. ``Somebody who cared about the child may not
know this child has been found.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators do know that the body _ a black child about 4 feet
tall between the ages of 5 and 7 _ is not one of 50 children and
teens who have been reported missing to DeKalb police and whose
whereabouts are still unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The body does not match that of any children reported missing in
metropolitan Atlanta, police said.
</P>
<P>
   It does not match the nearly 100 missing black children between
the ages of 5 and 7 whose names and descriptions were provided to
DeKalb investigators by the National Center for Missing and
Exploited Children, Kelhofer said.
</P>
<P>
   Medical examiners are awaiting the results of DNA tests that
will tell them the sex of the child, whose decomposed remains were
in the wood for three to six months before a gravedigger found them
last week. Pathologists have not yet determined a cause of death.
No signs of trauma, either old or recent, were detected, said Dr.
Gerald Gowitt, the county's chief associate medical examiner. But
investigators do suspect foul play.
</P>
<P>
   There are no firm figures available on the number of children
now missing in this country, said Cathy Nahirny, a spokeswoman for
the federally funded National Center for Missing and Exploited
Children. ``That's the real problem,'' she said. ``There is no
mandate that requires every missing child in America to be reported
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   But a U.S. Justice Department study published in 1990 _ the most
recent available _ estimated that in 1988, 163,200 children
disappeared when parents embroiled in divorces or custody battles
fled the state of residence or country with them.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 133,500 children ran away from home. And another
127,100 children were ``thrown-aways'' _ children who were ordered
out of the house by their parents or guardians; who ran away but no
one made any effort to find them; and children who were deserted or
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The report listed 139,100 children as injured, lost or missing.
</P>
<P>
   But, Nahirney acknowledged, finding a body of an unidentified,
dead child is rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a child abuse situation where they (a parent or
guardian) get so violent punishing the child that the child dies,''
Nahirney said. ``Maybe it was an accident. Maybe it wasn't. But
instead of reporting the child missing, they just dispose of the
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad reality is that parents do that.''
</P>
<P>
   R. Robin McDonald writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
