<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL SILVER CHARM ANSWER CRITICS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ For a sports star in the media age, Silver
Charm gets off easy. All that glory, none of those pesky
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   America's richest active thoroughbred has people to answer for
him when the nabobs of negativism come a-nattering. Has Mark
McGwire thought of this?
</P>
<P>
   And Silver Charm's reputation as the strong, silent type is
coming in particularly handy this week, when reporters and
horse-race handicappers wonder if the vulnerable favorite for
Saturday's $1 million Santa Anita Handicap is an athlete in
decline.
</P>
<P>
   The burden of rebutting the horse's detractors falls heavily on
his jockey, Gary Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to rebut anything,'' Stevens said on Santa
Anita's grandstand steps Tuesday morning as he watched one of
Silver Charm's rivals work out. ``He's made a lot of money, he's
one of the best horses we've seen, and he'll either win or lose
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``His races speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't stop everyone else from speaking about Silver Charm,
the 1997 Kentucky Derby and Preakness champion with the knack for
winning the close ones. He's the talk of any race he runs, whether
he's the lone attraction, as is often the case, or one of a handful
of horses with Grade I credentials, as in this unusually deep Big
'Cap.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita, which is advertising its signature race as ``Silver
Charm vs. (an) All-Star Field,'' figures the chatter will add 5,000
to a turnstile count that has straddled the 30,000 mark in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Until lately, the talk of Silver Charm was uniformly flattering
(as if he's susceptible to flattery).
</P>
<P>
   He didn't just have gray good looks and popular connections in
Stevens, trainer Bob Baffert and owners Bob and Beverly Lewis of
Newport Beach. He had two-thirds of a Triple Crown, a victory over
some of the world's best in the 1998 Dubai World Cup, and a
sensational string of 15 races at the beginning of his career
without a finish as low as third.
</P>
<P>
   He went into this, his 5-year-old season, unquestionably the
nation's top older horse, since 1998 Horse of the Year Skip Away
and Breeders' Cup Classic winner Awesome Again had retired. With
$6,513,006 in the bank, he gazed down a clear path to Cigar's
career earnings record of $9,999,815.
</P>
<P>
   The questions began, strangely enough, following a
season-opening victory in the San Pasqual Handicap at Santa Anita.
In a first-time occurrence that Stevens calls ``a mystery,'' Silver
Charm dropped more than eight lengths behind the leader midway
through the 1 1/16-mile race before rallying to win in an
unimpressive time.
</P>
<P>
   To handicappers, the performance indicated Silver Charm had lost
his early speed and maybe his interest in racing.
</P>
<P>
   The new skeptics seemed to be vindicated three weeks later when
Silver Charm, racing for the first time at Gulfstream Park near
Miami, dropped a little farther off the pace in the 1[-mile Donn
Handicap and this time finished third to Puerto Madero and Behrens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Signs of a Fading Star?'' headlined a Daily Racing Form
column.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the question that everyone keeps asking me _ me as a
jockey not even involved with Silver Charm!'' said Kent Desormeaux,
who rides Puerto Madero, leader of a Richard Mandella-trained
troika in the Big 'Cap. ``People are asking me if I think this
horse is done . . . `Is he going to come back? . . . Is this horse
finished? . . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was Puerto Madero who Stevens watched train on Tuesday
morning. The rival's half-mile workout in a sharp 47 1/5 seconds
didn't shake the jockey's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm's Florida race, Stevens argued, was better than it
appeared. They started from the far outside in a 12-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't sluggish from the gate,'' Stevens said. ``He broke
half a length in front of most of the rest of the field. I had to
decide really quick if I was going to take him back and save ground
or use (precious energy) to get up with the leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens applied the brakes and tried to settle in midpack, close
to the rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the field spread out and instead of being four lengths
back as I wanted, I was 11 lengths back,'' Stevens said. ``I knew
three-eighths (of a mile from the finish) I was toast. He overcame
a lot to be third.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Stevens and Baffert have tried to drill the speed
back into Silver Charm with a series of fast workouts, the latest a
five-eighths-of-a-mile blast Monday whose 57-second clocking was
best of the morning by 1 3/5.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who was aboard, said that's as well as Silver Charm has
ever trained.
</P>
<P>
   It's dangerous to discount the old boy. He has been as good when
he isn't favored (4 for 7, including the Derby and Preakness wins)
as when he is (6 for 13). So his opponents' handlers take nothing
for granted this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never throw out Silver Charm,'' Desormeaux said.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of gamblers will throw him out, looking for a big
payoff in the Big 'Cap. If they're right, the questions will
continue from here to Dubai, where Silver Charm is scheduled to
defend his championship later in the month.
</P>
<P>
   He won't have to answer there either, having never learned
Arabic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
