<HEADLINE>
FROM SPIN CYCLE TO SOAP OPERA 
SRO AT THE PLAZA FOR A HILLARY EVENT 
DESIGNER'S PONCHO, WITH A TWIST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif., Conn.)  (nk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if the line between fiction and reality on television was not
blurry enough, consider this: when the fictional character Ally
McBeal has a daydream, it involves a real person talking about her.
Specifically, former White House press secretary Michael D.
McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   There he was on the Fox nighttime soap opera on Monday, telling
reporters about Ally's guilt-ridden love of Billy, a colleague she
once dated. Billy is now married to Georgia, another partner in
their law firm. Last week, Ally and Billy went so far as to kiss.
</P>
<P>
   This time, McCurry did not say he was out of the loop, though he
was. (More about that later.) He simply explained her feelings
better than she had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, she feels remorse,'' McCurry said. ``She's
embarrassed. But she didn't lie to Georgia. She just didn't
volunteer information.''
</P>
<P>
   So why was McCurry on ``Ally McBeal?''
</P>
<P>
   He and the executive producer, David E. Kelley, have known each
other since 1975, when Kelley was a freshman at Princeton
University and McCurry was a senior and his resident adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had this bright idea for a cameo,'' McCurry said, ``and it
sounded like it would be fun to do on a layover on the West Coast.
It took all of about 20 minutes to actually tape.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the four sentences that McCurry said on camera, ``He
actually wrote that,'' McCurry said, referring to Kelley. ``His
script minders wanted to make sure I said that word for word, no
impromptu allowed. I'm not used to being so programmed in my
responses.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, about McCurry being out of the loop when it came to the
goings-on on ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to confess that being a baby boomer who usually falls
asleep by 9 o'clock at night, I have yet to see a complete
episode,'' he said. ``It looks like it's a fun show.''
</P>
<P>
   SRO AT THE PLAZA FOR A HILLARY EVENT
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton is scheduled to be there. George A. Dean,
a 69-year-old former advertising executive from Southport, Conn.,
is not.
</P>
<P>
   Dean wanted to buy a ticket to what is likely to be Wednesday's
hottest fund-raiser, a lunch at the Plaza Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But the event is sold out. The Democratic National Committee
said 300 people on a waiting list had to be turned away.
</P>
<P>
   This was after the Democrats expanded the guest list to 900, 400
more than when the lunch was scheduled three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was before all the talk about whether Mrs.
Clinton should, would or could run for the Senate seat being
vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I was disappointed'' to have been turned away, said
Dean, adding that he is not a Democrat. ``I used to be a
Republican, but I voted for Ralph Nader last time.''
</P>
<P>
   He became a fan of Mrs. Clinton's after he heard her speak last
year in Westport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have her as a senator from here in Connecticut,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his career is pretty much over. It's conceivable if
she wins in the Senate, in 2004 or 2008, she could be running
against Liddy Dole for the presidency. Stranger things have
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Designer's Poncho, With a Twist
</P>
<P>
   First Andy Warhol, then Keith Haring, now the fashion designer
Kate Spade.
</P>
<P>
   Warhol and Haring did paintings of Absolut vodka bottles that
appeared in advertisements. Ms. Spade, who is known for accessories
like handbags, messenger bags and cosmetic bags, has created a
plastic rain poncho for Absolut. She will sell it for $25 in her
stores in SoHo, Boston and Los Angeles, with $20 from each sale
going to the Horticultural Society of New York.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, she drinks the product. She said she likes vodka
martinis, straight up with an olive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
