<HEADLINE>
TIMES' TOP AD POST CHANGES HANDS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Daniel H. Cohen, the senior vice president for
advertising at The New York Times, is resigning to start a
television production company that will work in tandem with the
Times Electronic Media Co., developing programming to attract an
audience of young people more wedded to television than to print
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Janet L. Robinson, the newspaper's president and general
manager, announced Cohen's departure Tuesday and said that Jyll F.
Holzman, an advertising executive with wide experience in magazine
publishing, would succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Holzman has been a vice president for advertising at the
Times since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the newspaper became the first publication ever to
generate more than $1 billion in advertising revenues in a year.
Ms. Robinson, in a statement, noted that Cohen ``has been
instrumental in the growth of the print expansion of the Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, 46, joined the company in 1983. Earlier, he was vice
president for business affairs at Fort Worth Productions, an
independent film production company. He began his career as a
broadcast journalist and director at WESH-TV in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is the son of Dr. Judith P. Sulzberger, a director of the
Times Co., and a cousin of Arthur Sulzberger Jr., the chairman and
chief executive of the company. In a memo to the staff Tuesday,
Sulzberger said of Cohen, ``Even as he led the Times to
unparalleled levels of print advertising revenue, he has been a
strong voice for our electronic future, both on the Internet and in
broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   Sulzberger continued: ``Dan, at heart, has always had a strong
streak of the entrepreneur in him. He must be related to Adolph
Ochs.'' Like Sulzberger, Cohen is a great-grandson of Ochs, who
purchased the Times in 1896.
</P>
<P>
   ``This next stage of Dan's life will give him the freedom that
every entrepreneur needs,'' Sulzberger said. ``But he will be very
much missed from our day-to-day activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Holzman, 46, has worked at the Times Co. for five years,
starting as advertising director of Child magazine, part of a group
that the company sold in 1994. After working for a year for the
magazine Family Fun, owned by the Walt Disney Co., she joined the
Times in 1995 as a vice president.
</P>
<P>
   One of her immediate challenges will be to sustain advertising
revenue growth at a time when newspapers from Los Angeles to Boston
and New York have been experiencing weakness in help-wanted
classified advertising, the segment that traditionally produces the
largest profit margins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
