u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGANDA-KIDNAP-ART-1ST     03-02 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-KIDNAP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
8 TOURISTS, INCLUDING A U.S. COUPLE, KILLED IN UGANDA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new grafs 8-13, identifying victims, beginning
``The Oregon couple ...; 2nd and 3rd grafs rewritten; number of
tourists attacked has changed from 30 to 31.)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Treks through the Bwindi Impenetrable Forest of southwestern
Uganda to see the rare mountain gorillas are small, exclusive
forays that begin in a tranquil agricultural valley.
</P>
<P>
   But that calm was shattered on Monday when eight tourists,
including an American couple, were hacked or bludgeoned to death in
the jungle by a band of Hutu rebels armed with automatic rifles,
machetes and spears _ remnants of the murderous army that laid
waste to Rwanda in 1994. Four Ugandan park employees were slain in
the campsites.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign victims included four Britons and two New Zealanders
as well as the Americans, who were executives for Intel Corp., the
Oregon-based computer chip manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that I saw had their heads crushed in and deep
slashes,'' said Mark Ross, an American tour leader who was released
by the attackers after a forced march into the jungle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women that we'd been told would be escorted back had been
killed on the spot,'' said Ross, speaking to reporters at a news
conference Tuesday in the Ugandan capital of Kampala. ``It looks
like one was raped prior to being killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the attack on the 31 tourists apparently lies
rooted in the murky violence that has beset central Africa for
years, gradually seeping over the national borders linking Rwanda,
the Congo and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors said as many as 150 ragtag soldiers materialized out
of the trees and sought out Americans and Britons among the
tourists. The State Department said the soldiers were Hutu, the
ethnic group that fled neighboring Rwanda after killing over
500,000 rival Tutsi and moderate Hutu in the genocide of five years
ago. Now regrouped in the wilds of the Congo, the Hutu oppose
American and British support for the Ugandan military and others
who are seen as sympathizing with the Tutsi.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon couple who died were identified as Robert Haubner,
48, and Susan Miller, 42, who had spent their honeymoon in Africa
and had returned with some friends from Intel for their third trip.
</P>
<P>
   Haubner, a 16-year Intel employee, was the worldwide director of
customer support. His wife, who had worked there 15 years, was a
senior trade show manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're shocked and stunned by this news,'' said Bill Calder, a
spokesman for the company. ``These were two valued employees with
very distinguished careers. They loved to travel around the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The British Foreign Office said the names of the British victims
would be released Wednesday. New Zealand Foreign Ministry officials
told Reuters that Rhonda Avis, 27, and Michelle Strathern, 26, were
believed to have been slain and that Ms. Avis' husband had
survived.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Britons killed was Mark Lindgren, 23, a recent
graduate of Nottingham University, a young British man who was on a
three-month tour of Africa before concentrating on his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Times of London quoted his father, John Lindgren, as saying,
``Mark was kindhearted, generous, bright and loved life.'' His
father said he was ``respected by the people he worked with and he
had a bright future ahead of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the border with Congo is easily within an hour's
walk from the entrance to the forest park, the violence there
seemed far away on Monday as the camp was gradually coming to life
at 6:45 a.m. The sun was up, but it had yet to peek over the
surrounding hills.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the tourists were shaking themselves from sleep at that
point, since the starting time for the trek up into the hills was
at 8 a.m. They never made it.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels burst into the camp with a blast of grenades and
automatic weapons fire. The Ugandans _ a game warden and three park
rangers _ were killed in the initial assault. The rebels looted the
buildings, setting a few on fire and torching the vehicles they
came across as well.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors said that initially the rebels herded 31 tourists into
the Abercrombie and Kent encampment and began stripping them of
their valuables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly some soldiers came in the tent and they asked for
money, for jewelry, for watches,'' said Anne Peltier, the deputy
ambassador to Uganda for France, who was among the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At first the rebels seemed to be treating the tourists well, but
some of those captured had a foreboding of what was to come by the
treatment of one group of British tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Adams, 54, from California, was among the 15 hostages
rounded up and sent into the jungle with the troops about 40
minutes after the first attack. She had already seen that the
British man sitting next to her had purple toenails from where he
had been beaten on the feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British people were being forced to walk barefoot if they
had no shoes,'' said Mrs. Adams, who feigned an asthma attack and
waved her inhaler as the march got under way. The soldiers let her
walk back into the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Studd, the mother of Susan Studd, a 46-year-old Oregon
woman who survived the attack, said she talked to her daughter in
Kampala Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   She said her daughter and the daughter's husband, Robert
McLaurin, 44, were awakened in their tent in the Abercrombie and
Kent encampment by grenade explosions and gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``They heard a woman scream, so they got out the back of their
tent and went into the bush and hid there,'' said Mrs. Studd. ``It
was just a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Another American, Elizabeth Garland, 29, a Fulbright scholar
from the University of Chicago, told her father that she escaped by
hiding in her tent. Her father, James Garland, the president of
Miami University in Ohio, told The Associated Press that his
daughter, too, had been awakened by gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Western governments had already warned tourists against
traveling through much of western Uganda because of rebel and
bandit activity near the border with Congo. Up until now, however,
the Bwindi gorilla reserve had been considered safe.
</P>
<P>
   The attack struck a blow at Uganda, itself on the mend after
years of chaos. The State Department warned American citizens to
postpone travel to the region until further notice, and at least
two tour companies said they were suspending trips to the region
until further notice.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Acacia Expeditions said six of the people killed were
on one of its tours. Its travelers, known as ``overlanders,'' are
generally budget tourists who spend weeks traveling across Africa
in large, open trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The other tour group, the upscale Abercrombie and Kent, which
ran the most exclusive tent encampment at the forest, announced
Tuesday that it was closing the facility until it had assurances
that security could be maintained. Its clients would be offered
full refunds or alternative trips, said Alistair Ballantine,
president of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their income level, the tourists at the Impenetrable
Forest all lived in fairly close proximity in a series of clearings
that resembled a small village built near the entrance to the park.
</P>
<P>
   The most budget-conscious tourists _ including most of those
sent by Acacia_ camped in a clearing. Nearby was a series of round
African huts known as bandas and a lodge run by the African Pearl
safari tour company. The Abercrombie and Kent Gorilla Forest Camp
was a series of ten tents with concrete floors that were tucked in
amongst the trees for privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The search for a site of the mountain gorillas had become
especially popular after the 1988 movie ``Gorillas in the Mist,''
which starred Sigourney Weaver as the researcher Dian Fossey, who
dedicated her life to saving the gorillas in Rwanda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
