<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XYLAN-PROFILE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XYLAN HAS SEEN STAR RISE LATELY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. -- Tuesday's announcement that Alcatel SA,
Europe's No. 2 phone equipment maker, has bought Xylan Corp. for
nearly $2 billion caps what has been an impressive five-year run
for the local electronics manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Xylan makes computer network equipment -- high-tech routers and
switches that speed information through data networks like the
Internet and corporate ``intranets.'' The company's 4,000-plus
customers include telecom companies like Sprint and MCI-WorldCom,
data-reliant firms such as IBM and 3M Co., and educational
organizations including Texas A&AMP;M University and the Getty Center
museum.
</P>
<P>
   With the volume of global data traffic worldwide growing far
faster than that of voice calls, firms like Xylan have been in the
ascendancy of late, while traditional phone equipment makers like
Alcatel have been playing catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   To bridge the gap, telecom giants have been gobbling up
data-equipment makers, highlighted in January by Lucent
Technologies' agreement to pay $20 billion for Ascend
Communications. Xylan, which generated about one-tenth that price
from Alcatel, is simply the latest in that trend.
</P>
<P>
   The Calabasas company in suburban Los Angeles County was formed
in 1993 by Douglas Hill, who developed the company's marketing
team; Steve Kim, now the chairman and chief executive; Yuri
Pikover, who built the company's sales force; and John Bailey, who
built the engineering organization. Together the team raised $30
million in start-up capital, then went public in early 1996 with a
stock offering that generated $130 million.
</P>
<P>
   Xylan turned its first profit in the fourth quarter of 1995, and
in the last two years has been growing at an impressive 65 percent
annual rate based on revenues. The company had 1998 sales of $348
million, has no debt and is sitting on about $200 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said his company ``has grown beyond anyone's expectations
over the last five years'' and the deal with Alcatel will give
Xylan ``a dramatic boost.'' He noted in frustration that part of
the impetus to sell was the fact that the company's share price had
not kept pace with its sales and earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   But as buyers go, Alcatel seems a logical fit. Xylan got more
than 12 percent of its fourth-quarter revenue from sales to
Alcatel, and the French firm already owned 6 percent of Xylan's
stock from a 1995 deal.
</P>
<P>
   The $37-per-share price Alcatel has offered should also help
smooth the transition. According to Xylan spokeswoman Kim Kadish,
most employees have some degree of stock options, which last year
were revalued to an exercise price of $15.8125. At a $37 purchase
price, that means each option can now be cashed in for more than
$21 profit before taxes and transaction fees.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the biggest winners from the stock option program are
the founders and other top executives like Kim, Pikover and Bailey,
who have between 7,000 and 130,000 options each, according to the
company's most recent Securities and Exchange Commission filings,
in addition to the hundreds of thousands of shares they already
own.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, for example, owns 3.3 million shares and Pikover owns 2.4
million. After Tuesday morning's announcement of the deal, shares
of Xylan soared 32.7 percent, increasing Kim's stake in the company
from $89.6 million to $118.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
