A5434 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XYLAN-DEAL-LADN     03-02 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XYLAN-DEAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH TELECOM BEHEMOTH ALCATEL CONFIRMS XYLAN DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. -- The rumors are finally right: Xylan Corp.
is being bought.
</P>
<P>
   French telecommunications giant Alcatel SA said Tuesday it will
pay nearly $2 billion for the Calabasas-based maker of network
switching equipment, ending months of speculation over Xylan's
future.
</P>
<P>
   The Calabasas company in suburban Los Angeles County had been a
rumored takeover target for more than 18 months, with Paris-based
Alcatel always considered a likely bidder. The reason: The
Internet. Amid slowing sales of its voice equipment, the Xylan
purchase will boost Alcatel's position as an equipment supplier to
telephone companies looking to become or expand their roles as
Internet service providers, and to large corporations with growing
data networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something Alcatel really needed,'' said analyst Marc
Woodward at Battery Ventures in San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Alcatel's dearth of in-house products in the data
network arena has been an albatross around its neck. Due in part to
the Internet business it lost to competitors last year, the company
was forced in September to announce it would miss earnings
estimates, sending the firm's share price into a nose dive that
erased 38 percent of its value in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   The company tried to make do by buying from a variety of
hardware suppliers including Ascend Communications, Cisco Systems,
Xylan and others. But as several of those companies were themselves
bought by Alcatel competitors, the field of potential dance
partners quickly narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   Cash-rich after a three-year reorganization that saw it sell off
$4.7 billion worth of assets, Alcatel last year began a shopping
spree which, even with the Xylan deal, does not appear to be over.
It paid $4.4 billion in stock for DSC Communications Corp. of
Plano, Texas, beefing up its U.S. sales team and adding several
North American clients. And in December it bought Packet Engines
Inc., a computer-networking company based in Spokane, Wash., for
$315 million cash.
</P>
<P>
   The January purchase of Ascend, the No. 4 network equipment
maker, by Lucent Technologies for $20 billion added extra urgency
to the situation, and may have been what prompted Alcatel to move
on Xylan now.
</P>
<P>
   Already owning 6.5 percent of Xylan from a 1995 deal -- and
accounting for more than 12 percent of the smaller firm's fourth
quarter sales -- Alcatel offered the company $37 per share for its
remaining stock and stock options, a 37 percent premium over the
issue's closing price Monday. Xylan shares had already risen nearly
40 percent in recent weeks on speculation that some sort of deal
was in the works, and the issue closed up $8.8125 Tuesday at
$35.75, a one-day gain of 32.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel chairman Serge Tchuruk said on Tuesday that his firm
would likely buy another company by week's end. He declined to say
which firm was being considered, but said it would provide Alcatel
with the ability to link mobile computers to local networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world of communications and networking is undergoing
fundamental changes,'' Olivier Houssin, executive vice president of
Alcatel Telecom, said in explaining the flood of recent deals.
``Voice and data are converging. The new world will not contain
voice companies and data companies. It will only contain
information companies.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping round out Alcatel's bullpen, Tuesday's
proposed purchase, which must still be approved by regulators on
both sides of the Atlantic, is seen as a plus for Xylan, too. The
company, which will remain a wholly-owned subsidiary of Alcatel,
was already being overshadowed by larger players such as Cisco and
Ascend, a trend that would likely have continued without a large
parent to back it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the face of industry giants, Xylan has grown beyond
anyone's expectations,'' Chairman and chief executive Steve Kim
said Tuesday. Still, Kim said, he had been frustrated because even
as its sales grew, the company's stock price until very recently
did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's investors are favoring the large companies,'' Kim told
the Associated Press. ``They see us as still small.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
