<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BECKENSTEIN-MOVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABOUT NEW YORK: THE DRAPERIES TRY TO MATCH THE SHOPPERS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite the promise of Orchard Street's sylvan name,
who needs trees lining its sidewalks? This Lower East Side shopping
paradise is a bargain-hunter's Garden of Eden, with dozens of
leather jackets and bags dangling from awnings and waiting to be
plucked. And while it isn't exactly a pastoral symphony, the
kinetic come-ons from hawkers provide a steady sound track for a
stroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got leathers for less,'' one vendor shouted to no one and
everyone. ``Check it out. Check it out.''
</P>
<P>
   No spiel-makers are needed at Beckenstein Home Fabrics, a home
decorating business that has lured generations of design-savvy
shoppers to its store inside a former telephone company switch
exchange at 130 Orchard St. It is part of a small empire that
Samuel Beckenstein started some 80 years ago selling rags from a
pushcart on Water Street. He grew the business and diversified into
men's tailoring, women's clothing, draperies and upholstery. Other
businesses came and went in the neighborhood, but Beckenstein's
stayed and prospered.
</P>
<P>
   But like the immigrants who passed through the nearby tenements
on their way to success, uptown beckons. Garry Greenberg, 46, the
third-generation president of the home fabric store, is moving to a
new location at Fifth Avenue and West 20th Street in the Flatiron
district later this month, the better to compete with the other
upscale home decor stores in that area.
</P>
<P>
   His explanation for the move is similar to what he tells
customers who are overwhelmed by the thousands of imported fabric
swatches and custom room designs he displays in his store. ``All
this reflects a variety of choices, but in reality there are few
answers,'' he said. ``This is definitely a great neighborhood for
people who want to stretch the buck. But it's a different type of
person now. Nothing is wrong with that. It's just not my
clientele.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes that brought about this move began decades ago. The
clothing stores that attracted plenty of curious shoppers to the
block could not compete with uptown department stores that sold
discounted mass-produced suits. The 1970s repeal of the city's blue
laws, which had made stores close one day a week, ended the
advantage of local Jewish shopkeepers who were off on Saturdays and
open for business on Sundays. Older merchants either leased their
buildings to other businesses or converted them into apartments.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Greenberg saw his competitors moving uptown. He
also lost sales to those new, big-box stores that were opening up
in the Flatiron district. By last year, he had decided to move. His
father, Murray, who started the home decor division, agreed it was
a smart decision, even if his son was leaving the area both of them
had known for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to go with the times and the times are uptown,''
Murray said. ``Today, you can't go on emotion. You have to go where
you can cover your overhead.''
</P>
<P>
   Or where you can make your own mark. Garry is in awe of his
grandfather, who came to this country from Poland and built up his
business while managing to get his family out of Europe before
World War II began. Samuel Beckenstein had enough ingenuity to find
a profitable niche in making trousers to match worn-out suits.
While he made a tidy sum off the seats of other people's pants, he
ran his business with an expertise that was hardly seat of the
pants. Relatives knew something big had happened when he asked how
to spell ``million.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm baffled,'' Garry said. ``He grew a business and he didn't
even write English. The only way he communicated with the business
community was through his accountants and lawyers. Here I am, a
well-educated man, there's no way I could duplicate his success. He
identified opportunity. The second generation maintained the
accomplishments of the first. And my generation just spreads it out
a little bit. But no one ever took it to another level. That's what
I'm trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   While he's moving uptown, Garry still comes across as sincere
and unassuming. Celebrities shop at his store, but he remains
unfazed, much as he was in the 1980s when the Indian Prime
Minister, Rajiv Gandhi, and his wife shopped at Beckensteins.
Months later, they invited him to a state dinner in Washington. He
declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was during the summer and I'm a big Hamptons guy,'' he
explained. ``I'm not giving up a weekend in the Hamptons to sit in
the Rose Garden. I let my father and mother go. I went to the
beach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
