<SLUG> BC-IRIDIUM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRIDIUM WILL MISS QUARTERLY SALES TARGET
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REBECCA ROWLING  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
Iridium, the global satellite tele phone network dreamed up by
three Motorola engineers in Chandler, said Tuesday that it does not
expect to meet its sales and customer goals for the quarter. Its
stock price fell 12 percent on the news.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Iridium LLC said it will likely fail to meet the minimum sales
and subscriber targets for the first quar ter of 1999 that were set
in the company's $800 million senior se cured credit agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The report drove Iridium stock down 2 to close at 21, well below
its 52-week high of 72 reached in May.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium blamed its troubles on difficulty in getting its phones
to customers and building a fully trained sales force.
</P>
<P>
   Although the service was launched in November, it wasn't until
the middle of February that Kyocera Corp. of Japan, one of the two
companies making Iridium handsets, began shipping the prod ucts.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Kyocera has resolved software problems with the phones,
it can start distributing them to a waiting list of customers
around the world. Iridium isn't saying how many are waiting for
phones but says the demand is especially strong in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium wholesales its service to 15 franchises around the world
that are responsible for sales in their region. Some of the
franchises, including Iridium North America, rely upon service
providers like Sprint PCS to sell the phones to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium has certified 85 service providers, another 85 are
undergo ing certification and 50 more have signed up to become
providers. The expanded sales force should help the company sign up
more custom ers.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium maintains that demand for its costly service is high. An
Iridium phone costs $3,000, and calls cost between $2 and $7 a
minute. Some analysts have ques tioned how many people would be
willing to pay that kind of money to use the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The causes of the delays in Iridium's subscriber ramp-up have
not been associated with the level of market demand for our
product, which we believe to be strong,'' an Iridium statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium was expected to have $30 million in accrued revenue from
subscriber billings and at least 52,000 subscribers by the
quarter's end.
</P>
<P>
   It had only 3,000 subscribers and $186,000 in accrued revenue at
the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium said it expects to begin discussions with its banks,
Chase Manhattan Corp. and Barclays Plc, to renegotiate its
agreements. Ana lysts expect the banks to be willing to deal, since
it's in nobody's interest for Iridium to default.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium said its shortfall will not affect its ability to meet
its debts.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. lowered Iridium's corporate and secured
bank loan debt rating one notch upon word that the company would
not meet its goals.
</P>
<P>
   At least one analyst said that the bench marks were too high and
that it was no surprise that Iridium failed to the meet them.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium says it's ``very confi dent'' it will meet its
previously announced goal of 500,000 to 600,000 customers by the
year's end.
</P>
<P>
   That's because strong demand exists and Iridium is working out
the kinks of being a global business from the first day of
operation, spokeswoman Michelle Lyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola characterized Iridium's troubles as the growing pains
of a start-up company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motorola is very confident that the market segment exists for
the Iridium system and they will be able to capture that market
here with time,'' spokesman Robert Edwards said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
