<HEADER>
A5456 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSUN-PRESIDENT-LADN     03-02 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSUN-PRESIDENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT OF CAL STATE NORTHRIDGE QUITTING AFTER SEVEN YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Editors: Daily News Staff Writer Greg Gittrich contributed to this
story.) 
BY SHARLINE CHIANG  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- California State University, Northridge,
President Blenda J. Wilson announced Tuesday she is ending her
sometimes stormy seven-year tenure at the college and taking a job
with an education foundation on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said after graduation ceremonies in early June she will
leave to serve as president and chief operating officer of the
newly founded Nellie Mae Foundation. The Braintree, Mass.-based
nonprofit organization provides educational grants to low-income
and disadvantaged students across New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was offered the perfect job for me, to promote access,
quality and effectiveness in education,'' said Wilson, 56, the
first African-American president in the CSU system and Northridge's
first woman president.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said by leading the foundation she can help improve the
quality of K-12 learning, pointedly noting 67 percent of CSUN's
incoming freshman need remediation in math and 62 percent in
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our higher education system is the best in the world,'' she
said. ``The threat to education is that our schools are not
performing. This gives me an opportunity to focus entirely in
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said she chose to leave the suburban Los Angeles campus
voluntarily, although she added: ``I regret that I can't be here
and some place else at the same time too . . . that I will not have
been here as long as I would've liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who had been one of the top finalists for the
president's post at Wayne State University in Detroit in August
1997, has been highly praised for reopening CSUN in time for the
spring semester four weeks after the devastating 1994 Northridge
Earthquake and for leading the herculean rebuilding program that
continues today. The quake caused more than $400 million in damages
to the San Fernando Valley campus approximately 25 miles northwest
of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared written statement, California State University
Chancellor Charles B. Reed praised Wilson, saying she has ``made an
indelible impression at CSUN.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She had the courage and vision to keep classes open (after the
earthquake),'' Reed said. ``We thank her for her contributions and
wish her well in her new endeavors.''
</P>
<P>
   But the university's image also has suffered at times under her
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, former women's basketball coach Michael Abraham
was arrested on allegations of crack cocaine possession and
distribution. The case triggered the resignation of athletic
director Paul Bubb and his assistant, Judy Brame.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1997, Wilson came under harsh criticism for announcing
that four popular men's sports would be cut to balance the athletic
department budget and meet gender-equity requirements. Student
athletes and community members blasted the decision, calling it
abrupt and void of public input.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1998, the Federal Emergency Management Agency
investigated allegations of misuse of federal funds, including
reports that moving crews working on quake repairs moved office
equipment for Wilson's husband, Louis Fair Jr.
</P>
<P>
   While FEMA eventually dropped its investigation, the California
State University conducted an independent audit and found Wilson
exerted ``undue influence'' over movers, who may have felt
pressured to help the president. It was undetermined whether work
was performed on FEMA time or on the workers' own time.
</P>
<P>
   A separate, routine audit of CSUN's finances and management,
done every two years, will be released next week, said CSU
spokeswoman Colleen Bentley-Adler.
</P>
<P>
   Leadership has been unstable. At least six high-ranking campus
officials -- including Bubb and Brame -- have resigned over the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President of Student Affairs Ron Kopita, whose tasks
included overseeing athletics, announced in early February he will
leave his post by June 5 to consider other career options,
including teaching at CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President of Administration and Finance Art Elbert,
who was in charge of overseeing FEMA funds, stepped down last
December to take a re-assignment at the CSU Chancellor's Office in
Long Beach. Part of his time is spent at the Northridge campus.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence O'Toole, the Nellie Mae foundation's chief executive
officer, said Wilson was selected to become the foundation's first
president from 200 candidates nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted to have her,'' he said. We ``selected her
because of the caliber of her intellectual curiosity and the
emotional commitment she displays toward helping kids learn.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN student body President Joaquin Macias called Wilson's
announcement ``a real loss for the university.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's terrible. You're killing me,'' Macias said when he
learned the news. ``I know she's been working real hard to get CSUN
back on its feet. She's held up real well under all the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Stennis, a CSU trustee from Los Angeles who has served
on the board for six years, said Wilson is ``one of our best
presidents and most popular ones.'' He said Reed told trustees the
news Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Stennis said he doubts controversies pressured Wilson to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that. Knowing Blenda and the kind of person she
is, that would not affect her taking the position at all,'' Stennis
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bentley-Adler, a nationwide search will be
conducted for Wilson's replacement and an interim president will
likely be named to steer the campus after Wilson departs in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get a national search done in that short amount of
time,'' she said. ``It takes at least six months to do a search.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson previously was chancellor of the University of Michigan
at Dearborn from 1988-92 and served on the governor's cabinet as
executive director of the Colorado Commission on Higher Education
from 1984-88.
</P>
<P>
   She began her career in higher education administration at
Rutgers University in New Jersey in 1969 and was associate dean at
the Harvard University Graduate School of Education from 1972-82.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
