<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT NIP KNICKS IN OVERTIME, 85-84 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ All the animosity and pride that have formed the
foundation of the Heat-Knicks rivalry bubbled to the surface on
Tuesday night. It provided fuel for the Knicks. They would not fold
in their third game in three nights. They would stand up and keep
attacking until the end.
</P>
<P>
   The end came in overtime when Patrick Ewing missed a 13-foot
running jumper over P.J. Brown as the Heat prevailed, 85-84, at the
Miami Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Playing 43 minutes, Ewing ended the game with 31 points and 16
rebounds, while his Georgetown buddy, Alonzo Mourning, had 28
points and 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Two free throws by Terry Porter with 54.8 seconds left gave the
Heat the deciding margin. Tim Hardaway returned after missing one
game with a hyperextended knee and added 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief moment, it looked as if the fumes were catching up
to the Knicks (9-6) in the fourth quarter. A lively Larry Johnson
started to fade as he missed five consecutive shots down the
stretch, and gave the Heat a chance to take a 68-67 lead on a
baseline jumper from Brown.
</P>
<P>
   One possession later, Brown gobbled up an offensive rebound, and
fired it back out to Rex Walters, who nailed a 3-pointer with seven
minutes left in the game. That gave the Heat a 71-67 lead and
ignited the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But Ewing came back with a dunk and then Allan Houston came back
from a dreadful night. After hitting just 2 of his first 12 shots,
he popped off a screen and delivered an 18-foot jumper with 34.3
seconds left to tie the game. Each team had a chance to issue the
final blow, but Ewing missed on a running jumper with 3.2 seconds
left. And then Porter, driving the baseline with 2.8 seconds left,
failed to get the call as he smacked up against Ewing. A failed
tip-in by Mourning, and the game went into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being satisfied with an inspired first half, the
Knicks refused to give in to fatigue and a quick Heat lead to tie
the game at 53 on a 15-8 run. Yes, the Knicks lashed back. The
bodies were banging, the intensity was rising and was punctuated by
hard fouls and a pileup on loose balls.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing gave the Knicks the lead back on a breakaway dunk
opportunity that turned into a hard foul by Brown. Ewing collected
his body, then hit two free throws to give the Knicks a 55-53 lead.
After a back-and-forth, he stepped back for a jumper over
Mourning's outstretched arms. Ewing kept on coming, and went to the
free-throw line to deliver four consecutive times.
</P>
<P>
   As an encore, he twisted on a reverse tip-in off a deflected
shot. Ewing, and Ewing alone, gave the Knicks a 65-62 lead as a
raucous third quarter ended. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one could have been sure that the Knicks _ and specifically
the 36-year-old Ewing _ would have this kind of effort in reserve
as they faced their third game in three nights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
