<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TIE STARS, 2-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a wonderfully rugged game at Madison Square Garden
on Tuesday night, the New York Rangers played the best team in the
National Hockey League to a 2-2 draw in an inspired effort that
sometimes brought the fans to their feet to chant and cheer and
scream at the referee.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, the playoff-seeking Rangers led the Dallas Stars, who are
a top contender for the Stanley Cup. Twice, the Stars came back to
tie. Twice, Rangers goalie Mike Richter played unprotected when his
helmet and mask were knocked from his head and face in collisions
around his net. But the Rangers never lost face, and both teams
settled for a point in the standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure both teams probably felt they should have won the
hockey game,'' said Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   On most nights, either team would have. Each team had at least
10 good scoring chances. Pucks rolled through painted creases,
trickled near goal lines and clanged off posts. Bodies banged
against the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Playing their third consecutive game without defeat and without
their superstar center Wayne Gretzky, the Rangers got a balanced
effort, especially from their three top centers: Petr Nedved, Marc
Savard and Manny Malhotra.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Graves and Scott Fraser scored for the Rangers. For Graves,
it was goal No. 30 in a comeback season. Jamie Langenbrunner and
Joe Nieuwendyk scored for Dallas. All goal were at even strength.
The Stars had seven power plays and the Rangers had only three.
Although the Ranger fans didn't like the decision-making of referee
Paul Devorski, Hitchcock joked that it was his team that got the
worst of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really got cheated,'' Hitchcock said. ``He didn't give us
the opportunity to decline all those power plays. That was the
worst thing that happened to us all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the top penalty-killers was Graves, who seems to have
added a dimension to his game as he approaches unrestricted free
agency at the age of 31 this summer. Graves has been ragging the
puck, protecting it with his stick, skates and body, wearing out
the opposition even when it has the manpower advantage. And he has
scored six goals in his last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you lose the greatest player that ever played the
game, it's a huge void,'' Graves said of Gretzky, who will miss
about two weeks with a disc problem near his neck. ``Everyone has
to take on more responsibility. I think guys are enjoying the
opportunity and trying to take advantage of it and playing as hard
as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Fraser, called up three games ago to replace Todd
Harvey, who is out for about a month with a broken thumb. Fraser
has two goals in those three games and has added a element of speed
to what has not been a fast team.
</P>
<P>
   Muckler said Fraser is now showing why the Rangers picked him up
last summer as a free agent from Edmonton. He struggled early in
the season, but skates now as if he does not plan to return to the
minor leagues. Overall, of the team, Muckler said:
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe in themselves. They're playing as a team. They're
working hard. They trust each other. We're very positive in our
thinking. We're very aggressive in our thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Devorski gave the Stars more power plays than the
Rangers, the Rangers came close to winning during a brief power
play in overtime. And they also came close while killing a penalty
late in the third period, when Niklas Sundstrom's shot hit a post
behind Dallas goalie Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Graves scored the first goal of the game at the 70-second mark
of the first period. Graves got open in the left-wing face-off
circle during a forechecking foray and beat Belfour high on the
glove side with a soft shot that deflected off a defenseman after
Nedved had passed the puck to Graves from the corner. MacLean got
the other assist.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars tied the score at 1-1 at 16:26 of the first period on
a goal by Langenbrunner, who stood in front of Richter and
deflected a shot by Jere Lehtinen, who fired from the slot after
Mike Modano won the puck and worked it out from behind the goal
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers took their second lead of the game at 3:04 of the
second period on an even-strength goal by Fraser, who scored for
the second time in three games since being recalled from the
Hartford Wolf Pack farm team to replace the injured Todd Harvey.
With Belfour down after stopping Marc Savard's shot, Fraser took
appropriate time before flipping the puck high and under the cross
bar to give the Rangers a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas tied the score at 2-2 in the final minute of the second
period when Joe Nieuwendyk finished off a play that evolved when
the Rangers had trouble clearing the puck out of their zone along
the wall. Shawn Chambers got the assist at 19:32.
</P>
<P>
   The result gave the Rangers a three-game undefeated streak and a
4-1-1 record in their last six games. The Stars are 8-1-2 in their
last 10.
</P>
<P>
   In the Rangers' struggle for the eighth and final playoff berth
in the Eastern Conference, with a quarter of the season remaining,
three of the four closest Ranger rivals played on Tuesday night and
all of them won. Boston, holding the eighth place, beat Phoenix.
The Bruins now have 62 points, 2 ahead of idle Florida, which holds
ninth. Montreal and Washington, which began the night behind the
Rangers, also won.
</P>
<P>
   The tie gave the Rangers 58 points, good for a 10th-place tie
with Montreal and 2 behind ninth place Florida. The Capitals, now
in 12th, have 57.
</P>
</TEXT>
