</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZONA-DRY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA FORESTS THREATENED WITH FIERCE FIRE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forest fire expert Dave Killebrew remembers all too well the
bone-dry March that led to the Lone fire incinerating the Four
Peaks area three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And the hellish dry winds of May and June 1990 that preceded the
state's deadliest fire ever, the Dude fire north of Payson.
</P>
<P>
   So take it to the bank when Killebrew, fire specialist for Tonto
National Forest in Phoenix, issues a warning. This is the driest
winter for vegetation in the forest since records have been kept of
such things, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take significant moisture in March and April to
even get us up to the level of dryness of those earlier years,''
Killebrew says.
</P>
<P>
   The indicators of a potentially horrific fire season are
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In what is normally the peak time of year for snowpack,
firefighters battled significant blazes near the entrances to the
communities of Pine and Strawberry and in other areas near Payson
during the past week. One of the fires even broke out at night,
which fire observers say is unprecedented this early in the year.
At even higher altitudes southeast of Flagstaff, they fought a
pesky 30-acre fire they burned for four days.
</P>
<P>
   Runoff into the six lakes of the Salt River basin is less than
one-fifth of normal and expected to stay that way the next few
months. The Arizona Snowbowl ski area gave up and closed Sunday
after never being able to open more than half its runs and having
its second-worst season on record up to this point.
</P>
<P>
   Flagstaff normally has had 71 inches of snow by this time each
winter. It has had only 23 inches this season. Prescott and Payson
have also had less than a third of their normal precipitation.
</P>
<P>
   There's little hope for relief as a high-pressure ridge
continues to hang around the Southwest, bouncing La Nina storms
from the Pacific Ocean to the north. La Nina is a weather
phenomenon caused by abnormal cooling of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Moisture estimates by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration indicate that the Southwest will be up to one-third
drier than normal for the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   The parched forest has already led to talk among public-lands
officials of closures, manning of fire towers and mobilization of
firefighting equipment two months before the normal time. Prescott
National Forest workers have already placed their signs warning of
extreme fire danger in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is very troubling to Paul Coe, chief of the
Pine-Strawberry Fire District.
</P>
<P>
   After the scare from the fire near the south entrance to Pine
last week, he said he suggested to the Forest Service that it
conduct a ``controlled burn'' in the area to try to reduce the
vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did it, and it looked like a fire from the height of the
fire season,'' Coe said. ``The fire was going into the crowns of
the trees and the lengths of the flames were going up to 25 and 30
feet. I don't think anyone can believe how dry things are.''
</P>
<P>
   So dry that a fire broke out shortly before 9 p.m. Monday at the
6,000-foot level about a mile east of Pine. It took a valiant
effort by 18 firefighters to keep it from climbing the nearby
Mogollon Rim, Coe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been daylight, it would have gone over the top of
the Rim,'' Coe said. ``I mean, whoever heard of a forest fire on a
winter night? And the ignition source apparently was something
which had smoldered for a few days. It wasn't even a campfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry McCoy, a ranger for Coconino National Forest southeast of
Flagstaff, also said that fire specialists were shocked when a
wildfire broke out last week at the 7,000-foot level between
Marshall Lake and Walnut Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put it mildly, people were surprised when they saw smoke in
the air. But we really do have late May conditions in early
March,'' McCoy said. ``We've got higher fire danger now than we had
in 1996. But we're in better shape than the Tonto and Prescott
forests because we got some moisture in October and November and
they got none.''
</P>
<P>
   The winter of 1995-96 has been the driest on record.
</P>
<P>
   According to Scott Harelson, a spokesman for Salt River Project,
only 132,000 acre-feet of water ran off from the watershed of the
Salt and Verde rivers that year. In a normal year, 850,000
acre-feet will run off into the six reservoirs north and east of
the Valley. SRP officials are predicting a runoff of 161,000
acre-feet this year, although that estimate may be high, Harelson
said.
</P>
<P>
   An acre-foot is the amount that would cover an acre to a depth
of 1 foot, or 325,851 gallons. It would meet the needs of a family
of five for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I overheard one of our hydrologists talking about how this
looks like it will be the worst year for dryness since 1710, using
tree-ring data as a measure from that time,'' Harelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of moisture is also taking a toll on the reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Harelson said that Horseshoe Lake on the Verde River is at only
13 percent of capacity and Roosevelt Lake on the Salt River is only
40 percent of capacity. SRP will increase its groundwater pumping
in the Phoenix area this year but has not determined by how much,
Harelson said. &QL; 
 &UR; Mark Shaffer can be reached at 444-8057 or at mark.shaffer &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
